<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-ARMSTRONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEARS AND PAIN FAIL TO STOP ARMSTRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The warm glow radiating from Trace Armstrong after
his three sacks last Sunday that helped the Miami Dolphins gain
their first road playoff victory in 28 years made it easier for him
to dismiss the message his body was sending. ``This time of year,
you're almost bankrupt physically,'' said Armstrong, a defensive
end.
</P>
<P>
   In his 11th National Football League season, Armstrong, who
recently turned 34 years old, spent his day off Monday mixing
plenty of rest with several hours of physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   His neck was still bothering him when he showed up Tuesday to
begin practice for Miami's American Football Conference playoff
game Saturday at Jacksonville. His performance in the 20-17 victory
over Seattle gave him a team-leading 10.5 sacks for the season.
That led to the question of whether he felt more like 24 than 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I feel more like 54,'' he said with a wane smile. ``Ask
me on Thursday or Friday. What is this anyway, Week 20?''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's body may be balking, but he has been playing his
whole career for the national stage that looms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature plays a cruel trick on you in this game,'' he said
softly. ``Just when you start to figure it out mentally, your
physical skills start to go. But when you get in a game like the
one this week, experience helps. Because playoff games are
different from regular-season games. The intensity level is higher.
The mistakes that are made are magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is used mostly in passing situations, so the
6-foot-4-inch, 270-pounder must hope that his teammates can slow
down Jacksonville's running game, which he described today as the
league's best. But his value extends beyond his playing ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He studies film like a coach,'' said assistant head coach Dave
Wannstedt. ``He's like having another coach on the field. Plus, he
practices the way he plays. I had him seven years ago in Chicago
and he practices as hard now working on the little things as he did
then. That's the kind of example you hope a veteran sets.''
</P>
<P>
   His fellow defensive end Jason Taylor, in his third pro season,
makes it a point to sit next to Armstrong in meetings and said ``he
helps me every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Taylor is more than nine years younger.
Armstrong, who also is president of the National Football League
Players Association, is accustomed to being viewed as one of the
team's sages.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'm beyond even that stage,'' he said. ``I'm pretty
sure they view me like some antique.''
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, he added: ``I just enjoy helping players. If it's
in a meeting room, talking about how to run a stunt, or something
to think about on a blitz; or if it's off the field, guys wondering
about finances _ I just enjoy doing anything to help out.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is widely known that Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino,
now in his 17th season, has yet to get a Super Bowl ring, Armstrong
also is without one, having spent his first six seasons with
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized going into this year that we had an opportunity,
and you don't get them all the time,'' he said. ``You just start to
develop this feeling of urgency because you know you're not going
to be back too many more times or have too many more
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong plans to get a law degree when his football career is
over. Some even have called him the heir apparent to Gene Upshaw as
executive director of the players association.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't plan to quit playing the game for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have to run me off,'' he said. ``You have to realize
I've been a football player since I was 7. One of the strange
things about this game is you're 34, and in regular society that's
still a fairly young man, and they're starting to tell you you're
too old any more to do what you've done your whole life. It's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong understands he could be looking at his chance of a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very solid football team,'' he said Tuesday. ``It's
not like we feel everybody has to play their best game for us to
win on Saturday.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
