<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-MEANING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLICING BUDGET NUMBERS: JUST WHAT DO THEY MEAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki's proposed new state budget is
$76.8 billion, a 5.5 percent increase. Right? Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to gauge what a governor's proposed budget actually means
is akin to palm-reading. The numbers are sliced so many ways, so
subject to manipulation and so prone to comparisons that make
``apples to oranges'' sound pretty good, that it is often hard to
know what to believe.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there are three budgets, not one. The core is the
general fund, about half the total, which generally includes state
taxes and the things they pay for.
</P>
<P>
   The next category is called the state funds budget, which
includes the general fund and various other sources of state
revenue and expenses, like tuition paid by students in the State
University system, and totals more than $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the all-funds budget, that $76.8 billion number,
which includes federal grants for things like welfare and Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki likes to talk about the general fund as being the
important figure, because it is the one that rises slowest. But,
like Gov. Mario Cuomo before him, he has dampened that rate of
increase simply by declaring that certain things are not part of
the general fund any more, though they are still reflected in the
state funds and all-funds budgets.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year-old state program to lower the property taxes charged
by local school districts also skews the results. It shows up on
the books as a spending item _ payments to the districts _ not as a
drop in revenue, the way an ordinary tax cut would. If this program
were calculated like other tax cuts, the overall spending increase
would be 3.4 percent, not 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also routinely overestimates what programs will cost, and
underestimates tax revenue, as a way of restraining the
Legislature's tendency to spend freely. That makes comparisons to
past years difficult. The State Senate and the Assembly, in
drafting their budget plans, will change those estimates,
``finding'' billions of dollars more to spend but claiming that the
total is the same as the governor's.
</P>
<P>
   The final budget tends to lean toward the governor's penchant
for caution. For example, the 1998-99 budget was called a $71.4
billion plan when it was adopted, but once the fiscal year ended,
it turned out that the state had spent $70.6 billion. How much is
the 1999-2000 state budget? No one will really know until after the
fiscal year ends March 31. The administration is calling it $72.8
billion, but that is just an estimate.
</P>
<P>
   So the 5.5 percent increase in the governor's new proposed
budget is arrived at by dividing a projection by an estimate. In
other words, don't bet on that figure turning out to be accurate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
