</HEADLINE>
  
 DeVRY GIVES CAREER TRAINING THE OLD COLLEGE TRY  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or (bl)  
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A knit cap on his head, his long legs encased in
baggy jeans, Issan Duke was perched on a stool in the computer
laboratory at the DeVry Institute of Technology, an upstart college
in the Long Island City section of Queens that believes it has
created a practical and efficient form of career-oriented liberal
arts education.
</P>
<P>
   In the lab, a bright, cavernous room with row after row of
computers and other technical equipment, Duke, a 20-year-old
first-term student, patiently pinched clamps onto thin wires,
measuring voltage.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Jayson Burton, an ebullient 18-year-old freshman, was
learning to use Microsoft's PowerPoint software program. And Jaya
Ramathal, a fourth-semester student, was working on an accounting
assignment that called for using software to send out checks and
bills.
</P>
<P>
   In its concentration on career skills, DeVry _ a part of DeVry
Inc., one of the largest commercial higher education groups in the
United States _ sounds like those ubiquitous proprietary or career
schools that used to be a staple of matchbook covers. Those
no-frills schools promise to prepare students quickly for rewarding
careers in business and technology, without the extras of a rounded
liberal arts education.
</P>
<P>
   DeVry, too, promises a quick path to a career, but the
resemblance ends there. The DeVry Institutes are a chain of 17
accredited colleges that grant baccalaureate degrees but have
followed a McDonald's formula: Their programs are quick, relatively
inexpensive (for a private college) and quality-controlled. That
translates into a limited curriculum of standard courses designed
at the company's headquarters in Oakbrook Terrace, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to produce Harvard graduates,'' said Ronald
Taylor, DeVry Inc.'s president. ``Our students are interested in a
career and want the skills _ technical and nontechnical _ to do the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the focus is on practical knowledge and careers, DeVry
also makes a substantial effort to give students a traditional,
though abbreviated, general education. A bachelor's degree
candidate, for example, must take 12 credits of humanities, 12
credits of social sciences and 13 credits of communications,
including composition, professional writing and public speaking.
</P>
<P>
   There are no sororities or fraternities, no football team and no
summer vacations (they are not considered a good use of the
student's time or the school's physical plant). But DeVry says that
more than 92 percent of its graduates who look for jobs in their
field find them within six months of graduation.
</P>
<P>
   DeVry differs from traditional colleges in other ways, too. It
uses market research to help choose the fields it offers and
television advertisements to attract students. And its faculty in
Queens _ a mix of 25 full-time and 41 part-time teachers _ is on
contract (there is no tenure), and all teachers are evaluated
annually. The only criterion is teaching, not research, although
many members of the faculty _ more than half of whom have
doctorates _ conduct research on their own time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a much more vigorous accountability system than at
other colleges,'' said Roger Andersen, president of the Queens
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratory work is at the heart of what the college offers.
Other colleges assign homework, but for students at DeVry,
projects, problems and papers are commonly done during class on
computers or machines.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of study and less than $40,000 in tuition
(less for programs like accounting that require only eight
semesters), students emerge with a bachelor's degree, a smattering
of humanities and social sciences, and hands-on training in a
business or technical field like electronics, computer information
systems or accounting.
</P>
<P>
   DeVry's businesslike approach, which some see as a threat to
more traditional, not-for-profit colleges, has paid dividends not
only in steadily rising revenues and earnings (DeVry Inc. earned a
record $39 million last fiscal year on revenues of $421 million),
but also in an expanding student body. In November, the company had
43,063 undergraduates, and another 6,180 graduate students at its
graduate school of management.
</P>
<P>
   While the formula may be efficient, some educators at more
traditional colleges are concerned that students are shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of college should be to expand horizons and allow
students to explore,'' said Joanne Reitano, a history professor at
CUNY's La Guardia Community College, just a block from DeVry. ``The
purpose of education is to nurture, not to narrow.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an old industrial neighborhood near the 59th Street Bridge,
the Queens campus is DeVry's first in New York City, but Taylor
envisions two or three eventually. And despite abundant
competition, the 14-month-old campus is ahead of projections, DeVry
executives say. With 1,248 students this term _ three-quarters of
them black or Hispanic _ the college has already exercised its
option to expand to three floors from two in its building, the
former International Design Center of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Students say the expansion will come none too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``DeVry is overpopulated,'' said Nelson Fong, a third-term
student who transferred from the State University of New York at
Buffalo. ``Sometimes when we're scheduled for labs we can't get
computers. You just stand around and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the hands-on lab work, DeVry's formula calls for
students to plunge immediately into their areas of concentration.
The formula also calls for them to attend three 15-week semesters a
year _ basically year round. Students must be in school five hours
a day, five days a week, and virtually every minute in classes and
labs is accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   That approach appeals to many students. Duke, who is 20 and in
his first semester of study to be an electronics technician,
transferred to DeVry from City University's New York City Technical
College after repeatedly failing CUNY's writing examination.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeVry is more expensive (about $4,400 a semester, vs.
$1,600 for New York residents at a CUNY senior college), Duke said
he was attracted by the hands-on learning and the year-round
schedule, which will let him earn an associate's degree in less
than two years. ``I knew I could finish in a certain time and get
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Qureshi, a 21-year-old student from Pakistan who wants to
be an information technology consultant, transferred to DeVry from
Hudson County Community College in New Jersey to follow his
favorite professor, Eli Weissman. He said he found DeVry ``much
faster and up to date'' than Hudson, and liked being able to take
more computer courses and fewer general education courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Hudson, I would have graduated in June with an associate's
degree,'' he said. ``Now I'll graduate in another year with a
bachelor's degree.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Nalisha Bhimsingh came to DeVry from her native Trinidad after
hearing about it from a cousin in Canada. Now in the fourth
semester of the five-semester electronics technician program, she
works as a tutor and lab assistant and expects to earn her
associate's degree in June.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that DeVry works for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Fong, who transferred to DeVry from the State University at
Buffalo, said he had been attracted by DeVry's smaller classes and
fewer general education requirements. But after a year, he said, he
told the dean that DeVry was not offering the courses he needed and
that some of the teachers were not very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that I don't have to take too many courses that
don't pertain to my interests,'' Fong said. ``But it's more narrow
than I expected.'' He said some of his classmates had left and he
was considering leaving, too.
</P>
<P>
   DeVry executives will not talk about dropout rates for any
single campus, but they say the national graduation rate is close
to 40 percent, in line with national averages.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen says that as the college grows, it will expand its
offerings, making it more attractive. In the meantime, he has his
sights set on the college's first graduation, in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
