u a BC-OBIT-ANDERSON-NYT &LR;      01-12 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ANDERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERVIS ANDERSON, 67, WRITER FOR NEW YORKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jervis Anderson, a staff writer for The New Yorker
for 30 years and a leading chronicler of African-American life best
known for his biographies of A. Philip Randolph and Bayard Rustin,
died sometime over the Christmas and New Year holidays at his home
here. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently died of natural causes, according to Ellen
Borakove, a spokeswoman for the New York City medical examiner. His
body was found Jan. 7 after neighbors noticed newspapers and mail
piling up.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's most recent book, ``Bayard Rustin: Troubles I've
Seen,'' a biography of the civil rights advocate who played a
leading role in organizing the 1963 March on Washington, made the
New York Times best-seller list in 1997. In reviewing the biography
in The Times Book Review, Alan Brinkley, a professor of history at
Columbia University, wrote of Anderson: ``He provides the first
thorough account of Rustin's life and career, and he suggests how
Rustin became so eminent a figure without ever becoming a genuine
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was born in Jamaica, then a British colony, on Oct. 1,
1932. He attended the Kingston Technical School at Kingston's
University of the West Indies. He worked as a reporter for The
Daily Gleaner, the island's leading newspaper, and as a young man
became part of the circle around independence leader Michael
Manley. He wrote frequently for Public Opinion, a weekly magazine
edited by Manley's father, N.W. Manley.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson moved to New York in 1958 to attend New York
University, where he studied with philosopher Sidney Hook. In the
early 1960s he began to write for publications associated with New
York intellectual life, including Commentary and Dissent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Anderson became a staff writer for The New Yorker,
where he remained until his retirement in 1998. For most of that
time, he was the magazine's only black staff writer.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrik Hertzberg, senior editor at The New Yorker, who was a
friend and colleague of Anderson for 31 years, said that Anderson
was one of the last of a breed, ``the independent intellectual and
a man of letters.'' Hertzberg added, ``Without academic or
university affiliation, and with very little financial reward, he
followed his nose, his heart and his mind wherever they took him.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Anderson made a splash when his profile of A. Philip
Randolph, the labor and civil rights leader and Harlem Renaissance
figure, ran in three successive issues of The New Yorker. Published
as a book the following year, ``A. Philip Randolph: A Biographical
Portrait'' remains in print and is considered the definitive work
to date on Randolph, the founder and longtime president of the
Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing an exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
1969 about Harlem's cultural history, Anderson wrote: ``To the
majority of blacks who are attracted by it, a yearning for Harlem
is akin to the call of home: where struggling, hoping, speaking,
loving, laughing, dancing, singing and sharing in the rich fund of
black American myth produce a sense of common experience, style and
cause; a place, too, where eyes and faces and gestures speak a
language so familiar that it registers not so much in the brains as
in the bones.''
</P>
<P>
   At The New Yorker, Anderson also wrote a four-part series of
articles on the cultural history of Harlem, published in book form
in 1982 as ``This Was Harlem: A Cultural Portrait, 1900-1950,'' In
the 90's, his articles for the magazine included profiles of Derek
Walcott, the Nobel Prize-winning poet; Cornel West, the scholar and
writer, and Wynton Marsalis, the jazz musician. David Remnick,
editor of The New Yorker, said, ``One of the most unforgettable
pieces he ever published here was a long profile of Ralph Ellison
in which he went back to Oklahoma with Ellison and painted the
deepest portrait of an extremely private man.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his books on Randolph, Rustin and Harlem,
Anderson was the author of ``Guns in American Life,'' a
journalistic study of America's fascination with firearms.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson's retirement from The New Yorker in 1998, he
remained active as a writer and scholar. At the time of his death,
he was working on a book about the young manhood of novelist Ralph
Ellison and a memoir of his own youth in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
