<HEADLINE>
OBITUARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerome Goldstein, 77, Founder Of a Furniture Polish Company &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Goldstein, who built a modest business selling a homemade
wood restorer into a multimillion-dollar, publicly traded company
called Scott's Liquid Gold, died Jan. 15 in Denver. He was 77 and
lived in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was large-cell lymphoma, said his son, Mark
Goldstein, the president and chief executive of the Denver company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, Goldstein's mother, Ida, bought the formula for Scott's
Liquid Gold, a type of furniture polish, from a door-to-door
salesman for $350; the salesman had acquired it from a chemist, Lee
Scott, who developed it early in the century.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein and his two brothers began mixing and bottling the
liquid in a small garage in East Denver and sold it door to door. A
year later, Goldstein took the company public, and since then it
has expanded and developed new products like air fresheners and
cosmetics. .
</P>
<P>
   For several years, the company also owned the Aquafilter Corp.,
one of the world's largest manufacturers of cigarette filters.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped down as president and chief executive of Scott's in
1990 but retained the title of chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein was born on Sept. 23, 1922, in Denver and attended the
University of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Goldie, died in 1998. Besides his son, Goldstein
is survived by his second wife, Shirley Francis Goldstein; two
daughters, Leslee Brooks, of Encino, Calif., and Teri Owen, of
Manhattan; two brothers, Ivan Goldstein and Max Goldstein, both of
Jerusalem, and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Marcantonio Vilaca, 38; Art Dealer Promoted Brazilians
</P>
<P>
   Marcantonio Vilaca, an art dealer whose gallery in Sao Paolo was
as instrumental in introducing European and North American artists
to South America as it was in promoting young South American
artists abroad, died Jan. 1 at his parents' home in Recife, Brazil.
He was 38.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said Karla Meneghel Ferraz de
Camargo, Vilaca's partner.
</P>
<P>
   Vilaca was born in Recife in 1962 and began collecting at the
age of 15. He graduated from Mackenzie University in Sao Paulo in
1985, majoring in law. Vilaca began his art career in the late
1980s, working first as director of Galeria Algodoeira Palmceirense
and then as co-owner of Galeria Passargada de Arte Contemporanca,
both in Sao Paulo. In 1992 he opened Galerie Camargo Vilaca with
Ms. Camargo. The gallery promoted, often with first shows, such
internationally known Brazilian artists as Beatriz Milhazes,
Ernesto Neto, Valeska Soares, Jac Leiner and Adriana Varejao.
Artists from the United States and Europe who had their first South
American exhibitions at Camargo Vilaca included Charles Long,
Fabian Marcaccio, Juan Usle, Pedro Cabrita Reis and Saint Clair
Cemin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his parents, Maria and Marcos Vilaca, he is
survived by a sister, Taciana Vilaca Bezerra of Recife, and a
brother, Rodrigo, of Sao Paulo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
