<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CONTEST FOR CONSERVATIVE VOTERS, 4 REPUBLICANS SHOWCASE A
CONSERVATIVE EDGE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reflecting the growing competition for the party's most
ideologically conservative voters, four of the Republican
presidential contenders are unveiling new television advertisements
emphasizing conservative positions on issues like abortion and
offering the harshest critiques to date on the Clinton
administration's moral authority and record on the military.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four, Sens. John McCain of Arizona and Orrin Hatch of
Utah, take on President Clinton in perhaps the toughest language of
the campaign on the airwaves. In a new McCain commercial running in
South Carolina, Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., one of the managers of
President Clinton's impeachment trial, calls the senator ``the
conservative who will stop Bill Clinton's betrayal of our
military.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, in a 28-minute speech in the form of an advertisement,
says the stewardship of Clinton and Vice President Al Gore may be
remembered ``as the most deceitful and corrupt in our nation's
history.'' The video is scheduled to debut Wednesday night on
WMUR-TV in Manchester, N.H., and will also run in Des Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements arrive in the midst of a intensifying
struggle among the candidates over who has the truest claim to be
the standard-bearer for conservatives, a group that votes in
disproportionately high numbers in primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher Steve Forbes has a new 30-second spot in Iowa
devoted exclusively to his stand against abortion. And in Texas
Gov. George W. Bush's latest commercial, which begins running
Wednesday in South Carolina, the closing slogan, ``A fresh start
for America,'' has been modified to ``Conservative values, and a
fresh start for America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been talking about values and the compassionate
conservative agenda,'' said Mark McKinnon, Bush's media adviser.
``It's really just marrying the governor's agenda on values and his
conservative background.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial is the latest in Bush's rapidly expanding
national advertising campaign. McKinnon said the candidacy this
week added two more states, Virginia and Washington _ which hold
primaries on Feb. 29 _ that bring to eight the number in which Bush
is running commercials.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, McCain has concentrated his media buys in three
states with early primaries, New Hampshire, South Carolina and
Michigan, while Forbes is spending most of his money in two, Iowa
and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, McCain, a prisoner of war in Vietnam, has
counted on building a base of support among the state's many
military retirees. In the new commercial, Graham says that McCain
``showed us what honor really means, a value we respect in South
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood up for our families, with a 17-year pro-life voting
record, and has voted to take pornography off the Internet,'' the
congressman continues. ``John McCain will bring honor back to the
Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot, Bush campaign officials say, is in stark contrast to
the less ideological image McCain has projected in his
advertisements in New Hampshire, where, for example, he has not
emphasized his position on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very seriously doubt he'd run that spot on WMUR in New
Hampshire, or on `Ally McBeal,''' said Stuart Stevens, one of
Bush's media advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's new spot seems designed as a message to McCain's intended
base in South Carolina. In the commercial, titled ``Respect,''
images of older people alternate with shots of Bush in front of a
large American flag. One interlude has an older man in veteran's
uniform standing by a flagpole, raising a flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our greatest generation deserves our greatest respect,'' Bush
says, a reference to a phrase popularized by Tom Brokaw's
best-seller about World War II and the soldiers who fought it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
