<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ROUND ONE AT SHEPHERDSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Jan. 12:
</P>
<P>
   The first round of peace talks between Israel and Syria got off
to a grindingly slow start in Shepherdstown, W.Va., before
adjourning this week. But there is still a good chance of meeting
the deadline, set by Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, for a
broad peace agreement late this year. For that to happen Syria will
have to do more to show that it is prepared to offer Israel
friendly relations and special security guarantees in exchange for
the return of all or most of the strategically valuable Golan
Heights. Thus far, Damascus has wanted to talk only about
territory. Its attitude toward these other essential dimensions of
peace has been chilly and unpromising.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Syria's foreign minister, Farouk al-Shara, plan to
return for further talks next week. In the initial sessions, both
sides played to public opinion back home, advertising their
determination to defend national interests. That was necessary,
particularly in the case of Israel, where any agreement will be
submitted to a public referendum. But having staked out their
opening positions, both sides should return to the talks prepared
to show some flexibility as well.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has said that the depth of its withdrawal from the Golan
will correspond to the strength of the security guarantees it
receives from Syria and to Syria's willingness to offer real peace.
The Barak government has also suggested that Israel would withdraw
no further than the internationally recognized boundary between
British Palestine and French Syria established after World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, for its part, has insisted on a return to the unofficial
boundary that existed before the June 1967 Mideast war. That line
runs some 30 feet farther west, giving Syria access to the Sea of
Galilee, Israel's largest reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has the stronger legal case. Drawing the border where
Syria wants would let Damascus keep the territory it took by force
in the first two decades of Israel's existence while requiring
Israel to surrender everything it took by force in 1967. But any
agreement on borders needs to reflect contemporary political needs,
not just legal history. Adjustments in one direction or another
could be justified by other elements of a comprehensive deal.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, meanwhile, needs to recognize that Israel must retain the
ability to get early warning of Syrian military movements,
information Israel now gets from its monitoring stations atop the
heights. If Israel withdraws, such intelligence will have to come
from an American or international force stationed on the heights,
perhaps with some Israeli participants. Syria also must extend full
recognition to Israel, halting bellicose government propaganda and
denying sanctuary to violent Palestinian groups.
</P>
<P>
   Progress in the first round was mainly limited to getting
Israelis and Syrians to meet and refine their disputes about the
negotiating agenda. Even then, it took several personal
interventions by President Clinton to keep the talks going. Next
week the two sides should begin to tackle some of the underlying
issues. Despite substantial opposition in Israel to a Golan deal,
Barak's ultimate willingness to compromise is not in serious doubt.
On his return to Israel on Tuesday night, he offered a relatively
optimistic assessment of the talks. But for these to succeed,
Shara's boss, President Hafez Assad, must prove equally willing to
make trade-offs in the interest of peace.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 0026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
