r a BC-CENSUS-CALIFORNIA-LAD     01-12 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-CALIFORNIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS UNVEIL NEW CENSUS PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BILL HILLBURG 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stung by criticism that a 1990 undercount cost
California about $2.2 billion in federal funding over the decade,
Census Bureau officials on Tuesday unveiled a new program designed
to increase response to the mail-in effort that begins in March.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, ``How America Knows What America Needs,''
information kits will be sent to thousands of civic leaders
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   From March 27 to April 11, the Census Bureau will post response
rates, updated daily, for thousands of cities on two Internet sites
(www.census.gov and www.HAKWAN.com).
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt expressed confidence that
the program would result in a 5 percentage point increase over 1990
census' 65 percent in California and nationwide mail response rate
a 5 point drop from the 1980 response.
</P>
<P>
   Census forms will be mailed to 100 million households nationwide
in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Some 83 percent of all households will receive a short form
asking basic demographic questions. The remaining 17 percent will
be asked to fill out more detailed long forms.
</P>
<P>
   Households that do not respond by April 11 will be canvassed by
enumerators, or census takers, from late April through early July.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, response rates to the 1990 mailed census
surveys were generally higher in upper- and middle-income
communities and dropped in those with lower-income residents and
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The best response rates were posted by La Canada Flintridge (85
percent) and Thousand Oaks and Westlake Village (both 80 percent).
Vernon (39 percent) and Compton (49 percent) had the region's
lowest response rates.
</P>
<P>
   Other 1990 census response levels included Los Angeles (60
percent), Long Beach (63 percent), San Bernardino (59 percent),
West Covina (69 percent), Pasadena (68 percent), Santa Clarita (69
percent), San Fernando (67 percent), Ontario (61 percent), Downey
(73 percent) and Lompoc (67 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt blamed the declining response on ``the public's
indifference and cynicism about civic responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is committed to doing a better job of counting the
poor and immigrants. To do that, the bureau is hiring thousands of
census takers from ethnic communities to canvass neighborhoods and
urge participation.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for California, with about 40 percent of the
nation's 25 million foreign-born residents, many undocumented.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, undercounts ranging from 7 percent to 10 percent were
estimated among Southern California's Latinos, Asians and
African-Americans, including a shortfall of 50 percent in Long
Beach's large Cambodian community.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials, who estimated an overall undercount of
5.1 percent and a loss of $104 million in federal funding, later
joined with other cities in an unsuccessful court challenge of 1990
census data.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the census, which is also used to determine reapportion
congressional districts, cost California one seat.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates for the 2000 census predict a gain of two House seats.
</P>
<P>
   A state Department of Finance found that in July 1997 those
overlooked mainly came from the fast-growing minority population.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990-97, Latinos increased from 7.7 million to 9.6 million,
raising their percentage of the state's total population of 33
million from 26 percent to 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian population rose from 2.7 million to 3.6 million during
the same period, up from 9 percent to 11 percent of the state
total.
</P>
<P>
   The number of whites was unchanged at 17 million, but the
percentage fell from 57 percent to 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The African-American population remained at 2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The state survey found Latinos and Asians are the fastest
growing groups in Los Angeles, San Bernardino, Ventura and Santa
Barbara counties.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 census will feature several innovations, including
filing the short form via the Internet. Two statistical methods,
one for determining federal funding levels and the other to
determine House reapportionment, will be used.
</P>
<P>
   For federal funding, traditional methods of mail-in
questionnaires and canvassing should come up with 90 percent of the
total count. The rest will be tallied by the block sampling, which
used trends to possibly cut the undercount in half.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans successfully sued last year to force
use of mailed forms and canvassing for all reapportionment data.
Critics claimed the GOP was worried sampling would help Democrats
by increasing the tally of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 2000 census will do a better job of racial and ethnic
identification. Respondents, formerly limited to choosing a single
ethnic category out of six choices, will now be able to check any
and all categories that fit their personal multiracial and
multiethnic profiles.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
