A3438 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     01-12 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS DEAL SELVES, GRIFFEY A BETTER HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Aaron Sele ``falls like a star out of the sky'' and
lands prominently in the Mariners rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Gillick gets a phone call from Sele's agent Monday morning
saying the Northwest native is urgently awaiting an offer from the
Mariners. The call comes a week after Gillick thought Sele was
completely lost to the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   As if signing John Olerud, Arthur Rhodes, Mark McLemore, Stan
Javier and Kazuhiro Sasaki weren't enough proof that the new
general manager is here to improve the Mariners, Gillick has the
luck of stealing a 29-year-old free-agent prize out from under
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   If only the Mariners had had this kind of mindset, checkbook and
aggressive will last winter. Maybe then, at least some of the
Gillick's unfinished and less pleasant business would not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if the M's had had a more competitive team in 1999, Ken
Griffey Jr. would have spent more time chasing the AL West pennant
and less time pondering his future _ one he eventually told the
Mariners did not include Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That was November. Now it's January. So much has happened in
terms of player transactions for the M's, yet bottom line, one
critical scenario remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mariners fans have speculated that Griffey might be cheered
by all these signings that have brought closers, speed and some
versatility. That does not seem to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for all the moves Gillick has made to improve the
Mariners, they all bump up against this immovable object called
``The Griffey Situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an odd mix. On the one hand, there is all this good
feeling about deals that seem to bolster the M's. On the other
hand, there is all this weirdness and speculation about the team if
Griffey stays or goes.
</P>
<P>
   The center fielder says he will come back and play out the final
year of his contract. This comes after Griffey's list of teams to
which he said he would accept a trade dwindled from seven to four
to one.
</P>
<P>
   If Griffey will still accept a trade to the Reds, the Mariners
seem quite willing to investigate what must be their limited
options in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Gillick confirmed that someone from the Mariners front
office has been in touch with a senior Reds' official, though not
general manager Pat Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   If the Reds have any sort of deal in mind, the Mariners have
said they want to hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some conversations _ the organization has _ fairly
recently,'' Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   A trade before spring training is still possible but far from
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a dead issue for me,'' Gillick said about trading
Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go back to the joint statement that was issued for
what Kenny's desires were. We're still taking into consideration
what he wants to do. Even though something hasn't happened now,
we're still proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm going to say is that we're going to try, as it was
mentioned in the joint statement, to comply with Kenny's request
and try and get him closer to home.''
</P>
<P>
   Since November, when the M's and Griffey met in Florida and were
told about his long-term goals, Griffey's feelings of benevolence
toward the Mariners appears to have changed.
</P>
<P>
   In December, he took extreme exception to off-hand remarks
attributed to Gillick during the owners meetings. Later, another
unnamed Mariner official told a newspaper Griffey is acting like a
``spoiled brat.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever high hopes Griffey had for a smooth transition to
wherever it is he really wanted to go have blown up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gillick said despite Griffey's anger toward him, the
lines of communication remain open. Griffey, at least though his
agent, is exchanging notes and ideas, especially since the M's have
talked to the Reds again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably Kenny got a little miffed at me when I said he
changes his mind,'' Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think as time goes on, everybody _ ballclubs, the Reds
_ things change. ... Different things happen on clubs that change
their mind. So I would think that changing your mind is an ongoing
process,'' Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this all along, it wasn't my request to go closer to
home. I would be very, very satisfied if Kenny Griffey and Alex
Rodriguez played their entire careers here with the Mariners. ...
Those are the types of players you look for, players with those
types of skill levels.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gillick is trying to soft-peddle the intent of his earlier
comments regarding Griffey, it may be too late. Griffey, notorious
for his self-described elephant-like memory, is hard-pressed to
forgive and forget _ even if it would help get him wherever it is
he wants to be quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Gillick wheels and deals wisely with a healthy Mariner
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had told both of our All-Star players, both Griffey and
Alex Rodriguez as well as Edgar (Martinez) and Olerud, that we were
going to improve this team. So I guess the best way to prove it is
to do it. So I guess you can say we've put our money where our
mouth is,'' Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   As of January, it sure seems that what was once Griffey's team
has become Gillick's team.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
