</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COURTS-FAVORITISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI INVESTIGATING FAVORITISM IN BROOKLYN COURTS, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal investigators have begun an inquiry into in
an unusual letter that surfaced in Brooklyn political circles last
month hinting that party loyalties and court-appointed legal work
in the borough's court system go hand in hand, two officials
familiar with investigation said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, refused
to provide specific details about the inquiry stemming from the
letter, which was written by two lawyers with strong ties to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The officials stressed that the investigation was in its
earliest stages. Word of it came a day after the state's top judge,
Judith S. Kaye, announced that she was appointing a special
investigator to check on allegations that judges favor lawyers with
strong political ties when granting court receiverships or
surrogate work throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Court watchdog groups have long voiced despair over the
potential for favoritism in a system in which party leaders hold
great sway over which judges are placed on the ballot. In recent
days, the issue has focused on Brooklyn, where a nomination to the
bench by the Democratic Party is tantamount to election.
</P>
<P>
   According to the two officials, the current investigation stems
from a letter written on Dec. 20 by two Democratic Party loyalists,
Thomas J. Garry and Arnold J. Ludwig. In their letter, which was
sent to more than 40 Democratic Party officials in Brooklyn, the
two men bitterly complained that a fellow lawyer, who holds no
party office, had excluded them from a sizable court-awarded
assignment despite their ``unquestioned'' fidelity to the party for
more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer accused in the letter, Ravi Batra, has defended
himself by saying that he fired the two men as legal advisers in
handling the affairs of a failed cemetery in Brooklyn because they
were trying to ``churn legal fees to the detriment of the estate.''
As the court-appointed receiver for the property, the Cypress Hills
Cemetery, Batra said he had a responsibility to protect the
estate's assets, and asserted that he acted correctly by dismissing
Ludwig and Garry.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three men returned phone calls Tuesday seeking
comment. David Bookstaver, a spokesman for the state's Office of
Court Administration, said he no knowledge of the federal
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 0041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
