<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT H. CRAFT, 93, LONGTIME SECURITIES INDUSTRY EXECUTIVE
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Ariz.)  (nk) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert H. Craft, a prominent international investment banker in
the 1950s and '60s, died on Dec. 26 at his home in Carefree, Ariz.,
near Phoenix. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   In a 50-year career that began a month before the stock market
crash of October 1929, Craft held executive and consulting
positions in international finance, including the presidency of the
Paribas Corp. in New York and of Chase Manhattan Bank's overseas
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Craft was born on Feb. 9, 1906, in Cedarhurst, N.Y. He began his
career with the Guaranty Trust Co. of New York, a predecessor of
the Morgan Guaranty Trust Co., after graduation from the Wharton
School of the University of Pennsylvania in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   He rose from bond analyst to vice president and treasurer at the
company. In 1953, he took a leave of absence to accept an
appointment as a technical consultant to the Federal Reserve's
rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There, Craft was instrumental in developing the ``bills only''
policy, which holds that the Fed should try to influence only
short-term interest rates, those paid on Treasury bills, letting
market forces decide long-term rates, paid on bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Craft did not return to Guaranty Trust after the Fed appointment
ended. Instead, from 1953 to 1956, he was executive vice president
of the American Securities Corp., an investment bank. In 1956, he
became president and later vice chairman of the Chase International
Investment Corp., the overseas financing unit of Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1960, Craft was named president and chairman of the
executive committee of the Paribas Corp., then the U.S. investment
banking subsidiary of the Banque de Paris et des Pays-Bas, the
largest financial institution in France not owned by the
government. He served in those posts until 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, he became chairman of the finance committee of the
Missouri Pacific Railroad. He stayed with the railroad until 1975,
also serving as chairman of its parent company, the Mississippi
River Corp., from 1971 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Craft was also a consultant to the World Bank, served on the
boards of numerous corporations and, in 1956-57 was president of
the Investment Bankers Association, the predecessor of the
Securities Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Before moving to Arizona in the mid-'70s, Craft was a longtime
resident of Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Janet; two sons, Robert Jr., of
Washington and George, of Houston; a daughter, Carol Schaefer, of
Greenwich, Conn.; and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 0045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
