<HEADER>
A3449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HISTORY-TEACHERS-EDUC     01-12 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-TEACHERS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASS ACT IS SNUFFED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (bl)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERSET, Mass. _ Robert Crouch and Paul McManus taught the same
class together in the same room at Somerset High School for 30
years, longer than many marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Somerset, 30 miles west of Cape Cod, knew that
whatever educational fads came and went, the subject examined by
Crouch and McManus never varied: American history from the colonies
to the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was a graduate school course in the 10th grade, one in
which the only textbooks were primary source documents like John
Smith's account of the Jamestown settlement and George Washington's
correspondence. The two teachers cross-examined students as if they
were on trial and demanded that they ``refute, support or respond
to'' quotations from leading historians.
</P>
<P>
   This school year, however, like the producers of a long-running
Broadway show closed before its time, Crouch and McManus had to end
their class. The reason: it did not fit the new curriculum
guidelines issued by Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The state says that American history before 1865 should be
taught in the eighth grade. Tenth-graders, the state suggests,
should be taught world history from 1815 to the present. That
course is a sequel to the recommended ninth-grade course, on world
history from the fall of Rome to 1815.
</P>
<P>
   Although school districts are not bound by the frameworks, the
state test at the end of eighth grade is on American history
through the Civil War; the test at the end of 10th grade requires
two years of world history.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch and McManus are committed to teaching high school, and
are not sure that eighth graders can handle their course. So they
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do mourn the class,'' McManus said. ``It was so much fun to
teach. Every year, you'd do additional reading. You'd add a new
source, a new document. And then Crouchie and I would go at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are quick to say that the overall standards movement,
which spawned the Massachusetts frameworks, is a vast improvement
over what existed before: an absence of any articulated
expectations of what students should know. In Massachusetts, for
example, state requirements for high school graduation before this
year were four years of physical education and a year of American
history. Forty-nine states now have, or are writing, guidelines on
what should be taught when.
</P>
<P>
   But as with any innovation, however well-intentioned, something
always gets lost in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   I say this not as an impartial observer. I took ``Crouch and
McManus,'' as their course was known, almost two decades ago. For
me, it was like watching Bjorn Borg and John McEnroe at Wimbledon
and then taking tennis lessons from them afterward. The way they
taught that course made me want to be a nonfiction writer _ one who
writes, more often than not, about learning.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent, New-England-gray afternoon, I joined Crouch and
McManus at T.K. O'Malley's, a sports bar across the Taunton River
from Somerset High. Over 20-ounce glasses of beer, they recalled
their decisions to become teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, it turns out, was able to look out at his own high
school graduation and see his father. McManus, who grew up in a
Fall River housing project, watched his father go off to World War
II and never return. Crouch, reared in the projects of Dorchester
and Roxbury, lost his father, a railroad car inspector, in an
accident on the Boston &AMP; Maine.
</P>
<P>
   McManus thought he might change the world from the front of a
classroom. Crouch was thinking more about the handful of very good
teachers he had had _ and the larger roster of bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after they joined the faculty at Somerset High, they
combined their two 25-student classes into one room, the better for
the students to hear alternating points of view.
</P>
<P>
   They are warhorses now, at least in their profession _ McManus
is 57, Crouch 55 _ and yet they are starting over: just as they
have for three decades, they are back in Room 310. This time,
though, like immigrants learning a new language, they are teaching
world history.
</P>
<P>
   To recreate what they once had, they are working overtime _
Crouch took a college refresher course; McManus is often reading a
chapter ahead of the class _ studying primary sources like ``The
Communist Manifesto'' and then wielding them to sharpen students'
critical thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just last week, I was doing a class on Italian unification,''
McManus said. ``I was talking about Mazzini and Garibaldi, and I'm
talking about Victor Emmanuel and Cavour, and Napoleon III and
Bismarck, and all of a sudden I wasn't sure what I was talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked over at Crouchie and said, `Help!' ''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, he added, ``It was wonderful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 0046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
