<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NEWZEALAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BOATS STAY IN CONTENTION FOR LAST SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ On a day when the winds blew with
authority and the waves splashed over the bows and rails of the
competing yachts, the Prada Challenge and Stars and Stripes both
managed to win and keep pace with each other for the remaining spot
in the America's Cup challenger final.
</P>
<P>
   Prada defeated Le Defi Francais by just 9 seconds, holding on in
the final leg against the French boat Sixth Sense, the fastest boat
downwind in Auckland. Stars and Stripes had a less stressful time
down the stretch, defeating America True by 46 seconds to get its
first victory against its fellow Californians in four attempts.
</P>
<P>
   With one race remaining, Prada has 6 points; Stars and Stripes
has 5 points with two races remaining. No matter which team
qualifies, its opponent in the next round is certain because
America One, which represents the St. Francis Yacht Club in San
Francisco, clinched its place Wednesday with a 17-second victory
over the Japanese syndicate, Nippon Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave Paul Cayard's crew its eighth victory in nine
starts in these challenger semifinals. Its only defeat came in its
second race when it suffered a jib breakdown against America True.
But just as Cayard's syndicate rebounded in style from some
personnel defections and fund-raising concerns in the preparatory
phases of its campaign, America One rebounded from that equipment
breakdown, as well. And now the team and its new, versatile boat
USA 61 will be favored to win the right to face Team New Zealand in
the America's Cup defense in February.
</P>
<P>
   Even though America One won't race again under pressure until
Jan. 25, when the challengers final is set to begin, it still has a
role to play on the water in these semifinals. Its last race in
this round is scheduled for Thursday against Stars and Stripes, but
it remains to be seen whether Cayard will risk his men and material
in a race of no importance to his syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting,'' said Stars and Stripes tactician Tom
Whidden. ``If it's pretty windy, I'd be surprised if he came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard agreed. ``I might make the call in the morning.'' he
said. `` It's a tough call. I don't want to jeopardize my assets. I
don't have as many masts as Prada.''
</P>
<P>
   Prada will face Nippon, now eliminated, in its final race. Stars
and Stripes is scheduled to face America One and then America True
again in a makeup race for one postponed because of repair work to
Stars and Stripes' transom.
</P>
<P>
   If Prada and Stars and Stripes sweep their remaining races, both
will finish with 7 points, which would force a one-race sail-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty amazing,'' said Stars and Stripes helmsman Ken
Read. ``Who would have guessed this on Sept. 1 when we sailed this
boat for the first time?''
</P>
<P>
   Stars and Stripes did indeed get a much later start than its
primary competitors, but its nonracing skipper, Dennis Conner, has
plenty of America's Cup experience and plenty of friends from New
Zealand who have helped him study the local weather and conditions.
Wednesday, Conner gave his crew another motivational speech over
breakfast, the latest in a series in this round.
</P>
<P>
   The weather conditions were also motivational for Stars and
Stripes, whose boat, USA-55, is relatively sturdy and relatively
wide in comparison to its rivals and thrives in stronger winds. The
winds reached speeds of up to 23 knots on course Wednesday and the
sea conditions were choppier than at any other time during this
round.
</P>
<P>
   But America True, just like the French, did not race Wednesday
like a team that has already been eliminated. After the second
windward mark, Stars and Stripes led by 24 seconds, but when
Whidden and the afterguard changed spinnaker sets late in the beat,
the crew had difficulty reacting quick enough and several precious
seconds elapsed before their chute finally opened.
</P>
<P>
   At the next mark, the lead was only seven seconds but then Stars
and Stripes pulled away upwind, gaining nearly a minute in the
heavy conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Prada also had spinnaker problems, fouling up a complicated drop
at the first leeward mark and getting the spinnaker hung up in its
mast. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
