<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GEORGE PATAKI, CENTRIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Jan. 12.:
</P>
<P>
   With his new $76.8 billion budget for the next fiscal year, Gov.
George Pataki has proposed again to tap New York State's huge
surpluses for modest spending increases and tax cuts, building on
his increasingly centrist politics of the last couple of years. The
major exception to that approach is in school aid, for which Pataki
recommended a package that shortchanges New York City and is
certain to provoke a battle in the Legislature. In a welcome
gesture to fiscal prudence, the governor also recommended setting
aside more than $2 billion in surpluses generated by boom times as
reserves for future use, and he endorsed a constitutional amendment
to curb state borrowing and restore the state's abysmal credit
rating.
</P>
<P>
   There have been fights over school aid every year since Pataki
took office in 1995, and this one immediately looked familiar as
the Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, vowed to restore cuts in
funds for preschool, teacher pay and smaller classes in New York
City. The governor countered that he was actually increasing school
aid over all by $355 million, but his budget aides conceded that
the city would get less than 29 percent of this money even though
it has 37 percent of the state's pupils. Pataki apparently
calculates that no matter how much aid he puts in for the city, the
Legislature will always try to raise the ante, so it makes sense to
start with a low figure. But these fights create an atmosphere of
debilitating hostility when the need in the city is so great.
</P>
<P>
   A complicating factor in this year's fight is politics. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani is gearing up to run for Senate against Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who may announce her candidacy as early as next
month. Silver, an ardent Democrat who supports Mrs. Clinton, will
somehow have to work with the mayor to win more aid. Giuliani, who
tried to block the appointment of Harold Levy as schools chancellor
on the ground that he was too close to Silver, also needs to set
aside his antipathy for the speaker to do what is best for the
city. In the end, presidential politics may persuade Pataki to make
more money available to avoid undercutting the education message of
his presidential candidate, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's recommendation to curb the state's debt contains
an especially important proposal to end a disguised form of
borrowing that began in the Rockefeller years and is now spiraling
out of control. Under a plan that would have to be approved by two
sessions of the Legislature and then the voters, the state would
have to disclose all its borrowing schemes and cap them at a low
level. In making this reform, the Legislature has to make sure that
Pataki does not cap borrowing at such a low level that it would
hurt the state's ability to meet its infrastructure needs in a
decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   After five years in office, Pataki has emerged more and more as
a moderate Republican. He has backed several environmental projects
and in December worked out a deal with the Democrats to raise
tobacco taxes and use the revenues for health care. This is
expected to be the first year in a long time that will not feature
the usual battles over cuts in Medicaid pushed by the governor.
Despite his tax cuts that could produce deficits if the current
prosperity evaporates, Pataki's recent centrist course marks a
significant change. It shows he is thinking about his political
future and his overall record. It also suggests that the state
Republican Party will be going into the next election as the party
of something other than cutting government across the board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
