<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDER? INSIDER? A LAWYER WINS AS BOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the nonchalant elegance of Astaire, the lawyer Ted Wells
tap dances at the edge of the abyss for his clients _ CEOs and
politicians, mostly. On behalf of a national Cabinet secretary he
addressed a jury for three days, without notes; on behalf of
another, Wells, after having had his way with the 70 witnesses the
federal government had put on the stand, didn't bother putting on
any of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Both times he won acquittals, of course. White-collar
litigators, not typically generous with praise unless they're
looking in the mirror, invariably speak of Wells' record _
recently, seven for seven _ as ``staggering,'' his courtroom
performances ``magnificent,'' and his standing as one of the
``premier trial lawyers in America.''
</P>
<P>
   So why, in conversation the other day, was he being so cautious?
</P>
<P>
   For just when a topic would take flight, he would bring it back
to earth _ deftly, with a toothy smile _ and order it off the
record, or retool it with tamped-down language. You could almost
see him weighing every remark against the reaction of all the
constituencies who may be taking notice, because of his new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little nervous,'' said Wells, on his sixth day at Paul,
Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, where he is the first outsider
in 30 years to be brought in as a partner. He was not only named
co-chairman of its 150-lawyer litigation department, but is also
expected to revive the luster that dimmed with the passing of its
superstar, Arthur L. Liman, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A tale from his activist days in the black students' movement is
followed by: ``I don't want people to think there's some
rabble-rouser at Paul, Weiss. Don't do that to me!''
</P>
<P>
   Charming grin, apology, explanation of sorts: ``I try to play at
a lot of different levels. I want to do the Microsofts. And my guy
is running for president.'' Wells is campaign treasurer for a
friend of more than 20 years, Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   That layered look is what makes Wells, 49, so intriguing, this
moment such a mix of accolades and agita. In moving from Lowenstein
Sandler, his New Jersey firm for 22 years, to Paul, Weiss, an
international powerhouse, he can compete for the biggest cases in
the country, billing $575 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Wells, a behind-the-scenes force in New Jersey
politics, has moved to a national stage. He has helped raise nearly
$28 million for Bradley, by wheedling and holding fund-raisers at
the Livingston, N.J., home he calls ``my expensive steal,'' where
he lives with Nina, his wife of 28 years, who is also a lawyer.
Their two children are on leave from college to toil for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   His professional ambition and political activism are shaped by
his self-awareness as a role model. He is Paul, Weiss' only black
partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My age group is very sensitive to its responsibilities in
terms of giving back to the African-American community,'' Wells
said. ``As opposed to black people under 35 who say, `I'm doing
this on my own and I don't want to hear about being black.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``My litigation practice has ranged from Michael Milken to Floyd
Flake to Exxon to the NAACP,'' he continued. ``Mike Espy and Ray
Donovan'' _ the former Cabinet secretaries _ ``came to me when they
were in trouble. Great trial lawyers are not limited to a select
group of white males. There's a social value in having
African-American lawyers thought of in that ilk, and it's important
to break the mold.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who attended Holy Cross on a football scholarship and has
a master's in business and a law degree from Harvard, was raised in
Washington on a shoestring by his mother, who worked in a Navy mail
room. Ma Wells, as she is known, attends all his Washington cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``She owns the federal courthouse!'' he said. ``She exudes love.
My mother just embarrasses mean people into being nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Something of that compassionate demeanor translates into her
son's courtroom style, described as approachable and appealing
rather than dazzling and theatrical. To get juries to trust him, he
will concede that his clients have made mistakes, and then argue
why they still deserve to be acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said I love juries, and I believe in unconditional
love,'' said Wells, who is 6 foot 3 with an athlete's energy and
grace. ``And I'll say, `I can't just love you when you vote my way
_ I have to love you however you vote.'''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, making jurors feel guilt-ridden if they find his
clients guilty. ``I haven't just won,''` he said. ``I've won and
had jurors embrace the client. That's the real goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for trials close to home, Wells moves into a hotel, getting
pumped in a high-end bunker with legal briefs, room service and
daily workouts. Next will be the Rihga Royal to prep for the Jan.
24 criminal trial of Dr. Niels Lauersen, a Park Avenue specialist
accused of insurance fraud over billing for infertility treatments,
which are not covered, as standard gynecological care. ``It's a
very difficult case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't turn down cases because the facts are bad,'' said
Wells, who rejected opportunities to be a federal judge or U.S.
attorney _ too staid. He would love to square off against David
Boies, who prosecuted the Microsoft case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet! We're all just big kids,'' Wells said with his bright
grin. ``Bottom line? `Hey, let's draw!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 0057EST &QL; 
