<HEADER>
A3463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     01-12 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BY the time he finished praising Chan Gailey, you wondered why on
earth Jerry Jones had fired him. Oh, yeah, right. Not enough wins.
</P>
<P>
   Firing a coach is one of those exercises that does not get
easier with practice. You think of the French, cutting off the
buttons and epaulets of a disgraced officer while a steady drumbeat
breaks the silence.
</P>
<P>
   Jones drums them out of the corps with kindness. As he announced
the firing Tuesday, he recalled having hired Gailey because he had
``a character beyond reproach,'' and virtues that included
ambition, integrity, seriousness and imagination. He was also
expected to ``put in an offense that fit the personnel that we had,
and I hoped to acquire in the future, so that we could do great
things for the Dallas Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in this latter department that Gailey fell short, failing
to produce the right answers. Jerry needed someone more intuitive,
more inscrutable. He should have hired Charlie Chan.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of the Cowboys has been a source of disenchantment
to the team's fans and of puzzlement to the owner. The Cowboys have
employed four coaches dating to 1960, and under Jones three have
come and gone in the last 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was a perception that the Dallas job had become a
revolving door, he replied, just a tad defensively, ``The other two
changes I've been a part of, I knew those guys for 30 years each
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference was to his former Arkansas soul mates, Jimmy
Johnson, who won back-to-back Super Bowls, and Barry Switzer, who
was never accepted in Dallas but did not prevent the Cowboys from
winning a third ring in the '90s. While it would not be technically
correct to say either was fired, both left with settlements
described as generous.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, in his first official act as the new owner of the team
in 1989, Jones broke the news to Tom Landry that after 29 seasons,
his services were no longer required. A firestorm followed what was
seen as the rude treatment of a legend, and Jones needed years, and
two Super Bowls, to overcome that first impression. He learned, as
most owners do, the difference between honor and dumb.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, you note that Landry needed five seasons before the
Cowboys reached the .500 mark and a sixth before they won more
games than they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine any coach in the NFL getting a grace period of
six years in today's broiling pressure? Jones did not invent the
era of the quick thumb, but he has moved it along. Gailey lasted
two seasons, ending both with playoff losses in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   In what might be seen as an acknowledgment of the turmoil that
has been so much a part of the team's recent history, Jones said:
``This decision was about football.'' It was not, he added, about
egos or clashes or contentiousness or ``friendships gone awry.''
</P>
<P>
   Which of them had control split up the act between the two JJs,
and the troubling image of drugs, guns and girls cut short
Switzer's tenure. Jones gave Gailey credit for helping clean up the
team's act, and the somber ex-coach accepted it. ``I think our guys
understood how to handle themselves,'' he said, ``and I appreciate
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a kind of mea culpa _ at times sounding as if he were
testifying before the House Ethics Committee _ Jones added that the
firing was not about ``a structure that created problems in making
decisions.'' Translation: Gailey's insistence on being his own
offensive coordinator was not a fatal issue.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he sacrificed on the altar of Troy Aikman's discontent,
although at times the quarterback clearly felt restrained by the
offense. The Cowboys lost their last eight road games, including
Sunday's 27-10 defeat at Minnesota. Four of those losses were to
teams that scored only 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say the players undermined me,'' Gailey said. ``I
think they told the truth about what they believed. You think there
are always extenuating circumstances that might play into
decisions. But sometimes you go by the bottom line, and that was
what happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was grateful Jones did not keep him dangling. There were
clearly few other reasons for gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity to be a head coach,'' he said, ``to be in the
NFL, to be with this organization. I'm going to look back on it and
say I learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been a mildly surprising choice, an assistant for 10
years, two as the offense coordinator for the Steelers. His only
head coaching experience had been at Troy State. None of the three
men hired by Jones had held the top job in the NFL, and he would
not discuss his criteria for the next adventurer.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey leaves with his dignity intact, but we never really
got to know him. He was asked if he could envision what he would be
doing today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finish packing,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
