<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 
ROBITAILLE HONORED FOR 1,000th GAME 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Kings left-winger Luc Robitaille was
honored before Tuesday's game for recording his 1,000th career game
during the last road trip.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed his appreciation the only way he knows, scoring his
17th goal of the year in the first period against the Ottawa
Senators and the 534th of his career. That put him 20th all-time,
passing Hall of Famer Frank Mahovalich. Stan Mikita is next at 544
and then Robitaille's boyhood idol, Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard, at
541.
</P>
<P>
   For his 1,000th game, Robitaille was presented two off-road
motorcycles from his teammates, a trip to Hawaii from Kings
management, a crystal trophy from NHL commissioner Gary Bettman and
a painting from the Senators depicting youth hockey in his native
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who was honored last year for scoring his 500th
career goal, said the significance of the individual milestones he
has reached the past two seasons won't mean much until after he
retires.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who turns 34 next month, says the only thing that is
important now is winning a Stanley Cup. Two years after the Kings
reached the finals in 1993 against Montreal, Robitaille was traded
to the Pittsburgh Penguins and then on to the New York Rangers
before returning for the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get as close as we did that year, you realize how
truly special it is,'' Robitaille said. ``You're sure it can happen
again if you just work a little harder, but things change and it
never happens again. Going all the way would be incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille's career has been marked by more than just games and
goals. He has been active in the community and a part-owner of the
Iceoplex skating facility in North Hills, where the Kings train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luc has been the most popular player on this team since the
day he walked in here,'' general manager and former teammate Dave
Taylor said. ``He always has had time for everyone and has been a
great asset to the community. Even though he left here for a few
years, Luc will always be remembered as a King first.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Out awhile: Robitaille scored his goal while playing on the
second line, where he'll remain while Jozef Stumpel is out of the
lineup with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille moved back to the second unit last week when Donald
Audette suffered an ankle sprain and has stayed even though Stumpel
is sidelined. The Kings are now going with a first line of Len
Barrie, who scored two goals on Thursday against Florida, and
Vladimir Tsyplakov.
</P>
<P>
   But there is not doubt Stumpel is missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the Jozef Stumpel from two years ago,'' coach Andy
Murray said. ``The center on the first line is so critical to the
whole team, but injuries have really slowed him. We're hoping to
get him back soon, but he'll probably be out at least another
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, who missed six weeks earlier this season after
abdominal surgery, scored 79 points two seasons ago, including a
team-high 58 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he was slowed by the abdominal problem that carried
over to this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very frustrating because I felt very good after coming
back,'' Stumpel said. ``I sat around so long all I could think
about was being in there and helping the team. Hopefully this won't
be too much longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
