   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIME-MICROSOFT (Undated) _ To the company's adversaries, the
very name ``Microsoft'' suggests menacing power. It has been called
the Death Star, an 800-pound gorilla and worse. And in the
government's sweeping antitrust case, Microsoft was portrayed in
convincing detail as a monopolistic bully. America Online Inc., in
particular, was bent to Microsoft's will, according to court
testimony. But after America Online's move on Monday to buy Time
Warner Inc., the largest merger in history, Microsoft suddenly
seems less threatening. The deal, to be sure, changes none of the
facts in the antitrust case. But antitrust experts say it could
figure into the calculations the court makes on sanctions against
Microsoft, if it loses the case, or in settlement talks. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-IMAGES (Undated) _ Inserting digital images has become
increasingly common in sports and entertainment programming but has
been considered out of line on news shows. Not any more. By Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIME-CULTURE (Undated) _ When Gerald M. Levin, Time Warner's
chairman, urged the assembled press corps earlier this week to
`look at the body language` among the executives on stage as proof
of how harmoniously his company would blend with America Online,
there was an uncomfortable silence. Then Robert W. Pittman,
president of AOL, put his arms around his Time Warner neighbors.
The gesture drew laughter and diffused an awkward moment, but it
did not necessarily provide assurances of a happy cultural mesh. By
Amy Harmon and Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic have been sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIME-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ The merger agreement between AOL
and Time Warner is reverberating throughout the communications and
media industries. But its most important impact on consumers may be
in how it advances the deployment of high-speed Internet access,
enabling people to zip about the Internet at speeds previously
enjoyed mostly by well-heeled businesses. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIME-OLDMEDIA (Undated) _ Does the deal put pressure on
traditional media companies like Times Mirror and the Washington
Post Co., to make a more aggressive push into the Internet? How do
they plan to respond? By Felicity Barringer.
