<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS GIVE WESTPHAL FIRST VICTORY OVER HIS FORMER TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A part of Sonics coach Paul Westphal wants you to
believe it was just another game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the next one will be. But just call the Sonics' 101-88
victory over the Phoenix Suns Tuesday night at KeyArena a slight
exercise in revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The win was Westphal's first in five tries against his former
team since he took control of the Sonics in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd be a little more giddy,'' said Westphal, who was
fired as head coach of the Suns in 1996. ``It's about time, really.
We've played them five times. It's a good win. I'm glad I don't
have to talk about it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal and the Sonics had already lost a Nov. 21 matchup at
Phoenix earlier this season. Phoenix won all three meetings last
season.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was little doubt Tuesday Westphal would finally
down the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' offense ran smoothly and their defense held the
run-and-gun Suns to a crawl. Westphal watched a six-point halftime
lead expand to 13 points late in the third, and the Sonics kept
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   They led by 20 points with 4:08 left in the game after Gary
Payton fed Brent Barry for a fast-break layup. Curiously, Barry,
Payton, Rashard Lewis, Horace Grant and Greg Foster were on the
floor against the Suns' `C' team late in the game with the Sonics
up 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just making sure,'' Westphal said, smiling. ``But it's not any
personal vindication for me.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Sonics have taken to heart are their up-and-down
performances at home.
</P>
<P>
   Their victory against the Suns was characterized by consistent
performances on both ends. The last time the Sonics played in
KeyArena, they blew a 19-point first-half lead and lost to the Los
Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, though, set the tone defensively. He slowed down Suns
point guard Jason Kidd most of the game. Kidd finished with 15
assists, but had just 12 points on 5-for-15 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics disrupted the Suns' offense by forcing other players
to handle the ball. Phoenix settled for jump shots and struggled to
score inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed on our man,'' Payton said. ``We stayed in front of
Jason and made him throw passes over us. This is the first time
we've done this at home in a while. We needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton actually won the point guard duel even though the younger
Kidd has replaced him as the leading vote-getter among Western
Conference guards in All-Star balloting. Payton, who started the
past two All-Star games, is third behind Kidd and Lakers guard Kobe
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, Kidd and Bryant would start. Payton would
likely be added to the West roster by the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   That subplot finished with Payton amassing 23 points and 13
assists in 43 minutes. He turned the ball over just once, which
epitomized the Sonics' offense. They committed just 11 turnovers,
patiently waited for good looks at the basket and shot 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're good offensively and don't turn the ball over and get
decent shots, then (teams) can't get in transition,'' Westphal
said. ``I thought they didn't hurt us very much with their
transition., and they're a great transition team.''
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of ways, the Suns and Sonics mirror each other. Both
teams use small lineups and rely on outside shooting and fast-break
baskets. The Suns have emphasized defense more since Scott Skiles
took over as head coach when Danny Ainge resigned last month.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Suns did little to stop the Sonics from running
toward easy baskets. Barry's aggressiveness translated to 21
points, and the Sonics got a second consecutive quality performance
from Rashard Lewis off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 12 points, including three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very impressed with that young man,'' Westphal said. ``I
mean, in tough situations, he gets bigger and bigger, and that's a
sign of a guy who's got a great future.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Lewis' 3-pointer that put the Sonics ahead for good. They
led 34-33 with 7:37 left in the second. That was the Sonics' first
lead since they went ahead 13-12 in the first.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 25-19 after the first quarter, the Sonics
held a 51-45 advantage at halftime. The Suns never got any closer
than nine points after the third.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had not beaten Phoenix since March 1, 1998, and snapped
a six-game losing streak to the Suns. Westphal, who spent most of
his NBA life in the Suns organization as a player and coach, left
the court smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been in the league a long time, you know you want to
beat your former team,'' Sonics center Horace Grant said. ``We sort
of knew it, but (Westphal) never brought it up.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
