<HEADER>
A3504 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG     01-12 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR LAPSES PROVE COSTLY AGAINST SENATORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Kings had never lost to the Ottawa
Senators in six games at home.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, they couldn't help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Every time they mounted a little momentum, the Kings did their
best to play their worst in a 4-3 loss in front of 14,224 at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they pulled within a goal with 12 minutes left, they
lost Luc Robitaille for the rest of the game with a slashing
penalty and a game misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   It was only one of several indiscretions that caused the Kings
to look more like the team that dropped six straight in December
than the club that recorded a win and a tie in its last two games.
</P>
<P>
   There were the two power-play goals by Ottawa's Joe Juneau they
allowed in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Even after tying the game, the Kings gave up a brutal goal to
former King Scott McEachern in the first minute of the second
period after defenseman Aki Berg fanned on a clearing pass in front
of goaltender Stephane Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes later, Fiset, who had started the last
eight games, was the culprit when Marcus Arvedson scored on a long
goal beyond the right faceoff circle. Fiset was pulled in favor of
Marcel Cousineau, who did not allow another goal.
</P>
<P>
   But the game was lost right there even though the Kings scored
their third goal early in the third period on Mattias Norstrom's
first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators have built a solid season despite a controversial
contract holdout by its best player, Alexei Yashin. They also were
playing the first of back-to-back games in Southern California with
a game tonight against the Mighty Ducks at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the team is for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But in this one, the Kings were the ones who looked distracted.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings seemed to clean up their mess after tying the game in
the final minutes of the first period after dropping behind 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, honored before the game for reaching the 1,000th
game of his career, tied it after the Kings had been outshot 16-1
in the first 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Kings were sluggish and the Senators took
advantage. Juneau's first goal came on a blast from beyond the left
faceoff circle. With Bryan Smolinski off for cross checking, Ottawa
center Radek Bonk cleared the middle, but Juneau's shot struck
Fiset and trickled in with 10:38 gone in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes later, the Kings found themselves in a
similar situation. Robitaille was off for cross checking. This
time, the Senators had three whacks at Fiset, one after the puck
glanced off Berg's skate. Juneau poked the last one in and Ottawa
led 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The second one stirred the Kings for the final 5 1/2 minutes of
the period.
</P>
<P>
   Playing short-handed with Vladimir Tsyplakov off for
interference, captain Rob Blake got things going when he picked up
a Smolinski pass along the right boards and skated into the
Senators end. He then slid before sliding a pass in front to Dan
Bylsma, who beat Patrick Lalime.
</P>
<P>
   With just over a minute left in the period and Ottawa coming off
a penalty kill, Robitaille tied the game at 2. After a blast by
Blake, he missed on the rebound but lifted the puck over Lalime's
left shoulder for his 17th goal.
</P>
<P>
   Things looked good, but not for long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
