A3505 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-NUKINGS-LADN-(SLA     01-12 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NUKINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET ACCEPTS BLAME FOR LOSS TO SENATORS
</HEADLINE>
 ... KINGS WRITETHRU (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even though Stephane Fiset was pulled early in the
second period Tuesday night, he knew there would be a few more
shots fired his way.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood in the Los Angeles Kings' postgame dressing room
after their 4-3 loss to the Ottawa Senators, Fiset took the blame
for his team's worst game since its six-game meltdown last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was my fault, no question,'' said Fiset, who left
just 3:26 into the second period after giving up a long goal to
Marcus Arvedson. ``We need some big saves to keep us in the game
and I just didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset, who was playing his eighth consecutive game since Jamie
Storr suffered a concussion, wasn't tired. The team came in after
four days off and had a win and a tie in its two previous games.
But not only did Fiset play poorly, he had company.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators, who hadn't won in six career tries in Los Angeles,
looked at home in front of 14,224 at Staples Center. They had the
benefit of five power-play opportunities in the first period and
Joe Juneau scored on two of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are the league's most penalized team, Ottawa the
least. The results were predictable and too much to overcome, even
after Fiset left and Mattias Norstrom made it a one-goal game with
12:41 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``No goalie wants to go through that, nobody wants to get
pulled,'' said Fiset. ``But it was the right decision. That's hard
to say, too. We back ourselves into a corner, then built a little
momentum. Then we gave it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Norstrom's goal made it 4-3, but less than a minute later, Luc
Robitaille received two minutes for slashing and a game misconduct
that ended his night.
</P>
<P>
   On the night he was honored for his 1,000th career game,
Robitaille also tied the game at 2-2 with just over a minute left
in the first period. But this was not a game to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kings were outshot 16-1 in the first 15 minutes of
the game, the game was decided early in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Even after tying the game, the Kings gave up a brutal goal to
former King Scott McEachern in the first minute of the second
period after defenseman Aki Berg fanned on a clearing pass in front
of Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a play that can't happen against a team like Ottawa,''
Kings coach Andy Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes later, Fiset was the culprit when
Arvedson scored on a long goal beyond the right faceoff circle.
Fiset was pulled in favor of Marcel Cousineau, who stopped 12 shots
and did not allow another goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators have built a solid season despite a controversial
contract holdout by its best player, Alexei Yashin. They also were
playing the first of back-to-back games in Southern California with
a game tonight against the Mighty Ducks at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and the team is for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But in this one, the Kings were the ones who looked distracted.
They seemed to clean up their mess after tying the game in the
final minutes of the first period after dropping behind 2-0.
Instead of responding to Robitaille's goal, the Kings came out with
their worst hockey since the three-game, 23-goal fiasco in
mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   But it was that way all night. Playing short-handed with
Vladimir Tsyplakov off for interference in the first period,
captain Rob Blake got things going when he picked up a Bryan
Smolinski pass along the right boards and skated into the Senators
end. He then slid before sliding a pass in front to Dan Bylsma, who
beat Patrick Lalime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about turning points, I thought we would have
responded after the short-handed goal,'' Murray said. ``But it
really never happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
