<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-WATER-DISPUTE-SFCHRON     01-12 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-DISPUTE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL PITS ENVIRONMENTALISTS, FARMERS AGAINST DEVELOPERS IN WATER 
 DISPUTE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ A odd political alliance of farmers and
environmentalists squares off Wednesday against builders and cities
in the latest round of a nearly decadelong fight to block new
housing developments that don't have a sufficient water supply.
<P>
   The battle began in 1991 when East Bay Municipal Utilities
District refused to provide water to developers of the 11,000-home
Dougherty Valley project near San Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight has since taken on statewide importance as
California grapples with the prospect of accommodating some 3.6
million new residents over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more people move here, we have to be more responsible in
our use of resources. And water has been one of those things we've
said we're not going to worry about because it's always there,''
said Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, D-Santa Monica. ``I don't think
that's responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehl is the author of a bill that requires cities and counties
to show that once a new housing tract is built there will still be
enough water available _ even in drought years _ to meet all
agricultural, residential and business needs.
</P>
<P>
   The measure will be heard Wednesday in the Assembly Local
Government committee.
</P>
<P>
   Each year since 1991, on bill after bill, EBMUD and its farmer
and environmentalist allies have been defeated by a politically
powerful coalition of builders, realtors, cities, counties and the
California Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists like the idea of making housing projects
contingent on water availability because it could slow development.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers back the measure because they don't want to lose their
share of California's water to urban and suburban users.
</P>
<P>
   EBMUD fears overextending itself by having to provide more and
more water to new developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make sure you can meet the needs of your existing
customers before you take on additional ones,'' said Randy Kanouse,
EBMUD's lobbyist. ``One-third of the water we sell is to
businesses. They have expectations that they'll get all the water
they need.''
</P>
<P>
   But builders, realtors and Shappell Industries _ one of the
developers of Dougherty Valley _ say the solution to California's
water needs is more dams and reservoirs, not added restrictions on
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill punishes those who are looking for an affordable
place to live,'' said Tim Coyle, lobbyist for the California
Building Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``What public policy interest does this serve? Safeguards
already exist at the local level,'' Coyle said ``A home doesn't get
built unless there is an adequate supply of water.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities also oppose the bill because they say they already
consider water supply in making development decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Two East Bay Democrats _ Assemblymembers Tom Torlakson of
Antioch and Ellen Corbett of San Leandro _ are pivotal to the
bill's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Torlakson wanted to gut a similar bill so both sides
could work out their differences.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when Torlakson was a Contra Costa County supervisor,
the county approved the Dougherty Valley development that rankled
EBMUD.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the board voted to oppose a bill like the one Kuehl is
carrying this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom is still deliberating, although he's acutely concerned
about the issue,'' said Robert Oakes, a Torlakson spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Corbett said she is inclined to support it. ``It makes sense to
determine if water is available when making decisions on land
use,'' she said. EBMUD's problems with Dougherty Valley were
resolved in 1998 when Shappell and another developer, Windemere
Ranch Partners, paid $18 million to Zone 7, the Tri-Valley's water
district to provide the project's water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 0332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3507 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-AOL-INTERNET-SFCHRON &LR;      01-12 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSTS SEE A CLEAR BENEFIT IN AOL'S MOVE  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online's stock fell almost 12 percent Tuesday on
morning-after worries that many of the expected benefits from its
acquisition of Time Warner won't come easily _ with one exception.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts agreed that AOL's $160 billion purchase will
hasten its ability to provide customers with high-speed Internet
service and a wider variety of online content from Time Warner's
vast libraries of music, magazines and movies.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also could speed the day when Bay Area residents have
a choice of cable Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, AT&AMP;T is the only company providing cable Internet
service in most parts of the Bay Area. The company has an exclusive
agreement with ExciteAtHome, which provides high-speed Internet
service over AT&AMP;T's cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T says it eventually will sign similar deals with other
Internet service providers, but only after its pact with
ExciteAtHome expires in mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
   But several experts predicted Tuesday that the AOL-Time Warner
deal will put pressure on AT&AMP;T to open its network to other
Internet service providers, like America Online, right away.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Battle for Open Cable Lines
</P>
<P>
   AOL had been leading the charge for ``open access,'' or giving
customers a choice of high-speed Internet service providers by
forcing cable monopolies to open their lines to competing ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   It also will be able to lead by example: In taking over Time
Warner, the nation's No. 2 cable company after AT&AMP;T, it can
immediately open up  &LR; its own cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Time Warner also has an exclusive agreement with a
single company, RoadRunner, to provide high-speed Internet service
through its cable lines. But AOL President Steve Case said Monday
that he will continue to support open access.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, which would like to gain access to AT&AMP;T's vast cable
network, could gain additional leverage with its purchase of Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has been trying to persuade Time Warner to let it sell
local telephone service over Time Warner's cables. Now AOL could
offer to let AT&AMP;T do just that _ in exchange for letting AOL sell
Internet access over AT&AMP;T's cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly (AOL) has a monster negotiating chip,'' said Barry
Parr, an Internet analyst with International Data Corp. in Mountain
View.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts said the deal puts more steam behind the
open-access push.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears this will speed along open access ... and put more
pressure on AT&AMP;T,'' said Cliff Staton, executive director of the
Open Access Alliance of the Bay Area, which has been championing
the issue locally.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T insists its plans remain unchanged. ``We're committed to
giving customers a choice,'' said spokesman Clay Ryder, ``but we
will honor our exclusive agreement'' with ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T did end the pact early, analysts said the clear loser
would be ExciteAtHome. The Redwood City company estimates it
reaches between 15 and 20 percent of its 1.1 million Net customers
nationwide through AT&AMP;T's cable TV lines. If ExciteAtHome lost its
exclusive contract, other ISPs could  &LR; would try to steal those
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But ExciteAtHome Vice President Richard Gringras insisted that
his deal with AT&AMP;T is not in jeopardy. An early end to the contract
``is simply not in the cards,'' Gringras said.
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned whether AOL is really committed to open
access, saying the company might only open access to affiliated
companies or give its rivals worse terms than its allies.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Gringras argues, the AOL-Time Warner deal will give
ExciteAtHome a boost by publicizing the attraction of high-speed
connections. ``We only think this will help stimulate our growth
and consumer awareness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Michael Graham of Robertson Stephens in San
Francisco said, ``I don't think it means that much at all for
AtHome.'' He added that some ExciteAtHome investors might be
disappointed that America Online didn't buy their company instead
of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   In a dismal day for tech stocks overall, ExciteAtHome shares
were down $2.75 to $37.25. AOL fell $8.63 to $64. And Time Warner,
which on Monday gained more than $25, or 39 percent, gave back
$6.25 to close at $86.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts worried that AOL's breakneck growth rate would
slow with Time Warner's stodgier media properties included. Others
wondered whether employees who originally came from Time Inc.,
Warner Communications, Turner Broadcasting, Netscape and AOL could
become one big happy family.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also questioned how the deal would affect Yahoo, which
offers a variety of content including stock quotes and chat, for
free on the Web. Many analysts said the move puts pressure on Yahoo
to acquire other media companies to keep up with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   With Time Warner, AOL gains access to an enormous breadth of
media brands ranging from Sports Illustrated to CNN to Bugs Bunny.
Theoretically, it could offer some of this content exclusively to
customers to help persuade them to sign up with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculated that Yahoo could buy Walt Disney Co.,
another giant media company that, like Time Warner, has had trouble
moving its successful brands online. Yahoo, with a market
capitalization of $105 billion (versus $75 billion for Disney) is
one of the few Net companies big enough to acquire Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time seeing a market where (America Online and
Time Warner) is a unique marriage,'' said Clay Ryder, an analyst
with Zona Research in Redwood City. ``This is just the first.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Carrie Kirby contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
