r l BC-BODY-WRAP13-COX     01-12 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODY-WRAP13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mineral slimming's mantra: Wrap it up, I'm not taking it home
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ My sister and I have this holiday
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Each year we inevitably find ourselves side by side in our
parents' bedroom, next to the mirrored closet, comparing the size,
shape and relative attractiveness of our butts. (Don't worry _
we're fully clothed.)
</P>
<P>
   Racked by body-image issues, each of us is convinced the other
has been more blessed by the gluteus maximus gods. Which made this
the perfect time of year, I thought, to subject myself to a mineral
body wrap and give my caboose a boost.
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the promise of walking out several inches smaller in
circumference _ without any messy huffing, puffing and sweating or
any calorie counting
</P>
<P>
   _ I visited the offices of Slimmer Bodies.
</P>
<P>
   All I have to do, according to the Slimmer Bodies press release
that landed on my desk a few weeks earlier, is get bundled in
mineral-soaked bandages and lurch around _ think Boris Karloff _
for an hour. Sounded like, pardon the pun, a cinch.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Slawson, Slimmer Bodies owner (and, yes, the owner of a
slimmer body), is on the phone with a potential body-wrap client
when I arrive (a man, she says, who needs a little hand-holding).
Wearing a casual black dress, she's open and friendly, the kind of
woman who soothes your insecurities by dishing about her own figure
flaws.
</P>
<P>
   She first has me fill out a brief health form, which questions
how devoted I'll be to a healthy diet and exercise plan after my
wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure, whatever. Bring on the bandages.
</P>
<P>
   I am shown to a dressing room where I change into my blue
gingham, '40s-style swimsuit (most folks wear their undies _ but
for the sake of the photographer I have in tow, I take the demure
route). On my way to the measuring room, Slawson has me drink a
Dixie cup full of what tastes vaguely like grape juice. She says
it's a concoction that will boost my supply of minerals and
vitamins. That way, when the wrap begins its sucking action, I
won't be drained of nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the moment I've feared: Slawson and her tape measure.
She measures my upper arm (small), my forearm (smaller) and my
wrist (smallest). The area above my bust (small), below my bust
(smaller) and my rib cage (smallest). And finally the dreaded lower
extremities: mid-thigh (large), upper thigh (larger) and hips
(largest). A total of 18 measurements in all, which Slawson notes
down to a one-eighth of an inch on a chart.
</P>
<P>
   The Slimmer Bodies wrap, which is actually the Victoria Morton
Body Wrap (as seen on Extra! and Sally Jessy Raphael), doesn't
promise lost pounds, although you are weighed before and after.
</P>
<P>
   Developed 30 years ago, the wrap does guarantee, however, that
inches will melt away. It's not a dehydration wrap, the Slimmer
Bodies literature assures. Inches are lost through the use of a
secret solution, ``composed entirely of food-grade inorganic
minerals and distilled water.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery minerals seep into your skin, pull out whatever
``toxins'' you're toting around and shrink your tissues to leave
you six to 20 inches smaller (remember, that's a 20-inch total loss
spread over 18 separate measurements). In other words, you cannot
will the ``toxins'' to exit from your ample thighs and and take up
refuge in your meager chest.
</P>
<P>
   (And now a word from a medical professional. . . While a body
wrap temporarily could leave you a sliver of your former self, it's
not a permanent solution to feeling you're too big for your
britches. ``You don't need to be a physician to know you're not
going to lose any fat by that means. You lose fat by burning more
calories than you take in,'' says Dr. Patrick O'Neil, director of
the Weight Management Center at the Medical University of South
Carolina. But he does concede that wraps can provide the illusion
of being thinner: ``If that's what somebody's after and they know
that's what they're getting, then you're in business.'')
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, that's what I want. And so begins the short process of
binding. The key is to wrap tight, Slawson says. And boy does she.
She swaddles my legs, hips and stomach in moist Ace bandages as if
she's Hattie McDaniel, I'm Vivien Leigh, and we're replaying the
corset scene from ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   My legs start to go slightly numb, but Slawson assures me that
as soon as I start ambling around the Slimmer Bodies office, I'll
feel more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   And then Slawson, like some fairy godmother to the posteriorly
cursed, asks if I want a ``butt lift.'' Heck, yes! Gimme the
Jennifer Lopez special! Slawson yanks bandages up between my legs
to create a huge, diaper-like wedgie. And with my wrapped hands, it
is impossible to unwedge myself.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she accessorizes my flesh-toned ensemble with a rain
poncho to keep me warm and clear plastic bags on my hands and feet.
The bags will catch the ``toxins'' that escape my body, she
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, I'm fairly toxic. During the hourlong session of
``mummy aerobics,'' which amounts to me walking clumsily in circles
in a large, spartan room at the back of Slimmer Bodies while we
watch videotapes of Victoria Morton performing body wraps on talk
show after talk show, the toxin-filled bags must be dumped every 10
minutes. I become obsessed with how much runoff I'm producing,
holding up my left hand to check the bag's toxin level every couple
of minutes. Slawson wears surgical gloves to empty the bags _
otherwise, my toxins will irritate her skin, she says. (I have to
wonder what all these poisons are doing to my insides.)
</P>
<P>
   In between the emptying of the toxin bags, Slawson slathers me
with more of Slimmer Bodies' secret sauce, which is kept warm in
the kind of rectangular double boiler you see on a buffet. Then
it's back to the main room for more shuffling in a circle, more
watching of exercise videos whose moves my bandaged limbs have no
hope of mimicking, and more idle chitchat.
</P>
<P>
   I learn that Slawson takes Tae Kwon Do. She demonstrates a
powerful, shoulder-high kick that I realize could easily level me
in my mummified state.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, an hour has passed and Slawson quickly unspools the
bandages from my now-shivering body as if they were on fire and she
is trying to save me from the burning fabric. She then reaches for
that blasted tape measure.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, the tape measure is now my friend! I am almost 12
inches smaller. My forearms, wrists, rib cage and calves are the
same, but who cares? I lost 7/8 of an inch from each upper thigh,
7/8 of an inch from my hips and an inch from my tummy. That's big
news in the land of the pear-shaped.
</P>
<P>
   And when I later see photos of my bikinied backside, I realize
my sister could be in for some tough competition this year.
</P>
<P>
   We have liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   Slawson says I can maintain my shrunken silhouette as long as I
don't gain any weight. She was right. I felt slimmer for several
days. But then I started gulping eggnog almost daily throughout the
holidays. (Which explains why I'm pushing maximum density again.)
</P>
<P>
   Would I return to Slimmer Bodies? If I had a spare $85, sure.
The feeling of suddenly occupying less space provided a nifty
albeit temporary boost to my self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention my butt.
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: stacisturrock(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
