r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN13-COX     01-12 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Favorite years are a surprise
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The teachers at the Muse Machine workshop sat
around the table, engaging in an activity for which their day jobs
afford little opportunity: a philosophical conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The topic: ``What was your favorite year?''
</P>
<P>
   ``1985 _ the year I got married,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   ``1995 _ the year I got divorced,'' countered another.
</P>
<P>
   ``1973 _ my junior year in high school,'' piped in a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a better junior year than I did,'' groused a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation-starter was this weekend's Muse Machine
performance of the 1992 Broadway musical My Favorite Year. The
story, based on the 1982 movie starring Peter O'Toole, follows a
tumultuous few weeks in the life of aspiring young comedy writer
Benjy Stone. The year is 1954, and Benjy is charged with
``babysitting'' dissolute former matinee idol Alan Swann, based on
Errol Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   Director and choreographer Nat Horne's favorite year just
happens to be 1954: ``That's the year I came to New York and
decided to go into show business and give up plans to become a
professor of math. I had to starve for a month and eat oatmeal. So
1954 was not the best year, but my favorite year, because it was
the year I decided, 'I'm doing this and nothing else.' And I did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That dichotomy was also present in the response of co-director
and music director David Dusing, who couldn't single out one year
as his favorite:
</P>
<P>
   ``The year I started performing professionally. The year I first
toured. The year of a long-ago failed romance that when recalled
still, for some odd reason, has a sadness and sting.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The years that come back most vividly are the
tumultuous ones, the times of struggle and change. I suppose I
should say my favorite year is the year I got married (who needs
that stress)? or the years my children were born (who needs the 4
a.m. feedings)? Instead I think of my first job, when we were all
young and hungry, one big happy dysfunctional family. Or the year I
fell in love for the first time, with all the attendant expectation
and misery. Or the year I started dating my husband, with all the
attendant skepticism and surreptitious happiness. Or this year,
when my children have become so suddenly, so completely, their own
people.
</P>
<P>
   What would the Muse Machine's young cast members _ all high
school students _ have to say on the subject?
</P>
<P>
   Ben Magnuson, a high school junior who plays Alan Swann, said
this year is his favorite year: ``The day after one show ends,
another begins. That's really what I want to be doing. It's nice
having no life.''
</P>
<P>
   Katharine Jackson, a senior, is in her seventh year with the
Muse Machine. The daughter of Helen and Isaiah Jackson, former
conductor of the Dayton Philharmonic Orchestra, she has graduated
from a one-word part in Music Man to last year's stunning turn as
Lola in Damn Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   On reflection, Jackson chose her sophomore year, when she landed
an ingenue role in Mame: ``That's when I was in the middle, looking
up at the stars. I could see how far I'd come, and I could see how
much I have to look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, how she doesn't pick the easiest year, or the happiest
year, or the year of her greatest triumph. How she understands, at
such a young age, that any year that you're striving, looking at
the stars, most fully alive, can turn out to be your favorite year.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
