<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Son's unsportsmanlike outbursts troubling
 &HT;    By Dr. Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A reader recently presented the following problem:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. LeCrone: Our son is an excellent tennis player but he
seems to have a terrible problem dealing with the occasional losses
that he experiences. He has broken and thrown his racket numerous
times. On other occasions he has lost his temper at the end of the
match and yelled obscenities at his opponent and the line judges.
He won't even speak to anyone, including his girlfriend, for
several days after a loss. He doesn't exhibit this behavior in any
other situations including school, social relationships or other
competitive sports. Can you make any helpful suggestions that we
might pass on to him?
</P>
<P>
   Dear reader:
</P>
<P>
   Has your son picked up some bad habits of modeling after other
athletes who exhibit unsportsmanlike conduct when losing?
Occasionally, I have seen young athletes who actually admire the
antics displayed by the poor sports in their particular sport.
Close inspection sometimes reveals that this is an
attention-getting mechanism and that they are willing to resort to
negative behaviors to receive the attention of others.
</P>
<P>
   Other athletes with your son's problem are so focused on the
outcome of a particular event that they lose track of the process.
The big picture in becoming proficient and a consistent winner in
any sport is to recognize that getting there takes time and
experience. Getting better includes competition with those who have
more experience, and this translates into some losses as a part of
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the opportunity to learn from a less than desirable
outcome is one of the great keys to success in athletes. This
includes observing the behavior of the more proficient opponent and
learning from his or her style and technique.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals who go ballistic when they lose are often
individuals with problems of low self-esteem. They view their
performance as a direct measure of their self-worth, becoming so
absorbed in winning that they equate losing with being a rotten,
lousy, totally unsuccessful individual in all respects of life.
</P>
<P>
   The poor loser needs to frequently remind him- or herself that
sports are designed to entertain, and having winners and losers
makes the event more interesting. If the outcome were certain,
there would be much less interest in playing or watching the sport
in the first place. Sports losses are disappointments, not death
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Helping your son learn to deal with loss now can be a great
benefit in helping him deal with the many challenges of adult life
in the world outside of play.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a clinical psychologist whose column appears
in The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas. If you have questions or
topics you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write him 4555 Lake
Shore Drive, Waco, Texas, 76710. E-mail: hlecrone(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3624 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE     01-12 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take 1 of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q : A question on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' recently
asked whose jurisdiction the U.S. Coast Guard was under. The answer
was the Department of Transportation. When did it change from the
Treasury Department?
</P>
<P>
   A: The most recent change occurred on April 1, 1967, when the
DOT was formed. Before that, control of the Coast Guard _ an
amalgamation of five formerly distinct federal services _ had been
changed a number of times.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard was formed under that name on Jan. 28, 1915,
when the Life-Saving Service and Revenue Cutter Service were
combined. The Revenue Cutter Service was created in 1790. The
Life-Saving Service was an independent bureau of the Treasury
Department. On April 6, 1917, with the declaration of war against
Germany, the Coast Guard was transferred to the Navy Department. On
Aug. 28, 1919, it reverted to the Treasury Department. On Nov. 1,
1941, it was transferred back to the Navy Department. On Jan. 1,
1946, it returned to the Treasury Department. And then, 21 years
later, it made its change to the Transportation Department, where
it remains to date.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The incident involving Atlanta Braves relief pitcher John
Rocker's controversial comments in Sports Illustrated reminds me of
that famous quote: ``I may not agree with anything that you say,
but I will defend to the death your right to say it.'' Who first
said that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some sources attribute the statement _ ``I disapprove of what
you say, but I will defend to the death your right to say it'' _ to
French philosopher Voltaire (1694-1778). But the Oxford Dictionary
of Quotations said the words, in fact, are S.G. Tallentyre's
summary of his attitude toward Claude Adrien Helvetius after the
condemnation and burning by the French parliament of Helvetius'
book ``De l'Esprit'' in 1759.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A brief announcement on TV said the nuclear submarine Topeka
was at the international dateline at midnight Dec. 31 so its crew
could be the first people to welcome the new year. I didn't see or
hear anything else about it. Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Pearl Harbor-based Navy sub was straddling the
international dateline 400 feet below the surface of the Pacific at
the stroke of midnight Dec. 31, meaning its bow was in one year and
its stern in another. It also was straddling the equator, meaning
it was in both the northern and southern hemispheres.
</P>
<P>
   The sub's commanding officer, Cmdr. Mark Patton of Cheyenne,
Wyo., said the Topeka's positioning was intended to demonstrate the
Navy's confidence that it was ready to handle the so-called Y2K
computer bug, and not a publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   The 360-foot-long sub, with a crew of 130, used sophisticated
satellite positioning technology to determine the proper location.
Up above, boats of various sizes circled the area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article Dec. 31 reported that Sarah Knauss, the world's
oldest living person, had died at 119. Who is now the oldest living
person, and what is the age?
</P>
<P>
   A: Researchers at Guinness Book of World Records are trying to
track down several people who would inherit the title, Guinness
spokeswoman Louise Wilson, in London, told Q&AMP;A. They include a
woman in Poland who is said to be 118, and a man in Oregon who may
be 111.
</P>
<P>
   Until their ages are authenticated _ meaning that a birth
certificate or other undisputed proof of age is provided to the
researchers _ the oldest authenticated person is a Scottish woman,
Marget Eaton McHowat, 107, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   McHowat was born as Marget Eaton Webster on Dec. 4, 1892, in
Brechin, Scotland. She became the oldest living person in Scotland
in April 1999. The eldest child of David and Marget Webster, she
was married to Robert McHowat from 1923 until his death in 1957.
They had two children, Margaret Jean (1926-71) and Irene Anne (born
in 1930 and still living).
</P>
<P>
   Outliving both her brother and sister (who died at 94 and 71,
respectively), and reaching a greater age than her parents (78 and
82), Marget McHowat claims never having a day's illness in her
life, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A list of notable deaths in 1999 included the name of
Elizabeth Guthrie Foster. Is that the author of the children's book
``Gigi,'' about a merry-go-round horse?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Elizabeth Guthrie Foster, who died Nov. 4 at age 86, was
the first woman to head the Atlanta College of Art. She also was a
fellow in the National Association of Schools of Art and Design.
</P>
<P>
   The Elizabeth Foster who wrote the children's book about Gigi, a
horse on the Prater in Vienna when World War I broke out, was born
in Cleveland in 1905 and died in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My Bermuda grass has some pesky weeds I want to kill. I
understand that applying Round-up on dormant, brown Bermuda grass
in the winter will not harm the grass come spring. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. But there's an important condition, said Gil Landry a
turfgrass specialist with the University of Georgia Extension
Service's Experiment Station in Griffin. You must be certain the
grass is totally dormant, meaning there must be no green leaves
beneath the canopy. A grass often appears dormant on the top,
Landry explained, but when you look into the canopy or below the
top leaves, you can find green leaves. If that's the case, don't
apply the Round-up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a reprint of that famous photo of accordionist Graham
Jackson, with tears in his eyes, taken at the time of President
Franklin Roosevelt's death at the Little White House in Georgia.
Whatever became of him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jackson died in January 1983 at the age of 80. He drew
national attention in April 1945 when he was photographed by Life
magazine while playing ``Going Home'' at Warm Springs, Ga., after
FDR died.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain a Latin phrase in Larry McMurtry's ``Lonesome
Dove''? It is this: Uva uvam vivendo varia fit.
</P>
<P>
   A: Many interpretations have been offered by various Latin
scholars. Perhaps the one most agree on was offered first in 1988
by an unnamed Latin language instructor at San Diego State
University, who called it a ``pseudo'' Latin phrase: ``A grape
matures by looking at another grape.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Los Angeles Public Library, McMurtry himself
provided this same translation. In explanation, the library
suggested that McMurtry probably had begun with a self-composed
proverb in English, and ``fractured it a bit'' in attempting to
convert it to Latin.
</P>
<P>
   The literal translation, by the way, is something like this:
(The) versatile grape becomes a grape by living.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter-in-law received a ``pea coat'' for Christmas. We
think the name derives from the Navy in World War II, but we aren't
sure. Do you know the origin?
</P>
<P>
   A: The original ``P'' coat was issued by the Navy before World
War II. The ``P'' stands for ``pilot,'' referring to a ship's
navigator, not an aviator. You'll see it spelled as two words (pea
coat) or one (peacoat), or it might be called a ``pea jacket.'' By
whatever name, it remains a classic fashion statement. The
traditional style calls for eight buttons, in two rows, and a wide,
deeply notched collar. It's waist-length or slightly longer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent question about Al Gore referred to his Army
``enlistment.'' Somewhere I had gotten the impression that Gore
served as an officer. If so, your reference to ``enlistment'' is
inaccurate. I see this mistake frequently in various publications,
and I hear it on the air from time to time. Am I correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gore wasn't an officer, although he had graduated from
Harvard and could have chosen to train as an officer candidate.
</P>
<P>
   As widely reported for years, Gore volunteered for enlistment in
the Army after graduating in 1969, even though _ again, as widely
reported _ he was opposed to U.S. involvement in Vietnam and worked
in the campaign of anti-war presidential candidate Eugene McCarthy.
After he arrived in Vietnam, Spec. 5 Gore served seven months as a
reporter with the noncombat 20th Engineering Battalion, stationed
outside Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   You can check his background online at several sites, including
that of the nonpartisan Project Vote Smart
(http://www.vote-smart.org). You also can get biographical
information at Gore's official Web sites,
www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/OVP/index.html and
www.AlGore2000.com/gorefamily/gorefamily.html).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently was asked if Al Gore had enlisted in the Army
rather than having served as an officer. The person asking the
question said he had seen and heard it reported in the media that
Gore had enlisted, adding that this was a mistake. What do you call
it if he was an officer, if it's not an ``enlisted man''?
</P>
<P>
   A: A commissioned officer in the military has chosen to train
for appointment to a position of authority (``an officer''), but he
or she is not considered to have ``enlisted.'' This is the
definition of ``enlisted man'' (or ``enlisted person'') in
Webster's New World Dictionary: ``any person in the armed forces
who is not a commissioned officer or warrant officer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore wasn't an officer, although he would have been eligible to
enter officer training _ if he chose to do so _ after graduation
from Harvard University. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
