<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3627 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE     01-12 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS13-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of two.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Exactly what does it mean to say a lake is ``dead'' because
of pollution caused by toxic waste?
</P>
<P>
   A: It means a lake has become ``eutrophic.'' Eutrophic is a
technical term defined as ``pertaining to a lake containing a high
concentration of dissolved nutrients, either by natural means or
pollution, with periods of oxygen deficiency.'' When oxygen is
depleted, fish and other aquatic life are choked.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the cause of death of Wendy's CEO Gordon Teter ever
determined? An article mentioning his death reported that an
autopsy was planned, but I didn't see anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Initial reports indicated that Teter, 56, died of natural
causes on Dec. 18. A spokeswoman at the coroner's office in
Columbus, Ohio, told Q&AMP;A that autopsy reports typically aren't
available until six or eight weeks after death.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In all the reports I've seen about the influenza virus
spreading across the United States, there has been no mention of
the specific type. Some types are treatable and covered by current
vaccines. Is this one of them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The predominant influenza strain circulating this winter
is A Sydney. It was the strain anticipated by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, so people receiving the vaccine
this season ``should be pretty well protected,'' said CDC spokesman
Tom Skinner. And even if they contract flu, their symptoms should
be lessened.
</P>
<P>
   While the CDC has monitored increased flu activity nationwide in
the past few weeks, many different types of virus can cause upper
respiratory tract infections that may resemble flu, Skinner added.
So what people may think is flu could be something else.
</P>
<P>
   For people considered to be in ``high risk'' categories _ older
than 65, or residents of nursing homes or other closed
environments, or those with chronic heart and lung conditions _
Skinner emphasized the CDC's concern about having flu vaccinations
every year: ``This is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently saw the final half of the movie adaptation of
Tennessee Williams' ``Baby Doll'' on AMC. Since the cast wasn't
listed at the end, can you tell me who played the title role, what
other pictures she was in, and if she's still living?
</P>
<P>
   A: The baby doll in the steamy movie _ considered notorious when
it was released in 1956 _ was portrayed by Carroll Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Doll'' was Baker's second film. The role branded her as a
sexpot. As a result, her career was most vividly marked by her work
in it and other once-controversial productions, such as ``The
Carpetbaggers'' and ``Harlow.'' But she also appeared in ``The Big
Country,'' ``Giant,'' ``Mister Moses,'' ``How the West Was Won,''
``Cheyenne Autumn,'' ``Ironweed,'' ``Kindergarten Cop,'' ``Watcher
in the Woods'' and ``The Game,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   At last report the 68-year-old grandmother _ her daughter has
three children _ was married to British actor Donald Burton and
living in Los Angeles. Baker continues to turn up from time to time
in made-for-TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I didn't see anything about the White House greeting cards
sent by President and Mrs. Clinton, but David Letterman said on his
program that he received one. Can you share any details with us?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1999 card featured a rendering of a watercolor painting
depicting the North Portico of the White House. The design was by
artist Ray Ellis of Martha's Vineyard, Mass. Ellis, known for his
watercolor and oil landscapes, also designed the 1998 White House
holiday card, which featured a watercolor painting of the State
Dining Room.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokeswoman Marsha Berry said the White House was
chosen as the subject both years ``to pay tribute to an American
treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   The '99 message: ``Our family wishes you and yours a blessed
holiday season filled with treasured memories of past traditions
and joy and peace in the new millennium.'' It was signed by the
president and first lady and embossed with the presidential seal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife and I were born in the '50s, graduated from high
school in the '60's, finished college in the '70s, got married in
the '80s, and turned middle age in the '90s. Now we're looking
forward to retirement in the ??s. That's the question: When we talk
about this decade, exactly how do we specify it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Way back in 1993, Futurist magazine, which was living up to
its name, conducted a readership poll on this very issue. As you
might imagine, there was no definitive conclusion. And there seems
to be none now.
</P>
<P>
   Most futurists (64 percent) voted for ``the two-thousands.''
Individual years would be pronounced ``two-thousand-one, two-
thousand-two,'' and so on. Meanwhile, an additional 9 percent of
the futurists said they wanted to see the decade dubbed the
``twenty-ths.'' Five percent went for ``the oh-ohs,'' and an equal
percentage chose ``the double-ohs.'' Four percent went for ``the
zeros.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Simon Collier, chairman of the history department
at Vanderbilt University, ``the two thousands'' moniker most
closely reflects past traditions surrounding turns of the
centuries. ``With the years 1900 to 1909, we would always have
called those `the ninteen hundreds,' '' Collier said. But he
pointed out a complication: ``What's happened is that in the
English language, the terms `eighteen hundreds' or `nineteen
hundreds' have come to mean the whole century, rather than the
centuries' first decades.''
</P>
<P>
   So let's wait and see how the debate unfolds, as it most surely
will, now that the future is here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the expression ``Trip the light fantastic'' mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: It means ``to dance gaily,'' explains the Morris Dictionary
of Word and Phrase Origins. It comes from Milton's poem
``L'Allegro'' and begins ``Haste thee, Nymph, and bring with thee
Jest and youthful Jollity.'' Further on is this: ``Sport that
wrinkled Care derides,/ and Laughter holding both his sides./ Come,
and trip it as ye go/ On the light fantastic toe.''
</P>
<P>
   But the expression gained its greatest popularity in the lyrics
of ``The Sidewalks of New York'': ``Boys and girls together, me and
Mamie O'Rourke,/ Tripped the light fantastic on the sidewalks of
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: During the broadcasts of New Year's Eve festivities from
around the world, it was reported that midnight in Newfoundland is
10:30 p.m. Eastern Standard Time. Aren't all time zones one hour
apart?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. While most are one hour apart, there are exceptions.
World Book Encyclopedia explains that because it differs from its
neighboring zones by only a half-hour, the Newfoundland Time Zone
is not a ``true'' standard time zone.
</P>
<P>
   Other half-hour-zone situations exist in Pitcairn Island,
Norfolk Island, the Marquesas Islands and the Cook Islands, all in
the South Pacific; central Australia; the Andaman and Nicobar
islands, in the Andaman Sea south of Myanmar (the former Burma);
Sri Lanka; and India. And there are others.
</P>
<P>
   Nepal offers yet a different exception, of just 10 minutes. When
it's 5 o'clock in Karachi, Pakistan, the time is 5:30 in India, its
neighbor to the east. But it's 5:40 in Nepal, which is on India's
northeastern border.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. Naval Observatory says, nations are sovereign
powers. As such, they can _ and do _ change their timekeeping
systems as they see fit. So no universal rules apply.
</P>
<P>
   World Book Encyclopedia, in the T volume (look under Time), has
a two-page map of all zones. An accompanying table compares times
all over the globe. It's worth a trip to the library.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been saving all my lottery tickets because I was told
that if I ever won, I could use the non-winning tickets as an
offset on my tax liability. Is this true? I have a lot of unlucky
tickets in shoeboxes that I'd like to throw away if this is just a
hoax.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can toss those boxes of losing tickets for previous
years. Only those that were losers in the year in which you win the
lottery are deductible, said IRS spokesman Eric Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Leap year occurs every four years to adjust for the fact that
we circle the sun approximately every 365 1/4 days, so we add one
day every four years to account for that discrepancy. I remember
reading that this adjustment is too much, and that once every 400
years, we're not supposed to have a leap year. I thought 2000 was
one of those times, but all the 2000 calendars I have seen show a
Feb. 29. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the Gregorian calendar, which is the civil
calendar in use today, years evenly divisible by 4 are leap years,
with the exception of centurial years that are not evenly divisible
by 400. Therefore, the years 1700, 1800, 1900 and 2100 are not leap
years, but 1600, 2000 and 2400 are.
</P>
<P>
   If you're online and interested in the background, check this
U.S. Naval Observatory site:
http://aa.usno.navy.mil/AA/faq/docs/leapyears.html
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
