r d BC-GET-FRESH13-COX     01-12 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GET-FRESH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toss out the old, try a taste of the new in your kitchen
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's a brand new year _ a perfect time
for a fresh start in the kitchen. Start by embracing the winter
bounty of juicy oranges and sweet stone crabs. Kick off the century
with a sensible diet. Be adventurous and add new ingredients to
your pantry. While you're at it, get rid of those ancient spices
and clean the fridge! It will make cooking a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   FRESH FROM FLORIDA:
</P>
<P>
   These foods, wonderful in their essence, also work well in
creative dishes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Signature fruits _ the citrus family _ are in their glory now.
Cut them up, juice them, or leave them whole in a lovely dessert
that features spun caramel threads.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stone crab claws, the tempting sweet crustaceans, are a luxury
treat through May, when their season ends. You have a choice of
appetizer-sized jumbos or the mediums. Make your own garlic dip for
a new treat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red, ripe tomatoes are in fields ready for picking. Why not
preserve some this year to have the rest of the season? Make tomato
sauce and freeze it _ no canning needed. And the best part: You can
control the additives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Luscious strawberries will be in markets soon. Desserts are a
natural with this berry, but try a salad for something fresh. We
like spinach and red onion with berries, and a balsamic vinaigrette
over all.
</P>
<P>
   _ Corn in winter? You bet. For the up-and-down winter weather,
whip up a stew, hearty with beef, tomatoes and corn. It's a meal in
a pot and you don't even have to cut the kernels off the cobs.
</P>
<P>
   What's a New Year's without a dieting resolution? This year,
stick with the basics:
</P>
<P>
   _ Strive for the recommended ``five-a-day'' fruits and veggies.
Eat two of them raw _ to eliminate fat and calories added by
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Drink water daily _ most experts suggest eight 8-ounce glasses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eat breakfast as a true meal. Try to get at least three of the
major food groups in: eggs or some protein; oatmeal or whole-grain
cereal; some fruit or juice. You can lose weight by adding this
meal, since you won't be so hungry at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get your vitamins either from nutrient-rich foods, or from
supplements. Learn what your body needs and tailor your supplements
to you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exercise at any age: It keeps muscles and bones in shape and
it can increase weight-loss results by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FRESHEN YOUR PANTRY:
</P>
<P>
   _ Add soy _ it's the hot new food for the millennium, said to be
one of the healthiest. Tofu is soy _ so is soy sauce, soy milk and
soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try a new flavor of oil or vinegar. It doesn't take much of
either to add flavor to food, but it can change a dish radically.
Learn to deglaze a pan with vinegar or finish a soup with a dribble
of oil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go Asian: Change your spice cabinet from Mediterranean and add
fish sauce, too. Basil's run its course. Try citrus peel, ginger,
cardamom, cayenne and cinnamon in main dishes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toss out the tired old pasta, rice and potatoes, and move to
new sides such as couscous or quinoa or bulghur wheat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add anchovy paste. This small change can open up an ocean of
new cooking possibilities. Meats, sauces, dips and marinades
benefit from this humble fish.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE WAYS TO CLEAN AND ORGANIZE YOUR KITCHEN:
</P>
<P>
   _ Clean out that fridge! Toss the holiday pickles and fruitcakes
from the year before last. Use vinegar to wash the inside walls and
drawers for a clean smell.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a date: Buy several permanent markers and start marking
the date of purchase on food cans, boxes and frozen items. Start
rotating your stock to use the oldest first.
</P>
<P>
   _ De-bug your spice cabinets. If you have spices and herbs older
than six months, chuck them _ you won't lose any flavors! Replace,
and get busy marking them with date of purchase.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reassess those messy utensil drawers. Gadgets are no good if
you don't use them _ toss out the useless things. Real chefs don't
rummage around for tools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clean filters and disposals. Your stove fan has a filter
that's best cleaned with straight ammonia. Pour a bleach solution (
1/4 cup per gallon of water) down the sink disposal with the water
running.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Norris writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
