<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3630 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-HASH13-COX     01-12 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-HASH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hashing it out: The forgotten staple of yesteryear is just as
good today
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you think you're too time-pressed to fix
dinner, consider your grandmother, who didn't have a microwave,
dishwasher or a cupboard full of convenience foods at her
fingertips. Now, there was a woman who had to work to get dinner on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   And she had some pretty good ideas about how to do it as
efficiently as possible. Sometimes she made a hash of it.
Literally.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that today's cooks have forgotten about the simple
supper called hash. At its most basic, hash is nothing more than
cooked meat or chicken _ the leftovers from Sunday's roast cut up
into little pieces _ plus potatoes and onion. Cook the mixture in a
little butter until crisp, and that's hash. New Englanders put
beets in their beef hash and called it red flannel hash, and they
sometimes made hash with fresh codfish, but neither version had a
place in homes in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are variables. Depending on what was on hand,
some cooks added green pepper or mushrooms. As comfort cooking has
made a comeback, chefs have made upscale versions of hash,
substituting smoked salmon for beef and adding lots of seasonings
that Grandma never kept on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The potatoes can be raw or cooked, peeled or not; the meat,
potatoes and onion can be chopped by hand, ground in a meat grinder
or chopped in a food processor. Purists insist on chopping them by
hand.
</P>
<P>
   And as cookbook author James McNair points out, there are two
basic versions of hash: one is crisp, the other is soft.
</P>
<P>
   For a refresher course, we turned back the clock to older
cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old edition of Joy of Cooking passed down at this
newspaper makes hash using leftover gravy. One recipe for a quick
hash calls for a can of cream of mushroom soup and a cup of
frankfurters, which could destroy your faith in that book forever.
</P>
<P>
   The late James Beard, the dean of American cookery, offers
homage to recipes for beef and chicken hash in his book
appropriately named American Cookery. They are traditional
no-nonsense recipes, with nothing more unusual than a grinding of
nutmeg or a touch of cream. But even Beard offers a quick corned
beef hash recipe that begins with a can of corned beef and a can of
corned beef hash.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have never tasted hash _ except from a can _ we
offer two basic versions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In his most recent book, ``James McNair's Favorites''
(Chronicle, $29.95), the author offers a recipe for corned beef
made from scratch. Leftover corned beef brisket is cut into thin
strips. Potatoes are cooked fresh and cut into strips. Red bell
pepper is added to the mixture, along with some garlic. Seasonings
include Worcestershire sauce and thyme. It may not be for weekday
cooks but it makes a fine Sunday supper.
</P>
<P>
   Note that the beef, potatoes and peppers are cut into similar
sized strips rather than cubed in the traditional fashion. If
you're starting from scratch, cook the corned beef in simmering
water, figuring on
</P>
<P>
   1 hour per pound.
</P>
<P>
   NEW FASHIONED CORNED BEEF HASH
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cooked red potatoes, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced onion
</P>
<P>
   2 red bell peppers, stemmed, seeded and cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cups cooked corned beef
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh thyme or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   salt
</P>
<P>
   freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh flat leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Cut the cooked potatoes into narrow strips and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat the oil and two tablespoons of the
butter. Add onion and sweet pepper, and cook over medium heat,
stirring frequently, until vegetables are very soft but not
browned, about 10 minutes. Stir in the garlic and cook a minute
longer. Add the remaining 2 tablespoons butter, the reserved
potatoes, corned beef, thyme, Worcestershire sauce, as well as salt
and pepper to taste. Cook, stirring occasionally, to bring up
browned bits of the crust (easily done with a spatula). When
browned bits are well incorporated in the hash, stir in the parsley
and press down to allow the hash brown fully on bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Serve on warmed plates. If desired, top with a poached egg.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use either leftover beef or corned beef for this recipe. Even
accomplished cooks favor serving the hash with ketchup, though
Beard favored bottled chili sauce _ slightly warmed. Top with
poached eggs for a traditional hash supper.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC SKILLET BROWNED HASH
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cooked meat
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cubes raw potatoes, with or without skins
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   With a sharp knife, cut the meat into small pieces. Combine the
meat, potatoes and onion in a bowl and season with salt and pepper.
Turn into a hot, well-greased skilled. Cook over medium-low heat
until a crust forms on the bottom. Use a spatula to turn the hash
and brown the other side. Stir it from time to time to let the hash
brown throughout. Shortly before it is done, pat it down firmly to
form an unbroken cake. This will require a half-hour cooking in
all. Serve with chili sauce or ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   Note: A little cream added toward the end of the cooking process
helps the browning and eliminates any dryness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a contemporary version of hash, consider Elisabeth Rozin's
recipe for Curried Turkey Hash. It's from her bookBlue Corn and
Chocolate (Knopf, $25), which is devoted to native American
resources such as turkey. She combines cumin, turmeric, fenugreek,
ginger and ground coriander to make a curry seasoning. If you don't
have fenugreek, just leave it out. You can also experiment using
curry powder, which already is a mix of those spices.
</P>
<P>
   CURRIED TURKEY HASH
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fenugreek
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon coriander
</P>
<P>
   3 cups finely chopped cooked turkey
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cups diced cooked potato
</P>
<P>
   2 large stalks celery, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup light cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken or turkey stock
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   several dashes Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   several grinds black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a small skillet, saute the onion in the butter until just
wilted. Add the cumin, turmeric, fenugreek, ginger and coriander
and cook, stirring, another few minutes. In a large bowl combine
the turkey, potato and celery. Scraped the spiced onion mixture
into the turkey mixture and blend thoroughly. The recipe can be
made ahead to this point and refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl whisk the egg lightly. Stir in the cream, stock
and the remaining seasonings. Blend thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Generously butter a large shallow casserole or baking dish,
approximately 9 by 13 inches. Spoon the turkey mixture into the
casserole, pressing down and smoothing with a spatula. Pour the egg
mixture over the turkey. Bake for 30 to 35 minutes, until set and
lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago Daytonians looking for an early a.m. bite to eat
stopped in at the Purple Cow restaurant, in the old Miami Hotel,
recently demolished as part of the Lazarus implosion. A favorite
was corned beef hash and eggs. All they did was cut a slice from
canned corned beef hash, brown it and top with a poached egg.
</P>
<P>
   This quick version also relies on canned corned beef hash, but
James Beard jazzed it up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES BEARD'S QUICK CORNED BEEF HASH
</P>
<P>
   1 can corned beef
</P>
<P>
   1 can corned beef hash
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter or beef drippings
</P>
<P>
   Chop the canned corned beef rather coarsely and combine with the
corned beef hash and chopped onion. Heat the butter or drippings in
a heavy skillet and cook the hash, pressing it down well to start a
crust. Scrape the bottom with a spatula and bring some of the crisp
bits to the top. Continue doing this until the crusty and soft
parts are equally mixed. Then let the bottom crust uniformly.
</P>
<P>
   Serve as is or top with poached eggs.
</P>
<P>
   MB HOPKINS/DAYTON DAILY NEWS
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recipes for Curried Turkey Hash and James Beard's Quick Corned
Beef Hash. 3C
</P>
<P>
   Try these!
</P>
<P>
