<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3631 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FRESH-RECIPES13-COX     01-12 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRESH-RECIPES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From salad to stew, start the New Year with great food
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here are recipes to give your cooking a
fresh start in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   This makes a nice lunch salad with two fresh ingredients _
tomatoes and hearts of palm, also known as swamp cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTS OF PALM SALAD WITH TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   2cans (14 ounces each) hearts of palms, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   1head Boston lettuce, broken into leaves
</P>
<P>
   1tomato, peeled and finely chopped with juice
</P>
<P>
   1cup cooked corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley or cilantro
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   11/2tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cut any large hearts lengthwise into quarters; cut medium-sized
hearts in half and leave small hearts whole. Line 4 salad plates
with the lettuce. Arrange the hearts of palm in neat rows on top.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine the tomatoes with their juice, corn,
parsley or cilantro, lime juice and oil. Season with salt and
pepper. Spoon the tomato mixture over the hearts of palm in a neat
row down the center over the lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From Steven Raichlen's ``Healthy Latin Cooking,'' Rodale Press,
1998.)
</P>
<P>
   This dip is ideal for serving with other fresh fruits on a
brunch, breakfast or dessert buffet. If using for dessert, serve
cubes of angel food or chocolate pound cake for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY ALMOND CREME
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup pureed strawberries (process about 12 to 15 small berries
in a blender or food processor)
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons confectioner's sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, fold strawberries into sour cream. Fold in
yogurt. Gently stir in almond extract and sugar. Chill in the
freezer for 20 minutes (set a timer) then move to the refrigerator
for 1 hour. Serve with skewered fruits, berries or pieces of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3/4 cup.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Chips, Dips and Salsas,'' by Judy Walker and Kim
MacEachern, Northland Publishing, 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   This Caribbean stew is a favorite in Colombia, South America, as
well. It's terrific for a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   SANCOCHO
</P>
<P>
   For meat and marinade:
</P>
<P>
   12ounces lean pork tenderloin, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   12ounces boneless, skinless chicken breasts, cut into 1-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   8ounces lean beef (such as chuck) or lamb, cut into 1-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup sour orange juice or 6 tablespoons lime juice plus 2
tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   3cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   For sofrito:
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1large onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   5scallions, trimmed and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1green bell pepper, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3to 6 jalapeno chile peppers, seeded if desired, and finely
chopped (wear plastic gloves while chopping)
</P>
<P>
   6leaves culantro or 6 sprigs fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   12cups water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   12ounces taro, peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   12ounces yuca, peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces (see note)
</P>
<P>
   12ounces calabaza, peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   12ounces yams or sweet potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1green plantain, cut crosswise into 8 pieces
</P>
<P>
   2ears corn, shucked and cut crosswise into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1to 2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   To make the meat and marinade: In a large glass or stainless
steel bowl, combine the pork, chicken, beef or lamb. Add the sour
orange juice or lime juice mixture, garlic and bay leaves. Toss to
coat. Cover and marinate in the refrigerator for 30 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To make the sofrito: Heat the oil in a large stockpot over
medium heat. Add the onions, scallions, bell peppers, garlic, chile
peppers, culantro or cilantro, 4 tablespoons of the parsley and 4
tablespoons of the cilantro. Cook, stirring occasionally, for 4
minutes, or until the onions are soft but not brown. Add the meat
and marinade. Cook for 5 minutes. Increase the heat to high, add
the water, and bring to a boil. Skim off any foam that rises to the
surface. Reduce the heat to medium and simmer, skimming
occasionally, for 30 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Add the taro, yuca, calabaza, yams or potatoes, plantains and
corn. Simmer for 1 hour, or until the calabaza has disintegrated
and the meat is soft and tender. Stir in 1 tablespoon of the
vinegar, the remaining 2 tablespoons parsley and the remaining 2
tablespoons cilantro. The broth should be highly seasoned; add more
vinegar, salt and black pepper if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To peel yuca, stand the pieces, cut side down, on a
cutting board. Cut off the peel with a paring knife using downward
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   (From Steven Raichlen's ``Healthy Latin Cooking,'' Rodale Press,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Use pasteurized eggs for this recipe as a safety measure, or use
commercial mayonnaise according to the directions that follow.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1whole egg
</P>
<P>
   1egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   2whole cloves of garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon hot Hungarian paprika (or use cayenne)
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4cups extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Moisten the bread crumbs with 3 tablespoons water. Squeeze all
of the water out and set aside. Place the egg, the yolk and garlic
in the bowl of a food processor. Blend until the egg is light and
frothy and the garlic is minced. Add the lemon juice, salt,
paprika, mustard and bread crumbs. Blend until the mixture is
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   With the processor running, add the olive oil in a slow, steady
stream through the feed tube. Stop the machine, scrape down the
sides of the bowl, then blend again. Adjust the seasoning to taste.
</P>
<P>
   To make with commercial mayonnaise: Combine 2 cups of
store-bought mayonnaise with 2 teaspoons chopped garlic, 1/8
teaspoon Hungarian paprika and 1/4 teaspoon Dijon mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Serve as a dipping sauce for stone crab claws or other seafoods.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``The Best Bread Ever'' by Charles Van Over, Broadway
Books, 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe will bring out the natural flavor of
oranges, but be forewarned_ it should be made on a nonhumid day to
prevent the sugar from melting off the oranges.
</P>
<P>
   GLACEED ORANGES
</P>
<P>
   12seedless navel oranges of good color
</P>
<P>
   4cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups water
</P>
<P>
   With an orange peel stripper, strip 20 or so pieces of peel from
the oranges. Immerse the peels in boiling water for 5 minutes, then
drain and cool. Peel the rest of the oranges, using a very sharp
knife. Remove all rind and membrane.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the sugar and water together in a heavy saucepan. Do not
stir. When sugar is dissolved, cover pan and boil for 5 minutes.
Remove cover. Syrup should be clear. Continue cooking to the hard
ball stage (250 degrees on a candy thermometer).
</P>
<P>
   Lower heat and, working quickly, dip each orange in the syrup,
using sharp pronged forks. Stack oranges in a serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   When all the oranges have been dipped, add the peels to the
syrup and cook over low heat 3 minutes. Remove the peels to an
oiled surface to cool. Keep pieces separate and use to decorate the
glazed oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To make the spun sugar netting over the oranges, dip a
fork in the hot sugar-syrup and drizzle back and forth over the
oranges quickly. As it hardens, the syrup will form the fine,
fragile threads. Do not refrigerate, as this will cause the threads
to soften and melt. Take care when working with this and all hot
sugar mixtures; they will stick to the skin, causing serious burns.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Entertaining,'' by Martha Stewart, Clarkson Potter,
1998, paperback.)
</P>
<P>
   Jan Norris writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
