<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-WINE-COLUMN13-COX     01-12 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weighing carefully the vino varieties
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Post-millennium musings:
</P>
<P>
   I was able to take some time off from work over the holidays,
and during that period, I tasted and slurped up some wonderful,
awesome, just really fine wines. Some were mine, but the best
fermented juice to cross my tongue belonged to friends generous
enough to share wines for which they paid, quite frankly, a pretty
penny. Tasting them reminded me of a question I've heard repeatedly
posed to wine sellers and tasters about expensive wines: ``Are they
worth that much more? Is a $50 wine really 10 times better than a
$5 bottle?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: No, of course not. And, the answer is: Well,
maybe.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to quantify the enjoyment of wine, or food, or
anything sensual, but for the sake of argument, let's say that a
$50 bottle of wine is 20 percent better than the $5 bottle. For
most folks, that price-to-quality ratio isn't going to make any
sense; they'll gladly take 10 bottles of the inexpensive wine. But
for others, that 20 percent boost in taste sensation or overall
enjoyment could well be worth a tenfold price increase, even if it
makes the logical, accounting-conscious part of our brain blanch.
(After all, it's that party-pooper-but-sensible part of the brain a
lot of folks ignored when they bought their millennium celebration
Champagnes and wines for their New Year's Eve events.)
</P>
<P>
   I was trying to pin down what made one particular wine _ it was
a 1982 Chateau Margaux _ that I shared recently (it wasn't mine,
alas) so special. And I'm not sure this captures it, but it comes
close, at least for me. Sure, the wine ``tasted good'' _ a lot of
wines do. But this was a wine that virtually commanded your
attention, grabbed you by the collar (subtly) and told you it was
special. I was carrying on a conversation with a friend while I
took a sip of the wine. A half-minute or so after I had swallowed
it, I could still taste the wine's flavors. In waves. At one point,
I stopped in midsentence and uttered something scholarly and
erudite, as only a wine columnist can, something like, ``Whoa!''
</P>
<P>
   It was good juice. And it was telling me, ``I'm special. You
can't ignore me.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it doesn't have to be an '82 Margaux in your glass to
capture that spirit. Depending on the atmosphere, the food, the
company, the circumstances, a far less expensive wine can push the
same buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, I advocate taking wine off its pedestal,
reminding folks it is at its core an agricultural product produced
by grape farmers and should not be treated with such reverence or
snootiness that it ends up intimidating people. But every once in a
while, I'm reminded there's a little bit of magic in wine, a magic
that, once experienced, is not easily forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a ``Whoa!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wine of the week: 1999 Altos Malbec Las Hormigas, $9.99: Yes,
a '99 for $9.99. This delicious red wine hails from Argentina,
which takes the Malbec grape that is used in small quantities in
Bordeaux blends to great heights. This wine isn't a nouveau _
remember, the folks in the Southern Hemisphere have summers during
our winter and vice versa, so this wine was harvested and fermented
in March and April of last year. It's jam-packed with fruit and has
enough spiciness to add interest (and maybe a little bit of that
aforementioned magic). Dry reds for less than $10 don't get any
better than this.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
