<HEADER>
A3633 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-NUHN-COLUMN13-COX     01-12 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NUHN-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez always delivered
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ John Bench was flashy. He hit home runs in
bunches, and even his foul home runs were majestic. He threw
runners out with a gun of an arm that could have been mounted on a
battleship.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Morgan was flashy. He had every skill God could give a
ballplayer. He hit for average and for power. He ran like
Secretariat. He could field and he could throw. And he had this
flapping-elbow deal going in the batters' box that set him even
farther apart.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose was flashy. He was a hitting machine. He did
everything at 100 mph. He dived into bases on his face. He would
run over his grandmother if it meant a victory. He finished every
game with the dirtiest uniform in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Perez was not flashy. Perez was a river on a July day when
it hadn't rained in a month. He was placid. Is Tony breathing? Is
he not? You could never tell.
</P>
<P>
   That was both the upside and the downside of Tony Perez.
</P>
<P>
   You knew as you watched them that Bench, Morgan and Rose were
first-ballot Hall of Famers. You never got that feeling when you
watched Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the doubt was removed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the announcement finally came: On his ninth try,
Atanasio Rigal Perez was elected to baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   I called a man who saw most of Perez's at-bats in Tony's 13
seasons as a Red. Jim Ferguson was the Reds' beat writer at The
Dayton Daily News from 1959-1972, then worked as the Reds public
relations director for another 18 years after that. He's now
director or media relations for Minor League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   I tested my theory that one knows a Hall of Famer when one sees
him _ Willie Mays, Hank Aaron, Sandy Koufax _ but I never felt that
watching Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it, either, when I watched him,'' he said. ``But
when his career was over, I knew it. It was the cumulative effect
of everything he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Tony was that he delivered and delivered and
delivered and delivered. He wasn't spectacular. If you needed a
single, Tony singled. If you needed a sacrifice fly, Tony got a
sacrifice fly.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a man in control of his emotions to deliver as Perez
did consistently through his career.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson told a story about that control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was traded after the 1976 season,'' Ferguson said. ``Some
of us were on the Reds' Caribbean Cruise at the time. We stopped at
an island and read about it in the paper. Pete Rose was on the
cruise. Ken Griffey. Bill Plummer. Everybody was stunned. The next
day the cruise ended in San Juan, where Tony lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez had been in the Reds' organization his entire career. But
he handled the trade as if it happened every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was there to meet us when the boat docked and he helped us
get through customs quickly because he pretty much knew everybody
on the island,'' Ferguson said. ``Then he took us out to his condo
and his wife, Pituka, fixed us lunch. We stayed there for six or
seven hours until our plane home. I don't know what was going on
inside Tony, but he was absolutely a great host.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez used that same self-control when he hit with 50,000 fans
screaming and a fastball coming at 94 mph.
</P>
<P>
   I was a doubter, but I can say now without hesitance:
Cooperstown is a better place today than it was yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: gnuhncoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
