<P>
   THE LATEST FROM NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE:
</P>
<P>
   -----------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL PROFILING WIDELY ACKNOWLEDGED BY ALL
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN OF JUAN SEGUIN
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP FOR `NUEVA AMERICA'
</P>
<P>
   `SKEWED' VIEWS OF GAMING REVENUES
</P>
<P>
   STAYING ON GUARD: A BREAST CANCER SURVIVOR'S STORY
</P>
<P>
   These articles, described below, have been sent to clients of
NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE, available exclusively from The New York
Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   NEW AMERICA NEW SERVICE is a special wire service dedicated to
stories that reflect our nation's varied social and ethnic makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Having attended UNITY '99, we understand the needs of editors
across the nation who are on the hunt for topnotch multicultural
material for their publications.
</P>
<P>
   --- New America News Service is the answer.---
</P>
<P>
   For more information about NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE _ or to see
the articles in their entirety _ please contact sales
representative Ana Pena by phone, (212) 499-3333, or fax, (212)
499-3382.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about our 30-day free trial!
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown ...
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL PROFILING WIDELY ACKNOWLEDGED BY ALL. Two years ago, most
white people had not heard of racial profiling, such as DWB
(driving or dining while black), and certainly would not publicly
acknowledge that people of color were suspects of crimes simply
because of their race or ethnicity. But with the advent of video
cameras, the Internet and various cable-television stations and
news services, news stories about racial profiling abound. In this
commentary, columnist Akilah Monifa reports on the results of a
recent Gallup telephone poll of 2,006 people, including 1,001
African-Americans, in which those polled were asked what they
thought about racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN OF JUAN SEGUIN _ This week, columnist Juan Gonzalez
reflects on the life of Juan Seguin, the forgotten father of Latino
politics in the United States. Seguin served as both a senator of
the Texas Republic and mayor of San Antonio. Gonzalez believes that
how our nation comes to terms with Seguin's legacy will determine
much about American politics during the 21st century. The reason is
simple: The political influence of Hispanic-Americans is growing at
breakneck speed. For example, between the 1976 and 1996
presidential elections, Hispanic voter registration in the United
States increased 164 percent compared to only 31 percent among
non-Hispanics. ``Descendants of Juan Seguin _ who will number one
out of every four Americans by 2050 _ are finally ready to write a
new chapter in the story of American democracy,'' Gonzalez writes.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP FOR `NUEVA AMERICA.' _ Columnist James Garcia has
always been ambivalent about Geraldo Rivera. ``I sometimes wonder
whether his primary objective is to entertain or to inform,'' he
writes. However, Rivera's latest CNBC documentary, ``Nueva
America,'' merits special recognition. It's an important
achievement because it introduces Rivera's largely white mainstream
viewing audience to the nation's fast-growing, increasingly
powerful and diverse Latino community. In this commentary, Garcia
applauds Rivera's work and highlights the documentary's finer
moments.
</P>
<P>
   `SKEWED' VIEWS OF GAMING REVENUES _ Columnist Tim Giago believes
that there is a skewed tendency by charitable foundations and other
contributors to charities and causes to assume that because there
are some Indian nations that have grown wealthy from their gambling
revenues, these tribes should bear the brunt of contributions to
needy Indian programs or institutions. But only 5 percent of gaming
tribes are amassing 90 percent of the gambling revenues. This
means, of course, that 95 percent of the Indian nations are still
struggling to bring jobs, better schools and improved health care
to their people. In this commentary, Giago presents his solutions
to the financial problems and other ills that Native-Americans now
face.
</P>
<P>
   STAYING ON GUARD: A BREAST CANCER SURVIVOR'S STORY _ For two
years, Jackie Young missed getting her annual mammogram. ``I was
too busy _ running for office, writing my memoirs, traveling,'' she
writes in this feature from KoreAm Journal. But in January 1998,
when she needed a refill for Premarin, an estrogen pill she had
been taking daily since 1980 after her hysterectomy, her doctor
asked her to undergo a routine checkup. A mammogram was included.
``I was aware of the statistics for women in my age group (I'm 65),
but I thought that being Asian was on my side,'' she writes. ``I
had heard that Asian women had a lower incidence of breast cancer.
And besides, my family had no history of cancer.'' Unfortunately,
the test and a subsequent biopsy confirmed her worst fear: She had
cancer. In this feature, Young describes how she coped with the
diagnosis and treatment. A sidebar titled ``The Facts on Breast
Cancer'' is included.
</P>
<P>
