<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3658 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-BILL-MACY-INTERVIEW-A     01-12 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILL-MACY-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACY'S PARADE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By HILARY DEVRIES  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Nobody can play frustration quite like Bill Macy. You can see it
in Jerry Lundegaard, the pathetic, scheming car salesman he played
in ``Fargo,'' in Little Bill, the cuckolded porno director of
``Boogie Nights'' _ and in William H. Macy, bona fide movie star.
</P>
<P>
   Over a tuna sandwich, Macy is anguishing over what ought to be a
welcome rite of passage: construction of his new house in the
Hollywood Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 14 months and thousands and thousands of dollars, I
basically have a very expensive hole,'' he says dejectedly.
</P>
<P>
   He seems even reluctant to accept the good fortune that his
performance in ``Fargo'' brought him: an Oscar nomination and a
career switched onto the express track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hit, that's the main thing,'' Macy says with the
caution that comes from working steadily in films for 20 years
before finally _ at nearly 50 _ grasping Hollywood's brass ring.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, it's time to acknowledge that he has indeed taken
hold of that ring _ at least according to his wife of two years,
actress Felicity Huffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lovely wife, who is so smart, said to me last year, `You
need new goals,''' says Macy, who has something like half a dozen
films under his belt in the last 12 months _ including ``Mystery
Men,'' ``Happy Texas'' and now ``Magnolia,'' the third film from
``Boogie Nights'' wunderkind Paul Thomas Anderson _ and ought to be
the last person to need career counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand what she meant at first, but then I
realized I was operating too long under the assumption all actors
do, the `I've got to get a career' thing. Well,'' he acknowledges,
``I have a career. So now I'm trying to redefine my goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Macy decides to tackle next _ screenwriting (he wrote
TNT's ``A Slight Case of Murder''), directing (HBO's ``Lip
Service'') or finding that elusive role in which he finally gets
the girl _ his performance in ``Magnolia'' as Donnie Smith, a
fading 1950s quiz-show star, can be seen as a step in that new
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote the role of Donnie to bust Macy out of his box,'' says
Anderson, who directed the actor in ``Boogie Nights'' and who
conceived the character, which he describes as ``the smartest loser
of all time,'' specifically with Macy in mind.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Anderson wanted the stage-trained actor to forgo
some of the rigorous, anti-Method acting principles that he's
famous for _ theories that have fueled a career that includes an
Emmy-nominated guest stint on ``E.R.'' and more than two decades of
acclaimed theater work in Chicago and New York, where Macy
occasionally teaches a few lucky students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as character. It's just a trick we play
on the audience, with their participation, that's based on
scientific principles,'' says Macy, who first earned his acting
chops at the feet of David Mamet nearly 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright and screenwriter, who has since cofounded two
theaters with Macy and remains one of the actor's closest friends,
was working as an acting teacher at Vermont's Goddard College when
Macy enrolled in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't a very good student, and Goddard was an alternative
school in Vermont where the women didn't wear brassieres, and what
more information do you need?'' says Macy, who was born in Miami
but grew up in Virginia and Maryland, where he was the high-school
class president and a folk singer who hoped to become a
veterinarian until he got a good look at the science requirements.
Acting was not only easier, but ``Dave,'' recalls Macy, his voice
tinged with awe, ``made it a calling.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a trade, no different from bricklaying or the
woodworking Macy pursues during his off-hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can be an actor. It's a craft anyone can practice,''
insists Macy, who found ``Magnolia's'' emotion-fraught bar scene _
in which Donnie breaks down, confronting the wreck of his life and
drunkenly declaring his love for the studly bartender _ one of the
most difficult he'd ever encountered. (``Macy still doesn't think
he delivers,'' says Anderson with a chuckle. ``But it's just that
he's uncomfortable with emotions.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard because the objective wasn't clear, and it also
shifted because he was drunk,'' says Macy, who admits his distaste
for playing emotions is part of the fallout from his
``white-bread'' upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest son of a Southern belle mother and a buttoned-down
father _ a World War II hero turned insurance salesman _ Macy grew
up in a household where overt displays of emotion were discouraged.
He can play what he calls ``the imploding WASP'' so beautifully _
all those dispeptic losers that crowd his credits _ because, he
says, he is one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some actors can cry at the drop of a hat, they're so
accessible to themselves,'' he says. ``Felicity is so emotionally
alive she's like a racehorse. Well,'' he concludes, ``I'm a
camel.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Hilary DeVries is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
