   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOREANS-GAYS (San Francisco) _ Korean-American pastors are
teaming up with the conservative Christian Coalition to support an
anti-gay initiative that has little chance of ever appear on the
ballot in California. Still, the alliance is deeply troubling to
the Korean-Americans who have formed an organization to counter
what they believe is misinformation the churches are spreading. By
JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   COPS-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Police have arranged for back up
security forces if needed at demonstrations outside the upcoming
Amadou Diallo trial and backed away from a statement last week that
bullhorns would be banned. By MELISSA GRACE.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-SIRENS (Bethlehem, N.Y.) _ For 35 years, Benjamin Castle
has lived only half a block from the Delmar fire station and its
wailing siren, which he says knocks him off the deck of his house.
The siren rings at 130 decibels _ louder than a jet at take off.
While volunteer fire companies across the country are silencing
sirens in favor of pagers, some of the departments in this slice of
upstate New York cling to tradition. By KERI P. MATTOX.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HOUSING (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Gov. Gray Davis
said he is working with Mayor Willie Brown to create special zones
in San Francisco and San Jose so teachers, police, paramedics and
firefighters can afford to live where they work. Davis blamed the
Bay Area's critical housing shortage on the obvious: The area's
incredible new wealth has prompted the rich to overbid on houses
and send the middle-class to Central Valley towns like Modesto and
Tracy. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSPAPER-SUIT (San Francisco) _ Former mayoral candidate Clint
Reilly is suing to stop The Hearst Corporation, owner of The San
Francisco Examiner, from buying the morning San Francisco Chronicle
and merging The City's two daily newspapers. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   BIKES-CARS (San Francisco) _ When bicycles and cars collide in
San Francisco, cyclists say, police haven't been responsive enough,
too often automatically siding with motorists. The Board of
Supervisors' Land Use and Transportation Committee took a step
toward leveling the
</P>
<P>
   playing field after approving a resolution urging police to give
motorists and bicyclists involved in an accident equal treatment.
By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (`f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON-EXPLORE (San Francisco) _ Chevron Corp. plans to spend
$5.2
</P>
<P>
   billion in 2000, of which $3.6 billion will be for worldwide
</P>
<P>
   exploration and production and $1.3 billion for projects in
</P>
<P>
   the United States. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHDAY-PARTIES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Children's birthday parties
used to be a simple affair _ hang some streamers, blow up a few
balloons, bake a cake. But parents no longer throw parties. They
buy them _ dance parties, days at the salon, museum tours,
gymnastics lessons and even $17,000 sleepover parties at F.A.O.
Schwartz. By KERI P. MATTOX.
</P>
