<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE DOES ELIAN BELONG? NO QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time magazine poses the question as if the answer is debatable:
``Where does he belong?''
</P>
<P>
   There can be no debate, of course, regarding the identity of the
``he'' whose future is at issue. The magazine cover features a
photo of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, perhaps the most photographed
child since Baby Jessica fell into that Texas well back in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the story. Elian was pulled from the Atlantic
Ocean near Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on Thanksgiving Day after his
mother died at sea during a desperate attempt to flee Cuba and win
freedom in the United States. At approximately the same moment that
the boy was rescued, he was turned into a political football.
</P>
<P>
   And while Elian's fate is kicked around by politicians and
activists in Cuba and the United States, he remains in Florida _
separated from his Cuban father, whose pleas to be reunited with
his son go unheeded.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service finally got around to
deciding that the boy should be sent home to his dad, but then a
judge in Miami one-upped the INS by ruling that Elian should remain
in this country until at least March 6. That's when the court plans
to hear legal arguments from relatives of Elian who want him to
remain in the U.S. permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Let's give Elian's relatives the benefit of the doubt and assume
that they have the kid's best interests at heart _ even though
logic tells us that anyone who really cared about the boy would
want to see him reunited with his father. Maybe the relatives know
something about the father that the rest of us don't know, or maybe
they sincerely believe that a 6-year-old is better off visiting
Disney World with his cousins, aunts and uncles than enjoying the
loving companionship of a devoted father.
</P>
<P>
   Misguided relatives aside, there is no excusing the conduct of
the politicians, bureaucrats and political activists who have
allowed _ no, make that ``encouraged'' _ the continuation of this
fiasco for all these weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro has brazenly made Elian a cause
celebre in his country, exploiting the child's situation to stir up
anti-American sentiment among his subjects. In the United States,
anti-Castro zealots and Castro-bashing pols have buried Elian's
best interests beneath an avalanche of flag-waving rhetoric that is
entirely irrelevant to the proper disposition of a child custody
case.
</P>
<P>
   And child custody is what this is all about, no matter how hard
some groups and individuals try to turn it into a showdown between
the dismal tyranny of Castro's communist Cuba and the glorious
liberty of the world's greatest democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Castro and his enemies can debate the relative merits of Marxism
and a free society till the cows come home. But there is nothing
debatable about the need for a child to be with his father.
</P>
<P>
   No one has turned up a shred of evidence that Juan Miguel
Gonzalez is an unfit father _ indeed, news reports suggest that
Elian's dad couldn't be a more loving, more devoted father.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem here? American politicians and Cuban
exiles in the U.S. don't like the Cuban government, and therefore a
perfectly qualified parent should be deprived of his son?
</P>
<P>
   What would the United States say _ and do _ if some foreign
country got its hands on an American child and cavalierly decided
to keep him because the country's leaders and activists disapproved
of America's values and system of government?
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for us that the Soviet Union no longer exists _ and that
Castro no longer has the resources of a military superpower at his
beck and call.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida judge who decided to prevent Elian from going home
said that if the boy went back to Cuba, he would face ``loss of due
process rights and harm to his physical and mental health and
emotional well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. What about the loss of a child's right to be with his
father? What about the emotional harm of a boy's forced separation
from his only living parent?
</P>
<P>
   Where does he belong? It's not debatable.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
