<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHORE-GUIDE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home maintenance and improvement planner
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Jan. 13.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year, do yourself and your home a favor.
</P>
<P>
   Develop a master plan for maintenance and repairs that outlines
everything that needs to be done within the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing a list of interior and exterior projects may seem
tedious and time consuming now, but a little planning makes it
easier to shop for competitive product prices and arrange project
financing. It will also give you time to get at least three
estimates and find the best professional for the job after checking
credentials and references.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is for the homeowner to get as much
information as they can. That way they can make an informed
decision and know that they're spending their money wisely,'' says
Lou Manfredini, an adviser to www.OurHouse.com, a Web site that
helps consumers find the supplies and contractors they need for
repair or renovation projects.
</P>
<P>
   Home improvement experts recommend negotiating contracts and
scheduling service calls as much as three months before the work
should begin. That's particularly true for seasonal projects that
can take weeks to schedule when consumer demand is at its peak,
such as sweeping the chimney or servicing the furnace.
</P>
<P>
   Winter
</P>
<P>
   J A N U A R Y _ F E B R U A R Y
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create a ``home file'' for the entire year with warranties,
product manuals, receipts and service agreements for major
household appliances and equipment. Include such items as furnaces,
wood-burning stoves, central air-conditioning systems and
humidifiers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make a list of major and minor home repairs, improvements and
remodeling projects to be completed within the year. Keep the list
handy and check off finished projects. Make a note of upcoming home
shows and classes to attend to help plan the projects.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prioritize projects and develop a schedule for completing the
work, designating items as routine maintenance or home improvement.
Include everything from interior/exterior painting to renovations,
plumbing upgrades and roof repairs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Colder months are a good time for inside projects, such as
painting or renovating kitchens, bedrooms and other living areas.
Be prepared for temporary delays if temperatures drop too low to
leave windows open for ventilation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Solicit estimates for the work. Negotiate contracts and
arrange financing the season before you want the work done.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Landscaping contracts should be finalized by February, so lawn
service can begin by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Major appliances, tools and equipment go on sale throughout
the year, but January and February are the best times to find
savings on merchandise discontinued from the previous year,
according to the National Retail Federation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Review service agreements for appliances and equipment to be
serviced in spring.
</P>
<P>
   Spring
</P>
<P>
   M A R C H _ M A Y
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When setting clocks forward, change batteries in smoke alarms
and carbon monoxide detectors. Check fire extinguishers throughout
home and replace if needed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean, repair or replace storm doors and windows. Replace or
repair screens on sun porches, doors and windows.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Service central air-conditioning system or install
air-conditioning window units. Clean fans (ceiling, box, window,
etc.) and check electrical connections.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean gutters, downspouts and storm drains.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check the roof for leaks. Repair or replace now or in early
fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Weatherproof deck for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have swimming pools cleaned; check liners and filters. Clean
and service outdoor Jacuzzis and hot tubs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Treat or remove mildew or fungus on deck or house. Pressure
wash exterior of house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start outdoor repair and improvement projects, such as
building patios, porches or decks or painting trim/exterior of
home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for pre-summer savings on fans and window
air-conditioning units.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Review service agreements for appliances and equipment to be
serviced in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Summer
</P>
<P>
   J U N E _ A U G U S T
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Repair cracks in the driveway, walkways or patio caused by
cold weather and spring rains.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check siding on house, filling holes or replacing caulk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make note of projects to be completed in time for the
holidays. This includes painting or replacing kitchen cabinets,
shampooing or replacing carpets, steam-cleaning furniture, painting
rooms, changing wallpaper and buying new appliances.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get estimates for the projects, shop for contractors and
arrange financing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paint trim/exterior of home if it not done in spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In late summer, make arrangements for heating system to be
checked or replaced and chimneys to be cleaned. Schedule work for
early to midfall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Protect against burglaries while on summer vacation by
installing timers for interior and exterior lights and, if
possible, television and stereo systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Review service contracts for appliances and equipment to be
serviced in fall.
</P>
<P>
   Fall
</P>
<P>
   S E P T E M B E R _ D E C E M B E R
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean gutters and storm drains again. Make sure downspouts
carry water at least 3 feet away from home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When setting clocks back, change batteries in smoke alarms and
carbon monoxide detectors. Check fire extinguishers throughout the
home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean chimney of soot buildup; make sure fireplace doors fit
tightly and wood-burning stoves are in proper working order.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean sliding windows. Note air leaks and apply putty,
caulking or weatherstripping where cracks appear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean or replace furnace filters and have system serviced.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clean and vacuum vents, baseboard heaters and ducts. Winterize
air-conditioning units by placing a plastic cover over them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Insulate exterior faucets before the first frost.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check shelter supports and foundation on porches, patios and
decks for rotting wood or separation. Make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check roof and schedule last-minute repairs before cold
weather hits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shut down outdoor irrigation systems to prevent freezing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Negotiate contracts and schedule household maintenance and/or
improvement projects to be done in January and early winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for end-of-year close-out sales on tools, equipment and
major appliances.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Review service contracts for appliances and equipment to be
serviced in winter.
</P>
<P>
   For information or help on your next home improvement project,
check out these Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.improvenet.com: ImproveNet, in Redwood City, Calif.,
offers how-to advice, product info and a resource base of
prescreened contractors, architects and designers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.hssonline.com: The Home Service Store in Rutland, Vt.,
provides free estimates, a network of prescreened contractors,
referrals and home improvement financing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.ourhouse.com: Our House, based in Chicago, offers how-to
advice, product information and online chats with contractors and
home improvement experts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.southface.org: The Southface Energy Institute in Atlanta
features home-building classes, an energy hotline, energy
conservation tips and facts.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrations by Aaron Steckelberg for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
