<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-AOL-TIME-MICROSOF     01-12 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AOL-TIME-MICROSOFT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESIDE MICROSOFT, A NEW 800-POUND GORILLA LOOMS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the company's adversaries, the very name ``Microsoft''
suggests menacing power. It has been called the Death Star, an
800-pound gorilla and worse.
</P>
<P>
   And in the government's sweeping antitrust case, the Microsoft
Corp. was portrayed in convincing detail as a monopolistic bully.
America Online Inc., in particular, was bent to Microsoft's will,
according to court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But after America Online's move on Monday to buy Time Warner
Inc., at $165 billion the largest merger in history, Microsoft
suddenly seems less threatening _ less the irresistible army of the
Internet era. AOL Time Warner, as the new company will be called,
promises to be a formidable power in its own right, perhaps more
powerful in some ways than Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, to be sure, quickly gained the upper hand in its
first Internet battle _ against the Netscape Communications Corp.,
which America Online bought last year. Microsoft saw Netscape, the
pioneer in Web browsing software, as a threat to its dominance of
personal computing. Microsoft's response was swift and aggressive,
and, according to the Justice Department and 19 states, against the
law.
</P>
<P>
   The America Online-Time Warner deal changes none of the facts in
the antitrust case. But antitrust experts say it could figure into
the calculations the court makes on sanctions against Microsoft, if
it loses the case, or in settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Microsoft is an 800-pound gorilla, then there is certainly
another beefy gorilla out there now,'' observed William Kovacic,
professor at the George Washington University law school. ``This
deal does underline the possibilities for upheaval and
transformation in this industry. That could well make it more
difficult for a judge to choose a remedy that has dramatic,
irreversible effects, like breaking up the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The America Online-Time Warner merger, if completed, would
create a powerhouse for the next phase of Internet business:
selling information and entertainment services to consumers who may
tap into them using digital cell phones, handheld devices and
television set-top boxes in addition to personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Time Warner deal, America Online had been
bulking itself up to prepare for this so-called post-PC era with a
multibillion-dollar investment campaign over the last couple of
years, since the Microsoft antitrust suit was filed, to strengthen
its network technology and to add services. The acquisitions
include Netscape, Compuserve, MapQuest.com, MovieFone and a
$1.5-billion investment in Hughes Electronics to promote satellite
delivery of Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has gone on its own multibillion-dollar investment
spree, much of it to secure assured distribution for high-speed
Internet access over telecommunications and cable television
networks, both in the United States and abroad. In the last year
alone, Microsoft invested $5 billion in AT&AMP;T, $660 million in
Nextel, $500 million in NTL and $300 million in United Pan-European
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the online business, Microsoft finds itself in the
unfamiliar position of being David to America Online's Goliath. In
the online access market, in which subscribers pay fees,
Microsoft's MSN service had 1.9 million members in the third
quarter of last year, compared with 18 million for America Online,
according to Jupiter Communications, a research firm. America
Online says it now has 20 million subscribers, while Microsoft did
not disclose its current numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft does have some popular sites on the World Wide Web,
like its Expedia travel site and Carpoint auto site, which can be
reached by users through any Internet access service. Yet even by
the measure of number of visitors to its Web sites, Microsoft is
well behind America Online. According to Media Metrix, which
monitors Web traffic, America Online had 54 million visitors in
November, compared with 38 million for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has made some media investments including its joint
venture with NBC for a cable television and online news service,
MSNBC, but recently it had been shifting away from trying to become
a media company. Instead, it has been trying to build up its Web
offerings as delivering personalized information online _ e-mail,
news, stock prices, travel advice, even horoscopes _ that people
use to make them ``more productive,'' just as Microsoft's popular
Office software makes people more productive at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new strategy for MSN is about taking us back to our roots
but twisted and adopted for the Internet,'' Brad Chase, a senior
vice president explained in a recent interview before the America
Online-Time Warner deal was announced. ``There are parts of the
media business that we do, selling ads and so forth. But our main
focus is not going to be on creating content and media, which is
what we had been trying to do for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's senior executive team met on Monday to discuss the
implications of America Online's move, which is a big step in
becoming a media company. So is Microsoft rethinking its strategy
yet again _ as the richest company in the world, it could afford
virtually any acquisition _ or does it plan to stick to pursuing
its very different Internet strategy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear in mind, we've had one day to chew on it,'' Chase said
Tuesday, ``but I think this deal is kind of positive for us in a
way. It reinforces the very different road we're taking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL is saying that its primary anchor is going to be media,''
he added. ``Our primary anchor is going to be services and software
distributed over the Internet that will help consumers run their
lives better, make them more productive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To help revive its online business, Microsoft recruited a new
executive last fall, Richard Belluzo, to head its consumer group.
He came from Silicon Graphics, where he had been chief executive,
but Belluzo was probably best known for his previous work at
Hewlett-Packard, where he built the consumer printer and consumer
personal computer businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insists it is still very early in the Internet
business and that America Online's lead is by no means
insurmountable. ``As a mass-market consumer medium, the Internet is
just beginning to emerge and it will be accessed from many devices
other than the PC,'' Belluzo said. ``People talk about all the
subscribers AOL has, but in a few years we will look back and say
those numbers are trivial.''
</P>
<P>
   In the markets where Microsoft has engineered come-from-behind
winners, the company has followed a formula: make competitive
products, but also change the economics of the target market. In
office productivity software, Microsoft once trailed Lotus in
spreadsheets and Wordperfect in word processing. Microsoft steadily
improved its offerings, Excel and Word, but also bundled them into
a single Office suite and priced the bundled offering at about the
same price as rivals were charging for a single office application.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-11-00 2039EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
