<HEADLINE>
`OLD' VS. `NEW' IN TIME WARNER TAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're calling the America Online Inc.-Time Warner Inc. deal a
merger, but it's really a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The new firm will be called AOL Time Warner, not the other way
around. And AOL shareholders will get most of the bounty _ 55
percent of the new company, compared to 45 percent for Time Warner
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the little pipsqueak of a company that's buying the big
behemoth,'' said telecommunications industry analyst Jeffrey Kagan.
``But that's how it's happening these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by the immense value of its stock, AOL has carried out
the first ``new media'' takeover of an ``old media'' company. And
there may be more such deals in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to combine powerful brands in traditional media with a
hot, young on-line company isn't exactly new. Up to now, many
assumed that the big, established old media companies would be the
buyers rather than the bought. That's what nearly happened last
year when Waltham-based Lycos Inc. tried to merge with some of the
television and retailing assets of USA Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Lycos CEO Bob Davis said that a link with USA
Networks would have given his Internet company a solid foothold in
the world of traditional media. For this, he was willing to create
a new company in which Lycos shareholders would have gotten at most
a 35 percent stake. In essence, the old media people would have
ended up owning the new media company.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal enraged many Lycos investors. At the time, Lycos
shares were soaring above $130, while USA Networks shares were
hovering in the mid-30s. Defenders of the deal stressed that USA
Networks was bringing a variety of assets, like the Home Shopping
Network, which had solid cash flow and a large base of customers.
But shareholders were convinced that Lycos was selling itself too
cheaply, given the run-up in Internet stock values.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, such objections killed the Lycos deal. Charles Conn,
CEO of Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch Inc., one of the USA Networks
companies, thinks the AOL-Time Warner merger shows that Lycos and
USA Networks were on the right track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about vindication, but I do think it shows the
power and credibility of bringing together new media companies and
traditional media companies,'' Conn said.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, it's the new media company that's calling the
tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had asked me a year ago would this merger happen, I
would have said I don't think so,'' said Bruce Leichtman, director
of media and entertainment strategies for the Boston-based Yankee
Group. ``To see AOL as the big fish gobbling the little fish is
almost impossible to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL may be the most successful Internet company, but it's small
fry compared to Time Warner. AOL has just over 12,000 employees,
compared to Time Warner's 67,500. In the quarter ended September
1999, AOL had $1.5 billion in revenues; Time Warner raked in $6.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Time Warner's vast array of physical assets,
from printing presses to television studios. Time Warner CEO Gerald
Levin said Monday that his company's CNN cable news service alone
reaches up to a billion people worldwide. There's also the
company's other TV networks, like TNT, TBN, and the WB Network; its
recorded music business; its Warner Bros. movie and TV production
business; and a stable of magazines including Time, People,
Fortune, and Sports Illustrated. By comparison, AOL offers 22
million subscribers to its AOL and CompuServe Internet services,
and about 50 million monthly visits to AOL's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, all this was outweighed by AOL's extraordinary
market capitalization, which stood at $165 billion when the market
opened Monday morning. By comparison, Time Warner began the day
valued at $71 billion. For all its assets and worldwide reach, Time
Warner was still at the mercy of a stock market that has made AOL a
far more valuable company than Time Warner. Investors have made a
huge bet that AOL and other top Internet companies will acquire
hundreds of millions of subscribers worldwide in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, AOL badly needs Time Warner's old-media assets,
especially its cable television business, which is accessible to 21
million homes nationwide. AOL faces a severe threat to its
business, as AT&AMP;T Corp. and other cable firms start deploying
high-speed Internet connections to homes.
</P>
<P>
   The cable firms have cut their own deals with Internet providers
and frozen out AOL, whose customers would have to pay extra to use
AOL on cable systems. That could lead to massive defections from
AOL's customer base. AOL has been fighting in courtrooms across the
country in an effort to force cable firms to grant it ``open
access'' to their cable Internet services. The Time Warner deal
assures that AOL won't be frozen out of many American homes.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Time Warner badly needs an Internet strategy. The
company was one of the first old media companies to foresee the
significance of the World Wide Web. In 1994, the company launched
Pathfinder, a major Web site that was to feature on-line content
from a variety of Time Warner media properties. But Pathfinder
never caught on, leaving one of the world's major media companies
with almost no significant Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't deliver service over the Internet,'' said
industry analyst Kagan, ``you're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the news of the AOL Time Warner deal sent shares of Lycos
and Web leader Yahoo Inc. soaring as investors considered the
prospect that other Internet companies would begin making big
investments in traditional media firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's official,'' said Yankee Group analyst Melissa Bane. ``The
Internet company, at least in this deal, has been seen as the media
leader of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-10-00 2106EST &QL;
</P>
