<HEADLINE>
AOL CHAIRMAN IS USED TO ADAPTING TO CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the only thing stranger than America Online's chairman,
Stephen M. Case, announcing plans to assume the helm of the world's
largest media conglomerate on Monday was the fact that he wore a
suit and tie to do it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Case, 41, heads an Internet company perpetually
thought to be doomed and is known for clinging to his casual
costume of denim shirts and khakis on even the most formal
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But if his attire changes with his company's acquisition of Time
Warner, it should come as no surprise. Since the days of 300-baud
modems, Case has survived the Internet's accelerated evolution with
a series of transformations. His deal with Time Warner is only the
most recent.
</P>
<P>
   It is a character trait that did not go unnoticed by Time
Warner's chairman, Gerald Levin, who had shed his own tie before
Monday's news conference announcing the deal and who took a certain
relish in welcoming the ``suits from Virginia,'' where America
Online is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Steve proposed that I be CEO in that very first phone
call, it caught my attention, because it said something about who
he is,'' Levin said Monday of Case's approach. ``Here is someone
who has built an extremely successful company, still early in his
career, and he was saying `I'm going to give my baby to you as the
CEO because I think that is what's best for both companies.'''
</P>
<P>
   The decision underscored the combination of idealism and
pragmatism that has served Case well through several episodes of
turmoil. Seemingly shy and reserved, Case conceived of a grand
vision for America Online over a decade ago and refused to abandon
it, despite competition that seemed insurmountable and detractors
unwilling to be appeased.
</P>
<P>
   James Kimsey, the company's co-founder and former chairman, said
Case was weaned on crisis. In America Online's earliest years, the
company was constantly running out of money. Trying to find new
partners to carry it through was part of Case's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was well schooled in the harrowing ways of high tech and
particularly in an emerging medium,'' Kimsey said. ``We had very
few resources so we were forced to figure out how to get other
people to carry our water.''
</P>
<P>
   Case, who was raised in Hawaii and received a bachelor's degree
in political science from Williams College, spent his first
postcollege years working in marketing for giants like PepsiCo and
Procter &AMP; Gamble _ he helped invent the slogan ``Towelette? You
bet!'' and then watched the P&AMP;G product fail.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1983, when he hooked up his Kaypro computer to an early
version of an online service, he began to envision an interactive
world where people all over the country could gather. At a company
then known as Quantum Computer Services, he and Kimsey pursued that
vision.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was that IBM and Sears had a similar idea.
Their venture, Prodigy, was an online service started a year before
America Online and had parents with deep pockets, so it was easy
for industry watchers to see that the fledgling America Online
would lose that battle. But Prodigy, which was slower to introduce
Internet access and e-mail, stumbled as Case's company gathered
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Case, who frequently pops jelly beans during interviews, has
three children from his first marriage. He was remarried in 1998 to
Jean Villanueva, America Online's former communications chief, who
has since left the company.
</P>
<P>
   With the birth of the World Wide Web, industry pundits again
predicted the end for proprietary services like America Online. But
partly in response to the Web's popularity, the service switched to
flat-rate pricing in 1996 and attracted more interest than it could
handle. Its lack of preparation resulted in one of the worst
moments in the company's history, as millions of customers were
shut out with busy signals.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. Case quickly expanded capacity and announced a
series of executive appointments aimed at getting back in his
customers' good graces. With his frequently posted letters to
subscribers, Case fostered an image of the company as friendly and
open to criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In its first incarnation, America Online billed itself as an
online community. With the new executive team _ including Robert
Pittman, who had built the MTV brand _ in place, the company began
to advertise itself as a vehicle for convenience. Now it is looking
to expand its revenues from e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Once disdained by techies as poorly designed training wheels for
the real Internet, America Online last year acquired Netscape
Communications, a Silicon Valley darling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both grew up with a belief that change is good and should
be embraced rather than feared,'' said Daniel H. Case III, Case's
older brother, who is chief executive of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
``Growing up in Hawaii, you had to wonder: What'sundary?
When we went to college our father told us, `It's all a long way
away, why not go to the East Coast?' So if you're trying to invent
a new industry, why not be the leader?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Case's willingness to adapt to the changing environment does
not come without its casualties. He has pushed aside executives,
including Ted Leonsis, a former president who was once slated to
run the company's media ventures, when he decided on a change of
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In inviting Levin to be chief executive, Case displayed a shrewd
negotiating tactic, but perhaps at the expense of some America
Online executives who have run the company's day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Case says, he wants to evolve once more as chairman of Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade ago, AOL had less than 100,000 members and the World
Wide Web hadn't been invented,'' he said. ``Now I'm a billionaire
and on the cover of all these magazines, but I hope my personal
legacy is not about making money. It may sound corny, but I want to
focus on the things I care about. I want to change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Case will be able to exercise as much control over his
own company's evolution in the wake of a combination remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``With America Online, you always got the feeling that they
wanted you to like them,'' wrote one subscriber on an America
Online bulletin board on Monday. He added, ``I have never felt such
vibes from Time Warner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-10-00 2237EST &QL;
</P>
