<HEADLINE>
MERGER MAY BE AN INTERNET TRAILBLAZER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BRUCE RAMSEY   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online's merger with Time Warner is not just the biggest
merger deal ever.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the one that defines the next step for corporate
America on the Internet. And the obvious question is who is taking
the next step? Microsoft and Sony or Disney? Yahoo! and CBS?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is thinking of which deal is next,'' said Stewart
Halpern, who follows AOL for Banc of America Securities in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   There was little more than speculation, Monday. And it was
clearly affecting the stock market. Time Warner jumped by $27.50
per share Monday. But other media companies not part of the deal
started to dance, too: Walt Disney Co. up $4.75, Comcast up $5.44,
CBS up $4.06, Liberty Media up $8.44 and AT&AMP;T up $2.
</P>
<P>
   And the most frequently mentioned partners at this new hoedown
were Microsoft, Yahoo! and AT&AMP;T, News Corp., Sony, Viacom/CBS and
MGM.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition defines what a media company is going to look
like,'' said Paul Noglows, a managing director for Chase H&AMP;Q, the
former Hambrecht &AMP; Quist investment firm. ``We're not going to have
`new-media companies.' Every media company is going to have a
new-media component.''
</P>
<P>
   The AOL-Time Warner deal increases the pressure on everybody
else. ``There's questions about what Viacom does long term, and
Disney and certainly News Corporation,'' Noglows said. ``I don't
think anybody has an offering that's even close to what AOL Time
Warner's going to have.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL now gets control of Time Warner's cable-TV systems, cable-TV
programming (which it bought from Ted Turner), movies, music,
magazines and books _ a menagerie of ``content'' from executive
profiles in Fortune to the cartoon antics of Yakko, Wacko and Dot.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Internet service msn.com has nothing like it.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Tom Pilla said the acquisition
``demonstrates how differently people can view the market.''
Microsoft, he said, sees itself as ``a great software and services
platform company that will work with any media company that wants
to offer its content on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a big difference from the idea a few years ago that
Microsoft would become a media company on its own, starting with
Sidewalk, Slate and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Noglows said the AOL deal is a challenge to Microsoft, and ``I
think they're going to have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The AOL-Time Warner merger also challenges Internet companies to
invest in cable. The Time Warner cable systems, most of them local
monopolies, provide a ``broad-band'' conduit that can deliver
television and movies over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're AOL, you need that fast pipe,'' Halpern said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has also been investing aggressively in cable. Last
year it invested $5 billion in AT&AMP;T, $500 million in NTL Inc., $300
million in United Pan-Europe Communications and $400 million in
Rogers Communications Inc., the No. 1 cable company in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   For Paul Allen, the Mercer Island billionaire and Microsoft
co-founder who has been talking about ``broad band'' for a decade,
the AOL-Time Warner deal is a big ``I told you so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the No. 1 provider of narrow-band connectivity
merging with the No. 1 owner of cable companies. If that isn't a
huge lot cast with Paul Allen's wired world, I don't know what
is,'' said Bill Savoy, president of Allen's Vulcan Ventures in
Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   Savoy said the combination of Internet and television, long
talked about, is ``a foregone conclusion, at least at Time
Warner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it validates what Internet distribution is really
worth,'' said spokesman Mark Peterson of Allen-controlled Go2Net
Inc. in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, Go2Net has been part of Allen's effort to open up
his own ``fast pipe'' to 7 million homes connected to his cable
companies. It also has a deal with Hasbro, the company with rights
to Monopoly, Risk and Clue, to provide games over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A Seattle-area company with a direct stake is InfoSpace.com,
which provides software and content to AOL. Vice President Joni
Hanson said the merger ``is fine with us, because we provide
services to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger is also an example of Internet stock valuations.
Compare Time Warner with AOL. Three years ago, Time Warner was at
about $20 per share.
</P>
<P>
   It has gone up about 4.6 times, much of it Monday. Three years
ago, AOL was at about $1.50. It has gone up 48 times.
</P>
<P>
   But revenue at AOL is still less than one-quarter the size of
Time Warner. But its revenue is growing four times faster.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday's announcement, the market value of AOL was about
double that of Time Warner. That's why AOL bought Time Warner, and
not the other way around, even though AOL was founded only in 1985
and Time Warner goes back to the 1920s, when Time magazine and
Warner Brothers Pictures were founded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-11-00 0004EST &QL;
</P>
