<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-AOL-TIME-IMPACT-N     01-12 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-AOL-TIME-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN, TIME MAGAZINE AMONG BUSINESSES AFFECTED BY MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI and BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The America Online-Time Warner merger was such a closely guarded
secret that even the journalists who work for Time Warner, from its
magazines likes Time, Fortune and Money, to its television channels
like CNN, had no inkling it was about to happen. But it became
clear as the news spread Monday that the deal would have a
potentially enormous impact on the company's individual units.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate was seen for CNN, which would benefit from
the promotional strength offered by AOL's 20 million subscribers. A
huge impact, if not immediate, is also expected for Time Warner's
music division, which will become the first major record company to
be so closely affiliated with an Internet company with an ability
to deliver music online.
</P>
<P>
   One executive, who was involved in the deal but insisted on
anonymity, foresaw CNN becoming the key anchor of AOL's news area.
``The news area may be renamed CNN. Or I could envision a new area
that has the look and feel of CNN on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the clear goals for AOL has been to become more and
more important globally,'' said one senior executive who was
involved in the merger deal. ``And there is no more global brand
than CNN. The reality is that CNN will be part of a super charge
forward internationally by AOL.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the deal is completed, CNN is likely to be prominently
cross-promoted to Internet users by AOL, and CNN would
cross-promote AOL's services during its programs.
</P>
<P>
   AOL has an existing deal with CBS to be its broadcast news
partner. The executive involved in the merger agreement said, ``The
CBS deal is for a finite period of time.'' He added quickly, ``AOL
won't be making any efforts to push partners out. That would
obviously bring some interest on the anti-trust side. But the
agreement with CBS is for the USA only. AOL could do a CNN
international connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive said that news stories _ rather than appearing on
CNN first, then in a reformatted version online later _ could be
delivered to several news platforms simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   But executives at CNN emphasized that the chief executives at
both AOL and Time Warner had given complete assurances that CNN's
journalistic mission would not be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   The Warner Music Group, which has been in a free fall recently,
could also be transformed by the promotional and digital
distribution opportunities of AOL.
</P>
<P>
   It is that digital technology _ the ability of consumers to
easily and quickly download music directly off the internet _ that
prompted Robert W. Pittman, the president and chief operating
officer of AOL, to predict Monday that the new company will be
``doing for the next decade what the CD did for the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin said that because ``the music business is built on
exhibition,'' the merger with AOL would allow Warner Bros.
unprecedented promotional access to the millions of AOL daily
viewers. He also pointed out the benefit of finding musical talent
through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third, it's not an accident that music lends itself to
electronic commerce as a packaged good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Nathanson, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.,
said that the new alignment catapults Time-Warner and its ailing
music division onto a different plane and may change the
recorded-music industry at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL was happy to sell their audience eyeballs to other
companies trying to sell their own music,'' he said. ``But they
were not trying to advance the industry in terms of consumer
technology and now they have that obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No other of the four major record companies will have this
marketing and promotional clout, the ability to show 20 million
people the new Warner Bros. musical act every morning on AOL,'' he
said. ``It's impressive and it's hard to build that kind of traffic
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The music division posted third-quarter earnings in October 1999
of $76 million before interest, taxes and amortization, down from
$99 million in the third quarter the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of film, the transaction should give Time-Warner's film
studio, Warner Brothers, a vast new medium for distributing its
movies and television programs. Indeed, the merger is expected to
spur Warner Brothers' rival studios to move more aggressively onto
the Internet. Some analysts say there could be a spate of deals
between studios and Internet companies similar to those that have
already occurred in which filmmaking operations have been combined
with cable and television distribution, as exemplified by Viacom's
recent purchase of CBS. Hollywood in general has been somewhat wary
of the Internet, which is unfamiliar to Hollywood and is seen as
contributing to piracy of its programs and threatening its hold on
creating and distributing entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that upstart AOL has now swallowed the world's largest
media company is likely to contribute to a feeling of insecurity
among entertainment moguls, who are seeing their wealth surpassed
and their seats at the best Hollywood restaurants usurped by the
new media titans _ young e-commerce entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner Brothers has been more aggressive than most studios
in trying to exploit the Internet. In November it launched
Entertaindom, a Web site showing its Looney Tunes cartoons as well
as a variety of programs made just for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For Time Inc., Time-Warner's magazine division, the changes will
most likely manifest themselves first in the arena of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc.'s revenues for 1998 were $4.5 billion to Time-Warner's
$26.8 billion. Time Inc. will become a relatively smaller entity in
the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Time-Warner has tried to exploit the content of Time Inc.
magazines _ Time, People, Sports Illustrated and Fortune are among
the company's titles _ in the electronic universe. Its ardent but
foiled foray into the Internet, the Pathfinder portal, was shut
down last year, and since then it has been reconfiguring its
Internet presence under new management.
</P>
<P>
   Generally recognized as the highest-grossing magazine publisher
in the world, Time Inc. publishes 31 magazines that in 1998
accounted for 21 percent of the total advertising revenues
generated by U.S. consumer magazines. Combined advertising and
subscription revenue for People, Time and Sports Illustrated _
three of the top five highest-grossing magazines in the United
States _ tally up to almost $2.5 billion for 1998. The only
specific provision made for Time Inc. magazines in the announced
deal pertained to In Style magazine, Time Inc.'s frothy celebrity
fashion monthly, which America Online will begin to incorporate
into its Internet service, expanding on the content already
supplied to AOL by People, Teen People and Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Nelson, In Style's managing editor, said that the
magazine had been planning to introduce In Style.com in 2000, a
content and electronic commerce site that will offer clothing and
other goods for purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will clearly make it a more secure strategy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-10-00 2105EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
