<HEADLINE>
TIME TO GET REAL AND CHANGE THAT BATTERY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: When I bought my computer in 1994, the clock
was so accurate that I used to set my watch by it. A few weeks ago,
I noticed my clock was a few minutes off. This variance has now
gotten so bad that when I boot up each morning, my clock and date
will be as much as 48 hours late. _ Clock Watcher
</P>
<P>
   Dear Watcher: If your PC has been around since 1994, I'm
surprised the whole thing isn't falling apart. A computer of that
vintage can have all sorts of things go wrong: The steam turbine
bearings could burn out, the mainspring might go ``sproinng,'' and
even the hand crank could break off if the gearbox freezes.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing you might check is the clock battery. If I recall
correctly, yours is made of strips of metal suspended in a series
of acid-filled bell jars, connected by heavy-gauge wires. It's
probably worn out after all these years, so it can't hurt to get a
replacement, which you can get at just about any computer store.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to pop the top on the PC, find the old battery, then
make the switch, but that's relatively easy, especially if you're
one of the three or four computer owners in this country who hasn't
thrown away the manual. One precaution: Get into the PC's setup
program and write down all the stuff you find there in the event
that unhooking the old battery flushes your computer's identity
down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   I've never owned a computer with a real-time clock that didn't
stink, so I'm surprised that yours worked as well as it did. If the
battery doesn't fix things, get a time synchronizer from a
shareware site like www.tucows.com. These dealies go out on the
Internet and check the time at someplace official like the U.S.
Naval Observatory, then set your system clock. I'm assuming, of
course, that your Samuel Morse-autographed modem is still sending
out those dots and dashes.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: What are the pros and cons of leaving the
computer on all day as opposed to shutting it down? I am on and off
the Internet three or four times a day. What should I do? _ Chicken
or Egg
</P>
<P>
   Dear Egg: Stop spending so much time on the Internet and go
outside for some fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   Don't try to figure out who's right in this argument, because
it's been going on since some caveperson turned on the first
computer shortly after the dinosaurs disappeared. You leave the
thing on, and the moving parts will wear out as the accumulated
heat slowly fries things. You turn it on each time you sit down to
work, and the sudden surges of power will eventually kill things.
In real life, by the time any major damage is done either way, your
computer will be so obsolete you ought to replace it. Unless you're
the guy in the first question, that is.
</P>
<P>
   I turn mine off on those rare occasions when I haven't passed
out at the keyboard after a three-day Quake death match, but the
only reason I do is that I have a continuous connection to the
Internet with a nonchanging address, and I'm slightly paranoid
about all those nasty things I used to say about hackers. If you
use a dial-up account, you don't have that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: My regular telephone broke, and I wanted to use
the phone dialer in Win98. It dials OK and the call goes out OK,
but I don't hear the person's voice on my speakers. _ Mr. Watson's
Nightmare
</P>
<P>
   Dear Nightmare: Uh, the dialer only dials the number. You can't
actually use it to talk to other people. Got 10 bucks? Go buy a
phone.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay is ordinarily much meaner than that. He let
that last guy off entirely too easily. Something must be wrong.
E-mail your concerns to drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com (snail-mail:
Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax:
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-05-00 2036EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
