<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A WHOLE LOT OF COOKING IN THIS CD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Y2K has passed and home computers are still running,
let's assume the gas, electric and water services are still
working. That way, The Complete MasterCook Suite Featuring Betty
Crocker can be put to work in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The program (Windows; about $45-$50) is not simply another
cooking program, notes publisher SierraHome. It is five complete
recipe collections, making it the largest collection of Betty
Crocker recipes on CD-ROM. There are about 1,000 recipes from Betty
Crocker and another 5,000 from MasterCook Deluxe.
</P>
<P>
   The program allows users to search through recipes by
ingredient, watch video clips for instructions and develop
plan-ahead menus. Recipes can be imported from the Internet, and
the program can provide an instant analysis of any recipes. The
recipes can also be sent through e-mail to friends.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most impressive new features is an ``import
assistant'' which lets users take recipes from the Web and drop
them directly into the program. In addition, a rating system allows
cooks to customize a recipe's attributes based on personal judgment
to rank the recipe's spiciness, preparation time and other
qualities.
</P>
<P>
   The suite includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Crocker's Cooking Basics, with more than 100 simple
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Crocker's Best of Baking, featuring 350 baked recipes
ranging from break to desserts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Crocker's Best of Healthy and Hearty Cooking has more
than 400 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Crocker's Cookie Book offers 225 cookie recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MasterCook Deluxe 5.0 is a collection of more than 5,000 recipes
from food associations, well-known chefs and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   The suite also has a pantry management system and more advanced
search capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   MINDGYM: Here's a fun program that works the brain harder than
the mouse: Mind-Gym from Simon &AMP; Schuster Interactive. This series
of mental exercises with an attitude won the British Academy of
Film and Television Arts' Best Comedy CD award.
</P>
<P>
   The program's interface is like a gym, and a changing room
provides the center of activity. There, first-time users are told
to sign in, then given a series of puzzles and challenges to
determine mental strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it is off to three areas: a game room; pool of
ideas; and a think tank. There are progress reports along the way
and the challenges get harder as the player gets better.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com.) The
Ledger is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-07-00 1555EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3777 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE     01-12 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST PCS HAVE MAINTENANCE SOFTWARE, BUT USERS MAY WANT TO MAKE
ADDITIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: Santa was good to me. Got a new computer for
Christmas. Sure beats the old 486 I was using. I read your section
every week, but I want to know just what kind of software I need to
keep it running. Does it come with everything I need to maintain
it, or is there something I should buy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most modern PCs have a slew of features that help keep them
running well, but you have to know where they are and how to use
them. Most computer makers don't point you to them for a variety of
reasons, including worries that novices might do more harm than
good.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Windows 98 comes with a feature called the
Maintenance Wizard that automates the process of defragmenting your
hard drive, removing temporary files and scanning the hard drive
for errors. It can also be used to turn off programs that launch
automatically via the Startup folder. You can find this wizard in
the Accessories/System Tools folder.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful Windows feature overlooked by many users is the
System Information Utility, also found in Accessories/System Tools.
On the surface, it looks as though all it does is give you detailed
information about your system. But there's a Tools menu item that
is full of goodies, including programs that can restore missing or
corrupt files and another that can turn off even more items that
launch automatically through the Registry.
</P>
<P>
   There are other things you need for maintaining your PC that
don't come with it, or or if they do, they are anemic.
</P>
<P>
   For example, some PCs come with a virus scanner. But often it
includes only one or two free upgrades to a database of known
viruses. Since new viruses are found all the time, it's important
to keep your virus signatures up to date. You should either buy a
full-powered antivirus program or upgrade the one that came with
your computer. This is going to cost you some money, but you'll be
glad you did it. The two most popular are McAfee's VirusScan
(www.mcafee.com) and Norton AntiVirus (www.symantec.com).
</P>
<P>
   Also, all Windows users should have an un-install program on
their systems. Even though Windows comes with its own Add/Remove
Programs module in the Control Panel, you may find programs you
want to remove that don't have a listing there. This category of
software usually has other useful features, such as deleting
temporary files or transferring programs between drives or even
between computers.
</P>
<P>
   The two most popular are Norton's CleanSweep and McAfee's
UnInstaller.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you're willing to tackle problems yourself, you may
want to get a utility suite, such as McAfee Office 2000, Ontrack's
SystemSuite 2000 or Norton SystemWorks 2000. These are collections
of software designed to track down and fix problems. If you are a
serious novice but nervous about getting under the hood of your PC,
these programs can help.
</P>
<P>
   These suites also contain both antivirus and un-install
programs, and you save money by buying them as a package.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My new hobby is converting my old photos into digital
pictures on my computer. I've been using the JPG format, and have
been putting the pictures into ZIP files to save space. But I
notice that when I check the properties of the ZIPs, they don't
appear to have been compressed much. Is there any way to shrink
them further?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're trying to compress a file format that's already
compressed. The JPG format is ``tight'' already, and you're getting
only a couple of percentage points of extra compression by using
ZIP files. Unless you're working with larger file formats, such as
BMP, there's not much sense in using ZIP compression to store them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com. &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORYXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-07-00 1547EST &QL;
</P>
