<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIDDEN PROGRAMS THAT CAN THROW YOU
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If you're one of the many who found a new computer
under the Christmas tree, and that shiny new PC was bought from a
retailer, chances are you got a lot more than you bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a name-brand personal computer that uses Windows 98,
watch during the boot-up process at the number of icons that appear
in what's called the system tray, the area to the right in the
taskbar at the bottom of the screen that shows the time.
</P>
<P>
   You'll probably find at least half a dozen icons there in the
typical consumer computer bought at retail _ maybe more. Each one
represents a program running in the background. And that's only the
tip of the iceberg. There are usually even more active background
programs that don't place icons in the tray. You don't know they're
there unless you know how and where to look.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of these computers will tell you that these programs
add features that you'll like. But what they won't tell you is that
they can slow down a PC's performance, conflict with other programs
and possibly make your computing life a living hell.
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent, PC makers aren't solely to blame. The
services these background programs offer usually are useful and
well-intentioned. Manufacturers add these programs to make PCs
easier to use as well as to differentiate themselves from
competitors. You can also blame Microsoft's Windows 95/98 and the
way it manages what are called resources.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLOGGING POCKETS OF MEMORY
</P>
<P>
   Windows resources have little or nothing to do with the amount
of memory or hard-drive space on your computer. You can have
hundreds of megabytes of RAM and dozens of gigabytes of hard-drive
space and still run out of resources in short order.
</P>
<P>
   Resources are pockets of memory that Windows sets aside to
manage the operating system's status. They track such things as the
positions of open windows and applications, how memory is allocated
and what drivers are active.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of the legacy of Windows 3.1, the Microsoft shell
that protected early PC users from the horrors of the MS-DOS
command line. With the introduction of Windows 95, the amount of
resources increased dramatically. But modern programs take up more
resources than old Windows 3.1 software, so what was once a bounty
is again a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   This problem recently came to light with owners of new Compaq
Computer Corp. Presario machines. Owners of some models began
experiencing what appeared to be random lockups. But they weren't
random, and they weren't lockups.
</P>
<P>
   What was happening, according to a company spokeswoman, was that
Windows ran low on resources when a Compaq-specific application
kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   The program goes to a Compaq site on the Internet and checks for
updates to key software on the computer. The idea is to make it
easy to keep a system up to date. This is something many users
aren't aware should be done, or they don't know how, or they simply
don't want to be bothered. Automating the process, in theory, is a
good idea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SLOWDOWN LOOKED LIKE LOCKUP
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Presario owners, however, was that the program
would _ when combined with all the other programs that were running
_ drain Windows' resources. The systems would slow to a crawl,
which appeared to many users to be a lockup. In reality, the
computer had slowed down, and after a period of about a minute or
so, the spokeswoman said, activity would return to normal.
</P>
<P>
   But most users interpreted this slowdown as a lockup, and began
hitting buttons and clicking the mouse. This further overloaded
Windows' resources, and caused a real lockup, or a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has fixed this with a patch that changes how its own
software works. But it still doesn't address the root problem _
that many PCs are overloaded with background programs and Windows
can't handle that gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq is not alone in loading up its consumer PCs with
background programs, though the Houston-based company is certainly
zealous about it. Buy a system from Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Gateway
or a manufacturer that sells to consumers and you'll find virus
checkers, keyboard-button managers, video- and sound-settings
control panels, crash protectors and programs that check the Net
for updates. On computers that have rewriteable CD-ROM drives,
you'll find one or two more background programs running. And
notebook computers are even worse.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is aggravated by programs that users install later
that run even more background components. For example, install any
of the popular utilities suites, such as McAfee Office or Norton
SystemWorks, and watch your system tray get even more crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you can turn off a lot of these programs, disabling
them so they don't launch when your computer starts. On a Presario
5900 I recently tested, only 74 percent of system resources were
available on bootup. By turning off what I considered to be
non-essential, I got that number up to 89 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (You can find out how many system resources are available by
running the Resource Meter. Go to Start, Programs, Accessories,
System Tools, then click on Resource Meter. It appears as an icon
on the task bar and, yes, it also takes up resources. To learn how
to find and disable background programs, see the column I wrote
last February at
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/02/19/compute.html.)
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokeswoman said the company is working on ways of
increasing system resources in the next version of its consumer
operating system, which has the working name of Millennium and is
due out sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   But until Microsoft fixes the problem _ which, by the way, is
not a factor in Windows NT or the upcoming Windows 2000, both aimed
at corporate users _ PC makers should be more judicious in their
use of background programs. And they should work harder to make
sure their background programs use as few resources as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Users should be given a choice, either when they first turn on a
new computer or through a one-stop control panel, of what is
allowed to run in the background. Although you can do this now
through the System Information utility in Windows 98, it's not a
particularly friendly program. A graphical version, which clearly
explains what each program does and how many resources are
consumed, would be more useful.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can always vote with your pocketbook and buy
systems that are lean and mean. You'll send a message to PC makers,
and get a more stable computer in the process.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
