<HEADLINE>
`NEXT FRIDAY' A LOT LIKE `LAST FRIDAY'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
 
 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this sequel to the popular, crude comedy ``Friday,'' Ice Cube
once again plays the only reasonable man among a passel of lunatics
and excrement jokes. In that and most other ways, ``Next Friday''
isn't very much different from its predecessor. There is no Chris
Tucker in this one (which, though a mercy to some of us, will
disappointment many). And it largely takes place in Cucamonga
rather than South Central, which means nicer homes and cars, but
everyone in the suburbs is just as broad a caricature as the folks
in the first movie's 'hood were.
</P>
<P>
   As far as thematic variations on the concept go, that's about
it.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Cube's Craig _ despite being the smartest individual
in a several-mile radius _ still has no job. But he does have a
huge problem: Debo (Tiny Lister, reprising his ``Friday'' hulk) has
escaped from jail and is out to get the guy who so embarrassingly
whupped him.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing for his safety, Craig hides out in his lottery-winning
Uncle Elroy's (Don ``D.C.'' Curry) suburban digs. But even as Debo
slowly _ very slowly _ tracks him down, Craig discovers paradise
can be as wacky and dangerous as his old stomping grounds.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, his cousin Day-Day (Mike Epps, less irritating
than Tucker but not as funny, either) is being stalked by an
unhinged pregnant woman who Craig describes, in one of the film's
few witty lines, as ``worse than Left Eye from TLC.'' The hardcase
Latino ex-cons across the cul-de-sac will also prove problematic,
especially after Craig falls for their sweet sister Karla (Lisa
Rodriguez). And then there's the fact that irresponsible Uncle
Elroy has squandered the remains of his lottery winnings on chronic
and sex toys, and a serious property tax bill is coming due.
</P>
<P>
   There are also jokes about bad dogs, more drugs and every ethnic
stereotype imaginable. The pacing is leisurely at its quickest, and
the often broad performances are mainly adequate, with Cube's
controlled bemusement and Jacob Vargas' energetic portrayal of the
key bad neighbor standing out. John Witherspoon is back and more
manic than ever as Craig's dad, and Lister, once again, limits his
performance to barking threats and bonking people's heads.
</P>
<P>
   Cube wrote the script as well as produced. Music-video whiz
Steve Carr makes his feature-directing debut. If you liked the
first one, you probably won't care for this one as much but will
think it's OK. If you're not part of the franchise's apparently
devoted following, nothing in ``Next Friday'' is likely to make a
convert out of you. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: ``Next Friday'' (R; language, drug use, violence, sex). &QL; 
The stars: Ice Cube, Mike Epps, Justin Pierce, John Witherspoon,
Don ``D.C.'' Curry, Jacob Vargas, Lisa Rodriguez, Tommy ``Tiny''
Lister Jr. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Steve Carr. Written and produced by
Ice Cube. Released by New Line Cinema. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 33 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
