u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-NAMES-NY     01-12 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-NAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
800 INTERNET ADDRESSES REVOKED BECAUSE OF CHARACTER FLAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to avert a new twist on cybersquatting, the
body that oversees the Internet's address system said it was
revoking hundreds of new domain names because a software bug had
enabled people to claim addresses nearly identical to already
established Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The new trend, where people simply added a dash at the end of
registered addresses, resulted in new domains based on trademarks
like ``www.Microsoft-.com,'' ``www.yahoo-.com'' and a number of
short or catchy phrases, like ``inter-.net.''
</P>
<P>
   The revocation, approved late Tuesday night by the Internet
Corp. for Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann, is believed to the
first wholesale recall of Internet domain names. Officials said the
glitch was a byproduct of opening the lucrative business of
registering domain names to competition last year.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the revoked registrations, like
www.Microsoft-.com, could be classified as cybersquatting, the
practice of registering domain names with the intent of selling
them to others, especially trademark holders, at a hefty profit.
</P>
<P>
   Icann's president, Michael Roberts, said the more than 800
revoked addresses violated a long-standing policy that prohibits
any character but a numeral or letter at the end or beginning of a
domain name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake in the software,'' Roberts said. ``This was
something that shouldn't have been possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A check of the Internet addressing system's database indicates
that some of the registrations were made as early as November.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs who thought they had identified a new trend early
enough to cash in on it were crying foul Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Smith, the director of Consumer.net, a privacy resource for
consumers in Alexandria, Va., said he had registered 164 of the
now-revoked domain names at $30 apiece. He said neither Icann nor
BulkRegister.com, the company that registered his domains, had
informed him as of Wednesday that the registrations were invalid.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there were a mistake, he said, the domains should not be
revoked, as some people have already hired Web hosting services and
begun spending money on establishing a Web presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time they also had a rule that no numbers could be used
in domain names,'' Smith said, ``then 3Com came along and they
changed the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-05-00 1914EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
