<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3787 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-FOX-LADN &LR;      01-12 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX TRIES TO CLEAN UP ITS ACT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox Television Entertainment Group chairman Sandy Grushow
conceded Tuesday what everyone pretty much already knew: It's been
a lousy season for the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a press conference during the semi-annual TV Press
Tour, Grushow _ who was installed to oversee the network in
November after its disastrous fall premiere _ was blunt in his
assessment of the network's performance and its over-reliance on
stunt ``reality'' programming. ``It has been a pretty challenging
and dissatisfying year,'' Grushow said, ``but it was one that has
been several years in the making.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox failed to prepare for ``the natural aging of our franchise
programs, we failed to replace them with new franchise shows, and
we overly relied on the quick fix of shock programs, to the
dilution of our valuable brand identity,'' Grushow continued.
``Saturating the network with blood-and-guts reality specials has
undercut what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that many of the specials oriented on themes of
destruction and human suffering that have already been produced
will not be aired on the network.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing Fox's change in direction, he talked up new
production deals with respected Hollywood talents. Chief among
these are a new series from ``ER'' creator Michael Crichton, about
which details have yet to be decided, as well as a long-term deal
with ``Ally McBeal'' creator David E. Kelley, two sitcoms from the
Carsey Werner production company (``That '70s Show'') and a series
entitled ``Dark Angel'' from filmmaker James Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works: A live-action version of the comic book and
animated series ``The Tick,'' from filmmaker Barry Sonnenfeld;
``Fearsome,'' a series from the production company behind the film
hit ``The Blair Witch Project''; and ``The Street,'' a Wall Street
drama from ``Sex and the City'' creator Darren Starr. Actor Tom
Hanks is also developing a series for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   And, he vowed with particular vitriol while referring to a
previously reported piece of stunt broadcasting, ``The American
public will never see a 747 crash in the Mojave Desert on Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the high-profile washout of ``Action,'' a sitcom
that might have been controversial had audiences actually watched
it, Grushow said: ``I would rather fail with quality than succeed
with garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox entertainment president Doug Herzog _ joking that, ``Despite
appearances to the contrary, `beleaguered' is not part of my
official title'' _ likewise conceded defeat. ``We had a bad fall _
not like Sofia- Coppola-in-'Godfather III' bad, but
!ital!really!off! bad.'' Herzog admitted that the network's
association with the shock-reality programming had tainted its
image, which won't be immediately repaired once those specials
leave the network. ``Even if we went off them cold turkey, it'll
take years to shake that reputation _ it'll stay with the public,
it's hard to shake,'' Herzog said.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog also allowed that the network is ``not terribly proud''
of ``Greed,'' the game show the network rushed onto the air in the
wake of the phenomenal success of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
on ABC. Grushow added that ABC's reliance on that show's popularity
could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ABC spends a lot of time and energy in promoting
`Millionaire' at the expense of other quality series, they could be
left high and dry,'' Grushow said.
</P>
<P>
   Placing Grushow above Herzog at the network was seen in some
circles as a sign that Herzog _ who has only been in his job for a
year _ was in trouble. Grushow declined to say that Herzog's
position was secured, but said that their working relationship was
growing. ``We were obviously just thrown together, and we're just
getting to know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The network enjoyed its first piece of encouraging news in
months, with the highly rated debut of the critically lauded comedy
``Malcolm in the Middle'' on Sunday evening. ``Malcolm'' scored
Fox's highest rating for a series premiere in a decade _ since, in
fact, Fox mainstay ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great script, the show had a clear voice, and there
was a masterful job of directing,'' Grushow enthused. ``It's very
true to itself.'' He said that the decision to keep the show from
premiering in the fall and bringing it in as a midseason
replacement helped it's success ``a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about Fox _ when we get it right, it's a
cultural phenomenon,'' Grushow said. ``When we get it wrong, it's
ugly.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
