<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER BRIEFS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEB SITE OFFERS HELP WITH IRS PENALTIES
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common problems business owners face is being
hit with a penalty by the Internal Revenue Service for not
complying with its intricate rules for quickly turning over to the
government the income and payroll taxes withheld from paychecks.
Now some relief is available from a company that makes tax
software.
</P>
<P>
   At www.taxpenalty.com, a site owned by TimeValue Software of
Irvine, Calif., business owners can list the amount of their
payments and other data to check how much penalty, if any, is due
for late payments or underpayments. While IRS agents have been
shown in some cases to have guessed at the penalty, TimeValue built
its own database to calculate penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS proposed 3.7 million penalties in 1997 totaling $3.23
billion, an average of nearly $900 per case. That means penalties
were sought for about one of every seven payroll tax reports,
TimeValue estimated. The IRS reduces the penalties in about
one-fifth of the cases, but the remaining penalties still totaled
$1.2 billion, or an average of nearly $400 per case in 1997 _ the
most recent year for which data are available.
</P>
<P>
   Often the IRS proposes a larger penalty than is required under
the complex rules on timing of payments, said Tom Persky, a former
IRS executive who designed TimeValue's penalty calculation
software.
</P>
<P>
   He said 91 percent of the businesses that had used TimeValue's
site since it was launched in August had had their penalties
reduced or eliminated. He said that on average penalties are
reduced 44 percent after using the site.
</P>
<P>
   TimeValue, which is privately owned, charges $49 if its site
determines that a proposed penalty should be reduced by $500 or
more. If the penalty reduction is less than that, or no reduction
is warranted, the service is free. The site generates a printout to
send to the IRS to apply for a reduction in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE CAPITALIST'S PLAN TRIPPED UP BY NCAA
</P>
<P>
   When John Hummer, co-founding partner of Hummer Winblad Venture
Partners, the Silicon Valley venture capital firm, created a
collegiate competition for Internet business plans, he figured
``March Madness'' had a nice ring to it.
</P>
<P>
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association thought otherwise,
telling Hummer Winblad that the name infringed on a trademark
reserved for the NCAA basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Hummer expected better treatment. He had participated in the
collegiate tournament as Princeton's starting center in 1969, long
before the postseason playoff was known as March Madness. But the
6-foot-9-inch Hummer, who went on to a six-year career in the
National Basketball Association and averaged 6.9 points a game,
knew better than to fight the NCAA on the point.
</P>
<P>
   The new name for the Hummer Winblad tournament is the February
Madness Start-Up Tournament: Nothin' but the Net. Not exactly a
slam dunk, but at least it evokes the basketball court _ and keeps
Hummer out of court.
</P>
<P>
   _ BOB TEDESCHI
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-09-00 2048EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
