</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-BOOKBUYING-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET SHOWS SIGNS OF BECOMING TOP MARKETPLACE IN THE BOOK 
BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new holiday survey of seasoned Internet users indicates that
customers are straying from the bookshelves to buy titles online,
with a majority actually making more literary purchases in virtual
book shops than in standard stores.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting released the results last week of an
eight-day survey that showed that old-fashioned shopping remains an
enduring and robust custom but that books are the leading product
that this bellwether group of customers prefers to purchase online.
</P>
<P>
   Books and videotapes were the only items that more people bought
online than in stores, according to the survey, which polled 541
Internet users between Dec. 27 and Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This confirms that books are the leading edge of the
transition in shopping that's taking place across the economy,''
said David Brodwin, an associate partner who tracks media and
entertainment for Andersen Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven percent of the shoppers bought books online while 37
percent made purchases through traditional stores and the remainder
through catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, video customers made 35 percent of their purchases
through Web sites and 30 percent through physical stores.
</P>
<P>
   The same participants also were involved in a similar October
study. The surveys have a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books are much less risky to buy than buying a piece of
apparel so books have really taken off as a category,'' Brodwin
said, noting that a barrage of advertisements and marketing efforts
from companies like Amazon.com and Barnesandnoble.com had
apparently helped to reassure customers.
</P>
<P>
   He added that among the shopping categories, which ranged from
clothing and toys to computer software and consumer electronics,
books stood out as a safe electronic purchase.
</P>
<P>
   For example, customers can more easily mimic the retail shopping
experience in a store, by browsing chapters of books posted online.
Still, there appears to be a split developing between men and
women. Men appeared to prefer online shopping; 56 percent of the
men bought books over the Internet, compared with 40 percent of
women.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey suggests there are still limits to Internet
shopping. For example, 81 percent of the customers bought clothing
in conventional stores and 29 percent from electronic stores. The
numbers add up to more than 100 percent because of overlapping
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   And at the same time, the customers reported that the digital
shopping experience was not always smooth. Nine out of 10 shoppers
abandoned their electronic shopping baskets at some point during
their browsing.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly 40 percent reported some problem with the Internet
shopping experience, although they claimed the highest satisfaction
level with that form.
</P>
<P>
   The leading complaint was about out-of-stock products. After
that, users bemoaned that purchases were not delivered on time or
delivery charges were excessive. They also had trouble making
connections or navigating a site.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the dominant and overwhelming complaint about
holiday shopping in traditional stores centered on too many people:
overcrowding, long lines, limited parking. The exception to that
was another dominant complaint: the dearth of sales help to answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge with Internet shopping is that there's a
tremendous amount of capacity needed to do the site right,''
Brodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way of looking at this,'' he added, ``is that Internet
shopping is not so great. It still has profound flaws. The key
message is that these companies that want to play in this space
have got to fix these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-09-00 1822EST &QL;
</P>
