<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-REALNET     01-12 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-REALNETWORKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALNETWORKS GUNNING FOR MICROSOFT IN MEDIA-PLAYER SOFTWARE DUEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ When history records the names of Microsoft's great
adversaries, one that might someday join the list alongside Apple,
Netscape and America Online is an Internet company called
RealNetworks.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the intensifying competition, both companies
announced partnerships during the Consumer Electronics Show here to
utilize their software.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by one of Microsoft's former executives, Rob Glaser,
RealNetworks makes so-called media player software _ programs that
companies use to send video and audio files over the Internet and
that consumers use to listen to and view those files.
</P>
<P>
   With some 95 million registered users of its software,
RealNetworks is thought to have a commanding lead in the
media-player market. But lately the company's success has whetted
the competitive appetite of Glaser's former boss, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   For several years Microsoft has had a media player of its own
tucked into the company's market-dominating Windows operating
system for personal computers. Only in the last 12 months or so,
though, has the company been stepping up its efforts to make the
Windows Media Player a central selling point.
</P>
<P>
   At the industry show here, RealNetworks announced an agreement
with Seagram's Universal Music Group, the biggest record label,
which will begin providing music for use with a RealNetworks music
player known as Jukebox. Microsoft, not to be drowned out,
announced that several new portable digital devices coming soon
from various manufacturers would be compatible with Microsoft's
Windows Media Player technology.
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly intense competition, which is taking on
overtones of the Microsoft vs. Netscape and Microsoft Network vs.
America Online battles, underscores how much is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, industry analysts say, the contest is not
only about which software will be used to listen to music, or view
video snippets. Instead, the outcome could determine which
company's technology may be the basis for how television, film,
music and other media are distributed and digested in the coming
digital environment known as convergence. By most accounts,
convergence is still many years away, but it could mean huge
business for the companies that sell software to media
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do have convergence, these streaming media players
could be the ones who dominate it,'' said Allen Weiner, vice
president of analytical services for Nielsen/NetRatings, an
Internet research organization. ``This is the most significant
battle in the marketplace today.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiner and numerous other industry analysts say that, for now,
RealNetworks has a substantial lead in distributing its main media
player, called RealPlayer. More important, they say, there is far
more media material on the Internet that is compatible with
RealPlayer than with the Windows Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Nielsen/NetRatings reported that in the month of
November, various versions of RealPlayer were used by 8.9 million
people on the Internet, representing 12.1 percent of active
Internet users. Microsoft's Windows Media Player was not only far
behind; with 2.4 million users and a market share of 3.2 percent,
it was not even in second place.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 in November was Apple Computer's Quick Time media player,
with 5.4 million users and a 7.4 percent market share. But in key
ways, some analysts do not see Apple Quick Time as a direct
competitor with the other two programs. Unlike Quick Time, the
RealNetworks and Microsoft players are meant for so-called
streaming media.
</P>
<P>
   With streaming media, the audio or video files remain on a Web
company's site and are played as a continuous stream by the end
user, but are not stored on the user's computer. With Quick Time,
popular for viewing material likes sports clips or movie previews
online, the file must be downloaded onto the user's computer and
then played back. Although Weiner considers Quick Time part of the
digital media future, he does not see it as part of the
streaming-media showdown between RealNetworks and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser, 37, who founded RealNetworks in 1994 after leaving his
position as vice president for multimedia consumer systems at
Microsoft, said he was ``hugely confident in our leadership
position.'' He said RealNetworks planned to expand beyond media
player software to provide an ``integrated suite of media
delivery'' that would include forums for selling copyright-secured
music online, for offering streams of free music and video and for
placing advertising alongside the media content.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this business model is already in place with
RealNetworks' Jukebox software, which consumers can use to store
and organize music collections on their computers. So far consumers
have registered 20 million copies of Jukebox. Microsoft has no
analogous product, although a handful of companies make Web-based
jukeboxes that are based on the Windows Media Player technology.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts note that the online media market is too new to yet
declare RealNetworks the winner. They note that Microsoft has begun
calling its Media Player a ``key component'' of the Windows
operating system. And Microsoft is bundling the player technology
with its industrial-strength Windows NT Server software, which a
Web company could use to disseminate both video and audio in the
Media Player format.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage to a Web media company, Microsoft executives say,
is that they get a media server and corporate computing software
system for a single price. ``Otherwise, you have to buy Sun plus
RealNetworks or Linux plus RealNetworks,'' said Anthony Bay, vice
president for streaming media at Microsoft, referring to competing
industrial-strength software systems. ``Why buy both?''
</P>
<P>
   But RealNetworks executives say that price is largely beside the
point. To begin with, most of the downloads of the RealNetworks
server software used by Web companies are free, according to the
company. And while licenses for the more enhanced versions cost
upward of several thousand dollars, they say such fees are minimal,
compared with the cost of network transmission capacity a company
needs to make audio and video accessible to many users
simultaneously _ whether Microsoft or RealNetworks software is
used.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts note, however, that it is difficult to dismiss
Microsoft's ability to leverage its dominance in the operating
system market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very similar behavior pattern'' to the way Microsoft
went after the Netscape market, said Rob Enderle, vice president
and research leader at Giga Information Group, a market research
firm in Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Neither Microsoft nor RealNetworks much likes drawing parallels
to Netscape, whose early dominance in the Web-browser software
field was undermined by Microsoft's bundling of its own browser
into Windows. For its part, Microsoft _ amid an ongoing antitrust
case involving that very issue _ does not want to be characterized
as wielding Windows as an anti-competitive weapon in the
media-player war.
</P>
<P>
   And RealNetworks, lest it be cast prematurely as a Microsoft
victim, says the current battle is more analogous to Microsoft's
less successful effort to unseat America Online with the Microsoft
Network.
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks executives say their company's advantage is not
simply its millions more users, but the fact that so much more of
the media content on the Internet has been formatted for use with
RealPlayer software _ at least 85 percent of the audio and video
files available on the Net, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft offers no figure of its own, though it does not
dispute that RealNetworks holds an advantage so far. Yet Microsoft
officials contend that their rival's advantage primarily involves
aging material on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are legacy files,'' said Dave Fester, director of
marketing for Microsoft's streaming media division, who noted that
most newer content is compatible with both companies' media-player
software. The Web sites of CNN, Fox and NBC , for example, stream
their audio and video in both the RealPlayer and Windows Media
formats.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever this battle may lead, the rhetoric has become
increasingly testy between the two companies. Enderle of Giga
Information Group thinks Microsoft is especially intense because
Glaser once testified against his former employer's hardball
tactics at a Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Glaser believes the intensity is simply part of Microsoft's
culture. ``As a motivation technique,'' he said, ``they like to
package targets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-09-00 1651EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
