 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
TV plus computer equals a wild world 
By Jack Warner  
c. 2000 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here I sit on a Sunday afternoon, watching the mating
ritual of the crested iguana on the Animal Planet channel and
playing solitaire, all on the same screen. Does it get any better
than this?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, it can get a lot better than this, but we needn't go
into that.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt a lot of you are saying something like ``Oh, come on,
TV cards have been around for years.'' It reminds me of an e-mail I
got last week from a reader in Colorado who found it hard to
believe that a computer expert could make such an ordeal out of
formatting his hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   You, sir, have mistaken me for an expert. I am no expert. I am
comparable to the Brazilian tree frog, which I have just learned
may be mistaken for bird droppings until it moves. I'm here to make
the cyber-inept feel comfortable. Together, we muddle through, like
the African bullfrog, which, I see, squirms its ample rump into the
mud until it is completely encased, thus surviving 10 months of
drought.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having established and even justified my incompetence,
let's return to the subject of television on the computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not watching it from a card, but by way of a device called
the Lifeview USB LifeTV box, a snazzy little purple-and-gray box
that plugs into your USB port and your TV antenna or cable
connection. After installing the software, it appears in a little
box about 4 by 5 inches. I suppose it could be made larger, but 4x5
is large enough for iguanas and tree frogs. Adjustment may be
required should I encounter Pamela Anderson Lee or some similar,
larger creature.
</P>
<P>
   Audio comes from the box, although it can be fed into the
computer's audio system. An S-video input, such as you would want
for attaching a video camera, is available. So is software that
will capture still pictures from the video image as well as store
video clips in the computer.
</P>
<P>
   All this is very handy for me, since the memsahib recently
appropriated the computer room TV for her quilting room. This was
fine by me, because I seldom watch television.
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago, I spent a year working in television. A few
days after joining the news operation of a local station, the
assistant news director found me asleep in a video editing room,
the video to be observed bubbling along unviewed. A nice lady, she
worried about me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you all right?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sure, I'm OK,'' I replied. ``I've just got this little
problem. Every time I watch TV, I go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant news director looked at me curiously for a moment.
``Then why did you come to work here?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   So you can see how I only lasted a year.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the USB LifeTV doesn't seem to have lasted even
that long. Upon selecting the URL for the Web site listed on the
box, I arrived at the home of a Southern California pipe vendor's
association. Undaunted, I searched for LifeTV and wound up at an
online computer catalog that said ``Sorry, not selling it anymore.
(Too many bugs.)''
</P>
<P>
   I haven't encountered any bugs yet, although after the frogs
there were a lot of surly baboons and some zebras.
</P>
<P>
   So, there you are, a report full of croaks and whinnies,
signifying nothing. Welcome to the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-01-10-00 1131EST &QL;
</P>
