 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
In the digital house of the future, gadgets will work from one
console 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 2000 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Get a sneak preview of the digital house of the
future, at least for the rich, in the January issue of PC
Computing. In an article titled ``The Totally Digital House,'' the
magazine runs down major electronic improvements on the way. They
include things like the Panja 1000. It's a housewide system that
lets you control every electronic device in a home from one place
with the click of a button. Or IBM's Smart Start, a digital network
system built into the house during construction.
</P>
<P>
   As everyone knows, the Internet is changing the way many
companies do business. Authors Arthur B. Sculley and W. William A.
Woods chronicle those changes in a book, ``B2B Exchanges.'' The
authors make the bold claim that the rise of electronic commerce
will force most businesses to reinvent themselves. Published by ISI
Publications, ``B2B Exchanges'' retails for $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme, publisher of electronic atlases, has released the
latest version of Street Atlas USA for the Macintosh. This version,
labeled 6.0, features updated road information and the highlighting
of one-way roads in major cities. DeLorme has also improved its
door-to-door route instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Test your knowledge of the outdoors with a new computer CD game
titled ``Cabela's Outdoor Trivia Challenge.'' The game lets one to
three people play against each other or the computer. Questions
cover such topics as ecology, fishing, hunting, outdoor survival
and wildlife. Published by Head-Games, ``Outdoor Trivia Challenge''
is available only for PCs with Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of museums are putting representations of their
collections online. An example is the Smithsonian Institution's
American Art Museum. It has posted some 4,000 images online. You
can browse these images randomly or by artist. You'll find this
site at AmericanArt.si.edu/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
