 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Inexpensive printer targets young girls 
By James Cummings  
c. 2000 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you're a young lady with a new computer or
someone who has such a young lady in the family, you have until the
end of the month to buy a Barbie printer at a significant discount.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo, a division of Hewlett-Packard, normally sells its Barbie
model printer for $89.99. But you can get a $40 rebate on printer
purchases made by Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, one of the best-known computer accessory
companies, started marketing its inexpensive Apollo line last year.
The Apollo printers use HP Inkjet Technology like models costing
several hundred dollars, but they sell for less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   The Barbie printer is pink and white and comes with Barbie
decals to decorate the printer body. It comes packaged with a
Barbie Hair Styler CD-ROM that allows girls to experiment with
onscreen hairstyles for Barbie characters.
</P>
<P>
   The printer is not as fast and doesn't have the resolution of
more expensive models, but it's designed to handle the homework,
play and craft projects its young owners probably are interested
in. It can produce low-resolution color drafts at a rate of 1.5
pages per minute, and its highest color resolution is 300 by 300
dots per inch.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo printers offer easy set-up through the computer's
parallel port, and the installation process is guided by onscreen
help prompts. Apollo also offers round-the-clock toll free
telephone support.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo printers are being marketed nationally through Office
Depot, Wal-Mart and Best Buy stores. You can get additional
information, including online shopping sources, by visiting
www.myapollo.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
