<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-DELL-STORY11-COX &LR;      01-12 3968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DELL-STORY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Dell's direct line to the future 
By Jerry Mahoney  
c. 2000 Cox News Service  
 &HT;    AUSTIN, Texas _ The story of Dell Computer Corp. and Michael
Dell, its 34-year-old founder, chairman and chief executive, is
sprinkled liberally with superlatives like ``first,'' ``most'' and
``youngest.''
 &HT;    The company was the first big company to sell computers via the
Internet and the most profitable personal computer maker in the
'90s. Along the way, Michael Dell became the youngest CEO to lead
his company into the Fortune 500 and by far the richest American
younger than 40.
 &HT;    Now Dell can add to the list the title of best-performing stock
on the Nasdaq exchange in the 1990s. Shares of the Round Rock,
Texas, company appreciated 88,000 percent in the past decade. One
hundred dollars invested in Dell stock 10 years ago and held
through all seven splits would have grown to $88,000 today. During
the 1990s, which the personal computing industry might remember as
the Decade of Dell, the company evolved from upstart PC maker to
No. 1 in the United States.
 &HT;    Dell's success forced bigger rivals to copy parts of its direct
sales approach. And Michael Dell, once an introverted entrepreneur
who seemed uncomfortable in front of an audience, is now regarded
as a guru of e-commerce. Even giants of the Industrial Age, such as
Ford Motor Co., are seeking his guidance on doing business over the
Internet.
 &HT;    In an era of exuberant expectations, the question inevitably
comes up: What can Dell do for an encore?
 &HT;    Michael Dell _ intense, driven and curious himself about what
his company can achieve _ has no plans to slow down.
 &HT;    He believes Dell can ship four times as many computers in 2004
as it did in 1999.
 &HT;    ``If we were to increase our market share from only 9 percent
last year to only 20 percent, which is probably a goal that's too
low, that would be 47 million units for Dell in 2004,'' Dell said
in an interview last week.
 &HT;    That goal, modest or not, is based on his expectation that
worldwide personal computer sales will soar 69 percent by 2004 and
that Dell will account for more than half of that growth.
 &HT;    But then Michael Dell, who will be 35 on Feb. 23, may be the
most bullish executive in the personal computer industry. He
derides talk of the ``post-PC era'' as ``nonsense.''
 &HT;    ``The real question is whether a company can grow and expand,''
he said. &HT;    MORE OF A CURIOSITY
 &HT;    These days, it's common to hear about young techheads launching
Internet-based start-ups in cramped offices and becoming
multimillionaires when they sell stock to the public. They are
riding the financial tsunami created by Wall Street's infatuation
with electronic commerce and the Internet.
 &HT;    Michael Dell didn't have the Internet to inspire him for the
first 11 years of Dell Computer's existence. Instead, he invented a
radical new way of doing business that conveniently realizes its
full potential on the Internet.
 &HT;    He recognized the opportunity early on and seized it. But it was
serendipity, too, a necessary ingredient in every story of
phenomenal success. It didn't hurt that the establishment in the
personal computer industry viewed Dell as more of a curiosity than
a threat in the early 1990s.
 &HT;    Traditionalists believed that the then-Austin company's new idea
to sell computers directly to customers would fail in key segments
of the market, such as corporations. After all, big companies had
never bought computers directly from the manufacturer before.
 &HT;    The nerdy college dropout, complete with pocket protector and
black horn-rimmed glasses, was convinced that companies would grab
the chance to order a computer configured the way they wanted at a
lower cost and with better service than the big companies offered.
 &HT;    ``We basically had the foresight to break the rules of
traditional business, and we came up with a new set of rules that
were very effective for us,'' Dell said last week. ``And we stuck
by them.''
 &HT;    By the time bigger competitors understood the threat, sometime
in the middle of the decade, the Texas upstart was too big _ and
had too much momentum _ to stop.
 &HT;    In the second half of 1999, Dell achieved his goal and overtook
archrival Compaq Computer Corp. as the top seller of personal
computers in the United States, the world's biggest market.
 &HT;    The research and consulting firm, International Data Corp., said
in a report on the third quarter of 1999 that Dell is closing in on
No. 1 worldwide.
 &HT;    ``Dell continued its long march to market dominance,'' the
December report said. ``For the first time, the Austin-based dynamo
outstripped Compaq in a worldwide category: the commercial desktop
segment.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HISTORY OF THE COMPANY
 &HT;    Michael Dell likes to recount a revelation he had in 1982, when
he was still a high school senior in Houston. While upgrading
friends' computers for spending money, he figured out that IBM's
machines were selling for $3,000, but contained less than $700 in
parts. And he could buy the same parts.
 &HT;    ``Not only was there a high price markup from the dealer to the
customer, but there was an even higher markup from the manufacturer
to the dealer,'' Dell recalls in his book ``Direct from Dell:
Strategies that Revolutionized an Industry,'' published last year.
 &HT;    He enrolled in pre-med courses at the University of Texas in the
fall of 1983, where the computer hobby became his life's dream. By
January 1984, a month shy of his 19th birthday, Dell was moving
more than $50,000 a month in upgraded computers and parts through
his dormitory room in Jester Hall. In the spring, he incorporated
his business as PC's Limited and dropped out of college.
 &HT;    As the 1990s began, the company now called Dell Computer Corp.
had sales of $546 million, $27 million in profit and 2,000
Austin-area employees _ a tenth of its current work force.
 &HT;    Like Southwest Airlines, whose lower-cost operation allows it to
undercut prices of traditional carriers, Dell's success highlighted
the shortcomings of its competitors.
 &HT;    For the most part, computer makers went about their business in
the time-honored fashion: forecast what customers wanted, buy huge
stocks of inventory to build to those forecasts and mark up prices
to cover the costs of buying and holding the inventory.
 &HT;    Dell, meanwhile, was hearing what customers actually wanted
because it dealt with them directly. It avoided costly inventories
of parts and completed machines because it only made computers
ordered and paid for in advance. The result was less-costly
computers and better service. Moreover, working closely with
suppliers allowed Dell to avoid designing and making components
itself.
 &HT;    ``If we hadn't done any one of those, I don't think we would be
where we are today,'' Dell said.
 &HT;    While they scoffed at first, as far back as 1992, Compaq and
others were hedging their bets against Dell and trying to copy
aspects of the direct model.
 &HT;    ``The problem was they didn't understand what we were doing, and
they set it up wrong and it failed,'' Dell said. ``I think this
business of continuously not understanding what the threat is has
been going on for a long time. I think it even goes on today.''
 &HT;    Recently, other companies have acknowledged that they have to
compete on Dell's terms.
 &HT;    IBM last year pulled its consumer line out of retail. Last week,
Compaq paid $370 million for a distribution system that will allow
some of its biggest customers to order what they want and check
order status on the Web.
 &HT;    In a clear admission of Dell's impact, Compaq President Mike
Capellas said the direct system should increase the company's
sagging profits.
 &HT;    ``We'll be better equipped to meet the diverse and changing
needs of our U.S. customers, particularly our major accounts, which
clearly want to go direct,'' he said.
 &HT;    IDC, the research firm, said Dell's third-quarter revenue grew
twice as fast as its nearest competitors.
 &HT;    ``The Texas juggernaut continued to be the biggest share taker
of the total dollar pie,'' IDC said. ``Evidence also indicated
that, as a group, direct vendors ... gained ground on indirect
vendors.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOT EVERYTHING WORKED
 &HT;    Even in the fiercely intense world of high-tech companies, Dell
stands out. And like its accomplishments, its mistakes stemmed from
a relentless drive to grow.
 &HT;    In 1991, Michael Dell saw an industry consolidation coming. He
believed smaller companies such as his would be relegated to niche
markets, if they survived at all.
 &HT;    ``If we had stayed a small PC company, we would have been
killed,'' Dell said in his book. He was right about consolidation,
but hypergrowth in 1992 threatened Dell.
 &HT;    Compaq started a price war in 1992 with a new line of computers
that undercut the competition. Dell responded with 49 new products,
including the Dimension line of desktop computers for small
businesses and consumers.
 &HT;    Revenue shot up 127 percent and profits doubled. In April 1992,
the board of directors authorized a three-for-two stock split, the
company's first. Dell doubled its worldwide market share to 3.5
percent and elbowed its way from 11th to fifth among computer
makers.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, struggling Northgate Computer Corp. was forced to
sell out to a rival, and debt-laden Packard Bell Electronics Inc.
postponed a public stock offering. Several electronics companies,
including the Magnavox division of Philips Electronics N.V. and
Korea's Goldstar, gave up selling PCs under their own labels.
 &HT;    Dell was bigger, but in trouble.
 &HT;    ``We hit the wall in spectacular fashion and splintered into
thousands of pieces,'' Dell said in the book. ``And we had to pick
them all up and learn some new lessons.''
 &HT;    Scrambling to get overwhelmed systems up to the new speed, the
company ran into more problems in 1993. Cash was tight and Dell was
forced to cancel a planned secondary public stock offering when its
stock price weakened.
 &HT;    PC Magazine named Michael Dell its Man of the Year in the fall
of 1993. It cited Dell Computer's innovative sales, service and
manufacturing systems, which gave customers more choices.
 &HT;    Dell lost $76 million in the spring of 1993, including $39.3
million on notebook computer projects, abandoned because they would
have been behind the curve by the time they hit the market. It
finished the year with a $39.6 million loss _ the only time in the
company's history that it lost money.
 &HT;    Other problems loomed.
 &HT;    In August 1993, the Bureau of Export Administration of the U.S.
Commerce Department subpoenaed records of Dell's sales to Russia,
Iran, Iraq and Ireland. All investigations except the Iran sales
were closed without any findings of wrongdoing.
 &HT;    But in 1996, Dell paid $50,000 to settle a civil complaint. The
company acknowledged that in 1992, it mistakenly shipped 15 PCs to
Iran, which the U.S. government said had ties to terrorists.
 &HT;    Adding to Dell's 1993 woes, Compaq was making a stunning
turnaround by cutting costs and overhauling marketing and
manufacturing strategies.
 &HT;    In 1994, the company paid $13.4 million to settle a lawsuit by a
group of shareholders who alleged that Dell withheld information
when it was losing money in the spring of 1993.
 &HT;    But Dell roared back financially in 1994. GOOD CAME OF BAD
 &HT;    Looking back, 1994 was a major turning point for Dell. Seeds
were sown for the unprecedented growth and prosperity of the second
half of the decade, including six two-for-one stock splits.
 &HT;    At 29, Michael Dell knew his company needed stronger management.
He recruited Mort Topfer, recently retired from Motorola Inc., as
vice chairman in May 1994. The avuncular Topfer guided the company
in critical areas such as long-range planning and overseas
expansion.
 &HT;    That year, Dell ended its two-year experiment with retail sales.
Sales were strong, the company said, but profit was weak.
 &HT;    Finally, Dell started a Web site that allowed Internet-savvy
customers to get technical support. But a number of customers told
Dell they wanted to choose a computer and its specific features and
price alternatives online.
 &HT;    It was another example of how Dell's customers helped it evolve.
 &HT;    Dell allowed that late in 1995, and although it still took a
phone call to close the sale, customers' responses to Dell.com
convinced Michael Dell that the Internet was a natural extension of
the direct model.
 &HT;    ``The only thing more direct is mental telepathy,'' he has said
more than once.
 &HT;    By the end of 1996, Dell's online sales were $1 million a day.
Three years later, Dell.com brings in more than $35 million a day.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BUILDING A TEAM
 &HT;    Michael Dell, the longest-tenured CEO of a technology company,
was often dubbed an upstart, wunderkind or enfant terrible for the
way his company made life difficult for seasoned executives at
bigger companies, such as Compaq, IBM and Hewlett-Packard.
 &HT;    Dell's survival at the top and his evolution from entrepreneur
to chief executive is directly related to his willingness to
acknowledge areas where he needs help and to hire people to provide
it.
 &HT;    Michael Dell says that trying to hire good managers when the
company was still seen as a high risk was a ``tremendous
obstacle.''
 &HT;    ``The idea of going to work for a small company was not very
attractive to a lot of people,'' he said.
 &HT;    Stock options, now a common recruiting lure for high-tech
companies, were not well understood.
 &HT;    ``Most people, when you gave them a stock option, thought you
were trying to trick them,'' he said. ``We'd explain it and they
would say, `What was that again?'''
 &HT;    In 1998, Dell offered options as a way to keep employees. It
gave all employees 200 stock options and said new hires during the
next 10 quarters would also get them. The options allow employees
to buy 20 percent annually for five years.
 &HT;    Senior executives are hired with similar incentives, except
their options run in the hundreds of thousands.
 &HT;    Through the years Dell's drive remained, and it has infused the
company's culture, friends and associates said.
 &HT;    Pete Winstead, an Austin lawyer who has done both business and
personal work for Dell, recalls getting an e-mail recently from him
in which he confessed, ``I was born impatient.''
 &HT;    The intensity and the pace at the company _ where Dell works
standing up rather than sitting at a desk _ can be trying for
employees. The company uses precise measurements that compare goals
with actual performance. Raises, bonuses and job security are tied
to meeting ambitious goals.
 &HT;    Jerry Gregoire, at the time Dell's senior vice president and
chief information officer, told fellow CIOs at a meeting last year
that Dell is a ``very driven and demanding place.''
 &HT;    ``We have a growth trajectory that has us processing 60 percent
more transactions than we were processing just 12 months ago and
has us growing by at least that over the next 12 months,'' he said.
 &HT;    Gregoire had been a chief information officer for about 24
years, including 10 at Pepsi Cola Co., before joining Dell. He
retired in October, at age 47, to raise horses on his Austin-area
ranch.
 &HT;    ``I don't think that anything I have ever done up until now did
much to prepare me for what I'm experiencing at Dell,'' he said
last year.
 &HT;    Topfer recently announced he would retire in two years, but
executive-level turnover has not been a problem. Of 11 vice
presidents in 1995, seven are still with Dell. Steve Dube, of the
New York stock firm Wasserstein Pirella &AMP; Co., says Dell has the
strongest management team in the industry. Compaq, for example,
replaced at least five senior executives in 1999.
 &HT;    The stability includes the man at the top. Rod Canion at Compaq
and Steve Jobs at Apple Computer Inc. were fired within 10 years of
starting their companies. Michael Dell, who still owns about 14
percent of the company, has been at the helm for 15 years.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    DELL VS. COMPAQ
 &HT;    Compaq's rise in the mid-'90s as the No. 1 personal computer
maker made it a natural target for Dell, which wants to be first in
every segment of the industry. The two Texas companies became more
than rivals during the '90s _ they became enemies. Dell's success
played a role in the firing of Canion in 1991, after the company
suffered its first quarterly loss.
 &HT;    Eckhard Pfeiffer, who succeeded Canion as CEO and helped build
Compaq into a global power, seemed at times to be obsessed with
Dell.
 &HT;    ``I hate to use this word `direct' in any form,'' Pfeiffer told
Computer Reseller News in May 1997, when asked about Compaq's plans
to fight Dell on Dell's turf.
 &HT;    ``Talk about trying to duck a problem,'' Dell said last week
about the comment, which he had not heard before.
 &HT;    Pfeiffer was fired last April as Compaq faced huge losses and
damaged credibility on Wall Street.
 &HT;    Michael Dell is unfazed by the attacks of his rivals.
 &HT;    ``Having an enemy in the business is not all bad. It gives you
some focus,'' he said, ``but I think the primary focus really has
to be on the customers.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    THE INTERNET OPPORTUNITY
 &HT;    While competitors tried to mimic Dell's model, Dell further
exploited the Internet. Suppliers use the Web to monitor orders
from Dell customers as they come in. This link with customers
through Dell tells them when to deliver more components, which in
turn allows Dell to store and pay for minimal inventory.
 &HT;    The server business provides a telling example of the benefits
of what Michael Dell calls ``virtual integration'' and the direct
model.
 &HT;    In 1996, the company decided to launch a major effort to sell
servers, which are powerful computers that connect networks of
terminals and Web sites. It was an industry secret that Compaq,
which invented the server business, and IBM and Hewlett-Packard
were counting on fat profit margins for servers to subsidize
less-profitable products such as desktops and notebooks.
 &HT;    By the third quarter of 1997, Dell's servers and workstations
accounted for 10 percent of its sales, or nearly $300 million.
Analysts agreed that Dell forced competitors to drop prices on
servers about 15 percent, which further squeezed their profits.
 &HT;    Moreover, with results like that, Dell regularly blew past Wall
Street's expectations. The years 1996-98 were most responsible for
the extraordinary appreciation of Dell stock.
 &HT;    During that time, Dell opened a manufacturing plant in Penang,
Malaysia, to serve the Asia-Pacific countries and added a second
plant in Limerick, Ireland, to supply its rapidly growing European
business.
 &HT;    The expansion continued last year. Dell opened new plants in
Austin; Nashville, Tenn; Limerick; Xiamen, China; and Eldorado do
Sul, Brazil.
 &HT;    The late entry into the server market underscores another Dell
strategy. It has rarely been a leader in technology, relying on
standard components and features, most notably Intel processors and
Microsoft operating systems.
 &HT;    In a speech last year, Dell said standardization makes it
difficult for brands to stand out on performance alone.
 &HT;    ``As the information industry matures and the companies in it
become more fully developed, product differentiation is becoming
more difficult to achieve,'' he said. ``It will give way to process
innovation as the fundamental source of competitive advantage.''
 &HT;    Even Silicon Valley, which became the birthplace of the
information revolution through technological brilliance and product
innovation, sees Dell as a leader in the Internet economy.
 &HT;    ``Its responsiveness to customers has been the envy of the
industry out here,'' said Regis McKenna, the Silicon Valley
marketing guru whose clients have included many of the industry's
best-known companies.
 &HT;    ``For years (Silicon Valley) was focused on engineering,'' he
said. ``In the past five to seven years out here, there's been a
real appreciation for marketing.''
 &HT;    With rapidly growing acceptance of the Internet and new devices
to access it appearing constantly, Michael Dell maintains that the
Internet secures the personal computer's future.
 &HT;    ``I have every imaginable device known to mankind, because I
like to play with all this stuff,'' he said. ``But devices like
Web-enabled telephones, with tiny inch-high screens,'' he says,
``will not replace the PC.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A decade of Dell Computer Corp.
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Founded: May 1984
</P>
<P>
   Exchange: Nasdaq
</P>
<P>
   Ticker symbol: DELL
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and CEO: Michael S. Dell
</P>
<P>
   DELL IN 1990
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: 9505 Arboretum Blvd., Austin
</P>
<P>
   Number of employees: 2,000
</P>
<P>
   Business: Manufactures, sells and supports IBM compatible
computers, printers and monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Operations: Manufacturing plant in Austin; sales in United
States, Canada, United Kingdom, West Germany, France and Sweden
</P>
<P>
   DELL IN 2000
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: 1 Dell Way, Round Rock
</P>
<P>
   Number of employees: 20,800 in Central Texas, 33,200 worldwide
</P>
<P>
   Business: Manufactures, sells and supports complete line of
desktop and notebook computers, workstations, servers and storage
products.
</P>
<P>
   Operations: Manufacturing plants in Austin; Nashville, Tenn.;
Eldorado do Sul, Brazil; Limerick, Ireland; Penang, Malaysia; and
Xiamen, China; offices in 34 countries and sales and services in
170 countries and territories.
</P>
<P>
   KEY EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   1990: Opens manufacturing plant in Ireland
</P>
<P>
   1991: Introduces its first notebook computer
</P>
<P>
   1992: Joins Fortune 500
</P>
<P>
   1992: Cracks top 5 computer makers
</P>
<P>
   1996: Opens manufacturing plant in Malaysia
</P>
<P>
   _ Starts selling computers on the Internet
</P>
<P>
   _ Joins S&AMP;P 500 Index
</P>
<P>
   1997: Ships 10-millionth computer
</P>
<P>
   _ Introduces its first workstation
</P>
<P>
   1998: Opens manufacturing plant in China
</P>
<P>
   1999: Opens manufacturing plants in Tennessee and Brazil
</P>
<P>
   QUOTING MICHAEL
</P>
<P>
   On his dream of becoming No. 1:
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little boy has a dream. Mine happened to come true.''
</P>
<P>
   On Austin's role in Dell's success:
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin was obviously great for Dell. A great place to live
makes it easier to attract people from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   On the company's accomplishments:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm most proud of the team we've built and the fact that we
went from No. 25 out of 25 to No. 1. And that we've established a
clear leadership in the market and that we positioned ourselves for
opportunities going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   On how he develops his strategy:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say a lot of it is looking at ... near-term trends and
trying to anticipate technological change ... listening to
customers that are leading indicators of changes that are going on,
and listening to our best people. And then I guess there's a little
bit of intuition in there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   DELL DATA
</P>
<P>
   _ Analysts estimate Dell's revenue for the fiscal year ending
Jan. 28 will be $25 billion. That would be about 4,500 percent
higher than 1990 sales of $546 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ The company hired at least 4,700 people in Central Texas last
year, more than double its total employment of 2,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dell has built more than 5 million square feet of office and
manufacturing space in Central Texas since 1990. That's roughly
one-third of the enclosed space at UT's central campus.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1999, Michael Dell received about 2,000 invitations to
speak to all manner of groups, from schoolchildren to economists
and executives. He accepts about 20 a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Insider Research Services says Michael Dell has sold $2.7
billion of Dell stock since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1990, Dell's stock price ranged from $4.88 to $25.39 per
share. That's before adjusting for seven splits since 1992.
</P>
