<HEADLINE>
FISK KEY PART OF FENWAY LORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This was not Jerry Remy's introduction to Carlton Fisk,
but it was close.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was right after I'd been traded from the Angels,'' Remy
said Tuesday, ``and we were going to play the Yankees for the first
time since the trade. At the time, a couple of my good friends from
the Angels were on the Yankees, Mickey Rivers and (Ed) Figueroa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game at Fenway, Rivers came over and said `Hi.'
Well, Fisk came over and said to me, `We don't talk to them around
here.' His hate for the Yankees was very real. I'll never forget
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Remy came to the Red Sox in 1978. Three years earlier, in 1975,
a teenaged Dan Duquette was sitting in his living room in Dalton,
watching Game 6 of the World Series with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell asleep,'' Duquette said, ``but my dad's screaming woke
me up after (Bernie) Carbo's home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette joined in the shouting four innings later, when Fisk
hit the 12th-inning, game-winning home run off the left-field foul
pole that assured him immortality even before his election to
baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defining moment of his career came with the Red Sox,'' the
Red Sox general manager said. ``We've all seen it a hundred times,
but it's still a great shot, a great moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that he's working with the Red Sox again. This is a
good day for the Red Sox, a great day for Carlton Fisk. I'm sure
his mother and father are very proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   John Harrington, the Sox CEO and keeper of the Trust, like
Duquette acknowledged that the other player voted to the Hall, Tony
Perez, had Red Sox ties, too. Like Fisk, Perez hit a memorable home
run in the '75 Series. While playing for Cincinnati's Big Red
Machine, Perez hit one of Bill Lee's eephus pitches deep into the
Boston night for a two-run home run in Game 7, starting
Cincinnati's comeback from a 3-0 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of three home runs Perez hit in that Series, more
than any player on either team. He later played three seasons for
the Sox, from 1980-82, his first season in a Boston uniform
overlapping with Fisk's last.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of the entire Red Sox organization, I want to
congratulate both Carlton Fisk and Tony Perez on this great honor
and accomplishment,'' Harrington said in a statement. ``Personally,
I feel fortunate to have been able to watch both individuals play,
especially Carlton as a fellow New Englander. The entire Red Sox
Family shares a great sense of pride that their names will forever
be placed among the greatest baseball players of all-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk, an All-Star seven times in his Boston tenure, becomes only
the second Sox catcher voted to the Hall of Fame, joining Rick
Ferrell, who was inducted in 1984. At one time estranged from the
Sox organization, Fisk returned last year as a special assistant to
Duquette, and was behind the plate to receive Ted Williams's
ceremonial first pitch at last July's All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said that while Fisk will have numerous speaking
engagements and other obligations after his election, he hopes to
spend some time in uniform this spring in Fort Myers, Fla., working
with Boston's catchers in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm very happy for him,'' said Remy. ``I was hoping
it would be last year, but there was obviously a lot of
competition. I didn't have any doubt that he would be elected. He
certainly deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time I played with him, he was terrific. As a catcher, he
was better than anyone out there. He was a big guy, but he threw
well, with a quick release. And he was tough. Really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And he hated the Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
