<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CARE MERGERS OFTEN JUST DON'T WORK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet and media industries are ecstatic over the proposed
combination of America Online and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, people in health care were excited about the
benefits of mergers.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't so excited anymore. Harvard Pilgrim Health Care _
the result of a merger between two health maintenance organizations
_ is operating under state receivership after it said it would lose
$177 million in 1999. Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, a union
of two Boston teaching hospitals, recently announced a big staff
cut to cope with an expected $100 million loss in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is not confined to Massachusetts or the
not-for-profit sector. Across the country ambitious attempts to
consolidate pieces of the health care business have left investors
battered and bruised.
</P>
<P>
   Healthsouth, a huge chain of rehabilitation hospitals, has seen
its stock fall from 30 to 6 since the middle of 1998. MedPartners,
a company that bought doctor practices nationwide, lost more than
75 percent of its value in 1998 and decided to get out of the
business. Several of the country's largest nursing home chains
filed for bankruptcy last year after their aggressive acquisition
strategies went awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to find health mergers that produced the
results people were looking for,'' said Nancy Turnbull, a lecturer
at the Harvard School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Why the dismal outcomes? Executives in the medical business _
and those who follow the industry _ offer a variety of
explanations. They say that in health care:
</P>
<P>
   --Cost savings have proved elusive. In medicine, costs are
driven by factors like new technology and the aging of the
population that are terribly difficult to control. Beyond that,
costs are driven by doctors, a group with no obvious parallel in
other industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors are like independent contractors,'' said Turnbull.
``They don't really work for anybody.'' Doctors complain that the
beancounters have taken over health care. The bean counters, on the
other hand, complain that doctors still call the shots. Whoever is
right, costs are rising, not falling.
</P>
<P>
   Some merged health care companies have been able to cut costs on
items like supplies and computer systems. Compared to other
industries _ say banking and retailing _ the postmerger savings
have been puny.
</P>
<P>
   --Blending the cultures is difficult. Culture clashes can be a
problem in any merger. In health care, they are especially acute.
Exhibit A could be the merger of Beth Israel and Deaconess
hospitals in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In each medical speciality, the two hospitals tried to create a
single, unified department. It happens all the time in other
businesses: you combine the accounting staffs, the computer
departments, etc. With doctors, the results were disastrous: egos
were bruised, talent left and morale suffered. ``They did not pay
enough attention to cultural issues at every level of the
organization,'' said Steven Weiner, a health care lawyer with Mintz
Levin.
</P>
<P>
   --The business is stubbornly local. ``Tip O'Neill said all
politics is local. The same is true for health care,'' said Stephen
Caulfield, chairman of the Chickering Group, a Cambridge, Mass.
health insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Each health care market has its own style and personality, say
analysts. The fact that you own a hospital in California counts for
very little when you are trying to buy one in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Health care has proved very resistant to the idea of national
brand names _ a fact of life in practically every other business.
Rob Hallisey, a portfolio manager at John Hancock Funds, points out
that Columbia HCA, the nation's largest hospital chain, set out to
build a national presence. What Coke was to soft drinks, Columbia
was going to be to hospitals. The company has since retreated from
that ambitious goal.
</P>
<P>
   --The government is a big, but unreliable partner. All the talk
about the marketplace in health care misses an obvious point: the
government, through the Medicare and Medicaid programs, pays a big
share of health care costs. The average Massachusetts hospital, for
example, gets 50 percent of its revenue from the two government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Congress passed the Balanced Budget Act, a measure
designed to slow the growth in Medicare spending. The slowdown
turned into something more like a screeching halt. ``No one
realized how Draconian it was at the time,'' said a local hospital
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The spending cuts upset the plans of hospitals, nursing homes,
and home health companies, especially those who were counting on
increased revenue to make their merger math work out.
</P>
<P>
   Does the failure of the health mergers mean such combinations
can't work? Not necessarily. It does, however, suggest that the
early enthusiasm for any merger does not guarantee comparable
enthusiasm down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Are you listening AOL?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
