<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-WOM-CHICKS-ART-BOS &LR;      01-12 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-CHICKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 CHICKSONFOOTBALL.COM TICKLES FUNNY BONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In chickspeak, tearful Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre is the
drama queen, the frumpy leader of the Seattle Seahawks is Coach
Walrus, and the phrase ``potent offensive unit'' may or may not
have anything to do with yardage gained.
</P>
<P>
   Proceed only if you dare, because www.chicksonfootball.com is to
the typical sports Web site what a black-lace teddy is to plain
cotton underwear. The latter provides the basics, but the former
offers the potential for a lot more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Football, the chicks insist, is entertainment. ``We would rather
laugh and gossip and dish than we would argue and get angry,'' said
Becky Smyrnios of Peabody, Mass. ``We're not angry people, we're
giggly people.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly aren't airheaded people. In just the eight months
since Smyrnios and workout partner Stephanie Lee of Groveland began
to act on their chitchat about starting a Web site from which they
could share their love of football and tight pants, they've popped
up in Sports Illustrated (``smirkingly prurient'') and ESPN
magazine (``surprisingly smart''), launched a promising sideline of
radio guest appearances around the country, and will use the coming
offseason to explore avenues of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of work to be done,'' said Smyrnios.
</P>
<P>
   After an initial investment of about $10,000, they're already
breaking even on operating costs by selling fashion T-shirts and
other apparel known as chickwear. Too busy developing the concept
and content, they haven't even tried yet to sell ads for the site,
which went online in early July. Since the four-paragraph item in
SI last month, the two _ still working their day jobs in corporate
public relations (Lee) and the insurance industry (Smyrnios) _ have
been getting 200 e-mails a week, all of which they try to answer in
the 25 or so hours a week they devote to what is still a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more ideas than there are time and money,'' said
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Described by one wry observer as ``not your normal x's and o's
type of football,'' the site nonetheless betrays its founders'
knowledge of the game amid the double entendres and saucy asides.
By the end of the regular season, Lee was 125-110 for her picks
against the spread, while Smyrnios also broke .500 at 119-116. But
the chicks are far more intrigued by choosing an All-Stud Team (the
Patriots' Lawyer Milloy, they tease, ``can cross-examine us any
time, any place'') or issuing spankings to players behaving badly.
They're betting a lot of other people will be, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a unique approach to football,'' said John
Crowe, who has recruited Smyrnios and Lee to appear on Friday
mornings during the playoffs on ``Sports Radio 790 _ The Score''
out of Providence, R.I., where he is executive producer. ``It's
kind of refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fan is Owen Murphy, a producer at eyada.com, on which
they have appeared on internet radio broadcasts. ``They're funny as
hell,'' he said. ``They were a thousand times better than I ever
thought they could have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The chicks have also attracted the attention of academia. Mike
Reilley, a lecturer at the Medill School of Journalism at
Northwestern University, has linked to chicksonfootball from the
Web site for his graduate-level class on the Sociology and Economy
of Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show a lighter side to sports journalism, so to
speak,'' said Reilley, who covered the NFL for three years while
with the Los Angeles Times. ``It's silly and fun, and they mean it
to come across that way. I appreciate the different perspective and
the different voice to it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a voice by which some are troubled. ``I felt like I was
walking into a bad fraternity party, the kind where the music is
bad, the jokes are bad, the pickup lines are bad, and some bozo
spills beer in your shoes,'' said Christine Brennan, an author,
broadcaster, and sports columnist for USA Today. ``As I waded
around the frat-party muck, I laughed a few times. (But) I won't go
back. I would hope that our gender could do better than the boys.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that Smyrnios and Lee are well-versed in the
sport (``It's nice to see women talking football, when you weed out
the innuendo''), Brennan can't help but fear that some readers will
confuse their approach with that of serious female journalists. ``I
would hate to have people think this is how women cover sports,''
she said. ``This is how two women who call themselves chicks cover
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   And if two dudes got together and decided to give the same
treatment to, say, the WNBA? Said Reilley: ``It would be, to quote
REM, the end of the world as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even their biggest supporters suggest the chicks overdo some of
the sauciness. ``I think they sell themselves short a little bit,''
said Murphy. Reilley agreed, but quickly pointed out, ``If you're
too vanilla, you don't get mentioned in Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chicks themselves say they have gotten surprisingly few
negative comments. Although they were warned at the outset that
``men will hate you because you don't know anything and women will
hate you because you're sexist bimbos,'' they said, e-mail from
women often begins, ``I wasn't expecting to like you, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people take it for what it is,'' said Lee. ``We're women
who are taking a risk in a male-oriented profession, doing things
our own way.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole enterprise was born just last May, but the chicks'
friendship goes back to Danvers (Mass.) High School, Class of 1984,
where Smyrnios was a gymnast and Lee a cheerleader. While Lee went
to the University of New Hampshire to study journalism and then
Boston University for a masters in communication, Smyrnios got a
degree from Amherst College. Neither was much of a football fan;
that came via Becky's marriage to Peter Smyrnios, almost 10 years
ago, after which Sunday afternoons were given over to the games on
TV. When Lee started joining the chip-eating crowd in the
Smyrnioses' living room, she, too, soon caught the fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably one of the few women around who got into football
because of a girlfriend,'' quipped Lee, whose 4-month-old daughter,
Sydney, has spent every Sunday of her life watching football as
mommy works, after the pair decided it was time to get serious
about putting their voices out on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   From the first keystroke, the chicks knew their Web site would
be more gossip than news, more sarcasm than statistics. (``We're
bored by all the facts,'' explained Smyrnios.) Their naughty
cyperpersonalities, though, seemed to blossom naturally from what
made them laugh as they toiled. Themes on the site include
Smyrnios's ``sickening crush'' on Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy
Aikman, and any player with the last name of Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of like romance columnists,'' said Lee. ``We find
this great nugget and build from it.''
</P>
<P>
   And their husbands? While Stephanie's husband Michael is quietly
proud, Peter Smyrnios wants in on the action. ``(Becky) stole my
dream career,'' said the former Peabody High quarterback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
