<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 AFTER HARVARD, STRUGGLING MOTHER MUST REVISIT CUSTODY BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Late out of bed and still in her workout
clothes, the young woman with waist-length cinnamon hair rounds a
corner on Harvard Square pushing an empty stroller.
</P>
<P>
   Bopping along a few steps behind is the Harvard senior's 3
1/2-year-old, happy-go-lucky daughter, who little more than two
years ago ignited a bitter custody fight that provoked a national
debate over a mother's right to advance her career at the cost of a
father's visitation rights. The feud nearly prevented her mother
from returning to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Now in her final semester, Gina Ocon faces the end of her
cocoon-like world of grants, low-interest loans, and
university-subsidized housing. And the post-graduation reality will
test more than the 24-year-old's education, it will test her
ability to confront her past.
</P>
<P>
   The former beauty contestant turned social anthropology major
may soon have to wage another legal battle with her former
boyfriend in Southern California. After graduation in June, she
wants to stay in Cambridge with her daughter, Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I'm not sure what's going to happen,'' Ocon said in a
recent interview as Bailey chased pigeons and devoured spoonfuls of
vanilla ice cream and rainbow sprinkles. ``When he finds out I'm
not coming back, he'll definitely do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall semester of 1997, Ocon has built a life in
Cambridge, just across the Charles River from Boston. She has a
supportive community of friends and professors, a rock band she
sings with that has recorded a few compact discs, and a new
boyfriend, who has become something of a stand-in father to Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   But the terms of her custody could prevent her and Bailey from
staying. Sometime this spring, Ocon has to return to court in
Southern California for a review of her former boyfriend's
visitation rights. If the two don't agree on a new settlement _
Bailey now goes to California two weeks during the school year and
six weeks over the summer _ the girl's father, Tommaso Maggiore,
may again sue for custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would pretty much disappear, but he hasn't,''
Ocon said. ``On the surface, he doesn't appear interested. He
doesn't call for months. But then right before she's supposed to
visit him, he gets very controlling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two years since Ocon returned to Harvard with Bailey, not
much has changed in Maggiore's life. He still lives with his family
in Long Beach. He's still pursuing a degree part-time at a local
community college. And he still resents Ocon for taking his
daughter more than 2,500 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at a diving shop where he works in Long Beach, Maggiore,
24, said he would like to see his daughter more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I really don't know what I'll do,'' he said. ``I'm
supposed to get more liberal visitation than I have. Now, I have
pretty much next to nothing. The only thing I have had so far is
heartache.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, he says, he believes chances are slim that he'll
persuade a court to force Ocon and Bailey back to the West Coast.
In California, the law generally favors the custodial parent's
right to choose where he or she lives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Maggiore has a strong argument, lawyers say. When a court
decides what's in Bailey's best interests, especially as she nears
school age, it will be hard to discount having her father nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Maggiore and Ocon knew each other while growing up but didn't
become a couple until she returned to Southern California after her
freshman year at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed a parfect match. She had been a beauty contest
runner-up; he was a well-dressed, handsome heir to a popular
restaurant his family owns.
</P>
<P>
   When Ocon returned to Cambridge after the summer, she discovered
she was pregnant. After considering their options, the couple chose
to have the baby. Ocon took the year off and returned to Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Bailey's birth, the young family flew back to
Cambridge where Maggiore applied for a job at one of Harvard's
exclusive eating clubs. They hoped to sign up for campus housing,
but they arrived too late. The affordable apartments were already
taken.
</P>
<P>
   So, the three put off their plans for another year and moved
back to Long Beach. Three months after Bailey's birth, the
relationship unraveled. After several heated arguments, Ocon walked
out with Bailey. Three days later, Maggiore filed for custody.
</P>
<P>
   Months of tears and scorn followed. Accusations volleyed between
Ocon's and Maggiore's increasingly acrimonious families, before
Ocon eventually won the right to take Bailey back to Harvard for
the duration of her studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many lessons I learned,'' Ocon said. ``You
really better be in a serious relationship and know the person well
before you have children. I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ocon is eager to graduate after six years of balancing
single motherhood, hours of studying, and a legal battle, she's not
sure what she wants to do and she's worried about revisiting the
custody issues while starting payment on some $40,000 in student
loans.
</P>
<P>
   She does know, however, that she won't do what she planned on
before going to Harvard. After years of dealing with attorneys,
judges, and seemingly endless legal minutiae, Ocon has decided not
to become a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, she said, she'll apply for a job at Harvard's
fund-raising office, as a way to give back to an institution that
has staunchly supported her, with annual scholarships, hundreds of
dollars worth of day care, and free room and board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't envision wearing a business suit,'' she said. ``I'd
like to do something more academic. Definitely I see graduate
school in my future.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ocon spends her days running from day care to classes
to band rehearsals to poring over books and writing papers. When
she's alone with Bailey, a giggly girl with bright blue eyes and
stick-straight blond hair, everything else comes after the constant
cautioning, cajoling, and cuddling that goes with motherhood.
Writing an honors thesis, for example, is just too much while being
a single mother.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike many students, Ocon has learned how to budget her
time, and she appreciates her education. ``For me, there's a lot of
clarity for why I'm here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wiping off the vanilla ice cream smeared on Bailey's plump, pink
cheeks, Ocon says she has few regrets.
</P>
<P>
   She wishes she hadn't expended so much emotion during the
custody fight. There are some words she would take back if she
could. And she would have never gambled her Harvard education for a
fleeting relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one decision she doesn't regret: the decision to
have Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an expectation that you'd feel some resentment toward
her,'' Ocon said. ``Sure, there are the sleepless nights, and she
demands constant attention. But I really enjoy being a mom, and
Bailey's a great kid. The only resentment I have is for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
