<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3861 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WELCHS-SUCCESS-ART-BO     01-12 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELCHS-SUCCESS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 OTHERS FEEL SQUEEZED, BUT NOT WELCH'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many agricultural cooperatives, 1999 was a year they'd
rather forget. One exception: Welch Foods Inc. of Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to new products, wider distribution, and studies that
talk up the health benefits of grape juice, Welch's, the marketing
arm of the National Grape Cooperative Association Inc., has
recently outperformed much of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frankly hard pressed to come up with any other
(agricultural) product that is doing as well as Concord grapes,''
said Ralph Lawrence, a vice president of CoBank in Denver, which
lends money to many agricultural cooperatives, including Welch's.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last eight months, Welch's has seen monthly sales
running at more than 20 percent above last year's levels, said
Daniel P. Dillon, its president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   There are juice grapes as well as wine grapes. Welch's is about
juice grapes that are mostly grown in Michigan, New York, Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Washington state, and Ontario, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1983, Welch's headquarters were in Western New York wine
country. But to attract top talent for its management team, it
relocated to Concord, which around 1850 had given its name to one
of the varieties of grapes that Welch's specializes in.
</P>
<P>
   As grapes thrive, many other farm products are hurting. US
farmers have become so efficient that they now routinely produce
more than paying customers can eat. With supply often outpacing
demand, growers have seen prices for their crops plummet.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc. of Lakeville, Mass. is one visible
example of a cooperative that's struggling with oversupply and
falling prices.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, the relative success of the juice grape
``stands out like a beacon,'' Dillon said.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's may be thriving because it's doing a good job fulfilling
an agricultural cooperative's job description.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a publicly traded company, a cooperative's mission is not
simply to maximize shareholders' profits. It also seeks to preserve
the long-term livelihood of its member/growers.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of a cooperative's job is to stimulate demand through
marketing efforts and advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   While other coops change strategies, Welch's prides itself in
staying on message. Its ads relentlessly target families and
feature cute kids. New market efforts include a sponsorship of
iVillage, a Web site that caters to women. And soon Pokemon
characters will be enlisted in a Welch's promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Also stimulating demand is medical research that Welch's has
supported. This research claims that white grape juice may be the
easiest juice for a young child to digest and that purple grape
juice is as good for the heart as red wine.
</P>
<P>
   That research has ``really resonated with consumers'' and helped
to boost sales, said Brian Henehan, who follows the grape industry
at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   Effective marketing may be reflected in Welch's performance in
its most recent fiscal year. Sales rose about 5 percent to a record
$631 million. Net proceeds, the term a cooperative uses for
profits, also hit a record, though they increased only slightly
from $69.8 million to $70.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   For a publicly traded company, such gains would seem modest, but
for an agricultural cooperative, it's ``a phenomenal
counter-cyclical performance,'' said Rex Green, a managing director
for the Boston office of Advest Investment Banking, which advises
Welch's on acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   What's really impressive about last year, according to Dillon,
is that about one third of sales came from new products introduced
within the last five years; in the early 1990s, new products
accounted for about only 10 percent of overall sales.
</P>
<P>
   To a lay person, the phrase ``new product'' means something new
and completely different _ such as Welch's peanut butter and jelly
candy venture with Russell Stover. In industry parlance, however,
taking grape juice or jelly and putting it into a different sized
plastic container can also qualify as a new product.
</P>
<P>
   New containers don't sound like a big deal, but they can have a
big impact on sales.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Welch's products were largely confined to one area
of the supermarket. Because of new packaging, products can now be
found in many supermarket aisles, from the juice shelf to the
freezer case and refrigerated-foods section.
</P>
<P>
   New packaging and different sizes have also given Welch's a much
bigger presence in vending machines, convenience stores, and
membership wholesale clubs. Wider exposure has translated into
higher sales.
</P>
<P>
   Besides effective marketing and wider distribution, Welch's may
have another advantage in its board of directors, said investment
banker Green. Many coops have boards dominated by growers, and one
result is ``insular'' thinking, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's, in contrast, has a board that includes growers,
professional managers, and outside directors. A well-balanced board
is partly responsible for the cooperative's carefully thought-out
strategy, Green claims.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's traces its roots to Dr. Thomas Bramwell Welch. In 1869,
looking to make a communion wine that wouldn't make church goers
giddy, he applied the theories of Louis Pasteur to the processing
of Concord grapes. From this mix of religion and science, a
cooperative _ and the US fruit-juice industry _ was born, or so
states Welch's official history.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a search for a church wine today employs
1,250 workers, including about 200 in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges lie ahead. Competition is fierce as beverage makers
battle for a share of the consumer's stomach. In the supermarket, a
rival is as much a soft drink or a bottled water as another juice,
and soft-drink companies in particular have a lot more marketing
muscle than a small player such as Welch's.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the supermarket industry is rapidly consolidating,
and big chains sometimes throw their weight behind their own
store-brand juices and jellies, which can compete with Welch's.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the immediate outlook is bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture typically goes in cycles,'' said Cornell's
Henehan. And right now, Welch's has ``the right mix of conditions
to excel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
