<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AILING-HMO-VANGUARD-B     01-12 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AILING-HMO-VANGUARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS' GROUP VANGUARD WEIGHS OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Among the nail-biting health care providers who treat
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care's million-plus subscribers, none have
greater cause for alarm than those at Harvard Vanguard Medical
Associates, who provide care for nearly one Greater Boston resident
in every 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-three percent of Harvard Vanguard's 300,000 patients are
insured by Harvard Pilgrim, the giant Massachusetts health plan
which state officials took over last week to stave off financial
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The ties between the two go back 30 years. Harvard Pilgrim grew
out of the Harvard Community Health Plan, founded in 1969. Two
years ago, the Harvard Plan's 500 salaried, health center-based
doctors and staff morphed into Harvard Vanguard and split off from
the parent company. But their future is still tightly bound to the
beleaguered HMO.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of dependence, the question among Harvard
Vanguard staffers is: Can we survive?
</P>
<P>
   Internal memos and interviews Tuesday with Harvard Vanguard
executives provide a glimpse of the frantic activity that the
crisis has touched off among Vanguard staffers _ a distillation of
the anxiety that permeates the entire health care industry in
eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes far beyond Harvard Vanguard,'' said Kenneth Paulus,
who takes the reins as Harvard Vanguard's new chief executive next
Monday. ``Everybody has a fair percentage of their income at
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulus guessed there is a 20 percent chance that Harvard Pilgrim
will go bust. ``It would be a huge mistake if we let that happen,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety that permeates Harvard Vanguard was evident in an
email that greeted the group practice's 500 doctors and other
staffers when they reported for work on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither we nor outside experts believe that Harvard Pilgrim
Health Care will be allowed to go out of business,'' wrote Dr.
Gordon Vineyard, the medical group's interim chief executive, and
Dr. Robin Atlas, the chief medical officer. ``Still, we are
planning expeditiously for all contingencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Those contingencies, they acknowledged, include ``the worst-case
scenario _ a liquidation of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Vanguard's top priority, Paulus said, is to accelerate
efforts to win contracts from other health plans so that patients
who lose Harvard Pilgrim coverage can switch to another plan and
maintain their relationship with Vanguard's caregivers. This month
it began offering services to Tufts Health Plan subscribers for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much time we've got,'' Paulus said. ``I hope
to consummate agreements in the next 30 days. It's aggressive, but
it's doable.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Vanguard also must find a new source of capital, which
formerly came entirely from Harvard Pilgrim. Harvard Vanguard
officials said their operations would not be affected if a
now-suspended bond deal to inject new capital into the HMO
eventually goes through. Under that plan, eight of Vanguard's
health centers would be sold and leased back to Harvard Pilgrim.
Paulus did not rule out the possibility that Harvard Vanguard, the
largest physician group practice in Massachusetts except for the
comparably sized Lahey Clinic, might eventually become partners
with another provider group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's potential in our future to have a partnership with
another delivery system,'' said Paulus, currently a top official
with Partners Health Care, the region's largest such system. ``What
that means and how deep that would be, it's too early to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Harvard Vanguard is most at risk, its contingency planning
may be more intense than others'. But everyone responsible for
providing care, buying health insurance, or selling coverage is
feeling the chill.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming their fears, the state regulator in charge of
managing Harvard Pilgrim out of its crisis, insurance commissioner
Linda Ruthardt, Tuesday said she is doing some what-if planning of
her own. Ruthardt has directed Kevin Beagan of her staff to plot
out who might finance care for Harvard Pilgrim's members in case
the HMO can't be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will not have to liquidate,'' Ruthardt said.
``But we're already developing contingency plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers are so worried about the Massachusetts situation that,
for the first time, many are considering national health plans that
have developed local physician networks. While few have actually
jumped ship, many are comparing the networks offered by national
plans such as Aetna and United HealthCare, hoping to find one
similar in coverage to their Harvard Pilgrim plans.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty is motivating employers ``to think nationally
now,'' said Susan Connolly, a partner at the Boston benefits
consulting firm William M. Mercer. ``While it's too soon to say
what's going to happen to Harvard Pilgrim, for an employer to do
nothing at this point would be a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's enough to turn you gray,'' said Dolores Mitchell,
director of the state Group Insurance Commission, who is
responsible for buying health coverage on behalf of 255,000 state
workers, dependents, and retirees. Nearly 57,000 of those
individuals are currently insured through Harvard Pilgrim, more
than by any other health plan the state offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any responsible benefit administrator, public or private, has
to be thinking through the scenarios and be ready to move,''
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Barrett, chief executive of Lahey Clinic and formerly
of Minnesota's Mayo Clinic, said he has never encountered such a
precarious situation. ``There's no question that Harvard Pilgrim is
an organization we depend a great deal on for our financial
wellbeing,'' said Barrett, whose institution derives nearly 20
percent of its income from Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Barrett dreads most, he said, is having to
borrow money to pay bills _ a scenario that might unfold if there
is a long delay in repaying the $10 million in debt that Lahey
Clinic says Harvard Pilgrim owes for care provided in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to borrow money to pay bills, it becomes
desperate,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writer Steven Wilmsen contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
