<SLUG> BC-AOL-DEAL-MAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON NATIVE HELPED GET THE DEAL DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ But for a key meeting in Boston two days before
Christmas and the negotiating savvy of a prominent downtown lawyer,
the world might never have seen the epic proposed merger of America
Online Inc. and Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   AOL chairman Steve Case, Time Warner chairman Gerald Levin, and
his flamboyant vice chairman Ted Turner dominated the New York
press conference Monday to announce the $178 billion transaction.
But behind the scenes, one of the most crucial players hammering
out the deal was Kenneth J. Novack, AOL's vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Novack, 58, spends half his week working out of an AOL office a
short walk across the Public Garden from his Beacon Hill home. He
joined AOL in May 1998 as full-time vice chairman after more than
10 years serving as the company's outside counsel while with Boston
law firm Mintz, Levin, Cohn, Ferris, Glovsky, and Popeo.
</P>
<P>
   Novack handled AOL's initial public offering in 1992, as well as
its 1998 acquisition of CompuServe that added 2 million
subscribers. (AOL currently has more than 22 million.) Case has
called him ``a principal strategist in initiatives that have played
a critical role in our growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Novack's office at Heritage on the Common in Boston was the
scene of a key meeting Dec. 23. He and two top Time Warner
officials, president Richard D. Parsons and Time Warner Digital
Media chairman Richard J. Bressler, and their investment banker
began putting meat on plans Case hatched in Hong Kong two months
earlier for a blockbuster combination of the number one Internet
service provider and the number one media company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agreed that we should talk further right after the
holidays,'' Novack recalled of that session, which led to a
five-hour dinner meeting Thursday night at the Northern Virginia
home of AOL chairman Steve Case.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting around Case's dining room table, after enjoying ``a
terrific red wine from Steve's cellar,'' Novack, Case, Levin, and
Bressler were up until midnight working out the final details of
the deal announced Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Novack said the first, most important question was: ``Does this
merger really make sense?'' AOL had been considering several
options to expand, including buying a telecommunications company or
a media company, or simply pouring more resources into expanding
Net-based offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we presented the options to Steve, he had a very strong
instinct that the most dramatic thing we could do was a merger with
Time Warner,'' Novack recalled. ``Gerry and Steve really got it.
The coin dropped for them first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key here is that we are confident that the whole is a lot
greater than the sum of the parts,'' Novack said. ``We will really
build a new paradigm, a new business. We will generate content
which is from its inception multipurpose, and we will be working
hard to make sure that we spread the Internet DNA across Time
Warner.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the merits of the basic idea of an AOL-Time Warner marriage
became clear, Novack said the main focus of talks was how to mesh
the boards and management teams of the two firms, and working out
what became the 55-45 ownership split of the new company between
AOL and Time Warner, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Novack said he finds it ``amazing that the deal did not leak.
Think about AOL: There probably isn't a company in the world that
gets more ink than we do. I think that was a function of two
things: We kept this very, very tightly controlled. We really dealt
with it on an absolute need-to-know basis.''
</P>
<P>
   According to AOL's most recent proxy statement, issued in
September, Novack owned just under 200,000 shares, worth nearly $13
million, and had received during 1998 and 1999 restricted long-term
options to buy 2.08 million more shares. He earned $750,000 at AOL
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Novack, a father of four, held top roles at Mintz Levin for more
than 25 years before joining AOL. He remains of counsel at the
firm, which serves as general counsel to AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Novack was Mintz Levin's managing partner from 1972 to 1978 and
president and chief executive from 1991 to 1994, focusing on
technology firms including Biogen Inc. He is also a trustee of the
Museum of Science and New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Novack also became nationally known for establishing at Mintz
Levin one of the first and only in-house foundations connected to a
law firm, overseeing both how the firm gave away donations and
coordinating its efforts to have lawyers donate pro bono time
representing and advising charitable and social-service groups.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston native and lifelong resident of the area, Novack
graduated from Dartmouth College and Harvard Law School in its
class of 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his love of Boston, Novack said he tries to spend
half the week in the area and commute the other half of the week to
AOL headquarters in Dulles, Va.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said: ``I would only say I am `based' in Boston half the
week. The nature of my responsibilities is such that I am where the
action is. I play a lead role in most of our transactions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
