<HEADER>
A3873 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-HOOKS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     01-12 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-HOOKS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... in particular?''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steinem believes some of the criticism is spurred by
professional jealousy. Hooks has become sought out by major
publishing houses because her prose captures the imagination of
readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a readable scholar,'' says Sherrod. ``Most scholars try
to publish for their 10 friends, writing in jargon, and that
doesn't do any good for the book publishing industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Face to face, hooks exudes positive vibes that make you feel as
thoughyou're her best girlfriend. Her hair is pulled back in a bun
that emphasizes the roundness of her dimpled face. She wears a long
black skirt and pink sweater, which streamlines her short, rather
Rubenesque figure. (Hooks loves writing and discussion, but she has
just as much passion for jewelry and clothing.)
</P>
<P>
   If the conversation lulls for even a moment, this woman who
jokingly declares she wants to become the high priestess of love
hungrily starts probing into matters of the heart. As a
photographer shoots her portrait, hooks simultaneously flirts with
him and interrogates him about his romantic life as though she's a
detective on a particularly intriguing case.
</P>
<P>
   Is he married? What type of relationship did his mother and
father have? You get the feeling the information is being processed
and stored for future reference.
</P>
<P>
   As morning segues into afternoon, she also does not hesitate to
reveal lusty details about her own sexual hunger. She has a love
life that reads like a verse from Lou Bega's hit single ``Mambo No.
5.'' Instead of a little bit of Monica, Erica, and Rita, hooks
talks about Anthony, Nathaniel, and others. (Out of respect, she
doesn't reveal full names.)
</P>
<P>
   Hooks continually returns to two former relationships on this
day. There's the student hooks seduced while teaching at Yale who's
now a classical musician in Boston. And there's Anthony, the most
recent ex-boyfriend, who is 16 years her junior.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent lecture, ``somebody said to me, `Is it true that
you're really into young men?,' '' hooks says while stretched out
comfortably on the red-orange leather couch in her living room. ``I
say, `Actually it's not at all true.' I'm really interested in
feminist men, and when you look for men who are committed to
feminist thinking and action, I find them in the ranks of men who
are 35 and under as opposed to 35 and over, especially black men.''
</P>
<P>
   The complicated subject of love is one hooks began exploring at
age 16 when she began paging through Erich Fromm's ``The Art of
Loving.'' Hooks's intellect made her stand out quickly in her
Kentucky hometown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and community members would tell her, she says, that
they expected greatness from her. Although hooks's father, who
worked as a janitor, and mother, a homemaker, encouraged their son
and six daughters to read and value education, hooks's intelligence
didn't make her home life easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up in an age where we were expected to be seen, not
heard,'' says Gwenda Motley, 44, one of hooks's siblings, during a
telephone conversation from her home in Flint, Mich. ``Gloria in
particular was very outspoken when it just was not acceptable for
children to be outspoken and hence, yes, she would get the
discipline more so than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooks calls feminism the movement that finally empowered her to
love. Yet in the same breath she also criticizes it for portraying
love negatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to interest people in a movement, you don't trash
what they feel is most important in their life,'' hooks says
earnestly, while at the cafe. ``I think it was a big failure of the
movement to have abandoned that to the depoliticized new-age
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinem, who explored love in a chapter of her 1993 book
``Revolution From Within: A Book of Self-Esteem,'' defends the
movement's stance on love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much damage has been done to women in the name of love,'' she
says. ``It's natural that there would be a hard look and a critique
that came first. Perhaps bell's book is the beginning of a
different stage of reevaluating what's positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation winds to a close. And hooks begins to sound
positively forlorn as she talks about the lack of love in her
current life. Friends abound. She receives a telephone message from
former MTV ``Real World'' housemate and writer Kevin Powell. She
talks about a recent shopping expedition with Jada Pinkett Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But other forms of love elude her. Hooks considered adopting a
child, but fears her lifestyle is too selfish for that. She yearns
to be in a relationship with someone, but senses her intellectual
life may be too demanding to sustain one.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hooks reads a book a day. And four hours of her
morning is consumed with writing a set number of pages or
paragraphs in the closetlike study outside her bedroom. She talks
of plans to bring in the new year alone by lighting candles and
giving thanks for ``being able to realize one's deepest visions.''
She later adds, ``It's such a kind of strange, pathetic life.''
</P>
<P>
   Then hooks turns her attention to her guest, and the
thunderstorm of sadness passes. She switches to
high-priestess-of-love mode and begins asking probing questions. As
she analyzes and dissects the answers, she's where she wants to be:
at the intersection of logic and love.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
