<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JAN. 30, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The exhaust fan installed in the ceiling of my bathroom blows
the air straight up into the attic and this has caused a problem
with dampness and mildew accumulating on the overhead roof beams.
</P>
<P>
   I was told the fan's exhaust should be ducted directly to the
outside by running the duct up through the roof, but my peaked roof
is covered with expensive slate tile that I do not want to damage
and which I may not be able to replace if I do.
</P>
<P>
   There is no outside wall in the attic near this fan to which I
can connect the fan's exhaust duct, so can you suggest any other
solution?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you have a peaked or gable roof then chances are you have
overhanging eaves along the outside.
</P>
<P>
   If so, you can run a duct horizontally inside the attic from the
top of the fan opening to the inside of the eave as shown here.
</P>
<P>
   Have it go straight up from the fan as high as possible, then
angle it sideways and slope it down toward the eave opening with as
few bends or twists as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are worried about the security of the overhead door on our
attached garage since it is easy to break into the house from
inside the garage.
</P>
<P>
   The overhead door does have a lock, but it looks like it could
be easily forced open with a screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a better way we can secure this overhead door against a
possible break-in?
</P>
<P>
   A: Drill a hole through the side of one track just above one of
the door rollers inside that track. Then insert a long,
bicycle-type padlock through this hole while the door is closed.
</P>
<P>
   This will prevent the door from rolling upward unless someone
removes the padlock from inside the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The concrete floor of my basement leaves a powdery film that
gets tracked onto the carpet in an adjoining room in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything I can do to correct this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: The simplest solution would be to clean the concrete floor
thoroughly, then coat it with two coats of a good quality latex
deck enamel.
</P>
<P>
   The paint will effectively seal the surface and hold down the
dust or powder that keeps coming off on your shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The walls in my living room were covered with sheets of
prefinished wood paneling some years ago, which would be difficult
to remove as they were applied with cement over existing drywall.
</P>
<P>
   Now I want to cover the wood panels with some type of wallpaper,
but the panels have slight grooves between them.
</P>
<P>
   How can I smooth the surface so that I can hang wallpaper over
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The simplest way would be to hang a heavy duty lining canvas
directly over the wood panels.
</P>
<P>
   This type of canvas can be purchased or ordered from most
wallcovering stores for just this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the same as ordinary canvas lining material _ it is a
much heavier duty material that is capable of bridging and covering
up irregularities in the surface underneath, including the grooves
and seams normally found in wood panels.
</P>
<P>
   The material is put up with a special adhesive and leaves you
with a smooth surface over which you can apply paint or wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``ATTIC VENT'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Horizontal duct will exhaust air through overhanging
eave directly to the outside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
