<HEADER>
A3884 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-JOB-GAMES-ART-BOS &LR;      01-12 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-GAMES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMES, BRAINTEASERS THAT CAN GET YOU A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Eds.: Ravi Chhatpar is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During his job interview last year at Zefer, an Internet
solutions firm in Boston, Ravi Chhatpar was asked ``to build
something'' with a box of Lego blocks. The 23-year-old Harvard
University graduate was taken aback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told, `You have five minutes to build whatever you want,
then we'll talk about it,' '' he recalled. ``It was a complete
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Chhatpar didn't waste time.
</P>
<P>
   He constructed an aerated cognac snifter and then explained its
functional and aesthetic qualities. His ingenuity paid off: He
landed a job as a consultant in Zefer Co.'s dot-com division.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the nation's big accounting firms altered the
interview by introducing case studies, the old-fashioned sit-down
meeting is again going through a transition as Internet and
computer software firms struggle to find qualified applicants in an
increasingly competitive job market.
</P>
<P>
   The standard interview isn't dead yet, though.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional manufacturers and retailers rely on it as a primary
screening tool, and most employers require one or more face-to-face
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fast-paced world of the Internet, those seeking work
as consultants and computer programmers are being asked to solve
mathematical equations, brainteasers, or riddles, and to
participate in group games and exercises that test a candidate's
ability to collaborate and think under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Aylward has seen her share of odd interviews. As
president of Devon James Associates in Seattle, which develops
recruiting and interviewing strategies for Internet start-ups, she
designs them.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview, one of Aylward's hiring managers
pretended he had forgotten his dry cleaning order and asked the job
applicant to drive him to the shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to see the inside of the person's car,'' Aylward
recalled. ``He also wanted to see if the candidate could answer a
series of difficult questions and get to the dry cleaners on
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Aylward identified what she calls the single most important
factor driving the transformation of the conventional interview:
youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the CEOs we work for are between 28 and 34,'' she
said. ``They want to hire clones of themselves. They want people
with off-the-scale energy, wit, and intelligence. They want cowboys
_ people who don't necessarily follow the rules, who question
everything. With every new hire, there is the hope that this new
person will come up with an odd idea that will make the company's
stock soar.''
</P>
<P>
   At ChannelWave in Cambridge, Mass., which designs Web products
that link businesses to resellers, dealers and distributors,
co-founder Ron Schmelzer tosses mind-benders to unsuspecting
applicants. ``It's important to see how well and fast people can
think,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During one recent interview, Schmelzer asked: ``If you have two
pitchers of different colored water and you have to put them
together in a single pitcher and then separate them out, how do you
do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a problem is too difficult to solve,'' he said,
``and the goal is not necessarily to find the right answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The advent of teams, in which groups of professionals are
brought together to work on a project as a group, has played a
significant role in the industry's push to remake the interview,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old process is still necessary, but it isn't sufficient,''
said Jennifer Lawrence, assistant dean for career services at the
Boston University School of Management. ``It doesn't determine who
can strategically apply information, who can manipulate it, or who
can work with others cooperatively while doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Lubrano, director of career services at The Tuck School
at Dartmouth College, recalled an interview in which a top firm
asked candidates from the college to work together to solve a
problem. The firm's principals watched from behind a one-way
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students knew they were being observed, but they couldn't
see the members of the firm,'' Lubrano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we'd see this primarily at consulting firms,'' he
added. ``Now, we are seeing a proliferation of these interviewing
techniques at a lot of Internet companies where time is at a
premium and there is a need to determine intellectual capability
quickly and efficiently, something that cannot always be done
during a 30-minute interview.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because this is a full-employment economy and good people are
so difficult to find, companies realize they must be extremely
careful,'' Lawrence said. ``They realize that it's costly to bring
someone in and then discover that he doesn't fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are relying on professional facilitators to
conduct group exercises or interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Browne Center, an affiliate of the University of New
Hampshire, uses them to screen top college seniors for jobs at
Razorfish, an international computer services firm based in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Callanan, vice president of people at Razorfish, said the
company relies on an expert from the Browne Center to administer
games, problems, and team exercises to groups of 25 to 40 student
candidates. ``This allows us to see problem-solving, thinking out
of the box, and leadership ability,'' she said. ``We get to see
them in action and see how well they work in teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The sessions, usually held after the last round of interviews,
are designed to help hiring officers focus on behavioral issues
that might not have been evident during the regular recruitment
process.
</P>
<P>
   They're also fun _ a factor that can deceive candidates into
thinking their behavior doesn't matter. Although the company
informs candidates early on that the sessions are designed to test
creativity and behavior, the students are asked to dress casually,
and the environment is relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The activities are so engaging that people tend to relax and
be who they really are,'' acknowledged Pamela McFee, director of
the Browne Center.
</P>
<P>
   McFee, who has facilitated sessions at Razorfish for four years,
recalled an incident in which a candidate's suggestion that members
of the group work together elicited a hostile response from another
applicant.
</P>
<P>
   ``A peer turned and said, `It will never work!' '' McFee
recalled. ``The behavior was clearly inappropriate. It was also the
most extreme behavior we had seen. No matter how good the grades in
college or the personal interview, that type of trait will not work
at Razorfish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tuck School's Lubrano said consulting companies are relying
more on big social settings to screen MBA graduates for top jobs. A
company invites all types of employees, from administrative
assistants and line employees to the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see how you treat the secretary as well as the
chief executive officer,'' Lubrano noted. ``Is this a person who is
able to work with, and manage, people up and down the food chain?''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ravi Chhatpar received that pile of Legos at Zefer,
he had already attended a social event at the Zefer Cafe for
employees and friends interested in working at the company. The
cafe gives the company a chance to see prospective candidates
interact socially and gives applicants a taste of the company's
culture, a Zefer spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Chhatpar's creativity and social behavior were not
the only factors that landed him the job.
</P>
<P>
   Chhatpar, the older of two children, came to Zefer with a year's
experience in consulting, a science and technical background, a
degree from a respected Ivy League college, and fluency in English,
French, Italian, German, and Hindi.
</P>
<P>
   He also had a yen for new ideas. ``I wanted to be where the
newest idea was happening in the US,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before Chhatpar was offered a job, Zefer relied on a
different approach: It interviewed candidates in a tiny room with a
picture window overlooking a busy downtown street. The room was
equipped with two chairs and a table, at which applicants were
expected to create an object from clay or Lego blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would literally have to crawl up a little ladder to get
to that room,'' recalled Martha Stephens, executive vice president
for people at Zefer.
</P>
<P>
   Why go to such extremes?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all kinds of people working here, and we need to make
sure people are comfortable outside their particular discipline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
