<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FUNDS-GROWTH-BOS &LR;      01-12 1825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-GROWTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS THE FUND STREAK PEAKED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mutual fund was invented during the Roaring '20s, so it is
perhaps fitting that it came of age in the Booming '90s.
</P>
<P>
   After languishing for generations, the fund industry exploded
last decade, radically altering the investment world, bestowing
prosperity on millions of Americans, and changing how the middle
class enjoys its golden years.
</P>
<P>
   But after a streak as one of the nation's hottest industries,
the $6.5 trillion fund world has entered an Age of Uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is forcing many fund companies, often conservative
by nature, to grab the bull of innovation by the nose-ring and
offer new services and products. Competition is growing, both
within the industry and from cyber-upstarts. A decline in sales
gains has slashed profits at even the biggest companies. And
expectations from investors accustomed to lofty stock market
returns have some fund firms wondering how they will appeal to
customers in leaner times.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers even wonder if the industry has peaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a mature market in mutual funds in the United
States,'' said Burton Greenwald, a financial services consultant in
Philadelphia. While Greenwald expects the fund industry to double
in size over the next seven years, he said that its growth rate
would drop from 20 percent to 10 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, fund firms were a distinct species, and the
portfolio management business was concentrated in Boston. Now there
are hot players across the country, like Denver-based Janus Funds.
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. is best known as a big brokerage in San
Francisco _ but it has become a huge fund industry player by
selling other companies' products. Schwab competes with
Boston-based Fidelity Investments, the world's biggest fund firm _
but it also views Merrill Lynch, the brokerage giant that just
launched Web investing, as a major threat.
</P>
<P>
   Such a blurring of boundaries has led the fund industry to seek
new ways to help investors cultivate their financial gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the 1990s, the challenge was how fast can
you grab market share and growth,'' observed Avi Nachmany, a
financial services analyst at Strategic Insight, a New York
consulting company. ``Now for many firms, the challenge is to
ensure you're the premier financial relationship for your
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dot.com world, that task is accomplished with the Internet.
Last year, few fund firms had a Web site; now, 80 percent do. With
investors increasingly sophisticated and exposed to ever more
information through investment publications, news programs, and Web
sites, the Internet is allowing fund sellers to offer increasingly
tailored service, including financial planning, investment
education, account statements, daily portfolio pricing, tax
information, and real-time market and other news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most significant changes you'll see going forward at
Fidelity (come from) the impact of the Internet on our business,''
said Robert Pozen, the company's chief of investments. ``It's going
to allow us to deliver a very customized product.''
</P>
<P>
   For firms that sell funds through banks, brokers, and financial
advisers, the Internet poses special challenges. Such companies,
including Putnam Investments, American Fund Distributors, and MFS
Investment Management, have to balance the shift toward direct,
personalized service with the demands of their
intermediary-sellers, who fear Web services could cut them out.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the threat to the middleman is small. Only 13 percent of
funds are sold directly to investors by fund firms; the remaining
sales are through intermediaries or to employer-sponsored
retirement plans. Still, fund firms are beefing up their Web sites
to give third-party sellers more planning tools. With the Internet,
``we will see more effective, personalized, immediate ways of
communicating'' among fund sellers, investors and intermediaries,
said Putnam's chief executive, Lawrence Lasser.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's technological mindset is a response to fresh
competitive forces.
</P>
<P>
   Do-it-yourself Web investing, which has jolted Wall Street
enough to cause even staid brokerages to adopt on-line trading, has
put many fund firms on guard. For the fund world, Internet
stockpicking ``is clearly a competitive threat,'' said John
Brennan, chairman and chief executive at The Vanguard Group.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is especially dangerous to Vanguard, whose specialty,
index funds, made the Valley Forge, Pa., company the best-selling
fund group of the 1990s. Because index funds passively mirror a
benchmark's composition and involve no active stockpicking, they
are the antithesis of on-line stock trading. While Meir Statman, a
finance professor at California's Santa Clara University, said
investors appeared to have embraced self-directed stockpicking,
other observers call the trend overhyped. Nachmany said only 1
percent of the investing population had jumped into on-line
trading. And with some of the biggest fund sellers, like Fidelity
and Schwab, operating brokerages with on-line services, fund firms
have an edge in drawing Web traders.
</P>
<P>
   But other problems loom.
</P>
<P>
   After raking in $12.8 billion in net new cash in 1990, stock
funds, the most popular form of mutual fund, saw flows rise nearly
twentyfold, to a peak of $227.1 billion in 1997. The figures
reflect the amount of money going into funds minus sums going out,
or withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   Gross sales are still strong. But much of the new money has been
going to flavor-of-the-moment technology funds, a sign that
investors are chasing past gains and are perhaps less inclined to
treat mutual funds as a long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
   More striking is a dramatic rise in withdrawals, or redemptions.
Investors bought $815.3 million worth of stock funds in the first
11 months of 1999, 28 percent more than a year earlier, but they
also increased redemptions by nearly 40 percent, to $661.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The net result is a 6.3 percent drop in net sales of equity
funds last year through November; for some individual firms, the
decline is in double digits. Redemptions in bond funds have been
steeper still. David Haywood, an analyst at Financial Research
Corp., estimates that half of all fund companies are losing more
cash than they are taking in.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawals are costly to firms, since managing less money
produces lower fees. They are also disruptive to portfolio
managers, who must sell holdings to raise cash. And the slowdown
has led stocks of publicly traded fund companies to slump.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers call the fund industry a victim of its own
success, and say investors, who have captured heady gains, are
cashing out of funds to buy expensive goods.
</P>
<P>
   Others wonder if Americans have grown comfortable with saving
less. Another theory posits that investors have become greedy and
are pulling out money to gamble on Internet stocks or to trade on
line. Still another cites lingering investor trauma from Russia's
1998 financial collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its cause, the sales decline marks a turning point for
the industry, which was born in Boston in 1924, when Massachusetts
Investors Trust, now MFS, sold a fund full of shares in companies
like Union-Pacific Railroad and Edison Electric of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bright but brief beginning. By spoiling investors'
appetite for stocks, the Depression stifled the fund industry's
potential for decades. In the 1980s, the business awakened, as star
portfolio managers like Peter Lynch became household names and the
idea of low-cost, professionally managed portfolios gained mass
appeal. In the early 1990s, funds blossomed, as America's great
bull market took off and investors doubted the government's ability
to provide for their retirement _ a loss of faith that led to the
rise of the 401(k) corporate retirement plan, in which funds are
prominent.
</P>
<P>
   As revolutionary as credit cards and cash machines, the Great
Mutual Fund Revolution had huge consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Once shackled to expensive broker fees, Main Street now had an
affordable way to participate in Wall Street's boom. Scores of fund
owners became millionaires. Money once kept in banks and brokerage
accounts flowed to fund firms _ by 1998, fund assets surpassed bank
holdings for the first time in history. Individual investors now
control nearly 80 percent of the fund industry's assets, making
them a powerful force in markets. (Institutional investors,
insurers, and banks account for the remaining 20 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Riding that wave, the number of fund firms more than quadrupled
last decade, to more than 600. Funds, and their burgeoning
varieties, now outnumber listed stocks. Even other businesses
jumped on the bandwagon, with companies like General Motors and
United Airlines launching their own retail funds.
</P>
<P>
   But after years of uninterrupted growth and extraordinary
prosperity, the fund world is ripe for winnowing.
</P>
<P>
   About 72 percent of net sales were made by the 10 largest
players, according to Financial Research. The crowded field has led
analysts to predict that the largest and the smaller, niche firms
will survive, while mid-tier players, with tens of billions in
assets, will merge with other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The big guns have vowed to sit out the shakeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will definitely not be acquired, and we will not be
acquiring funds companies or banks or going public,'' said
Fidelity's Pozen. ``Although it's possible we could spin off a
non-core part of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   On other fronts, fund executives must now manage investors'
robust expectations. Bolstered by history's longest bull market,
the average US diversified stock fund has posted double-digit gains
for seven out of the past 10 years, including a 27.1 percent rise
in 1999, according to Lipper Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single biggest challenge going forward is the market and
investors' expectations,'' said Vanguard's Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   And firms that sell to 401(k) plans, a major source of profit
and growth to the fund industry, face pressure to lower
administrative fees as well as competition from alternative,
cheaper institutional accounts. The challenges have led Putnam to
introduce record-keeping for retirement plans with company stock,
and Fidelity to court the small-business retirement plan market
through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders have faith that the business can reinvent
itself. Putnam is launching hedge funds and hungrily eyeing foreign
retirement-plan markets, and most players are plotting ways to
capture money from baby boomers, who will need new homes for their
401(k) money after retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there is going to be more competition and more
innovation,'' said David Pottruck, Schwab's president and co-chief
executive. ``Fund firms have to find how to make themselves more
consumer-friendly. We need more new ideas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
