<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CASUALTY OF HISTORY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1920s, a time of emotional exhaustion, someone asked
James Joyce what he did during the Great War. The author replied:
``I wrote `Ulysses.' What did you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton did not write ``Ulysses,'' but has sometimes lived
it. As the Clinton era, a seven-year run-on sentence, grinds toward
its last chapter, the question of ``legacy'' haunts the Joycean
protagonist in the White House and has for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may never have been a president so widely read in
American history or so covetous of a large place in the history
books as Bill Clinton,'' William E. Leuchtenburg said last year.
``When I encountered the president at a White House picnic in
1994,'' the University of North Carolina historian added, ``Clinton
interrogated me closely, and knowledgeably, on Roosevelt. `This guy
can cite you details about every president,' one of his advisers
has asserted.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton knows that peace and prosperity are poor clay for Mount
Rushmore, which salutes those who handled war and tumult. Lists of
presidential quotes will cite Clinton for memorable denials: what
he didn't inhale and with whom he did not have sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Letters of a Nation,'' compiled in 1997, reprints epistles
from Benjamin Franklin, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Harry Truman, and
others. Bill Clinton is represented for his 1969 letter thanking
Colonel Eugene Holmes ``for saving me from the draft.'' The letter
is honeycombed with classically Clintonian swerves and cadenzas,
the type that baffle his opponents and activate itchy thumbs on
home C-span zappers.
</P>
<P>
   Eloquence was not on Clinton's to-do list. He enjoyed too much
success in Hope and Hot Springs putting the hay down where the
goats can get at it: no flights of fancy, no Kennedysque calls for
sacrifice, no call to arms against a common foe. Lars-Erik Nelson
explains Clinton's luck in the Jan. 20 New York Review of Books:
``Though he is an eloquent speaker, he seldom directs his oratory
against his enemies. Rather he lets them snarl themselves into
inchorence.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rules of legacy are harsher than the rules of life. ``In
this job, I am not worried about my enemies,'' President Warren G.
Harding once remarked. ``It is my friends who are giving me
trouble.'' When history judged Harding, he could not blame Albert
Fall, Harry Daugherty, or ``the Ohio Gang.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton is judged, he also will stand alone, without the
protective phalanx of Kevin Starr, Linda Tripp, and all the Zouaves
and zanies in Congress assembled by Newt Gingrich. The former House
speaker, at first beguiled, overreacted to Clinton's charm with a
self-destructive ferocity matched by Master-at-arms Claggart in
Herman Melville's ``Billy Budd.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, impeachment and investigations repelled more
people than they attracted, turning Clinton into a sympathetic
figure. But people can be fickle and cruel. In 1923, the nation
grieved when Harding died. When his personal and political scandals
were revealed, they laughed at him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would like to be remembered, Clinton has said that
he tried to help better people's lives. He was a strong case, both
at home and overseas. But history has a laugh track. If Mark Twain
is recalled more fondly than Benjamin Harrison, Jay Leno carries
more clout and longevity than Lanny Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legacy may be more comic than tragic, a tragedy in
itself. In 50, 75, or 100 years, readers of history may giggle at
Clinton, asking ``He did what? Where? With whom?''
</P>
<P>
   He has considerable skills and decent instincts, but often
overcalculates them into trivia. Polls and stagecraft can not
soothe Clinton's obsession with legacy because history is an
occupational hazard. ``We cannot escape history,'' Abraham Lincoln
said. James Joyce had a more mordant view, expressed by a character
in Ulysses: ``History,'' he said, ``is a nightmare from which I am
trying to awake.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
