<HEADER>
A3906 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WANTED-FOR-MURDER-BOS     01-12 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANTED-FOR-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCK RUNS OUT FOR 1976 SLAY SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Just six months after James Anthony Martin allegedly
shot to death a recent Harvard graduate in 1976, he was arrested on
a drug charge in California. Masking himself as Bruce Benjamin, a
small-time drug dealer, the man police in Boston and Cambridge,
Mass. were scrambling to find walked away free as a bird.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a quarter of a century, Martin, now 51, used more
than 20 aliases in slipping from the grips of authorities again and
again. He was arrested 16 times in Montreal alone _ and at least
twice in the United States _ but always stayed one step ahead of
those who hunted him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed his name with the climate,'' said Sergeant
Detective Patrick Nagle of the Cambridge Police Department. ``For
every crime he assumed a new alias.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, for the first time in 23 years, Martin, tall, thin and
graying, was back in the Boston area, being arraigned in Middlesex
Superior Court for the death of 28-year-old Edward Paulsen. Last
week, he was arrested in Montreal, where he has lived since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not guilty,'' he declared firmly.
</P>
<P>
   But to many in the courtroom, the question wasn't whether Martin
was guilty of the Paulsen murder, but how Martin managed to elude
authorities while making almost regular trips to the courthouse and
lock-up in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the rickety and poor neighborhood on the east side
of Montreal where Martin was known simply as ``Tony,'' some of his
Canadian friends described him as a modern-day Pied Piper, loved by
children and pets. A friend, Daniel Gagnon, said, ``He had a hard
life. You can tell by looking in his eyes that he has been through
hard stuff. (But) he changed his life. Tony is a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   But others saw him as a scoundrel who couldn't be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always trying to be what you would call a bad boy,''
said Daniel Bourbonnais, the owner of a local grocery store. ``He
even spit on one of our cashiers when he caught him trying to steal
a package of Kool Aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who spoke publicly last week before Canadian immigration
officials, insisted he is no longer the sly young exile whose only
care was to escape police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was selfish,'' Martin said to officials. ``I have changed
considerably. . . Before, there was no hope in my life. Now it's
different.''
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Sept. 9, 1976, police said, Martin was a drug
dealer and a robber who, in a flash of anger, became a murderer.
</P>
<P>
   At about 9:15 that night, Paulsen and his brother, Richard, went
to a Cambridge apartment carrying $1,600 they planned to exchange
for a kilo of hashish. A friend of Martin's, Gordon Kent Brown, had
offered to sell the drugs to them.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of the Paulsen boys, Edward, known as Ward, was a
recent Harvard graduate whose rise from a South Boston housing
project to one of the nation's most prestigious universities gave
him a sort of hero status, according to his sister Denise Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who apparently knew the Paulsens slightly through his
friend Brown, showed up, intending to rob the two men, according to
court documents. Waving a gun, Martin forced the Paulsens on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down on the floor,'' he ordered. ``Where is the money?''
</P>
<P>
   When Edward Paulsen raised his hands, according to court
documents, Martin, standing five feet away, shot him in the chest.
Richard Paulsen, who now lives in France, was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Martin's then-girlfriend, Meredith ``Patricia''
Weiss, police said, Brown and Martin trucked to New York City,
throwing the gun into the Mystic River on the way. They took a bus
to California, where Martin stayed with a distant cousin. He later
ended up in Richmond, Calif., where he was arrested for a small
drug charge under the name of Bruce Benjamin. By the time
California officials realized who he was, Martin had already left
California and moved to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, now 49, was captured in New Jersey and convicted of
second-degree murder in 1982. Martin, however, began a life in
Montreal, leaving behind his identity and any part he might have
played in Paulsen's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to Canada to flee the charges that we are now dealing
with in Massachusetts,'' he told immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
   During his years in Montreal, he gained an extremely long rap
sheet, said Francois Laberge, senior officer at the Immigration and
Refugee Board. Martin was charged with 31 crimes, including petty
theft, armed robbery, forcible confinement, and transporting
narcotics. Although he spent from 1991 to 1993 in a Canadian prison
on drug charges, said police, prison officials never discovered he
was wanted on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Canadian officials, tired of Martin's criminal ways,
deported him to the United States. He returned to Canada just two
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew the system. He was smart,'' said Cambridge detective
Sil Ferreira, who with the help of the FBI tracked Martin down last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Martin managed to cloak his past even from his friends and wife
in Canada. What people who knew him in Montreal believe about
Martin's youth is far from the reality. He was not raised in a
crime-riddled neighborhood somewhere in America, as they were told,
but in middle-class Englewood, N.J., just outside of New York City,
said David Bowman, Englewood's police chief and a high school
classmate of Martin.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, now in her 80s, still lives in the family's Green
Street home where she raised her children alone.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Martin played football and wrote poetry,
according to his younger sister, Julia Martin. Under James Anthony
Martin's photo in the Dwight Morrow High School 1967 yearbook is
his name and the nickname ``Bosco'' _ one of the many aliases
authorities say he used in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew him from going to the school system,'' Bowman
explained. ``I just remember seeing him in school with no sorts of
association. At the time it seemed to me he never had any set
buddies. He was either a loner or with different people all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Paulsen homicide, Englewood police set up surveillance
through the years during the holidays in case Martin showed up, but
police believe he never did.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Martin concentrated on building a new life in Canada.
Friends say he met his common-law wife, Silvie, in a
drug-rehabilitation center in Montreal. Although Martin told police
he has worked steadily, police say he survived by selling drugs,
stealing, and by defrauding the Canadian welfare system. Local
police say Martin apparently used an alias even with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The couple lived in a $325-a-month, two-bedroom apartment in
Montreal's rough eastside. On a snowy day last week, peeking from
his mailbox was a letter addressed to Robert Beal, the latest alias
he was using. Martin was also fond of the names Tony Bosco, Tony
Day, Tony Martin, and Edward Carlson, a name eerily similar in
sound to his alleged murder victim.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, neighbors watched the lean American trek up and
down the street with his Siberian husky and large black mutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tall black man with this big black dog stuck out in this
predominantly white neighborhood,'' said Norman Deshchamps, a
friend of Martin. His race and strong New Jersey accent fanned
suspicions that he was a drug dealer, said Deshchamps, adding, ``He
got his bike stolen three times but he didn't retaliate.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends say his illegal status in the country forced him to take
on under-the-table jobs and work at a scrap metal shop, but mostly
depend on financial help from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   As for Martin's common-law wife, who was unavailable to comment,
Gagnon said, ``She is crying and sad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writer John Ellement and Globe correspondent Karen
Eschbacher contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3911 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-12 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHALLOW CASE FOR THE SJC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depth perception was obviously not a strong suit of Joseph
O'Sullivan's. This deficiency could have evoked some sympathy,
since all of us have hurt ourselves during a rash impulse, a
seizure of stupidity or accidents where the placing of blame was
merely a laugh upon one self. In my family's case, to borrow from
an early 1990s Spike Lee sneaker ad, it was the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   My wife hates high heels because when she was in medical school,
she fell down the stairs at the wedding of a classmate and broke
her arm. I am four and a half years removed from a ripped Achilles
tendon, which occurred while playing tennis in bad shoes I borrowed
from a friend. The soles were already shredded. With every shot,
they disintegrated into debris that littered the court as I was
being driven away with my ice pack.
</P>
<P>
   It never occurred to my wife to look up a lawyer over her fall.
It never crossed my mind to sue my friend over the shoes. This is
where O'Sullivan goes from sympathy to silly.
</P>
<P>
   On a July night in 1996, O'Sullivan was at the pool of his
girlfriend's grandparents in Methuen, Mass. He decided to dive off
the shallow end. He had swum in the pool before so he knew its
dimensions. Since he was an experienced swimmer, he must have
understood through cultural osmosis that diving off shallow end of
a pool was potentially dangerous and therefore dumb.
</P>
<P>
   In swimming pools, depth does not discriminate. Whether they are
the budget round tubs of the working class, the in-ground concrete
pools of the middle class, the ornate tilings of hotels and
mansions, or the Olympic-length monsters of health clubs and
colleges, pools all have one thing in common: Shallow ends.
</P>
<P>
   Shallow ends are so clearly shallow that they need warning signs
about as much as you need a sign to keep you from walking across a
freeway. Even so-called ``deep'' ends of backyard pools are rarely
mistaken for the dropoff on the continental shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Shallow ends are a deliberate evolution. A San Diego Tribune
feature last year on home swimming pools said the kind of divable
pools once glamorized by Marilyn Monroe ``has almost disappeared, a
victim of concerns about safety and liability, as well as a deep
end that is getting shallower. The most popular pool configuration
today is two shallow ends, each about 3.5 feet, that gently slope
to a maximum depth of five feet in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there are few home pools where one can stand at the edge
of any end, strech the arms like Greg Louganis, and dive headfirst
with any confidence that you will pop back to the surface without
either a Michael Jackson nosejob or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what O'Sullivan did. He dived, enriching local
neurosurgeons who must have whispered a private ``tsk, tsk, tsk,''
over his two cracked cervical vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   As howling newspaper readers now know, O'Sullivan did not stop
at counting God's blessings that he was not permanently paralyzed.
He turned around and sued the grandparents of the girlfriend in a
case that is being heard by the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial
Court.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court said the pool owners were not responsible for
O'Sullivan's injuries under the concept of ``open and obvious''
dangers. Like walking across railroad tracks and getting diced by a
train. Sprinting across I-95 and getting splattered. Wearing
disintegrating tennis shoes. But the SJC, for reasons that may have
as much to do with needing a laugh as trying to draw a sober lines
of liability on pools, chose to hear O'Sullivan's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan wails a bottom line about hitting the bottom that
would appeal only to the personal injury law offices of Slick,
Trick and St. Nick. Despite being 21 at the time, O'Sullivan blamed
the pool owners for not stopping him from hurting himself. He said
others had been allowed to dive at the shallow end. The pool had no
lights, depth markers or depth warnings.
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan's attorney argues that since he received no personal
warning from the owners that diving in the shallows was dangerous,
the owners were negligent. This is nuts. If pool owners are
responsible for adults who choose to disregard one of the most
obvious of backyard dangers, then what about the guest who
volunteers to help you in the kitchen and then lops off a fingertip
with a knife? Or singe their hand on the stove? Or slips a disc
lifting a chair?
</P>
<P>
   The SJC should have its laugh and then dismiss this case. You
may think it was annoying a few years ago when people had yellow
caution ``Baby on board'' signs in their cars. You have not seen
ugly yet. Imagine a Martha Stewart nightmare, with deadly danger
signs on all toys, kitchen utensils, garden tools, heavy furniture,
electric sockets _ and tennis shoes and high heels. It still will
not be enough. There will always still be someone who cannot be
protected from himself, like Joseph O'Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Boston Globe columnist. His e-mail address
is jackson(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
