<HEADLINE>
NEW WEBSITE WOOS THE FAITHFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new independent, multifaith and comprehensive religion and
spirituality Web site has been launched on the Internet.
Beliefnet.com (www.beliefnet.com) intends to offer news,
information, reports, inspiration, and support in a way that treats
all faiths with equal respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike most religious sites, Beliefnet.com offers an open
community where all faiths and belief systems get careful editorial
coverage,'' said Robert Nylen, co-founder of Beliefnet.com and
founding CEO of the now defunct New England Monthly. ``We welcome
the pious as well as the curious, and we don't fear controversy. We
want to spark some healthy arguments. We welcome alternatives to
traditional thinking as well as conventional spiritual views.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet venture is funded by Highland Capital Partners of
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RELIGION NOTES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Religious repression in China has worsened in recent weeks
with the sentencing of Falun Gong and Christian leaders, according
to the US Commission on International Religious Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exercise of state power in trying to quash religious
expression _ including arrests, imprisonment, and the use of
state-run media to slander people because of their religious
practices, worship or teaching _ is alarming to all those who care
about religious freedom,'' said Rabbi David Saperstein, the
commission's chairman. ``This can only set back China's current
efforts to participate fully in a world community committed to
international rights and liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
