<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FRIDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE CUBE DISHES UP `FRIDAY' LITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
NEXT FRIDAY 
Directed by: Steve Carr 
Screenplay by: Ice Cube 
Starring: Ice Cube, John Witherspoon, Don ``DC'' Curry, Mike Epps,
Justin Pierce, Jacob Vargas, Lobo Sebastian, Rolando Molina, Lisa
Rodriguez, Tommy ``Tiny'' Lister, Jr. 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: R (strong language, drug use and sexual content) 
Star rating: 1 1/2 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Next Friday'' is a sequel to 1995's ``Friday,'' which at best
was a sort of ``Boyz N the Hood'' Lite. ``Next Friday'' is Liter
than Lite. Mostly, it's a string of cartoony vignettes pretending
to be a movie. At times, it all but turns invisible as it tries to
reverse the formula by sending Ice Cube's LA South Central dweller
out to the suburbs, where so much stuff comes at him that he soon
finds himself longing for the relative peace and quiet of the
'hood. A lot of energy goes into trying to pick this concept up and
run with it, but it doesn't go far.
</P>
<P>
   Cucamonga, an LA suburban town whose very name was regarded as a
sure-fire knee-slapper decades ago on old radio comedy shows,
apparently is still viewed as a source of mirth, but only in a
script as mediocre as this one. It ranges from lazy to nonexistent,
as it sends Ice Cube's cool dude named Craig out there to lay low
for a while when word gets out that the big bully Craig busted four
years ago is being released from prison and is in payback mode.
Craig's uncle, it seems, has hit the lottery and has bought a house
there.
</P>
<P>
   In Rancho Cucamonga, Craig's Uncle Elroy (Don ``DC'' Curry) is
able to keep himself in a marijuana haze and indulge himself with
kinky sex toys that would get him banned from the 'hood. Because
he's been inattentive to such details as property taxes, he's about
to lose the house, which adds to the woes of Craig's cousin Day-Day
(Mike Epps), who is embroiled with a couple of women far tougher
than he is. Given that, and the activities across their cul-de-sac
of a rough-edged trio of Hispanic drug-dealing brothers who have
taken over their mother's house, Craig, who thought he was fleeing
his problems, finds he has more of them than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The action is mostly witless and predictable. One measure of its
desperation and lack of respect for its audience is the frequency
with which it labors to wring humor from flatulence and excrement
gags. Mostly, it's Craig's father (John Witherspoon) who's saddled
with these, not to mention us.
</P>
<P>
   The only notable aspect of the crude, lame ``Next Friday'' is
that it furthers the producing career of Ice Cube, the rapper
turned movie star. ``Next Friday'' represents a step backward from
the last film he masterminded, ``The Player's Club.'' Still, he's
clearly a presence who not only stars in movies, but can make them
happen, and he's only just getting started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1345EST &QL; 
