<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3918 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      01-12 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNETTE AND WARREN; INTERNET PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All is perfectly wonderful at the Beatty-Bening house, in case
you were wondering. He's working on a movie, she's working on a
movie, he's flirting with the political press, she's flirting with
an Oscar, he's full of opinions about the candidates, she's
pregnant once again. Vanity Fair for February dines with the couple
of the moment, and there's really not much to report. Oh, except
some giggles about the beginnings of their relationship, when
Warren took Annette aside and said, ``I want to tell you that I'm
not making a pass at you, but if I were to be so lucky as to have
that occurrence happen, that I want to assure you that I would try
to make you pregnant immediately.'' His line worked, of course, and
nine or so months later, their first daughter was born.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair's mogul slot goes to Clive Davis, the legendary and
controversial music honcho who is about to be honored at the Grammy
Awards and inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. The long
article charts his ups and downs, including his current battle with
BMG Entertainment, but the more interesting bits involve his role
in the making of pop stars like Barry Manilow, Whitney Houston, and
Janis Joplin, who offered him a roll in the hay as a ``fitting and
proper'' way to cement their deal. Joplin wasn't happy when Davis
doctored ``Piece of My Heart'' for radio play _ he cut 65 seconds
and added another chorus _ but she didn't complain when the single
helped sell over a million albums.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Forum in the January Harper's focuses on privacy and what
will happen to ours as we continue to spill our personal data _
medical, financial, consumer _ onto the Internet. The conversation,
among the executive VP of Lycos, a law professor specializing in
privacy, a former New York prosecutor, and an academic involved in
Clinton's Internet regulation policy, is very smart stuff, with the
potential to make you more than a little paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the scarier notes are hit by the gentleman from Lycos,
who notes that ``the ultimate power of the Web potentially lies in
my ability to store and reduce your query strings _ what you type
into my search box _ and then give you information based on what
I've learned about your behavior.'' Gives new meaning to that
phrase about ``Be careful what you ask for . . .'' Right now, this
sort of information is anonymous _ the name of the user often
cannot be identified _ but who knows? ``The risk is that we could
become a society in which your future is predestined at birth,''
notes the academic. ``When if you come, informationally, from a
certain neighborhood, that information becomes a self-fulfilling
prophesy, defining the sort of offers that you receive, your credit
opportunities, your school choices, even the banner ads you see
when you get to a certain Web site. When the scope of your future
is limited by information in your profile at each step of your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Literally during the course of writing the previous paragraph, I
received an e-mail promotion from a company offering to help me
``get the facts on anyone using the Internet.'' The service _ a
software program and not a private detective agency _ will ``locate
missing persons'' and ``find out SECRETS about your relatives,
friends, enemies, and everyone else!''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? I hope so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever glanced at the European glossies, you've probably
noticed the intensified candor of the European hype machine.
Celebrities who make guarded chatter with American writers and bare
a shoulder for American photographers often remove quite a few more
veils when visiting the Continent. It's not uncommon to find
inter-celebrity-world insults and even a nipple here and there from
our very own stars (although Cameron Diaz's bun cleavage on the
January Vanity Fair cover was a first for me). They do as the
Romans do, or undo as the case may be.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I wasn't completely surprised to find the usually
buttoned-up Edward Norton revealing his pubic hair on the cover of
The Face, to promote ``The Fight Club.'' Looking like some sort of
London lad _ Norton doing Daniel Day Lewis doing Johnny in ``My
Beautiful Laundrette''? _ the actor pulls his pants right down to
the brim for the hipped-out British magazine, which some US
newsstands import. But Norton clings to his Stateside restraint in
the article itself, unwilling to go all the way in his fashionable
exhibitionism. About queries into his personal life, he reminds the
interviewer, ``Fame is very corrosive and you have to guard very
strictly against it.'' Yes, by pulling down your knickers on the
cover of an international publication . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
