<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3920 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SERBIA-CHECHNYA-HNS &LR;      01-12 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-CHECHNYA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. SHOULD PRACTICE WHAT IT PREACHES TO RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALEX A. VARDAMIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. _ Russia's military offensive in Chechnya is an
unintended result of NATO's attack on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   There are many similarities between the two conflicts, both in
concept and in execution. Russia has learned from our example.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombed Serbia into submission. Russia hopes to bomb
Chechnya into submission.
</P>
<P>
   NATO claimed that it did not target Serbian civilians. Russia
claims that it does not target Chechen civilians. A Russian
official complains, ``When you (Americans) bombed civilians in
Kosovo, you called it collateral damage. When we do it, you call it
a violation of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombardment caused hundreds of thousands of refugees to
flee from Kosovo. Russian bombs drive columns of refugees out of
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   NATO claimed that the war was necessary to defeat Serbian
terrorists, thugs and murderers. Russia claims it must, similarly,
rout Chechen terrorists, thugs and murderers.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombed because its credibility was in jeopardy. Russia
bombs, in the words of Soviet-era dissident Alexander Solzhenitsyn,
because, ``We have capitulated everywhere. Our country cannot
abandon the right to defend itself, and defense means completing
this operation.''
</P>
<P>
   The acting president of Russia, Vladimir Putin, echoed these
sentiments, saying, ``We will not tolerate any humiliation to the
national pride of Russians or any threat to the integrity of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO avoided a ground war, fearing heavy allied casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening to ``drop the bridges and turn out the lights'' if
Belgrade did not surrender, the West defeated Yugoslavia through
massive aerial bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Russia lost the first war in Chechnya in 1994-96 because it got
bogged down in ground combat.
</P>
<P>
   This time Moscow, seeking to minimize its losses, replicates
NATO's tactics. Recently, though, winter has set in and poor
visibility has made bombing difficult. Russian casualties have
begun to mount.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Russian entreaties against NATO's massive
application of force in Serbia were ignored. This winter, Western
condemnations of Russia's ``indiscriminate bombing'' are
disregarded in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   At a summit in Istanbul in mid-November, President Clinton
warned his ``good friend'' Boris Yeltsin that if attacks on
civilians continued, ``the world would not stand idly by.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who turned over power to Putin two weeks ago, responded
that Clinton could no longer claim the moral high ground. Wasn't
the attack on Serbia a war of ``disproportionate consequence?''
</P>
<P>
   Had not the United States used inflated estimates of hundreds of
thousands of murdered Kosovars as a pretext to interfere in a
sovereign nation's internal affairs?
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Clinton again warned that the offensive must stop.
Yeltsin reminded Washington ``that Russia has a full arsenal of
nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   How did we get to this war of words? What happened to glasnost
and perestroika?
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the Russians drove the Communists out of power
with the expectation that the Free World would embrace them as
allies. It never happened.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the collapse of the Berlin Wall, the West
promised that it would not expand eastward.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, NATO, with the inclusion of Poland, the Czech
Republic and Hungary, has moved up to the borders of the former
Soviet Union. It threatens to extend the alliance still further.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, reversing long-standing arms control
policy, seems determined to press ahead with an antimissile defense
that would abrogate the ABM treaty of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-conceived, poorly monitored infusion of billions of
dollars from the International Monetary Fund into Russia has
created a kleptocracy in which the shrewd and corrupt strip the
country of its assets and drive average, law-abiding citizens into
poverty. While criminals with foreign bank accounts live in regal
splendor, Russian pensioners go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   And to add insult to injury, at the very conference in which the
West demanded a withdrawal from Chechnya, a treaty designed to
squeeze Russia out of petroleum profits was signed. With Clinton as
smiling witness, Azerbaijan, Georgia and Turkey agreed to build a
pipeline that, intentionally bypassing Russia, would send Caspian
Sea oil directly into Western markets.
</P>
<P>
   Our idle threats over Chechnya are counterproductive. If we
truly want Moscow to stop targeting civilians, we should set the
example.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex A. Vardamis, the former director for European studies at
the Army War College, is a retired colonel who served as military
attache in Greece.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3923 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-HOOKS-2TAKES-B     01-12 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-HOOKS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL HOOKS OFFERS A NEW LOOK AT AN OLD SUBJECT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (bell hooks (lc) is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The subject is love and bell hooks is trying to
explain why she, a feminist theorist who found fame writing
provocative prose about sexism, racism, and other forms of
domination, would devote a whole book to it.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, her answers are hesitant, her focus on the
consumption of a raisin bagel and tea in a rustic cafe a few blocks
from her West Village apartment. Then, as the bread disappears and
she relaxes, her tongue loosens. She embarks on thoughtful
soliloquies about the subject that are punctuated by the hiss of an
espresso machine and the murmur of the thickening crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Hooks first summons up the words of 20-something author
Elizabeth Wurtzel, who wrote, ``My generation is afraid to love.''
Then there's her interview with hip-hop artist Lil' Kim, who told
hooks flatly, ``Love? What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   Hooks mentions the fights about love she and her former
boyfriend Anthony kept having a few years ago. He'd say he didn't
think he knew what love was. She pledged to find a book that would
teach him about it. When she couldn't unearth the right one, hooks
vowed, ``OK, I'm going to write you this book.'' That promise was
kept with ``All About Love: New Visions,'' published last month.
</P>
<P>
   She uses excerpts from books by Jack Kornfield, M. Scott Peck,
and Marianne Williamson and examples from her own life to define
love and discuss factors such as greed and dishonesty that keep
people from finding it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dedicated to (Anthony), you know,'' says hooks, 47, who
spells her name in lower-case letters so that the focus is on the
text, not the author. ``It's all the discussions we've had over
this period of 10 years as we struggled to make meaning out of
failed bonds in our lives. I just feel like it's where the struggle
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooks has become an intellectual superstar by finding the
struggles and writing about them. Her first scholarly work, 1981's
``Ain't I a Woman: Black Women and Feminism,'' explored black
women's roles in the feminist movement. Since then, she's written
18 books.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fierce in insisting that the injustices and political
systems based on both race and sex be seen as connected and be
addressed,'' says Gloria Steinem, a longtime friend. ``She doesn't
let white feminists off the hook on race ever, and she doesn't let
black men and women off the hook on justice for the female half of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As the number of hooks's books rose, so did her national
profile. Her essays on race and feminism have become required
reading in women's studies classes across the country. In the last
few years, The Atlantic Monthly named her a leading intellectual
and Utne Reader included her in a list of the ``100 Visionaries Who
Could Change Your Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooks is now one of the few female members of an
African-American academic elite that includes Henry Gates and
Cornel West, with whom she co-wrote the 1991 book ``Breaking Bread:
Insurgent Black Intellectual Life.'' Try to think of any other
black feminist today who is as high-profile as she.
</P>
<P>
   Success, however, has brought its own problems. As hooks has
climbed the intellectual heights, her prodigious literary output
has made her a punching bag for some critics. And her aggressive
pursuit of the writer's life has kept this self-described
love-obsessed woman from finding the very subject she's enthralled
with: love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I would have written all these books had I been
partnered in a living situation,'' says hooks in her
preternaturally girlish voice, while relaxing in the sparsely
decorated living room of her modest one-bedroom apartment. The work
of mixed-media artist Radcliffe Bailey and photographer Carrie Mae
Weems lean casually against a dining room wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sort of create this whole world of ideas and write and
think,'' she continues. ``The truth is that is not a life that you
can easily do in relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The persona of bell hooks was born 28 years ago at Stanford
University. It was there that the 19-year-old student Gloria Jean
Watkins, of Hopkinsville, Ky., took her maternal
great-grandmother's name as a pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   As an undergraduate at Stanford and doctoral candidate at the
University of California at Santa Cruz, hooks built the foundation
for becoming a feminist thinker. Teaching jobs at Yale University,
Oberlin College, and City College of New York, where she's been on
sabbatical for two years, economically sustained her literary
goals.
</P>
<P>
   It took hooks almost 10 years to find a publisher for the first
book. Then she began writing and writing.
</P>
<P>
   There were the fiery scholarly essays that condemned what she
calls a ``white supremacist culture'' for its negative
representation of black women in pop culture and its refusal to
admit black women into discussions about race. Memoirs explored her
childhood and detailed how a 15-year non-monogamous relationship
with a poet and scholar nurtured her own development as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   She even published a children's book, ``Happy to Be Nappy,''
about the joys of natural African-American hair, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is enchanted with hooks's work. This is from a
Washington Post review of ``Remembered Rapture: The Writer at
Work,'' a book of essays about the writing life that was also
published last year: ``Treating hooks as a writer . . . is to
address just how repetitive and ultimately tiresome her essays
often become. An all-purpose litany such as white supremacist
capitalism patriarchal dominance is longer on crude reductiveness
than it is on nuanced complexity _ and the same thing can be said
about the rhythms of her sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Michele Wallace, a feminist best known for her
critically acclaimed 1979 work ``Black Macho and the Myth of the
Superwoman,'' wrote a scathing review of hooks's literary output. A
month ago Wallace called hooks to apologize for the Village Voice
piece. But during a recent interview, she stood by her critique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just amazed by somebody like bell,'' says Wallace, 48, a
professor of English, women's studies, and film studies at City
College, where hooks is a Distinguished Professor of English, ``who
feels as though she has something of use to tell people on a
regular basis, like I mean once a year. It's one thing when Susan
L. Taylor does it or Iyanla Vanzant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when somebody who's as intelligent as bell is does it, you
have to wonder what is going on in her head,'' she continues,
adding sarcastically, ``but I guess you'd have to read all the
books to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooks blames Wallace's outbursts on the subjects she often
writes about.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the things that fueled her anger toward me had to do
with the sexist and very racist ways black women writers are
treated,'' says hooks during a telephone interview. ``People of
color often get pitted against one another by the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Displeasure about hooks's voluminous scholarly output, a theme
in many articles about her, is particularly galling to hooks and
her supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does no one ever say that about a man?'' asks Tracy
Sherrod, a senior editor at Pocket Books who, while at Henry Holt,
edited ``Remembered Rapture'' as well as hooks's memoirs ``Bone
Black: Memories of Girlhood'' and ``Wounds of Passion: A Writing
Life.'' ``No one says that about Joyce Carol Oates. Is it because
(hooks) is a black woman? What is it that makes people want to
silence her in particular?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
