<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AOL-TIME WARNER: SOOOOO 20TH CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It had to happen, but it happened awfully soon.
I heard the phrase ``You're too 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   The nasty comment wasn't directed at me, but it might as well
have been. A lot of us are not now and never have been dot-commies.
We're not broadband or multimedia enough to enter the new age
signaled by AOL's purchase of Time Warner _ the merger that's going
to change life on Earth as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   Or as USA Today put it in one of its dozens of headlines about
AOL on Tuesday: ``Will merger repackage life as we now live it?''
</P>
<P>
   Repackaged life, what a concept.
</P>
<P>
   Soon we'll be able to hear Madonna's singing, read Madonna's
book, watch Madonna's bulging arms, order Madonna's line of workout
wear and talk about Madonna in the Madonna chat room, all on one
screen with a click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   And multi-modality Madonna is the good part of the AOL-Time
Warner merger.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow I think this is the media merger that will affect my
life the least in the 21st century. And somehow I don't think AOL
will take over the world.
</P>
<P>
   If AOL does take over the world, does that mean the world is
going to be slow and ``kludgy,'' as the techies put it in their
portmanteau (portalmanteau?) word combining ``klutz'' and
``sludgy?''
</P>
<P>
   As a 20th century kind of guy I hate to say this, but AOL is so
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Little iMac Book,'' author Robin Williams (another one)
put it this way: ``America Online is a nice, friendly place. It's
like a safe, self-contained village. There are guides to help you,
`patrol officers' to make sure people are behaving properly,
instructions on where to go . But America Online is not the
Internet, nor is it the World Wide Web. When you are on America
Online, you are contained within their system of computers that
sits right in Virginia, the home of America Online.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams then said, ``If you think of America Online as a
village in Virginia, then the Internet is the big, wide world.''
</P>
<P>
   So basically, AOL is that great 20th century American concept, a
gated community. Like any other gated community, it offers the
illusion of comfort, but has disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   You actually lose privacy, because the management and anybody
else on AOL can keep track of your comings and goings.
</P>
<P>
   And they do it to sell you things. Spend some time in a Madonna
chat room, and you may find yourself getting spammed with offers to
buy the latest metal-covered book of naked Madonna photos.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than that, people can track their ex-spouses or employees
and see what chat rooms they're in.
</P>
<P>
   Despite looking clean and safe, AOL is built on that great 20th
century concept, talking dirty for fun and profit. It's a
classically seamy vision of American suburban life.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody gets together in the basement chat rooms of AOL's
gated community and anonymously propositions, brags and tells lies
to one another.
</P>
<P>
   AOL didn't invent on-line conversations, but brought them down
to the lowest common denominator. It all comes down to sex and
marketing, with a smiley face on the end.
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing against AOL now that I don't subscribe to it
anymore. Some chat rooms really are useful, like ones for senior
citizens and those with specialized interests, and not just sexual
ones.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that AOL doesn't work on iMacs very well, and I don't
need it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Even I, a technophobe, can get to the Internet without AOL.
</P>
<P>
   I hate AOL's ``buddy lists'' that allow people to spy and see if
I'm on line. They then can send me an instant message that I have
to respond to or seem impolite, which I am.
</P>
<P>
   I don't need the half-dozen anonymous names AOL allows
subscribers to use in chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The one time I went to a sex chat room (just for research, of
course) someone propositioned me within 30 seconds. Talk about
repackaging life. AOL repackaged singles bars in even more
frightening form.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst things about the AOL-Time Warner merger are
all the visions of a future we've been subjected to.
</P>
<P>
   Our TVs will be saying ``You've got mail,'' and not just when
that smarmy movie of the same name is on.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be able to shop for the same items of clothing worn by TV
and movie stars as we watch the shows. Just click on Buffy the
Vampire Slayer's mini-skirt or Mel Gibson's leather jacket.
</P>
<P>
   We can watch all the Atlanta Braves, Hawks and Thrashers games
we want _ and buy their logo sweat shirts without getting out of
the recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever there's a school shooting, we'll be able to call up
CNN's bloody footage as many times as we want, and not have to wait
for its half-hourly replays.
</P>
<P>
   According to one vision of ``repackaged life,'' we can even sit
in our remote-control home watching a program produced by Time
Warner's ``Cooking Light'' magazine and send a digital recipe to
our refrigerator, which could order ingredients it lacks from an
on-line grocery delivery service.
</P>
<P>
   That's all I need _ a refrigerator that talks to the world, and
not just to me. This is about as appealing as that old vision of
the future in which we ate food from squeeze tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Visions of the future are so 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
