<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A CENTURY OF MUSIC IN ONE SITTING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ We kicked it off at 8 p.m., with an unidentified
chorus singing, ``In the Good Old Summertime,'' and we ended it
seven hours and 40 minutes later with REM's ``Losing My Religion.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, Frank Sinatra led all artists with six appearances,
Billie Holiday came in second with four songs, and there was a
three-way tie for third among Giacomo Puccini, Judy Garland and
Glenn Miller, each with three.
</P>
<P>
   These are the results of a marathon music fest that anchored the
New Year's Eve party I attended. Besides black tie, champagne and a
home-cooked gourmet dish, our hostess Karen had required 10 songs
from each guest (and herself) _ one for every decade of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   All songs were submitted a couple of weeks ahead of time in CD,
tape or record form and transcribed onto three master cassettes by
our friend Stephen. Despite forgetting one choice for the 1950's _
Domenico Modugno's ``Volare'' _ Stephen turned in a super-human
performance. He even provided the sound of a train, then
helicopter, then jet, to carry us from one decade to another.
</P>
<P>
   If Karen hadn't exercised her hostess veto power and dinged a
few songs _ Madonna's ``Like a Virgin'' got the hook after six bars
_ we might have seen the sun come up to that last REM tune.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pick the most important or popular song from a
decade, we'd been told to choose the one song that best represented
our personal view of each 10-year span. Thus, many selections were
both esoteric and eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Todd chose ``Minnie the Moocher's Wedding Day'' for
the '30s; I chose ``Back Home Again in Indiana'' for the Teens, and
Peter chose a cut of his own son singing at the age of 6 for the
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth though, our band of 15 did choose eight
songs that made it onto National Public Radio's ``100 Most
Important American Musical Works of the Century.'' (The list was
compiled by NPR listeners and such musical luminaries as Wynton
Marsalis and San Francisco Symphony conductor Michael Tilson
Thomas.)
</P>
<P>
   Those were:
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy,'' performed by Patsy Cline; ``Give My Regards to
Broadway,'' performed by George M. Cohan; ``In the Mood,''
performed by Glenn Miller; ``Night and Day,'' performed by Bono of
U2; ``Take the A Train,'' performed by Duke Ellington; ``Purple
Haze,'' performed by Jimi Hendrix; ``Rock Around the Clock,''
performed by Bill Haley &AMP; the Comets; and ``Tonight'' from
``Westside Story,'' performed by Larry Kert and Carol Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra proved that, even in death, he's still chairman of our
board with ``One For My Baby,'' ``If You Are But a Dream,'' ``All
the Way,'' ``Young at Heart,'' ``In the Wee Small Hours'' and ``My
Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Holiday grabbed second with ``Love for Sale,'' ``It Had
To Be You,'' ``I Cried for You'' and ``Some Other Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Puccini's winners were E lucevan le stelle from ``Tosca,'' O mio
babbino caro from ``Gianni Schicci'' and Un bel di from ``Madama
Butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland's were ``Rockabye Your Baby,'' ``You Made Me Love You''
and ``Come Rain or Come Shine.''
</P>
<P>
   And Miller made it with ``In the Mood,'' ``Kalamazoo'' and
``Chattanoogo Choo-Choo.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a five-way tie for fourth among Fred Astaire (``The
Way You Look Tonight'' and ``They Can't Take That Away From Me''),
Duke Ellington (``A Train'' and ``Creole Love Call''), the Beatles
(``Hey, Jude'' and ``In My Life''), U2 (``Night and Day'' and
``One'') and REM (``Driver 8'' and ``Religion'').
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, our Most Valuable Player Award went to Shirley, who
couldn't make it to the party because she had the flu. She not only
submitted her 10 songs, she pinch hit in every decade for the less
imaginative among us with extra songs that ranged from ``Come
Josephine in My Flying Machine'' to the Pet Shop Boys' ``It's a
Sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of our '00-'69 highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Paul Robeson's rendition of ``Ol' Man River,'' Walter Huston's
``September Song,'' Bette Midler's ``The Glory of Love,'' Cliff
Edwards' ``When You Wish Upon a Star,'' Doris Day's ``Secret
Love,'' the Shirelles' ``Will You Still Love Me Tomorrow?'' Roy
Orbison's ``Only the Lonely,'' Connie Francis' ``Where the Boys
Are'' and The Who's ``My Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   From the '70s through 1999:
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dylan's ``Tangled Up in Blue,'' the Cars' ``Just What I
Needed,'' Odyssey's ``Native New Yorker,'' Pink Floyd's ``The
Gunner's Dream,'' ``Bryan Ferry's ``Name of the Game,'' Cake's
``The Distance,'' Bonnie Raitt's ``Come to Me,'' Kim Carnes'
``Bette Davis Eyes,'' Jane Siberey's ``Love Is Everything'' and the
song ``Without You'' from ``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   But as I said, those are only highlights. Except for the 10
minutes we took at midnight to ring in 2000, the hits just kept on
coming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
