<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTHDAY-PARTIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BIRTHDAY PARTIES FOR KIDS NO LONGER A PIECE OF CAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KERI P. MATTOX  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Children's birthday parties used to be a simple
affair _ hang some streamers, blow up a few balloons, bake a cake.
</P>
<P>
   But parents no longer throw parties. They buy them.
</P>
<P>
   Dance parties, days at the salon, museum tours, gymnastics
lessons and even $17,000 sleepover parties at F.A.O. Schwartz are
just a few of the lavish get-togethers parents plan for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, we've had one at a bowling alley, the roller
skating rink and a haunted miniature golf course,'' said Elena
Purritano of Watervliet, a Hudson River town north of Albany. She
says keeping parties exciting for her 10-year-old son, Anthony, and
her 9-year-old daughter, Anastasia, is a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do run out of ideas. It's not like it used to be. It's not
pin-the-tail-on-the-donkey anymore,'' she said. ``I did have one at
home and I had a ventriloquist.''
</P>
<P>
   The push by parents to give their kids the ``perfect party'' has
businesses fighting to outdo one another in their assortment of
party packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think parents over the years have definitely been doing
parties, but I think now parents are really looking for something
unique, for experts to make the birthday fun,'' said Jami Ehring,
owner of Tumbling Tykes of Colonie, an Albany suburb.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts warn that the event _ the birthday, the
graduation, the recital _ can lose some of its meaning if it's too
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly seems to me that over the past generation there
has been an enormous commercialization of family life. We now farm
out to strangers the acts of cleaning, cooking, caring for
children, caring for older loved ones and, in this case,
celebrating,'' said Dr. Elizabeth Berger, author of ``Raising
Children with Character'' and former faculty member at Columbia
University in New York. ``What the ordinary parent needs to focus
on is what is the take-home message for the child,'' she said. ``As
a celebration becomes less and less intimate, the emphasis becomes
more and more on the glossy appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Tumbling Tykes, which specializes in parties for kids ages 6 and
under, offers party plans from the $94 ``Basic'' to the $179
``Super-Duper'' for a 12-child party. Parents can sit back and
relax while Ehring's staff leads parachute play, story time, freeze
dancing and even pinata poking.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Tumbling Tykes hosted about 20 parties a month.
Now, with packed schedules for Thursday and Friday nights and all
day on Saturdays and Sundays, Tumbling Tykes squeezes in 30 parties
every month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly is very elaborate. Parents will bring in all kinds of
things. We've had catered parties,'' Ehring said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the New York State Museum in Albany courts parents. For
$100, 18 guests can choose from among eight slots available each
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We begin with a craft activity, an educational component, a
game or story time and then there's time available for presents and
snacks,'' said Barbara Lukas, the museum's public programs
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to turn people away because they just can't get the
date they want,'' Lukas said.
</P>
<P>
   But some families who opt for elaborate parties still try to
keep the focus on the family get-together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a family party and they have their own kids party,''
said Janice Chenot of Latham. Chenot's three children, Caitlin, 12,
Christie, 9, and Jordan, 7, have been having birthday bashes since
they started kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   For her 12th birthday, Caitlin and her parents threw a dance
party at a local dance studio for almost 50 preteen friends,
complete with a disc jockey, pizzas and soda. The bill for the
four-hour event, which totaled up at $350, was footed by both
Caitlin and her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a deal with our daughter _ that if she wanted to have
it she could, but she would have to pay for anything over $200,''
Chenot said. The expenses for each child's birthday party usually
run around $200, or $10 per guest, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Chenot kids have had plenty of parties at home _ with
swimming, magicians, ponies _ but almost all of their birthday
celebrations are held elsewhere now, Chenot said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that there isn't that much to do at home, but we're
all running out of ideas on how to keep the kids entertained.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3930 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FIRE-SIRENS-HNS &LR;      01-12 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-SIRENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIRE SIRENS REMAIN A (LOUD) FACT OF LIFE IN SOME COMMUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KERI P. MATTOX  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, N.Y. _ For 35 years, Benjamin Castle has lived only
half a block from the Delmar fire station and its wailing siren,
which he says knocks him off the deck of his house.
</P>
<P>
   Although the old siren was replaced three months ago with one
that emits a lower tone, Castle and his Adams Street neighbors
still get an earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem is that most of these firemen have two beepers, a
cell phone, a CB radio in their car,'' Castle said. ``I don't
understand. It's overkill.''
</P>
<P>
   The siren rings at 130 decibels _ louder than a jet at take off.
Many of the sirens were first installed as civil air defense
warnings during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, firehouses are silencing sirens in favor of
pagers. Others are restricting use of alarms after midnight and
before 7 a.m. But some fire companies in this slice of upstate New
York cling to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about going to all pagers, but we have so many of
our people that work outside that just can't hear the pagers
sometimes,'' said Delmar Fire Commissioner Gerald Day. ``I know
when I'm mowing the lawn, there's no way I would hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   The range of the Delmar siren is about a half mile, Day added.
``We have two stations, one on each end of the district, so between
the two of them, we can reach everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delmar fire company, which has 72 volunteers, does use
pagers for some calls.
</P>
<P>
   Delmar's original siren broke three months ago, so officials
decided to install a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first put it up _ it's an awful-looking thing _ there
was some concern, so I met with the neighbors and we talked about
it,'' Day said. ``We were going to have a second meeting, but there
weren't enough people still concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Castle and his neighbors tolerate the noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other one was a little bit more screechy,'' Castle said.
``This one's not as bad, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1353EST &QL; 
