A3931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FLEDGLING-FILMMAKERS-     01-12 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEDGLING-FILMMAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONFERENCE PROVIDES EXPOSURE FOR INDEPENDENT FILMMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fledgling filmmakers in search of a producer and
production companies on the lookout for filmmakers will have the
opportunity to hobnob Thursday through Sunday at the International
Film Financing Conference in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   IFFCON, now in its seventh year, is a key networking and funding
event. It includes workshops, panels, film screenings and scheduled
meetings between 60 selected independent filmmakers from North
America, Asia and Europe who have unfinished films in development,
and executives at film and television production houses such as
Home Box Office/Cinemax, Miramax Films, Four Films (United Kingdom)
and the Arte network (France), who can offer completion money for
projects.
</P>
<P>
   IFFCON alumni are not household names, but many are respected in
art-film circles and public broadcasting. They include Lynn
Hershman (``Conceiving Ada''), Lynn O'Donnell and Terry Zwigoff
(the documentary ``Crumb'') and Mitchell B. Robbins (``Next Stop
Wonderland'').
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers at IFFCON are selected by advisory committees of
fellow filmmakers and producers in a competitive application
process.
</P>
<P>
   Such wheeling and dealing outside Hollywood circles is the way
many serious feature films and documentaries are made, said Corey
Tong, the IFFCON director of special projects. Indeed, many are
co-productions with artists and executives from three or four
countries.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: ``Oaxaca Diary,'' a fictional film about a
group of filmmakers in Mexico, is being shot on location in the
Mexican state of Oaxaca. The director is Beijing-born Ning Ying.
The Peruvian screenwriter, Lorenzo O'Brien, studied at the
University of California at Los Angeles. Two of the actors are from
Japan. The finished movie, a $2 million feature, will be in English
and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Such internationalism and eclecticism are integral to IFFCON,
said Tong, who asserts that a movie with true international flavor
``can be very successful in the global marketplace, theatrically as
well as on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Renfrew, producer of ``Groove,'' a film about the San
Francisco underground rave party scene, said IFFCON's scope is part
of what appeals to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to funding, I'm looking for access to the
international market,'' said Renfrew, who applied to IFFCON for
``Groove'' in 1999 and was selected this time on her second try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've done before was done completely in the United
States,'' said Renfrew, who produced and directed ``Dear Dr.
Spencer,'' a documentary about an American physician ``who
performed safe abortions from the 1920s through the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently the chief financial officer for documentary film
company Concentric Media, Renfrew said about $200,000 of the
$500,000 budget for ``Groove'' has been raised so far.
</P>
<P>
   IFFCON itself operates on a budget of $250,000, according to
Wendy Braitman, the executive director of the conference and a film
producer who aims to help independents focus on the business side
of art.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest source of money for IFFCON, a nonprofit venture, is
the City of San Francisco, which pitched in $65,000 this year.
IFFCON has support from the National Endowment for the Arts and
corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded this year are global partners, such as Telefilm Canada
and the Ontario Film Development Corp., which underwrite Canadian
filmmakers who trek to IFFCON; Cinemart, an annual film marketing
session in Rotterdam, the Netherlands, which reserves slots for a
selected IFFCON filmmaker; and the New Zealand Film Commission,
which underwrites filmmakers from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealand partnership, especially, ``signals a sign of
expansion into non-North American territories,'' said Tong, who
added that filmmakers from Japan and China also will be attending
for the first time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1353EST &QL; 
