<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-KOREANS-GAYS-HNS &LR;      01-12 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREANS-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KOREAN-AMERICANS, CONSERVATIVE CHRISTIANS BACK ANTI-GAY
INITIATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIE CHAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In what is believed to be the first large-scale
political mobilization by Korean-American clergy, Korean churches
in California have launched an all-out effort to collect signatures
for an anti-gay initiative that is unlikely to appear on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance the churches have forged with the conservative
Christian Coalition is deeply troubling to the Korean-Americans who
have formed a new organization to counter what they believe is
misinformation the churches are spreading.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed initiative, titled the California Defense of Sexual
Responsibility Act, was written by an Orange County engineer and
has received virtually no major organizational or financial
support.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Korean-American pastors have seized the issue. They
have distributed petitions in church, enlisted volunteers to gather
signatures on the street and have taken up collections.
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuality ``is absolutely a violation to the conscience and
to biblical teaching and principle,'' said the Rev. Peter Kim, who
lives in Los Angeles. ``We firmly believe, what we are doing as
pastors, we are delivering this society from destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The ballot measure is simple but sweeping. It would prohibit
``public entities from endorsing, educating, recognizing or
promoting homosexuality as acceptable, moral behavior, and
prohibits public entities from using the phrase `sexual
orientation.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's laughable but it is outrageous,'' said Chris Hwang, staff
attorney at the National Center for Lesbian Rights in San Francisco
and a supporter of the newly formed Korean Americans for Civil
Rights, organized to support rights for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Also among those opposing the initiative is State Sen. Pete
Knight, R-Palmdale, the author a gay marriage proposition that will
appear on the March 7 ballot. Knight's Proposition 22 would define
marriage as between a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind the Defense of Sexual Responsibility Act, Lee
Olson of Huntington Beach, has done no fund-raising or organizing
beyond a World Wide Web page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not forcing it. I'm letting it happen on its own,'' Olson
said. ``People are either going to respond to the move of God or
they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   His goal is to repeal three bills signed into law by Gov. Gray
Davis that were considered major advances in rights for
homosexuals. They strengthen anti-discrimination laws in public
schools, housing and employment, and allow unmarried partners of
state employees to qualify for health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Since learning of Olson's initiative late last year, Korean
pastors of all denominations, with assistance from the Christian
Coalition, have been working throughout the state to get 700,000
signatures by Jan. 18, Kim said. He would not say how many he has;
419,260 valid signatures are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Full-page advertisements announcing the petition drive, with 267
names signed, ran in Korean-language newspapers last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of names in itself is unheard of, coming out in
these numbers for a single issue,'' said Roy Hong, executive
director of Korean Immigrant Workers Advocates in Los Angeles and a
founder of Korean Americans for Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Also vying for the November ballot is an initiative to legalize
gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census counted 260,000 Korean-Americans in California,
the vast majority in Southern California. Hong estimated there are
at least twice that number now. Less than half are eligible to
vote, Hong said, and voter registration and turnout have
historically been very low.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of Korean-Americans are either Christian or
Buddhist, Hong said. Southern California is home to roughly 600
Korean Protestant churches of all sizes. He said they have stayed
away from political and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition does not believe the anti-gay initiative
will succeed but sees the ties with Korean-American churches as the
beginning of a new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they're not going to get enough signatures for
this,'' said Miriam Archer, director of the Christian Coalition of
California. ``These are wonderful people who are not very savvy
politically, and they know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this effort, Archer said the Korean-Americans would
probably form their own chapter of the Christian Coalition and get
more politically involved. She said she was only aware of one other
minority chapter in the state, a Chinese-American group in Southern
California that is now inactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to turn out to be a very good thing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of an alliance with the Christian Coalition
troubles Hwang.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried this kind of mobilization is going to bring
people to the polls and say it's OK to be homophobic and vote for
the Knight initiative,'' Hwang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
