<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GRANDPARENTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court hears
arguments over the right of parents to raise their children as they
see fit vs. the right of grandparents to see those children. The
justices, six of whom are grandparents themselves, appear to lean
toward the parents' side. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   IMPLANTS (Washington) _ A National Institutes of Health panel of
medical experts urges the government to create a national registry
of devices implanted in people. The implants would be removed after
the individuals die if they consent in advance. A registry would
give researchers better understanding of how implants operate
inside the body, the panel says. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ While recent attention has
focused on great and near-great American presidents, it's fair to
say that more than half have been poor. Surprisingly, Richard Nixon
and Bill Clinton would be pretty well rated if it weren't for the
horrendous scandals that marred their tenure. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON.
</P>
