<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-MERGER-IMPACTS-YOU-87     01-12 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-IMPACTS-YOU-875&AMP;add-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MERGER THAT WILL PROFOUNDLY CHANGE ALL OUR LIVES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from Jan. 11)   (This timely ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 875 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,100.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The biggest deal the world has seen was born not in
New York or anywhere else in America.
</P>
<P>
   It was planted as the seed of an idea in the remote provinces of
southern China, and in Peking and Shanghai where Steve Case and
Gerald Levin spent a week together last October on a Time
magazine-sponsored news tour of China.
</P>
<P>
   Case, head of America Online (AOL), and Levin, chairman of Time
and the putative CEO of the new company, became friendly about a
year ago when they met at a conference. They kept in touch, purely
on a personal basis, after that.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until shortly after their China sojourn that Case
picked up a telephone in AOL headquarters in Dulles, Va., on the
outskirts of Washington, and speed-dialed Levin. (No, he did not
apparently, use his e-mail.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an idea,'' he said, ``let's put our two companies
together.'' Clearly, Levin did not take much persuading. The call
was placed barely two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said Monday that in considering AOL's advances, he knew
that if he didn't enter into such a marriage by the end of 2000 one
of the other media giants would have done so. And he didn't want to
be second.
</P>
<P>
   Both in terms of numbers and brand names, the merger is
dazzling. Time Warner brings the largest number of household brands
to the marriage: Time magazine, CNN, Warner Brothers, People, HBO,
Sports Illustrated, Warner Music Group, Fortune, Entertainment
Weekly, Looney Tunes and Cartoon Network, which features, among
others The Flintstones.
</P>
<P>
   AOL with its cyber assistant Connie is a brand in its own right,
of course. Among its other assets, however, you have Compuserve,
Netscape, Digital City and AOL Moviephone.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer reach that the new company will have can also be seen
in the subscriber numbers. Add them up and you have a mighty chunk
of our world.
</P>
<P>
   AOL has 20 million members, Time magazines have 30 million
subscribers and CNN is available to one billion television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Cable, the cable television network that AOL will be
able to tap into to distribute its product at super high speed, has
13 million subscribers. (Only AT&AMP;T's network in the U.S. is
bigger.)
</P>
<P>
   Transcending the deal itself, meanwhile, is the message it
delivers about our new Internet age and about the myriad new
companies crowding for a piece of it. It means we can believe in
it.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner is venerable, it is mighty and it is safe, but
Monday it sent an unmistakable message: the Internet is the future.
</P>
<P>
   A truth that has been creeping up on all of the media industry
for so many months has now been spelled out in blaring neon. The
future is called the broadband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something profound is taking place,'' Levin told a crammed New
York press conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He said something else terribly important too. The crazy,
insane, untenable valuations that have been put on Internet
companies in recent months _ on the Amazons and other dot-com
pioneers that are roaring up the information highway, and the stock
indices, with little early prospect of making any actual money _
are not crazy or insane at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the present valuations,'' he said. ``Their future
cash flow is so significant, that is how you justify it.'' And the
amounts of cash washing around the merger are mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner Monday described putting his name to the mega-merger
last Sunday night as not unlike his first experience of having sex
some four decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Putting ink to the proposed combination was, it would appear,
almost a religious experience for the old maverick from Atlanta.
You can understand that.
</P>
<P>
   With the 100 million shares that he owns in Time Warner,
acquired through the sale of his own beloved CNN to Time three
years ago, Turner was making himself roughly $2.5 billion richer.
</P>
<P>
   Probably, however, there was still more behind his excitement.
When the rest of the world learned about what was happening in the
boardroom that night, it would stand back in awe and amazement.
</P>
<P>
   Mega-mergers, where the figures are in billions not millions,
are commonplace. But this deal was clearly different and not just
because it was the biggest in corporate history.
</P>
<P>
   No single event could better capture what is happening to the
media industry as one millennium turns into the next.
</P>
<P>
   With one of the world's leading information and entertainment
companies linking up with the largest audience in cyberspace, it is
bound to influence the nature of what we see and hear.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will speed the rush among media providers to offer
tailored news and football results straight to customers' mobile
phones. Before long, trips to the video shop will be obsolete, as
films become available on demand through cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the ultimate symbol of the old media opening the
door to the new universe of digital and broadband communications _
a universe that both fascinates and frightens it _ and deciding to
abandon caution and leap through. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 875, OR CONTINUE TO 1,100 WORDS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Time Warner, a company with decades of history, is flinging
itself into the arms of AOL, a business just 15 years old and
barely known a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining event for Time Warner and America Online as
well as a pivotal moment in the unfolding of the Internet age,''
said Time Warner president Richard Parsons.
</P>
<P>
   Historians will also note the special timing. It was on Jan. 10,
1990 _ exactly 10 years ago _ that Time Warner was created out of
the fusion between the Time Inc. and Warner Communications, two
companies that had been founded in 1922. Time was the creation of
Henry Luce, whose name was repeatedly invoked in Monday's merger
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Most remarkable, however, may be the fact that this deal, or one
like it _ say between Disney and Yahoo! _ has not happened before.
Case said Monday with admirable restraint: ``This is the first time
a major Internet company has merged with a major media company and
the possibilities are endless.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the really observant among us would have seen this
merger coming a few short months ago when Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan
starred in a cute little romantic film called ``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Any AOL users will know where that phrase is from and will
recognize the on-screen icons that are featured in the film. They
are the signatures of that company. And who made the film? Warner
Brothers, of course. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 875-word (trimmed) article from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1432EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
