<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3969 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CHEVRON-EXPLORE-HNS &LR;      01-12 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-EXPLORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHEVRON CUTS SPENDING BECAUSE OF '99 DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GEORGE RAINE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chevron Corp. plans to spend $5.2 billion in
2000, of which $3.6 billion will be for worldwide exploration and
production and $1.3 billion for projects in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The spending plan is about 16.5 percent less than estimated 1999
spending because of major acquisitions in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One was the purchase of Rutherford Moran Oil Corp. as well as
taking over the operation of a gas and oil area in the Gulf of
Thailand. Chevron also acquired Petrolera Argentina San Jorge, an
exploration and producing company that accounts for 8 percent of
the oil production in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron said it is not disclosing the price it paid for San
Jorge. ``It's a business decision not to disclose the figure,''
said Fred Gorell, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Precise numbers for 1999 will not be known until the fourth
quarter and full-year reports are completed in a few weeks, said
Gorell.
</P>
<P>
   The spending plan was announced by Dave O'Reilly, a chemical
engineer who became Chevron's chairman and CEO Jan. 1, succeeding
Kenneth T. Derr, who retired.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, along with about 50 other Chevron employees, staffed
an office in San Ramon, Calif., over the New Year's Day weekend to
monitor Y2K roll-over in the 90 nations in which the company has
business interests. There were no disruptions as the new millennium
began seamlessly, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our spending program reflects continued confidence in our
company's prospects for growth,'' said O'Reilly, who joined Chevron
in 1968 and was elected vice chairman in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first operations O'Reilly is overseeing is the
transfer of all but 200 of 1,350 employees from the company's San
Francisco office space to the East Bay, mostly to offices in San
Ramon. The transfer will take place throughout the year, although
most of the people will move during the first quarter, said Gorell.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, the spending will be on projects in Kazakhstan,
Africa, Thailand and Canada. The U.S. projects include deep-water
oil fields called Gemini and Genesis in the Gulf of Mexico and
another underwater project off the coast of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it also plans to drill six deep-water
exploratory wildcat wells in 2000 and to increase its participation
in the U.S. power sector through increased investment in Dynegy
Inc. of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron expects to spend about $420 million for transportation,
most of it in Russia where the Caspian Pipeline Consortium is
laying pipe to connect the Tengiz Field to the Russian Black Sea
port of Novorossiysk. That is expected to be completed in mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately $830 million will be spent on worldwide refining
and marketing, of which $530 million will be spent in the U.S.,
said Chevron. Most of the remainder will be invested by Chevron's
50 percent-owned affiliate, Caltex Petroleum Corp., which operates
in about 60 countries in Asia, Africa and the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1432EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
