<HEADLINE>
CLICKING ON TO A BRAVE NEW CONSUMER WORLD  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary...RESENDING from Jan. 11)   (This pithy 500-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By HAMISH MCRAE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Monday was the day the Internet grew up.
</P>
<P>
   We knew this strange, amorphous communications network, tied
together by a few amateurs from personal computers, telephone wires
and a lot of clever software, would become the dominant technology
of the first quarter of this century.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Net was still dominated by the stand-alone
companies that helped to popularize it, it would remain outside the
corporate mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Internet companies are worth an enormous amount on the
stock exchanges. Sure, they are growing amazingly fast. But while
they have immense promise, they don't employ many people and have
not, in the main, been making any money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all is different. The merger between the world's biggest
Internet service provider and the world's largest media group means
the might of American capitalism will be devoted to pushing the new
technology into every aspect of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   There will now be a string of mergers, including British and
European ones, as other media groups try to gain electronic access
to our homes.
</P>
<P>
   Any firm with a message or a brand name in media will be
clamoring for our attention, trying to create services we will want
to buy.
</P>
<P>
   How they reach us _ whether through the PCs as at present, or by
interactive television, or by mobile phones, or even by video games
consoles _ is still for grabs. But over the next 10 years the
technology will race ahead and the variety of entertainment and
information services on offer will explode.
</P>
<P>
   The limit will not be technology; it will be our taste and our
time.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reasonable presumption that the American dominance of
the Internet will continue _ though the key invention, the World
Wide Web, was made by a Briton working in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   But while it would be right to expect the tidal wave of American
popular culture to flow even more strongly, the Net is ultimately a
democratic technology. It will do what we want of it.
</P>
<P>
   If we want to use it to watch Hollywood movies, we will download
them in seconds. If we want to revitalize local government, it will
create local discussion forums. If we want to buy shares, a few
clicks of the mouse will do that. And if we want to use the great
global library to educate ourselves better, then that too is
available for all.
</P>
<P>
   Not all giant mergers succeed. Companies _ and mergers _ succeed
only if they can create goods and services we want to buy.
</P>
<P>
   We, the consumers, are about to be offered an explosion of
choice: choice of entertainment, of education, of information. A
few years ago we had only four television channels. In 10 more
years there will be hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   This world will be as different as our supermarkets are now from
the family grocers of the Fifties. But it will be our choice: we,
as consumers, will win. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this pithy 500-word commentary from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
