<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-FOOD-GREENS-HNS &LR;      01-12 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-GREENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COOKING GREENS DON'T HAVE TO GIVE YOU THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greens give people the blues.
</P>
<P>
   Leafy green vegetables are known for being hard to clean, stinky
to cook and bitter to taste. Not exactly a ringing endorsement for
foods that are full of fiber and virtually fat-free. But in recent
years, chefs have developed recipes for greens that make cooking
the leaves faster and eating them, well easier.
</P>
<P>
   The first rule to handling greens, advises James Peterson in his
cookbook ``Vegetables,'' is cut first, wash later.
</P>
<P>
   Minute particles of dirt and sand can become trapped in the
veins of the leaves and between the stalks. So the more the head of
greens is separated, the easier it is to wash clean.
</P>
<P>
   To trim collards, kale and Swiss chard, which have tough,
unappetizing stems, separate the leaves and stack them on top of
each other, lining them up where the bottom of the leaf meets the
stem. With a chef's knife, chop off the stems and discard. Then,
using the tip of the chef's knife, or a paring knife, cut along
each side of the stem into the leaf to remove the remaining stem.
Hold the leftover leaf parts in a bunch and chop into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   When trimming bok choy, savoy cabbage, chicory, escarole or
other greens with more tender stems, simply cut off the tough
bottoms of the stems, then chop the leaves into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Once the greens are cut, fill a clean sink with cold water and
add the greens. Swish the greens around for a few minutes and then
let them rest for 10 to 15 minutes so any dirt or grit can settle
to the bottom of the sink. Using your hands, gently lift the washed
greens out of the sink, letting the water escape through your
fingers. Try not to disturb the water too much; you don't want to
stir up the grit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the leaves are very sandy or mud-caked, as they can be
in rainy seasons, this trick works well to get greens squeaky clean
in just one washing,'' says Victoria Wise in the ``Smith &AMP; Hawken
Gardeners' Community Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Once there was only one way to cook greens such as kale and
collards: simmer them for hours, even days, in a pot of water with
a slab of fatback or a ham hock, until even the stems were tender,
then they were served up with a bottle of chili-laced vinegar on
the side.
</P>
<P>
   These days, chefs say, you can cook a good pot of greens in as
little as 3 minutes. It all depends on which green you choose.
</P>
<P>
   Soft greens, like savoy cabbage, bok choy and spinach, cook the
quickest while collards, kale, chicory and escarole may take 10 to
15 minutes to become tender enough to eat. The only way to know
when the greens are done is to keep a careful watch on the pot.
When buying greens, keep in mind that smaller, younger leaves cook
faster.
</P>
<P>
   All greens don't have to be boiled. Softer ones, such as bok
choy, spinach, savoy cabbage (which also happen to be less bitter
than the tougher-leaf greens) can be sauteed in oil and seasoned
with accompaniments such as feta cheese, bacon, olives and
sun-dried tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes here include a couple of cooking methods and these
are just the start. Whenever you're in the store, buy what looks
freshest. You can substitute collards for kale, chicory for
escarole and bok choy for spinach.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   EGG ROLLS WITH SWEET-AND-SOUR DIPPING SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 5)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Sweet-and-Sour Dipping Sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound bok choy or other Asian green, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 spring onions, trimmed and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   10 egg roll wrappers
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for deep frying
</P>
<P>
   Prepare dipping sauce and set aside. (A store-bought sauce can
be used as well).
</P>
<P>
   Place the bok choy, spring onions, garlic, cilantro and ginger
in a bowl and toss to mix. Add soy sauce and toss again. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   To form the egg rolls, place a wrapper on the counter. Spread 2
tablespoons of the green mixture in the center. Roll up the
wrapper, envelope style, and, if necessary, seal the final fold
with a little water to keep the envelope from springing open.
Continue with the remaining egg roll wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 3/4-inch oil into a heavy skillet and heat until smoking.
Place as many egg rolls in the frying pan as will fit without
crowding and fry, turning once, until lightly browned and crispy, 1
minute. Lift the rolls out of the oil and transfer to paper towels
to drain. Continue with another batch until all the rolls are
fried.
</P>
<P>
   Serve right away with dipping sauce.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The filling mixture may be made in advance, but the
vegetables will wilt and release liquid. Drain the filling before
making the rolls or they will burst when fried.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: ``Smith &AMP; Hawken Gardeners' Community Cookbook,'' by
Victoria Wise (Workman, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SWEET-AND-SOUR DIPPING SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 1 1/4 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup packed, dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Pinch ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in a heavy saucepan. Bring to a boil over
medium heat, stirring constantly to prevent scorching. Reduce heat
to low and simmer, partially covered, for 15 minutes, until the
consistency is slightly sticky and the spices no longer taste raw.
</P>
<P>
   Remove and cool. Store, covered and refrigerated for up to 6
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   PASTA AND FRESH GREENS
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh greens, coarsely chopped, washed and drained
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound spaghetti, linguine or fettuccine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Place the greens, garlic and broth in a large pot. Bring to a
boil over high heat, then simmer until greens are tender, 3 to 10
minutes, depending on the greens. Remove from heat but do not
drain. Set aside in a warm place.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta until al dente. Drain briefly and transfer to a
large platter or bowl. Ladle the greens, along with a bit of their
cooking liquid over the pasta. Top with the cheese and serve.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: ``Smith &AMP; Hawken Gardeners' Community Cookbook,'' by
Victoria Wise (Workman, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SPICY COLLARDS
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 2)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds collard greens, cut and cleaned
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated gingerroot
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cardamom
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Drop collards into a large pot of boiling, salted water. Boil
until tender; timing varies, but 15 minutes is average. Test often.
Drain leaves well, then chop fine.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon butter in pan; stir in shallots and cook on
moderately low heat 3 minutes, or until soft. Add gingerroot,
cardamom, cinnamon, nutmeg and salt. Toss for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Add collards and stir 3 minutes to season and warm thoroughly.
Off heat, stir in remaining butter, cut in small pieces. Season to
taste. Serve warm or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: ``Uncommon Fruits and Vegetables: A Commonsense
Guide,'' by Elizabeth Schneider (1986 Harper &AMP; Row)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
