<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Jan. 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-POLICE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules, 5-4, that
police can stop and question someone who runs at the sight of a
police officer. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-LICENSE-DATA (Washington) _ Congress can protect
motorists' privacy by barring states from selling the personal
information on driver's licenses, the Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday. The law does not violate states' rights, the justices
said in a unanimous decision that ran counter to their recent trend
of reining in Congress' power over the states. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-U.S. (Burlington, Vt.) _ The Canadian woman suspected of
ferrying Algerians across the border illegally is back in court. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-INCINERATOR (East Liverpool, Ohio) _ Opponents of a
hazardous-waste incinerator that Al Gore first opposed as a vice
presidential candidate in 1992 are on his case again as the Ohio
primary approaches in March. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Monitoring the Elian Gonzalez situation. By
Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-PAY (Undated) _ A new study by Education Week documents
the yawning gap between the salaries of teachers and other
professionals, particularly those with advanced degrees. By Jacques
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-THREAT (Denver) _ A Colorado lawyer uses an usual
defense _ Internet addiction _ in the case of a Columbine kid who
sent a threatening note to a teacher after the Columbine shooting.
By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NH-VOICES (Dateline to kum, N.H.) _ In more than 50 interviews,
voters were hard pressed to come up with a nagging issue upon which
they would select their candidate. Instead, in a contrast to four
or eight years ago, when voters here were bursting with worries
about the economy, this year they seem relatively content. That
leaves them the luxury of tuning their political antenna on the
personal attributes of the candidates, their spouses, their parents
and, in case of Gore, their bosses. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Istanbul) _ Turkish leaders on Wednesday decided
to postpone the execution of the condemned Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan, meaning that he will probably remain alive for at
least a year. Their decision may accelerate Turkey's move toward
membership in the European Union. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-CHILE (Santiago) _ Reaction to Britain's Pinochet
announcement before Sunday's presidential runoff: Socialist and
conservative candidates speak of it carefully as analysts discuss
how it could affect very tight race. By Clifford Krauss
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-SPAIN (Madrid) _ Reaction to the Pinochet decision from
the Spanish judge seeking his extradition. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-NUKE (United Nations) _ Iraq said Wednesday that it would
allow a team of inspectors from the International Atomic Energy
Agency to visit the country next week to check its uranium
stockpiles, ending a month-long standoff between the agency and the
government of President Saddam Hussein. Other Iraq-U.N.
developments. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Russian official presents a video to
``prove'' Chechen rebels were behind the bombings in Russian cities
that killed 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SCHOLAR (Beijing) _ Major China scholars send protest
letter to China's president, Jiang Zemin, over the arrest of an
American-based Chinese scholar collecting historical documents.
They say the arrest threatens research and future exchanges. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (Beijing) _ China denounces a U.S. plan for an
anti-China resolution at U.N. Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-TRIAL (New Delhi, India) _ More chaos in trial of the
ousted President Sharif: an outraged judge quit the case because of
the large number of intelligence agents and army people in the
courtroom. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-FOOD (Paris) _ The European Union is creating its own
version of the U.S. FDA to try to improve food safety. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-WIRELESS (Undated) _ America Online, the company that made
the Internet invisible and less frightening, has been at the
forefront of developing so-called post-PC Internet appliances.
Indeed, while much of the talk about the Time Warner deal has been
about broadband, the next big thing is expected to be wireless, and
AOL is determined to be at the forefront. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-ASIA (Hong Kong) _ It is not clear that a combined AOL-Time
Warner will be able to make inroads into the potentially huge
market of Asia. Unlike in Europe, where AOL has built a valuable
regional franchise through its partnership with Bertelsmann, the
Internet in Asia remains a fractured business with few large
players and virtually none that cross national boundaries. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-INVESTORS (Undated) _ Shares of America Online and Time
Warner extend their slide.
</P>
<P>
   LUXURY-CARS (Detroit) _ After capturing a big share of the
American market for small and mid-sized cars, Japanese auto makers
set their sights a decade ago on the luxury market long dominated
by Cadillac and Lincoln. Indeed, both Cadillac and Lincoln were
dethroned in 1999 for the first time since the 1930s. Yet the
upstart was not Japanese, but European: Mercedes-Benz. There is
rare unanimity here about how the Europeans surged into first
place. They have the strongest brands, at a time when a rising
stock market and strong economy have meant that money is no object
for many buyers. The European ascendance in luxury cars has come at
a particularly disappointing time for American and Japanese
executives in the market segment. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were mixed in mid-afternoon trading.
The Dow Jones industrial average was up 43 points, the S&AMP;P 500 was
down 4 points and the Nasdaq composite index was down 36 points. By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FUND-MANAGERS (Undated) _ George Vanderheiden, manager of a
number of large stock mutual funds, plans to retire. Fidelity also
names 11 new stock fund managers. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-APPOINT (Undated) _ Merrill Lynch says David Bowers, its
chief European equity strategist, will become its chief investment
strategist, replacing Charles Clough. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BANKS (Singapore) _ The Indonesia government dismisses
Glenn Yusuf, the head of the agency responsible for cleaning up the
country's insolvent banking system. The announcement ends months of
speculation about the fate of Yusuf, a favorite of Western
financiers and one of the few holdover officials from the
administration of former President B.J. Habibie. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DAEWOO (Seoul) _ Looking at what is happening on the sale
of Daewoo Motor. Hyundai Motor says it may make a joint bid with an
unidentified foreign partner, while General Motors says it is
reconsidering its earlier bid.
</P>
