<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CUBABOY-US _ WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on
Wednesday upheld immigration officials' decision that 6-year-old
Elian Gonzalez must be returned to his father in Cuba. Reno said
any challenge to the decision must come in federal, not state
courts. The government is not expected to enforce its Friday
deadline for returning the boy. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CUBABOY-MIAMI _ MIAMI _ Reaction to the Justice Department's
statement that 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez must be returned to his
father in Cuba. (Williams, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Justice Department prosecutors appear
ready to propose that Microsoft Corp. be broken up in a negotiated
setllement to the federal government's antitrust suit. Microsoft is
expected to resist the plan, reported Wednesday in USA Today just
as the legal and business worlds were weighing the effect of the
AOL-Time Warner merger on the software giant. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-QUALITY _ WASHINGTON _ How your state stacks up in the
influential Quality Counts annual report, which says most states
don't make sure that all their teachers have the knowledge or
skills to instruct students or to see that they're paid as much as
similarly educated professionals in other fields. The report is to
be released here and on the Web at 10 a.m. Wednesday by Education
Week. This year's report emphasizes teacher quality, but includes
some 75 other indicators of the health of each state's education
system. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GRANDPARENTS _ WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Supreme Court hears
oral arguments in Troxel v. Granville, on whether a state statute
that grants grandparents a right to petition for visitation rights
interferes with a parent's basic interest in the ``care, custody
and companionship of a child.'' (Turay, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-MLK _ ATLANTA _ Months ago, the Catholic Archdiocese of
Atlanta invited Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., to deliver a speech
commemorating Martin Luther King Jr. The speech was to be delivered
this Saturday before an audience of thousands. Two weeks ago, Lewis
got a call from the archdiocese folks withdrawing the invitation.
Their reason? He is pro-choice Lewis, who makes a point out of
urging people to ``vote their conscience,'' is miffed. He had no
plans to discuss the A-word and he has turned down 10-15 offers to
speak on that day to other groups. (Carr/White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ Census numbers released today show that Hispanics will
surpass African-Americans as the nation's largest minority group in
four years. Other numbers: 1 in 3 Americans will be Hispanic in 100
years and 1 in 10 will be Asian immigrants. (Bixler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEXSKOL-FUNDS _ AUSTIN _ A State Board of Education Committee on
Wednesday will recommend which company should be hired to oversee
private managers of part of the Texas school trust fund. This comes
after the main firm bowed out, citing nasty board politics. That
firm, Richards and Tierney, are back in the running. We bring
readers up to date on the controversy, including legislative
committees gathering to recommend changes in the board and the
trust fund management when the Legislature convenes next year.
(Brooks, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Texas editors.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-BIBLE _ Bible classes taught in Florida's public schools
violate federal law, according to the People for the American Way.
On Thursday in Tallahassee, the advocacy group will release a
report on how the 15 school districts throughout the Sunshine State
teach the Bible to public school students. The main complaint is
that the classes draw on a Christian perspective instead of
non-sectarian instruction. The report takes particular aim at the
National Council on Bible Curriculum in Greensboro, N.C., the same
group that's trying to start a bible curriculum in Georgia.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH GRAPHIC showing
counties in Florida that teach Bible classes.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINMARY-SUIT _ Nancy Fowler, the Conyers woman who claims to
get visions from the Virgin Mary, has largely settled a lawsuit
against a group of pilgrims who helped her to stage the events. At
issue was whether the former pilgrims could use words and images
from the massive gatherings for books and other publications. The
group, Our Loving Mothers Children, decided it no longer wanted to
use the information from the gatherings. (Farber, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST _ LONDON _ Testimony continues in the libel trial over
a book that claimed a historian distorted aspects of the Holocaust.
David Irving is suing Emory University professor Deborah Lipstadt
and Penguin Books over the 1994 book ``Denying the Holocaust: The
Growing Assault on Truth and Memory,'' which claims he has denied
that the Nazis used gas chambers to exterminate the Jews, holds
extremist views and distorts history. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   UN-Q&AMP;A _ UNITED NATIONS _ Louise Frechette, deputy secretary
general of the United Nations, discusses the agency's reform effort
and the impact of donations by Ted Turner. A Q&AMP;A. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
