<HEADER>
A3996 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-FRIDAY-HN     01-12 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-FRIDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `NEXT FRIDAY' DESERVES A GOOD FLUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calling all fans of excrement: Your time has come.
</P>
<P>
   Fond of flatulence? Got a soft spot for stinky-toilet jokes?
Laugh uncontrollably when someone falls back-first into a massive
pile of Chihuahua poo, then stumbles through the rest of the movie
with an aromatic smear on the back of his overalls?
</P>
<P>
   If so _ if BMs are your be-all and end-all _ then run, don't
walk, to the nearest neighborhood screening of ``Next Friday,''
where you can soak in scatology to your heart's (or whatever's)
content. That the film tempers plop jokes with racist stereotypes
and near-constant ``Cheech &AMP; Chong''-esque marijuana consumption
will make it either more or less palatable to the individual
viewer. You decide.
</P>
<P>
   Helmed by video director Steve Carr, ``Next Friday'' is the
sequel to 1995's ``Friday,'' an exploitative, sort-of-funny film
about a pair of guys (Ice Cube and Chris Tucker) in South Central
L.A. who smoke $200 worth of dope and then scramble to pay the
dealer by Friday night. Ice Cube co-wrote that film, and he
co-wrote this one (both with the aptly named D.J. Pooh), and the
world would be a better place if he hadn't. Despite the man's
proven abilities as rapper and actor, when it comes to
screenwriting he ought to keep his anal fixations to himself.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, good egg Craig (Mr. Cube) is on the run from
escaped convict and hulking grudge-bearer Debo (Tommy ``Tiny''
Lister), last seen getting whupped by our hero in the first film.
Craig's Dad (John Witherspoon), a frequent voider, sends Craig to
live with his cousin Day-Day (Mike Epps) and Uncle Elroy (Don
``D.C.'' Curry), who hit it big in the lottery and now reside in a
sprawling suburban palazzo.
</P>
<P>
   Elroy is a leopard-printed Ladies Man who collects and displays
artificial phalluses in his bedroom. Day-Day, who does not, is
plagued by woman troubles that extend beyond his ex-girlfriend to
his ex-girlfriend's menacing sister; among the film's few comic
strokes is the fact that Day-Day holds court injunctions against
them both. On the Friday in question, Day-Day goes off to work at
Pinky's record shop while Craig, Elroy and Elroy's nymphomaniacal
squeeze, Sugar, smoke a blunt the size of a pickle.
</P>
<P>
   Craig soon learns that Elroy is about to lose the house for
failure to pay taxes. Concerned, he moseys down to Day-Day's place
of employ and meets an affable skateboarder, Roach (Justin Pierce).
Guess what Roach likes to do in his spare time? Craig, Day-Day and
Roach smoke a joint the size of a green bean. They get stoned. They
get fired. Then they head to Day-Day's house, where they ponder the
comings and goings of neighboring thugs (embodiments of Hispanic
stereotypes) and speculate about a hidden stash of cash. How much
is it? Is it drug money? Could they use it to pay Elroy's back
taxes?
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, and so it goes, with numerous weak attempts at
humor and an even weaker attempt at romance. It seems the thugs'
babe-ola sister, Carla (Lisa Rodriguez), has a thing for Craig. Of
course! Of course they find true love! Of course Debo tracks down
Craig! Of course Craig's father never removes the dog crap from his
back!
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Friday'' does have a few things going for it, among them
a brisk pace (93 minutes) and a couple of truly funny bits:
subtitles pop up at unexpected moments, and a sight gag involving a
vacuum cleaner almost redeems the feces.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the film is little more than a lot of trash. One
minute it's dwelling on a used prophylactic; the next it's telling
us that ``Fat b----es need love, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And as empowering as it is to have African-Americans up high in
Hollywood _ writing movies, directing them, producing them,
starring in them _ a film that portray blacks as drugged-addicted,
sex-obsessed, tax-avoiding, lax-boweled, lazy thieves is just
another form of blaxploitation. It trots out vile racist cliches,
and it asks us to laugh at them. Don't.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
