<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Jan. 13:
</P>
<P>
   SMART-HOUSES (Undated) _ If the 1990s brought widespread
consumer acceptance of in-home theater, wireless communications,
home PC's and smart appliances, the new decade brings promise _ or
threat _ of ``convergence,'' the ultimate integration of audio,
video and data systems. Some 7.5 million American homes _ about 7
percent _ are currently equipped with a degree of computer
networking that links automated security, entertainment and
lighting. The most advanced homes _ fewer than 4 percent _ can
coordinate heating and air conditioning; security, lighting and
home entertainment; Internet and e-mail devices even from afar _ by
cable, computer and satellite, through telephone lines and modem
connections. Appliances like vacuum cleaners or even window shades
can be taught to monitor themselves according to internal codes. By
Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   ZIA-SUN-SIGN (Undated) _ In a strange coda to a decade obsessed
with branding, controversy has broken out over a surprising symbol:
the Zia sun sign. The symbol _ a circle with lines radiating in
four directions _ is one of the best-known images in New Mexico. It
is on the state flag and on license plates. The 850-person Zia
pueblo, about 35 miles northwest of Albuquerque has been using the
symbol since the year 1200, tribal officials say. And now the
pueblo has asked the state of New Mexico to pay it $74 million in
compensation for employing without permission what the tribe's
elders variously call ``a sacred symbol'' and ``the symbol of our
collective identity.'' By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-ESTIMATES (New York) _ When the Nathaniel Appleton
silver-mounted secretary sold a year ago for $8.3 million _ after
an estimate by Sotheby's of $500,000 to $800,000 _ newcomers to the
auction game may have been shell-shocked, but the pros were not.
What the newcomers may not have known is that estimates at the
city's largest auction houses are kept deliberately, artificially
low, as a matter of strategy to bring in bidders and, at the same
time, make themselves look good. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   APARTMENT-BRIDGE (New York) _ Seth Schulaner had a vision that
would forever change his client's life _ or at least her
one-bedroom apartment. ``I see a bridge,'' Schulaner, a designer,
said. He meant it. Literally. For an apartment in Chelsea, he
imagined a bridge or catwalk that would slice across the
double-height living room, connecting the upper-level sleeping area
with a new adjacent home office. By Mitchel Owens.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
