<HEADER>
A3999 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA13-COX     01-12 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 0113: Old salt considers friends, job the spice
of life
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 0113
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters.
Photos and a sig/locator map are available.)
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The guests at William R. Carver's
birthday party wound their way around displays of caulking, varnish
and anchor lines into the back room of Hopkins Marine Hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Bill is as much a fixture there as the paint counter where he's
been stationed for the past 25 years. He's made a powerful
impression on a lot of people _ not the least, his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's amazing,'' says store manager Chris Janes. ``He knows
everything. He keeps track of everything in the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill earned his expertise by caring for five boats of his own
(he dearly misses that 35-footer he left behind in Ocean City,
N.J.) and by guiding countless others to safe harbor in 45 years
with the Coast Guard Auxiliary.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for everyone, Carver rarely misses a day's work. ``He
doesn't call in sick,'' Janes says. ``Even if he has a doctor's
appointment, he comes in right after.'' Such dedication may sound
more admirable than remarkable, except for this: This birthday is
his 95th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to stay active,'' he says. ``I keep moving. If you sit
too much, time passes too slowly. I like to work.''
</P>
<P>
   So work he does, every weekday from 9 a.m. to 2 p.m. He enjoys
the company of his co-worker and customers such as yacht captain
Mitch Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here two or three times a day, and I always look for
Bill,'' Armstrong says. ``He's been to my house. He knows my
children. We talk about boats and I enjoy listening to his
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Carver has a store of sea tales, and many more. He retired as
superintendent of a Gulf Oil plant in 1968 and moved to West Palm
Beach with his wife, Mary Elizabeth. They met at a barn dance in
1921.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in and saw her standing under a light in the very the
center of the floor,'' he says. ``I knew God was trying to tell me
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth died in 1981. They'd been married 57 years. ``I
still miss her,'' he says. She's the one who nudged Bill toward the
store that has become his second home. He'd taken a post-retirement
job as a bridge tender, but he wound up on the night shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't like being alone at night, so she asked me to look
for a day job,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So one night on the way to work at the Flagler Memorial Bridge,
he strolled up to the Sixth Street store and asked the manager for
a job. ``I told him about my boats and my experience and he hired
me,'' Bill says.
</P>
<P>
   Bill was 70 years old then. He's the only one from that era
still working in the store. He continues as a matter of love, not
money. ``You don't get rich working five hours a day,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He has no plans to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor says you use it or you lose it,'' Bill says. ``I'm
going to keep using it as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
