A4008 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     01-12 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWING YOUR RESOLUTIONS CALLS FOR PIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enough of this diet nonsense. A couple weeks into the new year,
and we're ready to throw in the fat counter. Here's a recipe from
Luby's to break the fast.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERNUT BROWNIE PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   4 extra-large egg whites, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   14 graham cracker squares, broken into 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Additional chopped pecans, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 300 degrees. Lightly grease 9-inch pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   In large mixing bowl, beat egg whites and baking powder until
soft peaks form. Add cream of tartar, beating constantly. Add 1 cup
sugar, a tablespoon at a time, beating constantly until stiff peaks
form. Using a rubber scraper, fold in graham crackers and pecan
pieces. Spoon into pie plate.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 30 minutes, or until wooden pick inserted in center comes
out clean. Cool completely on wire cooling rack.
</P>
<P>
   In chilled small bowl using chilled beaters, beat cream just
until it begins to thicken. Add remaining 1/4 cup sugar and vanilla
and continue beating until stiff peaks form. Don't overbeat. Top
pie with whipped cream. Sprinkle with pecans and refrigerate until
served.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 443 calories, 22 grams fat, 54
grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 233 milligrams cholesterol,
231 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Gail Perry writes, looking for a recipe for the queso dip served
years ago at Luminarias restaurant. This recipe first ran in the
food section when Joanne Vachule was editor during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   LUMINARIAS CHEESE DIP
</P>
<P>
   Yields 5 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 stick melted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup plus 1/8 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 chopped onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 green bell pepper, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno, diced
</P>
<P>
   4 cups milk, heated
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce jar Cheez Whiz
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion, bell pepper and jalapeno in butter for 5 minutes.
Add flour and stir with a whisk to make a roux. You will think
you've failed at this point because the mixture will clump up on
the whisk. Don't worry. Cook just until brown.
</P>
<P>
   Heat milk and add gradually to the roux mixture, stirring
constantly. Still whisking, add Cheez Whiz, Worcestershire sauce
and spices to flour/milk mixture. Cook until the mixture just
begins to boil, stirring with whisk constantly. Do not allow to
boil, or mixture will break down.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 34 calories, 2 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 4 milligrams cholesterol, 66
milligrams sodium, 65 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   LUMINARIAS HONEY MUSTARD DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons onion, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon MSG, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except oil. Stir until well-blended.
Continuing to stir, slowly add the oil in a thin stream.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 97 calories, 10 grams fat,
2 grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 3 milligrams cholesterol, 58
milligrams sodium, 93 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked for a hot water pie crust recipe that my mother
used to make. She got it out of an old Light Crust Flour cookbook.
My mother is deceased. I have tried Lee Bailey's recipe, and
recipes in every cookbook I can find. They are not as good. My
mother's recipe was very light and flaky and I could make up
several pie crusts at one time and put them in the freezer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Mann, Richland Hills, Texas
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been looking for years for a sweet potato dish that my
grandmother made. The potatoes were peeled and cut like french
fries. They were cooked in a baking dish and seemed to have butter
and sugar in them. They were not juicy and had a sugary crust on
top (white sugar). I have asked relatives to no avail. My
grandmother was from East Texas and attended Texas State School for
the Deaf in the 1890s and early 1900s. The rest of her life she
lived in Fort Worth. I have asked numerous folk about this recipe
and have looked in every Texas cookbook that I see. Please see if
any of your readers can help.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Margo Stites, Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
