<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-NEWSPAPER-SUIT-HNS &LR;      01-12 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUIT SEEKS TO BLOCK SALE OF SAN FRANCISCO DAILY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A former candidate for mayor is suing to stop
the Hearst Corporation, owner of the San Francisco Examiner, from
buying the morning San Francisco Chronicle and merging the city's
two daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court in The City,
Clint Reilly asked a judge to order Hearst and the Chronicle
Publishing Co. to abandon the reported $660 million transaction,
arguing that the deal would violate federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The sale was announced in August, and has been under Justice
Department review since then.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawsuit faces an uncertain future, and a labor leader
said that if the merger were blocked, hundreds of newspaper workers
might lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   By filing the lawsuit, Reilly upstaged Mayor Willie Brown, who
in his inaugural address earlier this month said he wanted to
preserve two dailies in San Francisco. City Attorney Louise Renne
and District Attorney Terence Hallinan also have said they were
considering a legal challenge to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's doing anything,'' said Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's
lawyer. ``I think the evidence is clear that private people are
required to enforce the antitrust laws because the officials won't
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is a veteran political consultant who finished fourth in
the mayor's race in November.
</P>
<P>
   It was his second lawsuit against Hearst. In 1993, Reilly
claimed that his ankle was broken in a conference-room altercation
with Phil Bronstein, executive editor of the Examiner. That case
was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly describes himself as a subscriber to both newspapers and
contends in the lawsuit that a merged San Francisco daily would
harm consumers by raising the price of subscriptions and
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Merging the papers would also deprive readers of differing
editorial and reportorial voices, the lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said Reilly hoped to prevent layoffs that he claimed were
inevitable if the merger occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always say that no one is going to be fired, but that
never happens,'' Alioto said. ``As soon as they do the deal, it's
`adios.'''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a court order blocking the deal, Reilly asks the
judge to order the newspapers to pay his legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both the Hearst Corporation and the Chronicle
declined to comment on the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ammiano, the president of the Board of Supervisors and
another unsuccessful candidate for mayor, said he welcomed Reilly's
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more the merrier,'' he said. ``I'm on the same page. I
would like a two-newspaper town.''
</P>
<P>
   But Doug Cuthbertson, executive officer of the Northern
California Media Workers Guild, which represents union writers and
editors, said he feared ``massive job losses'' unless Hearst was
allowed to purchase the Chronicle and merge the dailies.
</P>
<P>
   Cuthbertson said that Hearst had agreed to abide by existing
union contracts and had guaranteed jobs for the entire 2,700 work
force of the two newspapers. Any other buyer is almost certain to
lay off workers, Cuthbertson said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Reilly was a disappointed office seeker who
was ``causing trouble'' with the lawsuit because he didn't like
press coverage of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of look at Reilly's action here _ after a $4 million
campaign, in which he finished fourth _ and I would hope the court
would take a look at that and throw the whole thing out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a century, the Examiner and the Chronicle were
morning rivals. But in 1965, the newspapers entered into a joint
operating agreement (JOA) under which the Examiner switched to
afternoon publication. The newspapers maintain separate news staffs
and compete for stories, but the companies share printing and
business operations and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Such arrangements were later authorized by the Newspaper
Preservation Act of 1970, a federal law aimed at preserving
newspapers that would be forced to close without relief from the
expense of head-to-head economic competition.
</P>
<P>
   As the media business has changed, JOAs themselves have become
less profitable, and in the past 15 years the Justice Department
has allowed the agreements to be dissolved in a dozen cities. In
each case, the morning paper has survived while the afternoon paper
has ceased publication.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco JOA expires in 2005, but last year the owners
of Chronicle Publishing decided to sell all the company's assets.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department must approve the sale of the Chronicle to
Hearst. A decision is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has interests in publishing, broadcasting, syndication
and the Internet. It owns daily newspapers in Albany, N.Y.;
Edwardsville, Ill.; Bad Axe and Midland, Mich.; Seattle; and in the
Texas cities of Beaumont, Houston, Laredo, Midland, Plainview and
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing owns several television stations as well as
the Telegram &AMP; Gazette in Worcester, Mass., and the Bloomington
Pantagraph in Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
