<HEADER>
A4066 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-COCOAPOWER-2ndTake-TE     01-12 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCOAPOWER-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: taronga.com 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORANGE-SCENTED HOT CHOCOLATE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces bittersweet (not unsweetened) or semisweet chocolate,
chopped
</P>
<P>
   Three 2-by-1-inch slices orange peel (orange part only)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon instant espresso powder or instant coffee powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in heavy medium saucepan. Stir over low
heat until chocolate melts. Increase heat and bring to boil,
stirring often. Remove from heat; whisk until frothy. Return to
heat and bring to boil again. Remove from heat and whisk again.
Discard orange peel. (Can be prepared 2 hours ahead. Let stand at
room temperature. Before serving, bring just to boil. Remove from
heat and whisk until frothy.)
</P>
<P>
   Pour hot chocolate into mugs.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 339 calories, 25 grams fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 27 milligrams cholesterol,
98 milligrams sodium, 65 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.recipes.taronga.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The roots of hot chocolate
</P>
<P>
   We owe our neighbors to the south a huge debt when it comes to
chocolate. It was the pre-Columbian Mayans who were the first to
cultivate chocolate in plantations in the Yucatan in 600.
</P>
<P>
   The Aztecs ground cacao beans, mixed them with chile peppers,
vanilla, corn and annatto. The resulting paste was dried in discs
and rehydrated with cold water. Montezuma is said to have consumed
50 cups of chocolate a day.
</P>
<P>
   When Cortez returned to Spain with chocolate, the Mexican
version was considered far too bitter. It was the Spanish who added
sugar and other spices as well as occasional additions of nuts or
flower waters. It was also the Spanish who invented the molinillo,
a beater that frothed the warm chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   So taken were the Spanish with the exotic bounty of their
acquisition, they kept their discovery of chocolate a secret for
nearly a century.
</P>
<P>
   When the French, in their so-civilized way, designed the
chocolate pot, they devised a hole in the lid through which their
version of the chocolate beater could be inserted.
</P>
<P>
   Abuelita and Ibarra brands of chocolate are familiar sights at
Hispanic supermarkets. The individual discs, packaged in a yellow
and red box, are a combination of sugar, cocoa nibs, almonds,
cinnamon and lecithin. Consumed cold, this combination is not far
from the chocolate of the Aztecs, though they often added chiles
and/or honey to the mix. Mexican chocolate is grainy, so if you'd
like to achieve the same flavor with higher-quality chocolate,
simply add a pinch of cinnamon to processed cocoa.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Which ready-made mix makes a great stir?
</P>
<P>
   Land O' Lakes individual packets of dry milk, cocoa, sugar and
flavorings, such as raspberry, cinnamon and mocha, are designed to
be dissolved in hot water. About 69 cents each at most
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Hershey's Goodnight Kisses Hot Cocoa Mix is four packets of
cocoa that include miniature versions of the company's trademark
chocolate candies, which melt into the hot water or hot milk used
to make the drink. About $1.49 at most grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Godiva Dark Chocolate Truffle Cocoa is designed to pair with hot
milk _ no water for this aristocrat. Also available in milk
chocolate flavor. A package of four individual packets is $5 at
Godiva shops and Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Ghirardelli Double Chocolate is one of the company's five
varieties that combine chocolate, cocoa and sugar with flavoring.
Package directions recommend using milk, not water, with the mix.
$4.49 for a 20-serving tin at most supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Nestle Carnation Fat Free with Marshmallows is everything moms
and dads want. It's easy, it's quick and it includes the mandatory
floating bits of white spun sugar. Although it's not advertised as
such, this brand is also low in sugar. Eight packets are $2.59 at
most supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Nestle NesQuik _ new name but the same flavor we remember from
childhood. A plastic resealable canister (we like this) of 19
servings is $2.39.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Miss No Sugar Added is made with Splenda sweetener. Mixed
with hot water, each serving yields only 6 grams of sugar instead
of the 17 to 22 grams of most other brands. $2.29 at most
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
