<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4067 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-COCOAPOWER-1700(2Take     01-12 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCOAPOWER-1700(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT CHOCOLATE CAN STIR UP MEMORIES AND SWEETEN A BAD DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grown-ups and college English majors have coffee. The cosmic and
organic crowd has tea. But what about the rest of us? We're only
adults when the boss is watching, and we think ``cosmic'' was a TV
show by Carl Sagan.
</P>
<P>
   Our comfort lies in hot chocolate, the first warm drink that
most of us sample as children. Surely this most-comforting of
cold-weather drinks deserves its day in the sun. Topped with
bobbing miniature marshmallows, or crowned with a cloud of
marshmallow creme, hot cocoa gives the face a mustache and the
tummy a glow.
</P>
<P>
   It can be elegant, served in porcelain chocolate cups
accompanied by a crystal bowl of whipped cream, waving its excess
in peaks for all to see. Or it can be proletarian: Pour it into a
thick-walled institutional beaker, add some declasse marshmallows,
and curl up with the remote and Lifetime for Women.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PARISIAN HOT CHOCOLATE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 cups, Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened Dutch-processed cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces bittersweet or semisweet chocolate, very finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon superfine sugar
</P>
<P>
   In medium-size heavy-bottom saucepan, combine milk, cream and
cocoa powder. Warm over medium heat, stirring to dissolve cocoa.
Add chopped chocolate and stir until it melts completely. Bring
mixture to simmer, but don't boil. Return heat to medium and cook
for 5 minutes, stirring occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Remove saucepan from heat and stir in vanilla. Stir mixture to
cool briefly, then pour into serving cups.
</P>
<P>
   In bowl of a stand mixer, using wire whip attachment or in a
mixing bowl using a hand-held mixer, whip cream until frothy. Add
sugar and continue to whip until cream holds soft peaks. Place a
dollop of cream on top of each serving of hot chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 258 calories, 19 grams fat, 23
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 32 milligrams cholesterol, 47
milligrams sodium, 66 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``All About Chocolate'' by Carole Bloom (MacMillan, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   EASY HOT COCOA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chocolate syrup
</P>
<P>
   Dash of vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Mini marshmallows, optional
</P>
<P>
   Heat the milk in a microwave oven until very hot, about 1
minute. Stir in the syrup and the vanilla extract. If you like,
sprinkle with marshmallows before drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 261 calories, 12 grams fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 34 milligrams cholesterol,
152 milligrams sodium, 43 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Daily News
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BARELY LEGAL HOT CHOCOLATE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar or equivalent alternative sweetener
</P>
<P>
   Dash of cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup rice or almond milk
</P>
<P>
   Combine dry ingredients with fork until no lumps remain. Add 1
or 2 tablespoons rice or almond milk, and stir thoroughly to make a
paste. Add remainder of milk alternative and stir until smooth.
Warm over very low heat for 20 minutes, stirring periodically. (The
longer you heat it, the smoother it gets.) Top with boiling water
to make 1 cup and stir.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 127 calories, 4 grams fat, 22
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 25 milligrams
sodium, 31 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.vegweb.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CASTILIAN HOT CHOCOLATE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   7 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 quart (4 cups) milk
</P>
<P>
   Sift cocoa and sugar together into medium-size saucepan.
Dissolve cornstarch into the water and stir into cocoa and sugar
until it is a smooth paste. Begin heating mixture, stirring it with
a whisk. Gradually pour in the milk. Continue stirring with the
whisk as you bring liquid to a simmer. Allow chocolate to simmer
for about 10 minutes, stirring often, until it is thick, glossy and
completely smooth. Serve steaming hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 259 calories, 6 grams fat, 48
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 22 milligrams cholesterol, 83
milligrams sodium, 22 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.recipes.taronga.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
