<HEADLINE>
TEST YOUR LITERARY KNOWLEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A leading character's name often serves as the title for a
novel. Here are some well-known title characters (eight women,
eight men) to be matched with their authors. Some of these works,
both American and British, were published long ago; others appeared
much more recently. Score yourself one point for each correct
answer, and you may also gain an extra point (or two) by
identifying either the oldest or newest titles here (or both). You
pass with 10 points, but 12 points gives you an A. Answers are on
the opposite page.
</P>
<P>
   Literary works: Their authors:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Adam Bede'' a. Max Beerbohm
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Agnes Grey'' b. Anne Bronte
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Alice Adams'' c. James M. Cain
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Benito Cereno'' d. Winston Churchill
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Cress Delahanty'' e. Theodore Dreiser
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Daniel Martin'' f. George Eliot
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Guy Mannering'' g. Henry Fielding
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Henry Esmond'' h. John Fowles
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Jennie Gerhardt'' i. Jack London
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Lucy Crown'' j. Herman Melville
</P>
<P>
   11. ``Martin Eden'' k. Walter Scott
</P>
<P>
   12. ``Mary Poppins'' l. Irwin Shaw
</P>
<P>
   13. ``Mildred Pierce'' m. Booth Tarkington
</P>
<P>
   14. ``Richard Carvel'' n. W.M. Thackeray
</P>
<P>
   15. ``Tom Jones'' o. P.L. Travers
</P>
<P>
   16. ``Zuleika Dobson'' p. Jessamyn West
</P>
<P>
   Quiz answers: 1-f; 2-b; 3-m; 4-j; 5-p; 6-h; 7-k; 8-n; 9-e; 10-l;
11-i; 12-o; 13-c; 14-d; 15-g; 16-a. Fielding's ``Tom Jones'' (1749)
is the seniormost citizen among the novels; Fowles' ``Daniel
Martin'' (1977) is the newest.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
