<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4074 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ERGONOMIC-MOUSE-A     01-12 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ERGONOMIC-MOUSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS A LITTLE MOUSE HURTING YOU? EXPERTS SAY TRY A BIGGER ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Circuits) 
(af) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has sought to avoid mouse-inflicted wrist pain has
probably heard some version of the following: Move the mouse closer
to your body, avoid clutching the mouse when you`re not actually
using it, and in extreme circumstances avoid using the contraption
altogether. New research from Cornell University suggests another
option: Try a bigger mouse.
</P>
<P>
   A study conducted last summer by Alan Hedge, a Cornell professor
of ergonomics, compared how people responded in two-minute sessions
to a basic Microsoft mouse with the familiar raised bulge that fits
under the palm and a lesser-known variant called the Whale.
</P>
<P>
   The Whale mouse is a $99 device developed by a company called
Humanscale in New York and, befitting its name, is at least an inch
longer than the Microsoft mouse and can be extended up to another
inch for larger hands. The Whale is designed to keep fingers flat
and prevent the hand from curling around it.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge said he chose the Whale because it was the largest mouse
on the market, and he wanted to find out if a larger mouse might
keep people from extending their wrist beyond a neutral, relatively
flat position.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Hedge found, was yes. He and two graduate students,
Timothy Muss and Marisol Barrero, analyzed the wrist movements of
12 men and 12 women. Each wore sensors to track wrist extension
while scrolling and clicking. A wrist extension, in ergonomic
parlance, is the position of the wrist when the hand is tilted
upward while the lower arm is parallel to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors believe that carpal tunnel syndrome _ caused by a
pinched nerve and associated with tingling in the fingers _ is
exacerbated when the wrist is continually moved out of its neutral
position. ``You have a problem,'' Hedge said, ``when the extension
angle goes beyond 15 to 20 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   People in the study who used the larger mouse maintained an
acceptable wrist angle of less than 15.5 degrees twice as often as
with the smaller one. The larger mouse, Hedge said, required arm
movement rather than just hand movement.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge's study is not the final word on the carpal tunnel
problem. A report is available on the Cornell University Web site
at ergo.human.cornell.edu/CUEHnews.html, but the study has not been
published in a research journal or subjected to peer review. Many
ergonomics experts expressed reservations that such a small study
could shed light on an ailment that is associated with conflicting
and sometimes controversial reports of cures.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dr. Stephen Burastero, who runs an ergonomics
research program at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, in
Livermore, Calif., noted that wrist angle is only one factor
related to carpal tunnel syndrome. ``Force, muscle activity and
repetition also play a role,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Howard M. Sandler, of Melville, N.Y., who has worked on
occupational safety studies for the federal government and private
organizations, warned against putting too much stock in how
products are designed and not enough in how people actually use
them.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge considers his study a first step. ``We are not claiming
this is a solution to carpal tunnel,'' he said. ``But I think we've
established the principle that mouse design is important and that
is something we should start looking at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1604EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT13-COX     01-12 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT WAGES DEFENSIVE STRUGGLE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. found itself Wednesday waging a
series of defensive battles driven by its antitrust problems,
potential fallout from high-tech mega-mergers and its waning power
to set industry standards.
</P>
<P>
   How the software giant copes with these multiple challenges will
have bear heavily on its prospects well into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   One option _ breaking up the world's most valued corporation _
could end up benefiting investors, as did the breakup of the
telephone monopoly a generation ago. Despite a report in USA Today
that government lawyers favor such a step, such a split is not seen
as a viable solution by Justice Department trust-busters.
</P>
<P>
   The account is ``inaccurate in several important respects, and
it does not accurately represent our views,'' a spokeswoman for the
antitrust division of the Department of Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said that while it was
premature to discuss any settlement in the antitrust case, no basis
exists for any such ``outrageous remedy'' as a breakup. ``We
believe Microsoft and our innovations and products have been a boon
for consumers, for the personal computer industry and for the
high-tech industry in general,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, top Microsoft executives have cast a wary eye on
Monday's merger announcement by America Online Inc. and Time
Warner. That huge combination could imperil Microsoft's own bid to
become a key player in the converging entertainment and media
fields, chiefly by having its Windows CE software emerge as the de
facto standard on the next generation of interactive TV-cable
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, other technology giants are battling Microsoft in
their bid to gain a major share of the rapidly emerging wireless
Internet market. Earlier this week, both IBM and Oracle rolled out
separate deals to develop wireless access to cyberspace that would
effectively turn mobile phones into versatile hand-held computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is committed to its own wireless data service, dubbed
MSN Mobile 2.0. Scheduled for general release in the spring, it
promises to offer users ``tight integration'' with such other
Microsoft products as MSN Hotmail, MSN MoneyCentral, Expedia,
MSNBC, and MSN Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's combination, with the European giant Vodafone Airtouch,
came only days after it said it would make the Linux operating
system a centerpiece of its hardware strategy, as an alternative to
Microsoft's dominant Windows technology.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the power of Windows, one respected research firm,
International Data Corp., has concluded that Microsoft should be
broken up as a remedy in the federal antitrust lawsuit, with
Windows emerging as a separate corporate entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best outcome for consumers, for the industry and for
Microsoft is for the company to break itself up along functional
product lines,'' the new the 10-page analysis concluded.
``Microsoft would then gain access to more markets and repair its
reputation,'' it argued.
</P>
<P>
   While the researchers contend the best remedy would be to break
up Microsoft, they also say that such a move is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Microsoft prefers business as usual,'' the report
said. ``It will settle the suit only if it can do so without
jeopardizing its ability to build upon its dominant position on the
desktop to gain dominance in server operating environments.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the clock continues to run for a final ruling
from U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson. It could be
averted if a deal is struck in Chicago through the efforts of
Richard Posner, chief judge of the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals,
who seeks to broker a deal at Jackson's behest.
</P>
<P>
   With those close to the case are reluctant to discuss the
specifics, much of the discussion is being prompted by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most sensitive matters is the on-going rift between
the Justice Department and several key state attorneys general who
are partners in the case. Nevertheless, they are yoked together
legally.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that Microsoft would settle on the federal level
and continue to litigate with the states, who originally had
brought a wider lawsuit. It is equally unlikely that Jackson would
agree to sever twin complaints after combining them.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Microsoft lawyers are set to file with Jackson their
response to the government's proposed findings of law in the case.
That will be followed by a government reply, due the following
Tuesday, and a final Microsoft filing a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Final oral arguments are scheduled for Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
