   The account is ``inaccurate in several important respects, and
it does not accurately represent our views,'' a spokeswoman for the
antitrust division of the Department of Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said that while it was
premature to discuss any settlement in the antitrust case, no basis
exists for any such ``outrageous remedy'' as a breakup. ``We
believe Microsoft and our innovations and products have been a boon
for consumers, for the personal computer industry and for the
high-tech industry in general,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, top Microsoft executives have cast a wary eye on
Monday's merger announcement by America Online Inc. and Time
Warner. That huge combination could imperil Microsoft's own bid to
become a key player in the converging entertainment and media
fields, chiefly by having its Windows CE software emerge as the de
facto standard on the next generation of interactive TV-cable
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, other technology giants are battling Microsoft in
their bid to gain a major share of the rapidly emerging wireless
Internet market. Earlier this week, both IBM and Oracle rolled out
separate deals to develop wireless access to cyberspace that would
effectively turn mobile phones into versatile hand-held computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is committed to its own wireless data service, dubbed
MSN Mobile 2.0. Scheduled for general release in the spring, it
promises to offer users ``tight integration'' with such other
Microsoft products as MSN Hotmail, MSN MoneyCentral, Expedia,
MSNBC, and MSN Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's combination, with the European giant Vodafone Airtouch,
came only days after it said it would make the Linux operating
system a centerpiece of its hardware strategy, as an alternative to
Microsoft's dominant Windows technology.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the power of Windows, one respected research firm,
International Data Corp., has concluded that Microsoft should be
broken up as a remedy in the federal antitrust lawsuit, with
Windows emerging as a separate corporate entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best outcome for consumers, for the industry and for
Microsoft is for the company to break itself up along functional
product lines,'' the new the 10-page analysis concluded.
``Microsoft would then gain access to more markets and repair its
reputation,'' it argued.
</P>
<P>
   While the researchers contend the best remedy would be to break
up Microsoft, they also say that such a move is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Microsoft prefers business as usual,'' the report
said. ``It will settle the suit only if it can do so without
jeopardizing its ability to build upon its dominant position on the
desktop to gain dominance in server operating environments.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the clock continues to run for a final ruling
from U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson. It could be
averted if a deal is struck in Chicago through the efforts of
Richard Posner, chief judge of the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals,
who seeks to broker a deal at Jackson's behest.
</P>
<P>
   With those close to the case are reluctant to discuss the
specifics, much of the discussion is being prompted by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most sensitive matters is the on-going rift between
the Justice Department and several key state attorneys general who
are partners in the case. Nevertheless, they are yoked together
legally.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that Microsoft would settle on the federal level
and continue to litigate with the states, who originally had
brought a wider lawsuit. It is equally unlikely that Jackson would
agree to sever twin complaints after combining them.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Microsoft lawyers are set to file with Jackson their
response to the government's proposed findings of law in the case.
That will be followed by a government reply, due the following
Tuesday, and a final Microsoft filing a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Final oral arguments are scheduled for Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
