<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4077 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-CLIVEBARKER-TEX     01-12 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CLIVEBARKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ESSENTIAL CLIVE BARKER' A TOO-BIG SNACK OF FANTASTIQUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL H. PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Essential Clive Barker''
</P>
<P>
   by Clive Barker
</P>
<P>
   Collected fiction
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $27.50
</P>
<P>
   I can scarcely approach a Clive Barker yarn these days without
cringing in the dreadful anticipation that Something Wonderful Is
About To Happen. Wonderful, not spine-shivering. 'Twasn't always
thus, and in fact there was a splendid time when any Barker book
might have packed a written guarantee to do the reader irreparable,
if worthwhile, harm.
</P>
<P>
   That was longer ago than I care to reckon, back in the day when
a well-intentioned Stephen King could declare, ``I have seen the
future of horror, and it is Clive Barker,'' and mean every word of
it. Thus did King make life immeasurably easier for the
book-mongers who faced the daunting task of selling Barker, a
highfalutin Englishman who occupied a precarious ledge in the
history of hair-raising literature. With one foot planted squarely
in the grave of Edgar Allan Poe and the other on the slick new
surface of splatterpunk storytelling, Barker seemed to offer
extravagant promise _ and often made good on that promise, on the
spot. His work was as righteous as it was irrepressible _ and
hence, in a word, essential. It was at once a literature of ideas
and a literature of sensations, forcing those ill-matched values
into uneasily close quarters as a means of giving the reader a
heady mixture of shock value and provocative intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Barker's chosen idiom, the horror yarn, hadn't seen such
wide-awake ferocity since the Depression-era heyday of H.P.
Lovecraft and Hugh B. Cave. All during this past lapsed decade,
unfortunately, Barker has moved from Grand Guignol to epic-scale
``dark fantasy,'' a literary realm that might more honestly be
called ``horror lite.'' Barker prefers the highfalutin term
``fantastique,'' which is baloney any way you slice it. Tracking
his progress in this realm is rather like observing filmmaker James
Cameron move from the ragged-but-right terrors of ``Piranha 2: The
Spawning'' (1982) and ``The Terminator'' (1984) to the Something
Wonderful mock-horrors of ``The Abyss'' (1989) and, finally, to the
monument to insipidity that is ``Titanic'' (1997). (Barker, of
course, has pursued a parallel moviemaking career, with severely
mixed but often intriguing results. With the exception of his
crucial behind-the-scenes involvement on Bill Condon's ``Gods &AMP;
Monsters'' (1998), Barker has yet to top his work on the
``Hellraiser'' series' earliest pictures of 1987-88.)
</P>
<P>
   The Barker print opus of the moment is ``The Essential Clive
Barker,'' a regular Hungry Man TV dinner of a book _ more filling
than satisfying, and burdened with a culturally intimidating title
that values the presumptuous over the provocative. Hey! If I'm a
Serious Reader of Clive Barker, and this book has ``Essential''
written all over it, then how can I live without it?
</P>
<P>
   The first-blush reaction is to mistake ``The Essential C.B.''
for some definitive collection of the seminal ``Books of Blood,''
those collections whose outlandish yarns first announced Barker's
premature pre-eminence. But no: More a 570-page Cliff's Notes than
any fitting retrospective, the volume comprises 70-some odd
excerpts and only a scant clutch of short stories that are
available elsewhere. These are all tidily compartmentalized, like a
frozen dinner, into subsets with such precious designations as
``Doorways'' and ``Lives'' and ``Journeys'' and ``Visions and
Dreams.'' Some of these bits and pieces are self-contained and
effective enough, in their McNugget-ized way. Others seem
arbitrarily yanked from a sturdier context, the roots severed in
the process. The scraps of self-conscious fantastique, so to speak,
are at least mercifully brief. The short stories, including the
Kafkaesque political terrors of ``In the Hills, the Cities,'' are
fine _ but even these work better by far in their original
settings, surrounded by kindred audacious pieces, all written
before Clive Barker learned the greater importance of being Clive
Barker.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas filmmaker Tom Rainone, an occasional colleague of
Barker's in the horror-picture racket, once cobbled together a
feature-length presentation from nothing but short
coming-attractions trailers, one after the other, in bludgeoning
rapid-fire order. Now, a trailer can be a keen thing to watch,
especially for viewers with short attention spans, but even a
gee-whiz mentality will balk at watching more than half a dozen
trailers in unrelieved sequence. The blasted things will spoil your
appetite for the main feature, and they contain nothing of
satisfying dramatic substance to compensate for the intrusion.
``The Essential Clive Barker'' is a literary equivalent of
Rainone's pageant of short commercials-for-movies, giving the
reader only a teasing hint of the expected terrors, unexpected
delights and gag-reflex flights of Forced Wonderfulness that these
excerpts represent.
</P>
<P>
   The more genuinely essential Clive Barker, just in case the
point wants hammering, is that small set of ``Books of Blood,''
where gods and monsters (no metaphorical baggage intended) roam at
large and the sense of Edgar Allan Poe animates the nihilistic
sensibilities of the punk movement. Better a yarn you can sink your
teeth into, lest it sink its teeth into you first, than any volume
of Something Wonderful excursions along the Dream Sea of Quiddity
and the Dominions of Imajica.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate of deterioration, I should scarcely be surprised to
find Barker showing up next with a volume of ``Chicken Soup for the
(Lost) Soul.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael H. Price, president of the Fort Worth Film Festival,
has chronicled Clive Barker's career since the early 1980s. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
