<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4078 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-12 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     49ERS IN SEARCH OF SOMEONE TO BLAME FOR POOR SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY RATTO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN Francisco _ The news from the 49ers was as refreshing as it
was pleasing. The equipment guys are not being blamed for 1999, or
regarded as retardants to progress in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else? As ever, still guilty until proven innocent, with
no resolution in sight _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development in the 49ers' angst-o-rama came Monday
when Bill Walsh publicly snarled at the platoon of amateur jewelers
measuring his wrist for a retirement watch.
</P>
<P>
   He covered everything from ignorance to lack of respect to age
discrimination, and came very close to just dropping a blanket
``Shut your cakeholes!'' on the assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he may be saving that for his next press conference.
This
</P>
<P>
   is, after all, a very resourceful fellow when he puts his skull
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, though, he did something bad, which puts him in not
very exclusive company.
</P>
<P>
   Assembling all the 49ers post-mortems, we discover that the
following people have helped blow up the ammo dump: Eddie DeBartolo
Jr., Denise DeBartolo York, John York, Terry Donahue, Carmen
Policy, Dwight Clark, Vinny Cerrato, Paul Tagliabue, George
Seifert, Steve Mariucci, Steve Young, Ty Detmer, Jim Druckenmiller,
Jerry Rice, Terrell Owens, J.J. Stokes, Brent Jones, Greg Clark,
Ken Norton, Tim McDonald, Darnell Walker, Charles Haley, Deion
Sanders, ignorant writers, know-nothing TV types, oatmeal-headed
radio personalities, crypto-psychotic fans.
</P>
<P>
   And because he should never be left out of any Bay Area football
discussion, Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has his or her favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The players get it because they're all making too much money for
the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Policy/Clark/Cerrato get it for blowing too much money on old
guys and drafting lousy young ones.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie The Younger gets it for trying to outsmart a Louisiana
politician. Denise gets it for being related to Eddie, and John
gets it for being related to Denise. Mariucci gets it for being the
coach, Walsh gets it for being the general manager, and Donahue
gets it because of the time-honored legal concept of guilt by
association.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the media get it for reporting that the 49ers
finished 4-12 instead of staying with more popular figures like
12-4 and 13-3.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's been able, though, to provide the single smoking
bazooka with the set of fingerprints that solves the crime.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the way everyone could agree that Joe Thomas was the
source of all evil in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   This everyone-did-it deal, though, isn't working out for
anybody. Too
</P>
<P>
   much confusion, too much ambiguity. We need a villain. Or two.
Or in this case, everyone.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Whack everybody. The works. Whether they're named
York or Young, Walsh or Walker, Mariucci or McDonald. Every one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   They all did it (whatever ``it'' happens to be), so they all
have to go _ run off the land like diseased sheep in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about building for the future. This is about the
clarity of the past, which most 49ers understand far too readily.
The franchise was horrible, then it was great, with none of that
messy intermediate stage.
</P>
<P>
   Villains, then heroes. Very linear. Very easy to understand.
</P>
<P>
   This chemical spill, on the other hand, is anything but linear.
There's more blame than potholes on the freeway on-ramps, more
screwups than Willie Brown has hat blockers.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the interest of keeping it simple for everyone, we urge
complete administrative annihilation. Anyone who drew a payroll
check from the team last week gets a severance check this week, and
a decorative Gold Rush 2000 calendar.
</P>
<P>
   You know, just to be fair, until someone stands up and says,
``I'm the one. I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this won't help the 49ers any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   No owner, no coach, no front office, no players _ that's a lot
to overcome, no matter how many old trophies sit a'moldering in the
lobby. This is precisely the sort of thing that made the Cincinnati
Bengals what they are today.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, nobody has come up with a specific bright-eyed
replacement for any of the aforementioned guilty. Oh, Matt Millen's
name has been mentioned as a potential replacement for Walsh, but
he spends his football seasons talking on the radio next to Howard
David, and if you think that doesn't rust your brain _ man, you
still believe in the Easter Bunny, the Tooth Fairy and the plot
lines on ``Jerry Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we're still in the blame-delegation stage, and if you
can't be specific, you may as well be comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   So congratulations to the equipment staff for a sensational
year, and thanks for your service to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   And first dibs on the downstairs Coke machine.
</P>
</TEXT>
