<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4089 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-STEPHENFAUSTIN-T     01-12 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STEPHENFAUSTIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT MAN REVEALED IN GREAT DETAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Stephen F. Austin: Empresario of Texas''
</P>
<P>
   by Gregg Cantrell
</P>
<P>
   Biography
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Press, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   Philatelists treasure a 1936 Texas Centennial commemorative
stamp containing portraits of Stephen F. Austin and Sam Houston.
They are the twin icons of Texas history, but the stature of one is
national, whereas the other is known only by Texans and then often
too vaguely. Adult latecomers to the Lone Star State, lacking
elementary-school orientation to Texas history, may wonder why this
Stephen Austin fellow has a great city, a university and so many
streets named for him, and why he's called the ``Father of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Cantrell doesn't honor that title. His biography of the
state's strategic colonizer is subtitled ``Empresario of Texas,''
and it's evident from the start that Cantrell intends to
demythologize his subject. The author in his introduction
acknowledges as ``classic'' the only full-length biography of
Austin _ Eugene Barker's ``The Life of Stephen F. Austin,''
published almost 75 years ago _ and then downgrades it as
hagiography and insinuates an aim to set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
   This he surely has done. ``Exhaustively researched'' has become
a reviewer's cliche, but Cantrell has gone beyond exhaustion into
obsession for every important fact and trivial minutiae of his
subject's life and times.
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell writes clearly and well, if unexcitingly. He does
endeavor to pump more drama into a tale not deficient of it, with
such teasing pronouncements as: ``Throughout his life Stephen F.
Austin would chafe under this burden, which at times seemed
impossibly heavy. It would often bring him hardship and
frustration, and he could never escape it.''
</P>
<P>
   The historical narrative precedes the cradle. The author rather
laboriously fills in his subject's family background, with expected
substantial attention to Moses Austin, Stephen's quixotic,
ever-speculating father who had a get-rich-quick scheme to colonize
Mexican Texas with emigrants from the young United States.
</P>
<P>
   This mission was passed on to his son, and although Stephen was
reluctant, he was emotionally mortgaged (somewhat mysteriously) to
his father's will and whims. After Moses' death, the father's dream
became Stephen's obsession. He does not appear to have enjoyed the
quest or, indeed, to have enjoyed much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Fuller Austin, a handsome fellow who liked dancing with
attractive women but granted them little time and never married,
must have had some charm. The author grants him that, but it seldom
shows for the reader. Cantrell, though, makes Austin interesting in
his essential dullness.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is incomparably patient, and he perseveres against those
well-known overwhelming odds. Yet he seems unable to exult in any
triumph, so there's no surprise when, after Texas has gained its
independence, Austin loses the presidency to the charismatic
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Austin and Houston are not friends and bear their mutual respect
somewhat guardedly. After Houston appoints Austin his secretary of
state, the latter sets in motion the move for annexation to the
United States shortly before his
</P>
<P>
   death at age 43 and nine years before annexation becomes a fact.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, before 1836 when it all happened _ the Alamo, San
Jacinto, independence, a new government _ the familiar story of
Texas history is reprised in all its particulars, perhaps more
coherently than ever before. Through the progression from the
initial transplanting of 300 Anglo families in Mexican Texas in
1821 to the birth of the short-lived republic 15 years later, the
reader accrues admiration for Stephen F. Austin, even a sense of
wonder about him.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's true gift undoubtedly was diplomacy. His was not the
only Texas colonization effort, and he viewed others such as
Sterling Robertson's as rivals. Yet it seems that Austin alone had
faculties for dealing first with the Spanish government of Mexico,
then with the new government during a transition awkward for the
colonists as Mexico acquired its own independence, and ultimately
with Texans whose thirst for independence he came to share.
</P>
<P>
   The pageant of early Texas history has been imparted more
thrillingly by T.R. Fehrenbach and other chroniclers, but
Cantrell's contribution can hardly be faulted as historical
biography. One may wonder, though, if the author is fully aware of
how keenly his narrative illuminates the undoubted greatness of its
subject.
</P>
<P>
   So is, or is not, Stephen F. Austin justifiably the ``Father of
Texas''? More so, we'll say, than any other possible candidate for
a title so awesome.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
