<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Jan. 13. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Ned Kilkelly; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
kilkelly(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (ANKARA) _ The Turkish government on Wednesday
decided to put a hold on the death sentence of the Kurdish rebel
leader Abdullah Ocalan until a European court can review it. The
Ecevit government agreed to wait for the European Court of Human
Rights to review Ocalan's appeal before sending it to Turkey's
parliament for approval. Ecevit had warned that failing to comply
with the European court's request that the sentence be delayed
pending appeal would seriously damage Turkey's recently improved
relations with the European Union. (Summary from wires.) By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-GAYS-MILITARY (London) _ Left with no other choice after
a sweeping ruling by a European court last fall, the British
government announced Wednesday that it would no longer bar openly
gay men and women from serving in the military. The new policy,
which at a stroke ends Britain's decades-old practice of subjecting
gay men and women in the military to intrusive personal
investigations and dishonorable discharges, brings Britain into
line with most other NATO countries, including France, Canada and
Germany, all of which allow openly gay men and lesbians to serve in
armed forces. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-POLICE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday
that flight at the mere sight of a police officer could often, in
the context of other factors, be such suspicious behavior as to
justify the police in conducting a stop-and-frisk search. Although
all nine justices agreed with that broadly stated view, the court
split 5 to 4 on how to apply it to the facts of a Chicago case in
which a man bolted at the sight of a convoy of police cars. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-LICENSE-DATA (Washington) _ The Supreme Court on
Wednesday upheld a federal law that bars states from selling their
databases of personal information on licensed drivers and
automobile owners. The rare federal victory in the ongoing battle
at the court over federal versus state authority was unanimous. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
