<P>
   AOL-INVESTORS (Undated) _ The blockbuster America Online-Time
Warner merger hit more air pockets Wednesday as shares in both
companies plunged for the second straight day. America Online has
now fallen nearly 20 percent since the deal was announced, costing
AOL shareholders more than $30 billion. Investors on both sides
expressed concerns, with AOL shareholders worried that the merger
will slow the torrid growth of their company, while owners of Time
Warner stock complained that they were receiving less than half of
the combined company even though Time Warner has far more revenue
and cash flow than AOL. Nevertheless, both companies expressed
confidence that the deal would go forward, and some important
shareholders, including Janus Capital, which will likely be the
largest owner of the combined company, said the merger had their
full support. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
