<P>
   SCI-GALAXIES (Atlanta) _ From the first observations by a new
spacecraft, astronomers have found evidence that they say not only
confirms the existence of a halo of hot gases surrounding the Milky
Way galaxy but also seems to reveal how the gas got there, stays
hot and contributes recycled material for the formation of new
stars. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCHING-EXHIBIT (New York) _ The photographs that go on view
Friday at a Manhattan gallery may never fit comfortably into the
history of art, or for that matter, of photography. This is because
they are so deeply embedded in the history of hatred, specifically
the American history of hatred, which is often a matter of race.
They manifest this hatred shockingly, remorselessly, tragically.
The 60 photographs are of American lynchings that took place
between 1883 and 1960, mostly but not always in the South. Most of
them were taken by professional photographers immediately or a
short while after the crime, sometimes during. All but a few of the
victims were African-American men and women. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
