<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4092 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-FLIGHT-SIMULATOR-     01-12 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FLIGHT-SIMULATOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING THE `BIG IRON,' NO EXPERIENCE NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT4, NYT5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Circuits) 
(af) 
 By PAUL HOSEFROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coaxing the sleek jet's airspeed down to 134 knots for landing,
I eased the yoke forward and waited. Suddenly, breaking out of
thick, menacing clouds at 200 feet, the brash but welcome lead-in
lights of Runway 01 at Ronald Reagan National Airport in Washington
pointed home. The sweet chirp of tires touching down followed, and
another flight _ and another ordinary night _ was logged.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary for professional pilots perhaps, but for me, a private
pilot still learning in single-engine planes and a veteran of
desktop flight-simulation programs, it was a flight that changed
forever my notion of flying. I was playing the ultimate video game,
the Boeing 757 simulator at United Airlines' high-flight center in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   United began offering practice time at the center in the fall of
1996, in part to help defray the cost of its fleet of 30 very
expensive simulators, which are used by flight crews from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The company did not intend to offer a training course for
aspiring professionals. You do not have to have a pilot's license,
or even a driver's license, to use the simulator, just be ``an
able-bodied adult and at least 18 years old,'' according to a
United brochure.
</P>
<P>
   You also have to be able to pay the hefty price, ranging from
$950 for an hour on an Airbus A320 simulator to $1,550 for the
Boeing 777. (There are more expensive packages available for up to
two hours in the simulator.)
</P>
<P>
   The experience is probably the closest that amateur pilots like
me will get to flying ``the big iron,'' large, multi-engine
passenger jets. These sophisticated simulators duplicate more than
150 irregular and emergency procedures for things like wind shear
and snow, engine failures and landing gear collapses. Probably the
only part of flight the simulator cannot replicate is crashing.
When you crash a simulator _ and that happens quite often _ the
screen simply turns red.
</P>
<P>
   Susan M. Davis, the owner of a California printing business,
bought time in the 747 simulator for her 76-year-old father,
Richard, as a gift. He had been a P-51 fighter pilot during the
Second World War. Ms. Davis doesn't even fly on a home PC. ``He
flew, he landed,'' she said when their flights were over. ``I
crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   From the minute I set foot on the metal bridge crossing a
20-feet-wide divide between ``land'' and a large, white, windowless
box mounted on a huge, six-axis shaker platform housing the
simulator, something inside my pilot's brain said, ``This is
real.'' And once inside the cockpit with the door shut, I realized,
of course, that it was a real cockpit, right down to the two seats
that ride on L-shaped floor rails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience is so real,'' said Second Officer Dan
Tiedemann, a junior pilot with United. ``I've seen people in
multiple emergency situations act as if they'd forgotten it's a
simulator, it's so real.'' And, he added with a touch of macabre
humor, ``the instructor's in the back, laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   For my flight, I took along my own co-pilot, Andy Smith, a
friend who is also a private pilot. We decided to start from Runway
01, the principal north-south runway at Reagan Airport to work on
our takeoff and landing skills. The instructor for our flight was
John Ackerman, 31, who had previously flown Harrier jets in the
Marines. (Remember the plane Arnold Schwarzenegger flew in the
movie ``True Lies''?) Ackerman now trains pilots in Boeing's 757
and 767 models.
</P>
<P>
   I was co-pilot first and John, standing behind the pilot's
chair, patiently took me through the drill. I turned a switch on
the ceiling console and moved a toggle switch forward on the main
conson listened as the turbine spooled and set the fuel
valve to ``on.'' With that, I had just started two of the most
powerful jet engines made.
</P>
<P>
   Andy then took his turn at the controls, steering the plane
along the blue taxiway lights as we prepared to take off. The
simulator was set for nighttime, a more challenging environment
that sharply increased our sense of flying a real 757. ``Taxi into
position and hold,'' came the recorded instructions from tower.
</P>
<P>
   John had us line up, then reviewed takeoff procedures, using the
same small notebook that flight crews use for checklists. Flaps
were set with a lever on my side, and John told Andy what air
speeds to look for: ``In our configuration, V1 is 137 knots and
we'll rotate the nose at 140 knots. As we climb to 3,000 feet, our
initial clearance, flaps will be retracted at 188 knots and then
we'll trim for cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was my turn to try a takeoff, there was a pleasant
surprise in store. I had always wondered how the big planes were
steered on the ground. The Cessna Skyhawk I fly principally uses a
combination of power and a rudder controlled by the pilot's feet.
It prepared me well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're holding the center line better than some of my
students,'' he said, as the aircraft rumbled along at 80 knots.
</P>
<P>
   After a steep ascent, we turned the plane on course to the
northwest, the Washington Monument to our right and P-56, the
prohibited area around the White House, looming ahead. Staying
clear of Dulles Airport's airspace to the west, we began a circling
turn.
</P>
<P>
   From a point south of Mount Vernon, George Washington's home on
the Potomac River, we were guided by John, acting as the tower,
into an instrument landing on Runway 01, watching our speed and
position on the screen of the electronic flight director.
</P>
<P>
   While flying programs like Flight Simulator cannot compare with
the sensation of sitting inside the United cockpit, the view of the
ground from the simulator does match up. The program's ability to
mimic the pitch and yaw of actual flight is uncanny, so real that
when we braved an approach to San Francisco International Airport
on the United simulator, it all felt very familiar. ``Hey,'' I said
to Andy, ``we've done this before.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the comparison to video games ended. For me,
gone now are the innocent, if raucous, joys of arcade fighter
games. They chew up too many quarters and provide too few thrills.
And Flight Simulator, steady friend to thousands of desktop Walter
Mittys: you're good but a little too tame. A trip inside the United
simulator has ruined those simple pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   The evening flight home from Denver just did not seem the same.
Sitting in my seat, as the streetlights and buildings passed below,
I knew we were heading for Runway 36 at Dulles. But in my mind, I
was coaxing the sleek jet down to 134 knots and pushing the yoke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
