<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4116 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-CLASSICAL13-COX     01-12 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-CLASSICAL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Korean opera star in priceless form on `Les Bijoux'
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Korean coloratura Sumi Jo has been on the world opera scene for
a decade, but she's been getting a lot of media attention in recent
months _ especially when she repeated the role of Gilda in
``Rigoletto'' at the Metropolitan Opera just last month. This
caused a New York Times critic to praise her as ``even more
technically exquisite and stylistically informed'' than when she
made her Met debut in this role 10 years ago. Atlanta opera fans
can judge for themselves when she gives a recital Wednesday in
Symphony Hall _ or they can check out this elegant CD of French
opera arias. Some are as familiar as ``Ah! je ris'' (the ``Jewel
Song'') from Gounod's ``Faust.'' Others are as rarely heard as
Ophelia's mad scene from Ambroise Thomas' Reader's Digest Condensed
Opera version of ``Hamlet.'' All are sung with a clarity and
delicacy and fresh golden sound that's a joy to the ear. Jo is
equally at home with the sensuous perfumed lines of ``Depuis le
jour'' from Gustave Charpentier's ``Louise'' and the glittering
fireworks of ``Je suis Titania'' from Thomas' ``Mignon.'' And who
could resist any recording that includes an aria from Jacques
Offenbach's ``Robinson Crusoe''? (Umlaut and all.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Bijoux''
</P>
<P>
   Sumi Jo, soprano; English Chamber Orchestra, Giuliano Carella,
conductor. Erato Disques. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Sumi Jo performs 8 p.m. Wednesday. $40-$100. Atlanta Symphony
Hall, Woodruff Arts Center, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E. 404-733-4800.
</P>
<P>
   _Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
