<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4117 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TECH-DAY-JOBS-ART     01-12 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TECH-DAY-JOBS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY AT THE START-UP, A NIGHT AT THE OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6, 7 were sent Jan. 12 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JONATHAN MANDELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The four friends had met in college and moved here
two years ago to make it as performers, as young people have done
for generations. But on a recent Sunday, they were participating in
a series of meetings of an Internet start-up company, a company so
new it did not even have a name yet.
</P>
<P>
   What it had was a concept _ an all-powerful, all-purpose,
artificially intelligent concept _ that they called Wally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get across the concept of Wally, to create that
buzz before it launches,'' said the company's chief marketing
officer. ``Maybe we can get Al Sharpton to do a series of ads
arguing with Wally. Yes, Wally's omnipotent, but if someone
disagrees with him, it makes him more human.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the dot-com madness, the meeting was almost plausible. But
in fact, it was a spoof. The 12 people around the conference table
were making all of it up on the spot for an advanced class in
comedy improvisation. But an Internet start-up company is not just
something for them to joke about. Seven of the people in the class,
including the four friends, actually have day jobs in the computer
business, which is becoming an attractive alternative to waiting
tables for many aspiring performers.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Ari Voukydis, who had been playing the information
services director, started his first day on the job as an editor at
Bolt.com, which bills itself as ``one of the Internet's most
popular hangouts for high school and college students.'' It is just
the latest of his online jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In his new job, Voukydis joined Peter Olson, an old Wesleyan
classmate who was the chief applications developer in the
improvisation and has worked as a designer for Bolt.com for six
months. A third friend, Chad Carter, who played the chief
technology consultant, works as a programmer for Comvision.com, a
Web design firm.
</P>
<P>
   And the fourth friend, who goes by the stage name Dyna Moe and
was playing the art director, freelances as a Web graphic artist
and designer. Several more students in the class also have online
or technology jobs. Only one waits tables.
</P>
<P>
   That so many members of this one class of performers have online
jobs has a lot to do with their ages. Almost all of them are in
their early 20s. ``We sort of grew up with computers,'' Olson said,
``and that's where the jobs are.''
</P>
<P>
   But older performers are getting into the act as well. For Sal
Midolo, 35, a classically trained singer with steady work in church
choirs and light opera companies, working with computers has been a
return to an old love that has brought new income. ``When I was in
college,'' Midolo said, ``my music teachers used to say, `You're
spending too much time on your computers.''' When he moved to New
York a decade ago, he gave up computers completely.
</P>
<P>
   But four years ago, Midolo bought a new computer and had a Rip
Van Winkle experience. He discovered the new world of graphics
programs. In the next few years, he studied his way up from
Microangelo to Photoshop, then to 3D Studio Max, a program used to
create special effects in film and television (like the 3-D baby on
``Ally McBeal''). Now he is starting to get freelance work, but he
is aiming to be hired at an animation house.
</P>
<P>
   And his singing career? He paused. ``I'm not sure where it's
going to go,'' he said. ``I know I still get a sense of
satisfaction from it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to come by concrete statistics about how many
performing artists find day jobs in technology industries, but some
say the two pursuits make a good fit. ``Working online makes a lot
of sense for performers,'' said Kathy Schrier, the head of the
Actors' Work Program, a project of the Actors' Fund of America. The
program has been assisting performers of all kinds since 1987 to
find what Ms. Schrier calls ``dignified sideline careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Most performers, whether actors, singers, dancers, stand-up
comics or musicians, must find other ways to make a living. ``It's
a tough, tough business,'' Ms. Schrier said. ``You're always
looking for work. There is high unemployment: as many as 90 percent
are not performing at any given time. It's always temporary work;
that's the nature of the business.'' Even permanent employees of
repertory theaters, dance troupes, orchestras and opera companies
perform for a season that lasts only part of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For sideline careers, Ms. Schrier said, ``professional
entertainers want flexible, temporary work so they can go on
auditions and so that when they get cast, they can leave their
sideline job to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said Web jobs could fit into performers' lives. ``The
hours are long, but they're flexible,'' he said. ``It's unheard of
to clock in or clock out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Computer jobs will not replace waiting tables anytime soon for
professional performers, who number about 25,000 in New York City,
according to New York state statistics, nor for the countless
thousands more aspiring to become professionals. In 1998, the
latest year for which state statistics are available, the city had
37,000 jobs in computer-related fields and 142,000 jobs in
restaurants and bars.
</P>
<P>
   But in the city and nation, computer-related employment is
growing faster than occupations in any other industry, including
the restaurant business, the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics
reports. The number of workers in such jobs will more than double
by 2008, while the overall economy will grow by 15 percent, the
bureau said. .
</P>
<P>
   Some performers, like the ones in the comedy improvisation, turn
to computers while they try to break into their profession. But
others, like Frank Dellapolla, a 40-year-old dancer who now works
full time as a computer systems analyst and developer at the
brokerage Lazard Freres &AMP; Co., look at technology jobs as a way to
make an elegant exit. Still others learn computer skills in the
middle of their performing careers.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Carr, 50, has had the quintessential nonlinear career in
three decades as a singer, a dancer and an actress in Boston, Los
Angeles and Washington. She moved to New York last July with her
eye on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   She took classes offered by the Actors' Work Program in basic
computer skills and now works in two sideline careers _ as a
bartender in Broadway theaters (she is serving drinks at ``Miss
Saigon'') and as a weekend proofreader of computer graphics at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. With the money she is making, she plans
to buy her first computer. ``My aim is to start a home-based
business, for the flexibility and the income, and knowing computers
will allow me to do that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Izzy Flores, 40, an actor and model who was previously a
professional pianist and who was once nominated for a Grammy as a
songwriter, got inspired when his brother-in-law gave him a
hand-me-down Power Mac 6100 two years ago. With financing through
the Actors' Work Program, Flores took some courses at the Parsons
School of Design. Now, when he is not performing, he spends more
than a third of his time (between auditions) designing CD covers
for independent record companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some performers complain that their technology jobs are a kind
of tyranny rather than an opportunity, leading to a left
brain-right brain clash between their need to make a living and
their artistic bent. But Griff Braun, a dancer, doesn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a popular myth that there are two sides of the
brain, a linear side and a spatial side, and that some people are
creative and some scientific,'' said Braun, 31, who is both a
dancer with the American Ballet Theater and a Webmaster and site
designer. One of his Web clients is his dance company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carr agrees. ``I know a lot of actors who know the technical
aspect of the business,'' she said, ``who, for example, can program
the computers for the lighting design.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 75 dancers in his company, Braun said, about 30 own
computers. One of them, Tamara Barden, is as skilled with a
computer as he is, finding time to create Web sites after
performances and between rehearsals. ``To me, putting together a
Web site is a lot like putting together a dance,'' said Braun, who
designed the ballet company's site. ``It's just as creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Braun hopes that the often cited divide between art and business
is as artificial as the one between art and technology; he is
developing an Internet start-up, a dance education site. ``Right
now, I have a collection of names that I purchased, and I have a
concept,'' he said, though it is not an all-purpose, all-powerful
concept like Wally. He wouldn't even call it cool. ``I'm not going
for cool,'' he said. ``I'm going for something useful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
