<SLUG> BC-BIKES-CARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BICYCLISTS WANT POLICE TO BE MORE DILIGENT IN HANDLING
ACCIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RYAN KIM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When bicycles and cars collide in San Francisco,
cyclists say, police officers haven't been responsive enough, too
often automatically siding with motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The Land Use and Transportation Committee of the Board of
Supervisors on Tuesday took a step toward leveling the playing
field after approving a resolution urging the police to give
motorists and bicyclists involved in an accident equal treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution addresses a long-running complaint by bicyclists,
who say police officers have many times failed to take down
accident reports when a bicycle is involved.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution would require:
</P>
<P>
   _ Additional training of officers on traffic laws.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Police Department and the district attorney's office to
keep detailed records on the nature and number of bike riders who
are injured in accidents.
</P>
<P>
   _ The authorities to track the number of criminal charges filed
in those collisions for a period of six months.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, approved by Supervisors Leslie Katz, Michael
Yaki and Leland Yee, was also amended to include the same
protections for pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Bicycle Coalition began a cyclists' rights hot
line in November to document the way the police handled bicycle
accidents. It found police officers had failed to take a report for
three accidents involving injuries of the 19 incidents reported.
Officers filed three other reports on injury accidents only after
being pressured by the victims in the incident, according to the
coalition's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is a systematic bias against bicyclists on
the street,'' said Leah Shahum, program director for the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Several traffic officers appeared Tuesday at the committee
meeting and acknowledged that, in some cases, officers might not
have been following proper procedure in failing to take down
reports on accidents with injuries. But they said they were
isolated incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deny that that has happened,'' Sgt. Ray Shine said of
the bicyclists' complaints. ``But I'm not sure it's a big epidemic
problem in the Police Department.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1659EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
