u a BC-CALIF-HOUSING-HNS &LR;      01-12 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIF. GOVERNOR URGES SPECIAL ZONES WHERE PUBLIC SERVICE
WORKERS CAN LIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Gray Davis said he is working with
Mayor Willie Brown to create special zones in San Francisco and San
Jose so teachers, police, paramedics and firefighters can afford to
live where they work.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came a day after critics attacked his budget for
affordable housing as disgraceful.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting Tuesday with the Sacramento Press Club, Davis
blamed the San Francisco Bay area's critical housing shortage on
the area's incredible new wealth that has prompted the rich to
overbid on houses and send the middle-class to Central Valley towns
like Modesto and Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor said this new economic reality fueled by
the high-tech industry ``isn't a problem,'' but he added, ``There
is no way the taxpayers will give us enough money to compensate
teachers at the same rate they could get in the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Davis, who are close political allies, are working on
a plan to create special zones in this city and other expensive
areas of the state where public-service workers could get taxpayer
help to buy homes.
</P>
<P>
   Brown already has proposed setting up a special area on Treasure
Island near the San Francisco Bay Bridge for city workers who are
now priced out of the market and forced to live miles from the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways the housing problem in the Bay Area is the flip
side of (bay area workers') financial success. I bless them for it.
I think it's wonderful that they're successful,'' Davis said.
``Now, what can we do? We can try and get communities to understand
that at least (people in) certain professions warrant subsidies so
they can afford to live in the communities in which they serve.''
</P>
<P>
   After Davis unveiled his 2000-01 budget this week, he faced
intense criticism from housing advocates who said his request for
$11 million statewide for low-interest housing loans was too low.
Davis' budget also includes $35 million to $50 million in tax
credits for low-income housing, money for cold-weather homeless
shelters and migrant farm worker housing. Davis is offering cash
incentives, including a $10,000 forgivable-down-payment loan to
teachers who agree to work in low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Housing advocates say there is nothing dramatic in the budget to
address the lack of affordable homes and rental places for people
who don't work in schools, firehouses or police stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That budget is a disgrace,'' said Randy Shaw, executive
director of the Tenderloin Housing Clinic. ``What message is he
sending when poll after poll shows affordable housing to be the No.
1 issue, and the only thing in his budget is home ownership for
teachers and police.''
</P>
<P>
   When confronted Tuesday with similar comments, Davis said he was
working with Brown and San Jose Mayor Ron Gonzales to find areas
they can zone for subsidized housing for public service workers. If
they can, the governor said, then more money for the housing zones
will be proposed when the state budget is revised in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe those professions ought to include all emergencies
services _ paramedics, fire, police and teachers,'' Davis said,
``because you always run up against the NIMBY (not in my back yard)
problem when you say you want to have housing for the middle class
or low-income personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Kevin Shelley, a San Francisco Democrat, who will
push the housing-zone bill in the state legislature, said details
are being worked out on such issues as where the zones would be,
how much the subsidy would provide and whether it would be loan
assistance, matching grants or tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preferred option is to not have it geographically
specific,'' Shelley said, ``so there would be maximum choice for
the workers. But if we're limited in how we can apply the law, I'll
take affordable housing in an incredibly beautiful environment such
as Treasure Island over something else.''
</P>
<P>
   A report released Monday by the National Association of Home
Builders said only 11.9 percent of San Francisco families, those
earning a median $72,400 annual income, can afford a home in the
city. The median home price in San Francisco is $407,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1659EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
