<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini CD review
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Given Sunday''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Atlantic. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it really is about the company you keep. Because on this
soundtrack to Oliver Stone's football film the abundant rap acts
take their contributions to the extremes that Stone takes
conspiracy theories. Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott adds an almost
overpowering orchestra to a reminder to her boyfriend that she was
there before the money (``Who You Gonna Call''). The ``Reunion'' of
Capone-N-Noreaga is overblown by electronic horns. And at the other
end of the volume knob, LL Cool J whispers uncharacteristic
profanities in ``Shut 'Em Down.'' At least when rockers Hole and
P.O.D. pile on the guitars later it's what you expect. And with the
exception of actor/comedian Jamie Foxx's surprisingly smart team-up
with rappers Guru and Common on ``Any Given Sunday,'' many could
have scored with that: the expected.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
