<HEADER>
A4123 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MYSTERY13-COX     01-12 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MYSTERY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mystery Men' set out to save the city
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mystery Men'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   It's a spoof! It's an adventure! No, it's an amiable mess! The
mystery about ``Mystery Men'' is why so many sharp actors signed on
for a movie needing several more rewrites. The good news is, it
provides some giggles. It's unpretentious and goofy. And the
presence of the masterfully deadpan Janeane Garofalo (as the
Bowler) elevates any party.
</P>
<P>
   She's part of a cast including William H. Macy, Hank Azaria and
Ben Stiller, playing would-be superheroes with dubious powers.
(Azaria, for instance, throws forks.) Their goal is to win some of
the crime-fighting glory enjoyed by Champion City's Captain Amazing
(Greg Kinnear, in fine sneering mode), but to do so they have to
battle master criminal Casanova Frankenstein (Geoffrey Rush).
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the movie doesn't seem to know when it's mocking other
superhero flicks and when it's mocking itself. It's a comedy in
search of a real target and consistent rules. The movie is like its
hapless heroes. It's a wannabe that has the best intentions _
including a pronounced anti-gun stance _ but none of the knack it
takes to save the day, or itself.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1659EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4124 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL13-COX     01-12 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A mind-blowing menagerie of maddening movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mental hospitals have often been the way to go for the
Oscar-hungry actor. Jack Nicholson won one for ``One Flew Over the
Cuckoo's Nest.'' So did his co-star, Louise Fletcher. Olivia de
Havilland snagged a nomination for ``The Snake Pit,'' as did Brad
Dourif for ``Cuckoo's Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, Interrupted,'' which opens Friday, may offer similar
opportunities for its two stars, Winona Ryder and Angelina Jolie.
Here are some madhouse movies you might go nuts over:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' (1975; R): Ken Kesey's
'60s counterculture the-loonies-are-running-the-asylum novel was
just right as an anthem of anti-Establishment rebellion for early
'70s moviegoers. Kirk Douglas had been trying to make a movie out
of the material since 1963, when he brought a failed version to
Broadway. But it took his son Michael to finally get the project
onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson was first choice to play Randle P. McMurphy, the
social misfit (by the way, a convicted rapist in the book) who
feigns insanity to avoid prison for the ``cushier'' life in a state
mental institution. His antagonist, Nurse Ratched, was harder to
find because so many actresses found the role misogynistic. A
number of names turned it down _ reportedly, everyone from Jane
Fonda and Anne Bancroft to Ellen Burstyn and Geraldine Page _
before Fletcher, a relative unknown, was cast. Accepting the Oscar
for best actor, Nicholson deadpanned, ``Well, I guess this proves
there are as many nuts in the Academy as anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Snake Pit'' (1948; unrated): Though somewhat dated today
in terms of its attitude toward women and its methods of
psychiatric treatment, this is still a very watchable and sometimes
disturbing film. No wonder it was both a popular and a critical
success (six Academy Award nominations, including best picture). As
a depressed woman who suffers a breakdown and is committed, De
Havilland runs through a gamut of emotions _ including the
requisite transferal crush on her pipe-smoking therapist, Mark
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to the ward where they put the incurable cases
and where De Havilland, after a second breakdown, is temporarily
interred. Director Anatole Litvak's spiraling overhead shot,
receding from the mad inmates and reducing them to abstract
twitching figures, is still powerful 50 years later as is one
patient's plaintive rendition of ``Going Home'' that turns into an
eerie group sing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bedlam'' (1946; unrated): The last of the Val Lewton horror
pictures for RKO (the run that began with ``Cat People''),
``Bedlam'' is actually more of a terrifying historical drama than a
horror flick.
</P>
<P>
   Based on William Hogarth's painting _ that's how the credits
read _ the movie stars Boris Karloff as the sadistic Master Sims,
villainous director of the celebrated 18th-century madhouse. When a
young actress (Anna Lee) tries to expose the asylum's unsavory
practices, she herself is falsely committed.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is far more lurid than Lewton's other pictures,
possibly because he was determined to show Bedlam _ or the St. Mary
Hospital for the Insane as it was fully known _ as accurately as
possible. As for Karloff, he always referred to Lewton as ``the man
who rescued me from the living dead and restored my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Persecution and Assassination of Jean-Paul Marat as
Performed by the Inmates of the Asylum of Charenton Under the
Direction of the Marquis de Sade'' (1966; R): The title is a
mouthful; the movie's a mind-full. No wonder Peter Brook's
production of Peter Weiss' brilliant Brechtian madhouse epic is
usually referred to by the shorthand title, ``Marat/Sade.''
</P>
<P>
   The film version retains the original cast, most of them members
of the Royal Shakespeare Company. It's still more theater piece
than film, despite the director's efforts to make it ``cinematic.''
But it retains every bit of its chaotic power as the assorted
lunatics act out their version of the French Revolution before an
invited audience of lacy aristocrats.
</P>
<P>
   And look for two-time Oscar winner Glenda Jackson as Charlotte
Corday. It was her first time in a movie and in her opinion, ``I
gave an over-the-top performance. Much too much.'' Many critics
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
