<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turn up the heat with horseradish-like wasabi
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless you are a fan of sushi, you may not be familiar with
wasabi, the horseradish-like condiment most often served as a dip
with Japanese delicacies. But if the prediction of food and dining
trend watcher and cookbook author Rozanne Gold pans out, that is
about to change. If the inclinations of New York foodies spread
elsewhere, and they often do, people will be giving hot chile
peppers a break as they look to wasabi to turn up the amps on not
only traditional Japanese dishes but all kinds of other foods, too.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gold, wasabi is beginning to be appreciated as a
complement to just about anything that needs a little heat. Readily
available in Asian markets, it's starting to show up on supermarket
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Fine wasabi is difficult to grow and prized like fine wine by
Japanese chefs. It fetches more than $100 a pound in Japan and $45
over here.
</P>
<P>
   We checked the Internet and in 10 minutes learned all about
wasabi except what it tastes like.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Many people call wasabi Japanese horseradish, but we learned
at www.wasabi.co.nz/meet.html that it's in the mustard family,
similar to brussels sprouts. What you eat from the plant is the
thickened stem or exposed root, which is ground into a
sinus-clearing, pungent green paste. The site also provides more
detailed botanical information and relates a news service article
reporting that some researchers claim wasabi may stop the growth of
stomach cancer cd that it is commonly regarded to be
effective in preventing food poisoning. There are recipes for a
host of spicy dips, dressings, marinades and sauces and many
Japanese recipes as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pacific Farms, a supplier of fresh wasabi at
www.freshwasabi.com/recipes.html, says not to be fooled. The green
paste on the side of your sushi dish is rarely real wasabi. More
commonly it is ordinary horseradish with food coloring added. When
wasabi is used fresh, they say, it has a heat component that,
unlike chile peppers, is not long-lived on the palette and subsides
into an extremely pleasant, mild vegetable that even people who
normally dislike spicy foods can enjoy. The site includes other
interesting facts and recipes, including those for marinated
vegetables and wasabi and garlic wings. A sample box of fresh
plants, enough for eight people, cold packed and shipped overnight,
runs $22.90. They also include a special grater and instructions.
Wasabi releases its heat only when grated finely, not when chopped
up like a carrot. After grating it should be allowed to stand for
about 15 minutes to release its full flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It's hard to stay ahead of the Internet on much of anything,
but as far as wasabi recipes, we found that instead of the usual 10
million recipes available for any other given ingredient, wasabi
had comparatively few. The sites mentioned above have the best
variety of recipes, enough to get you started and ahead of the
curve. For an intriguing recipe for Crabmeat Batons With Soy
Dipping Sauce and Wasabi Cream by chef Robert Bruce of New Orleans'
Palace Cafe, see www.nawlins.com/rec23.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For two interesting articles on the upcoming popularity of
wasabi, see www.seattletimes.com
</P>
<P>
   /news/lifestyles/html98/pwasa19990711.html and
oregonlive.com/news/99/10/st101016.html.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Salmon With
</P>
<P>
   Wasabi Beer Glaze
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce wasabi powdered horseradish
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons golden lager or other beer
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Few drops honey
</P>
<P>
   6 salmon fillets (5 to 6 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   Place the wasabi powder in a small bowl. Slowly add the beer and
stir to form a smooth paste. Stir in the oyster sauce, salt and
white pepper. Add honey. Season the fish lightly with salt and
pepper. Brush the wasabi glaze on each fillet and let it stand 2
minutes. Grill, saute, broil or bake fish until cooked through.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with spicy rice or a steamed assortment of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 211 calories, 31 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 36), 1 gram carbohydrates, 64
milligrams cholesterol, 207 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
