<HEADER>
A4129 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP13-COX     01-12 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hershey's classic is frosting on cake for chocolate lovers
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After running Doris Goodin's e-mail request for the
chocolate icing from a Hershey's Cocoa can from about 1980, we
learned that some people have held on to the familiar dark brown
cans as if they were collectors' tins.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Parella of Tucker, Ga., took one she said is at least 30
years old off her shelf and copied the recipe for us. Yvonne
Roberts of Snellville, Ga., referred to hers purchased in 1972, the
year she was married; and Marcy Sproull of Rockmart, Ga., sent a
photocopy of the side of a tin from the '80s that she saved when
she cleaned out her father's house after his death.
</P>
<P>
   The frosting recipe, tested and given here along with the
Chocolate Town Special Cake on the cocoa cans, was the same through
the decades.
</P>
<P>
   Proving once again that some good things never change.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Fluffy Cocoa Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for a 9-inch, two-layer cake
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup Hershey's Cocoa
</P>
<P>
   4 cups confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, stir together cocoa and confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, cream together part of the cocoa-sugar mixture
with the butter. Blend in vanilla and half of the milk. Add
remaining cocoa-sugar mixture and blend well. Add remaining milk
and beat to desired spreading consistency. Additional milk may be
required.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (1/12th recipe): 252 calories, 2 grams protein, 9
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 33), 44 grams carbohydrates,
3 milligrams cholesterol, 116 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Town Special Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes one 9-inch, two-layer cake, 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups sifted cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour two 9-inch layer
cake pans and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, cream sugar and shortening until light and
fluffy. Add eggs, one at a time, beating well after each addition.
Add vanilla and blend well.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, sift together flour, baking soda and salt. Add
alternately to shortening mixture with buttermilk. Make a heavy,
smooth paste of the cocoa and boiling water; cool slightly, about 5
minutes. Add to batter and blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into prepared pans and bake about 35 minutes or until done.
Cool completely and frost with Fluffy Cocoa Frosting.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 545 calories, 6 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 32), 92 grams carbohydrates, 39
milligrams cholesterol, 351 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   In July we ran Mark Spieler's request for an Orange Mini
Chocolate Chip Cookie he thought had been published in this
newspaper several years ago. A search of the archives did not turn
up the recipe, nor has his Recipe Swap request. So we're asking
again. ...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  We're also holding out for responses to a question from Ellen
Hastie of Johnson City, Tenn., who wants to replace a lost recipe
for Sloppy Joes. It included browned ground beef and a sauce made
of Heinz chili sauce, yellow mustard and Karo syrup. Her children
enjoyed it 25 years ago, and now she'd like to make it for her
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
