<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4131 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-NOMAD-GAME-NYT &LR;      01-12 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NOMAD-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OMIKRON'S NETHER WORLD OF CYBERKARMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
(af) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In David Cronenberg's science-fiction horror film, ``Existenz,''
there is a moment when a character is seized by the impulse to eat
a dubious plate of food in the virtual reality game he's playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disgusting,'' he says, ``but I can't help myself.'' It
turns out that the crustacean he's eating contains parts of a gun
he must use later in the game. His vocal cords were temporarily
possessed by the system, to further the plot.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of moments like this in Omikron: The Nomad Soul,
a cyberpunk sci-fi adventure developed in France. Like most French
games, it's aesthetically gorgeous _ the interactive love child of
``Blade Runner'' and ``The Fifth Element,'' with a soundtrack by
David Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   It's highly cinematic, constantly segueing into letter-boxed
dramatic sequences in which the player has no participation. In
fact, it's less of a game than a fractured film on a 3-D sound
stage that the player must traverse in a particular fashion, sans
script.
</P>
<P>
   The game's conceit is that the player has been drawn through a
portal into the fantasy world of Omikron. On the other side of the
computer screen, your soul inhabits the body of Kay'l, a police
officer enmeshed in a conspiracy that involves the criminal
underworld, a revolutionary cult, the corrupt military government
and insidious high-tech corporations in league with Canaanite
demons _ standard fare.
</P>
<P>
   If Kay'l dies, your soul transfers into the next character who
touches him. Hence the game's subtitle, The Nomad Soul. Later in
the game, you can hop between characters at will, possessing the
bodies of guards, thugs, mercenaries and a number of innocent
bystanders, male and female. That ostensibly gives you a lot of
control and freedom to maneuver with impunity through Omikron's
dark streets, back alleys and dives.
</P>
<P>
   But your sense of control and the illusion of freedom are
frequently shattered by the game's tendency to take hold of the
puppet strings, prompting your character to take actions that have
no rational basis. For instance, you visit Sergeant Boog, head of
internal affairs at the police station. After some small talk, your
character says, ``I have a gift for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The game prompts you to call up your inventory. Meanwhile, the
burly sergeant looks up from his desk expectantly. You tap
everything you're carrying: police badge, weapon and ammunition,
money, scraps of paper. A beverage? Sandwich? The situation rapidly
becomes awkward.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that you were supposed to pick up a girlie poster
at the local sex shop to curry favor with Sarge. (Even though
Omikron is listed as being for ages 13 and up, it seems more
appropriate for people 17 and up.) In return, he's supposed to give
you the security headquarters master key, which gets you into your
dead partner's office. But if you didn't procure the nude pinup,
you're pitched into a schizophrenic conversational cul-de-sac from
which you can only pedal backward.
</P>
<P>
   You have lunch with your wife. You're about to tell her
something important when you're paged _ there's a supermarket
holdup nearby. You are invisible to your wife after that. Even
after you take down the supermarket gunmen and return to the
restaurant, she is oblivious to your presence.
</P>
<P>
   But then, most of Omikron is oblivious to your presence.
Hundreds of people are on the street but don't see you. If you step
into their paths, they simply continue on their way. Call girls
sidle up and shift their weight suggestively, but you can't hire
them. You can't even talk to them. The only people who will talk to
you are beggars, and they say only one sentence after you give them
money.
</P>
<P>
   So when story characters come out of the woodwork, it feels
stagy.
</P>
<P>
   Like, oh, you're talking to me, so I'm supposed to do something
really obvious now, and I'll be cued with the right line in a
second. How's the movie so far?
</P>
<P>
   That sort of scripted interaction didn't seem so jarring in
early computer games, in which the graphics were equally crude. But
in a universe whose surface is so finely detailed, it's surreal to
be surrounded by automatons (particularly when there are no street
signs). Especially if you've spent any time in a persistent
multiplayer world like Everquest or Ultima Online, where there are
thousands of characters animated by human beings and their subplots
and relationships and histories.
</P>
<P>
   Those worlds feel full because they convey a sense of human
presence. Omikron feels empty because its characters are walking
props. The buildings seem hollow because you know that no one is
living in them.
</P>
<P>
   No one is home, anywhere, ever. Everybody who acknowledges you
is a robot.
</P>
<P>
   And David Bowie, the maestro of futuristic alienation, is
crooning in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Albert Camus is smiling. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Omikron: The Nomad Soul, developed by Quantic Dream, published
by Eidos; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98; $39.99; ages 17 and up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1701EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
