<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-0113-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    HISTORIAN IS PRESSED IN COURT TO REJECT HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    600&AMP;add 
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON Jr. 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Maverick historical writer David Irving on Wednesday
evaded attempts in court to show that his public statements prove
that he rejects the conventional understanding of the Holocaust _ a
central issue in his libel suit against a professor from Atlanta's
Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by the judge to give his interpretation of the Holocaust,
Irving offered a cautiously worded response. ``The Holocaust is the
tragedy that befell the Jewish in World War II,'' he said. ``But it
was the whole of the Second World War and the people who died were
not just Jews but gypsies and homosexuals, the people of Coventry
and the people of Hiroshima.''
</P>
<P>
   But later on cross examination, he denied as a ``big lie'' that
millions of Jews were killed in gas chambers at Nazi death camps or
that their extermination was part of a systematic campaign by the
Third Reich and its leader, Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Irving is suing professor Deborah Lipstadt and her publisher
Penguin Books for libel over her 1994 book, ``Denying the
Holocaust: The Growing Assault on Truth and Memory.'' The book
depicts the self-made historian as a ``Holocaust denier'' who
twists history to support his belief that the scope of the mass
murder has been greatly exaggerated. He believes Jews have sought
to use the Holocaust story in a campaign to get increased
reparations from the German people.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream historians and others who accept the traditional
story of the Nazi's systematic slaughter of more than 6 million
Jews see the case as an opportunity to confront a well-known source
of what they consider misinformation over what really happened.
</P>
<P>
   Irving's public position on the Holocaust is central to his
argument that the book defamed him by untruthfully asserting that
he denies the Holocaust occurred. While many of Irving's public
statements seem to indicate that he has disputed the existence of
the Holocaust, Irving insisted that he only denied certain aspects
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deny that the Nazis could have liquidated millions of people
at gas chambers at any of their locations during the Third Reich,''
he said. He believes the gas chambers at Auschwitz were actually
built after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Irving, who is representing himself, said the logistics of
disposing of so many bodies would have been overwhelming, even for
the Germans. ``One million people weigh 100,000 tons _ it's a major
logistical problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nazis did murder many Jews, said Irving, who offered an estimate
of between 1 million and 4 million victim. But he said the evidence
indicates that the killing program was operated at a level below
Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Irving contends that Hitler was unaware of mass killings of Jews
until 1943. He also believes that Hitler actually was opposed to
such mass killings early in the war and gave orders to prevent the
slaughter of Jews and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a chain of documents that show that Hitler was a
negative influence (on the campaign to kill Jews),'' Irving said.
``There is no equal document chain to indicate that he was a
positive influence.''
</P>
<P>
   However, lead defense attorney Richard Rampton introduced a 1942
document sent to Hitler that reported that more than 363,000 Jews
had been killed in Poland. The defense intends to rely upon scores
of documents and expert witnesses to assail Irving's unorthodox
view of history.
</P>
<P>
   Irving responded that Hitler was probably too busy to take note
of this. ``He had a lot on his plate at that time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Irving, who has been accused of twisting facts to exonerate
Hitler, said he believed the dictator's reign was not all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when he was on the course and then he ran off
the rails,'' he said. ``You cannot praise his racial programs or
his penal methods, but he did pick his nation up out of the mire
and reunify it and gave it a sense of pride again.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving also defended himself against the book's passages linking
him to radical groups such as the Iranian-backed Hamas and
Hezbollah, the Nation of Islam and the Russian neo-Nazi group
Pamyat. While he didn't specifically deny any ties to these groups,
he said it was unfair to consider him guilty by association.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in general he did not consort with terrorists but
acknowledged that he knows people with views that others may
consider extreme. ``These people are extremists in the views of the
expert witnesses,'' he said. ``This is a very subjective
viewpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving, who is not a lawyer, often sounded more like someone
involved in a dissertation rather than someone trying to craft a
legal case. As an indicator of the mass of material he intends to
introduce into evidence, he said he had provided court reporters
with a spelling guide to 5,000 names he will be mentioning over the
course of what is expected to be a three-month trial.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Rampton said he was puzzled by Irving's
intentions. ``I don't have a clue what his case is,'' he told the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Charles Gray, a former libel lawyer, patiently
prodded Irving with questions and advice as the historian took the
stand as the first witness in his own case.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Irving appeared to be wearing the judge's patience thin
on only the second day of the trial. After introducing two
videotapes _ one of them lengthy _ with debatable relevance, Gray
warned him that he needed to deal with challenges to his
credibility as a historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's got to be grappled with _ the sooner the better
as far as I'm concerned,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial resumes Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr., can be reached by e-mail at:
bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
