<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBAY ADDICT'S DIARY: BUY HIGH, SELL LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am an eBay addict. I write that now with barely a twinge.
</P>
<P>
   For a long timeuded myself into thinking I only bought
essential items, like the 37 pieces of green glassware that I
needed to fill the alarmingly large and empty shelves of the
(third) desk on the first floor. Or the Cultural Revolution poster
that almost hides the crack on the den wall. Or the vintage flour
sifter, which my husband claims also sifts a little rust into cake
batter. ``That's cinnamon,'' I said (addiction symptom: lying).
</P>
<P>
   Then a few weeks ago, I saw an eBay listing for a used doll:
``Baby All Gone eats with a `magic spoon,' has soft pink body and
hard head, hardly played with.'' I bid $11 (symptom: failing to
think to self, `Yecch').
</P>
<P>
   I was outbid. I pored over the bid history (symptom: feeling
envious of person who buys worthless junk) and saw that the had bid $26.
</P>
<P>
   That astronomical amount jolted me. I had assumed that the
online auction bubble had burst, or at least deflated a little.
Sure, eBay has grown into a giant, becoming the world's biggest
flea market and offering 2.9 million items last week alone. But the
site has become increasingly complicated to navigate. Categories of
merchandise overlap. And bidders were bound to grow more
sophisticated. Even I was unwilling to bid at times, remembering an
identical item offered earlier at a better price. The crazy auction
madness of 1999 that saw millions of people trading the contents of
their attic for the contents of someone else's seemed as distant as
Dutch tulip-bulb mania.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there was no way to gauge this because eBay
refuses to release statistics on the percentage of items that sell
_ or even get a single bid. ``That statistic is not released by any
auction house, and it's too bad,'' said Martin De Bono, a senior
analyst at Gomez Advisors, which ranks online auctioneers at
www.gomez.com. An eBay spokeswoman told me that the company
considers sales figures proprietary. But, she added, $8 million
worth of merchandise sells every day.
</P>
<P>
   It then occurred to me that I could test eBay's staying power.
Instead of buying truckloads of stuff, I could sell, maybe from the
same pile of, er, collectibles that I had amassed over the last
year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   I had the perfect test item: a certain pink Depression-era glass
vase I had purchased a few months ago for about $12. (According to
De Bono, 70 percent of online auction buyers purchase items that
cost less than $100.) And, while not the sort of item that would
necessarily elicit a Baby All Gone level of demand, it had a subtle
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Would I make money after eBay took its cut? The site's charges
can add up fast. First, there is a listing fee, ranging from 25
cents to $2, depending on an item's opening value. The site also
takes a percentage _ generally from 1.25 percent to 5 percent _ of
the sale price. Sellers also pay to set a reserve price or to
include a photo in eBay's Gallery (where buyers preview thumbnails
of items) or even to list their items in bold type. If I did
without boldface, I would need only to sell at $12.85 to break
even.
</P>
<P>
   I followed the remarkably easy listing process on the eBay site.
I registered so that eBay would be able to charge my credit card.
Then I set the length of the auction (seven days), to choose from
among hundreds of listing categories (Pottery and Glass:
Depression: Anchor Hocking) and to upload an image to accompany my
listing. Here I deviated from the instructions slightly, playing
cards online while my husband took a digital photo of the vase,
edited it, uploaded it to my AOL home page, then embedded a link in
my listing. Although I was distracted by a particularly tense
online game of hearts, I think he worked for about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 28, at 7:38:05 PST, Item No. 226,790,186, ``Pink Fired
On Deco Vase,'' went live on eBay, soliciting an opening bid of $8.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly one week later, the auction closed _ with no bids.
</P>
<P>
   I was out 25 cents and my suspicions about online auctions were
strengthened. I could relist the item, and if it sold, I would not
have to pay an additional 25-cent listing fee. But if I failed
again? I'd be out 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Then I considered a worse possibility: no one liked my vase. At
that moment, it didn't matter to me that none of the three listings
described as ``fired on vases'' had gotten a single bid that week.
Nor did I care that neither did 17 of the 46 items in my category
whose auctions ended in the same five-hour period. No, my personal
taste was in question. I had spent (approximately) $12 for a vase
that apparently no one else wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Or did I just have a bad listing?
</P>
<P>
   For advice, I phoned Annette Graf, an online seller since early
1998 whose many successes _ she once sold a vintage Raggedy Ann
sewing pattern on eBay for more than $100 _ prompted her to write
and self-publish a book called ``How to Sell on eBay and Other
Online Auctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Critiquing my listing, Ms. Graf offered these tips: ``Relist it
in the middle of the day, when the most people are online, because
it will go to the top of the chronological list in the category.
Also, give it a good description so people will want to buy it. And
you might want to list it in a more general category, where more
people will see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The very existence of books like Ms. Graf's _ Amazon.com sells
more than a dozen books on the same topic _ suggests that selling
on eBay may require a lot more work than merely listing on Ebay.
</P>
<P>
   I made the changes. This time, I got one bid and sold my
``WONDERFUL Fired On Deco Vase.'' For $8. So, I went down to the
kitchen and dug out the rusty sifter. I am an eBay addict. And I'm
not alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
