<HEADLINE>
Q&AMP;A: GEARING UP FOR USB 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
(mk) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is there any way I can use USB devices if my computer has no
USB ports?
</P>
<P>
   A: Computers made before 1997 do not generally support the
Universal Serial Bus standard, but it might be possible to upgrade
your machine, depending on the type of computer and operating
system you are using. But there are a few hardware and software
factors to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies make USB add-in cards that will fit in one of a
computer's PCI slots on the motherboard. Adding such a card, which
can be as simple as adding a network card or a sound card, can give
you two or four USB ports on the back of your computer. A two-port
card for either a Windows PC or a Macintosh costs about $40. You
must have an available PCI slot on your motherboard and operating
system software that can handle USB.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95 has only limited support for USB, so it would be
advisable to upgrade to Windows 98, which offers full support.
Windows 98 users can download a free USB evaluation utility program
from www.usb.org/faq/ans3.html(NU)q1 that will check their hardware
and software for compatibility.
</P>
<P>
   Some USB cards require Macintosh users to be running recent
versions of the Mac operating system, and Mac owners may want to
download the USB Card Support patch from the software updates area
of Apple's Web site (asu.info.apple.com).
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to QandA(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
