<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-Y2K-COLLECTING-ART-NY     01-12 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLLECTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K SOUVENIRS: TREASURE OR TRASH? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ball was dropped. There were no Y2K bugs. Now, what to do
with those goofy year 2000 eyeglasses, the plastic-stemmed wine
glasses, bottle openers, sequin-encrusted party hats, paper plates,
calendars and the Evian millennium bottle of water?
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's wacko, wonderful or wow, save it,'' said Alex Shear, a
collector of popular American culture. (For him, that meant a sign
from a grocery store advertising ``Y2K water.'')
</P>
<P>
   But historically, few huge events have created valuable
keepsakes. Even if you acquire a collection of millennial hats and
swizzle sticks, you are not likely to make a killing. ``It's rarity
that makes things valuable,'' said Matthew Weigman, a spokesman for
Sotheby's. ``There were too many Y2K souvenirs made for most of
them to appreciate.''
</P>
<P>
   To put it in perspective, 1939 World's Fair souvenirs are just
now becoming desirable holdings. So you should be in it for the
long haul. Find a sturdy cardboard box and create a home-grown time
capsule. When you fill the carton, put a family spin on it: write a
letter describing what you did on New Year's Eve 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Allan, a 12-year-old British boy who lives in London and
was lucky enough to have watched the spectacular fireworks display
on the Thames, recalled his most cherished memory of the festive
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating an entire package of Twisties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If his parents save a Twisties package along with the millennial
mugs, banners, T-shirts, magazines, newspapers and cereal boxes,
that memory will be there if he opens the time capsule with his
children and grandchildren in the year 2050. The highest guaranteed
value for millennial keepsakes is that they will remind descendants
who those dowdy old Twistie-eating ancestors were. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
