<HEADLINE>
COMING TO A SUPERMARKET NEAR YOU: FOOD IN MULTIPACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Supermarkets are starting to look a lot like warehouse clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Multipacks, once the province of Sam's and Costco, are now
stocked in neighborhood grocery stores in every department, from
pet food to canned soup to the refrigerator cases.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first beneficiaries of bundling was the family pet.
Nine Lives began by shrink-wrapping four cans of cat food and
selling them, in the North Texas market, for 99 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that consumers would buy a certain amount of pet food
per visit,'' says Michael Mullen, company spokesman. ``If they
usually buy seven cans per visit they can grab two four-packs.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost savings, Mullen says, really go to the retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's faster to stock the four-packs on the shelves,'' he says,
``and it's faster to scan one unit than four individual cans.''
</P>
<P>
   Too, labels are less likely to tear, and cans packed together
are less likely to get dented, meaning that fewer items have to be
discarded or marked down.
</P>
<P>
   A year after it introduced the packaging, Nine Lives sells all
27 of its varieties in four-packs only. Although it all sounds like
retailing and consumer convenience, Mullen does say that one upshot
of the multipack packaging is that his brand is taking market share
from other cat-food brands.
</P>
<P>
   It was only natural for Nine Lives' parent company, Starkist, to
move the bulk-packaging concept to its tuna line. After all, 70
percent of all supermarket shoppers buy canned tuna. Because it's
such a pantry staple, it's logical to offer it in three-packs.
</P>
<P>
   Product popularity was also the reason that Campbell has been
offering its chicken noodle and tomato soups in four-packs. Both
soups, along with the company's cream of mushroom soup, rank in the
top 10 sellers in U.S. grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offered 12-packs of soup as a short-term promotion in the
fall for Y2K. The promotion was in response to trade requests to a
lot of other people in the (grocery) business,'' says John Faulkner
of Campbell Soup Co. ``It was a short-term thing that we don't plan
to continue right now.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the company is offering four-packs of its chicken
noodle soup and its tomato soup in some national markets.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt's is selling its tomato soup in four-packs, and Chef
Boyardee is bundling its canned ravioli into six-packs. Because
they're canned, both products make bulk sense. But look in the
refrigerator case, and you'll find a product that might be
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury's is selling its Poppin' Fresh refrigerated biscuits
in four-packs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've surveyed consumers to find out how often they use
refrigerated biscuits, and they way overestimate how often they use
them,'' Pillsbury spokesman Marlene Johnson says. ``They do that
with a lot of products they like. So we figure if we offer them in
multipacks, and they've got them in the refrigerator, they'll use
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Total gross UPC rankings of grocery products
</P>
<P>
   1. Coke Classic, 2-liter bottles
</P>
<P>
   2. Starkist tuna
</P>
<P>
   3. Campbell's chicken noodle soup
</P>
<P>
   4. Pepsi Cola, 2-liter bottles
</P>
<P>
   5. Coke Classic, 12-packs
</P>
<P>
   6. Campbell's tomato soup
</P>
<P>
   7. Kraft Macaroni &AMP; Cheese
</P>
<P>
   8. Private label bottled water
</P>
<P>
   9. Diet Coke, 2-liter bottles
</P>
<P>
   10. Campbell's cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
