<HEADER>
A4150 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DATA-COMPRESSION-     01-12 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DATA-COMPRESSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER DIGITAL IMAGES IN SMALLER FILES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
(mk) 
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer science may seem like mathematics to outsiders, but to
real mathematicians it is closer to basic arithmetic than it is to
the higher mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   But computer science is discovering that sophisticated math can
be very helpful in one of the most important and potentially
lucrative Web activities: the delivery of images and audio signals.
The math is needed for the compression of big files into smaller
files that take less time to download.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most anticipated compression technologies for images,
JPEG 2000, uses a set of math functions called ``wavelets.'' Using
waves to describe repetitive areas of an image is a standard part
of compression. Instead of all the ones and zeroes to represent
each spot of dark or light, for instance, the formula for a wave
can provide the information for repetitive variations, making it
possible to reconstruct the image with a much smaller pot of
digital data.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, most image compression systems used cosines,
familiar to most former high school trigonometry students. Both the
JPEG and MPEG systems, common today in digital cameras and digital
satellite systems, model a picture as a combination of several
cosine waves.
</P>
<P>
   The wavelet approaches also model the image as the combination
of a number of different waves, but they rely on a wider variety of
more complicated waves. Having a larger selection means that fewer
waves can do a better job of describing an image.
</P>
<P>
   Some new compression programs select particular waves that work
best for particular subjects. A picture of a text document, for
instance, has many sharp, high-contrast edges outlining the
letters. Sharply varying waves do a better job in modeling the
photo, so they also do a better job in compressing it. A photo of a
cloud-filled sky, however, has many subtle variations in blues and
whites. Smoother waves often produce smaller compressed files in
those cases.
</P>
<P>
   The original JPEG format, named after the Joint Photographic
Experts Group, which developed it, emerged in 1988. The same group,
made up of both academics and industry representatives, decided to
update the format using some of the latest wavelet research in
1995. When the group set a schedule that would produce a new
standard file format in 2000, it chose the name JPEG 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The wavelet software also uses what is called multiresolution
analysis to do more complicated compression. The first step is to
compress the whole photograph without paying much attention to
details. Then the program measures the quality of that
approximation and devotes more time to analyzing the regions that
are rendered poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a photo of mountains and a perfectly blue sky. The first
round of the multiresolution wavelet compression would do a good
job of modeling the sky, which has little detail, but it would fail
to capture all the detail of the mountains' majesty. The algorithm
would then reanalyze the lower part of the picture at a greater
resolution while ignoring the top part.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, multiresolution analysis is responsible for the
great success that many are reporting with the trial versions of
the JPEG 2000 format. The older JPEG format simply broke up each
image into 8-by-8 blocks of pixels, which was quite wasteful when
the sky turned out to be a 100-by-100 block of blue.
</P>
<P>
   The German company Luratech is a major contributor to the JPEG
2000 committee and is also trying to develop more advanced
solutions that it might keep proprietary. At this time, the JPEG
2000 group suggests that Part One of the standard will be available
free but Part Two can contain proprietary technology protected by
patents. Anyone who wanted to use the more advanced solutions would
need to negotiate a license.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Luo, director of marketing for the U.S. branch of Luratech,
said the company had already developed a proposed Part 2 extension
of the JPEG 2000 algorithm that identifies text and uses a special
wave for those regions. ``It separates the document into text and
image regions,'' she said, ``and it compresses the image using a
standard wave and the text region using a bitonal compression
algorithm. You can get 200-to-1 compression rates and keep the text
legible.''
</P>
<P>
   Segregating the free and patented parts of the format is a
challenge for the JPEG 2000 committee. Many Web developers are
frustrated by the fact that part of the popular GIF format is
protected by patents, and some Web designers are moving to a
royalty-free version known as PNG, for portable network graphics.
</P>
<P>
   The committee must tread a fine line. If the format has too many
patented pieces and requires too many license fees, no one will
adopt it. But if it is too open, the companies that paid for the
research behind the standard will not get any revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The JPEG 2000 format also promises to take new steps to address
the concerns of copyright holders. It will include two mechanisms
for adding tags that designate an image's ownership. One solution,
referred to as a ``license plate,'' will attach a number to each
image. That will help copyright holders track the use of the image
and collect royalties. JPEG 2000 will also allow invisible
watermarks to be embedded in an image. The watermarks will remain
even if an artist transfers the image to another document by
cutting and pasting.
</P>
<P>
   The JPEG 2000 standard will encounter plenty of competition.
There are already dozens of wavelet-based tools for special
applications on the market. Apple's Quicktime software, for
instance, lets the user add many extra algorithms, including ones
based on even more mathematical notions, like fractals.
</P>
<P>
   Still others wonder if there will be that much gain. Several
independent observers who posted their thoughts on the Internet and
the bulletin board Slashdot.org noted that an intelligent user
could coax better performance out of the older standards. One
poster on the Net commented that JPEG 2000 would succeed just
because it combines an acronym with a good history with an
up-to-date suffix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1720EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
