<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4152 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE13-COX     01-12 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So far, weathering winter has been easy for plants
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Jan. 16.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get it out of the way, right upfront; altogether, now,
There's no global warming. Having said that, I must add: There's a
whole lot of Atlanta warming. Ask the orange.
</P>
<P>
   It and much else in my garden have reflected what some experts
insist is a warm blip in our long-term weather pattern. The blip
meant that, despite a cold snap here and there, January arrived
wrapped in green leaves that used to be gone. Or at least browned.
Before the blip.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a couple of roses bore green and reddish foliage,
confusing winter with spring. In my herb pots, sage, parsley and
society garlic all seemed to feel so young _ greening on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, jutting from the base of the brick wall where it has
naturalized, grows old fennel, which was cut back to nothing a few
months ago. By the beginning of the year, however, it had risen to
become something again, coppery and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The chrysanthemum just refused to go away, still green after all
these months. Bloomless by New Year's Day, but still green. And the
banana shrub, which usually feels obligated to show the burn that
proves it's growing out of its range, remained as green as if it
were in Florida. Why not? It certainly has felt like Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Or Charleston. Or Savannah. Which is why the creeping fig vine
that I've been growing on the brick wall for years has reached its
greatest height ever; it's three bricks shy of the top. In past
times, it died to the ground in late autumn or early winter,
returning in the spring to start over in its effort to scale the
wall. If this Atlanta warming keeps up, this could be the year.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many gardeners, I have mixed feelings about these warm
times. El Nino, La Nina _ call them what what you will. Sure, I
enjoy piddling around the garden in shirt-sleeves when I know the
season ``should'' demand heavy wear. It's seductive in a tropical
kind of way to go outside and dig a hole, when you know the ground
might be frozen in ``normal'' years. To dream that the fig will
make it to the top.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, I don't quite feel right; there's something
out-of-sync about this excess of fine weather. Yes, at this writing
in January's second week, there's plenty of time for bitter cold to
bite, for heavy snows to sock us in. But so much warmth for so long
already has skewed my expectations. What is normal these days? What
bears embracing? What should be rejected?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing raises these questions more than the orange.
</P>
<P>
   Winters ago, I stopped moving a whole lot of plants indoors for
the winter, outside for the spring. What goes out must stay out, I
decided, reaching the point where time and energy were more
important than proving I could keep every geranium alive forever.
</P>
<P>
   So, last spring, when I put the orange outside, I was saying
goodbye. It wasn't easy, as I had started this common, unhardy tree
from seed of an after-dinner piece of fruit more than a dozen years
ago, in Washington, moved it to Atlanta and pruned it carefully to
its height of 4 feet, with a trunk the diameter of a walking stick.
It produced no fruit, never even bloomed, but it always stood as a
vivid reminder of the magic that comes when a seed touches dirt.
Despite our history, I decided to let it go _ in the interest of
paring down. Simplifying.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the calendar turn from summer to autumn to winter, I
felt a little of what Eskimos must have felt when they set the old
people on the ice to die.
</P>
<P>
   But the orange didn't die.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it weathered the cold snaps, a few leaves burning from
deep green to light olive color. Still, it hung on, proving its
perseverance each time its mottled green-and-gray trunk showed
lively lime when I scratched it.
</P>
<P>
   The orange was still around when the calendar flipped to
January. Imagine. Ever since then, I have bounced between hope that
it will survive winter and resignation that this old friend will be
gone come April. A couple of nights, I've even been on the verge of
bringing it inside, thinking a tender tree so determined deserves a
little help. Resisting, I decide its tough will is its own reward.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of my garden's eerily persistent greenery, the
orange faces life-and-death uncertainty, its fate hanging on the
vagaries of weather in our time of not global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May's Gardening Life column appears every other week in the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution Home and Garden section.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
