<HEADER>
A4154 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION1     01-12 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mecca of galleries, restaurants rich in history
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSWELL, Ga. _ While the search for gold brought Roswell's
founder to North Georgia in the 1820s, it was with water and cotton
that Roswell King made his fortune. Traveling through Cherokee land
that now makes up Roswell, King noticed the abundant water supply
from Vickery's Creek, a tributary of the Chattahoochee River, and
envisioned it as a source of power for a textile mill.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   From King's dream sprang a robust local industry in the form of
the Roswell Manufacturing Co., incorporated in 1839. The successful
company turned out cloth, tenting, rope, flannels, yarn and
woolens, including the famous Roswell Grey used in Confederate
uniforms. From the mill village, the community of Roswell emerged
and became one of the most important manufacturing towns in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Roswell's rich history is evident in its many magnificent homes
and churches. Bulloch Hall, the antebellum home of President
Theodore Roosevelt's mother, was built in 1840. The Greek Revival
structure, with its graceful columns, has been described as one of
the most significant houses in Georgia. Open daily for tours, the
home hosts exhibits and special events year-round.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith Plantation Home also offers visitors a peek at the
19th-century life of a well-to-do family. Here you can see the
original furnishings and outbuildings of 1840-1880.
</P>
<P>
   King's vision of a thriving community lives on in Roswell.
Visitors taking in the town's historic aspects can also find a
little shopping mecca in what locals call the heart of Roswell.
This area, which takes up much of Canton Street from Woodstock Road
to the north and Magnolia Street to the south, offers an eclectic
blend of antique and gift shops, art galleries and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the lovely houses lining the section of Canton
Street leading to the commercial area are now home to day spas,
architects and doctors offices as well as restaurants and shops,
you'll also notice that many residential properties remain. Folks
not only shop and work in the district, but many also call it home.
</P>
<P>
   As part owner of Ann Jackson Gallery and a member of the
merchants' association, Valerie Jackson has seen her share of
changes in historic Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got almost 30 years under our belt,'' she says. ``This
is part of the original 1840s shopping district. This area where
our gallery is _ and Fratelli's Restaurant and Heaven Blue Rose
next door _ used to be the Roswell Motor Co. back in the 1920s,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you wander to the rear of the gallery, you'll find a
door leading to the back of the building, and below are a handful
of working garages still in business.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street at Go With the Flow, shoppers can outfit
themselves for the thrill of white-water rafting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider ourselves the rogues of the area, since
historically this has been an antique and restaurant type of
shopping district,'' says owner David Schubert.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find antiques here, unless you count the building
itself. However, what you will encounter are more than 350 canoes,
kayaks and rafts, along with a variety of outdoor gear.
</P>
<P>
   Wander two doors down into Calico Quilter, and you'll find
notions, fabric and anything else needed to make a quilt _ even
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quilting is very popular right now. It's a very pleasant craft
and has a strong American tradition,'' says Ellen Jennings, Calico
Quilter's co-owner.
</P>
<P>
   For Sara Stadler who moved to Roswell last year from the Midwest
to be near her family, the historic district is now her stomping
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to come out here about once a week,'' she says. ``It's
so relaxing just to walk around, look in the shops and stop for a
bite of lunch. And the merchants are so friendly and gracious here.
It's just like the Southern hospitality I've always heard about.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From I-285, take Ga. 400 north to Exit 6
(Northridge Road). Bear right off the exit, crossing over Ga. 400.
Take a hard right onto Dunwoody Place. Turn right onto Roswell Road
and cross the Chattahoochee River. (Roswell Road turns into Atlanta
Street.) One mile down is the historic town square. Continue on
Atlanta Street and bear left onto Canton Street, and you'll be in
the heart of Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most businesses are open 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays. Several stores are closed Sundays and Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free. On-street parking and parking behind some
stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Located in the Historic Roswell Convention and
Visitors Bureau, 617 Atlanta St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are wheelchair-accessible.
Plenty of sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: The Historic Roswell Convention and Visitors
Bureau is open 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; 10 a.m.-4 p.m.
Saturdays; noon-3 p.m. Sundays. 770-640-3253.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a taste of southern France in the old South, stop by
Pastis Restaurant and Bar (936 Canton St., 770-640-3870). Snag one
of the tables on the balcony, and you can enjoy Salade Nicoise
($7.50) and Mussels Mariniere ($6.95) as you look down on the
milling crowds. Open for lunch and dinner daily.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fratelli di Napoli (928 Canton St., 770-642-9917)
doesn't offer lunch, try to stick around fearly dinner at
this exceptional Italian restaurant. Don't miss the rigatoni with
vodka sauce and wild mushrooms ($14) or veal Genovese ($18)
smothered beneath artichoke hearts, tomatoes, roasted peppers and
mushrooms. Note that all orders serve two or more, but half-orders
are available. Opening later this month, Asher restaurant (1085
Canton St., 770-650-9838) makes its home in a refurbished
blue-and-white Victorian built in the 1890s. Look for a four-course
prix fixe dinner menu ($39) Tuesdays-Saturdays and a three-course
prix fixe menu ($29) Monday evenings. The menu will change daily
according to what's available, but the sample winter menu includes
grilled scallops with warm potato salad, creme fraiche and caviar;
lobster wrapped in savoy cabbage and accompanied by a creamy
lobster broth; and fillet of beef poached in consomme with
chanterelles and horseradish cream.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bulloch Hall. Located at 180 Bulloch Ave., the antebellum
Greek Revival home of President Theodore Roosevelt's mother, Mittie
Bulloch, is open with tours on the hour from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m.
Mondays-Satur-
</P>
<P>
   days and from 1 to 3 p.m. Sundays. Admission is $5 per person
($4 per person for groups of 20 or more); $3 ages 6-16.
770-992-1731.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roswell Founders Club in the Old Bricks. Built in 1840 for
employees of the Roswell Mill, the Old Bricks are among the oldest
apartments in the United States. After extensive renovation, the
place is now used for social, cultural and business entertainment.
Luncheons for groups of six or more may be arranged. 65 Sloan St.,
770-992-4120.
</P>
<P>
   Shop talk
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of shops in the heart of Roswell:
</P>
<P>
   Antiques, collectibles
</P>
<P>
   King Galleries, 854 Atlanta St.
</P>
<P>
   Moss Blacksmith and Antiques, 1075 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Mulberry House Antiques, 1028 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Roswell Clock &AMP; Antique Co., 955 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts, home decor
</P>
<P>
   American Sampler, 959 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton Blossom, 944-B Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Eclectic Finds Home Accessories, 1159 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Fiddle-dee-dee, 944-C Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Sowers Pewter, Crystal &AMP; Gifts, 963 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandlery, 950 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Victorian Dreams, 944-A Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Art Galleries
</P>
<P>
   Ann Jackson Gallery, 932 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Gallery V Ltd., 10 Elizabeth Way
</P>
<P>
   Heaven Blue Rose Gallery, 934 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Raiford Gallery, 1169 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty shops
</P>
<P>
   Calico Quilter, 14 Elizabeth Way
</P>
<P>
   Cast-on Cottage Yarn Shop, 1003 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Go With the Flow Sports, 4 Elizabeth Way
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Flowers, 969 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree Salvage/Fabulous Fabrics, 970 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   ReRuns Fashion Boutique (consignments), 1066 Canton St.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
