<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ASTRONOMY-SPACELIFE13     01-12 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONOMY-SPACELIFE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARE WE MARTIANS? SCIENTISTS SAY LIFE MAY HAVE ORIGINATED ON MARS
 &HT;    Eds: This story includes the separately skedded ASTRONOMY-FUSE,
which is scratched.
 &HT;    730&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Life may have appeared on the Earth when microbes were
hurled from Mars aboard debris kicked up by crashing comets or
asteroids, an international team of scientists reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   During the first 500 million years of the Earth's existence, as
many as 50 billion Martian meteoroids probably fell to this planet
under conditions that would have allowed bacteria from the red
planet to survive the trip, the scientists calculated.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether life ever existed on Mars, but early in its
history it appears to have had a warm atmosphere and an abundance
of surface water.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the calculations _ which one of the scientists
admitted may be something of an intellectual exercise without
immediate importance _ was to lay out conditions necessary for the
interplanetary or interstellar spread of living forms.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the history of the solar system, so many comets and
other bodies were colliding with planets that debris was being
exchanged frequently, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, earthly life forms may have been transported to Mars by
the reverse route, the scientists reported at the annual meeting of
the American Astronomical Society here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life spreads very fast,'' said Swedish scientist Curt
Mileikowsky. ``Even if life did not form on Mars, the probability
of life forming on Earth and going to Mars and then coming back is
actually quite high, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mileikowsky said, life on Earth could have been
hurled to Mars, where it might have flourished. Then a cataclysmic
collision could have wiped out life on this planet by causing the
oceans to evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it might have been blown back to Earth from Mars after
the water rained back down out of the atmosphere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chances that life forms could have spread to the Earth from
another star system are far smaller, but even that would have been
theoretically possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mileikowsky was leader of the scientific team, which also
included scientists from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, as well as researchers from France, Germany and
Finland. The scientists, from widely different fields, set out to
determine:
</P>
<P>
   _ How well and for how long could colonies of microbes survive
in the harsh environment of interplanetary or interstellar space?
</P>
<P>
   _ How frequently are large rocks ejected from planetary surfaces
in cosmic impacts that do not overheat them and thus kill bacteria
that may exist within them?
</P>
<P>
   _ What is the likelihood that a meteoroid from one planet
collides with another planet?
</P>
<P>
   One type of stress that would threaten the survival of Martian
bacteria would be the sudden and massive acceleration caused by the
initial impact by comet or asteroid. The scientists calculated the
amount of acceleration that would be required to hurl pieces of the
Martian surface out of the planet's gravitational grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments in which common Earth bacteria were literally fired
from a gun showed that they could survive that kind of jolt,
Mileikowsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Another hazard would be the harsh radiation of space.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments conducted by NASA show that when two species of
common Earth bacteria _ ``deinococcus radioduranus'' and ``bacillu
subtillis'' _ were left unprotected in space for six years, a small
portion survived.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists calculated the amount of heat the interplanetary
``ejecta'' would endure because of collisions or high-speed flights
through an atmosphere and concluded it was likely some of the rock
would be heated to no more than 212 degrees Fahrenheit _ a level
below which some Earth bacteria have been shown to endure.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first 500 million years of the solar system's history,
the number of collisions that might generate conditions that could
have moved life between the Earth and Mars have dropped off
drastically, Mileikowsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 5 billion meteorites from Mars reached the Earth
under conditions that could have supported life during those 4
billion years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists calculated that the likelihood that life from a
different solar system could have survived a ride to the Earth on
planetary debris was approximately one chance in 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In another series of reports during the conference, scientists
described ``fountains'' of extremely hot gases that surround the
Milky Way, the galaxy in which the Earth is found.
</P>
<P>
   Observations with the Far Ultraviolet Spectroscopic Explorer
show the gases are blown out of the galaxy by exploding stars at
extreme temperatures and pumped in gigantic clouds above the flat
plane of the galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting from 5,000 to 10,000 light years into
intergalactic space, the clouds slow down, stop and rain back into
the galaxy, where they likely form the raw material of future
stars, said astronomer Blair Savage of the University of
Wisconsin-Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
