<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COURT-GRANDPARENTS13-     01-12 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-GRANDPARENTS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUSTICES SEEM SKEPTICAL OF GRANDPARENTS' VISITATION RIGHTS
 &HT;    Eds: Inserts 11th graf with timing of decision.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY JR.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Supreme Court justices seemed skeptical
Wednesday about laws guaranteeing child visitation rights as they
heard a case brought by a Washington state couple seeking a bigger
role in their grandchildren's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mark D. Olson, representing the grandparents, Jennifer
and Gary Troxel, argued that it would be in the best interests of
Isabelle, 8, and Natalie, 10, be able to visit their grandparents
more often.
</P>
<P>
   Olson said that if the grandparents were allowed to play a
bigger role in the girls' lives, the memory of their deceased
father would be preserved, and they will know kinship and where
they came from.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Catherine Smith responded that parents are in
the best position to decide what's best for their children and who
they can visit, and the courts should give parents that freedom as
long as the children are not being harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our society, parents decide who their children are going to
be with, what TV shows they watch and what candy they eat,'' Smith
said. ``We should not take that right away from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the justices expressed doubts about the Washington
law the Troxels cited in their suit. The broadly worded law allows
visitation rights if the visits are in the child's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be in the best interest of a lot of children to be
taken from their parents, but parents have rights,'' said Justice
Antonin Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor and several others said the ``best
interest'' argument would make it possible for anyone _ relative or
not _ to petition the court for visitation rights.
</P>
<P>
   Olson responded that the argument has been used in 48 states for
more than 40 years, to determine similar cases, and that it should
apply to this one.
</P>
<P>
   Some justices who criticized the Washington law, including
Stephen G. Breyer, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and John Paul Stevens, also
acknowledged the ``special relationship'' between some grandparents
and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A decision in the case is expected by summer.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' father, Brad Troxel, committed suicide in 1993, and
their mother, Tommie Granville, who is being sued by the Troxels,
has had custody of them. Granville limited the time the children
could spend with the Troxels, leading to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a trial judge decided that the grandparents should be
allowed visitation one weekend per month, one week during the
summer and four hours on each of the girls' birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Washington Court of Appeals reversed the visitation
order, saying that ``nonparents lack standing to petition for
visitation, unless there is a pending custody proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, the Washington Supreme Court struck down the
visitation law, saying the state could not interfere with parents'
fundamental rights in raising their children when there is no proof
that the children are being harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
