<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Jan. 13, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first widespread snow of the season in the Northeastern
states will fall from northern Pennsylvania to central and southern
New England as strengthening low-pressure streaks eastward south of
Long Island. The steadiest snow will streak from northeastern
Pennsylvania early Thursday morning across central New England at
midday. Snow will be mixed with rain and sleet near the southern
New England Coast and Long Island during the morning and midday,
but the precipitation will change to snow later in the day before
ending. The greatest accumulations are expected in a narrow band
from the Catskills to near Boston where over four inches will fall.
Locally higher amounts will occur in hilly terrain and in some
east-facing coastal areas. Much colder air will surge into the
Northeast at night on gusty winds from the northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Wintry chill will cover the upper Middle West. Clouds and
scattered flurries will linger from the eastern Dakotas to the
Great Lakes States. Farther south, cooler air will spread into the
interior Southeast in the wake of a cold front.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably mild weather will prevail over the southern parts
of the Rockies and Plains where sunshine will be plentiful. A trend
toward drier and milder conditions will develop in the northern
Rockies although variable clouds and a few mountain snow showers
will linger.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pacific disturbance will bring rain and mountain snow to
the northwest. The heaviest rain is expected near a low pressure
center as it approaches the southern Oregon coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Clippers
</P>
<P>
   Clipper is the nickname for fast-moving low-pressure systems
that dart across southern Canada and the northern United States
during winter. The name comes from the sleek mid-19th century
sailing ships that traveled at great speeds. Because of their speed
and lack of moisture along their paths, snowfalls with clippers
typically are no more than a few inches. Heavier accumulations can
occur near the Great Lakes and the Northeast Coast, where
additional moisture can be gleaned. In most cases, the light to
moderate snows that accompany clippers are followed by a surge of
arctic air.
</P>
</TEXT>
