<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4167 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DSL-INTERNET-ART-     01-12 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DSL-INTERNET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 RULES OF DSL: LOCATION, LOCATION, CONFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
(EDS: Optional sidebar at end of 2nd take) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT9, NYT10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Measured against other struggles that throw a family into crisis
_ war, disaster, control of the television remote control _ the
trials and tribulations of ordering DSL service may not loom large.
But it has been a bit of a tough time recently for Peggy Stout and
her three adult children, all members of one family, to be sure,
but not all able to get fast DSL connections for their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do not own computers _ 60 percent of the population _
may laugh. People who are just getting dial-up modems may smile.
But bandwidth envy is real enough, and there is a DSL stampede
nationwide. Ms. Stout and her children are in the middle of one in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, some people have been able to hook up to DSL
service with ease, while others have had miserable experiences.
Many other home computer users are facing the same problems and
trying to figure out who can get the service, which telephone
company or other kind of company to go with, how DSL service works
and when it will be available.
</P>
<P>
   DSL, which stands for digital subscriber line, delivers fast
Internet connections to homes and businesses over ordinary
telephone lines. It first came on the market in a big way early
last year, competing with cable and satellites in the rush to offer
high-bandwidth Internet connections. The competition has been
fierce, and Time Warner's cable operation was one of the things
that made it attractive to America Online, Time Warner's
prospective owner.
</P>
<P>
   But while cable television providers generally offer, or don't
offer, cable modem service in broad service areas, and satellite
links are widely available, DSL service is spottier.Your phone
company may provide it, but you may not be able to get it. And that
has confused consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for DSL is easy to understand. Web sites are
increasingly crammed with images and plug-ins that consume great
gulps of bandwidth and can tie up a dial-up modem seemingly
forever. And many e-mail files are loaded with bandwidth-greedy
images, video clips and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed is king _ speed is everything,'' said Steve Dimmitt,
vice president of consumer marketing at SBC Communications, whose
subsidiaries include Pacific Bell, Ameritech and Southwestern Bell.
``And that's why broadband in the home is more and more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Downloading data via DSL is anywhere from 8 to 100 times as fast
as with the fastest dial-up modems, depending on the type of DSL
service. Pieces of data travel over the same copper line that is
used for voice transmissions yet do not interfere with voice
conversations, which means that you can make or receive calls on
the same line you are using to connect to the Internet. Unlike
cable modem service, where neighbors share a line, DSL service
gives each customer a dedicated line, which makes the speed
fluctuate far less and can make the connection more secure. Basic
DSL service costs about $50, roughly comparable to cable modem
service.
</P>
<P>
   But getting DSL service can be tricky. In the flood of
advertising on the part of DSL companies, little mention is made of
the fact that if you live more than 17,500 feet (a little more than
three miles) from your phone company's closest central office, you
cannot get DSL service. That is because the signal rapidly weakens
with distance.
</P>
<P>
   If you call your local phone company to inquire about DSL
service, the phone company first checks to see if the nearest
central office has been upgraded to offer digital service. Then it
checks to see if your home or business is within 17,500 feet of the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Do not assume that this is a calculation you can make on your
own. Even if you get in your car and measure the most direct route
to the switching office, the distance you get is likely to differ
from the number the telephone company gets. What matters is the
actual length of the wire, which can take a circuitous route to
your house.
</P>
<P>
   DSL is just getting started in many areas. Among the nation's
30,000 central phone offices, 4,300 were equipped for DSL as of the
end of September, according to TeleChoice, a consulting firm in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz McCormick, an analyst at the Yankee Group, said there were
300,000 residential DSL subscribers and 1.1 million cable modem
subscribers at the end of 1999. The number of residential DSL
subscribers is expected to grow to 900,000 by the end of 2000.
McCormick, by the way, recently tried and failed to get DSL service
at his home in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies are trying to engineer a way around the
three-mile problem faced by many of the country's homes. But for
now, said John Britton, a spokesman for Pacific Bell, ``if you're
beyond the three miles, you're basically out of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a vexation, to be sure. Back in the 20th century, no one
thought to inquire about the distance to the nearest phone company
central office when purchasing a home or renting an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stout, who bought herin the Hollywood Hills in Los
Angeles last year, certainly didn't. When her son, Peter Black, 48,
an entrepreneur who lives 15 miles to the west, got DSL service
without a hitch in 1998 and told her how wonderful it was, Ms.
Stout began to covet it. She figured that getting it would be a
snap. ``I'm living in the middle of a hip, affluent neighborhood,''
she said. ``Ninety percent have computers, and many work in the
studios.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the phone company checked the line, she got bad news:
no service. Ms. Stout is still trying to determine whether that is
because she is too far from her local central office or because
that office has yet to be properly equipped. ``It's definitely a
disappointment,'' she said, but remained philosophical. ``It's not
the end of the world, but it's very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter Amy Corral, 34, who lives a few blocks away, has
also been unsuccessful in her attempts to get DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   Another daughter, Susan Black, 46, a graphic designer who lives
about 10 miles west of her mother, in west Los Angeles, got a bit
further. She signed up with a company called Flashcom, a DSL
provider that is one of dozens of new companies competing with
regional phone companies. But after many phone calls and a visit
from a Flashcom technician, Ms. Black was finally told that her
phone lines needed work and that she should hire a private
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had three different entities I was dealing with,'' said Ms.
Black, referring to Flashcom, Pacific Bell and Covad
Communications. Covad leases a separate copper line from phone
companies, then supplies it to Flashcom, which in turn sells the
DSL connection, along with Internet access, to each customer. ``It
wasn't coordinated at all,'' she said. ``I got the feeling that
they were not prepared for the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, while still in the throes of her ordeal, Ms. Black was
walking her dog and spotted a truck from GTE, a local phone
company, on a service call. She stopped to ask the technicians
about DSL service, and they persuaded her to order it from GTE,
which is the Los Angeles area's second-biggest local phone carrier.
She did. The installation was trouble-free; she was hooked up Dec.
30.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are below the magic threshold of 17,500 feet, you
could face other hurdles. Once the phone company has established
that you live close enough to the central office, the company must
check the line itself to see if it can handle DSL. The potential
impediments are devices that can be found on the phone lines
leading to your house called load coils and bridged taps, which let
phone lines serve more customers.
</P>
<P>
   DSL Customer service is another source of frustration for
subscribers and would-be subscribers. Phone companies and other
companies offering DSL need hundreds of customer service
representatives to handle the flood of inquiries and service
requests, so they are retraining and hiring workers. The result of
the shortage of trained personnel has been a multitude of mix-ups
and messes.
</P>
<P>
   John Bailin, a writer who lives in Brooklyn and works out of his
own office in Manhattan, said it had taken several weeks before
Bell Atlantic returned his call to say he could get DSL service at
work. So Bailin canceled an order he had already placed with
Flashcom.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bailin called Bell Atlantic to set up an installation
date, he was told that he could not get service after all. ``I got
a sense of complete disorganization,'' he said. A home installation
by Flashcom, on the other hand, went smoothly. Partly because of
his annoying experience, Bailin is now considering working from
home and may not renew his office lease.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Simpson, a Web site builder who lives in Brooklyn, also
ordered DSL from Flashcom. But when Bell Atlantic checked the line,
Simpson was told that he was too far from the closest central
office.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, Simpson moved six blocks to the southwest,
and his hopes soared when he heard that neighbors had DSL service.
He called a DSL company called Internet Connect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weeks went by and finally I called and harassed them enough to
actually talk to me,'' he said. An appointment was finally set up
for Bell Atlantic to check the line, but when technicians
repeatedly failed to arrive, Simpson gave up. Now he makes do with
a 56-kilobits-per-second modem.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the DSL problems, Ells Edwards, a Bell Atlantic
spokesman, said: ``We try to make the customer experience as good
as we possibly can. Sometimes there are miscommunications.''
</P>
<P>
   Some seasoned early adopters of new technology are impatient
with the complainers. They are quick to point out that all new
technologies are susceptible to glitchesDSL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so tired of hearing people whine about DSL horror
stories,'' said Eric Goldhagen, a technology consultant in New
York. ``DSL is a very new technology, and with that come problems
and delays in installation. The only problem is getting it
installed. After that, it seems to be very stable.'' Goldhagen
pointed out that he was referring to technologically adept people,
who, he said, should know better than to curse a technology still
in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications has a $6 billion program called Project
Pronto, which uses new fiber-optic lines and remote terminals to
extend the area that can be served by DSL The company promises to
make DSL available to 80 percent of its telephone customers by the
end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Competition could speed things up. The Federal Communications
Commission ruled recently that regional phone companies must share
lines with competitors like Covad. Companies like Covad must now
install a second phone line to offer DSL service, which increases
prices and delays.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stout, meanwhile, hasn't given up hope. She has resurrected
her application for service with Pacific Bell and has talked to
other companies, DSL but has come away more confused than ever.
``It's all baloney as far as I'm concerned,'' she said. ``I don't
even know what they're talking about. But this isn't going to
become the issue of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   DON'T TAKE NO FOR AN ANSWER, AT LEAST NOT TOO READILY
</P>
<P>
   If the prospect of ordering DSL is enticing but intimidating,
take heart. When it comes to getting DSL, a little legwork and a
lot of perseverance are likely to pay off. The first thing to do is
determine whether you are close enough to your local phone company
central office. If you are told that you cannot get service, do not
take no for an answer. The customer service representative is
likely to be still in training and could be wrong. Persist, even if
it means asking to speak with a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the definitive answer from the phone company is no, you
have an option: Call a competitor, like Covad, Rhythms or Flashcom,
or go to their Web sites. You might get lucky because on occasion,
competitors have installed DSL equipment in central offices that
the phone company itself has not yet upgraded. That is an oddity of
DSL, that competitors can set up their hardware in phone company
locations. You should also call local Internet service providers,
because many of them are now in partnership with phone companies to
offer DSL.
</P>
<P>
   If you are truly out of luck, then you will have to wait until
DSL service areas expand or new technologies overcome the distance
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some Web sites about DSL:
</P>
<P>
   2WIRE: www.2wire.com
</P>
<P>
   DSLDIGEST.COM: www.dsldigest.com
</P>
<P>
   DSLREPORTS.COM: dslreports.com/r3/dsl
</P>
<P>
   ADSL FORUM: www.adsl.com
</P>
<P>
   WHATIS: whatis.com/dsl.htm  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you can get service, call around for prices. ``Get as many
different quotes as you can,'' advised Laurie Falconer, an analyst
with Telechoice, a consulting firm in Boston. Prices from phone
company competitors will probably drop in the months to come
because of a recent federal ruling that phone companies must allow
competitors to share their phone lines instead of installing
separate lines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ By KATIE HAFNER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
