<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-RUSSIA-A-DEMOCRACY-NY     01-12 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-A-DEMOCRACY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE IS RUSSIA? WHAT IS RUSSIA? WHO IS RUSSIA? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By PAVEL PALAZCHENKO  
 c.2000 Metro International, Helsinki  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   By now, the excitement caused by Boris Yeltsin's New Year's Eve
bombshell-resignation as Russia's president has subsided.
</P>
<P>
   The experts and the pundits have had their say. The more honest
of them are admitting that they find Russia's prospects
unpredictable, but they still aren't shy about giving advice to
business and government leaders who solicit it.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, the advice offered now is a bit different from what
Russian and Western policy makers heard from many so-called experts
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In those heady first post-Soviet months, few doubted and even
fewer challenged the ``Washington consensus,'' which unreservedly
stated that Russia could achieve overnight economic success if it
followed a few simple prescriptions. It was taken for granted, of
course, that an economically Westernized Russia would not only be a
democracy but also a faithful ally of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, despite zig-zagging events, Western and particularly
U.S. leaders have been claiming their ideas and policies toward
Russia worked well _ which, some skeptics say, has meant closing
one's eyes to the failures and disasters so plentiful in recent
Russian history.
</P>
<P>
   And so today, despite an urgent desire to figure out what's
going on in Russia, there is uncertainty on the core questions
crucial to its place in the emerging world order: Who is in charge?
Is Russia a democracy? Whither its relations with the West?
</P>
<P>
   The answers to the first two questions are by no means simple
but the manner in which the handover of power from the ailing
Yeltsin to Acting President Vladimir Putin, the former KGB spy, was
accomplished speaks volumes. Rather than ``facilitating the
democratic process'' (in fact, the word democracy was not even
mentioned in Yeltsin's resignation speech), it was aimed at
clearing the way for Yeltsin's hand-picked successor while he is
riding the jingoistic wave of the military campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Russian government's virtually total control over the
electronic media and the dependence of most regional governors on
the Kremlin's good will, it is clear that what remains for the
Russian voters on March 26 is to ratify the choice made by Yeltsin
and his ``extended family'' _ the small group of compromised
officials and business tycoons whose greed is largely responsible
for Russia's current mess.
</P>
<P>
   As Lyudmila Telen, deputy editor of the weekly Moskovskiye
Novosti, or Moscow News, wrote in their special edition, ``having
appointed Putin acting president, Yeltsin in essence has appointed
us acting voters.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the March 26 election in Russia is likely to
resemble the polls held in the Central Asian republics of the
former Soviet Union or in some of the ethnic republics, where the
victory of ``the boss'' is 100 percent assured.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western commentators actually say that this ``stability''
is an inevitable and even welcome phase in Russia's ``evolving
democracy,'' or democratic evolution, depending on one's
predilection for phraseology. And the observers from various
European organizations are likely to deem the spring elections free
and fair.
</P>
<P>
   But surely this is not what most of us wanted or expected 10
years ago, nor is it the best that Russia could achieve.
</P>
<P>
   The hot topic of debate now is what policies Putin will pursue
once elected. Experts are already lining up to make pronouncements
but they have little on which to base their analysis. Putin's
recent ``mission statement'' _ an apparently well-meaning, eclectic
article about his policies and views and published on the
government's web site _ contains something for every taste.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of it (the patriotism, the need for Russia to
become competitive in the world market) could be endorsed by just
about everyone in Russia's political spectrum _ from the
pro-capitalist former Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko to the
Communist Party leader Gennadi A. Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   Very soon, however, Putin will have to show his true colors. No
litmus test will be more important than what he does and the
attitude he shows toward corruption and crime. Will Putin act as
someone beholden to the likes of the shady businessman and
political operator Boris Berezovsky, or will he take the risk of
challenging their power?
</P>
<P>
   The initial signs do not look good _ in fact it was on Putin's
watch as head of the FSB, or domestic intelligence agency, that the
books on a number of criminal investigations involving Russia's
``oligarchs'' were closed. But some believe that Putin could yet
surprise us.
</P>
<P>
   Another test will of course come in Chechnya, a test not just
for Putin but for the entire Russian society, which so uncritically
and apparently eagerly and proudly has been supporting a war in
which there will be no victors.
</P>
<P>
   So Russia is at best an imperfect or distorted democracy. Its
ruling class deserves no plaudits. As for the West, after years of
routine praise for Yeltsin because he was a good ally, does it mean
that relations with Russia are bound to deteriorate? Not
necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   There is no alternative to the policy of ``engaging Russia.''
Russia must be engaged not because it is good or bad but because it
is there. It would be wrong to call Russia nearly irrelevant, as
one Republican policy adviser recently did, just because its
``nuclear missiles are rusting in their silos.'' Even if that were
true, relations with Moscow should not be confined to the security
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the only specific bilateral issue President Clinton's
national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, mentioned in a recent
speech was to get Russia's agreement on U.S. efforts to build a
national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   What would best suit both Russian and American interests now is
a return to a wide-ranging and realistic dialogue unaffected either
by a sentimental attachment to Russia's ``democrats'' and
``reformers'' or by any residual Cold War mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Yeltsin's departure will make such a dialogue more
likely.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pavel Palazchenko is the author of ``My Years With Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze: The Memoir of a Soviet Interpreter'' (1997). His
columns have appeared in Moscow News; Metro International,
Helsinki, and other publications. During the Cold War, he published
commentary under the pen name, ``P. Vorobyev.'' He currently
teaches Russian language and contemporary politics at Colgate
University; he has also taught at Moscow Linguistic University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
