<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-APARTMENT-BRIDGE-770&AMP;     01-12 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APARTMENT-BRIDGE-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDING A ROOM IN THE AIR REQUIRES A BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seth Schulaner had a vision that would forever change
his client's life _ or at least her one-bedroom apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a bridge,'' Schulaner, a designer, said.
</P>
<P>
   He meant it. Literally. For an apartment in Chelsea, he imagined
a bridge or catwalk that would slice across the double-height
living room, connecting the upper-level sleeping area with a new
adjacent home office. As Schulaner's client, a bubbly woman in her
late 30s, recalled, ``That's when I panicked.''
</P>
<P>
   She had many plans for her new apartment. She needed an office
with a lot of bookshelves _ she works as an international human
resources consultant _ a second bathroom, significantly more
storage space and a chaise longue.
</P>
<P>
   ``All girls want a chaise,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of her daydreams, however, included a bridge. But
Schulaner, 36, got it, though not without compromise. ``In a
perfect world, it would have been cantilevered, but you can't have
everything,'' he said of the wood-floor plaster passage. A friend
of the client's for several years, he persuaded her to gut the
kitchen; she had planned to save it. The client did get her chaise
longue, though not the iron version she craved. ``Seth thought it
was too primitive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The job totaled $150,000 ``to the penny exactly,'' the client
said: $80,000 was allotted for construction, $70,000 was spent on
furnishings. ( Schulaner's fees were extra.)
</P>
<P>
   Good things may come in small packages, as any homeowner in
Manhattan knows, but this does not apply to real estate. On this
overbuilt isle, a small apartment is rarely a gem of opportunity:
awkward in proportion, deficient in natural light, more often than
not a considerable style challenge. When the client threw a
prerenovation party for 100 friends, no amount of Champagne could
detract from the apartment's mock-loft shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Guests funneled through a long, low-ceiling hall to a two-story
living area that was just large enough to provoke envy and just
high and narrow enough to give more than one person the atmospheric
jitters. Even though the living space at the time clocked in at
about 800 square feet, the effect was like crawling through a
tunnel only to end up at the bottom of a well. And the only natural
light came through a pair of sliding doors, above which,
inexplicably, floated a quartet of metal-frame windows.
</P>
<P>
   But ``it has all the variety of a home,'' the owner said,
pointing out the multiple levels, the walled garden, the
below-ground storage area. ``Since I would be working here, too, it
had an open feeling, so I wouldn't feel enclosed all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the heart of the renovation meant reducing the volume of
the living area. ``A bridge would maintain the space while
confining it,'' said Schulaner, who is an admirer of the organic
architecture practiced in the 1960s by the iconoclastic Bruce Goff.
``It's not about punching holes in walls. This is about space
evolving into a cohesive whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrow plaster uprights of the living area's built-in
storage niches connect, visually though not literally, to the
verticals of the bookcases that line the bridge above. Materials
repeat, too: birch plywood cabinets below, birch shelves above, a
birch island in the open kitchen. Another theme is tailoring. The
refrigerator is an under-counter model by Marvel; the full-size
original lives in the basement, used for large parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're paying $300 a square foot for an apartment, how
you utilize the space is crucial,'' said Schulaner, a New Jersey
native who studied design in Florida and briefly worked for Vicente
Wolf, the high priest of black-white-and-gold minimalism. ``You
have to cram in as much as you can without making it look
crammed.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explains, in part, why some elements of the client's life
_ books, china, linens _ are kept out of sight while others are
exposed, their casualness contrasting with the rigidly formatted
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The television is right out in the open, its black carcass
blending with the black granite shelf in the built-in storage space
of the living area. Compact discs are tucked into gridlike openings
in the living area's storage units. The cords of the 14
wall-mounted white-enamel lamps from Ikea openly dangle (they cost
$7 each). And the storage units are lighted by bare bulbs screwed
into old-fashioned porcelain light sockets in a sort of
retro-Edison chic.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an aesthetic for everyone. The client's more
traditional-minded family ``was horrified when they saw the bare
bulbs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schulaner shook his head and said, ``People have the weirdest
taboos.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When he decided to splurge, he bought choice items, like dining
chairs by the white-hot French designer Christian Liaigre, or
appliances specially scaled for tight spaces, like the barely
22-inch-deep Miele dishwasher. Otherwise, it was
style-on-a-shoestring all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Crate &AMP; Barrel is the provenance for the low-rise sofa, which
Schulaner upgraded with butter-cream-tone Ultrasuede. The glass
cocktail tables also are from Crate &AMP; Barrel. The leather for the
Liaigre dining chairs is from a shop on West 34th Street. ``It's
the same kind that the guys in the D.&AMP;D. use and mark up
incredibly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we hit Ikea for a lot of stuff,'' he added. The best buy?
The four over-counter kitchen cabinets, whose frosted-glass doors
gently glow thanks to interior lights. Cost: $250 each. Another
budget-conscious decision was to recycle the kitchen sink and to
work with, rather than against, the existing pipes and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Though designer and client are simpatico modernists, ``I wasn't
entirely convinced that everything had to show,'' the client said,
adding, ``What did you call it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Realism,'' he answered dryly.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for the apartment was a huge learning experience, the
client learned. ``Luckily, I had the time to tag along,'' she said.
One day the pair would visit the leather supplier. Another day
would be spent scouting sofas or dining chairs or hardware. ``For
two hours or so, we'd go looking at things,'' she said. ``It was
more of a pupil-teacher relationship. The one thing I learned was
the importance of scale. I found that fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the kitchen was done and the walls of the formerly
small enclosed room came tumbling down, she panicked again. ``The
apartment looked huge, and I thought we hadn't ordered enough
furniture,'' she said. ``As each piece of furniture was delivered,
the shape of the room changed. It put everything into perspective,
because I thought, `Oh, my God, we didn't buy enough stuff.'''
</P>
<P>
   The designer's sense of appropriate extended to fabrics, too.
``No satins, no silks, it wouldn't be fitting,'' he said. Not that
there aren't touches of luxury. For about $300, the client had Hy
Fishman, a Manhattan furrier, recycle a beaver coat into a lap robe
and matching bolster pillows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a princess, OK?'' she said with a burst of laughter. ``And
it was a very good coat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
