<HEADER>
A4193 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV18-     01-12 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY THE SISTERLY THING TO DO
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday Jan. 18)  
(nk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Madeline Armitage learned that her sister Bee Hogan was
leaving the hospital and needed special care, there was no question
who would provide it. Madeline made space for a hospital bed in her
mobile home in Windsor, Calif., and moved Bee in.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline, at 91, says she's always been the big sister and is
determined to care for 88-year-old Bee ``until I fall on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy work. Madeline moves slowly but determinedly,
cooking meals and making sure Bee takes her medication. ``Best
nurse I can find,'' says Bee.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline says they don't do much but ``get through the day.''
Yet it's obviously important to both that they do it together. Bee,
who has cancer, sleeps when she can, and Madeline says, ``When the
patient naps, the nurse naps.'' They have help from hospice, but
most of the work falls to Madeline who begins the day bringing a
warm wet washcloth to Bee and then starting breakfast. Usually tea
and toast.
</P>
<P>
   After all the years it comes down to the two of them plus a
third sister, Alice Finnegan, who is 86 and lives in a nearby
convalescent home. Before Bee got sick, she looked after Alice,
visiting her every Sunday. Now Madeline takes care of Bee.
</P>
<P>
   Bee and Madeline sit and reminisce about old vacation spots,
family dinners and their childhoods in San Francisco. Both are
widowed and neither has children. Madeline miscarried three times
in the first five years of her marriage, and Bee's son died of
polio when he was 12 years old. He got sick at dinnertime and died
in the night. It was two years before polio vaccine became
available, says Bee, a fact that still makes her cry.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline is practiced at her big sister role. When she was 10
years old, her mother was sick in bed for a year with rheumatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised to take care of the others,'' she says. ``We were
always a clanny bunch, together a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Madeline made hats for a living and then became a nurse,
``specializing in geriatrics of all things,'' she says, referring
to its usefulness now. She got out of nursing because, she says,
``I couldn't stand the pressure of losing patients,'' and worked in
a department store. ``Ladies lingerie _ we called it the
meatpacking department,'' she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Bee was a waitress most of her working life.
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters try to keep it light. They watch a little TV.
Bee reads her Unity Church ``Daily Word'' book and the Reader's
Digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laugh more than we cry,'' says Bee. Asked what it means to
live to the year 2000, Bee answers, ``I could care less,'' and her
sister chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   They don't talk much about death, although Madeline says ``You
never know when you go to bed if you're going to be here tomorrow
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   They both have made funeral arrangements, and Madeline plans on
going to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   She had a preview once. She was in an accident in 1980 when the
car she was in slid off the road and tumbled 125 feet, landing in a
gully and throwing Madeline into the brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of my body for a long time looking down at the whole
scene, and then I came back. You tell people that, and they think
you're crazy. But I believe that will happen to me again, and then
I'll go to heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other place is too darned hot,'' says her sister.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a pretty ordinary life for both, they say. They had
some great years when Bee and her husband, William, lived in a
cabin and Madeline and her husband, Clinton, would come for the
summer. They had different tastes. Bee liked night clubs. Madeline
liked the theater.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have a life plan. ``We just lived and here we are,''
says Madeline.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline says her only regret is she never got to Niagara Falls
or to Illinois, where her husband was from.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally they disagree. Regarding women's equality, which
was a new concept when they were girls, Bee says, ``I believe a
woman should have as much say as a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Madeline says, ``I think some women go too far. I like the
distinction of being a lady. I never wanted to be the counterpart
of my husband. I believe in the same pay for the same job, but I
liked having a man open the door for me, pull out my chair and look
at me like he idolized me.''
</P>
<P>
   They agree on most things. Madeline says, ``the world used to be
a lot simpler,'' and Bee adds, ``people used to be more sociable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I think you feel more like a stranger in a sea of strange
people.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason to have someone you've known all your life
bringing you tea and toast.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
