<SLUG> BC-MODEL-AMERICAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE COURTS JUSTICE, ONE MATCHSTICK AT A TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Justice hasn't always been forthcoming in
Mirsad Malkoc's life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he and his family fled Travnik, Bosnia, just ahead of
the war's deadly grasp. The family left a home with two gardens, a
swing beloved by their 5-year-old daughter, and rabbits, chickens
and the pet dog. They boarded a bus for Germany and tried not to
look back.
</P>
<P>
   Almost eight years later, Malkoc still pursues justice a little
each day. In his three-bedroom Fort Worth apartment, he has built a
sort of monument to his hopes, matchstick by matchstick, mimicking
the curves and angles of a Texas landmark: the Tarrant County
Courthouse in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Malkoc's finely wrought replica is 3 1/2 feet long, 2 feet high
and 2 feet deep. It's made of approximately 50,000 matches and has
more than 300 plastic windows. All the matches have been lit and
blown out, blackening their tops and giving the courthouse a
striped design.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the artwork sits on a table in the small living room,
obscuring the fireplace and vying for attention with the flickering
television.
</P>
<P>
   Malkoc loves his matchstick buildings _ he's halfway through the
Dallas County Courthouse right now _ but he'd like to make a living
from them, and regain for his family the financial security they
lost since fleeing their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give lifetime guarantee,'' he says, smiling and sweeping a
hand in front of his merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Malkoc first saw the Tarrant County Courthouse less than a year
ago, when he and his family arrived in Fort Worth from South
Dakota. Something about the architecture spoke to him. ``I like
history, I like culture,'' he says. ``I like Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned downtown on several occasions to sketch the 1895
building from various angles. He poked through archives for
photographs to copy and take home. He used only a handful of basic
materials: tweezers, an X-Acto knife, glue, paper and matches.
</P>
<P>
   Malkoc's four children, ages 5 to 17, think the sculpture is
``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never get to first base doing something like that,''
says Alex Brensike, a friend of the family who took Malkoc on his
first tour of downtown Fort Worth. ``It's amazing. He's so
meticulous.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Bosnia, the Malkoc family settled in Cologne,
Germany. Anica Malkoc resumed her career as a nurse. Mirsad,
formerly a machinist, went to work in a friend's restaurant. There,
he designed his first matchstick sculpture, a replica of the diner.
His reproduction of a European castle later sold for 7,000 German
marks, Mirsad says. (That's about $3,600 today.)
</P>
<P>
   The family has not been so financially lucky since coming to the
United States in 1997. Anica, whose English is rudimentary, cannot
yet earn her nursing certification and works in a nursing-home
kitchen. Mirsad, 48, who had a good job for eight months in a South
Dakota meat-packing plant, developed serious back problems. The
family moved to Texas a year ago for his health, but his physical
limitations have made it difficult for him to find work.
</P>
<P>
   So he returned to his matchstick hobby, toiling on the
courthouse every day for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, he would like to see his project end up in a public
space _ such as inside the real courthouse. ``Somewhere,'' says
12-year-old daughter Dina, ``where he can visit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Malkoc has his eye on the Denton County courthouse next. And
when he can afford fancier materials, he's eager to attempt the
White House and the Capitol building _ symbols of the justice his
new country might yet offer.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
