<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ANDYKAUFMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BIOS BRING ANDY KAUFMAN INTO CLEARER FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lost in the Funhouse: The Life and Mind of Andy Kaufman'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Zehme &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte, $25.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy Kaufman Revealed!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Zmuda with Matthew Scott Hansen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, $24 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kaufman was so weird that he imitated Elvis Presley BEFORE
ELVIS DIED.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that. Consider that this was also a man who was a firm
believer in transcendental meditation AND who sang the ``Mighty
Mouse'' theme on ``Saturday Night Live'' _ AND took an entire Radio
City Music Hall audience out for milk and cookies after a show AND
botched his career by insisting on wrestling women, even when it
became apparent that most of America found said wrestling
spectacularly unfunny.
</P>
<P>
   Was he a complex guy or just a troubled nut job who came up with
some great groundbreaking anti-comedy before imploding his career?
A genius or a troubled soul who retreated into a world of fantasy
at a young age and never came back?
</P>
<P>
   No one knows. But whatever he was, Kaufman is now a genuine big
deal all over again: lionized in song by R.E.M. and the subject of
a Milos Forman biopic, ``Man on the Moon'' starring Jim Carrey,
Kaufman is also the subject of two new biographies, ``Lost in the
Funhouse: The Life and Mind of Andy Kaufman,'' by Bill Zehme, and
``Andy Kaufman Revealed!,'' by his old pal Bob Zmuda (with help
from Matthew Scott Hansen).
</P>
<P>
   My advice to anyone interested in the man? Read both. This may
sound like overkill, but both books are so interesting _ and so
different stylistically and in point of view _ that reading both
never feels like an exercise or a chore.
</P>
<P>
   Zehme is a well-known journalist and the author of ``The Way You
Wear Your Hat,'' a fascinating study of Frank Sinatra's life and
style. ``Funhouse'' is every bit as readable; Zehme writes with a
verve that is rare among biographers, sometimes letting the prose
go into a voice reminiscent of Kaufman's own speech patterns. His
is a more true biography, with more info on Kaufman's life and the
perspective of people around him.
</P>
<P>
   Zmuda, on the other hand, provides a fly-on-the-wall view: He
was Kaufman's pal and partner in crime. Zmuda's book is also nicely
loose in style and portrays daily life with Kaufman _ which appears
to have been at once exhilarating and disquieting.
</P>
<P>
   Reading both books together is rewarding because of the
differences in point of view, and how much emphasis is put on
different events in Kaufman's life. And, truly, Kaufman's strange
and ultimately sad life warrant such close examination: That
neither effort really solves the mystery of how far Kaufman was
taking the joke (or if he even knew where the line was between
funny and merely obnoxious) makes both books (and Kaufman) all the
more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   We can examine this guy's life all we want, and interview as
many old cronies and former cast members as we would like, but the
lurking truth is that nobody will ever really know what was going
on in Kaufman's mind _ that it may have been a territory that
defied understanding, even by him.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
