<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SEXUAL-THEATER-REVIEW     01-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXUAL-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER REVIEW: MAMET? INNOCENCE? PERVERSITY HAS CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Mamet's work doesn't generally elicit feelings
of nostalgia. Still, when Deborah and Danny, the briefly coupled
characters in his comedy of manners from the 1970s, ``Sexual
Perversity in Chicago,'' go to bed together shortly after they meet
(they arrange a dinner date afterward), the play, even with its
wicked humor and gleeful vulgarity, creates a strangely innocent
aura. In 1975, when it was first performed in New York, this
one-act was shocking in its portrayal of the war between men and
women as played out between 20-somethings in Chicago. The
selfishness and suspicion, the fornication as foreplay, the extreme
ungentleness with which the four characters _ two men and two women
_ assault one another's self-esteem (and undermine their own)
constituted a vicious satire of a world run amok with
permissiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Time goes, though, doesn't it? In the straight-faced revival
that opened last night at the Atlantic Theater Company in Chelsea _
coupled, as it was a quarter century ago, with Mamet's youthful
homage to Beckett, ``The Duck Variations'' _ the play recalls a
post-sexual-revolution, pre-AIDS era in which there wasn't much at
risk from profligate behavior  &UR; except &LR;  self-esteem. Which, in
retrospect, doesn't seem like much at all. And as a result,
``Sexual Perversity'' _ in this production anyway _ seems more of
an entertaining period piece than anything else, an almost campy
artifact that would fit right in on ``Nick at Night'' if it weren't
so ``Midnight Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Presented on Alexander Dodge's multitiered set, which manages to
contain and economically suggest half a dozen separate rooms, the
play uses brief, jittery scenes separated by blackouts to follow
the consummation and subsequent courtship and breakup of Danny and
Deborah as witnessed by their best friends. These are Bernard, whom
Danny works with in a warehouse office, and Joan, the roommate
Deborah leaves and then returns to when she moves in with and then
out on Danny.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard and Joan are the angrier pair. He is a vulgar sexist
prone to explosive rants against the behavior of women, though he
is equally ardent in admiration of their body parts; she, a
schoolteacher, is prematurely bitter and prone to take out her
frustrations on her preschoolers. Their bilious influence
eventually reclaims the friends they were in danger of losing to
love, leaving everyone energetically miserable at the end.
</P>
<P>
   In the service of this story, the young actors are reasonably
deft with Mamet's peppery rhythms (and salty language). The women
seem period-perfect, managing to capture the 1970s-style of
feminism, which found all manner of young women trying on newly
encouraged postures of self-empowerment. Kate Blumberg plays
Deborah as someone in the midst of trying to transform a perky,
pliant girl into a tougher young woman with indignation at the
ready, and Kristin Reddick, as Joan, finds the note of loneliness
that makes her man-weary, world-weary posture transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Gregg (Bernard) and Josh Hamilton (Danny) _ perhaps
because the dynamic of their relationship (boastful leader and
marginally more sensible follower) is familiar in any generation _
have a harder time suggesting the era. Gregg actually brings a bit
of 1990s detachment to the role of Bernard, an anachronism that
doesn't help a character whose most salient feature is excess;
Bernard's wild story about making love to a girl turned on by a
military combat fantasy remains the play's most famous and funniest
set piece. Still, anyone who fondly remembers wide striped ties,
spread collars and polyester pants will feel instant camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic is celebrating its 15th anniversary with a
seasonful of early plays by Mamet, one of the company's founders.
(``The Water Engine'' and ``Mr. Happiness'' were presented in the
fall; ``American Buffalo'' is scheduled for a March opening.)
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Duck Variations,'' which introduces the evening, will
be of interest particularly (if not exclusively) to followers of
the playwright's career. It is something of an anomaly in Mamet's
work, a series of seemingly benign conversation snippets between
two old men on a bench looking out over Lake Michigan. The
recurring subject is ducks _ their lives, their deaths _ and in the
end, of course, the conversations suggest something both desperate
and satisfying about the lives of the men themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The play, written when Mamet was in his early 20s, winks
appreciatively, even gratefully, at Beckett. But the competitive
banter between the two old men also foreshadows Mamet's later
persistent probing of abrasive male relationships. Held against
Mamet's other plays of this type _ ``American Buffalo'' and
``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' for example _ this is a trifle, but it is
daunting for actors. Peter Maloney and John Tormey manage to
sustain both the tension and humor of a friendship that must endure
without much to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Production Notes:
</P>
<P>
   SEXUAL PERVERSITY IN CHICAGO and THE DUCK VARIATIONS
</P>
<P>
   By David Mamet; directed by Hilary Hinckle; sets by Alexander
Dodge; costumes by Rick Gradone; lighting by Robert Perry;
production stage manager, Darcy Stephens; general manager, Bardo S.
Ramirez. Presented by the Atlantic Theater Company, Neil Pepe,
artistic director; Ms. Hinckle, managing director. At the Atlantic
Theater Company, 336 West 26th St., Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: In ``Duck,'' John Tormey (Emil) and Peter Maloney
(George); in ``Chicago,'' Josh Hamilton (Danny), Clark Gregg
(Bernard), Kate Blumberg (Deborah) and Kristin Reddick (Joan). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
