<HEADLINE>
`MY MOVIE BUSINESS' IS AN INSIGHTFUL INSIDE LOOK AT FILMMAKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE KASKOVICH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My Movie Business'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By John Irving &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memoir &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $19.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turning a lengthy novel into a two-hour movie is a process of
elimination. A screenwriter must decide which scenes can be
sacrificed without gutting the novelist's tale.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tough task, rarely completed to the satisfaction of the
author. Unless, of course, the author is also the screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   In ``My Movie Business,'' John Irving relates his 13-year effort
to turn his 1985 novel, ``The Cider House Rules,'' into a feature
film. His odyssey encompassing four directors and ATQ0Z ATQ0Z
+++`fw1vs &QR; TQ
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
