<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPLANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PUBLIC FOUND TO HAVE UNREALISTIC VIEWS OF IMPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ A panel of 14 independent scientific and legal
experts called on the federal government Wednesday to develop an
information clearinghouse on medical implants so that patients can
be better informed about the lifespan of the devices and possible
complications that might arise.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations about the risks, benefits and lifespans of medical
implants are often unrealistic, the advisory panel concluded in a
20-page report delivered to the National Institutes of Health
(NIH).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Julia Weertman, co-chair of the panel and a materials
science professor at Northwesteersity in Evanston, Ill.,
said there is widespread misperception among consumers about the
durability of implants.
</P>
<P>
   ``People never think that they are going to wear out,'' she told
a news conference. Manufactured items implanted into the body
``don't last forever,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Wulf, president of the National Academy of
Engineering in Washington, D.C., said consumers should be advised
that, in general, a medical device could be expected to last
between 10 and 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to misperceptions about durability, consumers often
are unaware implants can spark medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Brandt, panel co-chair and a professor at the
University of Oklahoma Health Sciences Center, Oklahoma City,
Okla., said many people mistakenly believe that a seal of approval
from the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), the government agency
with responsibility over medical devices, means that implants are
trouble-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the sense that if the FDA approves it, it's going to
be perfect,'' Brandt said.
</P>
<P>
   Breast implants, for example, can cause serious local
complications such as painful hardening of the breast. In addition,
some models leak either saline or silicone solutions, requiring
repeat surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been implanting medical devices for over 40 years.
An estimated 25 million U.S. citizens _ 8 to 10 percent of the
population _ currently have some type of implanted medical device.
</P>
<P>
   There are three categories of implants:
</P>
<P>
   __ Form-enhancing implants, such as breast implants either for
cosmetic purposes or following breast cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   __ Life-saving implants, such as pacemakers and artificial heart
valves, which help regulate the functioning of a heart.
</P>
<P>
   __ Life-enhancing implants, such as an artificial hip, which
allow a patient better mobility and improved quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Implants are big business. In 1997, $49 billion was spent in the
United States on more than 65,000 different types of medical
devices made by almost 12,000 manufacturers, according to the
General Accounting Office, the congressional investigative branch.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's report called on the NIH and FDA to help develop an
Internet Web site to provide information on medical devices and how
they have performed in the past. In addition, the Web site should
urged scientists to ``retrieve'' the implants ``when they are no
longer of use.''
</P>
<P>
   This would enable researchers to develop a detailed database on
how well the devices perform. This data could lead to the
development of better, longer lasting medical implants. There are
now no systematic programs for the retrieval and analysis of
implants, the panel concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Implant retrievals, either after surgery or autopsy, are only
conducted on an ``ad hoc basis'' by manufacturers and some
university research centers, the panel found.
</P>
<P>
   The panel proposed that implant recipients receive a card to
carry in their wallets or purses, much like an organ donor consent
card, outlining the type of implant, make, model, serial number and
date of implantation. It would function as implant donor consent.
</P>
<P>
   The panel noted other barriers to the establishment of a
national implant retrieval system include not only the cost, but
fear of litigation for manufacturers, hospitals and doctors, and
the religious objections of patients and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's recommendations are advisory and are not binding for
NIH.
</P>
<P>
   NIH officials had no immediate reaction to the panel's report,
but in a statement the scientific agency agreed that researchers
need a better system for analyzing implants after removal in order
to develop improved models.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of such as system has impeded research in this
area,'' NIH said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail at:
eric &LR; hearstdc.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
