<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, Jan. 13. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOODSICK (Phoenix) - The greater Phoenix area has nearly three
times the number of illnesses caused by tainted food and water than
a community of this size should have, Maricopa County's top health
official says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The causes could be any one of a million things,'' ranging
from improperly cooked meals in homes or businesses to people not
washing their hands before they cook or eat, said Dr. Jonathan
Weisbuch. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN _ (Phoenix) Generations from now, palientologists
will look back in awe and envy at the events of January, 2000, when
journalists digging in the petrified muck near 19th Avenue and
Washington Street stumbled upon a living, breathing specimen from a
category of pre-historic beings long thought to be extinct. She was
immediately identified has a fully-preserved example of Crackpotus
Fanaticus, a small but vigorous sub-group of the genus and species
Numbskullus Politicus which thrived for a time in the area of the
Arizona State Capitol. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the
``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
</P>
