<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCAR-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCAR VEGAS': SHE STOLE HIS KIDNEY AND OTHER BAD LUCK TALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``For Ken Saro-Wiwa,'' reads the dedication of ``Scar Vegas,''
Tom Paine's arresting first collection of stories, ``Nigerian
writer and activist hanged for our insatiable oil gluttony Nov. 20,
1995.'' The ``our'' is presumably the United States or the West in
general, since Paine is identified on the dust jacket as a graduate
of Princeton and the Columbia master of fine arts program and as a
teacher of creative writing at Middlebury College.
</P>
<P>
   So we're into colonialist oppression here, and immediately one's
antennae go up for any ideological bias in the book's 10 stories,
which appeared in The New Yorker, Harper's, The New England Review
and Playboy, among other magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the opening piece, ``Will You Say Something,
Monsieur Eliot?'' is about a wealthy American whose yacht is
wrecked in a storm during a single-handed sail. After drifting with
part of his mast for days, he is picked up by a boat full of
Haitians whose sails have been destroyed by the storm. They are
ecstatic to learn that Eliot is a rich American because they are
naively certain that with him aboard they will all be rescued under
orders from the president of the United States. But when a
helicopter finally arrives, only Eliot is taken away and the
Haitians are left to go on drifting.
</P>
<P>
   Another story, ``The Hotel on Monkey Forest Road,'' concerns a
construction crew assigned to build a hotel complex on Bali. One of
the crew's leaders goes ``local'' and insists on appeasing the
area's spirits before construction begins, much to the detriment of
the project. The story's narrator leaves the question open about
whose outlook is correct.
</P>
<P>
   In the powerful final story, ``The Battle of Khafji,'' a bus
driver is mistakenly assigned to a reconnaissance platoon ``sent to
Saudi shortly after Saddam entered Kuwait,'' the narrator says.
After proving himself more able than anyone expects, the driver
asks: ``Is it still a war if nobody dies on one side? . . . I mean,
if thousands die on one side, and nobody at all dies on the other,
is that still a war? Maybe we should have a new word for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the stories, several of which have won prizes, can be
viewed as variations on the theme of how the powerful oppress the
weak. This even includes ``General Markman's Last Stand,'' about a
retiring Marine commander stealing a bra from the local post
exchange. In the story the general's fetish is paradoxically made
to stand for his humanity, whereas those who ridicule his weakness
come off as brutal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what impresses the reader about Paine's stories is not so
much their ideology as their extraordinary variety and narrative
verve. In each of them, the author immediately establishes an
extreme situation that rivets your attention, whether it is the
plight of Melanie Applebee, an out-of-work brokerage executive who
suddenly finds herself a derelict in ``A Predictable Nightmare on
the Eve of the Stock Market First Breaking 6,000,'' or the twin
brothers in ``Ceausescu's Cat,'' who struggle with their feeling of
being invisible in totalitarian Romania.
</P>
<P>
   In each story Paine shows himself to be a master mimic, whether
he is detailing the shipwreck in ``Will You Say Something, Monsieur
Eliot'' or parroting the cool dude language of the druggies
traveling to the Anarchist Convention in Portland, Ore., in ``The
Spoon Children,'' or doing the drawl of Johnny Loops, fresh out of
prison in Galveston, Tex., as he attends his sister's wedding in
``Scar Vegas.'' The message, however ideological, is rarely the
point. The issue in ``Unapproved Minutes of the Carthage, Vermont,
Zoning Board of Adjustment (As Recorded by Town Secretary Betty
Bradley)'' is whether station WIKD's 250-foot communications tower
is causing people to get cancer, appliances to malfunction and
rock-and-roll music to sound in people's teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it's corporate America versus the people. But a
sense of outrage isn't what carries the story along. Rather it's
the droll contrast between the townspeople's hysteria and the
deadpan language of the recording secretary: ``The oral cavity,
Cato noted, seemed to amplify the music, particularly in the
presence of saliva. The experience was not unlike having an
interior Walkman, and it would not have been a painful experience
except that he was a fan of bluegrass music and rock-and-roll made
his teeth ache.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Paine goes over the edge in the title story, ``Scar
Vegas,'' which was reprinted in ``The 1998 Pushcart Prize XXII.''
Having left his sister's bridal suite because, as the prospective
groom tells him, ``Fruit is in heat,'' Johnny wanders down to the
hotel lobby, meets a semipro football player and falls into a
discussion with him over what constitutes luck. `` `Luck ain't
something that don't happen,' I says. `Lots of things don't happen.
Luck is something that happens. When you been fingered out.'''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting a woman in a bar who is ``10 times better looking
than any woman who ever looked at me twice in my entire life,''
Johnny wakes up in the hospital to find that his kidney has been
surgically removed. His friend tells him he had found him in the
bar ``all messed up'' and complaining that his back hurt and took
him to the hospital. A doctor tells Johnny he has seen three
similar cases this year: ``On the black market your kidney might be
worth a hundred thousand or more. Some people are desperate. . . .
Consider yourself lucky to be alive, Loop. They might have taken
both kidneys.'' After admiring the scar on his back Johnny falls
asleep imagining ``over and over them fingering me, Johnny Loop,
out of all the crowds of nobodies and losers.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Paine saying here that nothing is safe from American
gluttony? Maybe so, but as an image of exploitation, stealing
Johnny's kidney seems so bizarre as to transcend ideology. Finally
it is the author's fervent imagination that rescues most of the
stories in ``Scar Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SCAR VEGAS'
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paine
</P>
<P>
   215 pages. Harcourt Inc. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
