<HEADER>
A4218 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-12 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE PREPARE BACK-UP FORCE TO DEAL WITH DIALLO TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MELISSA GRACE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The police have arranged for back-up security
forces if needed at demonstrations outside the upcoming Amadou
Diallo trial and backed away from a statement last week that
bullhorns would be banned.
</P>
<P>
   Chief John C. Nielsen said Tuesday that the police have not yet
made a decision regarding the use of bullhorns by demonstrators on
both sides of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the sound became so loud that it interfered with the rest
of the community, then we would deal with that issue at that
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief also said that if the number of demonstrators for the
trial grows into the thousands, he may call for assistance from the
Albany County Sheriff's Department and State Police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at all the contingencies,'' Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection in the case is set for Jan. 31 at the Albany
County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen said it was too early to predict what numbers of
protesters may arrive for the trial, and predictions from various
sources have ranged from very few to thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is a 300-mile round trip from New York City and
because the weather may turn cold, law enforcement officials are
predicting that the turnout will be low. Nonetheless they are
making plans for larger demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, 22, who was black, was hit by 19 out of 41 shots fired
by four white police officers in the vestibule of his Bronx
apartment building on Feb. 4, 1999. The officers said they opened
fire when they thought the unarmed street vendor was reaching for a
gun.
</P>
<P>
   The racially charged case _ which drew widespread protests in
New York City last winter and spring _ was transferred to Albany
last month by a state appeals court, which ruled that media
attention on the case had been so extensive that a fair jury could
not be picked in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, each charged with second-degree murder and
reckless endangerment in the shooting, are Kenneth Boss, Sean
Carroll, Edward McMellon and Richard Murphy. If convicted, they
each face 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   If demonstrators plan to protest in Albany, they will have to
apply for a permit and the police have said that depending on the
size of the crowds, restrictions may be placed on demonstrators _
who are expected to come to support the Diallo family and the
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen had said in an interview last week that bullhorns would
be banned to keep the noise down and that if any were used they
would be confiscated. However, he said Tuesday that he had never
committed to a policy that would ban bullhorns, and said that he
had only talked about it as an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the location of the courthouse, in the midst of an
area that has both residences and businesses as well as ... other
courtrooms, the people that are conducting their lives and
business, separate and uninvolved with Diallo, have a right to a
normal day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief also said that restricting protesters to Academy Park
in downtown Albany was also only an option under consideration, but
that no final plan had been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep the streets open ... if we try not to negatively
impact the streets, the most likely spot in close proximity to the
courthouse to put thousands of people is in that field,'' he said
referring to the park.
</P>
<P>
   A local activist who plans to be involved in the protests said
that her group wants to meet with Mayor Jerry Jennings and Nielsen
to see if they would be allowed to use bullhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a right to free speech,'' said Vickie A. Smith,
spokeswoman for the Capital Region Justice for Diallo Committee.
``We can exercise that in many ways, with signs, silently, or we
may also have bullhorns. We do not want to have that restriction
place on us. If we are peaceful and orderly that is the most
important thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
