<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Jan. 13 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Ned Kilkelly (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-POLICE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday
that flight at the mere sight of a police officer could often, in
the context of other factors, be such suspicious behavior as to
justify a stop-and-frisk search by police. Although all nine
justices agreed with that broadly stated view, the court split 5-4
on how to apply it to the facts of a Chicago case in which a man
bolted at the sight of a convoy of police cars. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NH-VOICES (Madbury, N.J.) _ In more than 50 interviews, voters
here were hard pressed to come up with a nagging issue upon which
they would select their candidate. Instead, in a contrast to four
or eight years ago, when voters were bursting with worries about
the economy, this year they seem relatively content. That leaves
them the luxury of tuning their political antenna on the personal
attributes of the candidates, their spouses, their parents and, in
case of Al Gore, their bosses. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Ankara) _ Responding to European pressure and
hoping to end a civil conflict that has shaken this country for 15
years, Turkish leaders decided on Wednesday to postpone executing
the country's most prominent rebel leader until a European rights
court has heard the case. The prisoner, Abdullah Ocalan, who
directed a guerrilla war aimed at winning more rights for Turkey's
Kurdish minority, was convicted of treason in June and sentenced to
die. Wednesday's decision means that he will probably remain alive
for at least a year. The decision may accelerate Turkey's move
toward membership in the European Union, which has become a
transcendent national goal. European leaders have urged Turkey not
to execute Ocalan. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokyo) _ More than any previous event in a history
full of serious mishaps, the nuclear accident in Japan last fall
rattled the coalition between industry and government that has long
made Japan the world's most ambitious user of nuclear energy.
Strikingly, in a country known for its political quiescence, the
sharp movement of public opinion against nuclear power has taken
the form of a genuine groundswell. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-GAYS-MILITARY (London) _ Left with no other choice after
a sweeping ruling by a European court last fall, the British
government announced Wednesday that it would no longer bar openly
gay men and women from serving in the military. The new policy,
which at a stroke ends Britain's decades-old practice of subjecting
gay men and women in the military to intrusive personal
investigations and dishonorable discharges, brings Britain into
line with most other NATO countries, including France, Canada and
Germany, all of which allow openly gay men and lesbians to serve in
armed forces. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   ENCRYPTION-EXPORT (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
substantially relaxes export controls on technology related to
computer encryption. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
</TEXT>
