<HEADLINE>
IT'S DIFFERENT THIS TIME AS ROE FACES WADE IN TRESPASSING CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Roe was there and so was Wade, facing each other across
a nearly empty courtroom and the chasm of a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything was different this time. Jane Roe was still
Norma McCorvey but Wade was Kristin, the Dallas Country criminal
court judge who bears the name of her legendary father-in-law,
former District Attorney Henry Wade.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was still abortion, sort of, but rather than being in
court to pursue a monumental legal precedent, Roe was in Wade's
court to defend one of the country's most ardent anti-abortion
activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference Jesus makes,'' said the Rev. Flip Benham,
who was on trial for yet another charge of misdemeanor trespass.
</P>
<P>
   McCorvey filed the lawsuit, styled Roe vs. Wade, nearly 30 years
ago that led to the 1973 Supreme Court decision that legalized
abortion. The district attorney she sued has long since retired,
but both his namesake son and daughter-in-law now serve on the
bench in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The two famous names were fated to be linked again when Benham's
case, stemming from a June 1999 charge of trespassing while
picketing a Dallas abortion clinic, was assigned to Kristin Wade's
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems more than a little ironic,'' Benham said during a
recess of the trial, which is expected to end Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As he picketed clinics across the country and sought souls to
convert, Benham never thought he would bag the biggest trophy of
all _ the woman who bulldozed the legal barriers to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But, in July 1995, she reversed her position on abortion and was
baptized by Benham in a backyard swimming pool the following month.
She has since started her own ministry, the church of No More Roe.
</P>
<P>
   With a handful of other witnesses, Roe filed into the courtroom
Wednesday afternoon, raised her right hand and was officially sworn
in by Wade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll get to testify or not,'' she said,
waiting in the corridor as the trial began. ``I hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, she has no quarrel with Wade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met her,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
