<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, in rebate item, name spelled Hrdy is cq.)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOO MANY PERIPHERALS? CLONE THAT USB PORT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Universal Serial Bus has made life easier for Macintosh and
PC users, giving them an easy way to connect monitors, scanners,
digital cameras and other devices to their hearts' content (up to
127 peripherals, at least in theory). While some devices can be
daisy-chained, saving USB port space on the computer, many users
find that the two ports commonly found on many computers are
quickly used up.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to buy a hub, and Belkin Components of Compton,
Calif., showed off a new one at the Consumer Electronics Show in
Las Vegas. The device is called the Bus Station and retails for
about $100. The basic unit consists of a stack of four modules that
add seven USB ports.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Bus Station particularly handy is the other
modules that can be added to the basic unit or swapped for one or
more of the basic modules. If you need more U.S.B. ports, for
example, you can buy (for $69.95) a module with four USB ports.
That can be added to the basic unit, or simply swapped out for a
basic module with one port (giving a net gain of three). Other
modules are for serial, Ethernet or SCSI ports.
</P>
<P>
   So if your goal is to hook up 127 peripherals, the Bus Station
can probably help you achieve it. You might have to add another
``hub'' in the basement, however, to handle the extra drain on your
electrical system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry Fountain
</P>
<P>
   A PHONE DEVICE THAT `HEARS' BY PICKING UP JAW VIBRATIONS
</P>
<P>
   So maybe you are one of those cellular phone users who is
concerned that using a phone may be hazardous to your health.
You've tried one of those earpiece-microphone combinations intended
to keep the phone away from your head, but you don't like having a
microphone dangling below your chin or pinned to your clothes.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to try a new product from EarHugger, a company
based in Provo, Utah, that markets cell phone accessories. The
device, which looks like a standard ear bud with a short stem on
it, includes a microphone that picks up sound through vibrations in
the jaw. The company says that sound quality is as good as other
more conventional hands-free sets.
</P>
<P>
   The EarHugger, which has a suggested retail price of $14.99, is
available for most major brands of phones, including Nokia and
Ericsson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry Fountain
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING YOUR PHONE DRY IN THE WILD
</P>
<P>
   What's the great outdoors without a cell phone?
</P>
<P>
   For those people who aren't shocked by that question, MDX
Industries of Newbury, Mass., has just the thing: a watertight
plastic canister for keeping your phone or other electronic device
safe during your next biking, hiking or kayaking trip.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Cell Safe, the canister is made of yellow hard
plastic, with interior foam to cushion any blows. It's big enough
to accommodate most cell phones, with a little space left over for
money, keys or other valuables. It opens like a book, and an O-ring
seal keeps out water. The device, which has a suggested retail
price of $24.99, can fit into the water bottle cage on a bicycle,
be hung from a belt or be strapped to a backpack or the top of a
kayak.
</P>
<P>
   Cell Safe offers one more advantage not listed by the
manufacturer: it will protect a cell phone from the angry campers
nearby after the phone rings and spoils their quiet evening around
the campfire.
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry Fountain
</P>
<P>
   TWO COMPANIES AGREE TO SEND SPEEDY REBATES TO CUSTOMERS
</P>
<P>
   After fielding numerous consumer complaints about rebates that
are slow to arrive, the Federal Trade Commission has reached
agreements with two computer product companies under which they
will provide more timely rebates to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements state that the companies, Memtek Products, which
sells the Memorex brand of computer disks, and Umax Technologies, a
distributor of PCs, scanners and digital cameras, must provide
checks to their customers within the times they specify in writing.
If no time is specified, the rebates must be provided within 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements stems from FTC charges that the companies
promised consumers they would receive cash rebates within 12 weeks
after purchasing specific products, but that they had failed to
deliver them until several months later.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Umax, for example, the FTC says that in several
instances, the company failed to send $50 rebates on its Astra
1220S scanner for five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to take on cases that have egregious violations of law
and touch on fundamental protections for consumers,'' said Alice
Hrdy, an FTC lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The companies agreed to the ruling out of court and with no
admissions of any legal wrongdoing, said Jodie Bernstein, director
of consumer protection at the commission. ``We want to send a
message to computer companies that these are rules they have to pay
attention to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Johnson, vice president of marketing at Memtek,
acknowledged that the company had run into trouble handling the
volume of rebate requests it had received. It has significantly
reduced the number of rebate offers as a result, he said. ``It was
a bad situation for everyone involved, but it's behind us, and
we're happy with the agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Catherine Greenman
</P>
<P>
   UPLOADING IMAGES FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE OCEAN
</P>
<P>
   Students whose interest in the ocean ended when Leonardo
diCaprio's character died at the end of ``Titanic'' may want to
tune their Web browsers to www.ocean.udel.edu/deepsea Thursday for
the first of eight live Internet classes being held from the bottom
of the sea. A University of Delaware scientist, Dr. Craig Cary,
will board the submersible Alvin and dive into the Gulf of
California, where he will talk to selected middle-school classes
and upload images to the Internet through a satellite connection.
Cary will be studying thermal vents and some creatures that dwell
there, like the Pompeii worm, an eyeless, mouthless creature that
can withstand temperatures of more than 235 degrees Fahrenheit.
Hey, nobody thought Leonardo diCaprio was going to be a big star,
either.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruce Headlam
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
