<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      01-12 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: LITERARY ADVOCATES FOR BLACK VOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the wild inconsistencies of book publishing, it should
come as no surprise that in an industry populated mostly by liberal
thinkers and based, finally, on an openness of thought and
expression, there are only a handful of black literary agents.
There is a huge growth opportunity for blacks who want to be
agents, though, because agents are mostly self-employed and do not
have to be hired by anyone but writers.
</P>
<P>
   The few African-American agents are doing well, but publishing
needs more entrepreneurial blacks and Hispanics who are interested
in books and want to represent authors. More writing by and about
African-Americans is in bookstores than ever before, and agents say
that there are many more blacks trying to get published.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises these questions: Do black literary agents face
special challenges in an industry that is ruefully almost entirely
white? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Do black agents feel a particular obligation to give priority to
black clients? The answer, if for some a subliminal yes, also has a
major caveat. The established black agents all have white clients,
and they are business people who would smash just about anyone,
regardless or race, on behalf of their writers. Black agents do not
practice apartheid agenting.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that they aren't mindful of special problems
and contradictions. Black agents say they are often overwhelmed
with unsolicited manuscripts from African-Americans who believe a
black agent would be more receptive than a white one. Black agents
welcome more black colleagues to share the load. On the other hand,
it is not uncommon for a black agent to successfully establish a
writer's career only to have the author switch to a white agent in
the hopes of getting a better deal in a white industry.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Stinson, a highly respected black agent whose office is
in Detroit, said, ``White agents have told me that the reason they
get black clients is the writer feels more validated with a white
agent, or they feel it would be stupid to leave a white agent in a
white industry for a black agent.'' But the reverse has also been
true also, she said. Ms. Stinson has gotten black clients who left
white agents, and has negotiated their biggest advances.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stinson, who is also starting a small publishing house for
Christian fiction, sells more than 30 books a year, three-quarters
of them by blacks, and has had her best sellers, including Pearl
Cleage's novel ``What Looks Like Crazy on an Ordinary Day'' (Avon,
1998). She would like to see more black editors, but she must sell
mostly to whites, ``who have been very receptive to
African-American material and really fought for things for me.''
(The shortage of black editors is acute, and it is not a result of
discrimination, but economics: Entry-level jobs in publishing have
such low salaries that few beginners without financial help can
afford them.)
</P>
<P>
   But black writers, and therefore their agents, have problems
beyond the shortage of black editors. Ms. Stinson said:
``Publishers are looking for material that can have a 100,000-copy
first printing. Few African-American commercial writers can get
that. Most are in the 30,000-to-50,000 first-copy range, a good
range to build a career on, but it looks as if many of these
authors are settling in there.''
</P>
<P>
   A breakthrough for black writers was the success in 1992 of
Terry McMillan's ``Waiting to Exhale'' (Viking), a novel about the
friendship among four black women. Previously, crossover fiction by
blacks tended to be literary: Toni Morrison, Ralph Ellison, Richard
Wright, James Baldwin. Since ``Exhale,'' publishers are more
willing to take a gamble on black popular fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Tanya McKinnon, a young black agent, has sold 13 books, ``seven
figures worth,'' in about a year and a half working in an agency
owned by Mary Evans, who is white. The recent successes of
African-American books, she said, ``shows that people of color read
and buy books, and the black market is a lucrative one; there's a
new kind of person, the multicultural person.'' She has a
parti-colored list of clients, but said, ``I'm certainly delighted
when I find a talented black writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the emergence of black agents has been singularly
important for black writers. Adrienne Ingrum, a former book editor
and publisher who is the associate publisher of The Black Issues
Book Review, said that in ``no way would there be the boom in black
books without a black literary agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Even though a lot of blacks are handled by white
agents, it was black agents who cultivated new black talent. Often
white editors and publishers don't understand the talent in the
black community, and if it isn't for black agents communicating
that culture to a very white culture, there would be a lot fewer
black books.''
</P>
<P>
   What used to be unutterable is now acknowledged: Many blacks who
were becoming agents, like many of the whites, simply were not very
good at it. The handful of prominent ones who have survived the
publishing wars _ Marie Brown, Faith Childs, Lawrence Jordan, Ms.
McKinnon and Ms. Stinson, for instance _ are respected
professionals who have earned the most necessary tool of all:
access _ the ability to pick up the phone and get an important
editor on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, a former Doubleday editor, has a client list that is
mostly black. She says that although there are many black writers
who feel more significant with white agents, ``there are just as
many who really feel they are in better hands with black agents
because of their subject matter, and our commitment to selling
publishers more diverse writing.'' But black agents are overwhelmed
with submissions from blacks who want to write, and there is a need
for more African-American agents, she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Manie Barron, a black editor at Random House, said that
curiously enough, as book publishing has become more politically
correct, discernment about the black story has lessened. ``In the
late '60s and early '70s, there were the black exploitation films,
exploiting the ghetto with stories of criminals,'' he said. ``Now
publishers want to obliterate this. Well, I came from Harlem, and
that was the reality I grew up with and most people grew up with in
the inner city. The professional people grew up with the bad ones.
A black editor or agent knows that unless you can show the dirt,
you don't get the message across.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, an agent with black and white clients, agreed.
``Publishing needs more blacks, editors and sales reps as well as
agents to come along and push the envelope to publishing places we
cannot now imagine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently he sold a book about a black woman's relationship with
her late mother. It took him 18 months to find a publisher who
thought that this black story was worth telling. White and black
editors turned it down. Finally it was bought by Jeremy P.
Tarcher/Putnam by a white editor and will be published as ``Life
Lessons My Mother Taught Me'' at the end of the month. The writer
is Andrea Young. The mother was Jean Young. The father and husband
is Andrew Young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
