<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MYSTERY-REVIEW-NYT     01-12 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MYSTERY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOUCHING EVIL': A DETECTIVE FEELS GUILTY IN HIS VERY HUMAN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Creegan isn't an inspired detective. He makes mistakes. Big
ones. And then he gets so tied up in knots over them that he's
liable to make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   Creegan is an inspired character, though, a nonhero who somehow
manages a heroic moment or two. He is at the center of the British
series ``Touching Evil,'' which returns Thursday night to the PBS
anthology ``Mystery.'' Creegan and the other all-too-human members
of the Organized and Serial Crime Unit will be tested by three
cases, each presented in two hourlong episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night Creegan, played with angst-soaked intensity by
Robson Green, is on the trail of a killer who has been preying on
young women in London while a tabloid reporter named David Laney
(James Nesbitt) pumps up the public's hysteria. Creegan and his
colleagues Susan Taylor (Nicola Walker) and Mark Rivers (Shaun
Dingwall) quickly figure out who the killer is, but even though
Creegan and Rivers corner the man with his latest victim, a college
student, they fail to thwart her death. The anguished detectives
stand, guns in their hands, as her throat is slit.
</P>
<P>
   When the guilt-ridden Creegan is confronted by the student's
father, Michael Hawkins (John Duttine), the scene offers a window
into this policeman's unsettled soul. It also demonstrates why
``Touching Evil'' transcends the usual cop drama.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by his inability to learn from the authorities the
details of his daughter's death, Hawkins asks Creegan if he saw her
die. Creegan nods affirmatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was she awake when it happened?'' Hawkins demands. ``Did she _
did she suffer?''
</P>
<P>
   Creegan cannot answer. He stares wordlessly at Hawkins, eyes
bulging as if to contain the tears. Hawkins gasps, then says: ``I
see. You know, that's the first time anyone's been honest with
me.'' In this dark world, honesty can be heard only in silence.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dark world: night and day, indoors and out; a world ever
shrouded in shadows of midnight blue, where what light there is
comes from unexpected directions. The story (script by Mike Cullen;
series created by Paul Abbott), the acting and the visual elements
(directed by Sheree Folkson; photographed by David Odd; production
design by Claire Kenny) are blended with unusual skill into a
somber concoction that holds your attention. You'll want to see how
this tale winds down.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there are pedestrian elements here. The serial killer, a nut
case named Emerson (Tony Curran), is no more than a standard-issue
New Age villain who declares: ``Nobody knows me. Nobody stops me.''
Take heed, please, that this show is not for children; it contains
nudity, coarse language and disturbing depictions of killings.
</P>
<P>
   But many grown-ups will be satisfied to note that there are
adult ideas in play. When the reporter Laney tries to seduce the
lonely Taylor, he reminds her how tightly they are both bound to
the killer, whose identity the police have not yet learned. In the
last year, ``he's taken over my life,'' Laney says of the focus of
their attention. ``You go catchin' 'im, I'm out of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of next Thursday's installment the case will be
closed, although not to the total satisfaction of anyone on the
screen. The viewer, however, can be forgiven for thinking that
things turned out rather well.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MYSTERY: Touching Evil'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Thursday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   A co-production of United Film and Television Productions and
WGBH Boston. Michele Buck, Simon Lewis and Susan Hogg, executive
producers, United; Mike Cullen and Sian Orrells, writers; Sheree
Folkson, Rachel Talalay and Alex Pillai, directors; David Odd,
director of photography; Claire Kenny, production designer; Adrian
Johnston, composer; Rebecca Eaton, executive producer, WGBH; Diana
Rigg, host.
</P>
<P>
   With: Robson Green (Dave Creegan), Nicola Walker (Susan Taylor),
Shaun Dingwall (Mark Rivers), Tony Curran (Emerson), John Duttine
(Michael Hawkins) and James Nesbitt (David Laney).
</P>
</TEXT>
