<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      01-12 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIRY ROSES  
 VISITING PRIVATE GARDENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the endnote instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I don't ask much for my new property, just a shrub that keeps
its blooms from spring to early winter in an upstate New York
climate. Someone suggested Fairy roses. I don't want an English
manicured look for my rustic Catskills cottage, but I was told
Fairy roses don't look like real roses. True?
</P>
<P>
   A. False from start to finish (although I assume you are being
humorous about the modesty of your request). Roses and cottages go
together like bagels and cream cheese. The English look _ at least
as imitated in this country _ is usually crowded, informal,
anything but manicured. And if we define ``real'' as original, or
wild, individual Fairy roses look more like real roses than the
uptight hybrid teas at the florist.
</P>
<P>
   But individual roses are not the point. This plant, which is
technically a polyantha named the Fairy, is famous for covering
itself with long, loose clusters of pale pink flowers from late
spring until hard frost. The many-petaled blossoms are small, round
in bud and flattish after they open. The foliage is dense. The
leaves are shiny and dark green. The Fairy is, comparatively,
cold-hardy and disease-resistant and has been a big seller since it
was introduced in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   But before you fall in love, bear in mind that shrub refers more
to shape than size. The Fairy usually grows no taller than 2 1/2
feet. And don't expect any fragrance. You'll get more perfume from
Carefree Beauty, a tough, generous bloomer, with bigger, darker
pink flowers on a bigger bush. And if, after all, you go for the
classic rose-covered bower beside the cottage door, try doing the
covering with Autumn Sunset, a hardy, repeat-blooming climber,
whose fragrant flowers glow apricot gold.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairy and Carefree Beauty are available at well-stocked
garden centers. Autumn Sunset can be ordered from Lowe's Roses, 6
Sheffield Rd., Nashua, N.H. 03062; (603) 888-2214; catalog, $3; and
Royall River Roses, P.O. Box 370, Yarmouth, Maine 04096; (800)
820-5830; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Private Gardens
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in New Orleans at the end of March and am
interested in visiting home gardens. Could you supply me with the
names of garden clubs or horticulture societies that I could get in
touch with? Is there a directory of such organizations to which I
could refer when I am traveling?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you're not on the Internet already, garden touring may be
reason enough to get wired _ or at least to visit a cybercafe. A
quick Web search for ``garden club tours'' yielded 25,900 entries,
and while most of them were undoubtedly dead ends, many of the
first couple of hundred looked promising. You can also go directly
to www.gardentourist.com.
</P>
<P>
   This site is a regularly updated electronic version of the
Garden Tourist, a paperback calendar-guide organized by state. It
is available in bookstores or directly from the Garden Tourist
Press, 330 W. 72nd St., Suite 12B, New York, N.Y. 10023, for
$21.95, plus $3 shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an easy shortcut to inside looks at some of the
loveliest (and most private) private gardens in the United States,
the Garden Conservancy's Open Days Directory.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit conservancy is dedicated to preserving fine
gardens all over America, and on open days visitors are welcomed
into hundreds of them. Directories are $14.95, plus $3.50 for
shipping and handling for nonmembers.
</P>
<P>
   Directories, discount coupons and membership information are
available from the Garden Conservancy, P.O. Box 219, Cold Spring,
N.Y. 10516; telephone, (914) 265-2029.
</P>
<P>
   (Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 W.
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.)
</P>
</TEXT>
