<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-REFORMERS-2000-HNS &LR;      01-12 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORMERS-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISSUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
REFORMERS BRADLEY, McCAIN REMAIN UNDER SCRUTINY ON CAMPAIGN-FINANCEBy BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston oilman Oscar Wyatt co-wrote a letter to John McCain,
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, in May 1997, complaining
about the lack of federal help in prodding the British government
to open up slots at London's Gatwick Airport for his airline
venture.
</P>
<P>
   McCain responded within days to the complaint by Wyatt and
partner Sir Freddie Laker, the owners of Laker Airways. The
powerful senator fired off a letter to the head of the U.S.
Department of Transportation asking that he send a ``prompt
response addressing the issue directly to Mr. Wyatt and Sir Freddie
Laker.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt was prompt in returning the favor, sending $5,000 in
campaign contributions from himself and the political action
committee of Coastal Corp., his Houston oil firm, according to
Federal Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions were perfectly legal and the sequence of
events just part of life in Washington, state capitals and city
halls.
</P>
<P>
   But now McCain and Democrat Bill Bradley, an 18-year veteran of
the U.S. Senate, are running for president on a crusade to cleanse
Washington of special-interest money. Because they've set such high
standards for the rest of the country, the reformers find
themselves under much more scrutiny than their rivals on the
campaign-finance issue.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have made inroads against their party's front-runners,
Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush, by portraying
themselves as mavericks who will challenge the political
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of reports recently have revealed that both men
have also played the insider's game in Congress, willing to give a
hand to contributors who want pressure applied within the
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe this week reported that Bradley had received
$500 contributions from officers of Sigma Corp., a New Jersey
company that sought his help with the Commerce Department to
resolve a trade dispute. The account was published after Bradley
challenged reporters ``to go take a look'' at whether he had ever
written letters to federal agencies on behalf of contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was recently criticized in a new report by the Center
for Public Integrity for his close ties to Wall Street and the
large amounts of money he has taken from big financial firms and
pharmaceutical companies. The report alleges that as a senator from
New Jersey, Bradley regularly pushed legislation that helped these
donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a practice,'' Bradley said Wednesday while
campaigning in Indianola, Iowa. ``I also said ... maybe there was
one (incident) out there. That was a letter on behalf of a
constituent. It said, please make a decision. It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he would help this company, which had donated to
his campaign, rather than other companies that might have needed
similar help, Bradley responded, ``There might be others there that
I've written on behalf of constituents. No, I don't think it's
wrong at all.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was questioned recently about a letter to the Federal
Communications Commission on behalf of a large Florida-based
contributor, Paxson Communications, which was seeking a television
license.
</P>
<P>
   McCain abruptly canceled a fund-raiser that was to be hosted by
the company's president after the letters were made public.
Nevertheless he still received $20,000 in contributions from the
company's executives for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To contain any damage, McCain made public more than 500 letters
he has written to the federal agencies, a majority of which, his
staff claimed, were written on behalf of individuals or companies
who were not major contributors to his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The letter written for Wyatt was included in a pile of what the
senator's staff said were communications on behalf of
noncontributors. While Wyatt gave money for McCain's last Senate
campaign, he has not contributed to his presidential effort.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal Corp.'s PAC gave $5,000 to McCain's chief rival, George
W. Bush. And Wyatt's wife, Lynn, gave $1,000 to former GOP
contender Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   A Coastal spokeswoman said Wednesday only that the contributions
are ``a matter of public record, and we will let the record speak
for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Political experts differ on the fairness of the recent criticism
of McCain and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the oldest principles of human nature is people in
glass houses shouldn't be throwing boulders,'' said Larry Sabato,
professor of political science at the University of Virginia, ``Mr.
Clean and Mr. Integrity can't live up to their Mother Teresa
image.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said the candidates invited criticism of their record by
not living up to their campaign rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are sanctimonious and play holier than thou you bring
this thing on yourself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others say it is unreasonable to expect McCain and Bradley,
who left the Senate in 1996, not to carry out what are considered
normal duties, such as writing letters for constituents, including
those that donate to their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an elected official you're expected to be a player,'' said
Thomas Mann, a political expert at the Brookings Institution. ``It
is not a matter of selling votes or acting inappropriately. It
partly comes with the territory, the expectation of what members of
Congress will do on behalf of constituents and private citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann and others still give McCain and Bradley credit for trying
to change the entrenched system.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who appears to have weathered the initial controversy,
has acknowledged that he is tainted by the current campaign-finance
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you do is under suspicion,'' he told voters
Wednesday at a town hall meeting in Milford, N.H. He had been asked
to clarify whether his intercession on behalf of Paxson was
legitimate advocacy or ``pandering to special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Arizona senator also said he was prodding a slow-moving
federal bureaucracy into action. McCain has said the two letters he
wrote on behalf of the company to the FCC did not recommend a
specific action, only ask that it move quickly on a case it had
been sitting on for two years.
</P>
<P>
   McCain then pledged to destroy what he called the ``the iron
triangle of big money, lobbyists and the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his staff believe he has weathered the controversy
although the senator responded testily when asked about
contributions from Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I raised several million dollars in that campaign,''
he said. ``I have no recollection of that. Nor do I care. I'm
getting a little weary of this business.''
</P>
<P>
   And voters who have flocked to hear McCain in New Hampshire also
appear ready to move on. Many say they accept his explanation that
he was doing his job regarding his letters to the FCC on behalf of
Paxson Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have to like it. But I understand it,'' said
Paul Amato, a 47-year-old owner of a candle factory and McCain
supporter who showed up at the senator's town hall meeting in
Milford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Alan Bernstein in Houston and Kim Cobb in
Indianola, Iowa, contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
