<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4244 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-COURT-PAINTERS-ART-2T     01-12 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PAINTERS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ART AND POWER WERE A GOOD MATCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ The 20th century's experience with the dubious
aesthetics of Fascism, Nazism and communism left several clear
lessons: works of art commissioned by governments are generally
mediocre; creativity does not flourish inside ideological
boundaries; artistic expression is by definition a kind of
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, judging by some reactions to the Brooklyn Museum of
Art's recent show ``Sensation: Young British Artists From the
Saatchi Collection,'' even the motives of private arts patrons are
not above suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   But step back a few centuries and the focus changes. Without the
``interference'' of the Vatican, the Italian principalities and the
royal courts of Vienna, Paris, Madrid, London and Brussels, among
others, Europe's artistic heritage would be a great deal poorer.
</P>
<P>
   From the 15th century to the 18th century, many fine painters
were wooed with money, security and status and in exchange spent
their time glorifying the ``ideology'' of the Roman Catholic Church
and exalting assorted popes, monarchs and military heroes. They
also produced prodigious art.
</P>
<P>
   This was certainly the case with three masters of the
post-Renaissance whose relationship with power is the subject of
``Velazquez, Rubens, Van Dyck: Court Painters of the 17th
Century,'' a new exhibition at the Prado Museum in Madrid that runs
through March 5. Each artist had his own style of painting, but
they nonetheless had much in common: their careers coincided during
two decades; they supported the Catholic Counter-Reformation;
Velazquez and Van Dyck looked up to Rubens, 22 years their senior;
and all revered Titian, who died in 1576, the year before Rubens'
birth. But what most united them was that they were first and
foremost court painters.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, Peter Paul Rubens was the most adept at juggling
patrons. After leaving Antwerp for Venice in 1600, he was promptly
hired by the Duke of Mantua. Returning home in 1608, he again
became court painter, this time to the regents of the Spanish
Netherlands in Brussels. In 1622, he accepted commissions from
Louis XIII of France and the queen mother, Marie de Medicis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1625, he was painting the Duke of Buckingham in London. Four
years later, he was in Madrid, working in the royal palace. A good
linguist as well as a skilled diplomat, he was even knighted by
both Charles I and Philip IV for his role in negotiating peace
between England and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Van Dyck, who studied with Rubens around 1618, evidently
learned more than art from his sophisticated and peripatetic
mentor. After making his name in Antwerp as a precocious young
artist with an eye to the good life, he traveled first to London,
where he painted a portrait of the Earl of Arundel, and then to
Italy, where he painted numerous oils of aristocrats and their
children as well as religious works.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a fresh stretch in Antwerp, he returned to London
in 1632 and was appointed ``principalle Paynter'' to Charles I, a
post that he held with distinction and aplomb until his death in
1641.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Velazquez, in contrast, had the least eventful career of
the three: he was just 24 when he was named royal painter by Philip
IV of Spain, and he held the post until his death in 1660. Although
he twice traveled to Italy (where he painted his remarkable
portrait of Pope Innocent X), most of his nonroyal work was done
while still a young man in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   In the palace, he was absorbed by official painting and,
increasingly, by nonartistic duties. Successively he was named
gentleman usher to the king, gentleman of the bedchamber and
finally chamberlain of the palace. No wonder that, compared with
Rubens and Van Dyck, his output was small, with fewer than 100 of
his paintings surviving today.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is Velazquez, or rather the 400th anniversary of his
birth in Seville in June 1599, that inspired this show. In theory,
the centennial might have justified a Velazquez blockbuster, but
one was held at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York in 1989
and an even larger one at the Prado in 1990. And it could not be
repeated so soon (or, who knows, ever).
</P>
<P>
   So, to follow other anniversary exhibitions, notably ``Velazquez
and Seville'' in Seville last fall and ``Velazquez in New York
Museums'' currently at the Frick Collection, the Prado invited the
art historian Jonathan Brown to organize a more modest, more
didactic show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is worth emphasizing the exploratory nature of this
effort,'' Brown writes in a catalog essay, noting that the
exhibition is designed to raise questions and provoke debates as
much as to produce conclusions. ``It is, in reality, an exercise in
comparative history, a kind of history that because of its
intrinsic difficulties is rarely attempted and even less so in the
history of art.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth centenary of Van Dyck's birth, which also fell last
year, provides additional topicality, although the Flemish painter
was amply celebrated in a major retrospective seen first at the
Royal Museum of Fine Arts in Antwerp last summer and again at the
Royal Academy in London in the fall. In fact, there was just time
for some of the Van Dycks, including his magisterial
``Self-Portrait With Sunflower'' and ``Charles I in the Order of
the Garter,'' to travel from London for the opening here on Dec.
17.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of the 44 works on display (17 by Velazquez, 14 by Van Dyck, 12
by Rubens and one copy of a Rubens), however, 14 come from the
Prado's own collection.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition itself is divided into five thematic sections _
self-portrait; monarchy; court portraits; mythology and fable; and
religion and faith _ that serve to underline what the three
painters had in common. Yet from the first room, their different
personalities become apparent. Velazquez's 1640 self-portrait _ one
of just two that survive (excluding his appearance in ``Las
Meninas,'' which is on permanent display elsewhere in the Prado) _
shows a stern man in simple clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyck's 1633 self-portrait with a sunflower captures the
dandy in him. Rubens' 1638-1640 self-portrait, with glove, sword
and elegant hat, glows with his pride at achieving social
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   The section on the monarchy dwells on military prowess, as in
Velazquez's legendary ``Surrender at Breda'' and Rubens' ``Triumph
of Henri IV.'' More space is given to court portraiture, with two
equestrian paintings, Velazquez's ``Philip IV on Horseback'' and
Rubens' ``Cardinal-Prince Fernando of Austria in the Battle of
Nordlingen,'' contrasting Velazquez's directness with Rubens'
affection for allegorical reference.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in Van Dyck's portraits, whether of Charles I or
assorted child princes, there is a lushness absent in Velazquez's
undramatic portraits of, say, Philip IV and Queen Mariana of
Austria. Here again, personality played a role: Van Dyck was eager
to flatter his subjects, while Velazquez painted what he saw (so
much so that Philip IV refused to be painted in later life).
</P>
<P>
   In the gallery dedicated to mythology and fable, the show
illustrates how Velazquez handled subjects also tackled by Van Dyck
and Rubens. Beside Velazquez's remarkably realistic ``Forge of
Vulcan'' hangs Van Dyck's almost Romantic ``Tetis in the Forge of
Vulcan.'' Versions of ``Mercury and Argus'' by Velazquez and Rubens
again contrast the Spaniard's eye for the unexpected with the
Fleming's more classical approach. And when both men paid tribute
to Titian's ``Rape of Europa,'' Rubens copied the original, while
Velazquez tucked his version into the background of ``The
Spinners.''
</P>
<P>
   Still more distinct is Velazquez's majestically simple religious
painting. Surprisingly, given Philip IV's position as a prominent
Catholic monarch, his court painter did little religious work. This
show nonetheless presents crucifixions by all three artists:
Rubens' ``Martyrdom of St. Andrew'' is full of color and movement,
with angels on high; Van Dyck's ``Christ on the Cross'' shows a
single cross standing against an almost pastoral scene, with all
the drama focused on Christ's tortured face; Velazquez's ``Christ
on the Cross,'' set against a black background, is moving in its
austerity.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if a conclusion to this show may be risked, it is that
Velazquez, seemingly the most tied-down of the three painters, in
fact exercised the greatest freedom in his approach to the themes
of his day. While Rubens and Van Dyck were engaged in meeting the
expectations of a variety of patrons, the Sevillano had only one
master to please. And, by good fortune, Philip IV was a patron who
understood the notion of artistic license.
</P>
<P>
   The entire show is of course a tribute to royal patronage.
Indeed, because of the Prado's infamous space limitations, the
exhibition is embedded in the museum's main collection, a
collection that rests heavily on the treasures accumulated by
successive Hapsburg and Bourbon monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, visitors emerging from the show on the Villanueva Palace's
main floor immediately find themselves in galleries filled with
still more works executed by Velazquez, Rubens and Van Dyck as
court painters. And if they want to organize their own virtual
show, they can even look at the Prado's wonderful Titian collection
to see how much the Venetian inspired his 17th-century heirs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
