<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     01-12 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: CHOOSING THE CORRECT WOOD FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo and a graphic are being sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to applying a finish to wood, most
do-it-yourselfers automatically reach for a can of polyurethane
varnish. Polyurethane is an ideal choice for many projects, because
it produces a hard protective film that is more durable than any
other finish. This makes it a good choice for tabletops, floors and
cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   But polyurethane does have a down side. It creates a cold, hard
glossy finish that makes wood look like it is encased in plastic.
Another problem is that it cannot readily be applied to surfaces
that are already finished. Polyurethane simply will not stick to
other finishes, not even to itself, if the film has cured. In order
to apply a coat of polyurethane, the old finish must either be
removed or roughened up with sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with polyurethane is that it tends to peel when
exposed to sunlight for long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   Varnishes differ depending on the type of resin used in their
composition. Traditional varnishes use natural gum resins, like
damar, which is obtained from conifer trees. Modern varnishes are
made from synthetic resins like polyurethane or alkyd.
</P>
<P>
   Alkyd varnish has almost the same properties as polyurethane
varnish. It is easy to apply and just as durable. Moreover, the
final finish has more warmth and clarity, so it is a better choice
for furniture.
</P>
<P>
   All varnishes have a long curing time (also called the open
time). This makes them easy to apply with a brush or rag. But this
also means that the varnish film can attract a lot of airborne dust
as it dries, making it necessary to hand rub the finish with steel
wool or pumice after it cures.
</P>
<P>
   Most manufacturers choose lacquer to finish their furniture,
because it is easy to spray on and it has a very short open time.
Do-it-yourselfers will find it difficult to spray lacquer unless
they purchase professional equipment. However, there is a brush-on
lacquer suitable for home use.
</P>
<P>
   The lacquer film is not as durable or scratch-resistant as
varnish, but it has a clarity that brings out the warmth in wood.
Lacquer has a very short open time, so you must work quickly and
methodically to create a smooth, even finish. A lacquer finish is
easy to repair because the solvent in lacquer will melt existing
layers, making it easy to blend successive coats into one another.
The potent solvent in lacquer is more toxic and flammable than the
solvents in other finishes, so you must wear proper safety gear and
work in a well-ventilated area.
</P>
<P>
   Shellac is a traditional finish that is rarely used today. It is
not as durable as varnish or lacquer and it is not resistant to
water. Liquid shellac has a short shelf life. Old shellac turns
gummy as it ages and won't harden properly on any surface. However,
it is available in flakes, which can be dissolved in denatured
alcohol (alcohol is less toxic than the solvents in many other
finishes) to make a fresh solution when you need it.
</P>
<P>
   A shellac finish, however, is warm _ ranging from almost
transparent to dark amber _ and it enhances the natural beauty of
wood. It can be brushed on, or applied with a polishing pad in a
technique known as French polishing (featured in the Home Clinic,
July 5, 1998). Shellac is a good finish for furniture and interior
trim.
</P>
<P>
   Another type of finish that has recently become available is a
water-based finish. These products are often labeled as varnishes
with polyurethane or acrylic resins, but they have different
properties than solvent-based polyurethane or alkyd varnish. They
are not as durable as solvent-based varnishes, and many woodworkers
find that the finish is often flat and dull.
</P>
<P>
   Water-based finishes are sensitive to fluctuations in air
temperature and humidity. They can be slow to cure on a humid day.
In contrast, when the air is warm and dry, they can dry too quickly
and trap air bubbles in the film. Water-based finishes can also
raise the grain in some woods and may require sanding afterward.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, these finishes clean up easily with soap and
water and the solvent is not flammable and less toxic than others,
so they are easier to work with indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are the oil finishes, like linseed oil and tung
oil. Oils must be heated so they penetrate into the wood. The heat
for a tung oil finish is best generated by applying it with a
coarse rag and rubbing hard. Linseed oil must be heated in a double
boiler (never in a pan over a direct flame). Tung oil provides a
warmer glow to wood than linseed oil does, but neither offers much
protection against wear or water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
