<HEADLINE>
FOOD RETAILER MEETING FOCUSES ON WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By DEBORAH CIRCELLI   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAINES CITY, Fla. _ Retailers are no longer just in the business
of brick and mortar. They're now also in the business of click and
mortar or what is known as e-commerce, said Bruce Peterson, vice
president and general merchandise manager of perishables for
Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet offers unlimited information and unlimited
choices to the consumer,'' Peterson told a group of retailers at a
food and citrus conference sponsored in part by the Florida
Department of Citrus. The two-day ``Selling Food in the New
Millennium'' conference focused on global expansion and the
opportunities of selling food products over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which ended Tuesday, featured speakers from
several online companies and food retailers such as Homegrocer.com,
Priceline.com, McDonald's Corp., 7-Eleven Inc. and a Japanese
consulting firm, Fujii Office, which specializes in foodservice.
The conference was funded in part by the Florida Department of
Citrus.
</P>
<P>
   John Laing, chief operating officer of Food.com, based in San
Francisco, said America Online's plan to purchase Time Warner is an
example of the Internet's importance. Laing said the Internet
provides unlimited opportunities, citing estimates that every 1.67
seconds someone new logs onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is experiencing explosive growth,'' said Laing,
whose company is the largest takeout and delivery service on the
Internet. ``It's a phenomenal way to reach people.''
</P>
<P>
   Food.com has 14,000 restaurants that participate in delivery
service through the Web site and more than 800,000 Internet members
who order food online. The site also offers listings of more than
300,000 restaurants. As far as the Internet as a whole, advertising
sales are expected to reach $15 billion in 2003, up from $2.7
billion in 1999, Laing said. Spending on the Internet is expected
to go as high as $425.7 billion in 2003, up from $67.1 billion in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-commerce is here to stay,'' Laing said. ``The time to get
online is now. Three years ago, the Amazon was a very big river in
Latin America. Today, it is the No. 1 retailer on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Stockberger, president of SBN Network, said the ultimate
marketing tool today is the Internet. SBN.com is a database of 50
million business listings, including 20 million in the United
States. The site includes the yellow pages, white pages, toll-free
numbers and Web sites. He said statistics show 4 trillion e-mails
were mailed last year compared with 1.4 billion first-class letters
mailed. More than half of all businesses in America are online and
almost 30 percent of Americans use the Internet on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more Internet users than readers of Time, Newsweek,
Consumer Reports, Cosmopolitan and Playboy magazines,'' Stockberger
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sit back and expect people to beat a path to your door,
it won't work,'' Stockberger said. ``The Web is absolutely going to
continue to grow. If you're not on it, you'll have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Circelli writes for The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla., which is
a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SILENT-MOVIE-THEATER-     01-12 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILENT-MOVIE-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THEATER WHERE SILENT FILMS GET A SECOND CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Australia)  (js) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ All Charlie Lustman wanted was a falafel sandwich.
He was driving down Fairfax Avenue, searching the passing
storefronts for a Middle Eastern restaurant he had eaten at before,
when he caught sight of a dilapidated movie theater with a for-sale
sign on the front in a faceless row of nursing homes and parking
lots across from Fairfax High School. ``My infamous falafel
sandwich,'' Lustman said, ``that ended up costing me a million
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Lustman, 34, a former songwriter who lives in Santa Monica,
Calif., is today the owner, proprietor and programmer of the
nation's only movie theater dedicated to showing silent films. The
Silent Movie Theater, which has a history as melodramatic as any of
its features, opened in November with a new screen from England, an
upstairs coffeehouse, a backyard patio, an antique projector and a
new neon sign that bathes the sidewalk in a lavender glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a day job, but it has consumed my life
completely,'' Lustman said. ``I did this whole thing on credit
cards. I have no idea what I'm doing, I'm just doing it. But
Hollywood was built on the backs of these silent-movie pioneers,
and it's something that I think needs to be appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Silent Movie Theater shows silent films six nights a week.
(Talkies are relegated to Tuesdays, and only those made before 1949
are allowed even then.) That, Lustman said, makes it the only
theater in the United State dedicated year-round to showing silent
movies. Some theaters, like New York's Film Forum, have regular
silent-movie series, but he said no other theater had a regular,
weekly program of silent classics. He had thought his was the only
such movie theater in the world but then discovered another one in
Queensland, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   For those who love silent movies, the new theater is part of a
slow reawakening. ``It used to be absolutely impossible to see
silent films in a theater, but lately it's gotten a little
better,'' said David. B. Pearson, whose www.silent-movies.com is
one of the most popular silent-film sites on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The people who kept the medium alive through the years were the
collectors, Pearson said _ not only of old films but of memorabilia
and antique technical equipment as well. Only recently, with the
advent of videotapes and now DVD, has the quality of available
films improved markedly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lustman's small theater in Hollywood _ just 224 seats _ was
built in 1942 by John and Dorothy Hampton, a couple from Oklahoma
City who moved to Los Angeles for the climate and dedicated
themselves to finding, restoring and exhibiting silent films.
Hampton, who died in 1990, hand-lettered his own posters and often
blended pools of toxic chemicals in the bathtub of his apartment on
the theater's second floor, using the mixtures to try to save
deteriorating films. In 1978, without warning, the theater closed.
</P>
<P>
   People thought the Hamptons had moved back to Oklahoma, but they
were still living above the theater, almost as recluses. In a
hidden storage room beneath the projection booth, Hampton had cans
filled with hundreds of moldering silent films.
</P>
<P>
   After he died, his wife moved into a nearby nursing home where
she befriended Laurence Austin, who had attended the high school
across the street. He persuaded Mrs. Hampton to reopen the theater,
which the two of them did in 1991. Often Mrs. Hampton, in a
wheelchair, would sell popcorn in the cramped lobby.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Mrs. Hampton signed over control of the theater
to Austin, purportedly on a cocktail napkin. Later Austin
supposedly signed a similar napkin that made his roommate and the
theater's projectionist, James Van Sickle, his partner and heir. In
1997 a young man watching a comedy short from the back row of the
theater, a crowd-warmer for the feature presentation (F.W. Murnau's
1927 ``Sunrise''), stood up, walked into the lobby and shot Austin
dead. When a 19-year-old man was charged in the shooting, the
police also charged Van Sickle with hiring him to do the job. The
pair were convicted and sentenced to life in prison. The theater
closed and fell into disrepair again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not plan to sign any napkins,'' Lustman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lustman had been living in Copenhagen for several years, he
said, writing songs for Danish artists who wanted to record in
English, but in early 1999 he tired of that and moved back to Santa
Monica. ``I was turned off by the music industry scene, but I
didn't know what to do,'' he said. ``I was searching around for
something to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So he called the number on the for-sale sign at the theater,
made an appointment and was shown into the dark, dusty space last
April. ``I immediately felt the magic of the place,'' he said. Some
of Hampton's hand-lettered signs were still on the walls, along
with caricatures of silent-film stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called some investors, rich people, friends of friends,'' he
said, and by May he was able to close on the theater, contents and
all, for $650,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Silent Movie Theater reopened in November with Chaplin's
``Modern Times.'' Business since then has been good, Lustman said,
``although I don't expect to get rich from this.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater and its coffeehouse open at 6 p.m. The show begins
at 8 p.m., always with musical accompaniment. Often experts are
brought in to introduce the films or show props or memorabilia.
Tickets are $8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just, `Come to see a movie,''' Lustman said. ``It's,
`Come and have an experience of Old Hollywood as they saw it years
ago.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesdays and Thursdays are dedicated to silent dramas. One
comic film or a collection of shorts, usually Chaplin, Buster
Keaton, Harold Lloyd or Laurel and Hardy, plays on weekends. The
offerings on ``Talking Tuesdays'' include films like ``King Kong''
(1933) and ``Captain Blood'' (1935).
</P>
<P>
   Lustman says he has received enormous support from many people
who collect or admire silent films, particularly David Shepard,
whose Film Preservation Associates has been instrumental in saving
many aging films and who has allowed the theater to show his prints
free. Yet he has also drawn grumbling from many fans and experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's collectors, some people in the silent-film
business,'' he said. ``As long as they pay their eight bucks to get
in, they can say what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson, though, said the grumblers are in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in general everybody is very happy about the theater
reopening,'' Pearson said. ``Oh, there is a perfectionist group who
wish it was exactly the way it was in 1926. They object to the
theater showing Chaplin's `City Lights' because it was made during
the sound era.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest controversy involves Lustman's plan to stage a
``tribute'' to Austin, the theater's former owner. Next Wednesday
and Thursday the theater will screen Murnau's ``Sunrise,'' the film
that was never shown the night Austin was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten calls, threats, it hasn't been pretty,'' Lustman
said. ``Some people think it's kind of morbid. I don't know; I'm
just some guy who doesn't know squat about silent movies who drove
by and bought it on a whim. But the bottom line is, the place is
still alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
