<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-HI-TECH-VISION-TEST-N     01-12 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HI-TECH-VISION-TEST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER FINDS HIDDEN VISION PROBLEMS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By SHAWN O'LEARY  
 c.2000 HealthSurfing.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shannon Rose can see the recipes in the cookbook she uses, but
her right eye isn't seeing the full page. One day while updating a
prescription for contact lenses, her optician detected vision
trouble, prompting further examination. An ophthalmologist found a
small cancerous tumor on her retina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just really odd and scary to think that there's
something like that in your eye that's just sitting there, and you
have no idea,'' says Rose. ``When that kind of news is delivered, I
think you do go into shock. I don't know if it still has sunk in.''
</P>
<P>
   The tumor in Rose's eye creates a hole in her vision. Dr.
William Freeman, professor of ophthalmology at Shiley Eye Center at
the University of California, San Diego, says Rose can't see the
hole because her brain compensates for the loss, ``telling'' her
other eye to fill in the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your brain kind of wants there to be a full picture, and it
fills it in,'' Freeman says.
</P>
<P>
   Based on this phenomenon, Freeman and his research colleagues,
in conjunction with Microvision Inc. of Bothell, Wash., developed a
machine that informs doctors precisely where vision is blocked,
allowing a more accurate diagnosis and treatment of the problem.
Called entoptic perimetry, it borrows electronic display imaging
technology first developed for military applications.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mix of patients in trials, entoptic perimetry has been
used to diagnose peripheral scotomas caused by cytomegalovirus
retinitis, an opportunistic infection experienced by people in
advanced stages of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have found in AIDS patients is that patients who are
completely unaware that they have an infection in the retina can
immediately see that there's something wrong,'' Freeman says.
</P>
<P>
   The test could also be used to diagnose vision problems among
brain tumor patients and others. ``When the doctor or your
pediatrician looks in the eye with a little hand-held
ophthalmoscope, that only shows him really the very center, he
would miss a retinal detachment, peripheral diabetes, tumors of the
retina, and things like that,'' says Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   RETINAL IMAGE PROJECTION
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Plummer, Ph.D., visual psychophysicist at Shiley Eye
Center, says that when Rose looks into the lens of the testing
instrument with her bad eye, she sees an image projected directly
into her eye, an image similar to the ``snowstorm'' on a TV screen
that is not tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also cool that people are looking inside this machine
which doesn't have a screen inside of it, and yet they're seeing
the computer monitor inside their eye,'' says Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   The exam also increases patient awareness and responsibility in
treating their disease, serving to motivate patients to stick to
their drug regimen in cases when the eye can be healed. ``If you
break your leg, you know that your leg is broken. Something hurts.
You have pain. They're able to suddenly somehow understand what's
going on in the retina and why they need treatment,'' says Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   In the test, dots projected onto the eye move so fast that the
brain doesn't have time to fill in the missing parts of vision. In
a darkened exam room, staring into the examination lens, the only
one in the world, Rose is asked about the relative location of the
hole that she perceives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They draw on the computer monitor where they see the defect,''
says Freeman, considered a retinal specialist. ``That corresponds
very closely to exactly where the tumor or infection, or whatever
it is, on the retina.''
</P>
<P>
   With the test, Rose reports a black hole toward the side of her
vision. ``That whole area was blocked out,'' she says. ``It's just
a dark triangle. It's just black. So you would think that I
wouldn't be able to see out of that corner of my eye or that I
would notice the blockage.'' Doctors estimate she had been
suffering the condition for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The test takes under a minute, and early studies show it's
highly accurate, with a detection sensitivity figures of 95 percent
and specificity of greater than 95 percent. While the test is
presently only available in the San Diego area, the researchers
hope it will become a standard test used by optometrists and other
eye care practitioners when it becomes widely available, most
likely in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies have yet to announce whether they'll cover
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site at http://healthsurfing.com
contains further information.)
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
