<HEADER>
A4253 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-IRRESISTIBLEFORC     01-12 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IRRESISTIBLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER INSTALLMENT OF PERFECTLY APPOINTED PLASTIC LIVES
</HEADLINE>
 FORCES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY BOLDUC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Irresistible Forces'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Danielle Steel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte, $26.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What can you say about a book that describes sex between two
characters as ``four-star,'' and has a character expressing his
love for the heroine by personally reserving the ideal hotel room
for her during a Hawaiian business retreat _ in sandy and white
tones that ``looked like a spread from a magazine''? Either author
Danielle Steel spends too much time lounging in fancy hotels and
restaurants, or her jet-setting, stunning characters in
``Irresistible Forces,'' while glamorous, also seem too slick and
superficial, stuck in the '80s and about as warmblooded as Barbie
and Ken dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her plastic characters, Steel shows off her trademarked
ability to keep the pages turning, although the pacing gets a slow
start _ the only real problem or obstacle the heroine faces in the
first 150 pages is an executive's bitter opposition to her taking a
client's company public. Until then, protagonist Meredith Whitman
sees her life as ``perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Blond, slender and (of course) beautiful, our heroine enjoys a
blazingly successful career as a Wall Street investment banking
firm partner. She even holds the respect of senior partners who
make up ``a secret fraternity that still had trouble acknowledging
women.''
</P>
<P>
   She is married to a dark, handsome (but not vain) ER surgeon,
Steve, who works superhuman hours saving lives, yet finds time to
cook for her. Their love burns like an ``eternal flame.''
</P>
<P>
   She is in full control and things are running, as the cliche
goes, as smoothly as silk _ as in her ``silky'' blond hair and
``silky'' skin. She is probably the kind of woman Steel visualizes
her readers wanting to be _ and the author lets the readers loll in
the silken sheets of this supposedly glamorous, luxurious life for
chapter after chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Steve aches for a child, but Meredith sees no place in their
busy lives for distractions. She is committed to her job, to the
excitement of proving herself, the glamour of wearing lovely
clothes and impressing people.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Callan Dow, a dashing ``financial wizard'' client with a
vaguely described Palo Alto computer-related company. You can see
this train coming from miles away, but Meredith won't get off the
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons with Steve begin: Blond, Ferrari-driving,
Hermes-tie-wearing Cal looks like a GQ ad, even after all-day work
marathons, while intense, practical Steve looks as if he dressed in
a thrift shop. Cal loves fine dining; Steve settles for hamburgers
and pizza. Steve doesn't even care about (sheesh) money. Steve
represents comfortable history. Cal is a project for the future: He
has a storybook home and three children, but a heart broken by an
icy ex-wife who ditched the family.
</P>
<P>
   But don't most Ferrari-driving Ken dolls turn out to be jerks in
real life, Meredith?
</P>
<P>
   After Meredith helps engineer a successful IPO for Cal's
company, jetting around the country and Europe with him on a
promotional tour, she accepts a California job from him, turning
her marriage into a long-distance relationship _ with her husband's
improbable blessing. (He'll move to the West Coast later, once he
finds a job there.) Then even the weather and illness, along with
business conflicts, conspire to keep the couple on separate coasts.
Meredith's attraction to Cal grows.
</P>
<P>
   Will she resist this forbidden fruit? Will Steve, meanwhile,
overcome his attraction to New York co-worker Anna, a ripe-looking
Puerto Rican single mom with soft ``chocolate-colored'' eyes? This
soap opera plays out with tears, tense scenes, volcanic (sometimes
stormlike) passions and a gunshot wound.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after the dramatic tension is finally turned up, characters'
motivations still come off as too pat. Poor-but-proud Anna has the
noble goal of doing medical work in Third World countries. Cal and
Meredith bask in praise after pulling off a high-flying stock
launch for his computer-related company, but would that really take
genius in today's economy? And Anna and Cal are cast as victims,
still wounded by cold-hearted (but long-gone) ex-spouses and in
need of healing. Isn't this a bit too button-pushingly
manipulative?
</P>
<P>
   The reader ends up suspecting that Steel has written this book _
or parts of it _ before and is too lazy to create believable,
realistic people. .MDBR/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
