<SLUG> BC-CREATIVE-GRANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ARTISTS WIN MAJORITY OF A FOUNDATION'S FIRST GRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the first round of grants by the Creative Capital
Foundation is any guide, this city is, hands down, the nation's
creative capital. And much of the innovative work being done by
artists in the performing, visual, media and computer-based arts is
_ in contrast to a lot of the art that wins news media attention _
hardly controversial at all.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing applications from more than 1,800 artists from
46 states, the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico, Creative
Capital is awarding a total of $563,700 to 75 artists, 40 of whom
live in Manhattan, Brooklyn, the Bronx or Staten Island. Two others
live elsewhere in New York state, 12 in California and 3 in
Minnesota. Thirteen other states and the District had one or two
award recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Capital was founded last May to provide financial aid
to artists whose work may challenge convention. The money is
intended to help make up for the halt in federal grants to
individuals that took effect in 1994 after years of controversy in
Congress over the financing of works dealing with nudity, sexuality
and other provocative subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from descriptions of the projects provided by Creative
Capital, several deal with homosexuality or race, but only a few
seem to have much potential to stir controversy. For example, a
$5,000 grant went to Ray Thomas, the pseudonym of an artist in
Loudonville, N.Y., for RTMark.com, a Web site and promotion and
financing system that gives aid to ``creative subversion and
blacklisted cultural production.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave the review panels total leeway to pick the strongest
projects,'' said Ruby Lerner, Creative Capital's executive
director. ``We never said we would fund only controversial
projects; we said we wouldn't shy away from them.''
</P>
<P>
   She described several of the winning proposals as ``really
lyrical,'' but added, ``A lot of these projects are in their early
stages, and you never know how something will be received.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the grants were reported earlier this month, based on
descriptions provided in mailings to the artists.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lerner said she was ``a little disappointed'' that the list
of winners was not more diverse geographically. Before the
application deadline next September for the second round of grants,
she said, Creative Capital will try to reach out to more artists,
particularly in the Southeast, Hawaii, Minnesota and California,
where some of Creative Capital's financial backers are based.
</P>
<P>
   In other respects, the grants, which range from $3,200 to
$20,000, are more evenly distributed. They went to 40 men and 35
women, most in the early or middle stage of their careers. Only a
few recipients are well established, like Meredith Monk, the
composer, Ralph Lemon and Elizabeth Streb, performance artists, and
Mary Ellen Strom, an installation artist and choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   The grants are also spread fairly evenly among Creative
Capital's four award categories. The winners include 23 performing
artists, 20 visual artists, 20 film or video artists and 12 who
want to create Web sites, computer games, CD-ROMs or other
technology-based projects.
</P>
<P>
   The largest award, $20,000, went to Wendy Jacob, creator of the
sculpture ``Squeeze Chair,'' a large, overstuffed chair with arms
that inflate and hug the sitter in an embrace. When it was
exhibited, some saw its potential for calming autistic children who
are frightened or overstimulated by human touch. Ms. Jacob will use
the money to design a prototype that can be manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   The grant recipients were selected from a pool of 220 finalists,
whose detailed proposals were evaluated by panels of curators, arts
administrators and artists in November. The recipients are also
eligible for supplemental grants, and Creative Capital has set
aside $356,000 more for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Capital's founders have said since the start that grant
winners would be required to work with marketing experts to build
audiences for their works and then to share profits from the
projects in amounts to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   In this first round, artists will agree to a budget figure
(which includes wages, or fees for their time, and depreciation for
their personal equipment). Artists can keep any revenue received up
to that figure. Beyond that, Creative Capital is to receive a
percentage of profits equal to the percentage of the budget it
financed. When Creative Capital recoups its investment, its
percentage of the profits will be halved.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Capital, which is based in Greenwich Village, started
out with 22 patrons and now has 28 contributors, including the Ford
Foundation, which recently agreed to donate $250,000 over four
years. It has received more than $5 million and hopes eventually to
raise at least $40 million. The group will use some of the money to
hold a retreat for its grant recipients in August at the Skowhegan
School of Painting and Sculpture in Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
