<HEADLINE>
KEY VOICE COMBINES VOICE AND DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Va.) (nk) 
 By MATTHEW SAUER   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Key Voice Technologies is winning recognition
for a new product it developed that unifies voice mail, faxes and
e-mail into a single, universal ``inbox.''
</P>
<P>
   The product, called iNTerchange, debuted in August and this week
it received the 1999 Product of the Year award from Communication
Solutions magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The product provides users with an inbox on their computer that
lists e-mail and voice mail messages and faxes. It allows someone
to listen to e-mail messages and it converts punctuation,
abbreviations, shorthand and other written forms into natural
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Other applications include allowing users to listen to voice
mail through their computer speakers or allowing them to reroute
faxes to be sent along with forwarded e-mail or voice mail
messages.
</P>
<P>
   The product can be integrated with more than 100 different
telephone systems.
</P>
<P>
   The iNTerchange product is sold through Key Voice's 500 dealers.
The Sarasota company also has access to other sales channels
through its parent company, publicly traded Comdial Corp. of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Communications Solutions noted that the convergence of voice and
data in products such as iNTerchange is becoming almost too complex
to track.
</P>
<P>
   ``As voice and data converge, commingling ever more intimately,
they give rise to a teeming array of hybrids,'' the magazine said.
``These hybrids have grown so numerous, that they pose a challenge
to anyone who would divine their relationships to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Key Voice also develops and manufactures a line of voice mail,
automated attendant and fax processing products. The company was
founded in 1993 by Nick Branica, who remains its president under
Comdial.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia company bought Key Voice four years ago for $18.3
million in cash, notes, and Comdial common stock.
</P>
<P>
   Comdial, based in Charlottesville, Va., also makes
computer-telephone integration software, digital voice services and
voice processing products, wireless phones and paging systems. The
company posted fiscal 1998 net income of $17.2 million on sales of
$129 million. Its shares trade on the Nasdaq under the ticker
``CMDL.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1852EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4257 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-BURRDUEL-TEX     01-12 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BURRDUEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BOOKS DISSECT THE HAMILTON- BURR DUEL _ AND ONE EMERGES THE
WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM FUQUAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Duel: Alexander Hamilton, Aaron Burr and the Future of
America'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Fleming &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American History &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Basic Books, $30 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Burr, Hamilton and Jefferson: A Study in Character'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Roger C. Kennedy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American History &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University Press, $30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his excellent single-volume biography of George Washington,
James Thomas Flexner includes but a single line about Aaron Burr.
When Burr's name comes up for a possible political appointment,
Washington first pauses, then rejects Burr as of unsuitable
character.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the reaction of the first president, whose ability to
judge and manage men was perhaps his most valuable asset. At the
same time, Washington confidently named Alexander Hamilton his
chief of staff. Nearly two centuries after their 1804 shootout,
Burr and Hamilton continue to be contrasted in history books.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Fleming, author of more than a dozen volumes of history
and historical fiction, zeros in on the final, fatal encounter
between Burr and Hamilton. He skillfully describes the young
nation, its factions and its partisans that set the stage for the
dispute that claimed Hamilton's life.
</P>
<P>
   Both men craved recognition. Both borrowed heavily to build
country estates and lived beyond their means. Both engaged in
numerous sexual dalliances. President John Adams reviled Hamilton
for ``his audacious and unblushing attempts upon ladies of the
highest rank and purest virtue.'' Adams concluded: ``Hamilton
couldn't cool his iron in his own trough!'' Burr's conquests, too,
were legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Neither could claim the moral high ground in matters political,
either. In 1799, when Burr was a New York assemblyman, he agreed to
help European speculators acquire land in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a mere $5,000, which he distributed to members of the New
York legislature, Burr obtain a law waiving the ban on foreigners
owning land,'' Fleming writes. For his effort, he accepted $5,500,
which was disguised as a loan that was never repaid, along with an
opportunity to buy 100,000 acres of the speculators' land. But the
speculators approached Burr only after first going to Hamilton, who
agreed to help them on the condition that they loan his
father-in-law $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The two men nevertheless found themselves at opposite ends of
the political spectrum. At a time when ``party politics was
unquestionably becoming an integral part of the American system,
Hamilton and his fellow federalists ... saw themselves as the party
of the wise and good, men of virtues, talents, and property best
suited by birth and/or achievement to run the country.'' The
Republicans, led by Jefferson, ``called themselves the spokesmen of
the average man,'' the true standard-bearers of the Revolution's
ideals of liberty and equality.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? The barbs and criticisms of the day also
resonate in our contemporary insult barrages. For example, in 1790,
Hamilton had persuaded Washington to fund the $80 million
Revolutionary War debt by issuing debt certificates to veterans and
other supporters of the conflict, rather than cash. Within a few
years, most of that script, whose repayment was uncertain, was in
the hands of speculators who acquired it for cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamilton defended this deliberate concentration of wealth in
the hands of a few by arguing that without capital, America would
never build a powerful economy,'' Fleming writes. The Republicans
demonized Hamilton, accusing him of ``trying to turn America into a
mirror image of England, a country where financial speculation,
political corruption and mobs of disenfranchised factory workers
required a standing army to keep the aristocrats in power.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Burr, by the time he came to serve in 1800 as vice
president under Jefferson, he had given his peers ample opportunity
to form their opinions of him. While not trusted, his style was
renowned.
</P>
<P>
   In a telling example, when Burr was accused of fraud in the
European land deal, he quickly challenged his accuser to a duel.
Neither man was hurt. But observers recalled that Burr was
remarkably calm _ even when it was clear that his gun would not
fire properly and his opponent's bullet passed through Burr's coat.
Burr was reloading when his antagonist apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly intriguing is Fleming's detailed treatment of
Hamilton's ``insult'' and Burr's response. At a private dinner
party, Hamilton called Burr ``despicable,'' among other things, and
his words subsequently were published without his knowledge in a
partisan newspaper. The adjective barely met the day's standard for
besmirching a gentleman's honor. Indeed, Burr pressed Hamilton for
examples that would justify the term, while Hamilton, clearly eager
to avoid a duel, attempted to soften the insult even as he refused
to retract it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although dueling was already in some disfavor in New England
and New York, it was still the quintessential test of a man in the
South and West,'' Fleming writes. Given that both men were
recognized military heroes, whoever backed down would sacrifice all
influence and power.
</P>
<P>
   Roger C. Kennedy takes a broader approach in his take on the
subject matter, reflecting the events of the early 1800s in America
through the multifaceted prisms of Burr, Hamilton and Jefferson.
Assessing character and motives nearly two centuries distant is
hazardous at best, and Kennedy admits that though ample personal
writings exist to judge Jefferson and Hamilton, Burr left little
behind. The author proceeds to fill the vacuum with his own
speculations.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the messy duel was behind him, Burr traveled to
Florida and then westward, where he hit upon the idea of
establishing a plantation settlement in what is now northeast
Louisiana. He acquired hundreds of thousands of acres, called the
Bastrop Tract, in 1806. By spring 1807, then-President Jefferson
accused him of treason on grounds of promoting a new nation in
those western lands. Burr was cleared, but his reputation never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   There might be a convincing argument for Burr in Kennedy's
volume. If so, it is hidden in a factual thicket that could stand a
good pruning. Eager to take Jefferson down a notch or two, the
author elevates Burr correspondingly. Where virtually all of Burr's
contemporaries concluded he was not trustworthy, Kennedy tells us
Jefferson was the true self-aggrandizer and Burr more an
adventurer.
</P>
<P>
   If Kennedy wishes to change minds about Burr's character, he
might take a cue from Fleming and focus on a defining event _
Burr's western vision, perhaps _ to build a case. Both books offer
a glimpse of political intrigue in the nation's early years.
Fleming's seems the more likely to earn a place on the bookshelf.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
