<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Finished Work of Christ'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Francis A. Schaeffer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crossway, $19.99 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He being dead yet speaketh.'' That biblical phrase was not
written about noted evangelical Francis Schaeffer, who died in
1984, but ``The Finished Work of Christ'' calls it to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer's 1998 posthumously published commentary on the first
eight chapters of Romans was distilled from taped discussions of
Paul's epistle. The Swiss theologian emphasizes the reality of God,
the historicity of the Bible's events, the rational nature of
humanity, and individuals' utter inability to save themselves. The
only hope for man, Schaeffer writes, lies in the title phrase of
his book.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century says that ``faith has value as a thing in and
of itself ...,'' he writes. ``To this modern notion of faith, the
Bible absolutely says no! ... the important thing is not the faith
itself but the object of the faith: the God who is there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Finished Work of Christ'' uses the King James Version for
its text, but the archaic language of that translation is
counterbalanced by the casual, conversational style of Schaeffer's
comments. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hezekiah Walker &AMP; the Love Fellowship Crusade Choir &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Affair'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lil' Man/Interscope Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of five CDs, New York's Hezekiah Walker &AMP; the
Love Fellowship Crusade Choir have established themselves as one of
the leading lights of contemporary gospel. After less than six
weeks in the stores, this sixth CD has risen to No. 2 on the
national gospel charts and is probably settling in for a long stay
in the Top 5.
</P>
<P>
   All well and good _ except that this is as schizophrenic a
gospel CD as I've ever heard. At times, it's simply boring: Songs
such as the opening ``Power Belongs to God'' and ``Wonderful Is
Your Name'' just go on and on, with the choir wailing away, singing
the chorus over and over and OVER, with no lead singer to give the
tune focus.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there are moments when the CD lifts off and shows
Walker's and the choir's strength and versatility. Several songs,
including ``Let's Dance'' and ``Give 'em Your Life,'' get strong
contributions from rappers J. Moss and Mel Moss; rarely have rap
and gospel been integrated so smoothly. Both these songs boast a
winning funk underpinning and memorable choruses _ and both (hint,
hint) are among the shortest songs on the CD. Either could, and
should, be a major crossover hit single.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are songs in which a lead singer steps forward to
lead the choir and ups the intensity of the CD as a whole; a good
example is ``Never Leave Me Alone,'' which features Kirvy Brown on
lead vocals.
</P>
<P>
   And, literally last but definitely not least is ``Finally,'' a
stirring summit meeting of Hez and his bunch with R&AMP;B superstars
Blackstreet; here, the balance of voices is perfect. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Dave Ferman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
