A4259 &Cx1f; taf-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     01-12 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ADVANTAGES OF BEING A 100-YEAR-OLD BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday Jan. 14)  
(DW) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I must confess that the Y2K fizzle has been a big disappointment
to me, and not just because I squandered my entire New Year's Eve
crouched in front of an automatic teller machine with an open
grocery bag in my hands.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming instantly rich is not always a blessing, plus there
might have been some legal ramifications attached to a windfall of
that kind that would ultimately have taken some of the joy out of
the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   My disappointment mostly has to do with a perverse curiosity as
to what the world would be like without computers or, more
accurately, what the world would be like with computers that act
like they've swallowed large quantities of LSD.
</P>
<P>
   It's an irresponsible fantasy, I admit, if for no other reason
than the fact that the company I work for would go belly-up faster
than you can say ``final edition'' and I would be forced to find a
well-paying job that takes advantage of my other job skill, which
basically consists of taking long naps between snacks.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a concern now because the Y2K bug has turned out to
be as ineffectual as the Nevada Boxing Commission. The most
shocking news story to emerge from the whole sorry, over-hyped
``crisis,'' other than a few strands of Christmas lights dimming
momentarily at an Arkansas nuclear power plant, was a tabloid
report of a 100-year-old Danish baby.
</P>
<P>
   The Reuters news service, quoting the tabloid, said a computer
in a Copenhagen hospital initially registered the year's first
newborn as being 100 years old and born in the year 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Although I don't know the name of the tabloid, the name of the
hospital or even if the Y2K bug was the cause of the glitch, I
think we can safely assume that this story is authentic in every
regard and that there is a child out there _ in Denmark,
specifically _ who is doomed to go through life 100 years older
than he or she actually is.
</P>
<P>
   The first question we need to ask ourselves is: Is this a good
thing or a bad thing? Is there an advantage to being 100 years
older than all the other babies in the nursery or would you be
looked upon as some sort of freak? Or would anyone be able to tell
the difference?
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it would be an advantage to be the only kid in
your preschool who gets monthly Social Security checks.
Buying-power, no matter how modest, is sure to impress little
people who look upon Big Bird with the same sense of awe and
admiration that adults have for Albert Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you wouldn't be tall enough to reach the
mailbox, which could hinder your financial independence.
</P>
<P>
   If the 100-year-old baby moved to Florida, he could renew his
driver's license, by mail, for another six years, which would
elevate him tremendously in the esteem of the pre-potty-trained
set. Daily viewings of the Pokemon movie might not appeal to most
parents, but to a 100-year-old baby, it may pack all the dramatic
wallop of ``War and Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to predict what the job market or dating scene would
be like for someone who, according to the computer, is the oldest
person on Earth before he or she gets out of high school. My guess
is it would be just as frustrating and depressing as it is for
people of normal age.
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests that if the Y2K bug had bitten us as hard
as many had predicted, our lives might not necessarily have taken a
turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if we all walked away with a shopping bag full of
free loot.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
