<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES UPHOLD DRIVER'S PRIVACY LAW AS WAY TO PROTECT CITIZENS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim, optional ending) 
(Note: keyword change) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court unanimously upheld a federal law
Wednesday that bans states from disclosing information from
driver's licence applications, calling the statute a valid
congressional effort to protect citizens' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law, the 1994 Driver's Privacy Protection
Act, in an effort to thwart violent stalkers who often rely on
public records to locate their victims.
</P>
<P>
   Federal lawmakers passed the statute after it was revealed that
Rebecca Schaeffer's killer, Robert John Bardo, tracked down the
California home address of the television actress through state
motor-vehicle records in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Texas had sold license-application information largely without
restriction until 1997, when state law came into compliance with
the federal statute. In the fiscal year before the 1997 law's
enactment, Texas garnered $207,735 in revenue from sale of the
information, the state Department of Public Safety reported.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The justices' surprising 9-0 decision to uphold the law was in
contrast to recent rulings in which the court has invalidated
similar federal statutes for encroaching on the traditional
authority of states to regulate activities within their borders. In
one 1997 decision, the court had struck down a provision of the
Brady gun-control law because it required local police officers to
conduct federal criminal background checks on would-be firearm
purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina, citing that decision, had challenged the privacy
law as an unconstitutional power grab by Congress at the authority
of states to decide unilaterally what they do with information they
collect from their residents. The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
agreed with South Carolina, ruling that the national government
could not require motor-vehicle workers, employed by the state, to
participate in a federal privacy program.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court overturned the 4th Circuit decision,
saying that the privacy law neither imposes a great burden on the
state or its employees nor requires state workers to perform a
federal function. Rather the law simply calls on the state to
refrain from disclosing application information.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy law ``does not require the South Carolina
Legislature to enact laws or regulations, and it does not require
state officials to assist in the enforcement of federal statutes
regulating private individuals,'' Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also said Congress could enact the statute under
the constitutional provision giving federal lawmakers say over the
regulation of interstate commerce. Information provided by drivers
is used nationwide by automobile manufacturers and car-parts
dealers in their sales pitches, the court noted.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union hailed the justices'
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We applaud the court's affirmation that Congress has a right
to enact legislation that protects our privacy and safety,'' said
Steven Shapiro, the ACLU's national legal director. ``Today's
decision is especially welcome given a series of recent decisions
by this court favoring states' rights over the federal
government.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Attorney General Charlie Condon, who brought the
case on behalf of the state, grudgingly accepted the court's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``States' rights and federalism are principles well worth
fighting for,'' Condon said. ``A one-size-fits-none attempt to
protect privacy will not work. The state of South Carolina, not
Washington, D.C., can best determine how to protect the privacy
rights of South Carolinians.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of driver's license information has proven quite
lucrative for states, as New York in one recent year earned $17
million from individuals and businesses who sought access to the
information, the federal government reported.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law prohibits states from disclosing,without the
person's consent, a driver's personal information, including name,
address, telephone number and photograph.
</P>
<P>
   The law does not prohibit states from disclosing information on
car accidents and driving violations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Texas law, in legal limbo due to a court challenge, would
require people seeking car-accident information to provide the name
of a person involved in the collision as well as the date or
location of the mishap. The law is designed to safeguard the
privacy of accident victims and protect them from being inundated
with business solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Daily Newspaper Association and the Texas Press
Association have challenged the law as violating the First
Amendment right of free press.
</P>
<P>
   Travis County District Judge Paul Davis Jr. has enjoined the
state from enforcing the law until he issues a ruling on its
constitutionality, which is expected within the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
