<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIBEROTPIC-STANDARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP AGREES TO SET FIBER-OPTIC TECHNICAL STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fledgling fiber-optic telecommunications community got a
major boost Wednesday when 50 mostly young optical equipment makers
and service providers, led by Sycamore Networks Inc., agreed to
create technical standards that would enable communications
carriers to provide complete end-to-end connections and software
services.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably absent from the nationwide industry initiative are
such established telecommunications suppliers as Cisco Systems,
Lucent Technologies Inc., and Nortel Networks Inc., which are
developing their own optical networking equipment that will tie
into existing electrical networking gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at all the players, the big, broad-based
companies like Cisco and Lucent don't necessarily want an open set
of standards that would enable other companies to enter their arena
and share the wealth,'' said Tom Nolle, president of CIMI Corp., a
telecommunications consulting firm in Voorhees, N.J. ``So this
group of smaller players led by Sycamore will go it alone, and, if
they are successful, they could be a force that the big players
cannot ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry group, which will hold its inaugural meeting next
Tuesday in Boston, wants to create ``open interfaces and signaling
protocols.'' These will enable equipment and service providers to
connect seamlessly optical and electrical devices to provide
high-speed delivery of Internet-based communications and ancillary
services for corporations and, eventually, consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Optical Domain Service Interconnect, the long-term
goal is to provide a fast and easy way for corporations and
consumers to better use the Internet both in sending and receiving
voice, data, video, and graphics, along with new services such as
video conferencing and new private networks, between a
corporation's suppliers and trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium, whose members are predominantly startups and
small companies formed in the mid- to late 1990s, plans to submit a
proposal in about a year for approval by technical organizations
that govern such guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the future is attracting and retaining corporate
customers through innovation, so this is not about east versus west
or big against small, but rather the new guys like us versus the
old guys,'' said Sean Welch, vice president of marketing and sales
at Tenor Networks Inc., referring to Lucent and Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ODSI initiative puts service providers a giant step closer
to the `Holy Grail' of new service provisioning,'' said Mick
Scully, chief executive of Appian Communications Inc. of
Boxborough, Mass., one of the group's 50 members.
</P>
<P>
   Led by fast-growing Sycamore Networks of Chelmsford, Mass.,
which began putting the nationwide group together two months ago,
nearly 20 of the 50 members are in New England _ the single largest
geographic contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists and industry analysts including Andrew Cray
of Aberdeen Group in Boston maintain the region, particularly
Massachusetts, is now the center for fiber-optic communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer networking was the hot button of the 1990s that came
out of California with Cisco, 3Com Corp., and parts of Bay Networks
providing the core switches used in the Internet,'' said Cray.
``But with fiber-optic technology, plus long-distance carriers
looking to provide corporations with high-speed connections and
enhanced services, the focus is back east, particularly in the
Greater Boston area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-AUCTION-ESTIMATES-ART     01-12 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-ESTIMATES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW ESTIMATES LURING BIDDERS TO AUCTION ROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 12 and 13 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Nathaniel Appleton silver-mounted secretary
sold a year ago for $8.3 million _ after an estimate by Sotheby's
of $500,000 to $800,000 _ newcomers to the auction game may have
been shellshocked, but the pros were not. When most of the other
major items of Americana went for prices well above their presale
estimates, these newcomers sighed, picked up their inked-up
catalogs and headed for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen them bewildered, with their mouths open and their
hands empty,'' said Carol Prisant, a decorative-arts writer and
former antiques appraiser. ``Right now, there are a whole lot of
inexperienced people who are going away disillusioned with the
auction process. The tyro gets no explanation. Only the old hands
really know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   What's going on is that the city's largest auction houses are
setting their estimates artificially low deliberately, as a matter
of strategy, to lure bidders and to make themselves look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the Big Tease,'' said John Hays, the head of
American decorative arts at Christie's, which, like Sotheby's, is
holding a big Americana auction next week to coincide with the
Winter Antiques Show at the Seventh Regiment Armory. ``Like
anything else in life,'' he said, ``people have to feel that they
have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneers, who freely admit the practice, and prominent
Americana dealers like Leigh Keno say lower-than-realistic
estimates can incite bidding from the floor, thereby generating
excitement that ratchets up prices, often to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   While in the recession of the early 1990s auctioneers used high
estimates to demonstrate worth _ and to get the bids moving _ that
approach is now regarded as a flop. ``They found out they weren't
going to pull in the bidders that way,'' said Keno, who once worked
at both Christie's and Doyle's. As times got better, auction houses
found that ``low estimates do entice buyers,'' he said, adding,
``So for the last five or six years, there's been more of a
conscious effort to be conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Auction officials are quick to concede that if they put down
what they really thought the best items would go for, nobody would
show up _ or customers might be reluctant to bid. ``Nobody would
want to be the first to put their hand up in the air,'' said Nancy
Druckman, the director of American folk art at Sotheby's. ``It's
scary _ I've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but if the auction house printed estimates based
on real expectations, it also might not be able to boast about
selling a piece at double the estimate (or more). After its last
Americana auction, Christie's trumpeted that sales ``totaled $6.6
million, well above the presale estimate of $4 million.'' In a
packed room, the release continued, ``many pieces sold for two,
three and four times their presale estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   For one would-be buyer, these triple and quadruple selling
prices are unnerving, to say the least. ``Something I really wanted
a lot went way over the top,'' said Jane Schulak, a designer from
Birmingham, Mich., who often travels to auctions, even as far as
Paris. Even there, a chair she wanted with an estimate of $12,000
ended up selling for $50,000. ``Once I hit $25,000, I said, `You're
sick,''' she said. ``I stopped.'' She paused. ``I was surprised,
but that might have been my lack of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Sotheby's and Christie's are hoping for record attendance
at next week's Americana sales in Manhattan, and dealers say that
with all the new Wall Street money, the auction floor will be full
of what Richard H. Jenrette, the longtime collector, calls the
Nasdaq nouveaux riches. While officials concede that some of these
bonus babies may not know the auction ropes, they insist that many
more of them are savvy enough to figure them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I always take the estimates with a grain of
salt,'' said Jenrette, the former chairman of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette and a preservationist who has restored and decorated six
historic houses, largely with furnishings bought at auction. ``I
wouldn't worry too much about the Nasdaq crowd,'' he added.
``They're used to seeing things soar.''
</P>
<P>
   Then which bidders are hurt by the practice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody,'' Keno said, ``except maybe the elderly couple from
Rumson, N.J. _ or anywhere _ who spend all week with the auction
catalog, find a chest estimated between $5,000 and $10,000, maybe
talk to their banker about a loan and arrive at the auction only to
see it start at $16,000.''
</P>
<P>
   But those buyers, the auctioneers say, are on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   Although auction officials also tend to play down the role of
the younger, more inexperienced auctiongoers _ Hays predicted the
new, younger blood at this year's sale will be only between 15 and
20 percent of the crowd _ Margaret B. Caldwell, an Americana dealer
and appraiser, disagrees with the auctioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bonus babies are who's buying,'' she said. ``The Old Guard
is shocked and horrified by the prices.'' By Old Guard, she added,
she means customers over 60.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is someone who may be hurt by low estimates: the
seller. Under New York City consumer laws, the minimum price he or
she must accept for the item is the lowest estimate, the
auctioneers say. Thus, if a chest of drawers is estimated to sell
for between $5,000 and $7,000, the auction house must sell it if
someone bids $5,000 or more. If it's a bad day for sellers, Uncle
George may end up selling his chest _ which he thought was worth at
least $10,000 _ for half that. (Of course, the sellers would also
be delighted if the estimate is tripled.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there is another problem, said Ms. Caldwell, who this year
helped authenticate the Winter Show's offerings and headed
Sotheby's 19th-century furniture department in New York for six
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your piece is damaged while it's at the auction house, the
insurance is based on the low estimate, so the auction house won't
reimburse you more than that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
