<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     01-12 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ, FISK A RESPECTABLE PAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Up on a stage, in front of cameras and microphones,
Carlton Fisk and Tony Perez sat side-by-side. One born in Cuba, the
other in Bellows Falls, Vt., they will walk shoulder-to-shoulder
through the gates of Cooperstown in July.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk and Perez first crossed paths in the 1975 World Series,
each hitting a dramatic homer in the final two games, then they
served the Boston Red Sox as teammates in 1980. On the day after
they were voted into the Hall of Fame, both talked about respect
for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony and I shared a passion for the game that might not be
present in other people's attitudes toward the game,'' said Fisk.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to this correspondent's favorite Fisk moment.
Reviewing the catcher's 24-year career, most New Englanders would
first cite Fisk's Game 6 Foul Pole Shot of ``Good Will Hunting''
fame (just as some young people think Bobby Orr's only goal was the
1970 Cup-clincher, there will be folks who think Fisk only hit one
homer in his career). Some Sox fans with long memories might prefer
to replay one of Catcher Carlton's fistfights with (pick a Yankee)
Thurman Munson, Gene Michael or Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   But the career moment that says the most about Fisk and his work
ethic, is the Deion Sanders incident in Yankee Stadium when Fisk
was a catcher for the White Sox more than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk gladly recounted the story Wednesday after his Manhattan
press conference:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be overly disrespectful, but I'll just tell
you what happened. Deion Sanders obviously had his own personality.
He would come up to the plate every at-bat and he'd draw a dollar
sign in the dirt. I was offended because I felt as though he was
pimping me when he came up there. I don't know whether I was right
in that feeling or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit a popup to the infield and didn't run. He didn't make a
move to run, whether he thought that he didn't have to. And I
thought that was so disrespectful to the game and to the uniform he
was wearing. And here he was, wearing a New York Yankees uniform.
So I yelled at him to run the ball out, using so many expletives.
And he looked at me quizzically and just broke off and went into
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was burning. I was fuming for some reason. And this was a
guy playing for the other team. So he comes up the next time and
draws his dollar sign in the dirt and says, `Hey man, the days of
slavery are over.' And I looked at him and said, `What the
(expletive) are you talking about?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I jumped up and got in his face badly and said to him,
`You know something, there's a right way and a wrong way to play
this game and you are playing it wrong and you know something, it
offends guys like me so if you don't play it right, I'm going to
kick your butt right here in Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   There. The ultimate Carlton Fisk moment. It encapsulates his
stubbornness, fearlessness, and competitive fire. It explains how a
boy from a town of 800 people (Charlestown, N.H.) made himself into
one of the top 100 baseball players of all-time, and only the
fourth catcher (joining Yogi Berra, Roy Campanella, and Johnny
Bench) elected to the Hall of Fame in the last 43 years. Fisk
caught more games and hit more home runs than any catcher in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to do it so long because I was really stubborn,''
he said. ``Maybe my New England roots had something to do with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk will be back in the Hub Thursday for the annual Boston
Baseball Writers' bash at the Sheraton. Perhaps then he'll admit
the obvious _ he plans to be immortalized with a Red Sox ``B'' on
his bronze plaque in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he'll be enshired as a Cincinnati Red. What else? He
was part of the Big Red Machine, which won consecutive World Series
in 1975-76. If Pete Rose hadn't bet on baseball, the '75 Reds would
be able to claim four Hall of Famers in their infield (catcher
Bench, first baseman Perez, second baseman Joe Morgan, and third
baseman Rose). Sixty-seven voters this year thought Dave
Concepcion, the '75 Reds' shortstop, was also Hall worthy.
Cincinnati manager Sparky Anderson is expected to join Perez and
Fisk when the Hall's Veterans Committee convenes in March. And
let's not forget that the '75 Reds outfield had 50-homer guy George
Foster and Ken Griffey Sr., father of one of the greatest players
in history.
</P>
<P>
   History. Respect. That's what this is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game itself,'' said a reverant Fisk. ``Being able to carry
the torch for the game is what I will cherish the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge homeboy Matt Damon, who won an Oscar for the script
that gave proper homage to Fisk's Game 6 shot, met Fisk during the
All-Star festivities last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' gushed Damon. ``He was standing there
telling me what an honor it was to be named one of the greatest
players of the century and he showed me his forearm. The hair was
standing up on his forearm! That's how much it meant to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk and Perez honored the uniform for more than 40 years. Their
joint induction, on the 25th anniversary of what might have been
the greatest World Series ever, should serve to remind us about
everything that is great about the game and why it still matters.
Even here in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1859EST &QL; 
