<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-AUCTION-ESTIMATES-ART     01-12 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-ESTIMATES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: she said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consignors, or sellers, are therefore often reluctant to list
their property at a price lower than they had hoped for. Auction
officials said they spent numerous lunches and dinners persuading
consignors to accept the lower estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low estimates equal high prices,'' said William W. Stahl Jr.,
the head of Sotheby's decorative arts division. (He clarified that
to say that he didn't mean ``ridiculously low estimates
would make a bidder think there was something wrong with the
piece.'')
</P>
<P>
   If the consignor won't go along with a price he or she believes
to be too low, ``then we tell them their property might be better
off not being sold at auction,'' Stahl said.
</P>
<P>
   So those numbers in the catalog are the result of a negotiation:
not too low, or the seller will balk, and not too high, or
potential bidders will lose interest.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times asked four independent dealers of note to
appraise catalog estimates for next week's two major Americana
auctions. All agreed that many of the estimates were low, part of
what they termed the general policy of the auction houses. Ms.
Caldwell was the only dealer who would allow her name to be used
when talking about specific items in the sales, with the
understanding that she would not offer comments on pieces she
planned to bid on _ either for herself or for clients who have
hired her.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed in particular to Christie's Item 159, the Hewlett
Family federal sideboard, estimated at between $70,000 and
$100,000. If the feet are ``right,'' she said, using the trade's
term for ``original,'' she said the sideboard might approach
$200,000. Both she and Peter M. Brant, a well-known collector and
the owner of Antiques Magazine, also pointed to a serving table
attributed to Thomas Seymour of Boston (circa 1810). The table is
estimated at $20,000 to $40,000. Even with its shortened legs,
Brant predicted a gavel price of more than $100,000, and Ms.
Caldwell said she would be conservative, guessing $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   She also pointed to two of the auction week's most exciting
offerings, both in the Christie's sale _ items that don't have
published estimates: the 1679 Joseph and Bathsheba Pope valuables
cabinet (which dealers have now nicknamed ``the box'') and the
Cornelius Stevenson Chippendale carved mahogany card table
(nicknamed ``the card table'').
</P>
<P>
   If you ask the auction house, the box is estimated at between
$600,000 and $900,000, and the card table between $1 million and $2
million _ but interested parties have to call to find that out.
``We want people to call us,'' said Hays, the decorative arts head.
Because the pieces are so rare and valuable, the auction house did
not feel confident estimating their worth when the catalogs were
sent off to the printer's months ago, Hays said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the dealers wanted to hazard a guess, either, on the
box, but Ms. Caldwell said she would not be surprised if the Card
Table sold for between $2 and $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' she said, ``where are you going to get another
one?''
</P>
<P>
   Other dealers were buzzing about the pair of carved Chippendale
card tables at Sotheby's. They were originally owned by James W.
Beekman, and were made in New York around 1760. Other card tablesowned by the Beekmans are on display at Winterthur and the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. The pair is estimated at $400,000 to
$600,000, but dealers say they are already lining up clients who
may be willing to top the estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, at Sotheby's, predicted that the tables ``will probably
bring more.'' (Leslie Keno, the director of American furniture
under Stahl _ and Leigh Keno's twin brother _ was more direct: He
said he would ``not be surprised if the tables brought over a
million dollars.'')
</P>
<P>
   Stahl was less cautious about Lot 706, the Queen Anne secretary
attributed to Samuel Harding of Philadelphia, with some exceptional
carvings of sunflowers and shells on its pediment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his own published estimate of $200,000 to $300,000, he
predicted the auction price ``will go through the roof.''
</P>
</TEXT>
