<HEADER>
A4273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      01-12 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release THURSDAY AMs, January 13, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Tel Aviv) _ The Vatican issues a politically
charged itinerary for the first papal pilgrimage to the Holy Land
in more than 35 years. John Paul II will visit some of the most
sacred sites of Judaism, Christianity and Islam, meet with leaders.
By Aliza Marcus. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ Russia's new leader, unfazed by Chechnya
setbacks and showing adroit political skills for someone who
emerged so quickly from obscurity, makes several moves likely to
bolster his already strong position. By Brian Whitmore. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BUSH (West Columbia, S.C.) _ George W. Bush is under
fire for holding a campaign event on a former slave plantation and
for not condemning a South Carolna legislator who called the NAACP
the national association for retarded people -- and then apologized
to retarded people. By Anne E. Kornblut. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISM-SUSPECT (Burlington, Vt.) _ A judge refuses to release
a Montreal woman suspected of terrorist ties after prosecutors used
phone records to make the strongest link yet between her and men
accused of conspiring to sneak explosives into the United States.
By Jeffrey Good. 900 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   NY-HUDSON (Undated) _ In an unusual foray into New York City
politics, Massachusetts Senators John Kerry and Edward M. Kennedy
are calling for a detailed environmental study of a $350 million
pier and park project on Manhattan's West Side, drawing a rebuke
from the office of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. By Scott Allen. 600
words.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HILLARY-LETTERMAN (New York) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton makes
her first appearance on ``The David Letterman Show.'' By Fred
Kaplan. 800 words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   MA-AILING-HMO (Boston) _ Massachusetts strips Harvard Pilgrim
Health Care's former chief executive and chief financial officer of
the $1.3 million in ``golden parachute'' severence pay they
negotiated when they left the troubled health plan last year. By
Richard A. Knox and Steven Wilmsen. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MA-POVERTY (Boston) _ With the nation nearing the ninth year of
an economic boom and Internet executives raking in millions, one in
four Massachusetts families still do not earn enough to pay for a
bare bones existence, study shows. By Kimberly Blanton. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   FIBEROPTIC-STANDARDS (Undated) _ The fledgling fiberoptic
telecommunications arena gets a major boost as 50 networking
manufacturers and service providers agree to seek technical
standards so optical switches can talk to other opitcal devices
seamlessly. By Ronald Rosenberg. 450 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Boston, Mass.) -- A grievance hearing to determine
the validity of Bill Belichick's contract with the New York Jets
will likely last a day, and possibly continue into Friday. By Nick
Cafardo. 950 words.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN (New York) _ Carlton Fisk and Tony Perez
first crossed paths in the 1975 World Series. Now, newly voted into
the Hall of Fame, both talk about respect for the game. By Dan
Shaughnessy.
</P>
