<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Jan. 13 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   RING-ROBBERY (Los Angeles) -- When a robber demanded Carl Phan's
money, he gave it up, but he refused to give up his wedding ring
cost him his life. Phan struggled with his assailant and was shot
and wounded. The robber fled, but Phan kept the ring and returned
to his wife of 12 years. ``The wedding ring that is the only
valuable thing I have,'' he said. ``It represents true love and
comittment to each other and that we are never going to separate
from each other until death.'' By Lisa Van Proyen. (Will move on
the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   XRATED-LAX (Los Angeles) -- New security systems at Los Angeles
International Airport and others are so powerful they actually can
reveal the naked curves of travelers, prompting complaints from
civil liberarians and passengers alike. The new $125,000 BodySearch
system uses very low doses of x-ray energy to scan and display an
image of the traveler's body on a screen. Hidden drugs, currency,
explosives and firearms even plastic weapons can then be
identified. By David R. Baker. (Will move on the ``n'' California
news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) -- The chairman of the Democratic
National Convention said Wednesday that plans are on schedule for
the August event in Los Angeles, with no problems so far in
arranging security, transportation, hotels or other areas. It will
be an opportunity to showcase the party and the city, officials
say. By Rick Orlov. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   KSWISS-SHOES (Los Angeles) -- Shares of K-Swiss Inc. were
hammered Wednesday after the Westlake Village-based athletic shoe
maker reported that sales slowed in the previous three months. By
Suzie St. John. (Will move on the ``f'' financial news wire.)
</P>
