<HEADLINE>
GORE VOWS `FRESH START' IN DEFENDING CHANCES OF WINNING PRESIDENCY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore defended his
electability Wednesday, both because and despite his relationship
with President Clinton, and was prompted by an undecided Iowa
Democrat to declare: ``I wouldn't have done that'' with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, national front-runner for the Democratic presidential
nomination, called Clinton's sexual liaisons near the Oval Office
with White House intern Lewinsky ``reprehensible'' but insisted
that the criticism did not begin to describe his many-layered
feelings about the man he has served closely for seven years and is
seeking to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president sought to convince a group of supporters and
undecided voters at Coe College of his political independence: ``I
am running for president on my own, as who I am, on my own vision,
on my agenda.'' His comments came as he pressed for support ahead
of the Iowa precinct caucuses Jan. 24 that will formally begin the
presidential nominating contest.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recalled that some Democrats in 1960 had said John F.
Kennedy could not win and that Republicans had said the same of
Ronald Reagan in 1980. Although claiming not to like polls ``at
all,'' Gore went on to contend that some national surveys had
turned around recently, and now showed he would have a better
chance than former Sen. Bill Bradley to defeat the Republican
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement in polls cited by Gore is marginal, and he
continues to trail Bush. A Newsweek poll showed Bush leading Gore
by 7 percentage points (50 percent to 43 percent) and Bush leading
Bradley by 12 points (54 percent to 38 percent). A Time-CNN poll
put Bush 17 percentage points (56 percent to 39 percent) over Gore
and 16 percentage points over Bradley (55 percent to 39 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that if he is the Democratic nominee he would
challenge the Republican standard-bearer to abandon television
commercials in favor of frequent debates.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Iowa on Tuesday night, Gore roused an
audience of his partisans with the pledge to ``hound that other
party from coast to coast and border to border with a challenge to
debate twice a week, accepting every format, accepting every
invitation within reason.'' Gore said he would apply the rule to
his campaign and the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has issued the same challenge to Bradley, who has refused,
and a similar rejection is almost certain from any Republican
nominee, which the vice president and his strategists almost
certainly know.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making Gore try to look high-minded, the
debates-only challenge would cut into any Republican attempt to use
television advertising to link Gore to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps concern about such commercials influenced a Gore remark
Wednesday night: ``We do not have to have this insipid approach to
having these little meaningless, poll-tested, fuzzy, clever,
ultimately destructive messages that demean our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   A debates-only campaign would remove the possibility that
Republican groups could hammer Gore with clips, including the vice
president's assertion, on the day of the impeachment vote in
December 1998, that Clinton was ``one of the greatest presidents''
in the nation's history. Independent groups, however, would not
necessarily be bound by such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Gore's long, nuanced answer about his relationship
with Clinton, which could be a major subtheme in the fall campaign,
would not fit neatly into a 30- or 60-second ad.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his relationship with Clinton had ``basically four
aspects.'' Those included becoming ``a genuinely good friend''
because of their working closely together, being shocked by
Clinton's ``personal mistake'' in the Lewinsky scandal, fighting
``an awful lot of battles'' over the seven years of their
administration, and running the current campaign ``on my own.'' The
successes, he said, included the economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing only one of those aspects, ``you won't get the whole
picture,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps unwittingly, later in a United Auto Workers union
hall in Waterloo, Gore voiced what almost certainly will be a major
Republican campaign theme and raised some doubt about how closely
he wants to be aligned with Clinton in voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is about fresh starts,'' Gore said. ``And we need a
fresh start. We need a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, it had taken Gore several minutes to lay out his answer
Wednesday after Craig Wood, a Cedar Rapids mental health worker,
challenged Gore's chances of winning the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that your ability to win the election is reduced
by your association with the Clinton scandal, and I think you've
got to come up with some way to make a statement that you're
separated from that somehow,'' Wood said. ``I would have a
suggestion for that statement which something along the lines of,
'I wouldn't have done that.'''
</P>
<P>
   As Wood continued to speak, Gore broke in to say: ``I wouldn't
have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore expressed confidence that during the next nine months he
could be accepted on his own by the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that presidential campaigns represent an
opportunity for the American people to get to know the candidates
personally and make a judgment about them personally,'' Gore said.
``Properly pursued a presidential campaign is a learning
experience, even a transformative experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said after the hour-plus forum that he was leaning toward
support for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he convinced me,'' Wood said. ``I understand that you
can be a friend and not approve of their behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said Gore trails Bush in national polls because of the
Clinton scandal, but if Gore ``can get his message out,'' he could
overcome voters' doubts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a favorite topic of reporters, Gore rarely gets
questions from voters about electability. He also faced inquiries
at Coe about other seldom raised issues, including one about
``transgender'' discrimination from a person who had a sex-change
operation and another from a farmer who pressed the vice president
for his position on ``ram shields,'' devices apparently banned in
Iowa that keep rambunctious male sheep from butting their minders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
