<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN TRIAL OF PAKISTAN'S OUSTED PREMIER QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The judge in the treason and hijacking case
against the ousted prime minister of Pakistan, Nawaz Sharif,
abruptly quit the proceedings Wednesday, complaining that
government intelligence agents were menacing his courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot provide a fair trial in these circumstances,'' said
the judge, Shabbir Ahmed, just before he stalked out, leaving
behind a stunned courtroom. ``Is it an open, free, fair and
impartial trial when intelligence people sit in my room in
plainclothes?''
</P>
<P>
   The judge then sent the troublesome case back to the same lower
court judge who only a month ago sent it his way.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another bizarre episode in an increasingly bizarre
situation _ and no way for Pakistan's military ruler to celebrate
the three-month mark of his coup.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Pervez Musharraf, the nation's self-proclaimed leader, had
explained his seizure of power on Oct. 12 as a reaction to a
murderous plot by Sharif. But the court case, which promised high
drama, has produced only farce.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing Wednesday in Karachi began routinely enough,
observers said. But then, one of Sharif's five co-defendants,
Shahid Khakan Abbasi, former head of the state airline, stood up to
complain about the conditions in the jail cells where he and the
others have been held. Abbasi added that a government intelligence
agent had taken a seat near the defendants and was listening to
their conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of someone from an intelligence service is not
particularly unusual at a high-profile political trial. But the
judge seemed to grow angry and began firing questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge just lost his temper,'' a defense lawyer, Khawaja
Naveed Ahmed, said. ``He said he wanted the intelligence officers
to be arrested, though that didn't happen. He said he wanted the
case transferred, and then he walked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif began speaking to reporters. ``It is very obvious that
the government wants to overpower the court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif has proclaimed his innocence of all charges, including
hijacking, kidnapping, attempted murder and plotting to wage war
against the state.
</P>
<P>
   The charges, which could incur the death penalty, stem from the
events of Oct. 12, when Sharif reportedly gave orders to prevent a
jet with 198 passengers from landing at the Karachi airport as it
was running out of fuel. Aboard the flight was Musharraf, who,
though he did not know it at the time, had been sacked as army
chief by Sharif. The general has insisted that an air calamity was
averted only because the military seized the airport in a hastily
orchestrated coup.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The case against Sharif was prepared in antiterrorism courts,
where rules have been written to produce quick verdicts. Near the
time for the official filing of charges, the government suddenly
rewrote the antiterrorism laws so that only a High Court judge
could preside.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ahmed was appointed, and although some defense lawyers
contend that the government had picked someone whom it could bully,
events seemed to prove otherwise. He repeatedly scolded prosecutors
for refusing to share evidence with the defense. One delay followed
another. The court has yet to ``frame'' the charges, the legal step
where the case is accepted for an actual trial. Meanwhile, the core
of the prosecution's case has been made public, with the filing of
summaries of witnesses' statements.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than neatly supporting Musharraf's account, the
statements are full of contradictions and could be read as a prime
minister's understandable efforts to head off a coup after having
exercised his constitutional right to replace his army chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weak case, and I don't think any judge would want to
try it under these circumstances,'' Ahmed, the defense lawyer,
said. ``I'm suspicious. What happened today seems preplanned. If
you were the judge, wouldn't you use a little drama to get out of
this case?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
