<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-SHAMBHALA-TEX     01-12 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHAMBHALA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANT ENLIGHTENMENT? TURN ON A LIGHT, BUT NOT TO READ THIS BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Secret of Shambhala: In Search of the Eleventh Insight'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by James Redfield &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel/Philosophy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warner, $23.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret of Shambhala,'' James Redfield's latest guide to
spiritual enlightenment, is a complete sham, and the only thing
that will be (en)lightened is your wallet.
</P>
<P>
   This is a torturous 235 pages of bunk, hokum, bilge, foolishness
and schlock.
</P>
<P>
   The tale opens as our hero, presumably Redfield since it's told
as a first-person yarn, receives a cryptic message from a friend
lost in Tibet while in search of Shambhala, first-cousin city to
Shangri-La.
</P>
<P>
   Shambhala is, we are led to believe, the land of enlightenment.
And so our paranoid hero dutifully trucks off to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   He imagines danger at every turn, presumably from Chinese
soldiers who seek to quash any mention of Shambhala. But the danger
is more perceived than real. It comes off as a device contrived to
inject some dramatic tension into a tale that, even so, has the
intellectual depth of TV's ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Redfield skulks about Tibet with the help of Yin, a native guide
and spiritual mentor who drones on about maintaining his ``prayer
field'' and ``synchronicity'' as they search for ``The
Extensions.'' On occasion, the two are aided by the Dakini, best
described as Shambhalan sprites.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Celestine Prophecy,'' an earlier unliterary mess,
Redfield went mucking around South America, where he fomented ``The
Ten Insights.'' Think of The Extensions as the Asian version of The
Insights.
</P>
<P>
   The First Extension is achieved by breathing in ``inner divine
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Visualize that this energy is coming into you and feel it as
it flows out into the world. Do this, and you will have completed
the First Extension,'' says Yin.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Extension, we learn, is all about ``setting your
field of energy so that it will enhance your life flow. You do this
by staying alert and expectant.'' It's much like a caffeine rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Extension,'' says Yin, `` is setting your
prayer-field to go out and increase the energy and vibrational
levels of others. When your prayer field reaches other people in
this way, they feel a hit of spiritual energy, clarity, intuition
and they will be more likely to give you the right information.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad that none of this has anything to do with clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's much more. Let us just say that Redfield does
find Shambhala, which turns out to be a physical place where the
people have mastered cold fusion and procreate by ``intuition.''
The unborn children also magically go away if the couple changes
(or loses?) its collective mind.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, great literature can entertain, educate and
enlighten. ``The Search for Shambhala'' is neither great nor
literature. Neither is it entertaining, educational or
enlightening.
</P>
<P>
   Easy answers to life's mysteries would be nice, but
enlightenment is neither a place nor a destination. It comes from
experience, self-evaluation and growth. And, most of all, it is a
journey one never completes, or finds in a James Redfield ``book.''
(Apologies to people who really do write books.)
</P>
<P>
   One almost can't blame Redfield for wanting to make a buck. What
is distressing is that so many desperately confused people allow
themselves to be taken in by this waste of good paper.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, World Shambhalaism is attained and maintained
through some kind of collective prayer field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to human progress,'' we are told, ``is to have enough
people who can beam a higher expectation of love into this human
field.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: ``Trust the Force, Luke!''
</P>
<P>
   This is snake oil. .MDUL/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
