<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-BANKS-310&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAKARTA REPLACES HEAD OF BANK RESTRUCTURING AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Indonesia's three-month-old government tightened its
control over the nation's much-disputed economic rebuilding effort
Wednesday, dismissing the chairman of its powerful bank
restructuring agency and replacing him with an official closer to
President Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Bambang Sudibyo told reporters that Glenn Yusuf
would step down Thursday as chairman of the Indonesian Bank
Restructuring Agency, a position Yusuf had held for the last 19
months.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Cacuk Sudarijanto, is a former
telecommunications executive whom Wahid had appointed as the
agency's vice chairman last November and who enjoys support among
the loose grouping of Muslim political parties instrumental in
Wahid's October election.
</P>
<P>
   The move puts control of the economy of Indonesia, the world's
fourth most populous nation, more firmly in the hands of the new
administration. The bank restructuring agency, which was
established in early 1998 as a condition of aid from the
International Monetary Fund, controls roughly $69 billion in assets
as well as the rescue of the nation's insolvent banks. It is in
charge of reviving the banking system by selling off the holdings
of troubled banks and recovering unpaid loans from recalcitrant
debtors.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the largest debtors are companies owned in part by the
friends and children of former President Suharto, who resigned amid
riots and mass protests in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There had long been some speculation that Yusuf would be
replaced, but it remained unclear Wednesday how the move would
affect relations between Jakarta and the IMF, which is overseeing a
$43 billion economic assistance package to Indonesia and has in the
past opposed efforts to politicize the agency. The IMF and
Indonesia are due to sign a new letter on the terms of that package
this month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The proposed appointment of a new chairman for the Indonesian
Bank Restructuring Agency comes at a critical juncture,'' said
Vasuki Shastry, an IMF spokesman in Washington. ``The IMF has been
working closely with IBRA on restructuring Indonesia's financial
system, a prerequisite for achieving broad economic recovery.'' He
said the agency would continue working with Indonesia but ``would
like to reiterate that maintaining IBRA's independence and
professionalism is absolutely essential and remains central to the
IMF program.''
</P>
<P>
   Other signs have emerged recently that Wahid's government is
maneuvering to gain more singular control over how to uproot the
corruption of Suharto's regime. Last week, the government asked the
parliament to remove the central bank governor after a state audit
found fault with the bank's account of billions of dollars in
futile rescue loans doled out to commercial banks in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a part of a wider pattern to assert partisan control
in Indonesia,'' said Andrew MacIntyre, an associate professor of
international relations at the University of California in San
Diego. ``But whether this new partisan leadership will get better
results is very much an open question.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication what Yusuf might do next or what would
happen to his immediate subordinates, although there was
speculation that some of them might be dismissed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Yusuf, a banking industry executive, was appointed under the
interim administration of Wahid's predecessor, B.J. Habibie, and
had earned the respect of the foreign bankers and investors whose
funds are crucial to raising the money necessary for Indonesia's
bank bailout.
</P>
<P>
   But Yusuf's close relationships with overseas financiers, as
well as his continued membership on the board of a securities firm
paid to advise the agency, had led to criticism by Indonesian
politicians that he had conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Yusuf and the agency became embroiled in a corruption
scandal after approving payments to Bank Bali that ended up at a
company controlled by the former ruling party. Though Yusuf was
never directly implicated, his reputation never recovered and the
agency's efforts to sell assets and repay interbank loans were
weakened.
</P>
<P>
   World of Yusuf's dismissal had little effect on Indonesia's
financial markets, partly because there had been some expectation
that it would happen at some point. The rupiah, the domestic
currency, weakened marginally to 7,135 to the dollar from 7,035
Tuesday, and Indonesia stocks fell 1 percent amid a broader retreat
in Asia shares.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid had named Cacuk vice chairman of the agency in November,
when he moved it out from under the Ministry of Finance and put it
under his direct control, ostensibly to make it more independent.
</P>
<P>
   Cacuk, formerly president director of the telecommunications
monopoly PT Telekomunikasi Indonesia, brings in a reputation as a
capable manager unsullied by links to the Suharto regime.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Muslim parties are also said to support Cacuk, and
analysts said there was a chance Cacuk might adopt their calls for
the agency to take a more populist role in revamping Indonesia's
economy, perhaps trying to redistribute assets to native
Indonesians rather than sell them to the highest-bidding
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Cacuk is also close to the former minister of cooperatives and
small enterprises, Adi Sasono, who has called for the creation of a
``people's economy.'' Early last year, Cacuk resigned as director
general of small-scale enterprises development to lead Sasono's
People's Sovereignty Party. Cacuk has said he is no longer a member
of the party and has denied any allegiance to Sasono.
</P>
</TEXT>
