<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT &LR;      01-12 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREMLIN RELEASES VIDEO IT CLAIMS LINKS CHECHENS TO TERROR
BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Kremlin on Wednesday offered what it called proof
that militants in Chechnya masterminded terrorist bombings last
fall at several Russian apartment houses: a video tour of a Chechen
bomb factory, replete with thumping music.
</P>
<P>
   The film of the factory, which officials said contained
explosives identical to those used in the bombings, appeared to
offer circumstantial evidence at best that the militants were
behind the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   But the secretary of the Russian government's security council,
Sergei Ivanov, said Russian forces are seeking two individuals in
Grozny and in rebel-held southern Chechnya who they believe are
tied to the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been charged in the bombings, which destroyed a
Russian barracks in Dagestan and vast apartment blocks in Moscow
and the southwest Russian town of Volgodonsk. More than 300
civilians were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen rebel leaders have denied any role in the bombings. The
most cynical Russians have suggested that the government itself
staged the blasts to fan nationalistic political support of the
Kremlin, a charge Ivanov on Wednesday called crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said Wednesday's release of the video was meant in part
to put such rumors to rest. ``This film proves the indisputable
link of the explosions to Chechnya,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The video was shot by the Federal Security Service, the
successor agency to the Soviet KGB. It depicts sites in
Urus-Martan, a town about 10 miles southwest of the Chechen
capital, Grozny, in which the Kremlin says bombs were made and
slave laborers and condemned prisoners were kept penned in cells.
</P>
<P>
   Among the scenes on the film are shots of containers said to be
filled with explosives; mixing vats, and bomb components such as
alarm clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said the sites held ammonium nitrate, a highly explosive
ingredient used in the apartment-house bombings, and a small amount
of hexagen, another explosive compound found in traces of the
terrorist bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the vigorous actions of our army, the militants
didn't manage to take everything out of these bases,'' he said.
``They left behind explosives that were identical to the ones used
in the explosions'' in Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the same ingredients, he said, were also used in car
bombings in 1998 in Uzbekistan, a former Soviet republic, in which
13 people died and more than 100 were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   He also charged that the rebels had executed 700 civilians who
refused to assist them and 300 hostages who were being held for
ransom. There was no way to corroborate those figures.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both Russian and Chechen propagandists have been
hurling wildly inflated accusations throughout the war, as well as
gross underestimations of their own casualties and battlefield
mistakes, so it is difficult to separate the war's truth from its
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, each side has complained that the other side
massacred civilians and waged chemical warfare. The latter charge
apparently stemmed from the bombing _ accidental or otherwise _ of
some chlorine tanks near Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's video could contain compelling evidence of Chechen
terrorist activity. Or it could simply be an element of the
Kremlin's effort to bolster support for the war at a time when
Russian troops are taking their heaviest losses yet, and when the
once-pliant media are growing restive.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov allowed Wednesday that the Kremlin is locked in an
``information war'' with the Chechen militants, a war that, he
said, was ``at least as fierce as combat in the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1922EST &QL; 
