<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-PEDOPHILIA-ART     01-12 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-PEDOPHILIA-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF SEX, VIOLENCE AND GREED IN A SMALL TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELBURNE, Nova Scotia _ Five years ago, this seaside fishing
village of gabled roofs and colonial alleys served as a movie set
for ``The Scarlet Letter.'' But in real life the witch hunt
haunting Shelburne revolves not around ``A'' for adulterer but
``P'' for pedophile.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 Patrick McDougall, a former employee of Shelburne School
for Boys, a provincial reformatory here, was convicted of sexually
abusing several boys in the 1960s and 1970s. He died in jail last
year.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial received wide publicity, 89 other former
residents of Nova Scotia's three reform schools came forward and
charged that they, too, had been physically or sexually abused
decades ago by him and other staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing an avalanche of lawsuits, the Nova Scotia provincial
government set up a $25 million compensation fund for victims.
Setting aside due process and the concept that the accused were
innocent until proven guilty, the government decided that the
complaints would be accepted largely on face value.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread like wildfire. The government advertised the fund in
newspapers. In some prisons, lawyers posted what inmates nicknamed
``the meat chart,'' an official compensation scale that ranged from
$3,500 for physical abuse up to $85,000 for sexual assault. Within
18 months the number of accusers ballooned to about 1,400, the
number of accusations into the thousands and the number of accused
to 363.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know of any employee who has not been accused,'' Lee
Keating, a former supervisor, said in an interview at a dockside
restaurant here. ``The original intent was to pay off a few
claimants, quick and dirty, and then sweep the whole matter under
the rug.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating says police investigators questioned him about only 20
of the approximately 75 allegations against him that were settled
with cash payments. He says that he is innocent and that the
government refuses to let him see details of the accusations or to
identify the accusers.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron S. McKinnon, a lawyer for Keating and 84 other former
reform school employees, said, ``In many cases our clients were not
even asked their side of the story before payments were made.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon contends that physical evidence has been largely
ignored. Pressed to make payments within 45 days of a complaint,
the fund administrators paid one former resident for an assault
that was alleged to have resulted in broken bones, even though
there were no medical records or contemporary X-rays to back up the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Another former resident, he said, received compensation for an
assault by an employee, even though records showed that the man no
longer worked at the school on the date of the alleged attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like going to buy the lottery ticket when you already
know the numbers,'' McKinnon said of the payment system.
Calculating the total number of claims at 14,500, he said,
``Fourteen thousand five hundred claims that went undetected over
40 years? It doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years two former Shelburne employees have committed
suicide on learning that they had been accused of sexual abuse.
After newspapers reported the suicide of one man who had been
accused, William Belliveau, about 20 other former residents filed
similar claims against him. Later, Royal Canadian Mounted Police
investigators cleared Belliveau of the original charge.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of the program, Anne Derrick, a lawyer for 450 former
residents, complained that a compassionate program has been
``turned on its head'' by critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe there was a significant amount of abusive
activity,'' she said, referring to violence at the reform schools.
``But you are talking, in some cases, about what happened 50 years
ago. There are no records. There are no witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that ``there is undoubtedly a certain amount of
fraud,'' but questioned why the accused were angry, noting that
``the money is not coming out of their pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   To some the controversy revolves around applying late 1990s
standards to 1960s behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the physical abuse was just the kind of smacking
around that the person got at home,'' said Terry Turple, a former
Shelburne resident who is now a house painter in Halifax and who
declined offers to file a suit. ``People getting whacked around was
more or less an every day thing there. We more or less accepted it.
We were bad kids in reform school.''
</P>
<P>
   With the initial compensation fund exhausted, the government has
added $8 million more. Millions more have been spent on an
investigation by the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, in what has
become one of the largest investigations in its history. But after
five years, there have been no new indictments for sexual or
physical abuse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reducing the scope of the Mounties' investigation, 403 payment
recipients signed waivers saying they did not want criminal
investigations of their abuse accusations. About 330 of the former
residents who came forward filed abuse claims against McDougall,
the convicted sex abuser who is now dead.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Mounties announced they had just located 7,000
boxes of files from the era _ time cards, employee shift schedules
and expense claim forms. These will have to be digested before any
indictments can be announced, said Sgt. Wayne Noonan, the Mounties'
spokesman for Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be charges,'' he said of the abuse allegations.
Noting that only 63 accusations of fraud over compensation claims
have been forwarded to the commercial crimes section, he said he
concludes that abuse of the compensation program was ``not
widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nova Scotia is now feeling pressure from national scrutiny
to take another look at how it has handled the matter. In
mid-November, Canada's respected public television network, CBC,
called the payout program ``too bad to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Wente, a Globe and Mail newspaper columnist in Toronto,
wrote that ``the real victims of the Shelburne scandal'' are ``the
vast majority of employees who dedicated their lives to helping
troubled kids, and are now seeing their names, reputations and life
work smeared forever by allegations of hideous crimes they never
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the provincial government has commissioned an
independent inquiry. To head the audit, they reached out to Quebec
to hire a retired judge, Fred R. Kaufman. In Halifax, the
compensation program has become such an industry, employing 144
lawyers, that the government was unable to find a member of the
local legal community who was not involved in it.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, most Shelburne employees were cowed into silence by
the combined weight of a hostile press and the government
investigation. Keating had time to mull over the situation when he
worked as a carpenter on the ``Scarlet Letter'' movie set here.
Speaking on a recent evening as chairman of a new group, Past
Employees for Restorative Justice, he said in a clear voice: ``We
want exoneration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CUBABOY-0113-COX     01-12 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBABOY-0113-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    RENO INSISTS FATHER HAS RIGHT TO CUSTODY OF CUBAN BOY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international, (a) national and (w) Washington
categories 
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The war of words over 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian
Gonzalez escalated Wednesday as his Miami relatives vowed not to
turn him over voluntarily and to file a federal lawsuit after
Attorney General Janet Reno brushed aside a Florida court ruling
that gave them temporary custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to turn over the boy,'' said Juan
Garcia-Pedrosa(cq), one of the family's attorneys. ``They either
have to take him by force, which would be scandalous, or they have
to go to federal court.''
</P>
<P>
   The family plans to file a federal lawsuit next week seeking to
keep Elian in this country, attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, meanwhile, lifted a Friday deadline for returning Elian to
his father in Cuba, saying the matter should be resolved in federal
court. But she firmly rejected a ruling on Monday by a Miami-Dade
County Family Court judge that gave temporary custody of Elian to
his Miami relatives, saying the court's order had ``no force or
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, the question of who may speak for a six-year-old child
in applying for admission or asylum is a matter of federal
immigration law,'' Reno said in a letter to attorneys for Elian's
Miami family.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Miami's volatile exile Cuban community called for the
public to remain calm in the aftermath of the latest developments,
although they warned that they are ready to call for new
demonstrations like the ones last week that tangled traffic and led
to more than 100 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use civil disobedience as a last resort,'' said
Ramon Saul Sanchez(cq), leader of the anti-Communist Democracy
Movement. ``But we are ready to use it if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The furor over Elian has grown steadily since he was found
clinging to an inner tube off Fort Lauderdale on Thanksgiving Day.
His mother and nine other people drowned after their cramped, tiny
boat sank in choppy seas during their attempt to flee Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the tug-of-war over the child has resembled a cross
between a soap opera and political theater, with U.S. presidential
candidates weighing in on the case even as protestors in Miami and
Cuba staged competing demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 5, U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Commissioner
Doris Meissner(cq) announced that Elian must go back to his father
in Cuba. The agency interviewed Juan Miguel Gonzalez twice in Cuba
and found him to be a loving, reliable father who wants his son
returned home, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision touched off a firestorm of protest in Miami, where
Cuban-American activists have made young Elian a cause celebre.
Chanting, flag-waving protestors took to the streets, vowing to
form a human chain around the Little Havana home of his
great-uncle.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, they insisted, is not free to speak his true
feelings on the matter because he is controlled by Cuban dictator
Fidel Castro. Sending Elian back to Cuba would subject him to
harassment, scorn and a dismal future, protesters said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Miami-Dade County Family Court Judge Rosa
Rodriguez(cq) agreed that the risk of such treatment was real, and
granted temporary custody to Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro
Gonzalez(cq). She also set a March 6 hearing on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts, however, were nearly unanimous in saying the
family court had no jurisdiction over an immigration case, the same
point made by Reno Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, news reports surfaced that Judge Rodriguez had
employed a spokesman for Elian's Miami family in her last political
campaign. The judge insisted she had no obligation to disclose the
matter, although some legal experts said she should have withdrawn
from the case to avoid the appearance of any impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   The matter now seems moot, as Elian's fate seems likely to be
decided in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   But the politics swirling around the case aren't likely to
disappear. Cuban-Americans in Congress have allied with
conservatives in proposing a special act granting Elian U.S.
citizenship, a move that would change his immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., has also issued a subpoena requesting
that Elian testify before a House committee, a ploy that Burton
admitted was aimed at keeping him in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's case has dominated the South Florida media for weeks,
with screaming headlines and breathless ``exclusive'' reports
breaking into normal programming. At one point television
helicopters hovered overhead, filming as the boy was whisked into a
car and taken home from his elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a mini-furor erupted when Miami television station
WPLG aired a tape of Elian playing in his yard. As a huge airplane
roars overhead, the boy jumps up and down and yells something about
going back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The station aired the tape, saying Elian apparently said he
wanted to go back to Cuba. That prompted a flood of angry telephone
calls and blistering criticism on Miami's ubiquitous Spanish talk
radio.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the station followed up by taking the tape onto
the streets of Miami and asking Spanish-speakers to view it. Half
those shown the report said Elian said he wanted to go home to
Cuba, but half thought the boy said just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, meanwhile, Elian's father hasn't been seen in several
days. He spoke with great emotion last week at a huge rally, saying
he will never go to Florida and that his son should be returned.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's maternal grandmother, Raquel Rodriguez, told reporters
Wednesday that the boy was kidnapped for the voyage to Florida and
that Elian's mother was tricked by her boyfriend into making the
journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my only daughter and my only grandson,'' she said,
arranging gifts around a Christmas tree she said she has kept ready
for Elian's return.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox News Service Staff Writer Larry Lipman contributed to this
report).
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
