<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4305 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-TOUR-SPI &LR;      01-12 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABELING SHOULD BE ABOUT SHOW'S QUALITY, NOT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ No midseason show is getting more buzz than
CBS's ``City of Angels,'' an ensemble hospital drama from Steven
Bochco that features a predominantly black cast. Bochco himself
calls it a ``black drama,'' even though he's never called ``NYPD
Blue'' a ``white drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochco is a master of market manipulation, so it's impossible
not to wonder if he's trying to deflect attention away from the
quality of the show by focusing on its racial makeup and its
significance as a sort of socio-political litmus test. (Early
consensus among critics gathered in Pasadena this week is that
``City of Angels'' isn't bad, but it's not great. At least not
yet.)
</P>
<P>
   Co-creator Paris Barclay, who is black, doesn't mind calling it
a black drama. ``You have to find a way to describe stuff,'' he
said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with just calling it another drama? I don't
recall ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' _ a beautifully crafted
series _ being described as a ``black'' or ``ethnic'' drama.
Critics who adored the show usually called it a very good drama
with fine acting and spectacular writing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Warren, an alumnus of Bochco's ``Hill Street Blues'' and
one of the stars of ``City of Angels,'' differs with Bochco on
labeling the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately it's all about stories,'' he said. ``I think that
if you put white characters in some of the stories they've created,
you will have a white point of view, but if you create interesting
characters it really doesn't matter who plays them.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, though he sems to be blowing the trumpet the
loudest, Bochco admitted that he hopes ``we don't get buried under
the burden of our historical significance.'' Seems to me that
calling it something other than a ``black drama'' would help.
``City of Angels'' premieres Sunday night, then moves to its
regular slot, Wednesdays, on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   _It's hard to let go of a profitable franchise. Executives at
Fox are still hoping ``The X-Files'' will return for an eighth
season, even though creator Chris Carter has said he's treating
this season as the last and the show's stars, David Duchovny and
Gillian Anderson, have been saying they're ready to move on, even
though Anderson is under contract for one more year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd probably say it's no better than 50/50,'' Fox
Entertainment Group chairman Sandy Grushow said this week, ``but I
can tell you our agenda is to try to get this show to come back for
an eighth season.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether it might resurface without Duchovny, Grushow said,
``We're really not there yet. ... If, in fact, we get to a point
that it's clear that David Duchovny absolutely, categorically
refuses to do another season of this show, I think that decision is
really going to rest with Chris Carter. If Chris Carter believes he
can make an eighth season of `The X-Files' without David Duchovny _
we bet on Chris thus far, we'd keep betting on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Grushow said that, logistically speaking, push will come to
shove on the ``X-Files'' question in about a month. He said he
believes Carter ``in his heart wants to come back.'' As for
Duchovny, he said, ``Everything is a negotiation in our business,
so there's all kinds of posturing going on. One of two things is
probably true: Either David definitely doesn't want to come back
... or his representatives are saying he doesn't want to come back
so as to drive up his price for coming back. Welcome to our
world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
