<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-HEY-DAD-TEX     01-12 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEY-DAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATION? WITH KIDS? FORGET IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Didn't you people learn ANYTHING from Chevy Chase? How to cover
a bald spot, how to execute a pratfall, how to fail in increasingly
interesting ways? Most important, haven't you learned from him _
well, not from him, technically, but from his portrayal of Clark
Griswold _ not to take your kids on vacation?
</P>
<P>
   You've seen his ``Vacation'' movies, right? They are, after all,
the ultimate collection of similarly themed films within the Chase
oeuvre _ and wacky to boot. The Griswold family loads up the kids
and heads to a favorite vacation spot (or, in the case of
``Christmas Vacation,'' other relatives head to the Griswold
household), only to be beset by mishaps so wackily amusing as to be
considered highly wacky. Most people blame Chase/Griswold for the
unending mischance and misfortune endured by his family, but I know
otherwise: It's the kids' fault.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappiness follows when you bring the little missy/nipper on
vacation, no matter your good intentions. This is not a new
concept, so why don't you get it, people? How do I know? I have
just returned from a week in our nation's fine capital, wherein the
lovely Mrs. Hey Dad and I spent our evenings frolicking in a
no-child-attached euphoria. We ate at fine restaurants, drank
splendid adult beverages, even kissed under the fireworks at the
Washington Monument on New Year's Eve. Most gloriously, we slept
till noon.
</P>
<P>
   It was relaxing, invigorating, good for the ol' _ and I do mean
ol' _ marital state. But those poor, silly tourists I saw dragging
their tired, whining children about had only themselves to blame.
Walking near the Lincoln Memorial, I saw one father literally
carrying two boys by their respective arms as one scream-cried, the
other pleaded for salvation. ``BUT I DON'T WANNA SEE ANOTHER
STATUE, DAAADYYY!''
</P>
<P>
   Of COURSE the toddlers and teens were leading vacations of
not-so-quiet desperation. They were bored. You can't watch ``Dragon
Ball Z'' at the Lincoln Memorial. You will not catch 'em all at the
National Archives, no matter if you gotta. And just try to play
Quidditch at the Corcoran Gallery of Art. These are the things
little kids enjoy: fantasy, new worlds, television. Those, and
Disney World, because there you can ride rides, get ice cream, talk
to giant mice. Kids are excited about vacations only when they
think it's an ``adventure.'' My daughter had a blast spending a
week in the woods with her grandmother, playing in the creek and
chasing birds. Simple fun is all a kid wants on a getaway. A friend
tells a story about the couple who took their kids on vacation, and
the munchkins were thrilled until they found they were supposed to
leave the hotel, since all they wanted to do was swim and call room
service.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers, or ``apathetic brats'' as they're sometimes called,
aren't any better. Sure, they understand more; maybe they've even
heard of Abraham Lincoln from watching that weird ``Star Trek''
episode where he's floating in front of the ``Enterprise,'' but
they don't care. Create a vacation spot with a Limp Bizkit
Monument, and they'd be stoked.
</P>
<P>
   There is a preteen age that children reach when they have enough
knowledge to appreciate history or architecture or pretty lights or
whatever it is that your vacation spot offers, and they are old
enough not to complain if they have to leave the Holiday Inn pool
to go sightseeing. These are called ``9-year-olds.'' But even they
probably aren't getting out of the trip what you, in some deluded
state of parental hopefulness (''Honey, it will be GOOD for
them''), had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into a mother with her 9ish-year-old at the American
History Museum, as I was touring the exhibit on the first ladies.
(Yes, I'm a dork.) They came upon a picture of Eleanor Roosevelt.
The young lass studied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, she isn't like, TOTALLY ugly, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, honey. Somewhere between ugly and cute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right. Mom, I'm hungry. Is there a Burger King here?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
