<SLUG> BC-GOP-OLD-SOUTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEDERATE TRADITIONS HAUNT PRESIDENTIAL RACE IN SOUTH CAROLINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, S.C. _ The Civil War is history, but ghosts of the
Old South can still haunt political campaigns, including the race
between George W. Bush and John McCain for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   With the Feb. 19 South Carolina primary looming as a potentially
pivotal showdown between the Texas governor and the Arizona
senator, regional issues and traditions in this state _ including
the Confederate flag and historic plantations _ can take on a life
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolinians have been arguing for months, for example,
over whether the Confederate flag should continue to fly over the
state Capitol in Columbia alongside the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning in New Hampshire, McCain sought to clarify his
position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he has made a number of conflicting statements about
the flag, which is embraced by conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he viewed the flag as a ``symbol of heritage'' but
recognized that South Carolinians would have to resolve the
emotional issues.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move for a politician who generally likes to speak
without using notes or props, McCain pulled out a paper and read
his formal position.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to how I view the flag I understand both sides,'' he said.
``Some view it as a symbol of slavery. Others view it as a symbol
of heritage. Personally I see the flag as a symbol of heritage. I
have ancestors who fought for the Confederacy, none of whom owned
slaves. I believe they fought admirably.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he had resorted to reading his position to avoid any
ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's gotten very Talmudic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refuses to take sides, even though he is greeted with the
flag question every time he comes to South Carolina. It happened
again Wednesday, and his answer remained the same:
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it (the flag question) as a local issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been preaching outreach to minority voters but has
been attracting mostly whites to recent campaign appearances, also
found himself defending his campaign's decision to hold a Tuesday
night rally at a South Carolina plantation, which once used slave
labor.
</P>
<P>
   Boone Hall, a sprawling plantation and popular tourist
attraction, is only a few miles from Charleston Harbor, where the
first shots in the Civil War were fired on Fort Sumter.
</P>
<P>
   An oyster roast hosted by Bush's South Carolina supporters
attracted several hundred people. It was held under a large white
tent erected near the main plantation house and only a few hundred
yards from a row of old slave quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boone Hall is a place where people hold public functions all
the time,'' Bush replied, when questioned about the plantation at a
news conference. He said he had been told that South Carolina's
Democratic governor had attended a function there on the previous
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shouldn't read into venue locations someone's heart,''
Bush added. ``I've got a lot of work to do in the minority
communities, and I recognize that, and I'm going to reach out to
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush received at least 40 percent of the Hispanic vote and a
significant share of the black vote during his 1998 re-election
race in Texas. He said he believed he would win votes in his
presidential campaign ``based upon public policy, and talking about
education and opportunity and economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was shouldered with a report that state Sen. Arthur
Ravenel of Charleston, a minor Bush supporter, had recently called
the NAACP ``the National Association of Retarded Persons.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights organization has threatened a tourist boycott
of South Carolina unless the rebel colors come down.
</P>
<P>
   Ravenel, who contributed $25 to Bush's re-election effort but
has no role in the governor's presidential campaign, said the
remark was a ``slip of the tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Ravenel's comments were ``unfortunate name-calling''
but said it would be up to the senator whether to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday in Wilmington, Del., Bush showcased his
``compassionate conservative'' credentials by touring the Ministry
of Caring, a non-profit, tax-exempt organization offering services
to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know oftentimes people with the word, Republican, by their
name are labeled, and I would like to break the label,'' he said in
a meeting with several caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters later that the label he was trying to break
was an assumption by many people that ``Republicans can't connect
or don't care about African-Americans or the downtrodden.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Bennett Roth contributed to this story from
Dublin, N.H. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
