<HEADER>
A4315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-GRANDPARENTS-1S     01-12 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-GRANDPARENTS-1STLD-WROTETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT WEIGHS VISITATION RIGHTS FOR GRANDPARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: RECASTS first three grafs)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Supreme Court struggled Wednesday with
arguments over whether Washington state's highest court made a
mistake last year when it ruled that parents there have a nearly
absolute right to restrict their children's access to anyone,
including grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Supreme Court ruled that parents can bar
grandparent visitation even when a neutral judge has determined
that such contact would be in the ``best interest'' of the
children.
</P>
<P>
   The state court's decision invalidated a Washington law that
allowed any person _ relative or non-relative _ to seek visitation
rights claiming they would be in the child's best
interest.Wednesday's highly-charged case has potentially
wide-ranging implications, not only for family life in general but
also for an emerging area of law that seeks to establish that
children have their own rights that may supersede those of their
parents. In hearing the arguments, several of the U.S. Supreme
Court justices appeared to lean toward giving parents the final say
in how their children are raised unless an outside party, such as a
grandparent or a court, could show that the children were being
harmed by the parents' decision.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist noted past rulings that gave
parents the right to decide how their youngsters would be brought
up and whom they were allowed to see.
</P>
<P>
   He added that reinstating the Washington law might result in
numerous court challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this mean next that a great aunt can come in and say, `I
want take the child to the movies every week because it's in the
best interest of the child to have a relationship with his great
aunt'?'' Rehnquist asked.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said the law's reliance on the
phrase ``in the child's best interest'' made the statute
``breathtakingly broad'' and meant that ``anyone can march in and
seek visitation rights to any child.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia also voiced strong concerns about the
so-called ``best-interest'' standard. ``It would be in the best
interest of many children to take them away from their parents and
give them to someone else. But the parents have rights,'' he
said.Justices Stephen G. Breyer and Ruth Bader Ginsburg also
questioned the Washington law. But Breyer, along with Justice David
Souter, also said there is a ``special relationship'' between some
grandparents and grandchildren that should be taken into account in
law.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's case involves an effort by Jenifer and Gary Troxel
from Anacortes, Wash., to see their two granddaughters, Natalie,
10, and Isabelle, 8, on a regular basis. The Troxels' son, Brad,
who fathered the two girls but never married their mother,
committed suicide in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels wanted to have the two girls visit twice a month,
but their mother, Tommie Granville Wynn, wanted to limit the visits
to once a month.Wynn had married a man with several children and
claimed that arranging a visit every two weeks with the
grandparents would be too complicated and time-consuming. Unable to
reach an agreement with Wynn, the Troxels sued in 1995.Later that
year a trial judge ruled in the Troxels' favor, but in a 5-4 vote
the state Supreme Court overturned his decision in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``A parent's constitutionally protected right to rear his or her
children without state interference has been recognized as a
fundamental liberty interest,'' the state court said in its ruling.
``Parents have a right to limit the visitation of their children
with other persons.'' But Mark Olson, a Seattle lawyer for the
Troxels, told the high court that granting the opportunity for
children to see their grandparents isn't a serious intrusion into
parents' constitutional right to family privacy, and that in some
states the right of grandparents to see their grandchildren is
protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court should balance all interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Catherine Smith, a Seattle lawyer for Wynn, argued that
courts should stay out of private family decisions. ``Courts should
not micro-manage families when no one is showing any harm to the
child,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The case is one of the most closely watched of the term and has
prompted friend-of-the-court briefs from many organizations and
more than a dozen states.Among those groups siding with the Troxels
are the American Association of Retired Persons (AARP), the
National Conference of State Legislatures, National League of
Cities and U.S. Conference of Mayors. Wynn is supported by
organizations that span the ideological spectrum from the American
Civil Liberties Union and gay-rights groups to the Christian Legal
Society.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states have some kind of grandparent-visitation law. In
some states, courts can order visits for grandparents only if
parents are deceased, divorced or unmarried. Some state laws
require proof of a close relationship between children and
grandparents before visits can be ordered. Still others insist that
courts consider the effect of such visits on parent-child
relationships. All states require that judges must determine,
before they permit visits between children and their grandparents,
whether such visits are in the best interest of the child.Some 31
percent of Americans, about 60 million people, are grandparents.
They include Rehnquist, O'Connor, Scalia, Ginsburg, Justice Anthony
Kennedy and Justice John Paul Stevens. Justice Clarence Thomas was
raised by his grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   An AARP survey released last week found about one in nine
grandparents over the age of 50 helps care for at least one
grandchild. The survey said 8 percent provide day care regularly
and 3 percent function as parents, rearing a grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
