u f BC-MA-POVERTY-BOS &LR;      01-12 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-POVERTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25% OF BAY STATE FAMILIES NOT EARNING ENOUGH: STUDY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the nation entering the ninth year of an economic
boom, one in four Massachusetts families still do not earn enough
to pay for the rising costs of housing, child care, and health
care, according to a study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, sponsored by the Women's Educational and Industrial
Union, portrayed the federal government's ``poverty level'' _
$16,700 a year for a family of four _ as an outmoded measure of
what it takes to support a basic standard of living. WEIU's
``sufficiency'' incomes range from $15,888 a year for a single
adult living in Boston to nearly $43,000 for a Boston family with
one toddler and one child in school.
</P>
<P>
   When sufficiency incomes are applied across the state, WEIU said
there are 602,100 families _ about one-quarter of all Massachusetts
families _ that do not earn enough money.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are a striking counterpoint to the economic
expansion, which in February will become the longest in US history
and has bestowed vast riches on the top tier of wealthy Americans
who own businesses or invest in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this wonderful, buoyant Nasdaq economy, most of the gains
have gone to the top,'' said former labor Secretary Robert Reich.
The standard of living for typical wage earners, he said, ``is
actually going nowhere. The person smack in the middle hasn't seen
much change, and the people below that are struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the median income is 5 percent lower than a
decade ago, despite a sharp drop in the state's unemployment rate
that has put many low-income individuals, especially minorities,
into the work force.
</P>
<P>
   Reich said families who earn too much to qualify for public aid
but are below WEIU's ``sufficiency'' income are ``caught in the
gap.'' Statewide, while 9 percent of the population is in poverty,
fully 27 percent of all families are below the income standards set
by WEIU.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of WEIU's income standards for families said they are
biased toward families with very young children whose child-care
costs are much higher than for, say, a family with two teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   But the study's authors, Laura Henze Russell of the WEIU and
Jean Bacon, a professor of sociology at Williams College, believe
their ``self-sufficiency'' standard is a more accurate measure of
living costs than are federal poverty guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty level was determined roughly by estimating the cost
of feeding a family and multiplying it by three. It was established
in the 1960s, before women entered the work force in droves and
families began paying for child care. Moreover, housing and health
care costs have risen much faster than food, factors that make the
inflation-adjusted poverty standard obsolete, WEIU said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal poverty line ``dramatically underestimates how many
families are struggling,'' Reich said.
</P>
<P>
   The authors urged state and federal lawmakers to adopt the
self-sufficiency standards as a first step toward changing
policies, from taxes to adult education, that would help a broader
group of struggling working Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend two-thirds of my income just on housing and food,''
said Maria Andrade of Dorchester, a single mother who is raising
three children, ages 5, 12, and 16, on her $30,000 annual salary.
</P>
<P>
   Policies that would help people like Andrade include tax relief
for working families, which is entering the political debate as the
candidates head into primary season. Republican candidates are
promising to slash taxes for all Americans, while President Clinton
this week proposed expanding the earned income tax credit for
working poor. Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley has
made poverty a central theme of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is doing more than most states to help low-wage
workers, the WEIU said. State lawmakers late last year raised in
the state's earned income tax credit to 15 percent of the federal
credit, up from 10 percent. State deductions for child and
dependent care, and the deduction for rent, also were raised.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the income levels looked at provide families with
only a ``bare-bones budget'' that does not include extra money for
savings, loan payments, or emergency funds.
</P>
<P>
   Across Massachusetts, the percent of families below the
self-sufficiency standard varied widely among cities and towns,
from 22 percent in Weymouth to 45 percent in Lawrence. Boston was
in the middle, with 34 percent under the standard.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors heavily influence how well a family is doing
financially: the number of children and the number of wage earners.
More children add huge expenses due to child-care costs. Bacon said
that a family with a second wage earner ``makes a big difference''
in improving a family's living standard.
</P>
<P>
   But expenses also rise dramatically for families with two
children or young children who require full-time day care. Over
three-fourths of children in Massachusetts are under 12 years of
age.
</P>
<P>
   WEIU's income standards vary widely by family size and by
geography: A single adult living in Boston needs $15,888 to live,
while earnings for a two-parent family with one preschool and one
school-age child living in Boston would need to be as high as
$42,564. The same four-member family living in Pittsfield would
need $35,100.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the ``average'' family pays $721 a month for housing,
$408 for taxes, $301 for child care and $276 for food.
</P>
<P>
   A single-parent family in Boston with two children _ one of
pre-school age and one of school age _ needs $39,156, while the
same family in Pittsfield needs $30,492.
</P>
<P>
   For a two-parent family with two teenagers, income requirements
drop dramatically when day care is no longer needed, to $27,720 in
Boston or $24,288 in Pittsfield, WEIU said.
</P>
</TEXT>
