<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE SCHEDULES TRIP TO THE HOLY LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Pope John Paul II will end up juggling delicate
Middle East politics with visits to the wellsprings of his faith,
according to a schedule announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Making public the itinerary for the second papal visit to
Israel, the Vatican said John Paul would tour Israel's memorial to
victims of the Holocaust as well as churches and shrines holy to
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerary, which is being closely analyzed by Israelis and
Palestinians, also includes a visit to a Palestinian refugee camp,
and to Jordan. Palestinians have sought to use the trip, scheduled
for March 20 to 26, to promote their drive for an independent
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The trip also lists stops to sites holy to Judaism and Islam, as
well as meetings with meetings with Palestinian, Jordanian and
Israeli political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials stressed that the main purpose of the visit was
spiritual. It is, they said, a holy pilgrimage by the frail
79-year-old pontiff to the Holy Land, where Christianity was born
and where it began to develop.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Middle East, politics and religion are rarely far
apart. The visit to Jordan, Israel and Palestinian-ruled Bethlehem
may be a spiritual pilgrimage, but it will also be a political
balancing act.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian committee for the pope's visit has planned a
stop in the Dheisheh refugee camp near Bethlehem in the West Bank.
This seems to be an attempt to raise the issue of the plight of
Palestinians who fled or who were forced out of their homes in
Palestine during Israel's fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   What to do about the refugees, whether to offer compensation or
to let some back to their old homes, now inside the Israeli state,
is one of the tougher issues in peace negotiations between Israel
and Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We organized his visit to Dheisheh to see first hand the
living conditions of the Palestinian refugees at the beginning of
the third millennium,'' said Emile Jarjoui, who heads the
Palestinian committee.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrimage may be grueling for the pontiff, who suffers from
symptoms of Parkinson's disease and who has trouble walking. But he
will be accompanied by vehicle called the ``popemobile,'' to keep
him off his feet as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, which established full diplomatic relations with the
Holy See in 1994, has said it welcomes the visit of someone whom it
views as a man of peace and a fighter of racism and anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's trip through the Jewish state will include official
meetings with President Ezer Weizman, Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
the country's chief rabbis and a visit to Yad Vashem, the memorial
to victims of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also will arrange the pontiff's trips to holy sites in
the Galilee, Nazareth and Jerusalem. This will be an intricate
exercise in logistics and security.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrimage could be physically grueling for the pontiff, who
suffers from symptoms of Parkinson's disease, and who has trouble
walking. But he will use the ``Popemobile,'' the vehicle screened
with bullet-proof glass, to keep him off his feet as much as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   In the alleys of Jerusalem's Old City, too narrow for the
Vatican vehicle, Israeli authorities are planning to test-drive a
smaller but equally comfortable limousine to take the pope around
securely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's going to try to read into the trip what they want
from their point of view, but the program's focus is on a Christian
pilgrimage,'' said an Israeli government spokesman, Moshe Fogel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to do everything we can to make his trip a
success,'' Fogel said.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Israel and the Holy See were strained for
decades after the Jewish state was founded in 1948. Israel felt the
Holy See had not done enough to fight the Holocaust while the Roman
Catholic Church backed the internationalization of Jerusalem, and
later was unhappy with Israel's rule over the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty between Israel and the Palestinians in 1993 paved the
way for full relations between the Holy See and Israel. John Paul's
visit will be the first since Pope Paul VI came in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   But in what might be a sign of Israeli uneasiness with some
details of the visit, Israel's Foreign Ministry expressed regret
Wednesday that John Paul would not be able to spend more time
studying the renewal of Jewish life in their holy land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of Israel is convinced that the pope, too,
regrets . . . he will be unable to dedicate more of his time to
study in depth the resurrection and renewal of the Jewish people in
the land of their forefathers,'' the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican said the pope would celebrate Masses in Bethlehem,
Nazareth and Jerusalem, the sites of Jesus' birth, boyhood and
death, and on the Mount of Beatitudes overlooking the Sea of
Galilee, where Jesus made his most celebrated sermons.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican representatives have tried to play down any political
significance to the pope's itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visit will be a spiritual pilgrimage; he is coming to the
Holy Land as a pilgrim, and any type of political explanation is
away from the essential meaning of the visit,'' said the Rev. Raed
Abu Salah, chancellor of the Latin Patriarchate, the Roman Catholic
Church in the Holy Land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
