<HEADER>
A4327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BASEMENT-SUIT-BOS &LR;      01-12 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEMENT-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER EXECUTIVE HITS BASEMENT CHIEF IN SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aisle 3, the new chain that Filene's Basement is hoping will
revitalize the company, is off to a poor start, and one reason the
famous retailer is now operating in bankruptcy protection is its
gross mismanagement, a former top executive named Kathleen Mason
has charged in court filings.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who claims she's owed $1.2 million in severance, also
alleged that chief executive Sam Gerson wants to turn the publicly
traded retailer into a private company.
</P>
<P>
   Citing pending legal action, Filene's Basement spokeswoman Nancy
Sterling declined to make a point-by-point rebuttal, but said of
Mason: ``She is a disgruntled employee, and any allegations,
however outrageous, should be viewed in that context.''
</P>
<P>
   In US Bankruptcy Court filings, Filene's Basement asserted that
Mason's allegations were ``scurrilous'' and ``inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason was one of several executives who held the title of
president at Filene's Basement. Sterling confirmed that the
highest-ranking president, Jay Carothers, had also left the
company, though under friendlier circumstances. Other top
executives remain, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Mason were unsuccessful. A call to her
attorney was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Wellesley-based Filene's Basement Corp. sought
bankruptcy protection, citing cash-flow problems. Over the next few
months, it said it would close 35 stores and reduce its work force
by 1,300 jobs as it looked to save itself by becoming a
lean-and-mean chain with about 22 stores and 3,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who previously held a top job with TJX Cos., joined
Filene's Basement in the late spring as the company's top merchant,
with an annual base salary of $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six months later, as it announced another round of
layoffs, Filene's Basement let Mason go on the grounds that a
smaller chain needed a smaller management team, Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   In court filings, Mason alleged that she was ``fraudulently
induced'' by Gerson to take a job at Filene's Basement.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mason, Gerson told her Filene's Basement was poised
for a dramatic turnaround, thanks to its new weekend-only warehouse
chain called Aisle 3 and a proposed retail Web site under the
direction of Gerson's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Although Filene's Basement had posted a profit only once in the
past five years, Mason, a 20-year veteran in the retail industry,
agreed to sign on with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Once on board, she concluded that Gerson had misrepresented the
condition of Filene's Basement and that Aisle 3 and the Internet
venture were ``failures,'' according to her court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the eight Aisle 3 stores have been open only for several
months. It may be premature to judge the chain as either a success
or a failure.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling declined to discuss sales results for Aisle 3.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mason, it was her reputation with vendors and the
retail financial community that made her valuable to Filene's
Basment; for a time, she claimed she was able to persuade reluctant
vendors to ship merchandise to the stores that they might have
otherwise withheld.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Mason claims to have argued
vehemently with Gerson against filing for Chapter 11, but Gerson
ignored her recommendations to pursue other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents, she alleged: ``Gerson grossly mismanaged the
company and has a personal agenda to take control of the company by
taking it private, which is intended to benefit Gerson personally
rather than shareholders and creditors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason also questioned the competency of some other Filene's
Basement managers and alleged that one executive collected a
six-figure annual salary while taking no active part in the
management of the company.
</P>
<P>
   In its court filings, Filene's Basement described Mason as a
``disruptive'' and ``counterproductive'' employee.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, Sterling said Filene's Basement held auctions
Wednesday to dispose of some of the real estate sites where it has
closed stores. So far, the auctions have raised ``millions of
dollars'' that will be used for operating capital, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement has said previously that it hopes to emerge
from Chapter 11 sometime this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
