A4329 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-EVIL13-COX     01-12 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EVIL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tortured hero faces double dose of `Evil'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deputy Inspector Dave Creegan has this little vertical scar on
his forehead, the result of an old gunshot wound. As you watch the
pressure build and build on him in ``Touching Evil,'' you keep
expecting that scar to start growing down his face, like a crack in
a cinder-block basement wall.
</P>
<P>
   He's that kind of guy, and it's that kind of show.
</P>
<P>
   American TV audiences first met Creegan in 1998, when PBS
imported the British series ``Touching Evil'' as part of its
``Mystery!'' series. Now Creegan and his Organized and Serial Crime
Unit are back for another round of three two-hour stories, doled
out an hour a week.
</P>
<P>
   Creegan (Robson Green) is a driven, obsessive loner, wracked
with guilt for what he has done and what he has failed to do. He's
probably not the jolliest guy to hang out at the pub with, but
definitely the sort you want tracking down psychopathic murderers.
(He makes ``The X-Files''' Fox Mulder look like Robin Williams.)
</P>
<P>
   In the first installment, which starts tonight and concludes
Jan. 20, Creegan has two psychos to contend with. The first one is
easy: a young man named Emerson who is prone to hippy-dippy
babbling about the expanding universe, and who has killed several
young women. Creegan and his crew nail Emerson fairly quickly and
lock him up, only to find that the murders are continuing, and that
Emerson appears to be directing an accomplice or copycat by proxy
from within his jail cell.
</P>
<P>
   As if Creegan needed more problems, his two assistants generally
just muck up the case. Susan Taylor has sex with the tabloid
reporter covering the murders, who may know more than he's telling.
And Mark Rivers is as unsteady as he is ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touching Evil'' takes place in a world of darkness, with light
provided by the cops' flashlights or streaming in from a single
window. It's a shadow universe, almost devoid of colors. The first
part lacks the creepy intensity of the 1998 debut _ where the
killer marked the boys' abduction spots with plastic daffodils _
and overall the series does not quite measure up to the best of
British police procedurals, such as ``Prime Suspect'' and
``Cracker.'' But it's still a worthy watchable for fans of the
genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touching Evil''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on WGTV
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
