u a BC-WIG-SHOP-SLAYINGS-HNS     01-12 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIG-SHOP-SLAYINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSED KILLER MAY LEAVE HOME TO HELP IN DEFENSE CASE, JUDGE SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A 21-year-old former college student who is accused of
killing a wig shop clerk will be allowed to leave his house under
certain conditions so he can help prepare his defense, a judge
ruled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came as Dror Haim Goldberg, who took off on a
globe-trotting backpacking trip before he was indicted, made his
first appearance in state District Judge Joan Campbell's court.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a former University of Houston student, sat quietly in
court next to his father. He's free on $100,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   He must wear an electronic ankle monitor so authorities can
track his movements and is under ``house arrest'' until his trial
for the Nov. 27, 1998, stabbing death of Manuela Silverio.
</P>
<P>
   But defense attorney Dick DeGuerin asked Campbell to allow him
to approach her without the knowledge of prosecutors to get
permission for Goldberg to leave his house to help prepare the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell agreed, but Goldberg must still wear the ankle monitor.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin later said it was essential prosecutors not know about
his requests so they would not try to track his client, though it
wouldn't be too hard considering he's wearing a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution is holding their cards very close and is
refusing to volunteer information about their case, and we don't
have to do it either,'' DeGuerin said. ``Just because he's on bond,
I don't want them to be able to find out what we're working on.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Chuck Rosenthal, who talked with DeGuerin about
discovery issues before the lawyers met with Campbell, said he had
no ``legal objection'' to DeGuerin's request.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said he would be ready for trial May 1, the date
Campbell picked Wednesday for jury selection to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Palmer, the daughter of Silverio, said she and her family
and their supporters would be ready too, though it would be like
going to their mother's funeral each day of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, wearing a small picture of her dead mother on her lapel,
sat behind Goldberg in court Wednesday and said ``it was very
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was (like) cold blood just running straight through your
body,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Silverio, 52, who worked at the wig shop for 23 years, was
stabbed to death at the business. The shop's owners, Roland
Ingrando, and wife, Roberta, survived their stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg was questioned by police shortly after Silverio's
death, but not arrested. Later, authorities said a license-plate
number taken down at the crime scene led investigators to a Lincoln
Navigator registered to a woman living with Goldberg's father, Dr.
Isaac Goldberg, a Houston obstetrician/gynecologist.
</P>
<P>
   Dror Goldberg, who lived a few blocks from the wig shop, was
also reportedly seen running from the location.
</P>
<P>
   But between the time he was questioned and the time he was
indicted for murder in February, Goldberg left the country for the
Middle East, and even his parents did not know where he was,
DeGuerin has said.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin said Goldberg didn't find out about the charge until he
called from Bangkok, Thailand, and spoke to his father after seeing
an ad in an internationally distributed newspaper asking him to
call home.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's father arranged for his son to fly from Bangkok to
Frankfurt, Germany, and then to Mexico City, where he would meet
him.
</P>
<P>
   DeGuerin has said the two planned to fly to Houston, and
Goldberg was to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   But in June, authorities arrested Goldberg in Frankfurt
preparing to board the plane for Mexico. He remained in a German
jail for months while his extradition to the United States was
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   He was brought back to Houston by U.S. marshals Dec. 17 and
turned over to local authorities. Campbell ordered him to surrender
his passport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
