<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-EUROPE-FOOD-NYT &LR;      01-12 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-FOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSION PROPOSES CREATION OF A EUROPEAN FOOD SAFETY AGENCY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the wake of repeated food scandals on this continent,
the European Commission Wednesday proposed the creation of a food
safety agency for all member countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal fell far short of what some consumer groups had
hoped for, since it envisioned a rather small advisory body of
scientists, not a powerful independent regulator like the Food and
Drug Administration in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference in Brussels introducing the plan, David
Byrne, the European Union Commissioner for health and consumer
affairs, became more and more defensive as reporters repeatedly
asked him versions of the same question: If the proposed body has
no power to inspect food, seize tainted shipments, punish violators
or propose rules, how effective can it be?
</P>
<P>
   Byrne responded that politicians who, he said, ``are answerable
to the people,'' should be the ones charged with enforcing food
safety, while scientists ``should stick to the lab.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts interviewed later said that existing European
treaties make it legally impossible to create a strong central
regulator and that lingering nationalism, especially about food,
makes it politically unthinkable. For now, they said,
responsibility for clean, safe food will remain with the same
flawed national agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 countries in the European Union are collectively the
world's largest importers and exporters of food. In the last few
years, successive scandals have terrified and disgusted consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or ``mad cow disease,'' struck
first in Britain, forcing the slaughter of more than 4 million cows
by 1998. The French still ban the import of British beef, making
the issue the single touchiest point in relations between the two
countries. The disease has also been found in cows in France and
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, motor oil contaminated with carcinogenic dioxin was
found in animal feed in Belgium. Sewage sludge was found to have
been deliberately added to animal feed in France.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the European Commission's new policy document
Wednesday, Byrne called for a ``major structural change in our
system of food safety'' to restore the public's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shopping cart is one of the most potent weapons on
earth,'' he said, and pointed out that lost confidence hurts
farmers, grocers and even national reputations.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, Europe has ``one of the best
food-safety systems in the world.'' The document he put forth would
essentially leave that system in place while adding a layer of
European Union scientists whose job would be to gather information,
assess risks and issue alerts.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Harrison, a public affairs officer at the Consumers'
Association of Great Britain, called the proposal ``a toothless
watchdog _ a talking shop that offers little prospect of real
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters at the news conference hammered at Byrne. One
journalist pointed out that when the policy document was proposed,
Romano Prodi, the president of the European Commission, mentioned
the FDA as a model. Another said that scientific advisory panels
had been ignored several times lately, including when France most
recently refused to accept British beef.
</P>
<P>
   No budget for the agency has been proposed. Byrne said he
envisioned its employees numbering ``in the hundreds.'' By
contrast, the Food and Drug Administration has 1,100 inspectors and
2,100 scientists, and the U.S. Department of Agriculture has 7,530
meat and poultry inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Only 8 European Union member countries have independent agencies
like the FDA or are creating them. The others rely on local
inspectors or their national agriculture or health departments.
</P>
<P>
   However, because the agriculture departments exist to promote
farming and agribusiness, their inspectors are saddled with the
perception that they will be under pressure to ignore problems or
cover up a crisis. Consequently, some countries are moving to take
those duties away from their agricultural agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission already has a Food and Veterinary Office
in Dublin with about 90 inspectors. Their missions include
spot-checking imported American beef for growth hormones, which are
forbidden here, and responding to reports like the scandal over
dioxin in Belgium. The new policy document envisions strengthening
the office, Byrne said, but he did not explain how beyond saying
that it could be the ``policeman's policeman'' and audit other
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers' groups welcomed the plan's outlines for writing new
laws on 80 topics. They include creating a list of ingredients
permitted in animal feed and other rules for tracking animal
diseases and tracing food ``from plow to plate,'' in order to hold
producers liable.
</P>
<P>
   The policy document also proposed creating new standards for
labeling food with ingredients grown from genetically modified
seeds. On Monday, the Commission approved a rule requiring labels
on food that contains 1 percent or more genetically modified
soybean or corn, most of which presumably would be imported from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray, the director of the European Consumers'
Organization, said of Byrne's report, ``The recipe is OK, but the
proof is in the cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray called it ``unrealistic'' to hope that any European Food
Authority would be as powerful as the FDA in the United States. In
Britain, he said, ``the idea that a European corps of inspectors
could come in and replace existing British inspectors ``is just not
a runner. Would they really accept a guy from a European agency who
happened to be French?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4340 &Cx1f; tdt-z
