<SLUG> BC-AILING-HMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO EXECUTIVES LOSE $1.3M IN `GOLDEN PARACHUTE' PACKAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts officials Wednesday stripped Harvard
Pilgrim Health Care's former chief executive and chief financial
officer of the $1.3 million in ``golden parachute'' severance pay
the two had negotiated when they abruptly left the troubled health
plan last May.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas Reilly said he terminated the
executives' contracts ``for cause,'' and added that it was related
to ``discrepancies that led to the receivership,'' referring to
last week's dramatic state takeover of Harvard Pilgrim to prevent
its financial collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly declined to say whether the state has discovered specinancial decisions that led to the decision to cancel Greenberg's
and Brophy's severance packages. However, one source in the
attorney general's office, who asked not to be named, said, ``We're
not done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance commissioner Linda Ruthardt, the court-appointed
receiver now overseeing Harvard Pilgrim, said her staff has not
``had time to do the forensic audits'' to determine if auditors
should have known earlier about the health plan's disastrous
condition. Such questions may ultimately involve legal liability on
the part of Harvard Pilgrim and its auditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now we honestly don't know,'' Ruthardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators are likely to question Harvard Pilgrim's past
accounting decisions as they attempt to unravel the health plan's
current financial tangle. People familiar with the probe said they
have already begun inquiries into why it took so long to recognize
the depths of Harvard Pilgrim's problems.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators are expected to question health plan officials
as well as outside accountants PricewaterhouseCoopers, which
audited Harvard Pilgrim's yearly financial statements, the
individuals said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials sidestepped questions about whether Harvard
Pilgrim executives should have known earlier what dire straits the
health plan was in _ or may have known. They also declined to
speculate if criminal liability might emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no reason to believe that the information we got last
Tuesday was less than timely and accurate,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt added: ``Of course we believe there was an error or we
it wouldn't be in receivership.'' But she said she couldn't answer
the question of prior knowledge by the HMO's executives or
accountants. ``So far we have no indication that's true,'' she
said. ``That's so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of former Harvard Pilgrim executives' severance
pay appears to have been motivated by a judgment that such
compensation was inappropriate, versus a discovery of specific
management decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys ran the place into the ground and walk away with
millions,'' said one source in the attorney general's office.
``It's offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of the severance packages will cost former
Harvard Pilgrim chief executive Allan I. Greenberg as much as $1.3
million and former financial chief Thomas J. Brophy up to $500,000.
The HMO had already paid Greenberg approximately $330,000 and
Brophy about $204,000 since they resigned, according to the AG's
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly also announced the resignation of Alan R. Morse, who was
Harvard Pilgrim's $175,000-a-year board chairman, retroactive to
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Greenberg, Brophy, and Morse were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg collected an annual salary of $565,000 from Harvard
Pilgrim, while Brophy was paid $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the HMO has not reported what its current CEO Charles
Baker is paid, sources say his salary is just below $500,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, Reilly noted, his actions will save financially
stressed Harvard Pilgrim almost $2 million. That's about 2.5
percent of what the HMO currently owes one its largest creditors,
Partners HealthCare, according to Partners officials.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Heffron, a spokesman for Reilly, said Ruthardt has broad
authority as Harvard Pilgrim's receiver to manage the company,
including termination of ongoing contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a provision in the severance contracts that says
they can be terminated `for cause,' '' Heffron said.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed on what he meant by ``for cause,'' Reilly turned to
J. David Leslie, a specialist in ailing insurance companies who has
been named special assistant attorney general for the Harvard
Pilgrim case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard Pilgrim reported surprising numbers last Monday
evening and Tuesday due to deficiencies in financial accounting
systems of long standing,'' Leslie said. ``Those deficiencies
should not have occurred. Therefore,'' Greenberg and Brophy
``merited termination for cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``surprising numbers'' Leslie referred to, which
precipitated the receivership, was the revelation that the HMO lost
as much as $177 million last year _ $58.5 million more than
projected.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said they had decided not to release Harvard
Pilgrim's current cash-flow numbers, as they had promised earlier
this week. ``It's a constantly changing situation,'' Reilly said.
``Today's numbers looked more favorable than yesterday's.''
</P>
<P>
   He said reports on the HMO's cash and on its leading creditors
would be released at some unspecified time.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt said she signed $5 million in payment checks to
hospitals and other health providers Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
