<HEADLINE>
ACADEMIC RESEARCH IN CHINA IMPERILED BY ARREST, SCHOLARS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Pa., Mass., Australia, Britain, Calif.)  (jw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The arrest here of a Pennsylvania-based Chinese
researcher as he collected historical documents from the Maoist era
has caused an uproar among Western scholars, who say it imperils
academic research and exchanges with China.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, more than 90 China scholars, including many leading
experts from American, Australian and British universities,
released a letter to President Jiang Zemin calling for the
immediate release of the researcher, Yongyi Song.
</P>
<P>
   The letter warns that Song's arrest _ on vague charges of
providing confidential information to foreigners _ could undermine
the academic exchanges that China has fostered over the last two
decades as it sought to modernize and end its former isolation.
Each year, thousands of Chinese students and professors study
abroad while smaller numbers of Western experts visit China to
study its history, politics and society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continued prosecution of this case will make it impossible for
foreign scholars or Chinese scholars associated with foreign
universities to conduct research in open sources in China with the
confidence that they will be safe from criminal prosecution,'' says
the letter, which was faxed to the Chinese Embassy in Washington on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the signers, Michel Oksenberg, a political scientist at
Stanford University and a former senior White House adviser on
China policy, said in an interview that by arresting an academic
researcher who was apparently seeking materials already in the
public domain, China might have violated the basic principles on
which the scholarly exchanges were based.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a sponsor and adviser of students who wish to do research
in China,'' Oksenberg said, ``I have some responsibility to ensure
that their research will not place them, or those in China who
assist them, at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Song, 50, is a researcher and librarian at Dickinson College in
Carlisle, Pa., and an authority on the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution,
when China was in turmoil and largely closed to outsiders. Song has
written a book and numerous articles in Chinese, but is best known
for his exhaustive bibliographic work on that chaotic decade.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer _ as he often had before _ he visited China to
collect materials from the period, including newspapers of the
radical young Red Guards, old books and mimeographed records that
lurk in second-hand book stores, street markets and private
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Many Western and Chinese scholars, including Chinese graduate
students at American universities, routinely engage in the same
kind of historical treasure hunt here.
</P>
<P>
   But on Aug. 7, Song _ a Chinese man who was on the verge of
becoming an American citizen _ was detained by security forces in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   After months of interrogations, on Dec. 24 he was charged with
``the purchase and illegal provision of intelligence to
foreigners.'' The charge is less severe than that for divulging
``state secrets,'' but depending on how the courts define the
gravity of his offense, Song could receive anything from a light
sentence to more than 10 years in prison. No trial date has been
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities have not revealed which of his activities
triggered the arrest. Song's wife, Helen Yao, a jewelry designer
who was detained along with her husband and held for more than two
months, said in a recent interview that when security officers
asked him about particular government documents he had acquired, he
argued that each had formerly been published in public sources.
</P>
<P>
   Roderick MacFarcquhar, a Harvard professor and author of a
multi-volume history of the origins of the Cultural Revolution,
said that the prosecution of Song would create two classes of China
scholars abroad: ``Westerners who can come and go with relative
freedom, and current or former Chinese citizens who will have to
tread very carefully for fear of being arrested or at least having
their relatives harassed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most affected will be Chinese scholars who live and work
in China, who fear that their already limited ability to pursue
historical evidence may be reduced even further. One historian in
Beijing said that he and his colleagues feared that collaborative
research with foreigners might become more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The international group of scholars, organized by David Strand,
a historian of China at Dickinson, also sent a copy of Wednesday's
letter to President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright in the hope that the administration would step up efforts
on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the American Embassy in Beijing said Wednesday
that senior embassy officials had ``brought up the matter of Yongyi
Song several times'' with the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   A subject of endless fascination for historians, the Cultural
Revolution remains among China's most politically sensitive topics,
and accounts published here are carefully censored in an effort to
protect the legitimacy of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mao's banner of continuing revolution, millions of people
were persecuted, imprisoned or killed, schooling came to a halt and
the economy was nearly destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   After Mao's death in 1976, his successors declared the Cultural
Revolution to have been a disastrous mistake and said that Mao had
erred under the baleful influence of a small group of leaders,
including the ``Gang of Four.'' But Mao's achievements greatly
outweighed his missteps, the official line declared, and his memory
as the heroic father of the People's Republic has been carefully
nurtured ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Many key documents from the Cultural Revolution remain in closed
archives, including Beijing directives that may implicate Mao or
other leaders like the revered Prime Minister Zhou Enlai in vicious
purges or other misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   But during the early years of the Cultural Revolution in
particular, competing factions of Red Guards, fanatical young
Maoists, often published leaders' speeches and other documents in
newspapers or other documents. Such materials have been avidly
collected by scholars and libraries, largely without trouble up to
now.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, as word spread about the criminal charges
against Song, members of Congress and the State Department have
expressed concern and China scholars have been up in arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of its unpredictability and the absence of clearly
stated rules,'' said Thomas P. Bernstein, an expert on Chinese
politics at Columbia University, the case was dangerous from the
point of view of anyone doing research on contemporary China.
</P>
<P>
   Strand, the historian and colleague of Song's at Dickinson, said
Wednesday, ``This case strikes at every aspect of the work we do,
both practical and ethical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I think of Song in his jail cell,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
