<HEADER>
A4345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LUXURY-CARS-ART-2TAKE     01-12 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-CARS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN LUXURY CARS OUTSELL CADILLAC AND LINCOLN FOR 1ST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ After capturing a big share of the American market for
small and midsized cars in the 1980s, Japanese automakers set their
sights a decade ago on Cadillac and Lincoln, which had dominated
the American luxury market since the 1930s. Detroit watched and
worried.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac and Lincoln, respectively the luxury divisions of
General Motors and Ford, held their lead through most of the 1990s
_ until last year, when they were passed by not one but two other
carmakers, with a third close on their bumper.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only one of the upstarts _ Lexus, the luxury division of
Toyota Motor Corp. _ was Japanese, and it took second place.
Roaring by the entire field was Mercedes-Benz, which took first
place, while BMW, whose sales were once tiny, pulled nearly even
with Cadillac and Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Outsold 3-1 by American luxury-car brands as recently as 1991,
European-brand luxury cars as a group managed for the first time
last year to accomplish what once seemed impossible: beating
American luxury brands in sales in their home market. Honda's Acura
and Nissan Motor's Infiniti have been also-rans and even Lexus has
been losing ground to the Europeans, especially the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most optimistic European executives had not anticipated
seizing the lead from Cadillac and Lincoln. ``We were surprised,''
said Juergen Hubbert, the DaimlerChrysler AG management board
member who runs Mercedes. ``It was not our target to become number
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Having spent much of the last decade casting nervous glances
across the Pacific, American executives at the North American
International Auto Show here this week are looking warily at the
appeal of cars coming across the Atlantic instead. ``It's not cheap
but it's very fine product and we need to learn from it,'' said
Harry Pearce, the vice chairman of GM, which said on Monday that it
would buy the half of Sweden's Saab that it did not already own.
</P>
<P>
   There is rare unanimity here about how the Europeans surged into
first place. They have the strongest brands, at a time when a
rising stock market and vibrant economy have meant that money is
little object for many buyers. Even so, the Europeans have aimed
many new models to appeal to the so-called entry-level luxury
market that features base model prices of $24,000 to $32,000. And
Americans simply think the latest European models look and drive
better than anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for, quite frankly, more European
proportions,'' said Richard Parry-Jones, Ford's group vice
president for vehicle development.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans focused on driving performance and fresh, crisply
lined models at a time when their American and Japanese rivals were
still producing cautious variations of designs that had done well
in the 1980s. Models like the BMW 3- and 5-series, the Audi TT, the
Jaguar S-Type and the Mercedes E-Class have grabbed the public's
attention in a way that models like the Cadillac Catera, Chrysler
LHS and Lexus ES300 have not.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, European manufacturers have been able to keep
their brand images unusually clear. BMW has been able to associate
its name with driving performance, something that younger drivers
especially value. Volvo Cars, the Swedish manufacturer Ford bought
last year, has coupled its name with safety. Jaguar of Britain,
another Ford subsidiary, is known for elegance, and Mercedes for
square-shouldered reliability.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for European cars is coming from the customers that
automakers covet most: successful young professionals like Joseph
Coviello, a 35-year-old financial adviser in Newark, Del., and his
wife, Karen. Coviello has just bought a BMW M3 convertible; he
owned an M3 sedan before it. Karen Coviello drove a Jeep Grand
Cherokee until two years ago, when the Jeep rolled over and its
roof caved in. She now drives a BMW, too, a 5-series wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like, in no particular order, the style, performance, safety
and reputation,'' Coviello said. ``The BMW literally handles like a
sports car, and if you've not driven one, you can't understand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The European ascendance in luxury cars has come at an especially
disappointing time for American and Japanese luxury car executives.
A decade ago, experts had thought millions of increasingly
prosperous baby boomers would want a little more pampering, and
would migrate to entry-level luxury cars that were just a little
more expensive than their Honda Accords, Toyota Camrys and Ford
Tauruses. Instead, affluent middle-aged buyers snapped up sport
utility vehicles during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Cars' share of the luxury market plummeted from 95 percent in
1990 to just 44 percent in 1996, as automakers introduced new
models like the Jeep Grand Cherokee and GMC Yukon; their share has
now leveled off at about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Holding a shrinking share of a stagnant market segment has been
a new and unpleasant experience for Japanese automakers in
particular. ``I don't think the growth has been there that we
anticipated in that segment of the market,'' said Richard Colliver,
Honda's executive vice president for North American Honda and Acura
sales.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The luxury car market is now starting to expand, however.
Americans seem to be falling in love again with the fine handling
and easy access that exquisitely engineered cars can provide.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, manufacturers' plans for sport utility
vehicles are being crimped by rising gasoline prices and growing
regulatory pressures to reduce the big vehicles' emissions, improve
their fuel economy and make them less deadly to other motorists
during crashes. DaimlerChrysler executives cited all these issues,
particularly the uncertainty about future regulations, in saying
this week that they had canceled their well-advanced preparations
to introduce a giant Jeep that would have cost more than $50,000
and would have competed against the Ford Excursion and Chevrolet
Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
