   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno says a
Florida state court has no power to stop the U.S. immigration
service from sending Elian Gonzalez, 6, back to his father in Cuba.
In Miami, an anti-Castro group seeking to keep the boy in the
United States threatens more protests. By PATTY REINERT and ARMANDO
VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GRANDPARENTS (Washington) _ The U.S. Supreme Court
struggles with arguments over whether Washington state's highest
court made a mistake last year when it ruled that parents there
have a nearly absolute right to restrict their children's access to
anyone, including grandparents. The state Supreme Court ruled that
parents can bar
</P>
<P>
   grandparent visitation even when a neutral judge has determined
that such contact would be in the ``best interest'' of the
children. By MARK HELM. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-STOPS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that the
police may stop and question people who run at the sight of an
officer. In a 5-4 decision, the justices say the police had enough
reason to stop a black Chicago man who ran after spotting officers
in an area known for narcotics trafficking. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRIVACY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules that
Congress can protect motorists' privacy by barring states from
selling the personal information on driver's licenses. The law does
not violate states' rights, the justices said in a unanimous
decision that ran counter to their recent trend of reining in
Congress' power over the states. By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPLANTS (Washington) _ A panel of 14 independent scientific and
legal experts call on the federal government to develop an
information clearinghouse on medical implants so that patients can
be better informed about the lifespan of the devices and possible
complications that might arise. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
