   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Cedar Rapids, Iowa) _ Vice President Al Gore defends
his electability in a meeting with undecided voters in Iowa, where
one man says Gore will never be elected unless he distances himself
from President Clinton. ``I never would have done that'' with
Monica Lewinsky, Gore said in response. By CRAGG HINES. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-OLD-SOUTH (Lexington, S.C.) _ The ghost of the Old South is
haunting the top two Republican candidates who will have what could
be their final face-off in South Carolina's primary on Feb. 19.
Sen. John McCain of Arizona has praised the state's flag, which
contains the Confederate symbol, as a sign of Southern heritage.
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, meanwhile, is under fire for campaigning
at a plantation where slaves were bought and sold. By CLAY ROBISON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   REFORMERS-2000 (Undated) _ Republican John McCain and Democrat
Bill Bradley are running for president on a crusade to cleanse
Washington of special-interest money. Because they have set such
high standards, the reformers find themselves under much more
scrutiny than their rivals on the campaign-finance issue. By
BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROE-WADE (Dallas) _ In an odd twist of fate, individuals
connected to the landmark Roe vs. Wade abortion case cross paths
again. Norma McCorvey (aka Jane Roe) testified on behalf of the
Rev. Flip Benham, accused of trespassing at an abortion clinic
where he was protesting. The judge hearing the case is the
daughter-in-law of former Dallas District Attorney Henry Wade,
whose effort to block McCorvey's abortion in the 1970s set the
stage for the hugely significant Supreme Court ruling on abortion.
By JIM HENDERSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WIG-SHOP-SLAYING (Houston) _ A judge rules that a 21-year-old
former college student who is accused of killing a wig shop clerk
will be allowed to leave his house under certain conditions so he
can help prepare his defense. The ruling came as Dror Haim
Goldberg, who took off on a globe-trotting backpacking trip before
he was indicted, made his first appearance in court. By STEVE
BREWER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-RACISM (Austin, Texas) _ The chairman of the Texas Public
Safety Commission warns that there is to be ``zero tolerance'' for
racist attitudes within the Department of Public Safety. ``You are
not welcome in DPS if you are going to conduct your business in a
racist or sexist way,'' chairman Jim Francis tells a meeting of the
commission. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAMS (Undated) _ The St. Louis Rams appear to have all the
advantages as they head into the playoffs for the first time in
nearly a decade. They have the best record in the NFC and the
home-field advantage that comes with it. They are coming off a
record-setting offensive season and have a trio of high-powered
stars to lead that attack. If all this sounds familiar, just look
back one year at last year's Minnesota Vikings team. By JODY
GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-VIKINGS (Undated) _ Last year the Minnesota Vikings were
everybody's favorite to reach the Super Bowl, coming off a
sparkling 15-1 regular season and a record-setting offensive year.
This season, the Vikings struggled early but came on strong down
the stretch and now have emerged as this year's trendy pick to make
the Super Bowl. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
