<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LUXURY-CARS-ART-2NDTA     01-12 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUXURY-CARS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DETROIT: Chevrolet Suburban. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To reclaim the luxury car market, American designers are setting
aside their pride and emulating German automotive fashions.
Japanese designers, who have long copied German approaches to the
luxury market, have begun producing cars that are even closer to
the originals.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the luxury car market's growth in recent years has
been in the entry-level segment, so manufacturers have focused
their efforts there. Ford has had an instant hit ever since it
introduced the $31,475 Lincoln LS last autumn, which looks and
drives a lot like a BMW 5-series but is $10,000 cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese luxury sedans being introduced at auto shows this year
reflect very similar influences. The sporty, new Lexus IS300 has a
compact but powerful 3-liter, V6 engine that produces 215
horsepower, putting it in the same league as German engines, while
the new Acura 3.2CL Type S sedan manages 260-horsepower from a
slightly larger engine. Japanese auto executives expect both to be
priced about the same as the Lincoln LS.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Toyota is so confident that the entry-level luxury car
market will expand that it plans to keep selling its Lexus ES300
after the almost identically priced IS300 goes on the market in
July. Selling similar cars for similar prices in the same showrooms
is usually considered a marketing mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryan Bergsteinsson, the group vice president and general
manager of Toyota's Lexus division in North America, said that the
rear-wheel-drive IS300 was slightly smaller and intended for
customers in their 30s who might not want the front-wheel-drive
ES300, for which the average age is 51. ``If you see them on the
showroom floor, you'll see the difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sales of entry-level luxury cars are also growing because
traditional luxury car manufacturers have been most aggressive
lately in expanding the bottom of their price ranges. Mercedes has
been very successful with its C-class sedans, which cost $30,000 to
$35,000, and plans to introduce a completely redesigned but
similarly priced model this autumn. Jaguar has already increased
sales sharply with the $43,000 S-Type.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers are also looking for ways to build luxury cars that
look a bit like sport utility vehicles on the outside _ a high
roof, high front end and all-wheel drive _ but retain the driving
performance and interior comforts of a car.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known example of such a so-called sport wagon or
car-based sport utility is the Lexus RX300, essentially a luxury
wagon version of a Toyota Camry but with a taller suspension and
all-wheel drive. The BMW X5, which just went on sale last month and
is marketed as a ``sport activity vehicle,'' is another example.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday morning, Acura introduced a prototype here of its
answer to the RX-300; the final model, which will go on sale this
autumn, has not yet been named. Other automakers, including even
Porsche, are also working on luxury sport wagons.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers are experimenting with sport wagons partly because of
a belief that people now in their 20s may not want luxury sedans as
they grow older. ``What a lot of them are looking for is
distinctiveness _ they look at the current car, the box, as
boring,'' said Tom Orbe, the general manager of Infiniti, which
plans to introduce a competitor to the RX300 in the autumn of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But judging by some prototypes displayed here and, even more so,
at the recent Tokyo Motor Show, engineers working on the new sport
wagons must walk a fine line to avoid humdrum designs. ``A lot of
them just look like station wagons that they raised up a little,''
said Donald V. Esmond, Toyota's group vice president and general
manager for the Toyota brand in America.
</P>
<P>
   American automakers, including Cadillac and Lincoln, are also
working on similar vehicles. GM and Ford have been buying European
brands like Saab and Volvo with proven track records. And Ford
acquired Jaguar and Aston Martin in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes and BMW executives say they have little to fear from
their American rivals. ``I think that the American manufacturers
have concentrated in the last years on the sport utility vehicle
side of the market and they've probably paid too little attention
to the passenger car side,'' said Henrich Heitmann, BMW's
management board member for worldwide sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   American managers respond that given the high profits in the
sport utility vehicle market, such a strategy makes sense. Larry
Burns, GM's vice president for research, development and planning,
said that with some Chevrolet sport utilities selling for as much
as $35,000, traditional definitions of luxury brands are breaking
down.
</P>
<P>
   But such views mask an underlying concern that the Europeans are
moving ahead. Ford even went so far last year as to hire BMW's star
executive, Wolfgang Reitzle, to take charge of all its luxury
divisions: Lincoln, Volvo, Jaguar and Aston Martin. Reitzle said
that his goal was to fill the garages of affluent families with a
variety of vehicles, everything from Lincoln Navigator sport
utility vehicles to Jaguar sports cars and Volvo wagons.
</P>
<P>
   To be successful, Ford will need to sustain a consistent
approach to advertising, management and brand strategy _ a
combination which, he said, has eluded American carmakers in the
luxury market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took BMW 20 years to come from a fairly good position to a
very good position,'' Reitzle said. ``It's a question of 10 years
or so to execute what we really think American luxury should be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
