<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-STODA-COLUMN13-CO     01-12 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STODA-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marino, J.J. are allies for playoff cause
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   ``Things look swell,
</P>
<P>
   things look great.
</P>
<P>
   Gonna have the whole world on a plate
</P>
<P>
   starting here, starting now, honey.
</P>
<P>
   Everything's coming up roses!''
</P>
<P>
   Let's not read too much into Jimmy Johnson's double thumbs-up
signal to Dan Marino or into Marino's wave back in acknowledgement
as coach and quarterback left the Kingdome field in triumph Sunday
afternoon in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That was nothing more than Johnson, giddy in playoff victory,
celebrating his team's performance, in general, and Marino's, in
particular. And what was Marino going to do once he saw it was
Johnson shouting his name and flashing those thumbs? Ignore him?
Hardly, because such behavior only would have served to exacerbate
the long-standing bitterness that has existed between them.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson-Marino relationship is what it is _ they are
antagonistic protagonists in the Miami Dolphins drama _ and nothing
that happens this month is going to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Not if they lose Saturday in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Not if they win there and then again and then again in the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   They are allies in a common cause, and that's all. Almost
certainly, one or the other or both of them will be gone from the
Dolphins soon after the season comes to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   This is worth noting in the wake of Miami's 20-17 victory
against the Seahawks, because suddenly there has arisen the notion
the above lyrics by Stephen Sondheim and Jule Styne written long
ago seem a perfect fit for these Dolphins these days.
</P>
<P>
   That's because AFC Central champion and top-seeded Jacksonville
recently has been beset by injury to significant players (left
tackle Tony Boselli is out and quarterback Mark Brunell is
hurting). It's also because there is the undeniable study that the
Jaguars compiled their 14-2 record during the regular season
against a weak schedule _ they haven't beaten a team with a winning
record and their only two losses came in encounters with Tennessee,
which went 13-3 and still is alive in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that no sixth-seeded team (that's what the Dolphins
are) has reached a conference championship game, or that teams
coming off a bye week (that's what Jacksonville is doing) are 30-6
in their next appearance since the playoffs expanded in 1990 to
their current format.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Miami still faces a very difficult assignment.
Hey, there's a reason the Dolphins are 8 1/2-point underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is to remind everyone that one man's thumbs-up and
another man's wave are not signs a Johnson-Marino lovefest is about
to blossom. At Seattle, they managed to do what was necessary to
move the team along its playoff path. But the connection remains as
fragile as Miami's season, which is now and forever on the edge of
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dolphins do somehow push to a Super Bowl title, all would
be mutually forgiven _ but never forgotten _ and the season would
end gloriously for both men. Anything less, though, and things will
get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   It's all well and good that Tuesday was a happy-face day at the
Dolphins practice facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think Dan and I have a very good relationship,''
Johnson said. ``Some people try to read more into every statement
made than what's really there.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino's reaction was that he doesn't pay much attention to any
of the stuff said or written about the team or Johnson or himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care about our critics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You could almost hear the singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtain up.
</P>
<P>
   Light the lights.
</P>
<P>
   We got nothing to hit but the heights.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be swell.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be great.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell, just you wait.
</P>
<P>
   That lucky star I talk about is due.
</P>
<P>
   Honey, everything's coming up roses for me and for you!''
</P>
<P>
   That's nice.
</P>
<P>
   Convenient, too.
</P>
<P>
   Because whether the Dolphins win or lose in Jacksonville, and
depending on your allegiance, roses are suitable for celebration or
sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
