<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-ARMSTRON     01-12 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-ARMSTRONG13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong teaching lesson in history
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ He is the oldest player on a young defense. So
Trace Armstrong's teammates like to tease him. They call him
``grandpa.'' They overhear reporters asking about being a history
buff and they cackle, saying of course he's a history buff ... he
was there when it happened.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   It's when they stop teasing that you need to worry. That's when
you know there is something to the age talk. That's when you know
you've reached the end.
</P>
<P>
   So go ahead and laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked him Tuesday if, two days after a
three-sack game at Seattle in the first-round of the NFL playoffs,
he felt more like 24 than 34, Armstrong smiled and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   OK, truth be told, he didn't really shake his head. Just moved
it slightly. His neck, which has been aching for a couple weeks, is
stiff again. So is just about everything else on his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I feel like about 54,'' he said. ``Ask me Thursday or
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   In a season filled with talk of passing birthdays _ specifically
whether Dan Marino should retire at age 38 _ Armstrong has a better
appreciation than most for what the Dolphins' quarterback has been
going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is who you are,'' he said. ``I've been playing football
since I was 7. I'm a father. I've been a student and a lot of other
things. But I've always been a football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the strange things about this game. You're 34. In
regular society, that's still a fairly young man, but in football
they're starting to tell you you're too old to do what you've done
your whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody is saying that to Armstrong today.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on Tuesday, the NFL named him the Defensive Player of
the Week for his performance in the 20-17 victory at Seattle. It is
the fourth time in his 11-year career Armstrong has received the
honor _ but the first since the Chicago Bears traded him to the
Dolphins in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as significant is the praise coming from his coach.
There was a time when it didn't look like it would work to have
Jimmy Johnson and Armstrong, two psychology majors, in the same
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson loves young players, players who won't rock the boat,
players who will stay in South Florida all summer.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong hasn't been young by NFL standards for a while. And he
has been known to rock the boat. He spends his off-seasons in
Gainesville. He was the youngest member to serve on the NFL Players
Association's six-member executive committee. And in 1996 _ the
year Johnson arrived in Miami _ Armstrong became the NFLPA
president.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Armstrong? It was like trying to put Jimmy Hoffa and
Bobby Kennedy on the same team.
</P>
<P>
   But with time, it has worked. Tuesday, Armstrong could be heard
gushing about the way Johnson ``refocused the team for the
playoffs.'' And Johnson could be heard praising Armstrong for
adjusting from being a starter for the first nine seasons of his
career to a pass-rushing specialist the past two.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first proposed this to him, I'm sure he wasn't all
that fired up about it,'' Johnson said. ``But I think it's doing a
couple things for him. It's allowing him to make an impact on the
game even more so than if he were an every-down player. It's
keeping him fresher and healthier. And I think it's going to extend
his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has one year remaining on the contract he signed when
he was traded to the Dolphins. The team could release him in March
if they opt not to pay him a $500,000 roster bonus. Considering the
way Armstrong has played, that seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   He has led the Dolphins in sacks three of the past four seasons.
And as good as he has been in the regular season _ a team-leading
40 sacks in the past five years _ he has been ever better in the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   While young players like Jason Taylor have fizzled late in the
year, Armstrong has hardly looked grizzled.
</P>
<P>
   Two years in a row, he has sealed first-round playoff victories.
Last January, he blind-sided Buffalo's Doug Flutie, jarring loose
the ball and making sure the Bills' quarterback didn't pull off
another last-minute miracle against Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend in Seattle, after Marino led an 85-yard,
fourth-quarter scoring drive, the Dolphins sacked Seahawks
quarterback Jon Kitna on the next three plays. Two of those sacks
were made by a defensive end who now has played NFL games in three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Marino and Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   It was, you might say, one for the aged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature plays a cruel trick on you in this game,'' Armstrong
said. ``Just when you're starting to figure it out, your physical
skills start to go. But you get in a game like last week and the
one this week and experience helps.''
</P>
<P>
   He is two games from the Super Bowl. He has been this far a few
times in his career. But never further. And although he isn't
thinking about retiring anytime soon _ ``They'll have to run me
off,'' he says _ he looks at Saturday's game at Jacksonville with a
perspective that you won't find in a 24-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized going into this year that we had an opportunity,''
he said. ``We tried to screw it up along the way, but we've been
fortunate and we're still in it. You just start to develop this
sense of urgency because you know you're not going to be back too
many more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong chuckled when asked what on his body hurts these days
_ or if it would be easier to say what doesn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of fires to put out,'' he said. ``But that's the
playoffs. It's a grind physically. You come in almost bankrupt
physically. And this is a time when you've got to dig and try to
find something to get out there and play with.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong digs a little differently than some of his teammates.
His fellow linemen bounce up and down when rap music comes blaring
over the loudspeakers. Armstrong is more of a Van Morrison guy. And
when he needs inspiration, he has been known to think about
American history.
</P>
<P>
   When he was growing up, he often would visit his grandparents'
farm in Virginia and find arrowheads, muskets and Confederate belt
buckles. That stoked an interest that continues to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I draw motivation from people who have been put in exceptional
circumstances and done amazing things,'' he said. ``There are
millions of stories throughout history of no-name guys doing
incredible things for their country, for the guys that they fought
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there may be a generation gap, the guys Armstrong is
fighting with these days appreciate what he does on their version
of a battle field. Rich Owens, who at age 27 led the team in
tackles this season, says he hopes to follow Armstrong's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives me hope that if I make it that long that I can still
be productive,'' Owens said. ``It's a testament to his work ethic
and that if you're smart, you can take care of yourself. Trace is
in great shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens stops and points at the reporter's notepad.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone his age,'' he says with a smile. ``Put that he's
in great shape for someone his age.''
</P>
<P>
   Still teasing.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
