<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    United 'rubbish' drawing fire
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Europe might have the world's most glamorous club
teams, but its two representatives at the FIFA World Club
Championship did nothing to endear themselves beyond the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United and Real Madrid, the reigning and 1998
European champions, respectively, both crashed out of group play in
lackluster fashion and earned substantial media derision as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, two Brazilian clubs, Vasco de Game and Corinthians,
will meet for the title at the Maracana Stadium in Rio de Janeiro.
Necaxa of Mexico will play Real Madrid for third place.
</P>
<P>
   A red card to midfielder David Beckham for an atrocious tackle
in an opening 1-1 draw with Mexican club Necaxa set a grim tone for
United. Vasco ripped United 3-1 while Real Madrid, reduced to eight
men, held off Raja Casablanca 3-2 but were nipped by Corinthians on
goal difference.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its stay in Brazil, the United entourage was openly
concerned about the summer heat and was lectured in the local press
for not venturing out more in public. Allusions were made to Rio's
high crime rate, especially its reputation as a haven for
pickpockets.
</P>
<P>
   United, which received enormous criticism in England for passing
up its defense of the FA Cup to come to Brazil, fielded a team
largely of youth players in beating South Melbourne of Australia
2-0 in its finale.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid was chastised in the Spanish press for getting three
red cards against Raja. Forward Fernando Morientes even accused his
teammates of being ``childish'' in their lack of discipline.
</P>
<P>
   But the most scathing comments were against United, the
international merchandising phenomenon that might have blown a good
chance to curry some favor _ and tap into new markets _ in South
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manchester United came here to drink whiskey and make the most
of the sun,'' said Gerson, a legend with Brazil's 1970 World Cup
champions. ``What they did was a joke. They played like rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SURPRISE IN STORE?
</P>
<P>
   After the spectacular end to the Invierno, or winter, playoffs
last month, the Torneo Verano, or summer, season kicks off this
weekend, after a flurry of player moves.
</P>
<P>
   Pachuca, which won its first league title in overtime in the
finale against Cruz Azul, is hoping to continue its momentum
despite losing Benjamin Galindo to Guadalajara. Former MLS
goalkeeper Jorge Campos had made what seems at best a lateral move.
He has gone from UNAM Pumas to UNL Tigres, neither of which made
the Invierno playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the move again is Los Angeles Galaxy forward Carlos
Hermosillo, who leaves Necaxa for a second tour of duty with Club
America, the wealthy Mexico City club that hasn't won a trophy in
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In Group 1, Cruz Azul and Guadalajara are the strongest teams,
while America should set the pace in Group 2. Necaxa is the
favorite in Group 3, and defending champion Toluca and Atlas should
knock heads in Group 4.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND: LIVERPOOL STUNNED
</P>
<P>
   A goal in the 85th minute by Nathan Blake was the difference as
First Division Blackburn Rovers ousted FA Cup co-favorite Liverpool
1-0 on Monday in fourth-round play. Two other Premier League teams
were defeated by lower division sides. Fulham trounced Wimbledon
3-0 and Tranmere Rovers edged Sunderland 1-0 after being allowed to
bring on a substitute after a player was red-carded. The FA let the
result stand in spite of the officiating error.... Chelsea has
obtained 1995 world player of the year George Weah on loan from AC
Milan, where he had become the fourth striker in a three-man
attack.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: MILOSEVIC MAY STAY
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after expressing a desire to play in Italy, Real
Zaragoza forward Savo Milosevic is hinting that Spain might be just
the place for him after all. On Sunday, he scored a league-leading
18th goal as Zaragoza trounced Valencia 4-2 to move to within three
points of Deportivo La Coruna in the Primera Division. The Yugoslav
international said if Zaragoza qualifies for the Champions League
next year he might stay. ... Rivaldo scored on a header in the 90th
minute, and Barcelona beat Celta Vigo 2-0 to move into third place.
It was the first action in three games for the European player of
the year, benched in a power struggle with coach Louis Van Gaal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
