<SLUG> BC-NY-HUDSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE CAUTIONING ON HUDSON RIVER PROJECT DRAWS NYC IRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unusual foray into New York City politics, Massachusetts
Senators John F. Kerry and Edward M. Kennedy are calling for a
detailed environmental study of a $350 million pier and park
project on Manhattan's West Side, drawing a sharp warning to back
off from the office of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry and Kennedy said the piers, which will cover 490 acres of
the Hudson River, could disrupt spawning for fish that New England
fishermen catch, such as striped bass, and they asked the Army
Corps of Engineers to require an environmental impact study before
allowing constuction to begin.
</P>
<P>
   But a top aide to Giuliani, concerned that the proposed Hudson
River Project is already behind schedule, accused Kennedy and Kerry
of meddling and causing delays. He said New York officials will
make sure that the environment is protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous that senators from Massachusetts are
interfering in the inner workings of the city of New York,'' said
Deputy Mayor Randy Levine.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed park is intended to revitalize the little-used
waterfront from Manhattan's Battery Park to 59th Street, where many
of the existing piers are rotting into the water. But the project
has divided environmentalists between mainstream groups that
support the project and 41 grassroots groups that argue it will
lead to large-scale private development.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Kerry's entry into the fray comes as the Republican
Giuliani is locked in a US Senate race with Hillary Clinton, but
observers said their intervention is unrelated. The need for an
environmental impact study has divided New York Democrats, while
Clinton has not addressed the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts senators, along with US Rep. William Delahunt
of Massachusetts, say they were drawn by appeals from Massachusetts
fishermen who fear that the new piers could reduce their already
depleted catch.
</P>
<P>
   Though the section of the Hudson that would be covered by the
piers is far from pristine, partly facing the Statue of Liberty, it
is a remarkably popular feeding area or nursery for at least 15
fish species from bass to eel to shad, many of which are ultimately
caught in the waters off New England.
</P>
<P>
   In an October 12 letter to Assistant Secretary of the Army
Joseph Westphal, who oversees federal approval for coastal
projects, the senators warned it would set ``a dangerous
precedent'' to allow the Hudson River Project to go ahead without a
detailed analysis of its environmental impacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members of Congress are very dedicated to protecting fish
habitat, so they stepped in and requested that the full letter of
the law be carried out,'' said Paul Parker of the Cape Cod
Commercial Hook Fishermen's Association. ``They did the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy's and Kerry's letter drew criticism from New York
politicians and some environmental groups as well. Members of the
Hudson Park Alliance, 31 groups supporting the park and pier, wrote
the senators assuring them that New York law already prohibits
damage to fish habitat during pier construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respectfully disagree with your request because the Hudson
River Park . . . does not have any significant impact on the
aquatic environment,'' wrote Alliance leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And officials in Mayor Giuliani's office argued the pair had no
business getting involved in the debate in the first place,
prompting Kerry aides to appeal for calm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the Red Sox versus the Yankees,'' said Kerry
spokesman David Wade. ``We're doing this because of the Cape Cod
fishermen.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, aides to Kennedy and Kerry say they would settle for less
than a full environmental study, but only if the Army engineers
require precautions to protect the fish that have been developed by
the National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Kerry is adamant that all of the conditions NMFS has
set forth should be included in the final project and that anything
less requires a full environmental impact study,'' said Wade.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps' decision on the piers is expected in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
