<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLINE LIFTED FOR RETURN OF RESCUED CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Fla.)  (jw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Wednesday
emphatically reaffirmed her belief that Elian Gonzalez, the
6-year-old boy rescued at sea clinging to an inner tube after his
mother drowned, should be returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter to lawyers for the boy's relatives in Miami,
Reno added that immigration officials had lifted their Friday
deadline for Elian to be returned to Cuba. She said the extra time
would give the relatives who hope to keep Elian in the United
States an opportunity to file a challenge in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Justice Department is considering going to
court itself this week to ask a federal judge to enforce the
immigration ruling in hopes of hastening a resolution to what has
become a difficult, emotional political and diplomatic problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has adopted a dual approach to
dealing with the poignant story of Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, officials are striving to show that their decision
giving Elian's father the right to make the decision for the boy is
the product of well-established law that sets a priority on family
unification, and they are willing to have it tested in federal
court. At the same time, the administration is moving to end the
stalemate quickly, possibly seeking a court order that could lead
to U.S. marshals' being sent to fetch Elian from the Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, Reno said that a separate lawsuit filed in
Florida state court by the relatives to gain custody of Elian had
no bearing on the case, which she said could only be decided in
federal court. Judge Rosa Rodriguez of the Miami-Dade Circuit Court
ruled Monday that Elian had to remain in the United States until a
March 6 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reno brushed aside that ruling Wednesday, saying that the
state court order ``has no force or effect'' on the Immigration and
Naturalization Service's decision in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of who may speak for a 6-year-old child in
applying for admission or asylum is a matter of federal immigration
law,'' Reno wrote. Spencer Eig, a Miami lawyer who represents the
Florida relatives, said in a telephone interview that the family
would soon take up Reno's invitation to file a challenge to the
immigration service ruling in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   But Eig said the relatives would also maintain their efforts to
have a state court award them legal custody of Elian. ``We are not
removing this case from the state court,'' he said. ``We will seek
protection for Elian's civil rights in federal court as a separate
action.''
</P>
<P>
   No clear end appears in sight in the stalemate over Elian's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials had been hoping that Elian's
relatives would not dig in their heels and refuse to allow the boy
to return to Cuba. But since last week's ruling by the immigration
service, hundreds of Cuban-Americans have taken to the streets in
South Florida, vowing to prevent his return.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's action in lifting the deadline is part of the
effort, officials said, to demonstrate that the decision to rule in
favor of the father is a product of the law.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that the deep fear behind all the legal
maneuvering was that the situation would deteriorate to a stage
where the federal government would have to use marshals to assume
physical custody of the boy. ``We are still hopeful that we can
resolve this matter soon,'' a senior official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eig said that the family would abide by any court decision and
fully understood that it would not be in the best interests of the
child to have any confrontation with federal authorities in which
Elian would be forcibly taken from them. But he left open the
possibility that the relatives might feel that a state court ruling
in their favor on custody could trump federal authorities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that Ms. Reno would not respect a state court
ruling on what is essentially a state matter,'' he said. Eig
asserted that it was common for federal courts to look to state
courts to determine a person's status in making immigration
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Reno Wednesday made it clear that she believed otherwise. She
also offered a long rebuttal to the lawyers' contention that
immigration service guidelines mandated that Elian be given a full
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Lichtman, a veteran immigration attorney in Washington
who has no connection to the case, said in an interview that he
believed the state court was ``getting into something clearly
beyond its jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Lichtman said it appeared that the Justice Department had been
correct in its approach, ``but the question is how are they going
to enforce it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
