<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AOL-PRIMER13-COX     01-12 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-PRIMER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A primer for the latest in tech gear
 &HT;    By Dan Neal
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   You've ignored the Internet. You've dissed DVD. You've taken a
Luddite-like pleasure in watching technology pass you by. But as
Monday's merger of AOL and Time Warner shows, the future is here,
and a high-tech colossus is headed for all our living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still plenty of time to get up to speed with the
latest and greatest.
</P>
<P>
   To help, here's a primer to yank even the most reluctant into
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   My kids are into MP3s. What are they and how can I play along?
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3'' stands for something too obscure to talk about, but what
it means is near CD-quality music that you can download quickly
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 is a technology that compresses music _ which typically
takes loads of computer storage space _ into tiny digital files.
Once compressed, these files can be dumped from the Web onto your
computer in a matter of minutes. And if you have a broadband
connection, it's even better. You can grab a standard three-minute
pop tune in less than 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Once the song is on your computer, you can play it back through
the computer's speakers. Or, if you have a recordable CD drive, you
can ``burn'' your own MP3 discs, or decompress the files and create
standard music CDs. While an audio CD holds about 13 songs in
standard format, it will hold as many as 200 songs in MP3.
</P>
<P>
   There's one catch: Right now, standard stereo CD players won't
play MP3 discs. But several companies have announced players that
will play both ordinary CDs plus MP3 CDs. Look for these in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   What is broadband and what can it do for me?
</P>
<P>
   In geek-speak, broadband has something to do with ``data
streams'' and ``bytes per second.'' But all you really need to know
is this: It's fast.
</P>
<P>
   A broadband Internet connection _ using a special phone line or
TV cable _ is 50 to 100 times faster than the standard 56K modem
that's built into most PCs.
</P>
<P>
   That means no more waiting for Web pages to ``load.'' They'll
snap into place almost instantly when you log on. And no more long
waits to download movie clips and music. A film trailer that took
an hour to download with your old modem will take about a minute
with a broadband connection. Also, broadband makes it possible to
watch video on the Web without all that herky-jerky motion that
ruins Webcasts when they're viewed through a standard connection.
</P>
<P>
   What is HDTV, and am I going to have to buy one to watch
``RugRats''?
</P>
<P>
   High-definition television is super high quality TV that will
change forever the way you watch your favorite shows. After one
glimpse of HDTV, standard color television will look as archaic as
Beaver Cleaver in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, you'll be able to buy only high-definition
television sets. But for now, don't rush to get one. They're
incredibly expensive (thousands of dollars), and stations are
broadcasting few HDTV shows. It will be years before HDTV rules the
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   What is DVD and should I buy one when the VCR conks out?
</P>
<P>
   The VCR is most definitely doomed. Its successor is DVD, which
stands for digital versatile disc.
</P>
<P>
   DVD discs look just like CDs, but there's one huge difference:
They can hold about 20 times more information. So rather than an
hour of music, a single disc could contain several versions of an
entire movie or a whole encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   All that extra space leaves room for lots of neat features.
While watching many DVD movies, you can click a button with your
remote and hear commentary by the film's cast and crew. You can
hear audio in several languages, watch the movie frame-by-frame or
even view different camera angles of the same scene. DVDs also
eliminate rewinding and let you jump instantly to any part of the
movie. Plus they look and sound much better than tape and never
wear out like videocassettes.
</P>
<P>
   There has been one drawback to DVD, though _ you can't record
from TV onto a DVD disc. But last week, Panasonic introduced the
first DVD recorder. It hooks to the TV just like a VCR and lets you
record from television as well as play back movies. The gadget
won't be available till fall, but these machines are almost certain
to be the VCRs of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's no hurry to get a DVD player: Tape still
rules in most video stores.
</P>
<P>
   Will the telephone be obsolete?
</P>
<P>
   The lowly telephone doesn't seem high-tech enough to compete
with something as big as an AOL-Time Warner merger, but it's not
going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are gizmos that will let you call Grandma for free
over the Internet and talk to her face to face on your television
set or computer monitor without ever dialing a phone. But few
people want or use them. After they get over the gee-whiz stage,
they go back to the phone because it's so much easier than cranking
up a computer program.
</P>
<P>
   Will my PC replace my TV? Or will my TV replace my PC?
</P>
<P>
   Neither. While it's possible right now to do almost anything on
a TV that you can do on a computer, and vice versa, neither is
going away. The reason is simple: People don't want to watch TV
while sitting at a desk, and they don't want to write a letter on
their televisions.
</P>
<P>
   I keep hearing about ``interactive TV.'' I want to interact with
my TV. Is it heading our way?
</P>
<P>
   The technology is already here. Products such as WebTV allow you
to watch television and use the Internet at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   During a basketball game, for instance, you can click on an icon
on the screen with your remote control and view player stats or
other information culled from the Web. Or you might order something
from the home shopping channel _ or after watching a commercial _
by clicking another icon. Interactive TV also lets you participate
in online/TV polls, and some companies are talking about creating
game shows that let viewers play along from their living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Other gadgets such as Replay TV and Tivo aren't necessarily
interactive, but they do give you new power over your TV viewing by
recording what you're watching without videotape. They let you
freeze a live TV show so you can take a phone call or answer the
door and then resume the show at the point where you left off. Or,
if you missed the beginning of the show, you can ``rewind'' it and
watch it in its entirety from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth noting: The days of the TV listing books are
numbered. All these devices _ as well as most new TVs and VCRs _
automatically display programming on your screen. To watch a show,
you click on the selection. Your set will change channels, and your
VCR, if you like, will start to record.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Computer columnist Craig Crossman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
