<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w BC-STATES-MUMIA-PA     01-12 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-MUMIA-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;   &QL;  &UR; Department of Justice to Review Abu-Jamal Case &QL;   &UR; Laura J.
Winter &QL;  &QC;  C. 2000 States News Service &QL;  &QC;  WASHINGTON, Jan. 12 -Justice
Department officials today gave assurances to an international
group of activists that they would review allegations that
death-row inmate Mumia Abu-Jamal's civil rights had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will review the information that they provided us,'' said
Christine DiBartolo, a department spokeswoman. ``We will certainly
respond to them. We don't' know how long it will take.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Committee tthe Life of Mumia Abu-Jamal
is seeking a new trial for the convicted cop killer. The
committee's delegation, led by AFL-CIO organizer Baldemar
Valesquez, presented 29 claims of civil rights violations that his
group believes transpired in Abu-Jamal's trail, sentencing and
post-sentencing proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the plight of Mumia Abu-Jamal,''
Valesquez said. ``We believe that if there is such a thing and the
death penalty of human beings, the we have to be certain about the
quality of due process.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which included a Spanish senator and European and
American union officials and actor Ozzie Davis, requested President
Bill Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno use their office to
secure a new trail for Abu-Jamal. What they got was a meeting with
Deputy Assistant Attorney General Steward Ishimaru, who assured
them he would review their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal, incarcerated in the Waynesburg, Pa. State prison, was
sentenced to death for the December, 1981 murder of Philadelphia
police officer, Daniel Faulkner. The state has issued two death
warrants since his 1982 sentencing. The last warrant was suspended
in October.
</P>
<P>
   In the closed-door conference, Alisa Wilkins, the national vice
president of the Lawyers Guild, explained each of the group's
claims. Ishimaru informed them he would review the claims and any
additional information that might be submitted at a later date,
said Lindsay McLaughlin, an International Longshore and Warehouse
Union official present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50 people waited outside the department's
Washington headquarters until the 10 core members of the delegation
returned with news.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge William H. Yohn Jr. in October put off
the Dec. 2 execution date indefinitely to allow prosecution and
defense lawyers to prepare arguments for and against a new trial.
The Supreme Court in earlier that month refused to act on his case.
His appeal has been refused at all levels of the state court
system. Gov. Tom Ridge has also refused act on Abu-Jamal's behalf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
