<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WOMEN-SEX-TRADE-NYT &LR;      01-12 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SEX-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMINIST COALITION PROTESTS U.S. STANCE ON SEX TRAFFICKING TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An unusual coalition of women's groups,
family-planning advocates and conservative Republicans is
protesting what it describes as the Clinton administration's effort
to weaken international laws against the trafficking of women and
children for prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week, the presidents of the National
Organization for Women and the Planned Parenthood Federation of
America, along with Gloria Steinem and other feminists, accused the
administration of taking a position that was ``extremely
detrimental to women'' in negotiations over a new U.N. treaty on
sex trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   They were referring to the administration's support for wording
in the treaty that would define ``forced prostitution'' _ but not
other types of prostitution _ as a form of ``sexual exploitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter to the State Department said that the wording would
make it more difficult to prosecute prostitution rings because the
definition ``would not cover some of the most common methods of sex
trafficking, which prey on and profit from the economic desperation
of women, girls and their families by securing their `consent.'''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Heritage Foundation and other politically
conservative groups sent a similar letter of protest last week to
the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton. Mrs. Clinton has focused on
the issue in her foreign travels and has repeatedly called for a
crackdown on all types of trafficking of women and children across
international borders.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials insist that American negotiators in
Vienna, where the U.N. treaty is being drafted, are seeking a
document that is as tough as possible in demanding punishment for
criminals who transport women or children across borders for
prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the United States risked alienating other
governments, and undermining international support for the treaty,
if it pressed too hard for a definition of sexual exploitation that
included all forms of prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   They said a number of European governments that have legalized
prostitution might refuse to sign the treaty unless it made a
distinction between forced prostitution and situations in which
women choose freely to become prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suggestion that we are trying to weaken laws on
international trafficking of prostitutes is nonsense,'' said James
P. Rubin, the State Department's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups estimate that each year hundreds of
thousands, and perhaps millions, of women and children are forced
into lives of sexual exploitation. Many are transported across
international borders by criminal organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the wording of the U.N. treaty pits the
administration against some of its natural constituencies in the
women's movement and among family-planning organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's position does have support from some human
rights organizations and women's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Regan Ralph, executive director of the women's rights division
of Human Rights Watch in Washington, said that the treaty was too
important to be undermined by a squabble over the exact wording of
one section.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is that the treaty is moving forward, and
that it offers significantly improved protections of the victims of
trafficking,'' she said. ``We shouldn't allow this debate to derail
those efforts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4367 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AOL-BURKE13-COX     01-12 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-BURKE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key Turner executive resigning
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill Burke, one of Turner Broadcasting's most
prominent young Turks, has unexpectedly resigned as head of the
company's fledgling Digital Media unit.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old executive says his resignation was independent
of the pending merger of company parent Time Warner and America
Online. Indeed, he actually resigned privately last week before he
knew of the $165 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Burke portrayed his departure as deeply personal. He has been on
a fast track at Turner Broadcasting and then Time Warner for the
past several years, running several of the company's cable TV
channels, and felt something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the point where I was thinking about what I could do
new with my career,'' said Burke. ``I didn't want to be looking for
a job while working at Turner Broadcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke is leaving one of the top assignments at Turner. As chief
executive of Time Warner Digital Media, his assignment was to
devise a new comprehensive strategy for CNN.com and the company's
other Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is a terrific guy in all respects,'' said Olaf Olafsson,
vice chairman of Time Warner Digital Media in New York. ``Like all
good people, he will be missed, but we want him to be content.
We've known about this for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke leaves Digital Media with his task largely complete. The
unit has developed a new game plan and has begun to put it in play.
</P>
<P>
   That plan calls for enriching CNN.com with new content and
functionality. To that end, the company has begun to announce deals
such as a recent one with Internet search engine LookSmart.
</P>
<P>
   The company has begun actively searching for a new chief
executive for Digital Media.
</P>
<P>
   Burke says he has no immediate plans other than hanging around
with his wife and two small children. ``I'm just going to take some
time off. I've worked very hard in the past several years. I'm
fortunate that I'm a company shareholder and can now afford to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke will also be thinking about what comes next for him. ``I
don't know what's missing, but I'm looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the things he is considering are teaching graduate school
or working with a start-up company. ``I used to speak to a media
class at Emory and always enjoyed it.'' His wife is a teacher at
the Galloway School.
</P>
<P>
   Burke had quite a run during his 7 1/2 years at Turner
Broadcasting. He was named president of TBS in 1995 at the age of
29.
</P>
<P>
   His mission was to raise the brand recognition of the channel,
which had been stagnating. Burke did so by adding lots of
contemporary reruns from network television.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
