<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TERRORISM-SUSPECT-BOS     01-12 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-SUSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EVIDENCE OF TERRORIST CONNECTION KEEPS WOMAN UNDER ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY GOOD GLOBE CORRESONDENT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ A web of mobile phone calls provides the
strongest evidence yet that a Montreal mother played a role in a
terrorist plot to smuggle explosives into the United States,
federal prosecutors said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While 35-year-old Lucia Garofalo has not been charged in
connection with the Dec. 14 smuggling attempt in Washington State,
the prosecutors' evidence persuaded a federal judge to keep her
jailed pending her trial on less serious immigration violations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Judge Jerome J. Niedermeier said he was
particularly troubled by a call made from Garofalo's phone to a man
prosecutors described as an ``associate'' of Ahmed Ressam, the
Algerian charged in the Washington State case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may only be one telephone call, but there is one telephone
call,'' Niedermeier said.
</P>
<P>
   That call went to Raja Aslam of Long Island, N.Y. Prosecutors
would not say Wednesday whether Aslam had been charged with any
crime. Reached at the home phone number given by prosecutors, Aslam
told a reporter that he does not know Ressam, Garofalo or anyone
else associated with a terrorist network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no connection with these people,'' said Aslam, who said
he was a Yellow Cab driver who was born in Pakistan and has lived
in the United States for 15 years. ``I have nothing to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Aslam said he thinks federal prosecutors are tying him to the
case because one of his former roommates had been stopped at the
border around Dec. 14 or 15 and called him. ``He told me he paid
$1,000 to some people to smuggle him back into the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Aslam identified his former roommate as ``Ahmed Shaheen.'' In
court filings, prosecutors said that on Dec. 15, Garofalo
unsuccessfully tried to bring an Algerian national named ``Ahmed
Saeen'' into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged telephone links between Garofalo and the men
arrested in the Washington explosives-smuggling case are
complicated. According to their statements and court filings:
</P>
<P>
   -- On Dec. 14 _ the day of the alleged smuggling attempt near
Seattle _ Garofalo used her mobile phone to call a mobile phone
belonging to Aslam, the Long Island man.
</P>
<P>
   -- From Dec. 14-16, Aslam made at least six phone calls to
another cellular phone number in New York.
</P>
<P>
   -- From Dec. 11-19, someone at that other cellular phone number
made more than 20 calls to a number belonging to Abdel Ghani, a
Brooklyn man who has been charged with being Ressam's
co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors acknowledge that the connections are circuitous, but
make no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a close and concerning link between Ms. Garofalo and
the investigation that is going on in New York and Seattle,'' said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Tristram Coffin. In documents filed in
Ghani's New York arrest, prosecutors said, ``Ghani has also
explained that each person involved would only know the tasks of
two others involved so that, in the event of an arrest, no one
could expose more than two other confederates.''
</P>
<P>
   Aslam said he did not know Ghani. Nor, he said, did he have
phone conversations with anyone at the number cited by prosecutors.
Aslam said FBI agents had spoken to him Wednesday, and he told them
the same thing. ``I have to clear my name.''
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury indicted Garofalo last week on charges that she had
transported illegal aliens from Canada to the United States during
December. While prosecutors alleged that ``it is likely that her
actions were taken on behalf of an Algerian terrorist organization
or organizations,'' they have not yet charged her with a crime
reflecting that alleged link.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered Wednesday's hearing after Garofalo's lawyer
complained that her client was being denied bail based on
suspicions of terrorist activity the government had yet to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo arrived looking more chipper than she had since her
arrest Dec. 19, dressed in a black blouse and green slacks. As
reporters and courthouse observers crammed the courtroom,
Garofalo's two daughters -- Melissa, 14, and Sabrina, 12 -- were
ushered in, their heads covered with scarves.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's lawyer, Maryanne Kampmann, called to the stand the
secretary of Garofalo's Montreal mosque to bolster the case that
she was a kindly woman who would pose no threat if released. Bahaa
Elbatal recalled Garofalo bringing a member of the mosque to cancer
treatments, and visiting him in the hospital before his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to take him from the mosque to the hospital for
treatments,'' he said. ``I heard that she used to go visit him
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's daughters did not testify, but they sat on a
honey-colored bench in plain view of the judge, giving mute
testimony to the wish for their mother's freedom. Niedermeier said
he did not doubt that wish, but he questioned why a devoted mother
would stand accused of shuttling illegal aliens during midnight
border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   Neidermeier said he saw an apparent contradiction between ``a
defendant who is concerned with her children ... and at the same
time is wandering around the border at 2 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Niedermeier seemed to give most weight to
the new evidence of a terrorist connection. Garofalo's lawyer
argued that this was not fair, especially since it was not her
client, but an unnamed ``gentleman'' who had made the call to
Aslam.
</P>
<P>
   ``She herself did not dial this phone number,'' Kampmann said.
``She does not know who Mr. Raja Aslam is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
