u a BC-CENSUS13-COX     01-12 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanics forecast to outnumber blacks
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The U.S. Census Bureau says Hispanics will replace
black people as the nation's largest minority group within five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The census report issued today forecasts the number of Hispanics
and Asians going up nationally even after the end of the current
wave of immigration, the greatest such influx of immigrants since
the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: The country's Hispanic and Asian populations are
relatively young and have high birth rates and low death rates,
said Frederick W. Hollmann, a demographer who helped conduct the
study.
</P>
<P>
   In 2005, the study says, Hispanics will make up 13.3 percent of
the national population, slightly higher than the 13.1 percent
figure for blacks. Hispanics already outnumber blacks in 21 states,
including California and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons of black and Hispanic populations are tricky because
Hispanics, though recognized as a distinct ethnic minority, may
count their race as white or black. Another way of crunching the
numbers _ comparing the nation's Hispanic population with its
population of blacks who are not of Hispanic origin _ shows that
Hispanics will outnumber non-Hispanic blacks in 2002 _ 12.4 percent
to 12.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL CUT _ Georgia specific)
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of Hispanics in Georgia doubled in the
1990s, according to previous census estimates, only 2.9 percent of
the state is Hispanic while 28.5 percent of Georgians are
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think historically we've been a black-white state and I
think we'll stay there,'' said Douglas C. Bachtel, a demographer at
the University of Georgia. He said ``not even in the foreseeable
future'' will Georgia's Hispanic population seriously rival the
state's black population for the claim of largest minority group.
</P>
<P>
   Bachtel said Georgia's Hispanic population has increased sharply
in recent years as Hispanics moved here to take hard-to-fill jobs.
He said large numbers of Hispanics work in carpet mills and poultry
plants in north Georgia and on farms in south Georgia. In metro
Atlanta, many Hispanics work in construction and landscaping
businesses and in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are jobs that Americans don't want _ hard physical labor
with low pay,'' the demographer said.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Rodarte, an announcer on a Spanish-language radio station
in Gwinnett County and who came here from Mexico 16 years ago, said
jobs lured most of his listeners to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have lived here one year, others already have lived here
eight years, others have lived here six months. The majority have
lived in other states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Formal estimates of the state's Hispanic population range from
220,000 to 480,000, but Bachtel said the real number might be
closer to 750,000.
</P>
<P>
   The census report says Asians and Pacific Islanders will remain
the fastest-growing racial or ethnic group for years to come. The
Asian population in Georgia increased about 92 percent since 1990,
but Asians and Pacific Islanders make up 1.9 percent of Georgia's
population.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
