<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT BACKS CITIZENS' RIGHT TO SUE TO FIGHT POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: S.C., Va.) (With SCOTUS-POLICE, SCOTUS-LICENSE-DATA) 
 (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an important environmental ruling Wednesday, the
Supreme Court removed a legal cloud from the ability of private
citizens to invoke federal environmental laws in suits to stop
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 decision in a case involving a hazardous waste
incinerator on a South Carolina river breathed new life into the
provisions of the Clean Water Act, the Clean Air Act and other laws
that authorize individuals to act as ``private attorneys general''
and collect fines on behalf of the federal treasury.
</P>
<P>
   These ``citizen suit'' provisions remove environmental
enforcement from the exclusive control of federal agencies, and
have long been opposed by businesses and conservative interest
groups. Recent decisions by the Supreme Court and lower federal
courts had suggested that citizen suits stood on dubious
constitutional ground because the plaintiffs _ individuals or, as
in this case, private environmental organizations _ did not meet
the ordinary requirements of standing to pursue cases in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision, in an opinion by Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg, reinstated a case under the Clean Water Act that had been
dismissed by the 4th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in Richmond,
Va. Ginsburg said members of the environmental groups had shown
sufficient personal injury from their loss of enjoyment of the
North Tyger River to entitle them to pursue their case even without
being able to prove direct harm to the river from discharges of
mercury that exceeded permissible levels.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg said the test was ``not injury to the environment but
injury to the plaintiff.'' She added that if the requirement for
standing was injury to the environment, it would be more difficult
to bring a case than to win one, since the ultimate question under
the Clean Water Act is whether the defendant has complied with a
permit for discharging substances into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Schiffer, the assistant attorney general for environment
and natural resources, said Wednesday that the decision ``assures
that citizens affected by pollution have the right to go to court
to enforce environmental laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the U.S. District Court in Columbia, S.C., found
that Laidlaw Environmental Services, the owner of the incinerator,
had violated the permissible limits on mercury discharges 489 times
from 1987 to 1995 and imposed a fine of $405,000.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Earth and a local group known as Clean brought
their suit in 1992. Soon after, Laidlaw installed new equipment and
corrected the problems that had led to the discharges. That led the
appellate court to declare the case moot and dismiss it, a ruling
that alarmed environmental advocates by indicating that a defendant
could avoid liability by bringing itself into compliance as soon as
a suit was filed. Laidlaw, now the Safety-Kleen Corp., an
industrial and hazardous waste management service based in
Columbia, subsequently closed the incinerator but retained its
discharge permit.
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion Wednesday, Friends of the Earth vs. Laidlaw, No.
98-822, Ginsburg said the 4th Circuit had confused the inquiry into
standing and mootness. She said that while the plaintiffs
indisputably had standing, the case might be moot, but only if it
was ``absolutely clear'' that the violations would not recur. The
court remanded to the district court both that question and the
question of whether the plaintiffs were entitled to reimbursement
of their attorneys' fees, which the 4th Circuit had rejected.
</P>
<P>
   In an important part of her analysis of the plaintiffs'
standing, Justice Ginsburg said the fact that fines won under
citizen suits went to the federal treasury and not the the
plaintiffs did not deprive citizen-plaintiffs of the requisite
concrete stake in the outcome of the case. The prospect of fines
encourages polluters to comply with the law, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Antonin Scalia said the citizen
suit provision ``does not provide a mechanism for individual relief
in any traditional sense, but turns over to private citizens the
function of enforcing the law.'' The provision, he added, gave
citizen plaintiffs ``massive bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia said the court had made ``new standing law'' that ``has
grave implications for democratic governance.'' Justice Clarence
Thomas joined the dissent.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of rulings since 1992, Scalia has been the driving
force on the court to limit access to court in environmental cases.
Wednesday's surprisingly lopsided vote to reject his position may
indicate not so much a turning point for the court on the issue as
a reflection that the 4th Circuit, the nation's most conservative
federal appellate court, had pressed the logical implications of
Scalia's opinions further than a Supreme Court majority was willing
to follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
