<HEADLINE>
`DUKES' IS GOOD FOR A ROYALLY ENTERTAINING TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not even a month into 2000, and the vid-game industry is still
digging up the grave of the past. Two latest _ and greatest _
examples:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dukes of Hazzard: Racing for Home'' (WB for PlayStation, $45):
Yes, those Dukes of Hazzard have their own video-game. What's even
scarier is that it's a really, really cool game. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   More thought than one could imagine went into creating this
thing. It features the voices of original ``Dukes'' cast members,
including Tom Wopat (Bo Duke) and country singer Waylon Jennings,
who sang the theme song and narrated. In one form or another,
Rosco, Daisy, Uncle Jesse, Cooter and Boss Hog are here, too, along
with the Dukes' car, the General Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Players must complete a series of missions _ rescue Daisy, save
Jesse's farm, thwart Boss Hog. Most of the time, you'll drive the
General, but there are times when you have to use Daisy's jeep or
Cooter's tow truck to complete a mission. So this isn't just
tearing through the hills of Hazzard, trying to outrun Rosco,
although you do spend a good amount getting chased by him and,
consequently, watching him wind up belly-up in a ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling certain ``stunts'' _ launching the General over a river,
for example _ is often required to finish a scene, multiplying the
challenge factor. In other words, there's a lot more going on than
there was with the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interstate '82'' (Activision for PC, $50): As the name
implies, this war-of-the-cars game _ and sequel to Interstate '76 _
is set in 1982: All the cars reflect the time period, the pink
shirt/white suit of lead character Taurus is in full effect and the
pumping music is straight out of an ex-''Miami Vice'' cast member's
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Really, the whole thing is sort of a ``Miami Vice'' marathon,
except there's very little talking, only cars blowing up. The story
line revolves around Taurus, who's trying to stop a rash of auto
terrorism. He does this by, naturally, mounting a bunch of weapons
on his Don Johnsonish lovemobile and driving around wasting the
bad-guy cars.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not as simple as that. Taurus has to complete a
grueling 40 missions, and a lot of them are frustrating to the
point of making you want to give up. What kind of keeps you going
is the fun factor: Players can choose from 15 different '80s-style
cars _ which tout realistic auto physics _ and customize 'em with
up to 25 weapons. It's so much fun to screech around corners and
blow enemies up, sometimes you just say, ``Forget the missions.''
</P>
<P>
   With lots of explosions, ``Interstate '82'' is definitely for
teen gamers. Younger kids can stick with ``Twisted Metal,'' which
is basically the same game, minus the pink shirt.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
