A4386 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-MLK13-COX     01-12 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-MLK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta archdiocese pulls lawmaker's invitation to speak for
King holiday
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Atlanta has quietly
withdrawn an invitation asking Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) to speak in
honor of the upcoming Martin Luther King Jr. holiday, because Lewis
believes women should have the right to choose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop John Donoghue decided to rescind the invitation just
before Christmas and some five months after Lewis was first asked
to commemorate the slain civil rights leader's nationally observed
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision surprised the congressman, a former civil rights
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis had looked forward to speaking about King, his mentor and
close friend, having turned down 28 other invitations in favor of
the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis had planned to talk about King's legacy of compassion, not
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply saddened by this,'' said Lewis, a Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese's decision upset Lewis, because he frequently
speaks at Catholic schools and churches across the country.
</P>
<P>
   His wife Lillian's father and sister are Catholic, and the
church has honored Lewis several times in the past for his
leadership during the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   If abortion had come up dur appearance, Lewis said he
would say what he always says about the politically explosive
issue: ``It's between you and your God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The invitation was a regrettable mistake on our part and we
offer apologies to Congressman Lewis for any inconvenience this may
have caused to his schedule,'' said Monsignor Peter Dora, spokesman
for the Atlanta archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Dora said Lewis was invited by the archdiocese's Office of Black
Catholics, which plans a King observance each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally opposed to abortion, and Congressman Lewis has
made it abundantly clear that he is 100 percent pro-choice,'' Dora
said. ``Whenever his name comes up, we hear vociferous complaints
from Catholics across North Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   But African-American Catholics, including those who oppose
abortion, said they were dismayed by the decision to withdraw the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The archbishop's view is a particularly narrow view,'' said
Lyn Vaughn, who was a eucharistic minister and lector at the Sacred
Heart Catholic Church in Atlanta before moving to Norfolk, Va., in
September. ``Given that many Catholics are pro-choice, it misses
the point and the spirit of Dr. King's life to uninvite him now.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Catholics praised the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the context of social justice, which is the framework
in which pro-life activities fall in the Catholic church, respect
for human life is the primary concern,'' said Kel MacDonald, an
active member of Georgia Right to Life who attends St. Philip
Benizi Catholic Church in Jonesboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to express himself in support of civil
rights, the most basic civil right of all is the right to life,''
MacDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
