<HEADLINE>
`MY MOVIE BUSINESS' IS AN INSIGHTFUL INSIDE LOOK AT FILMMAKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE KASKOVICH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My Movie Business'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By John Irving &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memoir &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $19.95 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turning a lengthy novel into a two-hour movie is a process of
elimination. A screenwriter must decide which scenes can be
sacrificed without gutting the novelist's tale.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tough task, rarely completed to the satisfaction of the
author. Unless, of course, the author is also the screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   In ``My Movie Business,'' John Irving relates his 13-year effort
to turn his 1985 novel, ``The Cider House Rules,'' into a feature
film. His odyssey encompassing four directors and multiple scripts
has a happy ending. The film, with Michael Caine playing orphanage
director-abortionist Dr. Wilbur Larch, was released just before
Christmas. (And Irving likes it.)
</P>
<P>
   As with any John Irving book, the beauty of ``My Movie
Business'' is in the details.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong wordsmith whose style of ``big'' novels with social
themes has been compared with that of Charles Dickens, Irving
brings a unique perspective to the quirky ways of Hollywood. In an
age when movies have overtaken novels as the most popular mode of
storytelling, this memoir offers a bird's-eye view of the two art
forms. Irving fans, in particular, will enjoy peeking into his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book involves an analysis of screenwriting
decisions: which scenes to leave in and which to leave out. Irving
bemoans this compression. A movie, he writes, offers less time for
character development or the passage of time. So things must be
simplified.
</P>
<P>
   What comes across is his passion for his creations. ``It pained
me to lose Melony, but I had to do it,'' he writes of one character
trimmed from the movie. He speaks of his fictional characters with
an attachment normally reserved for children.
</P>
<P>
   Irving's overriding concern is that the meaning of his story
survives on the big screen. ``The Cider House Rules'' is about
abortion, and Irving doesn't disguise his pro-choice beliefs. Set
in Maine in the 1930s and '40s, the novel centers on an orphan
named Homer Wells, who is taught to perform illegal abortions by
Dr. Larch and must decide whether to carry on his mentor's
profession.
</P>
<P>
   There are subplots, including Homer's romantic dalliance with
Candy, the girlfriend of a soldier off to war. Irving, who picked
the director and helped with casting, frets that he can't control
what is pictured on the movie poster. Sure enough, Miramax has
avoided the A-word in its marketing of ``The Cider House Rules.''
Homer and Candy are pictured in movie ads that evoke a
heart-rending romance.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders why a serious writer like Irving got involved with
Hollywood at all. He sees very few movies. (''I don't like sitting
in large dark rooms with a lot of strangers.'') He was minimally
involved when two previous books, ``The World According to Garp''
and ``The Hotel New Hampshire,'' were made into films. And he so
dissociated himself from 1998's ``Simon Burch,'' based loosely on
his masterpiece, ``A Prayer for Owen Meany,'' that it's not
mentioned at all in ``My Movie Business.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving never tells us, but it's obvious that he loves his
stories and he wants them told onscreen as well as in print. He has
completed a second screenplay, for ``A Son of the Circus,'' which
goes into production next year. Yet his primary love has not
changed; he's at work on his next book. ``When I feel like being a
director, I write a novel,'' he concedes.
</P>
<P>
   His cameo role in ``The Cider House Rules'' aptly describes his
offscreen role as screenwriter. He plays a disapproving railroad
stationmaster, shocked by the world moving past him. Ever a
novelist, Irving never fully approves of a cinematic world beyond
his control.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
