<SLUG> BC-FILM-WARZONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCESTUOUS FAMILY TALE IS GOOD, BUT GRIM GOING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Roth's acting choices have never shied from the
confrontational, so it's no surprise that his directing debut tells
a harsh tale. Nothing Roth has done as an actor, though, can quite
prepare us for the unsettling grimness of ``The War Zone,'' his
realization of Alexander Stuart's novel about a family imploding.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a good time, look elsewhere. This is not a
happy movie, and it's virtually devoid of comic relief. Even the
early scenes, which depict the chaos as 15-year-old Tom (Freddie
Cunliffe) and his family move from London to Devon on the craggy
English coast, carry a sense of foreboding. The family is isolated;
visitors are rare. Tom's dad (Ray Winstone) spends a lot of time on
the phone, in conversations that we never quite hear clearly. His
mom (Tilda Swinton) is pregnant with her third child, who is born
in tumult, literally upside-down after a car crash that the family
somehow survives.
</P>
<P>
   Tom, whose acne is barely distinguishable from his auto-wreck
scars, is already a brooding teen-ager, viewing everything around
him with a suspicious stare. You'd probably look askance, too, if
your family were this candid. It's not unusual for family members
to walk into one another's rooms unannounced and hold discussions
while one or the other is naked.
</P>
<P>
   Things take a turn for the worse when Tom suspects that his
father and his sister Jessie (Lara Belmont) are involved in incest.
She denies Tom's accusations until his suspicions _ and ours _ are
confirmed in a scene explicit enough to rattle even the most jaded
filmgoer. And it's not even the most jarring scene in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Roth and screenwriter Stuart, who adapted his novel, aren't the
first to discover evil amid banality, or to show that a beautiful
setting such as the English coast can conceal nasty doings. But
they're brutally matter-of-fact about their revelations, sparing in
their use of dialogue and allowing horrific things to happen in
near-silence. Even most of the spoken confrontations are whispered,
and the quietness makes the movie all the more unnerving.
</P>
<P>
   Roth is sympathetic to his actors, getting heartfelt
performances that belie his usually punky screen persona. Winstone
(who appeared in Roth crony Gary Oldman's ``Nil by Mouth'') and
Belmont pull off difficult roles as the near-sociopathic father and
the daughter who unaccountably protects him. Swinton's performance
is impressive in its lack of vanity. Cunliffe anchors the movie
with his growing, repressed rage.
</P>
<P>
   As well-executed as the movie is, though, it's also thoroughly
unpleasant, and its frankness is liable to prevent many viewers
from enjoying its artistry. ``The War Zone'' is disturbing, yes,
right down to the three questions asked at movie's end, and its
imagery can haunt you for days. Try finding redemption in it
though, and, once again, you might as well look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The War Zone'' is not rated. It's an R or possibly NC-17
equivalent for strong language, violence, nudity and frank
depictions of incest. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The War Zone'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Tim Roth &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Freddie Cunliffe, Lara Belmont, Ray Winstone &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 99 min. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
