<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-HUGHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING SAID READY TO BUY HUGHES' SATELLITE BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a big expansion into the space business, Boeing
Co &UR; . &LR;  is expected to announce soon that it is buying the satellite
manufacturing business of Hughes Electronics Corp &UR; . &LR;  for about
$3.75 billion in cash, executives close to the matter said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction would make Boeing the world's largest producer
of commercial communications satellites while transforming Hughes
almost entirely into an entertainment and communications company,
led by its DirecTV satellite television operation.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has been approved by the boards of Hughes and General
Motors Corp &UR; . &LR; , which owns Hughes, the executives said. Boeing's
board is scheduled to meet on Thursday, with an announcement
possible after that, they said. All three companies declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the move would be good for Hughes because the
satellite manufacturing business is growing slowly, if at all, and
has far lower profit margins than communications services. Hughes
can now invest more in DirecTV and in its planned Spaceway system
to provide Internet service from satellites. ``It is a fundamental
shift that will benefit shareholders,'' said Robert B. Kaimowitz,
satellite analyst for ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the move could also help Boeing strategically but
that the Seattle company might be paying too much. ``I'm in shock.
That's a big number,'' said Cai von Rumohr of S.G. Cowen &AMP; Co &UR; . &LR; ,
who had valued the satellite manufacturing operations at $2 billion
to $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, reported Wednesday by Bloomberg News, will most likely
renew speculation that GM will spin off Hughes to shareholders.
Some investors have been urging such a move, saying it would allow
the stock of Hughes to rise freely and also lift shares of GM.
</P>
<P>
   GM has generally discouraged such speculation, saying its
automobile operations benefit from the satellite company's
technology. The decision to sell the satellite manufacturing
business could indicate a new willingness on GM's part to separate
from Hughes. In Detroit, Harry Pearce, GM's vice chairman, said in
an interview on Monday that Hughes was well along in a broad review
of its long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hughes is undergoing its own internal review of its
enterprise,'' he said, while seeming to hint that changes might be
made soon. ``I always like to move more quickly than more slowly.
We can't let the grass grow under our feet.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, because the sale by itself will lift stock
prices, it could relieve some of the pressure for a broader
spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GM rose $3.4375, to $76.375, a gain of more than 4
percent. GM Class H shares, the tracking stock for Hughes, also
gained more than 4 percent, closing at $106.8125, up $4.25. Boeing
shares rose 18.75 cents, to $43.0625.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the satellite manufacturing unit, known as Hughes
Space and Communications, virtually ends Hughes' role as an
aerospace manufacturer, which began with the aircraft made by
Howard Hughes. The aircraft and other military operations were sold
to Raytheon in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes officials have said that the future of the company was in
services like fast-growing DirecTV, which delivers scores of
digital television channels to home dish antennas. DirecTV has 8
million customers, having added 1.6 million in 1999, and is now
turning profitable on a cash-flow basis. Hughes also provides
communications services for business and owns 81 percent of
PanAmSat, the nation's largest operator of communications
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Michael T. Smith, the chairman and chief executive of
Hughes, had maintained that manufacturing satellites gave the
company an edge in conceiving and developing new services like
DirecTV.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives say pressure to sell the satellite manufacturing
business has been growing in part because it was perceived that
owning it was holding down Hughes' share price. The shares have
doubled since early September nonetheless, mainly on the prospects
for fast growth of DirecTV.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite manufacturing business also got into hot water
over accusations made by Congress that it aided China's military
development. And it suffered manufacturing glitches that caused
Hughes to take a $125 million charge in the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, EchoStar Communications Corp., DirecTV's main
competitor, has done well without making its own satellites. ``We
haven't proved that there's any special advantage to owning your
own satellite company,'' said one Hughes executive, who added that
executives at DirecTV and the other service units wanted the
flexibility to buy satellites made by other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, meanwhile, has been pushing strongly into the satellite
and rocket launching business as a third leg for the company in
addition to its commercial aircraft and military operations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing already makes global positioning system satellites, a
business it acquired with the purchase of the aerospace business of
Rockwell International in 1996. Boeing recently won an estimated $5
billion contract to make the next generation of military spy
satellites, beating out the incumbent Lockheed Martin Corp. It also
won a contract to build commercial communications satellites for
Skybridge LP and has bid on manufacturing contracts for other
services like Ellipso, a proposed satellite telephone service, and
Teledesic, which would provide Internet service from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Buying the Hughes operation, which had estimated 1999 revenues
of $2.3 billion, would expand Boeing's $7 billion space and
communications division by more than 30 percent. It would also give
Boeing some expertise to develop some satellite communications
services it is planning, like one that would deliver Internet or
video to airplanes or ships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
