<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS SLIDE AS INVESTORS TURN CAUTIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks slumped again Wednesday, dragging
the Nasdaq market down 71.17 points, or 1.82 percent, in a nervous
session as investors braced for government reports on retail sales
and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates also kept investors cautious as did
further appraisal of the blockbuster merger proposed Monday by
America Online, which was down 4{, to 60, and Time Warner Inc.,
down 5], to 79 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been excess there,'' said Cummins Catherwood, managing
director of Rutherford, Brown &AMP; Catherwood in Philadelphia,
referring to the 1999 run-up in Internet and other high-technology
shares. ``Now there's a reshuffling of the deck.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth consecutive day in which the Nasdaq composite,
which ended at 3,850.02, ranged more than 100 points from high to
low.
</P>
<P>
   With some technology money moving into blue chips, the Dow Jones
industrials explored record territory for much of the day but gave
up more than half its best gain to finish ahead by 40.02 points, or
0.35 percent. The closing level, 11,551.10, was shy of the record
11,572.20 set on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fixation we've seen on high-tech and Internet has broken
somewhat,'' said Neil Eigen, a managing director at J.&AMP; W.
Seligman. ``Some sanity is returning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks were among the day's best performers, with J.P.
Morgan and Citigroup among the biggest contributors to the Dow's
advance. Analysts said investors might have decided that bank
stocks had been battered enough in anticipation of more
credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve, which has a policy
meeting scheduled for the first two days of February.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks also weighed heavily on the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index, which sagged 6.31 points, or 0.44 percent, to
1,432.25. The biggest depressants other than America Online were
Microsoft, down 3 9/16, to 105 13/16; Yahoo down 39 13/16, to 357
9/16, and Oracle, down 6}, to 105|.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues in the index narrowly outnumbered advancing
ones, 246 to 234, with 20 stocks unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors surged 3 7/16, to 76], after a report emerged
that Boeing planned to buy the satellite-manufacturing business of
Hughes Electronics, 69 percent owned by GM Hughes climbed 4\, to
106 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin rose 1\, to 21 3/16, after winning a Navy
missile contract, while Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing
benefited from a recommendation by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and
traded as high as 103| before settling at 100}, up \.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose 1 9/16, to 91\, as investors awaited its earnings
report today. Hewlett-Packard gained 3 13/16, to 112].
</P>
<P>
   ``The message so far this year is the first shall be last and
the last shall be first,'' said James Paulsen, chief investment
officer at Wells Capital Management. He noted that utilities also
posted broad, though modest, gains Wednesday and that beaten up
consumer stocks like McDonald's, up 1}, to 42}; Coca-Cola, up
11/16, to 61{, and Merck, up 1 7/16, to 74 7/16, have all bounced
higher of late.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume eased a bit on the New York Stock Exchange, to a
still heavy 974.6 million shares as 1,710 issues declined and 1,355
advanced. There were 85 stocks that hit 52-week lows and 53 that
hit new highs. Nasdaq volume was 1.52 billion, down from 1.65
billion Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign markets were mixed Wednesday. The Nikkei 225 in Tokyo
fell 0.92 percent, the Hang Seng in Hong Kong, 0.93 percent, and
the Paris CAC, 0.56 percent. Prices rose by 0.31 percent in
Frankfurt, 0.21 percent in London, 0.27 in Sao Paulo and 0.43
percent in Mexico City.
</P>
</TEXT>
