<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL AUTOMAKERS ANTE UP BIDS FOR AILING DAEWOO MOTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The General Motors Corp. sought to gain an
edge on Wednesday in the foreign competition to acquire the Daewoo
Motor Co., saying it wanted to preserve the ailing South Korean
automaker's national identity.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by GM came against a backdrop of rising concern
among Daewoo Motor employees about their fate. Their union has
protested what it calls the rushed effort by Daewoo creditors to
sell the company to an overseas buyer, and it has scheduled a Jan.
21 meeting to decide whether to strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested in acquiring all of Daewoo Motor's assets,
therefore allowing the highest number of employees without
disrupting the company,'' said Henry Wong, a GM spokesman. ``GM is
the world's largest automaker, and Daewoo Motor suppliers will gain
access to the rest of GM's network.''
</P>
<P>
   Both GM and the Ford Motor Co. have expressed strong interest in
acquiring Daewoo Motor to help anchor their expanding operations in
Asia, where vehicle sales are expected to jump as the region's
economy recovers from a financial crisis that began more than two
years ago. Daewoo Motor is a main affiliate of the Daewoo Group,
which has been struggling under an estimated $73 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, which recently hired a former Daewoo executive as an
adviser in talks with Korean creditors and government officials,
said it was reviewing Daewoo Motor's assets. ``We're still
interested in Daewoo Motor,'' said Jim Bright, a Ford spokesman.
``We feel we owe it to our stockholders to take a good look at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   A developing takeover struggle for Daewoo Motor began a month
ago when the South Korean government said it was likely to choose
GM as the exclusive buyer. Shortly afterward, Ford announced its
interest, and the government decided to conduct an auction, which
could take place in March.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai, South Korea's largest automaker, is also said to be
interested in Daewoo Motor, and other automakers may be interested,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The value of Daewoo Motor is unclear, partly because it holds
more than $16 billion of the parent company's debt. GM reportedly
had offered $6 billion to $7 billion plus the assumption of an
unspecified amount of Daewoo Motor's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Able to manufacture more than a million cars a year in its South
Korea factories, Daewoo Motor would be a valuable asset for any
major carmaker wishing to expand sales in Asia, which is expected
to generate most of the global growth in the industry in the next
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But Daewoo Motor's debt is rising and could ultimately
discourage any potential buyer. It is increasingly unclear how much
debt might be assumed by Daewoo Motor's creditors if there was a
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run Korea Development Bank, Daewoo Motor's main
creditor, recently provided the automaker with an additional $100
million in credit, said Seo Kyong Won, a Daewoo Motor spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors reached a tentative agreement in November to provide
Daewoo Motor about $440 million in additional operating funds, $1
billion to cover unpaid export fees and $250 million to cover
purchases of raw materials. But disagreements between individual
creditors led to delays in those payments, which began only
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cash infusions will pay for back wages for around
10,000 assembly line workers, but that may not soothe the anger
employees harbor toward the company.
</P>
<P>
   Park Doo-young, a union spokesman, said members were frustrated
by what he called the alienation they have felt from the government
and creditors during negotiations and offers that will determine
their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already planned our strikes,'' Park said. ``What comes
first should be funding support to normalize operations at our
plants. We will strike if the government continues with its
single-handed approach to find a foreign buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Korea Development Bank, which is overseeing the auction of
Daewoo Motor, intends to complete a sale by the end of June, said
Yang Won-seok, an official at the bank's Daewoo credit division.
The bank has formed a separate office to oversee the sale and plans
to receive letters of intent from interested buyers by the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
   But there is considerable skepticism about whether the bank can
sell Daewoo Motor by midyear. The South Korean government's last
attempt to sell an ailing carmaker, the Kia Motors Corp., which
went bankrupt in 1997, dragged on for almost a year as the
government haggled over how much debt a foreign buyer should
assume. Eventually Hyundai acquired Kia.
</P>
<P>
   ``First it was GM and Ford, and now everyone's jumped in,'' said
Joe Lee, an automotive industry analyst at Daiwa Securities. ``It's
going to be about who'll pay more for Daewoo Motor's debts. I don't
think that will be resolved in a few months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
