<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE13-COX     01-12 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas A&AMP;M chief may resign if probe finds lack of supervision in
bonfire
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen says he
will step down if investigators conclude that lax official
supervision played a role in the fatal Nov. 18 bonfire collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Amid lingering questions about the university's role, Bowen was
quoted in the local newspaper as saying he would resign if it is
determined that poor leadership contributed to the accident that
killed 12 and injured 27 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I say to someone, `I want you out of this job,' when
I'm at the top of that command?'' Bowen was quoted in The Eagle.
``I have to set that standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as the chairman of a special commission
looking at the collapse said the university's supervision will be
part of their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no plans specifically to bring the university into it
but, in trying to determine the cause, we're looking at the
physical, structural and behavioral issues _ and I can see where
the university's supervision could be a part of that,'' said Leo
Linbeck Jr., a Houston businessman whom Bowen selected as head of
the five-member panel. ``I don't think we should rule them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling Bowen's comments ``a pretty dramatic statement,''
Linbeck said they will not influence the commission's work. ``I
regret that this has spilled over into the life of the president in
this way, but that doesn't add any pressure to us,'' he said. ``I
can't imagine the stakes in this being any bigger than they already
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck said he was unaware of Bowen's stance until Wednesday,
but added: ``I would assume that his feelings reflect the gravity
with which he attaches to the occurrence. ... I know I think about
those 12 students every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which began preliminary work in December, is to
meet again Tuesday for an update from its consultants on the
inquiry. A&AMP;M officials earlier said they hoped to have a final
report by March 31, but some of the consultants have said they
expect it to take longer.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen, 63, has been president of the 45,000-student university
since June 1994, previously having served as interim president at
Oklahoma State University. He received a mechanical engineering
degree from A&AMP;M in 1958 and, while a student here, helped cut logs
for the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen could not be reached for comment Wednesday about his
remarks. But Cindy Lawson, the university's chief spokeswoman
confirmed that Bowen said he would resign if asked to or if a
failure of university leadership over the bonfire is eventually
found to have been a factor in its collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the ultimate leader, he feels he would be responsible,''
Lawson said. ``And that is not out of character for him. Honesty
and integrity are paramount to him. Taking responsibility goes with
that and doing what is right is part of the cost of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bonfire collapse, no one has publicly suggested Bowen
should resign. And A&AMP;M officials have repeatedly insisted that they
think the university provided proper oversight of the student-built
project.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent time came Tuesday at a press briefing, where the
university's official bonfire adviser and four top university
officials _ all of them previous bonfire advisers _ said safety of
the construction was closely monitored every year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though students planned and supervised the construction of
the bonfire _ reportedly the world's largest college bonfire, an
A&AMP;M tradition dating back 90 years _ the officials said the
university provided advisers to ride herd on the project, kept
track of the money and insurance, even capped its height at 55
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, the bonfire adviser, Rusty Thompson, admitted he
thought the ill-fated stack was 40 to 45 feet tall when it
collapsed. The investigation, however, showed it was 60 feet and
would have been at least 75 feet when completed. And, according to
investigators, student leaders knew they were building the bonfire
beyond the university's height limit.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, no design blueprints were ever required. And from
internal A&AMP;M documents made public so far, there appeared to be
little, if any, concern that an ill-built stack of logs might fall
over _ as it did on Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's student-run and staff-advised _ not by accident, but on
purpose,'' explained Bill Kibler, associate vice president for
student affairs and the bonfire adviser from 1983-92. ``Student
leadership is considered a fundamental part of A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
