<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BIBLE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida Bible classes illegal, group claims
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Bob Wright began teaching Bible history at a
public high school in Ocala, Fla., it made good sense to him to use
the Good Book as his primary text.
</P>
<P>
   But using the Bible is one of the problems with the course,
according to a liberal advocacy group that claims classes such as
Wright's are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Today in Tallahassee, Fla., the People for the American Way
Foundation will charge that 14 Florida public school districts use
the Bible as a history book and promote Protestant Christian
religion _ a violation of a U.S. Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation President Ralph Neas complains that including Bible
history on the state's list of classes has ``proven to be an open
invitation to local school districts to violate the Constitution
under the guise of teaching state-sanctioned courses.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Florida Department of Education said local
districts bear responsibility for any course. ``We do not monitor
how the districts teach the classes,'' said the department's JoAnn
Carrin.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida skirmish comes as some Georgia lawmakers push for
legislation that would force the state Board of Education to adopt
a Bible curriculum. Concerned about potential litigation, the
Georgia school board in December refused to vote on a request by
local districts that wanted funds for Bible classes.
</P>
<P>
   Neas, who will mail formal complaints to school superintendents
and Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, advises school boards to revise their
Bible classes now and ``not wait to be sued.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat shut down Wright's class this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're winning by intimidation,'' Wright said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the People for the American Way began surveying how 14
Florida public school districts taught Bible history. The inquiries
came after the group successfully sued the Lee County school board,
which had proposed a Bible class that relied on a Christian-based
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's course material was requested. But no one ever visited
his class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a proselytizer,'' Wright said. ``I just present what's
there. I'm not trying to convince students to be Christians. That's
not the way to teach it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 60-page report claims that's how it's been taught in
Florida, from Pensacola to Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Panhandle beach county of Santa Rosa, course material
``accepts the book of Revelation as primarily yet to be fulfilled
... We will accept the book as literal unless the facts are to the
contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   The report says that approach ``clearly teaches ... from a
religious perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
