<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AOL-INVESTORS-ART-NYT     01-12 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-INVESTORS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL, TIME WARNER SHARES DROP FOR 2ND STRAIGHT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also AOL-MEDIA-CONSOLIDATE) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online and Time Warner announced their engagement on
Monday, for richer or for poorer.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, investors decided the combination was for poorer,
sending shares of the two companies plunging for the second
consecutive day. The combined market value of America Online and
Time Warner is now less than before the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   With the specter of the 1999 failure of a similar merger between
USA Networks and Lycos hanging over them, AOL and Time Warner are
feverishly working to reassure investors that their combination
makes strategic sense, meeting with top shareholders, extolling the
virtues of the deal to the press and promising more details about
linkups between the two companies soon.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, people close to the deal say the drop in AOL shares was
not surprising, given that many AOL investors have come to count on
an extraordinary growth rate and care little about traditional
measures of stock value, like price-to-earnings ratios. Because
Time Warner is growing much more slowly than AOL, buying Time
Warner will dampen AOL's growth. Some AOL investors are selling
their shares as a result.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, AOL shares fell $4.50 to $60, and shares in Time
Warner shares dropped $5.375 to $79.625. While Time Warner's stock
price remains higher than it was on Friday, before the deal was
announced, shares in AOL have now lost one-fifth of their value in
three days. As a result, the total value of the two companies now
stands at about $280 billion. That compares with a total value of
$300 billion on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, investors believe the two companies are worth
$20 billion less together than they were separately. Still, the two
companies say the volatility will not derail the deal and point to
provisions in their agreement that lock them into a merger no
matter what their stocks do.
</P>
<P>
   So far, AOL's stock has been the loser. If it falls too far, AOL
shareholders may consider the merger unfair and rebel against it,
as Lycos shareholders did last year when their company announced a
merger with USA Networks. Lycos is a fast-growing new-media company
like AOL, while USA Networks is a traditional media company like
Time Warner. The collapse of the Lycos-USA deal was seen as a
signal that Internet investors would look very skeptically at
linkups with traditional companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``A merger of this magnitude, with old world meeting new world,
with different fundamental business models, relatively different
corporate cultures, different analysts and bankers covering the
companies, is a recipe for questions and concerns,'' said Jeff
Mallett, the president and chief operating officer of Yahoo, AOL's
largest competitor on the Internet. ``What they're trying to put
together is a big leap of faith, that these two companies should
coexist under a single roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as AOL shareholders wonder about their new company's growth
prospects, some Time Warner shareholders are frustrated that they
are receiving less than half the equity in the new company since
Time Warner will contribute 80 percent of the revenue and cash
flow.
</P>
<P>
   The gap in expectations has some merger experts bracing for
trouble. ``It's shaping up to be a fairly rough time,'' said Eric
Longmire, senior managing director of Wyser-Pratte, which
specializes in investing in mergers. ``You're going to get a
natural shift in investor base. Those people who own Time Warner
would want to own a Time Warner-type company, and not to own AOL.''
</P>
<P>
   While the executives and boards of Time Warner and AOL have
approved the deal, shareholders have the ultimate power. More than
half the shareholders of each company must vote in favor of the
merger before it can be completed later this year.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure the Lycos example is not repeated, AOL and Time
Warner executives spent Wednesday proclaiming the strategic
benefits of their deal and lining up influential shareholders to
express support for it. Executives of both companies say they
remain confident the deal will go through, and say long-term
benefits far outweigh any pain from short-term stock declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no outs,'' said Richard Bressler, the chairman of
Time Warner Digital Media and an architect of the merger. Because
AOL is exchanging its stock for Time Warner's, a drop in the price
of AOL shares lessens the value of the deal for Time Warner
shareholders. This agreement, unlike many other merger contracts,
does not enable Time Warner to walk away no matter how much AOL's
stock price falls, Bressler said. ``That means you're both locked
going forward together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there a collar on the deal that would allow for a change
in the ratio of 1.5 AOL shares for each Time Warner share. Whether
AOL stock rises or falls before the deal is completed, the ratio,
which will leave Time Warner shareholders with 45 percent of the
combined company, fairly represents the contributions of AOL and
Time Warner, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the deal are several large institutional investors,
including Janus Capital, which owns $12 billion in AOL and Time
Warner stock and would probably be the largest shareholder in the
combined company. John Schreiber, who follows Time Warner for
Janus, said Janus has bought shares in both AOL and Time Warner
since Monday's merger announcement. ``We think the combination is
far stronger than either of the two individually,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Michael Kelly, AOL's chief financial officer, said he and
other top company executives had met with big shareholders this
week. ``There's no concern about the deal,'' he said. ``We met with
the largest shareholders and they couldn't be more excited about
what we are creating.''
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate the benefits of the combination to investors, top
executives of AOL and Time Warner huddled Wednesday at AOL's
Virginia headquarters looking for ways to work together. When they
announced the deal, AOL and Time Warner described a number of minor
joint ventures, like adding content from InStyle magazine to
America Online. More joint ventures are coming, executives said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     01-12 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY CONSULTING FIRM URGES DISMANTLING OF MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A leading technology consulting and research
company says that Microsoft, to resolve its antitrust case with the
government, should pre-emptively break itself up into four or five
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a special report to its customers, International Data Corp.,
an independent research company with most of the world's major
technology companies as clients, concluded in a special bulletin
issued last month that a breakup of the company would be ``the best
outcome for consumers, for the industry and for Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-page document, which was first reported Wednesday in The
Los Angeles Times, was distributed privately to the software
companies that are the corporation's members _ including Microsoft,
which was given an advance look at the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their reaction was very professional,'' said Dan Kusnetzky, a
program director for the company who was one of the report's
authors. ``They thanked us for giving us notice that we intended to
publish it. They said most people don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Splitting Microsoft into several companies is one of a variety
of remedies state and federal prosecutors are discussing as a
possible resolution of the case, though in interviews Wednesday
several officials said no decision had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today reported Wednesday that government lawyers appeared to
have reached a consensus to break Microsoft into at least two and
perhaps three companies. Wednesday, the Justice Department said the
article ``does not accurately reflect our views.''
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman, Mark Murray, said, ``We can't speculate
on what the government is or isn't thinking. But a recommendation
to break up the company would be an extreme and radical proposal
that is not justified by anything in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials said a consensus was developing among the state
and federal officers involved in settlement talks with Microsoft
that a structural remedy was needed _ one that refashions the
company or its products in some way. But no final decision can be
reached until all 19 state attorneys general who are part of the
suit are consulted, and that has not occurred.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, senior executives of the Justice Department,
and perhaps others in the Clinton administration, must agree on an
approach. And that has not occurred, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement talks, overseen by Richard Posner, a federal
appeals court judge, have been under way since Nov. 30, and the two
sides have held regular meetings. But officials said they remained
far apart.
</P>
<P>
   The International Data report is unusual because most
independent companies working in the software field have been
reluctant to weigh in on this issue for fear of antagonizing
Microsoft and its allies. But Kusnetzky said many of the company's
clients asked for an analysis of this sort.
</P>
<P>
   After Thomas Penfield Jackson, the federal judge who is trying
the Microsoft case, issued his findings of fact in early November,
Kusnetzky said, ``We started getting questions from our subscribers
asking what this could mean for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's findings concluded that Microsoft was a rapacious
monopoly whose actions harmed the industry and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The International Data report runs through many of the remedy
ideas that have been discussed and dismisses most of them. Under
one proposal long favored by the states, as an example, Microsoft
would be forced to license the source code for the Windows
operating system to other companies, which would create
competition. But the report concludes that Windows is so riddled
with weaknesses and vulnerabilities that other companies would be
likely to say: ``I'm not going to invest my limited resources to
fix Microsoft's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company concludes: ``Our recommendation to
Microsoft is to take the bold step to settle immediately and
voluntarily spin off a set of technologically coherent companies
whose mission is to produce best-of-breed software'' and thereby
``adroitly maneuver out of the current PR disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   While that is the recommended solution, the company says,
Microsoft will more likely remain defiant and accept a more modest
settlement in the end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
