<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CDC-FUNDS13-COX     01-12 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDC-FUNDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big funding boost proposed for CDC
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The White House will announce today that it plans to
raise funding for an environmental research arm of the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention by almost 60 percent in its 2001
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The National Center for Environmental Health, based in Chamblee,
Ga., would receive $27 million under the plan, a $10 million
increase over its appropriation for the current year.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be targeted for research equipment and salaries,
said Dr. Richard Jackson, NCEH director. The center inhabits some
of the most dilapidated of the CDC's aging buildings, but
replacements have been funded by a separate appropriation and would
not be covered by the new money announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, whose lab is the only place in the country capable of
performing some extremely sensitive scientific tests, said the
funds would enhance the center's ability to test tiny biological
samples for exposure to toxins, and would assist in moving the
capacity to do those tests into communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big questions in environmental research is: What
are people exposed to?'' he said Wednesday. ``We often know what is
in water, air and food, but we don't usually know what is in
people. Being able to measure real people's exposures to real
toxins will help both allay fears when there is no problem and
focus our attention when we do find exposures. It's a question of
getting science to serve questions that people have in the real
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the environmental toxins the center is interested in, he
said, are potential causes for local clusters of breast and
prostate cancer, birth defects, asthma and non-Hodgkins lymphoma.
More than half of breast cancer cases have no known genetic or
lifestyle cause, and only 10 percent of prostate cancer cases can
be linked to genetics. Identifying environmental causes for even 10
percent of breast and prostate cancers could eliminate a potential
30,000 cases each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is technology transfer, moving these tools out to the
clinical world,'' Jackson said. ``Making these technologies faster,
cheaper, smarter and more reliable is extremely cost- effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the funds the White House is requesting _ which must be
approved by Congress when it debates the coming budget _ would be
earmarked for nationwide monitoring of more than 100 environmental
toxins and carcinogens to identify areas that are particularly
risky for women of childbearing age, children, minorities and the
elderly. Another portion would be funneled to state and local
health department investigations, the White House said. It did not
specify a dollar limit for either goal.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement marks the second time this week that the White
House has announced appropriations for the CDC in advance of
disclosing the entire 2001 budget.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, it said it would ask Congress for $65 million to
create a nationwide electronic communications system to collect
data on disease patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
