<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4403 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-12 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 COMMENTARY: THE GOOD GUYS WIN ONE AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Also see SCOTUS-LICENSE-DATA)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ My favorite toy is a fake cellular phone made of
black rubber. When self-important friends take out their real
status symbols, I jab impatiently at my rubber phone, smack it
twice against the wall in mock frustration, then, cursing, toss it
into an ashcan to the horror of all.
</P>
<P>
   But moved by ads for a device that won't pull my jacket out of
shape, last week I went to buy a real cellular phone at the local
AT&AMP;T store. I paid with a credit card and signed up for the
service. The salesgirl asked for my Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   I refused, of course; what business is that of AT&AMP;T's? ``Then
you'll have to pay a $1,000 deposit,'' she said. I told her to void
the sale and I'd try Bell Atlantic down the street. She then asked
her manager for a ``waiver'' of the Social Security requirement and
signed me up.
</P>
<P>
   That got me thinking: Why does AT&AMP;T collect that private
information? To sell to intrusive telemarketers, probably; the SS
number is not a credit credential but may indicate age and place of
first job and opens the door to collectors of other personal data.
</P>
<P>
   To see if a beloved colleague shared my privacy concerns, I got
on the Web to find his number. Sure enough, there it was in a
Securities and Exchange Commission filing. The SEC explained that
to stop making this available at a keystroke to every snoop around
the world, he would have to send in a new form without it. (When he
reads this, I trust he'll do that.)
</P>
<P>
   It's not illegal for AT&AMP;T or e-commerce con men to euchre your
Social Security number out of you. (There oughta be a law.)
Unfortunately, impelled by good publicity in tracking down
``deadbeat dads,'' Clinton policy has been in the opposite
direction _ toward a national ID card, a requirement that all
Americans carry ``papers.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's the good news: The Supreme Court, with all nine
justices in unaccustomed unison, Wednesday struck a blow against a
dangerous form of invasion of privacy: the sale by state
governments to private investigators of the personal data and
picture on your application for a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   Some states sell those applications, complete with color photo,
to anybody for about a buck a throw. A decade ago, a stalker in
California was able to use this license information to find and
identify a starlet named Rebecca Schaeffer _ and murdered her. That
led to a federal law, the Drivers Privacy Protection Act, that
allowed drivers to ``opt out'' _ putting the burden of refusal on
the applicant who did not want his personal information sold.
</P>
<P>
   The state of South Carolina challenged Congress' right to pass
such a law, saying it infringed on states' rights to regulate
driving. A federal appeals court agreed, ridiculing a right to
privacy in personal information such as a birth date on a license
``often needed to cash a check, board an airplane, or purchase
alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Rehnquist court has been powerful in stopping
Congress' three-generation habit of snatching power from the
states, the betting was that this case would continue that
anti-centralist trend.
</P>
<P>
   But to the relief of those who think personal freedom worth
preserving, the anti-centralist majority on the court, despite its
states'-rights predilections, stretched its reasoning to find that
Congress ``did not run afoul of the federalism principles.'' The
liberal minority joined in, resulting in a stunning 9-0 decision
upholding privacy.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the strengthening of the act by Sen. Richard
Shelby, supported by Frank Wolf in the House, will also pass
muster. They changed the weak ``opt out'' clause to a tough ``opt
in'' _ meaning that motor vehicle bureaus everywhere must soon seek
drivers' written consent before selling marketers photos and
information about age, domicile or disability.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said the decision ``will help protect women from
stalkers, keep telemarketers from interrupting dinner and give
people peace of mind that private information collected by the
government is secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates (Steve Forbes excepted) fail to see
privacy as a gut principle to defend, but the Supreme Court does.
As hope glimmers, pay cash and don't give out your Social Security
number.
</P>
</TEXT>
