u a BC-VIRGINMARY-SUIT13-COX     01-12 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGINMARY-SUIT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virgin Mary visionary, ex-followers settle suit
 &HT;    By Henry Farber
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nancy Fowler, the housewife who claimed to get visions
from the Virgin Mary, has settled a lawsuit with a group of her
former pilgrims who no longer are seeking to use her writings in
their literature.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale County Judge Sidney Nation closed the case on Fowler's
writings when he formally accepted a statement by the Our Loving
Mother's Children group relinquishing rights to some publications.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, group leader Robert Hughes said a religious
dispute of this nature should not be debated in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``After considerable prayer ... and discernment, it has been
determined that a court battle over Nancy Fowler's message is
inappropriate and displeasing to the Lord and the Blessed Mother,''
Hughes wrote. He listed a half-dozen titles of books and booklets
his group no longer wants to publish, including ``The
Commandment,'' ``There is Too Little Faith'' and ``Be Children of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rare example in court these days of somebody turning
the other cheek,'' said Michael Powell, an attorney for Our Loving
Mother's Children. ``Otherwise, this (litigation) would destroy
whatever good has come of the prayerfulness that has come to
Conyers through her visions.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement ends one lawsuit in a legal battle between Fowler
and Our Loving Mother's Children, which helped to organize huge
gatherings at Fowler's Rockdale County farm and published her
writings in several books.
</P>
<P>
   However, a larger dispute between Fowler and the organization
remains in a separate lawsuit in Rockdale County Superior Court. In
that suit, Fowler accuses Our Loving Mother's Children of
racketeering and fraud, claiming the group misappropriated money
from donations and book sales. Organizers had handled Fowler's
finances since 1987 until she distanced herself with a lawsuit last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Our Loving Mother's Children have said Fowler
is jealous because the group diverted its attention to a rival
visionary, Catalina Rivas of Bolivia, after Fowler stopped having
her visions.
</P>
<P>
   A Fowler lawyer said her representatives would not comment on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler announced in 1998 that she would no longer experience
visions of the Virgin Mary, which had attracted large Catholic
prayer groups to the property surrounding her home since the late
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
