<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AN HONEST VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first thing you should understand is that Terri
Thomson and Harold Levy are thoughtful, honorable and hard-working
individuals who care a great deal about the New York City school
system. Both spend an enormous amount of their time trying to make
it better. So when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani starts publicly
badmouthing them, recklessly assailing the motives of one and the
qualifications of the other, he does them a disservice.
</P>
<P>
   The school system in New York City is undergoing major changes
and can do without the bullying and the hysterics and the cheap
politics of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomson, the Board of Education member from Queens, has been
a reasonably steadfast ally of Giuliani's, although you'd never
know it from the mayor's most recent comments. When Giuliani and
his closest allies on the board became fed up with the latest
chancellor, Rudy Crew, Ms. Thomson was right there with the swing
vote that sent Crew packing.
</P>
<P>
   She has consistently sided with the mayor on major issues since
her appointment to the board in July 1998. But Ms. Thomson is not a
robot programmed by City Hall, and on Sunday she had the temerity
to cross the mayor by casting the deciding vote for Levy to serve
as an interim chancellor until a permanent replacement for Crew is
found.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's response was swift and ugly. As Abby Goodnough wrote
in Monday's Times: ``Mr. Giuliani said yesterday that Ms. Thomson's
vote was ethically questionable. `She gave no explanation for her
vote,' he said. `So, you know, in the absence of an explanation, we
have to search for one.'''
</P>
<P>
   That comment, a typically cheap shot, alluded to the fact that
Ms. Thomson and Levy both work at Citigroup. The question of any
potential conflict had been presented to Board of Education lawyers
well in advance of the vote and they ruled there was no problem.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's assertion that Ms. Thomson gave no reason for her
vote was wildly untrue. She has said again and again that she found
Levy's strong background in business management as well as
education compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover _ and this is where the politics get really twisted _
the mayor had initially made it clear to the board members and
others that he had no use for the man he ended up supporting for
the interim chancellor post, Robert Kiley. The mayor's acolytes,
board member Ninfa Segarra first among them, let it be known that
Kiley, the executive director of the New York City Partnership, was
not acceptable _ repeat, not acceptable _ to Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   And then, after the interviews had progressed and several board
members had been profoundly impressed by Levy, came a sudden change
from City Hall. Let the word go forth, it has to be Bob Kiley.
Forget all previous pronouncements. The mayor wants Kiley.
</P>
<P>
   To her credit, Terri Thomson did not succumb to the madness.
She's a fan of Robert Kiley, admires him a great deal. But she cast
her vote for Harold Levy because she felt he was the best choice.
</P>
<P>
   You can agree or disagree, but it was an honest vote.
</P>
<P>
   As for Levy, he's widely seen as a dedicated and gifted man. In
1994 he was chosen to head a commission that examined the physical
condition of the city's schools. The commission's report, issued in
June 1995, found that a generation of underfunding by the city and
the state, combined with ``flawed management'' by the Board of
Education, had brought school buildings ``to a state of imminent
calamity.''
</P>
<P>
   The report led to billions of dollars in new funding for
maintenance and repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Levy is a Citigroup executive and a lawyer who has immersed
himself for years in critical state and city education issues.
Until he was named interim chancellor, he was a member of the State
Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Giuliani insists in his snarling, contemptuous way
that Levy _ a thoroughly decent guy _ is not qualified to serve the
four or six months it is expected to take to appoint a new
chancellor. He'd rather have Robert Kiley, who was anathema to the
mayor until just a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   So which do you think is on the mayor's mind _ the million or so
kids in the public schools, or politics 101? (BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
