<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEXTFRIDAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE CUBE'S ANTICS IN THE 'BURBS GOOD FOR LAUGHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Friday,'' rapper-turned-actor Ice Cube's 1995 homage to
getting high in the 'hood, was at once memorable and forgettable.
You laughed all the way through it, but it's hard to remember why.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for the sequel, ``Next Friday.'' Like the first
installment, it was written and produced by Cube, who also plays
the lead role. ``Next Friday'' has moments of pure hilarity but
suffers from a lame plot; nonetheless, you find yourself laughing
despite its predictability.
</P>
<P>
   Cube reprises his role as Craig, a jobless schmo who still lives
at home with his parents and whose ambitions are few: getting high,
chasing girls, talking trash _ hmmm, kinda like Cube's real-life
music. Four years have passed since, in a moment of frustrated
bravery, Craig laid out the neighborhood bully Debo, played then
and now by Tommy ``Tiny'' Lister Jr. Debo's getting out of the pen,
though, so Craig's parents send him from the mean streets of Los
Angeles to live with his lottery-winning relatives in suburbia.
``Mo' money,'' as Puff Daddy says, ``mo' problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Suburbia, it seems, is infested with the same quandaries that
dogged Craig's hometown. Namely, a crew of punks lives across the
street. Craig's got his eye on one of their sisters (Lisa
Rodriguez). Insert chaos here.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating things, Debo and his bumbling companion Sticky
Fingaz (uh, that is his real name) have followed Craig by stowing
away in the dog-catcher truck owned by Craig's pop, in a role
reprised by John Witherspoon, whose creaky facial expressions and
mumbled one-liners offer some of the funniest moments in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Also consistently entertaining is comedian Don ``DC'' Curry, a
staple of African-American stand-up comedy shows. Curry plays
Elroy, Craig's outrageously feisty uncle. If we're lucky, Curry
will get some bigger and better roles out of this thing.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely missed is comedian Chris Tucker, who played Craig's
in-pot-we-trust friend in the first ``Friday.'' Newcomer Mike Epps
replaces Tucker as the gawky Day-Day, but Epps lacks Tucker's
elastic body language, which was the perfect balance to Cube's
cold, emotionless stare.
</P>
<P>
   If you saw the first ``Friday,'' you know how the rest goes, and
even if you didn't, it's not hard to predict: lots of bathroom
humor, pot-smoking scenes, racial slags, crass sex jokes and a plot
line that snowballs from a little tiff to, finally, The Big Fight.
Everyone goes home happy or goes to jail.
</P>
<P>
   So predictable, but so much fun, thanks to the film's rapid-fire
delivery. It's tough, in other words, to digest all the lame
moments, because you're still laughing at the good ones. Yet this
is anything but sophisticated, brainy humor. Think of it as Cheech
and Chong starring in ``There's Something About Mary'' _ it's
shallow, crude and hardly believable. You'll have fun forgetting
it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Next Friday'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Steve Carr &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Ice Cube, John Witherspoon, Michael Epps, Don ``DC''
Curry &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 95 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R for language, violence, sexual situations and
pot-smoking. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
