<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-UN-QANDA13-COX     01-12 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-QANDA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner's donations promote teamwork, U.N. official says
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two years ago, just as Atlanta businessman Ted Turner
was setting up the U.N. Foundation to administer his gift of $1
billion over 10 years to United Nations projects, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan appointed Louise Frechette as the
body's first deputy secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the foundation has distributed nearly $200 million,
mostly to projects on population and women's issues, children's
health and the environment. And Frechette, 53, a Canadian diplomat,
has helped implement Annan's U.N. reform, designed in part to
increase cooperation between different U.N. agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with staff writer Don Melvin, Frechette
talked of the U.N.'s ``10-year marriage'' with Turner, and said the
billionaire's goals mesh well with those of the international body.
Excerpts from that conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q: (Officials of Turner's U.N. Foundation) have gotten their
pace up to the $100 million a year they envisioned. Compared to the
$4billion a year spent by U.N. agencies on development, can that
type of money have a significant impact?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, absolutely. This is not an insignificant amount of money
in itself. Yes, of course, in relation to the full amount of ODA
(Official Development Aid) money spent around the world, or even
just by U.N. agencies, it's a small proportion.
</P>
<P>
   But first of all, Turner wanted to focus his effort. They chose
three very clear areas of concentration. Within that we have been
working with them _ quite productively, I must say _ in precisely
identifying where this kind of money can actually make a
difference. I think we've come a long way from a very general
concept of how we can work together, to now, a fairly detailed
understanding of what are the priorities.
</P>
<P>
   This is a kind of 10-year marriage we have with Turner, so I'm
sure that over time they may decide that they want to branch out or
add or subtract to the priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But once you start narrowing down the areas where you want to
work, (that amount) can make a big difference. Especially since
Turner is also very interested in, to the maximum extent possible,
trying to bring in other partners. And he wanted to use his money
to leverage other contributions or to leverage our own U.N. money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: (U.N. Foundation President) Tim Wirth has said that in
addition to the areas you were talking about, the U.N. Foundation
had other goals. One was promoting cooperation between different
agencies, another was strengthening the role of the
secretary-general, and another was building a constituency for the
U.N. in the United States. Taking those one at a time, how
effective has the U.N. Foundation been so far in strengthening the
role of the secretary-general?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is a tool the secretary-general can use to pursue his
reform. In a sense, point one and point two are intimately linked.
Since the projects pursued are based on recommendations the
secretary-general makes, it gives him a voice within the U.N.
system that he wouldn't have when contributions go directly to one
or another U.N. agency. In that sense, it's been helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Turner came in with his funds at the beginning of the
secretary-general's reform proposals. And we're seeing that this
and many other things have contributed, in fact, to creating quite
a different type of relationship within the U.N. system, where the
secretary-general is increasingly acting and recognized as sort of
the head of the family. The fact that we meet once a week to
video-conference, and that there's much, much closer interaction
between the secretary-general and the heads of the funds and
programs, as well as the heads of the departments here is another
example.
</P>
<P>
   So the Turner contribution fits in very well within the bigger
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some people might think that if the U.N. agencies have to
make Ted Turner happy _ after all, it's Turner's money _ that could
weaken the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not at all. Because I think the basis of our understanding
with Turner and Tim Wirth and the people in the U.N. Foundation is
that there is a very broad area of cooperation where Turner is
interested in doing things, and it fits very, very well within
established U.N. priorities.
</P>
<P>
   You know, I'm sure there are things that we might like to use
this money for, but this is not part of Turner's priorities, and
it's accepted. And in the same way, there may be things that one
day Turner would like to fund through the U.N. Foundation, but it's
not part of our established policy and priority, and they respect
that fully.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Increasingly, the U.N. Foundation is awarding grants only to
projects that have been developed jointly by two or more U.N.
agencies. Is that having an effect on the culture of the U.N.?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it is a contributing incentive to a trend that is now
pretty strong in the U.N. system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been told that in the past, in many places around the
world, representatives of different U.N. agencies rarely met, if
ever.
</P>
<P>
   A: Now they probably would say they meet too often.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When you have that situation, it seems it would be difficult
to have a coordinated assault on disease or poverty. How did the
U.N. evolve into such a state?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think (that) stems from a much greater degree of
sophistication in the U.N., and I'd say the international
community's understanding of the phenomenon of development _ that
there are complex interactions and interrelationships among various
dimensions of development. And that for successful development to
work, you really have to have a holistic understanding of the
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   So among what I call the inner family of the U.N. system _ the
UNDP, UNICEF, UNFPA (U.N. Development Program, U.N. Children's
Fund, and U.N. Population Fund) _ it is mandatory. They must work
together.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for the specialized agencies, who do not have any
formal accountability relationship with the secretary-general, this
comes in quite naturally, because that makes sense. So it is very
good to have the kinds of funds that Turner has offered to try to
relate to the team concept. That's fairly innovative. And I think
over time we want to develop more and more this notion that we can
fund not only one program or the other, but that we can fund a
team.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With regard to political support in the United States, you
have Republicans who campaign against allowing any troops to be
under U.N. command. You have a Democratic president who did an end
run around the U.N. when he felt military action was necessary in
Yugoslavia. What's your assessment of the support that the U.N. has
in the United States and the difference, or lack of it, that the
U.N. Foundation is making?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Better World Fund (a sister organization to the U.N.
Foundation) has done some very interesting polling in the United
States about the U.N., which demonstrates that in fact there is
quite a lot of support. And that the perception of opinion-makers
and leaders of that support is significantly lower than the
reality. So in a sense, it's very comforting to know that. We're
not operating in a hostile environment _ far from it.
</P>
<P>
   What this polling has shown, however, is that the knowledge and
understanding of what the U.N. actually does is pretty shallow.
There are things that make the headlines all the time. These things
tend to be peacekeeping, essentially. But in fact the U.N. is not
only about peacekeeping. It's about just about every aspect of
human life. What it does is in fact very concrete. You can trace
back some things that affect your daily life to action in the U.N.
But most people in the United States don't necessarily see that. In
developing countries our presence is that of those humanitarian and
development agencies. In the developed world it's a tougher sell.
And that's where I think Turner's efforts can help very much.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What, other than dollars, does Ted Turner bring to this
enterprise?
</P>
<P>
   A: What was very useful for the U.N. is that, by choosing to go
public with such a big commitment, he drew the attention around the
world to the U.N., to the fact that it needed the support of people
who have influence as well as money. And he really did challenge
people with similar resources to respond.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Former President Carter has said he thinks the biggest
problem in the new century is the increasing gap between the
world's rich and the world's poor. He doesn't see that turning
around, and it creates instability.
</P>
<P>
   A: I would share very much President Carter's assessment. I
think if you talk to most people in the U.N., that would probably
be the first thing they will mention _ the need to be more
aggressive on reducing the gap between rich and poor, and making a
real dent in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact is, it is possible. If one looks at it in a general
sense of, we'll eradicate poverty, some people tend to be very,
very skeptical. But if you break it down into concrete things, what
does it mean? It means people having access to clean water, and
having a primary education for all, and sending girls to school,
and eradicating some of the real endemic diseases like malaria and
a few other things, doing something on HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   All of these things, if you take them one by one and you look at
what would be needed, you realize that in fact you can make a real
difference if there is a convergence of efforts and a real
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   And, frankly, Ted Turner decided that he wanted to put his
weight behind the pursuit of a couple of goals. Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
