<HEADLINE>
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON LEAVES LETTERMAN CROWD LAUGHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton finally went on ``The Late
Show with David Letterman'' Wednesday night, and left the crowd _
and her once-taunting host _ laughing and cheering.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Letterman had been making an almost nightly shtick of
the First Lady's failure to appear on his CBS talk show, saying, at
one point, ``If she's going to be the Senator from New York, she
owes it to her constituency to be on this program because, it's no
secret, we are kingmakers.''
</P>
<P>
   His jokes about the Clintons were becoming more and more
merciless, and he began referring to Mrs. Clinton's campaign
staffers as ``pinheads'' and ``weasels.''
</P>
<P>
   When she at last sat in the guest chair, the funnyman was
gracious, even a little nervous, and the candidate-First Lady
stepped into the spirit of the show right out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that she has just moved into a new house in Chappaqua,
N.Y., Letterman asked if she was annoyed that ``every idiot is
going to drive by, honking.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton replied, ``Was that you?''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone loved it.
</P>
<P>
   Before she appeared, Walter Cronkite, the august former newsman,
walked out on stage and solemnly told Letterman, ``Tonight you're
interviewing the First Lady.'' Pause. ``Try not to be a jackass,
will you?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton came up with her own Top Ten list _ a parody of a
regular feature on the show: ``Top 10 Reasons Why I, Hillary
Clinton, Finally Decided to Appear on `The Late Show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Reason number 10 was ``I lost a bet with Tipper.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons: ``If Dan Quayle did it, how hard could it be?...
I needed an excuse to get out of dinner with Donald Trump... To
tell you the truth, I thought Johnny hosted this show.'' Finally,
Reason Number 1: ``If I can make it here, I can make it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   While hardly a crucial moment in the campaign, going on
Letterman was a step of risks and opportunities. If she came off as
awkward, it would reinforce her widespread stereotype as
standoffish. If she came off as relaxed, it could dispel the image.
In any case, videoclips could materialize at random all through
this year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Burnett, the show's executive producer, said Mrs. Clinton's
``people'' sent over the Top 10 list ahead of time, though he
didn't identify these people. He said there were no advance ground
rules to the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's campaign has not yet taken off. The latest polls
show her trailing Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani 49-41, with her
positive ratings falling below 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Burnett said the polls were not the reason behind her
appearance. For all Letterman's complaining, Mrs. Clinton's
campaign staff had said back in November that she would probably
appear in early January.
</P>
<P>
   She got in a few cracks at Giuliani, noting, ``He's done a lot
of stuff as mayor, but I think being a senator is a different kind
of job _ as senator, for instance, you can't go arrest a homeless
person.''
</P>
<P>
   She also dealt with the ``carpetbagger'' issue, saying she would
have lived in New York after the White House, even as a private
citizen, and, besides, ``New York has always attracted people from
all over the world _ that's what makes it such a great place to
live.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she aced a quiz about New York _ which Letterman
prefaced by saying her performance on it ``could make or break the
entire campaign'' _ identifying the state's official bird, tree,
number of counties, highest mountain range, and Great Lakes
borders.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Letterman _ who has had Giuliani on his show 16
times since 1994 and clearly gets along well with the mayor _
advised her: ``If you want to run a dirty campaign, mention
Giuliani's hair. It drives him nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton walked out of the studio at 6:30 _ the show is
taped hours before its 11:30 p.m. broadcast _ clearly elated,
telling reporters, ``I had a wonderful time.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Dees, a staffer on the program who saw her afterward,
said, ``She knew she hit a home run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
