<HEADER>
A4416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PHILIPS-HQ13-COX     01-12 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPS-HQ13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Philips Electronics expanding
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Downtown Atlanta has Philips Arena and the huge
Philips sign. But DeKalb County will keep the headquarters of
Philips Consumer Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Wednesday it has signed a lease to double its
office space near Perimeter Mall, where it will expand its North
American headquarters. Philips Electronics already has 370
employees and will use the extra space to accommodate growth and
relocate jobs from other cities, spokeswoman Katrina Blauvelt said.
</P>
<P>
   She would not say how many people Philips would add, but the
company doubled the amount of space it leases to 180,942 square
feet. It signed a 10-year lease. ``It's been a pretty rapid
growth,'' Blauvelt said.
</P>
<P>
   A division of Royal Philips Electronics of the Netherlands,
Philips Electronics relocated its North American headquarters from
Knoxville, Tenn., to Atlanta in April 1997. Philips Electronics,
which produces televisions, CDs, DVDs, radios, digital audio
players and other electronic goods for consumers, had considered
locations in North Carolina, Texas and New Jersey before selecting
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The move to Atlanta has been a very positive one for the
company,'' said Robert Minkhorst, president and chief executive of
Philips Consumer Electronics North America. ``You can see our
presence here when you drive by the Philips Arena, and now you will
be able to see our presence within Perimeter Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Blauvelt would not say if the new lease agreement will allow
Philips to hang a sign on the building. However, it is common for
landlords to allow major tenants to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In its recent search for a permanent North American
headquarters, Philips considered locations in DeKalb, Fulton and
Cobb counties. The company did not consider downtown because it
promised employees who moved to the Perimeter Mall area in 1997
that it would not stray too far when it selected its permanent
site, Blauvelt said.
</P>
<P>
   Philips' decision to stay in DeKalb reflects confidence in the
county's business environment, said DeKalb CEO Liane Levetan. ``We
didn't get the (Philips) Arena, but we are thrilled to have such a
prestigious worldwide organization be a part of the international
business community of DeKalb County,'' said Levetan, who personally
appealed to Philips to stay in the county.
</P>
<P>
   Philips' decision is another win for Perimeter Center and its
owner, Equity Office Properties Trust of Chicago. The real estate
investment trust bought the 3.3 million-square-foot park at
Interstate 285 and Ashford-Dunwoody Road in late 1997 as part of
its acquisition of Beacon Properties of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The lease also means Equity has started 2000 the same way it
ended 1999. Last year, several companies including BellSouth.net,
Nova Corp. and One Health Plan leased spaces of 90,000 square feet
or more at Perimeter Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing companies are our favorite problem,'' said Kristie
Abney, managing director at Equity. ``(Philips') decision to make
Perimeter Center their long-term home just really validates this
market's attractiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
