<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-VOICES-ART-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS IN N.H. DRAWN TO PERSONALITIES OVER ISSUES AS PRIMARY
NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 ( TRIMS) - NYT (ART ADV: Photos, NYT 22, 23, 24 and 25, of Chaffee, Foley, Shaw
and Burkholder have been sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADBURY, N.H. _ Joy Wilson, a 24-year-old music teacher here in
southeastern New Hampshire, decided to vote for Gov. George W. Bush
in the Republican presidential primary because he had skipped a
debate to attend an event in Texas honoring his wife. Although Bush
was savaged by local Republicans for not showing up, Ms. Wilson
says the decision illuminated his values.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the whole wife thing that clinched it for me,'' she said.
``Besides, I like his dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Cooper Burkholder, a semiretired saleswoman here who
describes herself as of Social Security age, said she favored Vice
President Al Gore, because ``he's a good man and seems to have a
very good wife.''
</P>
<P>
   David Parker, 61, a truck driver from New Ipswich, N.H., said he
was leaning toward Sen. John McCain, in part because McCain had
been a prisoner of war in Vietnam. ``We owe him something,'' Parker
said. ``That guy went through hell.''
</P>
<P>
   In more than 50 interviews in Madbury _ best known as the
hometown of the Democratic governor, Jeanne Shaheen _ and elsewhere
around this state, voters were hard pressed to come up with a
policy issue on which they would select their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in contrast to the New Hampshire primary voters of four
or eight years ago, who were bursting with worries about the
economy, the voters here this year seem fairly content. That leaves
them the luxury to focus even more than in recent elections on the
personal attributes of the candidates, the candidates' spouses, the
candidates' parents and, in the case of Gore, the candidate's boss.
Little is heard of issues raised in debates, in television
advertisements, in news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing McCain, for example, few voters mentioned the
intense coverage over letters he wrote to regulators on behalf of
contributors. The dueling remedies for health care put forth by
Gore and his Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, rarely
cropped up. Voters did not seem familiar with, or interested in,
the tax-cut proposals of Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch people and pick out a personality you like,'' said
Richard Colprit, 50, who owns a flower business here and mused
about candidates as if he were inspecting petals on the latest
bloom of roses. ``That's why these guys are out shaking hands and
kissing voters. It's personalities that get them the job. It's
who's got the biggest smile. That's what elects people.''
</P>
<P>
   Colprit, who favors Bush, is not the only one who looks for the
smile, the smirk or other telltale clues of character and
disposition in deciding a candidate's fitness for the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The views of New Hampshire voters should not be considered
lightly. They are among the most spoiled voters in the nation. Many
have been courted personally by candidates and they are far from
oblivious to the intense politicking.
</P>
<P>
   With just three weeks before the first primary takes place,
polls here show that Gore and Bradley are locked in a neck and neck
competition on the Democratic side; so are two Republicans, McCain
and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While the candidates are aggressively seeking to differentiate
themselves on issues, most voters interviewed said they did not see
much daylight between McCain and Bush _ or Gore and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, McCain and Bush are not that different,'' said
Colprit, who said his decision to back Bush has nothing to do with
the fact that the Bush campaign bought 1,000 yellow roses for a
Bush event when the governor first arrived in New Hampshire last
year. ``I've been a Bush supporter because of his family
background, his social values. And he has the whole party behind
him. McCain is a little better speaker. But I have complete faith
in George Bush, that he would gather good people around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Foley, 37, a special education teacher in Portsmouth,
said, ``I think Gore and Bradley are very similar. They're trying
to make themselves different. I'm leaning more toward Gore. My only
concern about Bradley is he may not have the experience or
sophistication to represent us internationally. His remarks can be
a little crude. His ideas don't seem as well thought out as Gore.
Gore seems to have more specific answers. But I like that Bradley
is somewhat of a maverick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Foley said she would not dare vote for Bush because of his
facial expressions. ``He has that Bill Clinton smirk that goes
right through me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Burkholder backs Gore, she said she ``would not be
heart-broken'' if Bradley snatches the nomination from him. ``They
are men who are a lot alike,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Likening her candidate to the ghost of Jacob Marley, Scrooge's
former businesss partner who was weighted down with a chain, Ms.
Burkholder said, ``Of course, he's dragging Clinton behind him like
Marley and his chain. Remember `A Christmas Carol?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
