<HEADER>
A4421 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      01-12 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS TO INTERVIEW SIDWELL FOR DEFENSIVE COORDINATOR JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New England Patriots' coaching carousel spins on as
the hunt to replace deposed Pete Carroll continues to play out.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Seattle Seahawks asked and received permission to
interview Patriots defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell for the same
position under Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell, who has been Carroll's defensive coordinator for three
years, confirmed he was in the process of setting a time to fly to
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Sidwell, who interviewed for the Patriots' head coaching
position last week, still has not heard back from Green Bay, which
asked permission to speak to him about its head job.
</P>
<P>
   Also associated with the Patriots' preference to land Bill
Belichick as their coach and general manager is a grievance hearing
to be held Thursday in New York to determine the validity of
Belichick's contract with the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Jets director of football operations Bill Parcells is also
expected to be at the hearing after Parcells had his first meeting
with new owner Robert ``Woody'' Johnson at the Jets' offices at
Hofstra University in Hempstead, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing appears to be the first step toward Belichick being
cleared to go elsewhere, presumably the Patriots, though
Belichick's side has been floating talk of other teams entering the
mix. There have been unconfirmed reports that Belichick is said to
be sought by the Dallas Cowboys, who fired Chan Gailey Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, who took over the Jets when Parcells retired at
season's end, quit Jan. 4 after one day as coach.
</P>
<P>
   If the decision is made that Belichick's contract is binding _
and the NFL has already made it clear it thinks it is _ either side
might then request Tagliabue to decide compensation through
arbitration. Tagliabue could also recommend a compensation figure,
but it would not be binding.
</P>
<P>
   That compensation will likely be less than the Patriots received
from the Jets three years ago when they forfeited a first-,
second-, third-, and fourth-round pick over a three-year period.
The compensation this time could be a second- and third-round pick
over a two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have decided not to interview any more candidates
to replace Pete Carroll until either the Belichick issue is
resolved or until St. Louis or Jacksonville is eliminated from the
playoffs. The Patriots are interested in talking to Rams offensive
coordinator Mike Martz and Jaguars defensive coordinator Dom
Capers.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coaches are preparing to head to Mobile, Ala., on
Monday for the Jan. 22 Senior Bowl, while Patriots vice president
of player personnel Bobby Grier will return from workouts for
Saturday's East-West Shrine game Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese's name is already
being tossed around as a possible head coach in Dallas after
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones bounced Gailey Tuesday. Gailey survived
only two seasons, going 18-16 in the regular season but 0-2 in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Zampese, 63, said Wednesday he's not interested. ``I've had
some opportunities in the past and I've turned them down,'' said
Zampese. ``That's not for me. I'm an offensive coordinator and
that's what I think I do best. I'm flattered when I hear that, but
I was meant to be sitting in that square box up there calling
plays. Nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampese was not interviewed for the Patriots' head job. He said,
to his knowledge, nobody had called the Patriots to ask permission
to speak to him about a job.
</P>
<P>
   With all of Zampese's contacts around the league and the
disciples of his offense, it appears he would have no trouble
finding work if he is fired by the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   One of his protege's is Martz, who is expected to get strong
consideration for one of the five jobs currently available. If
Martz gets a job, you can bet Zampese might be high atop his list
as a coordinator. Martz worked for Zampese with the Rams for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought (Washington Redskins coach and Zampese
follower) Norv (Turner) would be a very good head coach and I think
the same way about Mike,'' Zampese said. ``He's a bright young guy
with great ideas. You never know with anyone until you hire them
and give them the chance. Someone did that with Norv and someone
has to do that with Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong offensive coordinators are like gold around the league
nowadays. Jones is seeking an offensive coach to replace Gailey,
which is why Zampese's name has come up, as has Turner's. Zampese
said that Martz's system is a combination of what he does and what
Turner does, but ``it's all basically the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman likes Zampese and Turner, who
coached with Zampese in Dallas, and performed his best when they
were in control of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese still has no answers as to what went wrong with the
Patriots. ``If I knew, we would have corrected it,'' he said. ``I
thought we started well and then we just dropped off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampese has always had a decent offensive line and running back
to augment his passing game. Those two key elements were missing in
New England.
</P>
<P>
   In another matter, Patriots coaching candidate Willie Shaw,
fired by the Oakland Raiders Tuesday as their defensive coordinator
despite leading the league's fifth-ranked defense, spoke to the
Patriots Wednesday about his version of what transpired. Shaw had
interviewed with the Patriots last week for the head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   According to Shaw's agent, Ray Anderson, Raiders coach Jon
Gruden perceived Shaw as a threat to him. Anderson also blamed the
``dysfunctional'' Oakland organization for the happenings.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said after the Raiders removed the ``supervisory''
label off Shaw's job title Monday in order to give it to defensive
backs coach Chuck Bresnahan, the Raiders asked Shaw to keep guiet
about his dismissal. Shaw refused, saying he wasn't going to lie
about being fired.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's contract with the Raiders was up. The league is furious
with Al Davis about the firing because the league has worked hard
to put minority hiring programs in place, trying to expand the
number of minority coordinators and head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Rhodes was recently fired in Green Bay, leaving the league
with only two African-American head coaches, Tampa Bay's Tony Dungy
and Minnesota's Dennis Green, both of whom are still in the NFL
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With Shaw, Sherm Lewis and Emmitt Thomas, the Packers' offensive
and defensive coordinators who were let go with Rhodes, there are
only seven African-American coordinators left.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are now said to be considering Carroll for the
defensive coordinator's job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
