<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NH-VOICES-ART-2NDTAKE     01-12 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-VOICES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
MADBURY, N.H.: Christmas Carol?''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The interviews seemed to indicate that many voters were still
puzzling out the mystery of how they will vote Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But people described the leading candidates in strikingly
similar shorthand. Again and again, voters who were asked about
Bush mentioned his family heritage, namely his father, former
President Bush. As for McCain, voters repeatedly cited his
suffering as a prisoner of war in Vietnam and his
tell-it-like-it-is manner.
</P>
<P>
   The impression voters had of Gore was his relationship with
Clinton _ and very few thought it was a positive attribute, though
some gave the vice president credit for his seasoning in the White
House. People seemed to have less fixed opinions of Bradley; many
said they liked him because he seemed to be a fresher face than
Gore _ and was not burdened by the Clinton connection.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kurtz, 35, a Republican, said he was torn between Bush and
McCain, but said the governor may be more desirable because of his
family background. ``Bush has his father to rely on if he gets
stuck,'' said Kurtz, an air traffic controller at Logan airport in
Boston, as he was looking for a video to rent at a shop near his
home in Dover, N.H. ``That's a joke!''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was truly kidding, Kurtz turned serious: ``He has
connections. I liked his dad as president. McCain did very well in
the debate the other night. And he came up with the war stories _
that's pretty interesting stuff. But I don't know if he has the
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Ted Olivo, 28, a shipping supervisor at a Wal Mart in Dover,
said he too favors Bush because he liked his father. ``I'm sure
he'll give the same position on foreign policy that his father had:
Don't mess with the U.S. of A.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As he was pumping gas in Madbury on a wind-whipped night, Perry
Shaw, a supermarket manager, said he was leaning toward McCain.
``I'm watching the debates, listening to them all,'' he said. ``But
McCain seems like a straight shooter. He says what he thinks right
off. I respect him for what he's been through in Vietnam. That
wouldn't decide my vote, but it's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who is 48, said he was withholding judgment on Bush.
``He's raised a lot of money,'' he said. ``But I want to hear his
opinions more.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Democrats said Gore benefited from his experience in
the White House, voter after voter said his ties to Clinton were
his biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's forever doomed because he's linked to Clinton,''
said Diane Lynch, 28, a graduate social work student at the
University of New Hampshire. ``I think he wants to back away and
put some distances between himself and Bill Clinton. And who can
blame him? He thinks that's his ticket in, that's his way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ms. Lynch said she has nothing against Gore, but is
backing Bradley because she does not think the vice president can
overcome the cloud of Clinton. ``Does he rub me the wrong way?
No,'' she said of Gore. But she said Bradley appealed to her
because ``he's very similar to Gore but he's taking it to the next
liberal level.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Mary Desmond, 26, a systems anaylst from Hampton, N.H., said she
said backing Gore because ``he's not a snake like his boss. He just
seems to have a lot of family values and seems to be a normal
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hampsey, 36, a property rental manager from Jaffrey, N.H.,
who was one of the few voters interviewed who gave Gore credit for
the economy. ``I don't want to get off the bus right now, so that's
why I'm continuing to support Al Gore. Now if it was back in '90
when the economy stunk, then I'd consider trying to find somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore seemed widely disliked by Republicans, many had
nice things to say about Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley's the lesser of two evils they have on the
Democratic side,'' said Mark Chaffee, 28, a web systems developer
from the town near here of Somersworth. ``There's nothing that Bill
Bradley has said that I can disagree with. I've never liked Al Gore
at all. I don't find him to be very likable and being associated
with the administration is going to put him in a bad light for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaffee said that while ``it varies every day,'' on this day he
was leaning toward McCain but was also intrigued by Bush and Steve
Forbes, the wealthy publisher. ``I think I like McCain a little
more than the other two,'' he said. ``He seems to have a strong
character. That gives him an edge at this point.'' But, Chaffee
conceded, ``There's not a custom-made candidate for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who the perfect choice would be, he laughed, ``Ronald
Reagan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most voters brushed off the candidacies of the four other
Republican contenders. ``I kind of like Steve Forbes but he is
becoming kind of a joke,'' said Stacie Gregg, 28, a paramedical
worker in Dover. ``He keeps running and nothing happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Colprit, who owns the rose shop, was more direct. ``Forbes is a
joke,'' he said. ``You have to be realistic about whether they're
going to win. I'm sorry. Alan Keyes is a very nice person _ and I
hate to bust his bubble _ but he's not going to be elected
president.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Valerie, said she was also backing Bush, not for his
issue positions but because of his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just that Campbell's Chicken Noodle-style type of
family,'' said Mrs. Colprit, who is 40. ``The best feeling I'm
going to get is, God Bless America! Clinton is out and we've got
the Bush family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
