<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4425 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-OPIC13-COX     01-12 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPIC13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investment council targeting Latin America
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Overseas Private Investment Council is targeting
Latin America for U.S. investment deals, despite recent economic
turmoil in the region, and is looking to Atlanta to play a role.
</P>
<P>
   George Munoz, president and chief executive officer of the
federal agency, was in town last week to assess local interest in a
regional conference the agency is planning in Atlanta this year to
promote Latin American investment. He came away positive about
local interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an excitement and a definite capability,'' he said,
noting the involvement in Latin America of such local companies as
Coca-Cola, BellSouth, CNN, Southern Co. and Delta Air Lines.
``Atlanta is more and more coming to be known in Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   OPIC offers political risk insurance, project financing and
investment funds to U.S. businesses, large and small, that invest
in emerging markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has a portfolio of $18 billion and 650 projects
ranging from electric power plants to shrimp farms.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to foster economic development in countries that are
prime markets for U.S. exports, which in turn creates more jobs at
home. Since 1971, OPIC has supported $121 billion worth of
investments that it says will generate $58 billion in U.S. exports
and create more than 237,000 U.S. jobs. Congress recently
reauthorized funding for OPIC for four years, despite objections
from conservative activists who regard the agency as a risky
``corporate welfare program.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in $650 million worth of financing approved by OPIC's
board last month was $200 million in political risk insurance for
an expansion of BCP, BellSouth's cellular telephone network in Sao
Paulo, Brazil, that has 1.3 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Munoz, many big firms in the 1970s and 1980s
proceeded with investments in Latin America and elsewhere without
tapping OPIC programs because they didn't need them.
</P>
<P>
   But with recent economic turmoil in many emerging markets, OPIC
programs are becoming more popular. OPIC risk insurance, for
example, covers losses due to currency risk, expropriation and
political violence.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, said Munoz, carries about $400 million in risk
insurance for projects worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
