u a BC-MA-SWIFT-BABYSITTING-     01-12 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SWIFT-BABYSITTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABYSITTING, HELICOPTER CRISIS BRINGS APOLOGY FROM SWIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Abandoning her defiant stand, Lieutenant Governor Jane
Swift publicly apologized Wednesday for using her staff for
babysitting and moving chores, and said she should not have used a
state police helicopter to travel to her family's Berkshire County
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry if I accepted help from my staff even if it was
voluntary, because that can be perceived as an abuse of power,''
Swift said at a hastily called State House news conference. ``I
should not have done it and I will be very careful not to do it in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the most difficult crisis of her political career, Swift
also said she had asked the State Ethics Commission to investigate
whether she violated any laws by using the helicopter. She said she
would wait for the commission's response before deciding whether to
reimburse the state approximately $1,000 for the helicopter ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should not have used the helicopter,'' Swift said. She also
said she would cooperate with the ethics agency if it seeks to
investigate her use of her staff to watch her daughter and move her
family from Boston to an apartment in Northbridge.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor, who has for days been scolded by
Democrats, newspaper columnists and radio talkshows, appeared
humble and contrite. Swift had insisted for days she had done
nothing wrong, and blamed the media for spreading
``misinformation'' about her personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks had angered the public, especially other working
women who said they had to balance work and family life without the
perks of power.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci administration opponents had also seized on the
controversy, and Wednesday a state employees union demanded the
adminsitration clarify rules governing state workers babysitting
for their bosses and whether employees can bring children to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our workers, the same as Jane, have emergency situations where
their children get sick,'' said John Templeton, president and
executive director of the Local 509 of the Service Employees
International Union.
</P>
<P>
   The state Democratic Party was also on the attack. Mark White,
the party's executive director, said Swift should not have waited
so long to make the apology. ``The press conference today is a week
late and thousand dollars short,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Swift acknoweldged she had created a political crisis for
herself and the administration. Backing off her accusations about
the press, she said she was taking full responsibility for her
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Her sudden decision to change course came after conferring with
political advisers to Governor Paul Cellucci, other top
administration aides, and Republican colleagues Wednesday. Most of
them had been urging her to apologize and show remorse.
</P>
<P>
   Swift said she had talked to Cellucci, who is vacationing in
Florida, earlier in the day, but he had not advised her what to do,
other than ``keep my chin up.'' The governor's chief political
aide, Rob Gray, and Cellucci's chief of staff Steven O'Neill met
with Swift in strategy sessions at the State House Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Swift said she had resisted offering an apology because she was
trying to protect her family. She said she decided to apologize
after weighing public feedback for the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have come to this conclusion earlier, but I'm
willing to accept responsibility for my actions and say when I've
been wrong,'' Swift said. ``I'm still learning quite a few things
about being a mother and even more about being a lieutenant
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift called the press conference after a day in which she was
again beseiged by the media at State House. Camera crews and
reporters chased her down hallways, but she refused to respond to
questions. She offered the apology in a 5 p.m. press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy first erputed last week when the Boston Globe
reported that Swift used her staff to watch her daughter,
Elizabeth, at her home and in the office. The Globe also reported
she used two State House aides to move her and her family from
Boston to a new apartment in Northbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Swift said at the time the aides had all volunteered for the
duties and the two aides who moved her had taken vacation days to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Herald reported that she had used the state police
helicopter to commute from a conference at Logan Airport to her
family's western Massachusetts home just before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Sources have told the Globe that some of the aides had privately
complained about the requests from Swift to babysit but felt they
could not turn her down. Swift and her husband, Charles Hunt, had
used the aides to babysit last year on weekends they stayed in
their Boston apartment, rather than traveling home to western
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In September, they moved to Northbridge, and sources said Swift
has not used staff for babysitting at home since then.
</P>
<P>
   Swift said she used the helicopter for a pre-Thanksgiving ride
to western Massachusetts because she was anxious about her child,
who was at home with pneumonia. The conference was over at about 3
p.m. and she faced a drive of three hours or more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
