<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-BELICHICK-BOS &LR;      01-12 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK HIRES TOP SPORTS LABOR LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man has a great track record going head to head with the
National Football League and feels he ``has some powerful legal
arguments'' that could bring Bill Belichick to the New England
Patriots without any compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there is no basis for the league to issue any order
restricting Coach Belichick from coaching other teams,'' said New
York-based attorney Jeffrey Kessler, who is a last-minute hire to
represent Belichick when his case moves before commissioner Paul
Tagliabue and is heard in New York Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler is one of the top sports labor attorneys in the country.
He and partner Jim Quinn of the New York firm of Weil, Gotshal &AMP;
Manges, orchestrated the National Football League Players
Association's greatest win, bringing the players free agency in a
Minnesota courtroom in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler has also been heavily involved in union-league
confrontations in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick filed a grievance with Tagliabue shortly after
resigning as the New York Jets' head coach Jan. 4 _ after holding
the job that he inherited for a little more than 24 hours following
Bill Parcells's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 3, the Patriots had asked permission to speak with
Belichick about becoming their head coach and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue ruled at that point that Belichick was under contract
to the Jets and was not allowed to talk to any other team about
employment as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said Wednesday: ``I don't think there are any loopholes
(in Belichick's contract with the Jets), but I feel we have clear
and powerful arguments that he should be allowed to talk with any
team in the league about being head coach, without restriction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is no longer the head coach of the New York Jets, and for
the league to try to prevent him from getting a job as head coach
is an antitrust violation. This is just one of several strong
arguments I hope to bring to the commissioner. I have looked at
(Belichick's) contract and I feel it restricts him from receiving
offers from others teams under the current circumstances. The Jets
no longer want him as head coach. He should be allowed to talk to
other teams about being their head coach without restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said he will present his arguments to Tagliabue at about
9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will go on until early afternoon,'' said Kessler,
``and then I'm told that the commissioner will make a ruling, if he
feels he has all the information he needs, at that point in time.
If not, he will bring in the people from the Jets and get more
information from them (Friday), and then make a ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is represented by agent Neil Cornrich of Cleveland.
Kessler said he was not retained by Belichick/Cornrich ``until just
the other day, so I didn't have time to file any briefs with the
commissioner,'' he said. ``But I have seen the contract and feel it
is a clear antitrust violation to prevent Coach Belichick from
seeking another job in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to represent the Jets are team president
Steve Gutman and Parcells, the team's director of football
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets claim Belichick is under contract for them as head
coach for the next three years, and cannot take another job in the
league without the Jets getting compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, attorney Joel Kozol of Boston, representing
Parcells in a similar hearing before the commissioner, argued that
to prevent Parcells from going to New York from New England, would
be an antitrust violation. Tagliabue ruled in favor of the
Patriots. After being asked to negotiate a settlement by then-Jets
owner Leon Hess, Tagliabue awarded the Patriots four draft choices
over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Parcells told Hess not to pay the compensation, and
keep Belichick in place as head coach until the final year of the
Parcells contract with New England was up, and then Parcells take
over as head coach. Hess told Parcells that he didn't have much
longer to live (he died last year) and wanted to see Parcells coach
the team right away, which is why he opted to give the
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   It was this move that prompted the Jets to sign Belichick as
assistant head coach at the time, and future head coach of the Jets
when Parcells retired.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells retired following the final game of the season with
Seattle, announced Belichick the next day to succeed him, only to
have Belichick walk away 24 hours after that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
