<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XRATED-LAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRPORT SECURITY REVEALS BODY CURVES BENEATH CLOTHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES - A new security system used at Los Angeles
International and some other airports can peer beneath clothes and
show intimate body contours, upsetting privacy advocates.
</P>
<P>
   The new BodySearch system uses low-power X-rays to search
travelers for concealed weapons and contraband, providing an image
similar to a black-and-white negative.
</P>
<P>
   Because it also captures intimate body details the searches are
seen as an invasion of privacy by the American Civil Liberties
Union and others and most passengers picked out for searching would
rather be patted down than X-rayed because it takes less time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my daughter, my wife, my grandmother to be
subjected to something that will look at them like a Playboy
centerfold,'' said Erich Miller, media liaison for the Libertarian
Party of Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Customs Service, which has installed the $125,000
device in six international airports so far, counters that
BodySearch is a less-invasive alternative to physical searches by
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we originally had this machine developed is it's
not pleasant for any passenger to be patted down,'' said Customs
spokesman Dean Boyd. ``They don't like being touched. And honestly,
our inspectors don't like touching people either.''
</P>
<P>
   They also note that few people are ever searched.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Customs branch in Los Angeles did not have
figures for the number of people scanned so far at LAX. He also
said he was unaware of any contraband that had been detected at the
airport with the system.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials use the system as one tool to screen
passengers suspected of smuggling illegal drugs and guns into the
country. Passengers thought to be hiding contraband are first
questioned by inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   If inspectors still harbor suspicious about a passenger, they
will offer the subject a choice - BodySearch or a pat-down search.
</P>
<P>
   Those who chose the scan must first sign a consent form. Customs
officials then use the device, which runs a low-energy beam of
x-rays over passengers' bodies. The results show up on a screen
monitored by an agent of the same sex as the person being scanned.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process is conducted in private, out of the site of
other passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's going to see this or see you,'' Boyd said. ``There's
not a crowd gathered around.''
</P>
<P>
   The images are only saved if the scan turns up contraband, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the system is voluntary, it has still alarmed
civil-rights watchdogs. The American Civil Liberties Union has
raised questions about the use of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is ever a place where a person has a reasonable
expectation of privacy, it is under their clothing,'' ACLU
legislative counsel Gregory T. Nojeim said previously in testimony
before government panels on aviation safety and security.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, airline passengers questioned by customs
officials don't seem eager to step in front of the BodySearch
machine. Michael Fleming, a spokesman with the Customs Service's
Los Angeles branch, said most people given the choice have opted
for a pat-down instead.
</P>
<P>
   One reason may be that the pat-down is faster. While the scan
itself takes just a minute or two, inspectors must first explain
the procedure and obtain the passenger's written permission. The
whole process takes about 15 minutes, Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in a hurry,'' he said. ``They may have connecting
flights.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
