<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-KING-MARTYR-BOS &LR;      01-12 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-MARTYR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN LUTHER KING JR. ON LIST OF PROPOSED CATHOLIC MARTYRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., the Southern Baptist minister,
civil rights leader and inspirational orator, is a leading
candidate to be declared a martyr by the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   King, who would have celebrated his 71st birthday on Saturday,
would be an unusual choice for martyrdom for several reasons,
according to scholars . He was not Catholic, he was killed not
while preaching but while advocating for labor rights and his
personal life has been the subject of some debate in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But the US Catholic bishops have included King among a list of
two dozen Americans to be considered by the Vatican for a list of
20th Century martyrs that Pope John Paul II plans to unveil on May
7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King, whom I held in great personal esteem, is
somebody who was in many ways a charismatic figure and a prophet in
terms of civil rights,'' said Bishop Tod Brown of the Diocese of
Orange County in Southern California. ``His whole rationale had a
strong spiritual basis, and he immediately came to mind when we
started thinking about citizens of this country. I am hoping his
name will go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown headed the martyr nomination process for the United States
bishops, who wound up forwarding about two dozen names for
consideration to the Vatican. In all, the Vatican received about
9,000 nominations worldwide for inclusion on the list of martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the pope wants to do is, during this jubilee year, in
some way to honor men and women from the 20th century who have died
because of their faith,'' said Paul Henderson, executive director
of the Jubilee Year 2000 office at the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The list of nominees is not public, but most are likely to be
victims of totalitarian regimes, such as Nazi Germany and various
countries allied with the Soviet Union, or political violence,
particularly in Latin America. One of the nominees is expected to
be Archbishop Oscar Romero of San Salvador, who was murdered while
saying Mass in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The list of American nominees is small because few Americans
have been killed for their faith in this century. Among the
American nominees are four churchwomen who were murdered in El
Salvador in 1980, in killings that Representative J. Joseph
Moakley, the South Boston Democrat, used to criticize US policy
toward Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Undoubtedly, history will remember the 20th century as a time
of persecutions _ an era of martyrs,'' Bishop Michael Hrynchyshyn,
the chairman of the Vatican's new martyrs commission, said last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The early church frequently issued lists of martyrs in the first
several centuries after the death of Jesus, starting with the first
one, St. Stephen, an early Christian leader who was stoned to
death. But lists of martyrs, once essentially a compilation of
those honored by local communities, have become less common as the
Vatican has asserted more authority over the process of honoring
exemplary Christians, including naming some as saints.
</P>
<P>
   In the modern era, the Vatican has named only Roman Catholics as
saints. Martyrdom has traditionally been one of the main paths to
sainthood, but this year's list of new martyrs is to include
non-Catholics who probably will not be considered for canonization
as saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something absolutely new,'' said Lawrence Cunningham,
a a professor of theology at Notre Dame. ``The pope is aware of the
fact that it wasn't only Catholics that went to concentration camps
or Siberia, and he thinks it's only fair to make a list of all
Christians that died for the faith. He says he does not want these
people to be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said that naming non-Catholic martyrs carries great
symbolic importance as the Catholic Church reaches out to other
Christian denominations. King's very name _ Martin Luther _ is that
of the German theologian whose criticism of the church in the 16th
century led to the Protestant Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the pope to recognize Protestant martyrs is a very
important ecumenical move,'' said Daniel Boyarin, a professor at
the University of California at Berkeley and author of the new
book, ``Dying for God: Martyrdom and the Making of Christianity and
Judaism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only a few centuries ago,'' Boyarin said, ``when
Catholics and Protestants were burning each other at the stake.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, King is an obvious choice for special Vatican
recognition, some scholars said. He was a religious leader who was
inspired by his faith to work for social justice and who was killed
for his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always thought that ultimately the cause of social justice
related back to the Old Testament's prophets,'' said Clayborne
Carson, a history professor at Stanford University and the editor
of King's papers. ``His notion of his jeremiad was rooted in the
Old Testament notions, that the purpose of Christian faith was to
be a corrective in society and to challenge society.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a committed Baptist, King was ecumenical in his work.
He met with Pope John XXIII and attended many meetings with leaders
of other faiths, and spoke often of the importance of brotherhood.
Catholics, in turn, were often active in his civil rights marches.
</P>
<P>
   ``As early as the 1970s, people were asking: `Why can't
Catholics venerate Martin Luther King Jr.?' '' said Maureen Tilley,
a religious studies professor at the University of Dayton who has
written about martyrs. ``Martin Luther King, if he shows up on the
list, will show up as a martyr. . . for taking the message of Jesus
and seeing how it applied to a very concrete situation where his
aim was not primarily political but religious or humanitarian.''
</P>
<P>
   King's personal life has been questioned in recent years. Among
others, the Rev. Ralph Abernathy, a King confidant, said King had
had an affair with a Kentucky lawmaker, and the lawmaker later
acknowledged having had a relationship with King.
</P>
<P>
   Tilley said that King's personal life could be an issue at the
Vatican, but that others with blemished lives have been honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholics believe Mary Magdalene was a saint, and the legend
is that she was a prostitute,'' Tilley said. ``There's always a
chance of someone being a martyr for the faith after a pretty
dissolute life, but that always complicates holding the person up
as a martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   King repeatedly urged people not to see him as a saint, but
since his death he has been frequently seen as a kind of prophet,
according to Gerald Platt, a sociologist at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst who writes about King's image.
</P>
<P>
   ``People frequently make associations between him and people
like Christ and Moses, people who've led others out of tyranny,''
Platt said
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, in outlining his goals for the year 2000,
John Paul spelled out his intention to issue a list of new martyrs
who need not be Catholic, and who would not be subject to the
lengthy and grueling examination that attends formal canonization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church of the first millennium was born of the blood of
the martyrs,'' John Paul wrote. ``At the end of the second
millennium, the church has once again become a church of martyrs.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope made clear his ecumenical intentions, saying ``the
witness to Christ borne even to the shedding of blood has become a
common inheritance of Catholics, Orthodox, Anglicans and
Protestants,'' and called for compiling a new martyrology, saying:
``As far as possible, their witness should not be lost to the
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Martyrdom has a long history in Christianity, and martyrs are
looked upon as role models and objects of veneration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult to overestimate the importance of
martyrs in the Catholic tradition,'' said the Rev. Harvey Egan, a
Boston College theologian. ``Since Jesus died a violent, bloody
death reviled as a common criminal, to die for faith was viewed by
Christians as the supreme way to imitate Christ.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
