<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-TERM INTEREST RATES RISE WITH DATA ON ECONOMY DUE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long-term interest rates continued to move higher Wednesday as
investors awaited the release Thursday of government reports on
December retail sales and on producer prices. Retail sales are
expected to be strong, rising about 1 percent, while prices at the
producer level are forecast to increase 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Such results would confirm the current conviction among many
bond investors that the Federal Reserve will raise its short-term
interest rate target by half a percentage point over the next three
months. Fed policy-makers will next meet on Feb. 1 and 2, and
analysts expect at least a quarter-point increase, to 5.75 percent,
in the federal funds rate, the overnight loan rate between banks.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.71
percent from 6.67 on Tuesday. The price, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell 14/32, to 92 17/32. Long-term yields are
now at the highest in 2{ years. Shorter-term interest rates also
rose, with the yield on the Treasury's two-year note edging up to
6.45 percent from 6.43 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury auctioned $6 billion of new 10-year
inflation-linked notes Wednesday, and they received a surprisingly
warm reception. The real yield of 4.338 percent, which is adjusted
for inflation, was well below the 4.40 percent level at which the
last issue of such bonds, sold a year ago, was trading.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation-indexed bonds pay a coupon amount based on the stated
real rate, but their principal also increases by the amount of
inflation. In recent months, real rates have risen above 4 percent
for the first time since such bonds were first issued in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of increased public participation was noncompetitive
tenders _ an option used by individual investors to be assured of
buying bonds at auctions. These totaled nearly $81.8 million
Wednesday, the highest figure for any similar auction since the
first one, when such purchasers took $157 million in bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
