<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: THE BOND MARKET, REFUGE OF THE STODGY, READIES FOR
E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The corporate bond market took a step into e-commerce Wednesday
as parts of two major deals were sold on the Internet. And the
World Bank is planning a $3 billion offering that could be
all-Internet, including orders, purchases and trading afterward.
</P>
<P>
   As usual on Wall Street, there was a rush to take credit for
being first and then debate over what was really an Internet
transaction. In fact, in one deal the electronic transactions were
repeated in old-fashioned phone calls, this having been the first
test.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that the selling of new issues is moving in the
e-commerce direction and that it could open buying opportunities to
many small investors who did not have them before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time we expect that most, if not all, of our new issues
will have an Internet component,'' said Jeff Chandler, a managing
director for debt markets at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Tracey Curvey,
executive vice president of Fidelity Online Brokerage, which sold
some new bonds to its retail customers Wednesday, added, ``That is
the whole point of this _ to make these deals more accessible to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae, which buys home mortgages, sold $10 billion of notes
in two issues. The 10-year note was priced to yield 7.299 percent _
60.5 basis points, or hundredths of a percentage point, over the
yield on the 10-year Treasury note. The two-year note was priced to
yield 6.723 percent, 26 basis points over the yield on the
Treasury's two-year note.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lead managers, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said that
with its share of the new offering it had ``successfully launched
the firm's fully integrated online distribution capability for
institutional, middle-market and retail accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill White, the head of e-commerce for debt capital markets at
Morgan Stanley, said the sale included the first purchases by
individual investors on the brokerage firm's Web site. ``This is an
avenue for mom-and-pop investors that was not available before,''
White said, adding that there had been about 100 purchases through
the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   He said that for the first time at Morgan Stanley, institutional
investors had placed orders for the Fannie Mae notes electronically
and had the orders confirmed electronically. In excess of 35
percent, or more than $1 billion of the orders, came in
electronically. But he said that the final allocation _ in effect
the sale _ of the Fannie Mae notes was done by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   White says it is still unclear how far big investors want to go
with Internet sales. ``Institutional investors want to have a
relationship with a salesperson,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Merrill Lynch, another lead manager of the Fannie Mae deal, a
portion was also done over the Internet, including the final
allocation. But Chandler also said that this sale had been backed
up by the traditional telephone call between the institutional
investor and the Merrill Lynch sales representative. He would not
give the amount of sales made over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Ford Motor Credit sold $1.2 billion of
three-year notes, for which two-thirds of the orders were made over
the Internet. The note was priced to yield 7.34 percent, 80 basis
points over the three-year Treasury note. At the same time,
Fidelity Online Brokerage sold a portion of the notes to its retail
investors. Lehman Brothers said it received more than 200 orders
from retail investors through Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Weiss, head of global debt capital markets at Lehman
Brothers, the lead manager, said that as a ``fail safe'' measure,
all the orders and actual sales had been confirmed on the
telephone. He said it would take a couple of deals before all
investors would be comfortable with purely electronic buying,
adding, ``We will do this one and do another one, and as time goes
by, we will see where the comfort level is and then go to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weiss maintained that both institutional investors and
Lehman Brothers sales representatives were happy with moving to the
Internet. He said that with Web sites like Lehman's, which provide
a central place to obtain the information needed for assessing a
bond deal, institutional investors and sales representatives would
have more time to discuss the real value in a proposed bond sale.
The sales force, he said, will not be bogged down by administrative
details, including seeing that a prospectus got to an investor.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is not all the way to online selling, either. Ms.
Curvey said that while an investor could find out about the sale on
Fidelity's Web site, he or she still had to phone a salesman or go
to a local office to make the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that Fidelity is aiming to have an Internet buying
system ready in ``the next month or so.'' One difficulty in moving
to fully automated access is meeting all the government regulatory
concerns, she said, adding that once the system was operating,
retail investors would be able to buy new issues and also existing
issues, using various Fidelity sorting aids to help fit the bonds
with their particular financial strategies.
</P>
<P>
   With the World Bank deal, Goldman, Sachs and Lehman Brothers,
the lead underwriters, hope to make the leap into full Internet
commerce and trading.
</P>
<P>
   According to Victor Simone, Goldman's managing director for
e-commerce, institutional investors will be able to order and make
the final sale over the Internet, without any oral confirmation.
There is also an electronic syndicate being organized with the
Charles Schwab Corp. and Fidelity to bring the sale to the retail
level. He said that Schwab customers would be able to ``click and
buy'' the new issue.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, institutional and retail investors will still be able
to use the phone to buy the World Bank notes. But if this sale goes
well, the trend will be in the e-commerce direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
