<SLUG> BC-DICON-DICON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 DiCon Bringing Fiber Optics To Marina Bay  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A fast-growing East Bay fiber-optics manufacturer will develop 28
acres of Richmond's Marina Bay, one of several spots the city is
trying to transform into a high-tech mecca.
<P>
   Richmond officials yesterday said DiCon Fiberoptics Inc. will
build a 470,000-square-foot campus in the former shipyard in the
southwest part of the city. The new  &LR; $30 million facility, which
will house manufacturing, engineering and DiCon's corporate
headquarters, will supplement the company's existing 93,000 square
feet of offices in Berkeley's.
</P>
<P>
   DiCon employs about 400 people, but it expects to have between
1,600 and 1,900 workers by 2004, when the complex is complete. In
addition to the new campus, which will accommodate about 1,200, the
company said it has signed a five-year lease to rent 50,000 square
feet of space for 200 to 300 additional workers in Richmond's
Regatta Business Park.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said the expansion is the result of exploding
demand for fiber optics. Privately held DiCon had about $35 million
in revenues last year and expects to double that this year, as
companies like Cisco, Nortel and Alcatel gobble up its fiber-optics
components.
</P>
<P>
   These companies' optical networks ``are the backbone of the
Internet,'' said David Polinksy, DiCon's co-founder and vice
president for business development. ``Basically, the widespread
deployment of high-speed network connections to business and homes
is only limited by the pace at which component manufacturers,
including DiCon, can build and ship. So we're building buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   For Richmond, the move validates a 10-year-old strategy to
diversify the local economy by bringing multimedia, biotechnology
and other high-tech firms to an area better known for its oil
refineries. ``We've been a one-industry town for a long time, and
that's not good,'' said Richmond Mayor Rosemary Corbin. ``We are
looking for the industries of the 21st century and fiber optics is
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Corbin also lauded the company for signing an agreement to look
within Richmond to fill the varied positions _ from assembly line
workers to middle managers _ at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Despite yesterday's announcement and the city's high-tech push,
Richmond is losing one high-profile corporate resident. Pixar
Animation Studios, the company behind ``Toy Story'' and ``A Bug's
Life'' is scheduled to move its headquarters from Richmond to a new
facility in Emeryville later this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
