<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST  Internet Competitors See Nothing But Goodness
in AOL's Coup 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It must be nice to be an Internet media company this week, as
America Online pulls off the coup of the century and snaps up Time
Warner in the biggest merger ever.
<P>
   The reaction around Yahoo, apparently, was a big ``Yahoo!''
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief executive, Tim Koogle, speaking in a
conference call after the Santa Clara company released earnings
Tuesday, proclaimed, ``I see nothing but goodness.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the new behemoth represents your biggest rival? ``This
market is a big market,'' said Koogle calmly. ``It's more than big
enough to support several global branded network players, and we
fully intend to be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Koogle also took AOL and Time Warner execs at their word when
they said they would open up their cable networks to other Internet
service providers, and he saw goodness there, too. : &LR;   &LR; That means
more people will use cable to get on the Net and use services that
will benefit from high-speed connections, such as Broadcast.com,
which provides audio and visual programming over the Internet.
Broadcast.com is owned by, you got it, Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet chiefs hailed the deal _ Cnet CEO Halsey Minor
said it helps ``legitimize the currency of Internet stocks'' _ they
weren't entirely sure that it was a smart move for AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Now that AOL is such a huge company, it may have trouble
competing with ``a lot of very small, fast-moving, driven companies
focusing on very specific market segments,'' Minor said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Donnell, CEO of Salon.com, even went so far as to
suggest that the deal means AOL may no longer be an Internet stock.
O'Donnell watched as Wall Street punished AOL's stock _ it is down
18 percent since Friday _ and analysts reduced their estimates for
where the stock price would be in a year, with some targets falling
40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking a white-hot Net stock and partnering with one
of the world's biggest bricks-and-mortar companies,'' O'Donnell
said. ``AOL's investor base is used to these incredible Internet
run-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lycos tried a similar deal with Barry Diller's USA
Networks, Wall Street hammered the firms so hard the merger fell
apart.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when Salon engineered a deal with Cablevision, it
only sold 10 percent of the company. ``We did not want to take away
the Net value of the company by tying it to bricks and mortar,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo has done the same thing, shying away from buying any old
media firms, Koogle said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cnet and Salon are Internet firms, they are also
content providers, giving them more in common with Time Warner than
AOL. Yet neither company's CEO saw the deal putting pressure on
them to sell out to larger interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds of us acquiring a traditional media company over the
next five years are greater than that of a traditional company
acquiring us,'' Minor said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said Salon is ``not feeling this pressure that we've
got to consolidate, or sell the company, or get big with another
media company in a hurry.'' He said Salon only needs to spend about
$22 million a year to create its well-regarded editorial content,
and in the next two or three years it should become profitable.
</P>
<P>
   As a niche player, all Salon needs to do is stay in the 50
most-popular Web sites, not the top three, O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KNERD &QL; 
Cnet has made its name as an Internet company, but it's making
waves with its foray into radio. The San Francisco company, which
last week announced plans to air all-tech programming on radio
stations across the country, has plucked what it calls three
``rising young stars'' from San Francisco's most popular news radio
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Romine from KCBS and Kim Foster and Kevin Patrick from KGO
are joining the fledgling news team at Cnet, according to Brian
Cooley, the producer and leading on-air personality for the
venture.
</P>
<P>
   They'll start broadcasting at the end of this month on KNEW, at
910 AM, in San Francisco. The Cnet Radio venture is a partnership
with AMFM, the nation's largest owner of radio stations, which also
owns KNEW. Eventually, Cnet Radio will air on other AMFM-owned
stations in tech-savvy markets like Seattle and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   KNEW now simulcasts K101 FM, an adult-contemporary music
station, and may continue to do so on nights and weekends. Cnet
Radio will air from 5:30 a.m. to 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little ironic that Cnet has seen the future and it is
radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're forging new ground as an Internet company, using
100-year-old technology,'' joked Minor. Yet Minor says the radio
show should not only make money for Cnet, but help build the brand
and drive people to its Web sites. ``We view ourselves as a
prototypical media company for the 21st century, with the Internet
at its core,'' Minor said.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet already owns the domain www.radio.com and has been
Webcasting Cooley's reports there for the past four years. You're
most likely to hear it if you call Cnet and get put on hold. Cnet
plans to use a new domain, www.cnetradio.com, to promote its radio
endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   As for the content of Cnet Radio, Minor promises a focus on tech
stocks and personalities, and Cooley said his new hires demonstrate
a solid news approach, although none have tech-reporting
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet won't be the first to experiment with tech programming on
the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Garcia of San Francisco hosts a three-hour weekend advice
and call-in show, ``On Computers,'' that airs on 17 stations (none
in the Bay Area) and the Armed Forces Network. Garcia is hoping
KNEW will pick up his show, and he has calls in to Cooley.
</P>
<P>
   Bob O'Donnell has hosted ``O'Donnell on Computers'' on KSFO (560
AM), for almost four years.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, whose day job is research manager for PC displays at
the tech research firm IDC, said Cooley's program on www.radio.com
is ``a great concept, but nobody listens.'' And he said Cnet will
have ``a real uphill challenge'' in its new venture. ``It takes a
long time to establish brands on radio,'' he said. ``There is a
need for tech news,'' he added, ``but 12 to 14 hours a day is a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell's show ranks 20th in the Bay Area during its 1 p.m. to
4 p.m. Saturday time slot, with 51,100 people age 12 or older
tuning in at least five minutes, according to Greg Raab, marketing
director of KSFO, citing Arbitron ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Among O'Donnell's core audience _ males age 35 and older _ his
show ranks 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley dismissed shows like Garcia's and O'Donnell's as
``absolutely awful.'' He said they're geared toward ``hobbyists''
and are loaded with jargon and acronyms that confound the average
listener.
</P>
<P>
   One thing O'Donnell's show proves, however, is that computer
programming pulls in the ads. Even before dot-com companies began
flooding the radio airwaves last year, KSFO had ``phenomenal
success'' selling advertising on O'Donnell's show to
computer-makers and retailers.
</P>
