A4456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AOL-TIME-TRIBUNE-NYT &LR;      01-12 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-TIME-TRIBUNE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUNE CO.'S ASSETS LINKED TO AOL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   ( By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the fortunes of Time Warner Inc. and America Online are tied
up in the success of their proposed merger, the assets of at least
two other media companies will be directly affected by the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune Co., publisher of The Chicago Tribune and owner of
18 television stations, has the most at stake. It has a 25 percent
stake in Time Warner's WB network, whose increasing popularity and
revenue had helped push Tribune's stock price above $60 in November
from its 1998 low of slightly below $23, though it has since fallen
off that peak, closing Wednesday at $51.25.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune was also an early investor in America Online, buying a
stake at 7 cents a share in 1991, before the company went public,
according to Barry Hollingsworth, the company's investor relations
manager. That stake now totals 22 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   But 18 million of those shares are tied up in other financial
transactions. In April, Tribune issued 30-year bonds with a value
of $1.1 billion, based on the value then of 16 million of its AOL
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Any gain in the value of those shares will eventually be passed
along to bondholders as they redeem their notes. Another 2 million
of Tribune's AOL shares are also hedged.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the value of Tribune's remaining 4 million unencumbered
AOL shares is $240 million, based on Wednesday's closing price of
$60 _ about 1.9 percent of Tribune's current market value of $12.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   A Tribune spokeswoman, Katherine Sopranos, said the company had
no immediate plans to make any changes in its holdings of AOL stock
or the WB network.
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror, an early investor in Netscape, received AOL shares
in exchange for its Netscape holding when AOL bought the Internet
browser company. The company now owns about 1 million AOL shares,
which it has also hedged. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
