<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANNERS-SCANNERS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Improved Mobile Scanners Let Users Duplicate Documents Anywhere  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Until recently, even the most wired of mobile warriors had to
resort to pen, paper or copy machine if she came across a useful
article or image at a client's office or in the library. Even if
with a laptop, scanning the item in wasn't an option, because most
scanners were simply too bulky to take on the road.
<P>
   Today, however, that's changing: Some new models are small and
light enough for a briefcase, a purse or in some cases even a
pocket. Of course, these new mobile scanners are still far from
matching the capabilities of their desktop cousins, but little by
little, they're making scanning on the go a realistic possibility.
</P>
<P>
   These new-generation devices come in several sizes and shapes.
At least four companies now market pen-style mobile scanners. They
actually look more like a handyman's utility knife, but you use
them like a pen or highlighter, running them line by line over the
text you want to capture. They work without a computer connection,
storing scanned data temporarily in their own memory, so you can
use them on a plane, in a library or just about anywhere else, even
if you don't have a portable computer.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard has taken a different approach with its unique
CapShare 920. About the size of a sandwich, the $499 device
is &LR; scans entire blocks of text and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   For those who carry a notebook computer, NEC Technologies has
just released another intriguing option. Its new PetiScan, just
$149, is a flatbed color model that's no bigger than a book, weighs
only 1.3 pounds and gets its power from the computer it's connected
to.
</P>
<P>
   I recently put the PetiScan, the CapShare and two of the
pen-style units, Siemens' $99.95 Pocket Reader and Wizcom
Technologies' $149 QuickLink Pen, through their paces. Here's what
I found:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SIEMENS POCKET READER
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; In addition to being the least expensive of the scanners I tried,
the Pocket Reader works with more computer systems, including the
Mac and Linux.
</P>
<P>
   To scan text, you simply hold it at the beginning of a line,
press down gently and roll the scanning head across the line.
Built-in optical character recognition software instantly converts
the scanned image into digital text, the last 24 characters of
which show up in a one-line LCD window on the side. Then you go to
the start of the next line and do it again, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   When you're done, you connect the Pocket Reader to a computer,
via a serial cable, and then launch a small program where you can
download, edit and copy the text you've scanned.
</P>
<P>
   Although I appreciated the Pocket Reader's simplicity, I can't
recommend the device. First of all, it works only with type that's
between 8 and 16 points in size. That includes most standard text
in letters, books and magazines, but it excludes a lot: headlines
and much ad material on the big end and, in the opposite direction,
the fine print in product catalogs, stock listings and phone
directories, not to mention business cards.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Pocket Reader's memory is limited to about two pages
of text, so you can't scan much without offloading to your
computer. There's not much point, for instance, in taking the
device to a library to take notes unless you bring along a laptop
computer _ or unless you're looking for just a few tidbits of
information, in which case a pen and paper would probably do the
trick just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, I found the Pocket Reader's OCR feature
infuriatingly inaccurate. My results, even from clear, plainly
printed originals, were riddled with errors, sometimes to the point
of being flat-out incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said the company is aware of the limitations of the
Pocket Reader's OCR technology and hopes to offer improvements
soon. That's something to look forward to, but in the meantime I
can't see spending $100 on the product.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WIZCOM QUICKLINK PEN
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; The QuickLink Pen looks like the Pocket Reader, except that it has
a three-line window on the side and a slightly curved tip.
</P>
<P>
   The QuickLink Pen also works roughly like the Siemens product,
except that it can transfer text only to Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, though, the QuickLink Pen has fewer limitations. It
works with text of 6 to 22 points. And the QuickLink has more
memory than you're ever likely to need: It holds 1,000 pages
(according to the company _ I confess I didn't test this claim),
and if that's not enough, you can add an extra memory card.
</P>
<P>
   Wizcom's OCR engine also proved far more accurate. The price is
slower operation _ after each line you scan, there's a delay of 5
to 10 seconds. I ran into only one serious accuracy problem: In two
cases, the QuickLink inserted an extra digit into scanned numbers _
one a phone number, the other a product price. You can't correct
the mistake unless you wrote down the number _ which defeats the
whole purpose of scanning!
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that issue, my biggest gripe about the QuickLink Pen
is that it suffers from a severe case of featuritis. In addition to
free-form text notes, it has separate applications built into the
pen to handle URLs, tables and contact information. It even tries
to let you compose and edit text right on the pen, by selecting
letters one at a time on the screen or by scanning from a bar-coded
alphabet on a sheet pasted on the device's case.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, each of these features is a godsend to someone, but to
me _ and, I suspect, most users _ they're overkill. And you can't
just ignore them: The first thing the device does when you're ready
to scan is ask you to name the file, so you have to confront its
complex text-entry scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is compounded by an inadequate manual. It badly
needs an index and doesn't really give you step-by-step
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea of a pen scanner appeals to you, the QuickLink Pen
seems to be the one to get. Dedicated users can undoubtedly
accomplish a lot with its array of programs and features. Just be
prepared to spend a fair bit of time figuring it all out. And don't
forget to write down any critical numbers you scan.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HP CAPSHARE 920
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  The CapShare 920 is a critter of a very different species.
Instead of rolling over a line at a time, you drag it across entire
blocks of text. If the material is wider than the device's
5-inch-wide scanning head, you simply make another pass over the
remaining text, and the device automatically stitches together the
separate swathes into a single image. You can scan a whole page of
text _ a task that would probably take 10 minutes with a pen
scanner _ in about 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the pens, the CapShare can record text of any size, and
even graphics, though it doesn't preserve colors. The 920 model,
which replaced the original 910 in the fall, even has a ``flip
chart'' mode, where you can capture conference-room scribblings and
sketches at 25 percent of their original size.
</P>
<P>
   Also in contrast to the pens, the CapShare doesn't do OCR on the
fly; instead, it stores scanned material as images. The 4 megabytes
of memory built-in holds about 50 letter-size pages. A small LCD
screen on the unit lets you review and manage stored files, zooming
in to see details and even cropping out unwanted material. The
screen is dim and small, but text is quite readable in magnified
mode.
</P>
<P>
   When you're back at the office, you can print directly, and
wirelessly, from the CapShare to printers from HP and other vendors
that have infrared capabilities. Or you can transfer the files to
your PC or handheld, using either IR or a serial cable.
</P>
<P>
   ScanSoft PagisPro, an included document-management program,
gives you lots of other options, including printing, faxing and
editing scanned material or sending it to another PC application.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, it offers the option of having scanned text
recognized by ScanSoft's TextBridge Pro, which is included.
TextBridge is one of the best OCR programs available, and on my
test files it worked almost perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, I found the CapShare a pleasure to use. At $499,
it's clearly not for everyone, but for mobile professionals with a
serious need for scanning, I recommend it highly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEC PETISCAN
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  The PetiScan is different from the three products above, in that
it can't be used independently of a Mac or PC _ it has no memory to
hold scanned images on its own, and it even depends on the computer
for electric power, provided over the same USB cable through which
it transfers scanned data.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's really a conventional flatbed scanner, but so
small and light that it's easy to bring along with a laptop. It has
a resolution of 300 by 600 dots per inch, and it works in full
color.
</P>
<P>
   The PetiScan has a unique ``reversible scanning'' feature: If
you want to scan something that won't fit on its miniature flatbed,
such as a big book, or even a wall-mounted poster, you can remove
the flatbed's cover, flip the PetiScan over and place it on top of
the material you want scanned, using a see-through window to line
up the image properly.
</P>
<P>
   Bundled with the device are both Windows and Mac versions of
Adobe PhotoDeluxe, a simple image-editing application, and
NewSoft's Presto PageManager, a document-management and OCR package
roughly comparable to the PagisPro program included with HP's
CapShare. The NewSoft program isn't as polished as PagisPro, and
its OCR function isn't quite as accurate, but the Windows version
worked pretty well for me.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could say the same about the Mac version, which is
seriously buggy. It repeatedly stalled during scans, until I
figured out that I could keep it going just by sliding my finger
around on the iBook's touchpad. Several times, it froze solid.
</P>
<P>
   For both Mac and Windows users, the PetiScan has one serious
limitation: The maximum area you can scan at one time is only 5.8
by 3.9 inches. That's sufficient for postcards, small snapshots,
receipts and business cards, but not for most printed matter. It's
not even quite wide enough for the text in a standard letter
layout.
</P>
<P>
   Included software lets you stitch two scanned images together
but doesn't do it as seamlessly as HP's CapShare. And I never did
figure out how to stitch two pieces of scanned text together and
save them in a form PageManager could then OCR.
</P>
<P>
   In short, although the PetiScan is effective for images and
blocks of text small enough to fit its image area, it's not a good
choice if you expect to scan many documents larger than a postcard.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
