r f BC-DIALPAD-DIALPAD_SFCHR     01-12 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALPAD-DIALPAD </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Dialpad Delivers Free Phoning  &HT;     By David A. Steinberg 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Dialpad.com, which promises free long-distance calls to anyone
with a personal computer, Web access and a headset, can be a good
deal for someone on a budget, but less-than-pindrop quality means
AT&AMP;T, MCI and Sprint have little reason to be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Telephony _ the ability to place phone calls using your computer
_ could be one of the most useful benefits of the Internet to the
average computer user. Not long ago, the only way to use your
computer to make Internet calls was through a PC-to-PC system that
required both caller and recipient to have the same software and be
logged on at a prearranged time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, several companies offer PC-to-phone service at discounted
rates. Some only work when calling U.S. numbers; others extend the
service overseas. A few companies offer free calling if you provide
some basic demographic information and agree to watch or listen to
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Dialpad.com _ which yesterday said it has signed up 2
million users since its launch in October _ offers probably the
simplest system. Download the Dialpad software (at
www.dialpad.com), fill out a questionnaire so the company can
target its ads to your demographic niche and start making free
calls to anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: You log on to your account at the Dialpad
site and a minibrowser/dialer pops up. Dial the phone number (on
your keyboard or by using your mouse to punch the numbers
on-screen) and the call goes through. Banner ads run continuously
on the Dialpad dialer, but they're pretty unobtrusive. You can't
totally ignore them, though: If you pull up another program or Web
browser, the Dialpad dialer keeps reasserting itself to remain on
top.
</P>
<P>
   When you place your call, Dialpad routs it over the Internet,
then automatically relays it to the telephone number you're
calling.
</P>
<P>
   What's the catch? Well, the sound quality is inconsistent, and
depending on the speed of your modem (my 56K modem performed
adequately but a slower connection could cause problems), the
degree of Net traffic and other variables, holding a conversation
via Dialpad can be a frustrating experience.
</P>
<P>
   The quality is pretty much on par with calls made over a cell
phone: sometimes fine, sometimes awful. The first time I called my
sister in Los Angeles, she hung up twice because she couldn't hear
me. She probably thought it was a crank call. Now, I'm prepared to
yell ``Hello'' as soon as the call connects. She doesn't hang up on
me anymore, but if the sound quality is bad, she berates me for
calling on ``that damn Internet phone.''
</P>
<P>
   The same problem makes dealing with answering machines dicey.
Many of these devices are voice-activated, so if the sound quality
isn't great, the machine is liable to hang up before you can shout
your message.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to save money on long-distance bills, but I quickly
realized Dialpad would be useless for calling most of my relatives.
To put it delicately, they're somewhat technologically challenged.
There's no way my mother would put up with dropped words and the
occasional delay in the transmission. After all, this is a woman
who only recently accepted the inevitability of call waiting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the real advantages of Dialpad is being able to make
phone calls while online. For those who have just one phone line,
you can use Dialpad to call an East Coast technical support number
at noon and not worry about paying day rates to sit on hold for 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, you can work online with the technician to solve a
problem you're having. Log in to the Dialpad Web site and the
minibrowser/dialer pops up. Dial that East Coast number, get the
tech on the line, then switch to your main browser, word processor
or spreadsheet to keep working while you talk.
</P>
<P>
   Dialpad and its fee-based competitors are Java-based systems
that run strictly on Windows, so Mac users are out of luck. The
services are useful when conditions are optimal; just make sure you
have a speedy modem and aren't trying to run too many programs at
once.
</P>
<P>
   All require Windows 95, 98 or NT, a sound card, some sort of
microphone and speakers. The best option is to use a headset that
plugs into the sound in and sound out ports on your PC. It will be
easier to hear the person on the other end and your voice will be
transmitted more clearly. You'll also have more privacy than if you
try yelling toward a computer-mounted microphone and listening to
the response on speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Even when sound quality is fine, though, Dialpad has some
quirks. The service goes down occasionally, so during busy times,
you might get a ``no channel available'' message. Also, you can't
dial directory assistance numbers (although since you're already
online, you can surf over to 555-1212.com, InfoSpace.com or other
Web sites that look up phone numbers for free).
</P>
<P>
   It's definitely worthwhile trying out Dialpad if you have a 56K
or faster Internet connection, plan to call somewhat-forgiving
friends and want to save money on daytime toll calls. Just be aware
of its limitations and be prepared for occasional ribbing from
friends and relatives who think you're calling from inside a tin
can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
