<HEADER>
A4464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER-REAX13-COX     01-12 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-REAX13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker's remarks continue to generate controversy
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ Reaction was mixed in John Rocker's hometown after
his first public comments since his controversial remarks appeared
in Sports Illustrated last month.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rivera, a native of Puerto Rico currently living in
Macon, said Rocker's interview on ESPN did nothing to erase the
impact of his earlier comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the words are out of your mouth, there's nothing (you can
do),'' Rivera said. ``Everything you do has an effect. If I say
some racial statement, it may affect the four or five people around
me who hear it. If somebody like him says it, it may affect 5
million people.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Morey said he believes Rocker was sincere in his
interview, and that his earlier comments were the result of a
frustrated athlete blowing off steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's from New York fans being so rude,'' said
Morey, a bartender at Jocks &AMP; Jills. ``I don't think there was
anything else meant by it. I don't think it was right what he said,
but you show me somebody who's never made a racist comment some
time in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kennedy, a self-employed native of Macon, blamed the media
for the outcry over Rocker's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Barkley (former NBA forward) is black and because he's
black, he talks and the press lets him off the hook,'' Kennedy
said. ``John Rocker is white, and it's journalism of the 1990s and
2000 to be politically correct. A lot of what Charles says is true,
but a lot of what John says is true, too. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But ... he hasn't hurt anybody, he hasn't taken any drugs, he
hasn't committed any crimes. It's his constitutional right to say
whatever he wants to say.''
</P>
<P>
   And what should baseball do about Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   ``What to do about it? Nothing is what to do about it,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, however, some fans held a different opinion. Frank
Landgraff, a Braves season ticket holder, believes the team should
trade or release Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be interesting if he were a marginally good player,
because I think he would have been cut already,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an athlete, he is in a class that's consistent with a top
performer,'' said Mark Bogart of Marietta. ``Morally, it would seem
he's in a low class.''
</P>
<P>
   Landgraff, who watched the interview at the CNN Center, wasn't
impressed by Rocker's apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's easy after you make a statement like that to say
you're sorry,'' he said. ``The real proof of whether he means it or
not is if the team, if he does come back, accepts him.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Ken Sugiura
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
