<HEADER>
A4466 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-HNS &LR;      01-12 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
They were the first team to clinch a playoff berth, the first to
win a division title and the first to secure the home-field
advantage throughout the postseason.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet there are still plenty who doubt the St. Louis Rams are for
real.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they went 13-3 in the regular season, and they've had
enough bad years to have stockpiled a number of top draft picks.
Still, there are those who would put an asterisk by their record.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, they earned that record, but they did so in a year in
which the theme of the NFL was mediocrity. What does that mean for
the Rams? It means they're slightly better than mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what they're hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot of guys feel we have something to prove,
because we haven't gotten the respect we feel we deserve,'' St.
Louis quarterback Kurt Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams believe they've proved themselves over and over. They
scored the third-most points (526) in NFL history and outscored
their opponents by 284 points, the second-largest differential
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? The Minnesota Vikings made a similar run through
the league last season, scoring the most points ever (556) in
compiling a 15-1 record. But for all their flashy numbers, the
Vikings didn't make the Super Bowl, losing at home in the NFC
Championship Game to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams hope they can avoid such a fate Sunday against a
Vikings team that is a year wiser, if a lot less dominant. An
explosive offensive game is expected.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of those who believe the Vikings may be the
team that pulls off the upset this year. The Rams didn't exactly
have the toughest schedule, playing only four teams with winning
records at the time of the matchup. Of those four, only the
Tennessee Titans finished the season with a winning record. The
Titans handed St. Louis one of its three losses. The other two came
at the hands of Detroit and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no denying the numbers this Rams team put up.
Warner, the biggest surprise, was a last-minute fill-in (for the
injured Trent Green) better known for his exploits in the Arena
Football League and NFL Europe than in the NFL. Warner became the
NFL's Most Valuable Player this season, throwing for 4,353 yards
and 41 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been only half the story. Running back Marshall
Faulk, whom the Rams acquired from the Indianapolis Colts two days
before the April draft, led the NFL by gaining a record 2,429 yards
from scrimmage this season (1,381 rushing, 1,048 receiving).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rams figure it's time for the rest of the nation to see
how good they are,'' Warner said. ``We've played to the level of
talent that we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nation saw the Rams only on highlight clips.
Considering the team was 45-99 (.311) in the '90s coming into the
season, the networks weren't inclined to schedule their games
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But now that his team has center stage, St. Louis coach Dick
Vermeil hopes the Vikings won't steal the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're a pretty good defensive team, but they (the
Vikings) will test you,'' Vermeil said. ``They're going to score.
You just can't make a mistake and give them anything. If you can
prevent the one big-play type of thing, then you've got a shot at
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at Minnesota as being the best offensive team we
were going to play, or had the possibility to play, in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   So as much as these offenses have been getting attention, it's
the defenses that will likely make the difference between winning
and losing.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were the top-ranked pass offense in the league. The
Vikings ranked 30th in pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can score as many points as we scored last year,''
Vikings coach Dennis Green said. ``They have big-play receivers all
over the field. Marshall Faulk was very close to being the MVP. He
can make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' defense has been overshadowed this season by their
offense, but it's not afraid of the Vikings' powerful mix of the
run and pass. The Rams' defense ranked sixth overall and was the
NFL's best against the run. It didn't fare as well against the pass
_ 20th _ but that was in large part because of the enormous leads
that forced opponents to throw much of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams tied for the league lead in sacks with 57, thanks
mostly to defensive end Kevin Carter, the league's individual
leader with 17. The Rams also led the NFC with 29 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're No. 1 in points allowed, No. 1 in rush
defense (75.9 yards per game),'' St. Louis defensive coordinator
John Bunting said. ``I thought we'd be very good on defense this
year. I had no idea we'd be this good on offense. But I knew we'd
be good on defense. Now, we're going to get a chance to prove that
to everybody in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The way to do that is simple. Shut down the Vikings, and it will
be tough for even the most hardened cynics to continue doubting the
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be playing against Minnesota, it's a great thing,'' St.
Louis rookie cornerback Dre' Bly said. ``That was all the talk in
preseason: Randy Moss, Cris Carter and their offense _ their
explosive offense. I'm going to have my track shoes on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
