<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLU-DRUG-DEATHS-640&AMP;A     01-12 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-DRUG-DEATHS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA WARNS OF OVERUSE OF NEW DRUGS AGAINST FLU 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a widespread outbreak of influenza swamps
hospitals and doctors' offices around the nation, officials at the
Food and Drug Administration Wednesday warned that doctors appear
to be relying too heavily on two new influenza drugs, and said that
some patients may have died because they did not get the more
aggressive treatment they needed.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs, Relenza by Glaxo Wellcome and Tamiflu by
Hoffman-LaRoche, were both approved by the government in the last
six months and are being heavily marketed in television and print
advertisements. Both are intended for patients with uncomplicated
cases of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   But FDA officials said Wednesday that they had evidence that
doctors were prescribing these new antiviral drugs to patients with
complicated cases. Two flu patients whose conditions were
complicated by serious bacterial infections were prescribed Relenza
when they should have received antibiotics; both died, said Dr.
Heidi Jolson, director of the FDA's division of antiviral drug
products.
</P>
<P>
   Three other very sick flu patients taking Relenza also died;
some might have needed more intensive therapy, such as oxygen,
intravenous fluids and hospitalization, Jolson said. In addition, a
flu patient with a serious bacterial infection was prescribed
Tamiflu instead of an antibiotic; that patient recovered, Jolson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths among flu patients are not uncommon; an estimated 20,000
Americans, many of them elderly and infirm, die of the flu every
year. But Jolson said that, with intense media attention focusing
on two heavily advertised drugs during a flu season that is
particularly severe, the agency felt compelled to issue guidance to
doctors about how best to use the new drugs, as well as two older
drugs, amantadine and rimantadine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newer products are being very heavily promoted by the
pharmaceutical companies,'' Jolson said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the deaths, she said: ``These cases suggest that
these products are being in used in patients who are at higher risk
of adverse outcomes. We want to make certain that physicians
understand that there is no evidence that these products work in
those patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have written 300,000 prescriptions for Relenza, an
inhaled medication, according to Lisa Behrens, a spokeswoman for
Glaxo Wellcome. Precise figures for Tamiflu, which comes in pill
form, were not available, but the prescriptions number in the
hundreds of thousands, said Charles Alfaro, a spokesman for Hoffman
LaRoche.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behrens and Alfaro defended their companies' marketing
campaigns, saying the advertisements are intended to educate
consumers about the potential seriousness of influenza and how to
distinguish between the flu and a common cold. ``While we are being
aggressive, we are being responsible,'' Alfaro said.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, about 30 million Americans suffer from the flu,
which causes fever, aches and pains, and absences from work and
school. Officials at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta have said that the flu season arrived this year much
earlier than usual and has increased death rates from pneumonia and
other flu-related illnesses. Emergency rooms are crowded and
hospitals have been postponing elective surgery as a result of the
flood of flu cases.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the media attention to Relenza and Tamiflu, neither drug
is a miracle worker. They cut flu symptoms by a little more than a
day, reducing the duration of the disease to a little less than six
days from seven. As a result, a panel of outside experts was less
than enthusiastic when it considered an application for approval of
Relenza, the first of the two drugs to receive the FDA's approval.
The panel recommended that the FDA reject the drug, by a 13-4 vote,
but the agency took the rare step of ignoring its expert advice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition, Relenza may pose a risk for patients with severe
asthma and other breathing disorders, such as chronic obstructive
pulmonary disease. Clinical studies found that such patients may
experience a ``bronchospasm,'' a shutting down of the airways,
after taking the drug. As a result, Relenza's warning label
instructs doctors to use special caution when prescribing Relenza
for these patients. The FDA reiterated that warning Wednesday,
saying it had received ``reports of respiratory problems following
inhalation of Relenza.''
</P>
<P>
   In its advisory to doctors Wednesday, the agency said
vaccination remains the only way to prevent influenza. Although the
vaccine takes up to 14 days to produce antibodies that will protect
a patient against the flu, experts say that, even with the flu
season in full swing, it is not too late to get a flu shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
