<HEADER>
A4468 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COWBOYS-     01-12 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
 JOB OF HEAD COACH JUST A TRIVIALITY IN
JONES' EYES (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By RANDY
GALLOWAY c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ On second thought, we got it all wrong.
``We'' being the local media. ``We'' being the Cowboys' fandom who
applauded as Chan Gailey was canned.
</P>
<P>
   The story line from Valley Ranch seemed simple enough:
</P>
<P>
   Head coach fired.
</P>
<P>
   Give it a couple of weeks and the next story line will be:
</P>
<P>
   Head coach hired.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking of being canned, we can do just that with both
those story lines.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gailey ouster, what we actually had was an offensive
coordinator being fired. In the search for a new man, Jerry Jones
is seeking, yes, another offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The position of head coach at Valley Ranch has been declared not
just trivial, but also janitorial in importance. Mr. Jones does not
believe in the concept.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry first told us that six seasons ago with his famous
statement of ``there are 500 coaches who could ...''
</P>
<P>
   That was Jones' way of saying the just-departed Jimmy Johnson
meant nothing to the success of the Cowboys. And then Jerry put
mustard on his hot dog by bringing in a guy from off the couch in
Norman and making him what? Head coach/gopher.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, why was Gailey the choice of Jerry? Because in
the interview process, Jones took a crash course in Gailey's
offensive expertise, and then declared Chan the answer to what
ailed the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be wrong. But the pattern of how Gailey was
hired won't change anything. Jones is again searching for Mr. Right
at offensive coordinator, and to get him, he might find it
necessary to also throw a bone labeled ``head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry's logic goes something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``With me in charge, we don't need a head coach. Just somebody
to make Troy happy and call the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   I paraphrase with that, but it's the truth, and Jerry knows it's
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   One little tidbit leaking out after the Gailey dismissal this
week was how angry Chan had been at times over veteran players
being allowed an open-door policy to Jones' office. In particular,
the so-called superstars were always welcome to go over the top on
the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Again, that's just the way it is, and always will be at Valley
Ranch. Plus, this goes right back to the point of Jones having no
respect for the title of head coach.
</P>
<P>
   What Gailey failed to understand was how he ranked in Jerry's
pecking order. He was offensive coordinator, with the ``title'' of
head coach. Those players were going over the head of an offensive
coordinator in taking their gripes to Big Boss Man.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, it has been reported often, was one of the lowest-paid
head coaches in the NFL, if not the lowest. But at the same time,
he was the highest-paid offensive coordinator. Money, of course,
speaks loudly with Jones. Gailey's salary structure comes in louder
and clearer on what Jones considered important.
</P>
<P>
   But if Jerry is successful in finding his desired exacta of
offensive coordinator/head coach, the next victim should ask a lot
of questions about which players can pull rank, and why?
</P>
<P>
   Take Troy Aikman, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm Aikman, I'd have been holding my own media conference
yesterday, the day after Jones held his on the firing of Gailey.
There is some explaining that needs to be done after the way Jones
verbally lateraled a hot rivet right to Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Jones took about five minutes at one point to finally say the
neck of Gailey had been offered up by offensive players unhappy not
with Chan the man, but Chan the offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry never mentioned the name of Aikman, but he darn sure
didn't mean Flozell Adams.
</P>
<P>
   By attempting to distance himself from the move, Jones put the
smoking gun in Aikman's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Personal opinion _ it made Aikman look cheap and cheesy, kind of
like the Linda Tripp of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   For image purposes alone, it would seem Aikman would want to
address what had been said by Jones. But he didn't, at least not
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong _ in fact, it should be a given _ with
the offensive coordinator needing to be on the same page,
system-wise, with Aikman's abilities. (Despite hearing a thousand
different explanations, I still haven't figured out why Gailey's
wasn't).
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, there should also be the normal separation of
power. The head coach comes first, and then the offensive
coordinator, even if those positions are held by the same guy.
</P>
<P>
   But at Valley Ranch such a thing is impossible. Jerry is the one
and only power. Head coach means nothing, and the new one will be a
fool if he believes otherwise. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
