<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GAILEY-TEXFIREDGA     01-12 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GAILEY-TEX </SLUG>
 FIRED GAILEY PACKED AND GONE (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) By RAY BUCK c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Chan Gailey walked away from Valley Ranch
yesterday just as he had arrived 23 months earlier to the day.
</P>
<P>
   Through the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was fired Tuesday as coach of the Cowboys after getting
to fulfill only two-fifths of a five-year, $3.5-million contract.
He spent yesterday morning cleaning out his office, packing up his
belongings and moving himself.
</P>
<P>
   He received numerous phone calls of support from well-wishers
and friends inside the NFL coaching fraternity, including Atlanta's
Dan Reeves, Pittsburgh's Bill Cowher and Denver's Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday, though, Gailey had not yet received any phone
calls regarding interviews from teams that might be interested in
him for a coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, who spent 10 seasons as an NFL assistant in Denver and
Pittsburgh before receiving his first NFL head-coaching job two
years ago, has indicated that he is flexible in listening to
offers, i.e., college or pro, head coach or offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   It has been speculated that Reeves might try to find room on his
staff for Gailey. Both are from Americus, Ga., where the older
Reeves was Gailey's Little League coach. Reeves presently has an
offensive coordinator (George Sefcik) as well as a ``passing
game//playing calling'' coach (Jack Burns).
</P>
<P>
   Fired for the first time in his life, Gailey received some help
from a team employee in loading boxes into Gailey's red sports
utility vehicle. Now with Gailey gone, the focus now shifts to
Jerry Jones finding a successor.
</P>
<P>
   Whom will that be?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Cowboys owner does face a competitive market with no
fewer than four other NFL teams currently looking for head coaches:
New England, Green Bay, New Orleans and the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bill Parcells did meet for two hours yesterday with the
Jets' new billionaire owner, Robert Wood Johnson IV, and the
possibility exists that Parcells (now chief of football operations)
will un-resign and return to coach the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, Texas coach Mack Brown took himself out of any
possible Cowboys head-coaching search by issuing a brief statement
in Austin that he is staying put, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered anytime my name is brought up for an opening,''
Brown said. ``But we're in the midst of a great recruiting year
here. My goal is to win the national championship. And at Texas,
it's not a matter of if, it's a matter of when.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas coach Houston Nutt also nixed speculation made in
several Fort Worth-Dallas media outlets that he is a candidate to
succeed Gailey. Yesterday, Nutt received a raise to $950,000 for
the 2000 season (purely coincidental, according to Arkansas
athletic director Frank Broyles) and maintained that he was not
``officially contacted'' by the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   University of Miami football coach Butch Davis, who spent six
seasons coaching with the Cowboys, including two as the team's
defensive coordinator, said yesterday that he's not interested in
coaching in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am flattered every time my name is mentioned as a candidate
for another head-coaching job,'' Davis said. ``However, I have no
interest in any other head-coaching position.''
</P>
<P>
   The hottest name in the NFL head-coaching derby remains St.
Louis Rams offensive coordinator Mike Martz.
</P>
<P>
   New England already has formally requested the opportunity to
interview Martz as soon as the Rams' season is over. The Rams play
host to Minnesota in an NFC divisional-round game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay also has expressed an interest in Martz, but the
Packers, unlike the Patriots, have not bothered to put in a formal
request. It's a moot point since NFL rules don't allow coaches
under contract to be contacted by other teams until their season is
finished.
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain whether Jones plans to submit a formal request.
He was in New York yesterday on NFL business and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Martz, 48, is both smart (summa cum laude graduate of Fresno
State) and tough, described by one observer close to the team as
having both ``good people's skills'' and ``an edge to him.'' Last
summer, Martz yanked rookie quarterback Joe Germaine out of a
``preseason'' game for taking a sack rather than throwing the ball
away.
</P>
<P>
   What would appeal to Jones also is that Martz is a disciple of
Norv Turner and the Washington Redskins' offense. It's an offense
to which Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman is accustomed and what
seemed to give him a greater amount of faith than did Gailey's
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, 47, has gone on record this week saying that he plans to
stay in Washington. The Redskins are in the second round of the
playoffs. Owner Daniel Snyder has openly endorsed bringing Turner
back in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams likewise want to keep Martz. Team president John Shaw
has all but assured his valued offensive coordinator that he is the
heir apparent to Dick Vermeil, who wants to fulfill his contract
through 2001. Vermeil will be 65 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   While Gailey had been a head coach at both the pro (World League
Birmingham Fire) and college (Troy State and Samford) levels before
coming to the Cowboys, Martz has never been a head coach at any
level.
</P>
<P>
   Martz has worked with two Aikman favorites: Ernie Zampese with
the Los Angeles Rams (1992-93) and Turner with the Redskins
(1997-98).
</P>
<P>
   Jones, meanwhile, has a deep admiration (and has stayed in
contact) with former Chicago Bears head coach and Cowboys defensive
coordinator Dave Wannstedt, who is assistant head coach and heir
apparent to Jimmy Johnson with the Miami Dolphins. Johnson tried to
retire a year ago. When the Dolphins (at Jacksonville Saturday) are
finished with the postseason, Johnson could retire again, this time
for good.
</P>
<P>
   Jones will be looking for somebody who can bring in an offensive
philosophy to fit his core of veteran offensive players. If Jones
did settle on Wannstedt or another defensive coach, he would need
to turn to an offensive coordinator along the lines of Zampese, who
helped the Cowboys win a Super Bowl in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Zampese, 63, has one year left on his contract in New England.
There is strong speculation that Pete Carroll's successor will
immediately fire Zampese, who is being blamed for turning Drew
Bledsoe over the second half of the season (2-6) into a
six-touchdown, 17-interception quarterback ... who was sacked 36
times over the last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, there is one short list that counts.
</P>
<P>
   And that's inside Jerry Jones' head.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
