<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
 RANGERS BRING BACK OLIVER (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The transformation of the Rangers from an
offensive ballclub to one that relies heavily on pitching might be
complete.
</P>
<P>
   The latest step in the makeover was taken yesterday when general
manager Doug Melvin, pushed hard by owner Tom Hicks, signed
free-agent pitcher Darren Oliver to a three-year, $19 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed Oliver is expected to join left-handers Kenny
Rogers and Justin Thompson and right-handers Rick Helling and
Esteban Loaiza in the rotation, with right-handers Matt Perisho and
Mark Clark in reserve. Throw in top prospects Doug Davis, Ryan
Glynn and Corey Lee at Triple-A Oklahoma, and the Rangers have
significantly increased their starting pitching depth.
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on Thompson recovering from shoulder surgery, but
combine a deep rotation with a bullpen headed by All-Stars John
Wetteland and Jeff Zimmerman, and the Rangers might have their best
pitching staff ever.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since the Rangers entered spring
training feeling better about their pitching than they did about
their offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we're queasy about our pitching,'' Melvin said. ``But
if you put the bullpen next to the starters, this is the best since
I've been here. It's a good mix. The look is much better, and the
depth is much better. Now it's up to them to show it's our best
pitching staff ever.''
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, Oliver probably needs to take his game to a
higher level. The Rangers thought he was close to doing that when
he went 14-6 with a 4.66 ERA in 1996, helping them win a division
title.
</P>
<P>
   But he was 13-12 with a 4.20 ERA in 1997 and 6-7 with a 6.53 ERA
in 19 starts in 1998 before being traded to St. Louis. Oliver was
13-13 with a 4.26 ERA in 40 starts for the Cardinals, but they
thought enough of him to offer a four-year, $24 million contract
after last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can go out there every fifth day and keep building up my
innings, with the bullpen they have here, there's no reason why I
can't be a 15-game winner,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin suggested the Rangers were ``done'' when they signed
Rogers, another former Texas pitcher, to a three-year deal Dec. 29.
</P>
<P>
   But Hicks wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin admitted the owner ``challenged me'' to get something
done with Oliver. Negotiations with agent Scott Boras heated up
Monday and an agreement was reached yesterday after Oliver passed a
physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were open to getting both Kenny Rogers and Aaron Sele,''
Hicks said. ``We were open to getting Darren Oliver. The way Sele's
agent handled things was unfortunate, but Kenny Rogers was our No.
1 priority; we had to have a proven, experienced left-hander.
Getting Darren Oliver is a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's chances of re-signing with the Cardinals were
eliminated when they traded for Pat Hentgen and Darryl Kile. He
admitted he started getting nervous as the off-season proceeded
without him signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was kind of like a surprise for me,'' said Oliver, who
lives in Arlington with his wife, Melissa. ``I wasn't sure it would
happen. For some reason the market was frozen up; everything was
slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's contract calls for a base salary of $3 million in 2000
and $5 million in 2001 and 2002. He also gets a $6 million deferred
signing bonus, paid in installments starting in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have arbitration cases pending with Loaiza and
designated hitter Lee Stevens, but Hicks said the club will likely
have a payroll of around $67 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's $8 million to 9 million less than last year, but Hicks
said reducing the payroll wasn't the Rangers' most important issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three goals: develop a winning attitude, get younger
and more aggressive, and improve our pitching,'' Hicks said. ``I
think we've done that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
