<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-AFRICA-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA'S NEXT JOB: COOLING THE SITUATION IN BURUNDI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Nelson Mandela, the former South African
president, will step into a new role here next week when the
Security Council plans an open debate on how to deal with a rapidly
worsening political and economic situation in Burundi and the
threat of renewed ethnic warfare in an already devastated part of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Mandela, more than half a dozen African leaders have
been invited to New York for meetings on Burundi and later on Congo
by Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. representative and this month's
Security Council president.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the largest gathering of African presidents ever to
meet with the council, diplomats say. The list of those planning to
come over the next two weeks includes Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe,
Frederick Chiluba of Zambia, Yoweri Museveni of Uganda, Pasteur
Bizimungu of Rwanda, Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique and Sir
Ketumile Masire, a former president of Botswana who has been named
a mediator in the Congo civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke expressed optimism Wednesday that President Laurent
Kabila of Congo would also attend.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi's government, concerned that it will be under attack in
the council, will send a team of high-level ministers, although who
they will be was in some doubt after a cabinet shake-up on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela will address the council as the new international
mediator for Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi is mired in civil war and economic collapse and is under
pressure by relief and rights organizations, backed by some
diplomats, to make immediate changes in government policies before
any assistance can be extended.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the debate is Burundi's policy of
``regroupment.'' The Tutsi-led government of President Pierre
Buyoya has forcibly resettled about 300,000 mostly ethnic Hutus in
dozens of spartan camps. The purpose is to contain what the
government says is a rebel movement backed by the genocidal
Interahamwe militia, which was responsible for much of the killing
of Tutsi and moderate Hutu in neighboring Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Interahamwe and some exiled soldiers from the former Hutu
Rwandan army, chased out of Rwanda by a Tutsi force after the
genocide, have been returning to Rwanda and crossing into Burundi,
said Marc Nteturuye, Burundi's representative at the United
Nations. He said that Burundi's crisis can be dealt with only as
part of a larger regional problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Interahamwe is colluding with Burundi rebels and fighting
on Burundi soil,'' he said. ``Peace in Burundi depends also on
peace in the Congo. Burundi is mixed into that conflict.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nteturuye said that the aim of his government's policy is to
protect civilians, but the emptying of villages also deprives
rebels of support bases and hiding places.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. relief officials say they have been torn between a
conviction that the Burundian policy violates international law
governing the movement of populations and their own commitment to
meeting the needs of the civilians in the camps, where hunger and
disease are common. Complicating relief agency decisions was the
murder last year of two aid officials at one of the camps and the
government's failure to solve the case.
</P>
<P>
   Nteturuye said in an interview that the government had
identified the killers, who since fled across the border into
Tanzania and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the camps, people don't have everything they need, but they
are happy to be protected,'' he said. He added that if rebels were
allowed to continue to roam in and around the capital, there was
certain to be a backlash from other, presumably Tutsi, armed gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are extremists on both sides,'' he said. ``We have to
weaken them and strengthen the middle ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
