<HEADLINE>
DPS CHAIRMAN WARNS TOP OFFICIALS TO ROOT OUT RACISM, SEXISM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Department of Public Safety top officials were
ordered Wednesday to root out any vestiges of racism and sexism in
the agency and warned that there would be ``zero tolerance'' of
prejudicial activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not welcome in DPS if you are going to conduct your
business in a racist or sexist way,'' said James Francis of Dallas,
chairman of the three-member Public Safety Commission that oversees
DPS activities.
</P>
<P>
   His comments _ the strongest to date since reports surfaced
about birthday parties given for two black troopers more than a
decade ago by uniformed white troopers wearing Ku Klux Klan-type
hoods _ came during a Public Safety Commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to take every step you can possibly think of to
ensure that this never happens again in this agency,'' he added in
a stern warning to the agency's top leadership. ``I want you all to
enforce that in a relentless way. I mean zero tolerance, and it's
up to you all to root it out, not just turn your heads the other
way. I am serious. It cannot stand, people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday marked the first time the commission has met since
news of the parties, held on two different occasions in the
Livingston, Texas, office, surfaced last week.
</P>
<P>
   Francis earlier this week was reappointed by Gov. George W. Bush
to another six-year term on the commission; its other members are
M. Colleen McHugh of Corpus Christi and Robert Holt of Midland.
Francis also is chairman of a high-level fund-raising organization
for Bush's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, DPS suspended with pay four East Texas
troopers who participated in the most recent party and two others
allegedly involved in making racist comments in more recent
incidents. DPS is continuing its investigation of the incidents.
Final disciplinary action is pending completion of a DPS internal
affairs investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the activities became public Jan. 5, when former
Livingston state trooper Darron Anderson, 35, released pictures
taken at his party in 1988 or 1989. He made the snapshots public
the day before he was in court on an arson charge. He is accused of
setting fire to his truck last April in a botched scheme to collect
insurance; he was fired from DPS after the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has said he was traumatized by the KKK party but waited
years to come forward because as a rookie he feared for his job.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, one of Anderson's former supervisors has said that
Anderson himself requested the party after seeing photographs of a
similar affair thrown for another black trooper four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want, in any way, to leave any doubt in anybody's
mind: This commission will not tolerate any acts _ overt, covert,
serious, funny, whatever _ of racism or sexism in this
organization,'' Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Francis said that even if the parties were
thrown in jest, DPS employees should have known such behavior is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agency will not tolerate a jocular association with the
KKK. Period,'' he said. ``I'm not saying it was jocular, but given
some people are saying it was jocular, that's still not acceptable
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DPS not only needs to complete its investigation of these
activities but also ``look at the bigger picture of diversity
training, race relations, cultural sensitivity and we need to do a
better job. Obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long before the Jasper case, in which a black man was dragged to
death behind a pickup driven by three white men two years ago, East
Texas has had a history of racial problems and suspected Klan
activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things I asked our people to look into today
on a kind of a broader basis,'' Francis said. ``Is this an `old
trooper' problem? Are we dealing with old men who just don't get it
in the '90s?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
