<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MERRILL-APPOINT-ART-N     01-12 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-APPOINT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOICE OF GLOBAL STRATEGIST IS AFFIRMED BY MERRILL LYNCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT21 was sent Jan. 12 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. made it official Wednesday,
naming David Bowers to assume some of the responsibilities of its
longtime chief investment strategist, Charles Clough, who is
retiring this week.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Merrill announced plans to get out of some areas of
the commodities business, including the trading of futures
contracts on agricultural products and metals. The firm said it
would continue trading futures on oil and other energy products.
</P>
<P>
   Before the holidays, Merrill chose Bowers, who has been the
firm's European stock strategist in London, to be its global
strategist in New York. But it postponed announcing the appointment
as it sorted out who would fill which jobs on its strategy team.
Not all the seats have been filled.
</P>
<P>
   Clough's job is being split in two to create positions for a
global strategist and a United States strategist, a setup that
exists at some other big securities firms. At Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co., for example, Barton Biggs is the global strategist
and Byron Wien handles domestic strategy. On occasion, the two have
publicly disagreed on how much money investors should put into the
American stock and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers said Merrill was recruiting somebody to be the firm's
domestic strategist, the primary voice its 14,000 American brokers
will hear on the outlook for the market and particular sectors and
stocks. That search should be completed within three months, a
Merrill spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to have somebody on the team who really does
understand the American market and the mindset of American
investors,'' Bowers said. Although, he added, ``Europe in the last
three months has seen some pretty wacky valuations as well, so I'm
no stranger to unusual market levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Melnick, co-head of Merrill's investment research
department, said Bowers' focus would be ``broader than a United
States strategist's, to emphasize those particular parts of the
world that are the most attractive for global investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, 40, who is British, said that he and his wife, who is a
doctor in London, and their young son would move to New York in
about three weeks. After that, he said, he will begin publishing
and broadcasting his views on where in the world investors should
be putting their money.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clough, 57, annoyed some Merrill brokers with his
persistent bearishness about American stocks in recent years,
Bowers said he would be tough to follow because he was ``a great
raconteur, a great performer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a start, people will have to get used to a slightly
different accent,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Clough, who has commuted to Merrill's New York headquarters over
the last 14 years, plans to manage money for wealthy families and
nonprofit groups in Boston, where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   As for Merrill's decision to stop trading some commodities,
analysts predicted that it would have only a slight effect on
Merrill's finances. In the last few years, Merrill has derived only
about $200 million, or 1 percent of its annual revenue, from
commodities-trading commissions over all, said Guy Moszkowski, an
analyst with the Salomon Smith Barney unit of Citigroup. The
changes Merrill is making should reduce Merrill's revenue by less
than $100 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
