<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-DEPART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY MOVIE CHIEF LEAVING TO FORM OWN STUDIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Joe Roth, who has been in charge of Walt Disney
Motion Pictures since 1994 and chairman of Walt Disney Studios
since 1996, said Wednesday that he was leaving Disney to form his
own mini-studio, a company that will both make and distribute
movies. He is being replaced by Peter Schneider, his
second-in-command and the longtime head of the lucrative animation
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great time to be out forming a new company,'' Roth
said. ``As someone who has supervised over 250 movies over the last
15 years, I felt I would be happier cobbling together my own
company, which simply made movies, without the infrastructure and
cost and overhead that any big studio carries with it.''
</P>
<P>
   News of Roth's impending departure came as little surprise. He
had told friends and associates over the last year that he was
eager to run his own company again and unsure about remaining in a
corporate environment like Disney. ``Joe's been always saying he
wanted to get out and be his own boss and misses the independent
world,'' said Jerry Bruckheimer, who has produced several Disney
films during Roth's tenure, including the 1998 hit ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   It did, however, come as a big blow to Disney, which has been
struggling to overcome sagging earnings and has suffered other
high-level executive departures. Its shares fell $2.5625 Wednesday,
to $33.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's contract with Disney was extended last summer, but
negotiations on a new contract were delayed, and Roth, 51, said he
was asked by Michael D. Eisner, the chairman of Disney, to take
some time over the holidays and make a final decision about whether
he intended to stay with the studio or leave.
</P>
<P>
   It was while he was in Barbados with his family, Roth said, that
he finally decided that the time to break away from Disney and form
his own company was too ripe to resist, given the new and growing
opportunities offered by the Internet to market and, eventually,
distribute entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start thinking of this because of the AOL-Time
merger,'' Roth said, referring to Monday's deal between America
Online and Time Warner, ``but I did feel that there had to be a
coming convergence of new and old media.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked for three men in my life: Rupert Murdoch, Barry
Diller and Michael Eisner,'' he added. ``Kind of long shadows
there. It just seemed like a good time to go back out on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner and Roth discounted reports that Roth had been unhappy at
Disney or that he had chafed under Eisner's corporate rule. ``He
and I got along terrifically,'' Eisner said. ``It's just that the
entrepreneurial spirit is in the air. Joe is a guy who is an
adventurer. If he wants to do this, I'm behind him. The people who
do the jobs inside a corporation have to be really committed to it,
because they are really hard jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   During the six years that Roth played a role in building
Disney's slate of movies, the studio has been in first place at the
box office for five years and in second place for the remaining
year. In 1999, for instance, Disney was in first place on the
strength of successes like ``Toy Story 2,'' ``Tarzan'' and ``The
Sixth Sense.'' Some other Disney live-action efforts, though, like
``The Insider'' and ``Bicentennial Man,'' did not perform well at
the box office, although ``The Insider'' was a critical success and
is considered an Oscar contender.
</P>
<P>
   News of Roth's departure was to be made public next week, but
the announcement was moved forward when word began to leak out of
the studio _ particularly after a Los Angeles Times article
appeared Wednesday morning, quoting unnamed sources.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, 49, the longtime head of Disney's animation division,
was promoted a year ago to president of the studio. He was given
supervisory control of all films released under the Walt Disney
label (some of the studio's films are released under the Touchstone
and Hollywood Films banners). Schneider was also in charge of
Disney's theatrical efforts, including the Tony-winning Broadway
musical ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schneider was out of the country when the announcement was made
and unavailable for comment, studio spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner said that the change from Roth to Schneider did not
indicate that there would be a major strategic shift at the studio
_ for instance, that Disney would be making more Disney-banner,
family-oriented films and fewer adult-oriented, live-action
features _ although he expects that the new chairman's creative
sensibility will inevitably be felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of Disney films now and we will continue to do
more,'' Eisner said. But the studio will continue to release
significant live-action features, and films by Miramax, a wholly
owned subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said that he intended to begin looking for new office space
and talking to partners who might want to be part of his new
effort, adding that he had no partners lined up as yet. Some of the
creative people he worked with over the years _ he is known to have
extremely close relationships with actors like Bruce Willis and
Julia Roberts, as well as with producers like Bruckheimer _ will
probably announce in coming weeks that they will work with him
again, Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   His dream, he said, is to build a company that makes movies and
uses the new digital world in a creative way, to market and
distribute the films. In particular, he hopes to distribute his new
company's films himself, at least domestically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a place for a company that distributes film
and pictures, the way Miramax does, and that has strategic partners
who get to use these films in their own delivery,'' he said. ``I
got kind of caught up in the whole `Blair Witch' thing, when it
happened, on how you could use the Internet as a marketing tool,''
he said, referring to the movie that became a big hit last summer
largely on the strength of its online marketing campaign. ``If I
can do it, I would love to have a company that distributes itself,
at least in the U.S. market.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that the new company _ no name has been chosen yet _
will have a film in release by the summer of 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
