<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON FOOTBALL: JETS' NEW OWNER WANTS PARCELLS, AND WITH GOOD REASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What several National Football League owners said this week that
they most liked about Robert Wood Johnson IV, the man who just
spent $635 million to purchase the New York Jets, was his dogged,
almost religious conviction to acquire the team. When Johnson sets
his sights on something, it usually becomes his. And right now,
Johnson has targeted arguably one of the best coaches in sports
these days, Bill Parcells, and is willing to pay the former Jets
guru whatever it reasonably takes to pull him out of coaching
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   According to several NFL owners familiar with Johnson's
thinking, the new Jets owner is prepared to give Parcells a
financial package that would make it difficult for him to refuse
returning as coach and general manager for one more season. The
package might include the doubling of Parcells' salary, which could
make Parcells the first $5 million-a-year coach in football. He
would surpass Seattle coach Mike Holmgren, who is also the team's
general manager, as the NFL's highest-paid coach. Holmgren is
reportedly earning $4 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility for Johnson, though more unlikely, is that
Johnson would give Parcells a small piece of the Jets to come back
as head coach. Such a transfer, however, would first require the
approval of 24 of the league's 31 owners.
</P>
<P>
   There is even the chance that Johnson would pay Parcells
handsomely simply to have a daily involvement in the running of the
team for at least one year. In other words, Parcells would pick the
coach, then remain on as less of an adviser and more of a general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake about it: Johnson's first choice is to have
Parcells coach the team.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL owners said that Parcells and Johnson already had at
least one telephone conversation after Johnson had been approved as
owner Tuesday. Wednesday, , Parcells, team president Steve Gutman
and Johnson met at the Jets' complex in Hempstead, N.Y., for two
hours. Parcells and Johnson are likely to meet again, sans Gutman,
at least several times in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   So Johnson has found his man. It's Parcells, and knowing the way
Parcells loves money more than the average bear, it is hard to
imagine Parcells not accepting any significant offer from Johnson.
Not to mention that Parcells always does what is best for Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of teams are going up.
</P>
<P>
   The price of coaching is going up.
</P>
<P>
   The price of Tuna may be way above market price.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Parcells back out of retirement is the smartest thing
Johnson could do in a lot of ways. With all due respect to Al Groh,
or Bill Belichick, or almost anyone else, no one is better suited
to lead the Jets than Parcells. He dragged the team to an 8-8
record after a bleak start with nothing but his will after losing
quarterback Vinny Testaverde to a season-ending injury and
developing the backup thrower Ray Lucas into a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Parcells himself caused some of the turmoil the Jets
have endured. By not knowing that Belichick would leave the team,
he failed dramatically as a general manager. By not acquiring even
a decent backup quarterback, believing that Rick Mirer could do the
job when the rest of the league knew he was a bust, he failed
dramatically as a talent evaluator.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells is such a brilliant, strong and in some ways
maniacal personality, as well as a smart tactician once the games
begin, no one else in the NFL can repair the recent damage to the
Jets and then go on to lead the team to a championship. If Parcells
does not come back, the Jets will be a playoff team. If Parcells
does return, they are one of four American Conference teams in
Indianapolis, Jacksonville and Denver that could get to the Super
Bowl. For the Jets, Parcells on the sideline is like going into a
game already ahead by a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's prying Parcells off the golf course also helps
Johnson. If he is successful in bringing him back, Johnson will
look like a hero. Thus, Jets fans will fall in love with the
billionaire, and as good a person as Johnson may be, even he is
likely to be no stranger to vanity.
</P>
<P>
   When the NFL finance committee approved Johnson over Charles
Dolan, the chairman of Cablevision, they knew that Johnson would be
an easier man for the league's other owners to tolerate. While it
has been portrayed in the news media that Dolan had recently
surpassed Johnson in the bid for the Jets, that wasn't the case.
Most owners and members of the finance committee have always wanted
Johnson over Dolan, fretting over Dolan's intermingled interests
between his businesses and other sports franchises. For Dolan to
win, he would have needed to beat Johnson's bid significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the money had anything to do with it,'' Dolan
said. ``They had their concerns. Whatever I did wouldn't have
mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the NFL is concerned, Johnson was the better choice
anyway. He works quietly and won't let his ego get in the way.
There are already indications that he will do whatever it takes to
make the Jets better.
</P>
<P>
   And by getting Parcells, the Jets can instantly become better,
as in Super Bowl better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
