<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE CITES AN ADDICTION TO THE INTERNET IN THREAT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Texas)   (af)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A federal jury will be asked to consider whether a
Florida teen-ager who threatened to ``finish what begun'' at
Columbine High School did so because of an addiction to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old youth, Michael Ian Campbell, a high school
graduate and aspiring actor, has admitted he sent the message
through an online chat room in December to Erin Walton, who was a
Columbine sophomore when two students shot and killed 13 people and
themselves last April. Miss Walton notified Columbine officials of
the threat, and as a precaution the school was closed two days
early for the Christmas holiday break.
</P>
<P>
   Now Campell, indicted by a federal grand jury here on Monday,
faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine if convicted
of making a threat across state lines. But he has pleaded not
guilty, mounting a defense based on an untested legal theory of
Internet addiction stemming from his immersion in the virtual
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we can make this courtroom a classroom where we're
going to learn about the Internet, about the virtual, or
make-believe, world,'' his lawyer, Ellis Rubin, told reporters
outside the federal courthouse here on Tuesday, maintaining that
Campbell had made a virtual threat, not one made with a ``criminal
state of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin did not describe how much time his client had typically
spent online, and did not return a telephone call Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, free on $100,000 bail, apologized for the message,
calling it ``a stupid mistake'' and saying: ``I am horrified at
what I have done and its consequences. I did not really understand
what you in Colorado had gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, based in Miami, has achieved a certain reputation for
mounting similar unusual defenses, although few of his most
creative efforts have ever succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, he argued that a teen-ager charged with the murder of a
next-door neighbor, an 82-year-old woman, had been driven by
``television intoxication''; that defendant was convicted. And in
1991, he defended a woman charged with prostitution by arguing that
she had become a nymphomaniac because of her use of the
antidepressant drug Prozac; she eventually pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Other criminal lawyers expressed skepticism over Rubin's tactic
in the Campbell case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't pass the laugh test,'' said Victoria Toensing, a
prominent Washington lawyer. ``In a state court, he might be able
to find a situation where a judge would go off the reservation, but
it's not going to happen in a federal court. It sounds to me like
an attorney trying to get some publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Robinson, a defense lawyer here in Denver, said an
addiction defense would not serve the client nearly so well as
maintaining that he had simply been ``just talking, attempting to
impress a young woman in a chat room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a watershed legal theory,'' Robinson added, ``Internet
addiction ranks right up there with bloodletting as an established
medical cure.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Harvard law professor Alan Dershowitz said: ``This is
just another abuse excuse that will not and should not work. The
vast majority of people who are addicted to the Internet don't
issue violent threats. There is no logical connection between
addiction to the Internet, even if such a phenomenon existed, and
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ms. Toensing and Robinson compared Rubin's tactic to the
``Twinkie defense'' used by Dan White, the former San Francisco
city supervisor convicted in the fatal shooting of Mayor George
Moscone and Supervisor Harvey Milk in 1978. His lawyer argued that
White suffered from ``diminished capacity'' at the time of the
killings, in part because of an addiction to junk food with lots of
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, whose trial is scheduled to begin on Feb. 28, is not
the only teen-ager facing charges of making threats related to
Columbine. On Monday, a federal indictment was also returned
against a Houston man, Arthur Leon Thomas. It accuses him of
sending threatening letters and electronic messages to the
Jefferson County sheriff, John Stone, the lead investigator in the
Columbine shootings; to the school, and to a woman in Broomfield,
Colo., near Denver, whom the authorities did not identify.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
