<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JAGUARS-JITTERS-N     01-12 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-JITTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LIMPING JAGUARS, SPIRIT IS WILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Leon Searcy pulled a knee sock onto his
left leg Wednesday, effectively concealing the long white ribbon of
tape that is holding his ankle in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've felt all season,'' Searcy, the Jaguars'
offensive right tackle, said. ``When you're constantly banging and
pounding on your bones and joints for 17 weeks, it takes its
toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Searcy's signal of good health will be as soothing as a warm
bath to the aching injuries of the Jaguars. And as the Jaguars
prepare to play the Miami Dolphins on Saturday in an American
Football Conference divisional playoff game, they might consider
replacing the franchise logo of a growling jaguar with a photo of
an ice pack.
</P>
<P>
   Searcy's well-being is of particular concern because he will
line up across from the Dolphins' pass-rushing specialist, left end
Trace Armstrong, who had three sacks in the Dolphins' victory over
the Seattle Seahawks last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And that could pose a problem for quarterback Mark Brunnell, who
could be expected to scramble when necessary if he were not going
to be wearing two knee braces for the first time in his career.
That is, only if he starts, which seems likely after he rested the
sprained medial collateral ligament in his left knee for the
regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   Brunnell said Monday that he was ``94.89 percent'' better than
he felt during last year's playoffs, when he had a bad left ankle,
and added that he would start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But in a bit of player diplomacy, Brunnell backed off that
pronouncement Tuesday, saying it was a coach's decision. Brunnell
did not talk to reporters Wednesday, but coach Tom Coughlin said
Brunnell could not start in his present state, that his confidence
needs to improve as much as anything, that he would split snaps
evenly with the backup Jay Fiedler in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin added that the Jaguars would not start Brunnell ``if he
cannot defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending Brunnell became an acute problem when Tony Boselli,
the All-Pro left tackle, was lost for the playoffs after he tore
the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Brunnel is a left-hander, so Boselli, the team's best player,
protected his strong side, where the quarterback is likely to roll
out, if he can move at all. Boselli will be replaced by Ben
Coleman, who struggled as a guard, but has played well at tackle.
The Jaguars are 5-1 when he plays in place of Boselli.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dolphins, particularly Armstrong, sent a ripple of
shock through the Jaguars during Miami's 20-17 victory in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right tackle for Seattle was taking the punishment,''
Searcy said. ``Trace was bullying him. I was sitting there on TV
watching in awe at what he was doing to him. He tore him a new
frame. Everything he wanted to do, he did.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, Searcy, who is assuming that Brunnell will start,
was annoyed with Armstrong, who told The Miami Herald that he does
not think ``everybody has to play their best game to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little insulting to hear,'' Searcy said. ``He can't
bring his B game, because I'm going to have my A game. Trace is a
great pass rusher. You put him in a situation where he's
well-rested, and it comes down to third-down situations, his job is
to create havoc in the backfield. I know I'm going to have a very
vulnerable quarterback in the pocket and I'm going to do my best to
keep him off his heels.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, who led the league in rushing with 130.7 yards a
game and were third in rushing attempts with 516, could always turn
to its superb backfield duo of James Stewart and Fred Taylor. If
they are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart led the AFC in rushing yards with 931, a startling
number considering he started just seven games. He had finally
recovered from a torn ligament in his left knee that he sustained
last season, then he sprained his left foot Dec. 13 and missed the
next two games.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Taylor _ who as a rookie last season took over for
the injured Stewart and rushed for 1,223 yards _ had returned that
week from a strained hamstring that kept him out of six games.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget cornerback Fernando Bryant. He missed last
week's practices with a strained hamstring, although he, like
everyone except Boselli, is expected to play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea that if George Clooney won't return to the cast
of ``ER,'' there is an opportunity in private practice waiting for
him here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact of life in the NFL,'' Coughlin said. ``There are
some teams that manage to go through the season without these kinds
of things. We've had some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   No team is immune from injuries and certainly the Dolphins
suffered a high-profile one to Dan Marino, whose bone spur in his
back put his future in question. But the Jaguars are enduring a
succession of niggling pains at the worst possible time.
</P>
<P>
   They finished the season with the best record in the National
Football League at 14-2 _ albeit without beating a team that ended
the season with a winning record. They led the league in fewest
points allowed (217) with a defense that ranked fourth in yards
allowed and that tied for the league lead in sacks with 57. And
they led the league in rushing. But the questions _ and trainers _
are lingering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boselli going down shook up things a little,'' Searcy said.
``We have to scramble around a little bit. This is a wake-up call
for the offensive line. We have to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   And hope the supply of tape and braces holds out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
