<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERG TO BE BENCHED TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last time Aki Berg was benched, he responded
with some of the best hockey of his young career.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Kings hope pulling their 22-year-old defenseman
from tonight's game against St. Louis at Staples Center will have
the same effect after Berg's poor effort in Tuesday's 4-3 loss to
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were several Kings responsible for blowing a
winnable game, Berg played a part in three of the four Senators
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring came early in the second period when he fanned
on a pass in front of the Kings net and Shawn McEachern converted
the turnover into Ottawa's go-ahead goal. Less than three minutes
later, Berg tipped a long shot by Magnus Avardson that was
redirected over the left shoulder of goaltender Stephane Fiset.
Defensemen are taught to let opponents take shots that have little
chance of going in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to single out Aki for last night's game,'' Kings
coach Andy Murray said. ``But I want to sit him down for a game to
let him think about a few things.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this season, Berg was benched for back-to-back games due
to lackadaisical play. He missed all last year in a contract
dispute and the transition took longer than the coaching staff
expected. But Berg recovered and last month, when captain Rob Blake
was sidelined with a groin injury, he worked well on the power
play.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Berg was not completely to blame on the Senators'
third goal. It came so early in the second period that the ice was
not completely dry and the puck stuck in the playing surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he does have a habit of trying to slap the puck a little
instead of just pushing it and that is a problem,'' Murray said.
``He wants to get a little more on the pass, but he loses control.
That's what happened on that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg's place in the lineup will be taken by veteran defenseman
Garry Galley, who has been sidelined the past 3{ weeks with a
concussion. Murray said he does not know how the defense will shake
out after tonight's game, but the club sent Frantisek Kaberle to
minor-league Long Beach for Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is pleased with the play of Jaroslav Modry, who has two
goals and an assist in his last five games. Modry spent most of the
early season as a healthy scratch.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick whistles: Goaltender Jamie Storr, sidelined since
mid-December with a concussion, is hoping to play back-to-back
games this weekend for Long Beach and be cleared to return to the
Kings on Tuesday night as a backup. ``That will definitely let me
know where I stand,'' Storr said. ``Doing that will let be ready to
play right away in case I'm needed. It will be better than being
the backup and not knowing if I'm ready.'' . . . The Kings got a
scare late in Tuesday's loss when center Bryan Smolinski went down
with a knee injury and had to be helped to the dressing room.
Smolinski suffered an impingement to a nerve, which resulted in a
temporary paralysis. Feeling to the knee returned late Tuesday, and
he is expected to play. . . . Center Ian Laperriere returned to the
lineup after missing two games with a bruised left knee. One of the
team's top faceoff men, he won 15 of 17 against the Senators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
