<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HORNETS-PHILLS-NY     01-12 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HORNETS-PHILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS' BOBBY PHILLS DIES IN CAR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., La., Ohio)   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Phills, the Charlotte Hornets guard who parlayed a 10-day
contract into a nine-year National Basketball Association career
and who was once called by Michael Jordan the toughest defender he
had ever faced, was killed instantly Wednesday when the speeding
Porsche he was driving spun out of control and collided with
another vehicle moments after he left a morning practice. He was 30
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Phills' teammates were on the scene with club officials
immediately after the accident, which occurred less than a mile
from the Charlotte Coliseum. The Hornets' game scheduled for
Wednesday night against the Chicago Bulls was postponed as shock
was felt around the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The three-vehicle crash is under investigation by the
Charlotte-Mecklenburg Police Department, which is looking into
whether Phills and his best friend on the Hornets, starting point
guard David Wesley, the team's , had been racing along a stretch
near the arena. Wesley's car was not involved in the accident, and
he was questioned for a ftes at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Phills lost control of his car on a hilly curve where the posted
speed limit was 45 miles an hour, Capt. L.E. Blydenburgh, the crash
investigator, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skid marks indicate he was not going in a straight line,''
he said. ``A fourth car driven by David Wesley was in close
proximity to the collision at the time it occurred and has been
identified by a witness as driving at a high rate of speed also,''
the report said. Keith Bridges, a spokesman for the
Charlotte-Mecklenburg police, said, ``Charges are to be determined,
but racing is definitely illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is expected to take at least a week. An
autopsy on Phills was to be performed at the medical examiner's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred feet of skid marks, estimated by witnesses to be
about 150 yards, were made by Phills' vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The police report said Phills was traveling eastbound on West
Tyvola Road just before 11 a.m., less than a mile away from the
Charlotte Coliseum. Veering into the coming traffic, his black 1997
Porsche with a vanity license plate that read ``SLAM'N'' absorbed
the impact on the driver's side door. The car was hit by an
Oldsmobile Cutlass Sierra driven by Robert Taylor Woolard Jr., 31.
A minivan taxi driven by Yao Agbegbon hit the rear end of Woolard's
car almost instantaneously. Woolard and Agbegbon were listed in
stable condition at Presbyterian Hospital in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Mills, the father of Phills' former teammate, Chris
Mills, was called soon after the accident by Baron Davis, the
Hornets' rookie point guard. He said Davis told him his vehicle was
positioned behind both Phills and Wesley at a stop light when the
two cars accelerated as the light turned green.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Paul Silas of the Hornets and team members gathered around
the scene of the accident as police used yellow tape to cordon off
the area. Cameras filmed a frozen Wesley standing a few feet from
Phills' car, in obvious shock. Phills' wife, Kendall, and their
son, Bobby Ray Phills III, 3, and daughter, Kerstie, 1, arrived
soon after the accident. He is also survived by his parents.
</P>
<P>
   It took firefighters more than two hours to pry Phills' body
from the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was Bobby a tremendous person, but a great husband,
father and role model that everyone respected and admired,'' said
George Shinn, the Hornets' owner.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Ray Phills II was born on Dec. 20, 1969, in Baton Rouge,
La. The top 3-point shooter in the nation his senior year at
Southern University in Baton Rouge, Phills graduated with a degree
in animal science. Drafted in the second round in 1991 by the
Milwaukee Bucks, he was cut from the team that December, played in
the Continental Basketball Association, then was signed by the
Cleveland Cavaliers to a 10-day contract on March 19, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Standing a chiseled 6 feet 5 inches and 232 pounds, Phills
looked more like a National Football League linebacker or a
sculpted bodybuilder than a lithe NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   He was exceptionally strong, and while coaches and general
managers debated whether he was a shooting guard or a small
forward, Phills merely transformed himself into one of the game's
most menacing defenders. He was named to the NBA all-defensive team
after the 1995-96 season, the same season in which Jordan paid him
the ultimate compliment by calling him the toughest defender he had
ever faced.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fratello, the former Cleveland coach, remembered a young,
unproven Phills returning to the Cavaliers training camp without a
guaranteed contract in the fall of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him we would release him if we wanted, because we
already had 13 or 14 guaranteed deals and his chances of making it
were slim,'' Fratello said. ``I figured we'd give him a shot to
catch on with another team. Bobby came back the next day and said:
`I want to stay here, Coach. I'm just going to keep working.'''
</P>
<P>
   After a slew of injuries hit the Cavaliers, he became a starter
and led the team into the playoffs for the next four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   After six seasons in Cleveland, Phills was signed by the Hornets
on Aug. 19, 1997, as a free agent. Once classified in scouting
reports as a ``tweener'' and a long shot from a small school to
begin with, he signed a seven-year, $33 million contract with
Charlotte in 1997. Fourth on the team in scoring, a captain and a
leader and one of the Hornets' top reserves, he averaged 10.9
points, 3.2 rebounds and 2.7 assists a game for his career.
</P>
<P>
   Phills, active in the community, volunteered for children's
charities and related organizations. In 1998, he was one of four
finalists for the NBA's sportsmanship award. He also started the
Bobby Phills Educational Foundation, holding camps in Baton Rouge
each summer for children who were taught how to balance education
with athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby was a solid person,'' said Wayne Embry, the Cavaliers'
president.
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern called Phills ``one of the most
respected members of the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Sunday, every NBA team will have a moment of silence for
Phills before their home games.
</P>
<P>
   Phills was the fourth active NBA player to be killed in an
accident. The Nets' Drazen Petrovic died in 1993 and Terry Furlow
of the Jazz in 1980, both in car crashes, and the Pistons' Nick
Vanos was killed in a plane crash in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the second serious traffic this season involving
Hornets players. In October, the reserve guard Eldridge Recasner
was left with a broken shoulder and partly collapsed lung after an
accident. His teammate Derrick Coleman, driving the sport utility
vehicle in which Recasner was a passenger, was arrested on a
drunken driving charge. A female passenger was hurt in that
collision with a tractor-trailer. Recasner remains on the injured
list. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
