<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER13-COX     01-12 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker: 'I said a few things that are absolutely not me'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Rocker finally had an opportunity to tell his
side of the story Wednesday. Now he must begin to deal with the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking his three-week silence, Rocker spoke in an interview
with ESPN's Peter Gammons on his controversial comments that
appeared in Sports Illustrated last month. He began trying to undo
some of the damage he did to his image when he launched a vicious
tirade against New York fans.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the public heard from Rocker, it was in a stream
of scathing comments to SI writer Jeff Pearlman calling an unnamed
teammate ``a fat monkey,'' and disparaging minorities from
Hispanics and blacks to gays and Asians, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker issued an apology in a written statement through his
agents Dec. 22, but hadn't spoken publicly since. Baseball fans,
civic leaders, minorities and even his teammates may have cringed
at the thought of what else he might say, but Rocker just hopes
they were listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have been definitely grossly misrepresented,''
Rocker said. ``And that's really the hardest thing, despite the
fact the comments really offended a lot of people. That certainly
wasn't my intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ironically, Rocker followed the Braves' lead by trying to
separate himself from his own comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said things that (don't) cross my mind on a consistent
basis. It doesn't cross my mind, period,'' Rocker said. ``In a time
of thought and remembrance, I shot my mouth off and said a few
things that's absolutely not me.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what his reaction would be to reading someone else
making similar comments, Rocker said: ``I would think this guy is a
complete jerk. Who in the hell does he think he is mouthing off
like this? What kind of experiences does he have to talk from?''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker appeared uncomfortable upon hearing Gammons read back
some of his comments from the article. Rocker said they were aimed
at the people who mistreated him at Shea Stadium and described
incidents in which he was spit on, had beer spilled on him and a
battery thrown at his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a segment of comments made in the process of
remembering some pretty harsh things that were done to you, like
seeing the likes of you beaten with a baseball bat,'' Rocker said.
``Looking back, I probably should have distinguished those comments
a little better. ... I just lost my cool. I (was going to) use this
time to retaliate.''
</P>
<P>
   According to family friend Steve Rodgers, Rocker spent a
restless Tuesday night in Macon before speaking with Gammons for 40
minutes Wednesday morning at a friend's house. Later in the
afternoon, Rocker met with Macon Mayor Jack Ellis to work some
hometown damage control. Rocker declined to meet with any media
after his interview with Gammons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good conversation, an open and honest discussion,''
Ellis, who is black, told Macon TV station WMAZ. ``I came away
convinced he is truly sorry for what he said and the people he hurt
with his remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought Rocker was a racist, Ellis said: ``No,
I don't. I'm willing to give him the benefit of the doubt. ...
After talking with him, I truly believe he mispoke. He's truly
sorry for saying those words.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker said ``one comment'' doesn't make him a racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Rocker said when asked if he was a racist.
``If I were a racist, A, would I want a black guy to come into my
house? B, would I invite him to my house? I've done that three
times over.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was referring to, among others, Braves teammate Andruw
Jones living with him at his family's home in Macon when they
played together in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who underwent a psychological evaluation last week as
ordered by baseball commissioner Bud Selig, is still waiting to
hear his fate from Major League Baseball, whether it be suspension
or fine, or both, and possibly racial sensitivity training. The
Braves will then decide their course of action.
</P>
<P>
   How Rocker will be received by his teammates is the most
intriguing question. It was his reference to a teammate as a fat
monkey which may have caused the most stir. Rocker explained the
comment as clubhouse humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a black guy. It was a Latin player who I consider
to be a good friend. ... In the past I've said it to his face and
he'll fire with this, that or the other and we laugh about it,''
Rocker said. ``I let a reporter in on an aspect of clubhouse humor
and he took it literally. The people that know me best, the Braves
management, the Braves players, they know I'm not like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker said teammate and fellow reliever Rudy Seanez, who is of
Mexican descent, called him after the story came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `Where the heck did this come from?''' Rocker said.
``I said `Yeah, I got a little out of hand.' ... I think they know
me well enough to know I'm not really like this and it's been a
gross misrepresentation of the way I really am.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
