<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-512&AMP;ADD-N     01-12 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-512&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND MCCAIN TIPTOE THROUGH DIXIE MINEFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain both
walked gingerly through racial minefields Wednesday as Bush was
pressed anew to state his feelings about the presence of the
Confederate flag atop South Carolina's Statehouse and McCain sought
to clarify his position on that politically delicate issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was repeatedly asked about the flag both at a news
conference Wednesday morning in West Columbia, S.C., and at another
one here Wednesday afternoon, once again said that any decision
about the flag should be made by South Carolinians, and resolutely
left his answer at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it as a local issue,'' Bush said in West Columbia,
sounding a little exasperated. ``I've spoken to this issue every
time I've come to your state and I'm not going to say anything
more. The people of South Carolina can solve the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same news conference, Bush, who has aggressively
presented himself as a Republican eager to reach out and include
more minorities in the party, was asked about a Republican state
senator in South Carolina who recently made disparaging comments
about the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker, Arthur Ravenel, said the NAACP, which has fought
to have the Confederate flag removed, should be called the National
Association of Retarded People. Bush was also asked if Ravenel
should be forced to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be up to the senator to do that,'' Bush said, after
first branding Ravenel's remarks ``very unfortunate.'' Bush seemed
annoyed with the topic and eager to move past it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain exhibited little more interest in dwelling on the
subject. Campaigning in New Hampshire, the usually loquacious
candidate responded to seemingly conflicting remarks about his
position on the Confederate flag over the last few days by reading
aloud from a statement his campaign distributed earlier this week
in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand both sides,'' McCain read aloud. ``Some view it
as a symbol of slavery, others view it as a symbol of heritage.
Personally, I see the battle flag as a symbol of heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   The last word appropriated the language used frequently by
defenders of the flag and seemed to contradict emphatically
McCain's statements in a television interview on Sunday that the
flag was a symbol ``of racism and slavery'' and that he found it
``offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Wednesday that people were overanalyzing his
remarks. ``This is getting rather Talmudic,'' he said. ``We're
parsing words.''
</P>
<P>
   If both Bush and McCain seemed to be trying to straddle or
defuse the issue, it was little wonder. In South Carolina, which
holds a pivotal Republican primary on Feb. 19, many of the
staunchest, most reliable Republican voters support the presence of
the Confederate flag, and outright opposition to the position could
be politically fatal.
</P>
<P>
   But outright support could come back to haunt a Republican
nominee in a general election among voters nationwide.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Bush's case, it might undermine his appeal to swing voters in
the center of the political spectrum and his campaign slogan of
compassionate conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush frequently visits minority neighborhoods and
churches and makes public appearances with Hispanic and black
leaders, as he did Wednesday afternoon at a social services agency
in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   He talked with such leaders about the need for the government to
encourage religious and charitable organizations to do more social
work, and the need for Republicans to show that they care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know oftentimes people with the word Republican by their
name are labeled, and I'd like to break the label,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But only hours earlier, he was answering questions from
reporters about why, despite all his oratory of inclusion, it was
almost impossible to find a black person among the hundreds of
supporters who turned out to hear his speech in West Columbia
Wednesday morning or the thousands who attended an oyster roast on
Tuesday night at a former plantation in Mount Pleasant, S.C., now a
tourist site that both Republicans and Democrats have used for
political events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows how much work the Republican Party has to do to
make sure our message is explained clearly and people can hear
it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every time Bush goes to South Carolina, he is asked to go
beyond his statement that South Carolinians should settle their
disagreements about the flag, and every time, Bush simply
reiterates his position. Bush is a proponent of state and local
control on a variety of fronts.
</P>
<P>
   After the Republican debate on Monday in Grand Rapids, Mich.,
Bush said he would not choose to fly the flag in his own state of
Texas because of the flag's symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in Wilmington Wednesday afternoon what he meant by its
symbolism, he said, ``What that means is some people have _ people
have strong feelings about that. Some people feel one way about it.
Some people feel the other way about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked if not denouncing the flag might give voters the
impression that he was unwilling to lead on racial matters. ``I
don't think it reflects my heart at all,'' he said. ``It reflects
my understanding that the people of South Carolina can make up
their own minds on that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the Republican field, Steve Forbes lashed out at
the tax plans that his rivals have been fighting over for the past
few days, saying their proposals did not come close to the deep tax
cuts and tax code overhaul that he had suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Iowa, Forbes asserted that his plan would provide
$648 billion in cuts over five years, while Bush's proposal would
cut $483 billion and McCain's $237 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He urged voters to ``shop and compare,'' adding, ``I think they
will see that our plan will save them the most time and money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
