u f BC-DIGIHUB-PRIVACY-NYT &LR;      01-12 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGIHUB-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSULTING FIRM TO INVEST IN INTERTRUST TECHNOLOGIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SARA ROBINSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The InterTrust Technologies Corp., a start-up
based in Santa Clara, Calif., will announce on Thursday formation
of an alliance that puts it one step closer to its goal of becoming
the standard for managing the security of digital online content
like documents, music, videos and software.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers, the giant accounting and business
consulting firm, plans to use InterTrust's technology to develop
software and systems for its corporate customers to do transactions
with businesses and consumers while protecting and managing their
digital content, executives for both companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting firm will spend $25 million to develop
applications, train employees and license the InterTrust technology
and make an equity investment of an undisclosed amount in
InterTrust, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very big play for us,'' said John R. Stubbs, the
partner in charge of the global content management initiative at
PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``We think that new business models can be
exploited with InterTrust technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Shear, InterTrust's chief executive, said more such
alliances were in the works. InterTrust's technology has already
been adopted by two media heavyweights, Universal Music Group and
Bertelsmann AG, as well as by a host of other companies. But an
analyst said the PricewaterhouseCoopers alliance was a major coup.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers counts among its clients a majority of
the world's 5,000 largest concerns, including those in media,
financial services, retail sales, health care management and
government.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the Internet is expected to evolve into the
world's major distribution space for products ranging from videos
and recorded music to medical records and contracts. As this trend
unfolds, the demand to protect ownership of copyrights, keep
documents private and manage complex payment systems is expected to
grow exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   But the same technology that protects information can also be
used to exploit data, a fact that makes privacy advocates uneasy.
PricewaterhouseCoopers, for example, will also use InterTrust
technology to start a service called DigiHub, which will collect
and manage vast amounts of information about the people who use
content distributed by the firm's clients. The service, marketed as
a way to analyze market trends and optimize business operations,
will be tailored for specific businesses or industries, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Leigh, a vice president at Raymond James, predicted that
the DigiHub service would serve as a model for other big consulting
firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have the profiles of what people like, they have
better value to their clients,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet DigiHub is also likely to raise privacy concerns since the
information contains names and credit card numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have individual information on everyone who uses the
system, much like Visa does,'' Stubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that privacy is ``a huge, huge issue,'' he
added that tracking use information is a key part of doing business
on the Internet. He also asserted that as trusted auditors of
businesses around the globe, PriceWaterhouseCoopers is the best
choice for managing such information.
</P>
<P>
   InterTrust's digital commerce system, known as the MetaTrust
Utility, packages content in coded files known as DigiBoxes, which
also contain the rules of the content's use. To open a DigiBox
file, a user must install software that contains the user's credit
card information and automatically deducts payments according to
the attached rules.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Rosenoer, global strategic ventures leader at PWC,
says, for example, that the technology enables a transaction such
as downloading an InterTrust protected album to provide additional
marketing opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play two tracks for free, then get charged for the
rest,'' he said. ``Say I want to download it to a Rio (portable
music player); then there might be a extra $5 charge. If I don't
accept, I might get an offer for tickets to a performance at a
discount. If I pay with American Express, there might be special
additional offers I can take advantage of. If I send this to my
friend and they like it, I might get a bonus track.''
</P>
<P>
   Each step of the way, the consumer's behavior patterns can be _
and often will be _ monitored and recorded.
</P>
<P>
   He cites another example of how applications built on InterTrust
technology could be used for business-to-business e-commerce: When
products are imported, they have to be paid for, often with a draft
on the buyer's bank, customs authorities notified and taxes paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payments can be made efficiently, inventory is handled more
efficiently, costs go down significantly and tax authorities are
assured of payment,'' he said. ``You really optimize that whole
process when you start doing this across the Internet.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
