<SLUG> BC-BOEING-HUGHES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING NEAR PACT ON BUYING HUGHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing may be about to go where no company has gone
before in the space business.
</P>
<P>
   In a bold move that analysts said Wednesday will finally
establish the aerospace giant as the major player it wants to be in
the space business of the 21st Century, Boeing is reported to be
near an agreement to buy Hughes Space and Communications Co. for
$3.75 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is the world's largest manufacturer of commercial
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which could be announced within days, was first
reported by Bloomberg News. The Wall Street Journal and New York
Times quoted unnamed executives close to the matter as saying an
ageement is near.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespersons for Boeing and Hughes refused to comment on the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   With Hughes in the fold, Boeing would topple Lockheed Martin as
the world's leading space company, several analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing will have come from next to nothing to being the top
space company in the world,'' said Paul Nisbet of JSR Research in
Newport, R.I. ``And they will have done all that in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, Boeing spent $3 billion for the space business
of Rockwell, and followed that move a few months later with the $15
billion acquisition of defense giant McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Those acquisitions made Boeing the emerging leader in satellite
launch services, but what the company has lacked is a big time
satellite-making business.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is the missing piece that Boeing has needed to complete
its space business strategy, said Marco Caceres, senior space
analyst for the Teal Group, a market research firm in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific fit because Boeing right now is not a major
manufacturer of satellites,'' he said. ``That really is the big gap
in terms of Boeing being a complete space player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes Space and Communications, with projected 1999 sales of
around $2.3 billion, is part of Hughes Electronics Corp., which is
owned by General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite manufacturing part of Hughes is based in El
Segundo, Calif., near the Los Angeles International Airport. The
business, with about 8,000 employees, is just up the road from
Boeing's space division headquarters in Seal Beach. Last month
Boeing had about 37,000 employees in California, most of them
working in its space division.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes Space and Communications is part of Hughes Electronics,
which General Motors has wanted to sell so Hughes can focus on its
services business. That includes the company's DirecTV unit, the
largest U.S. satellite television service.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes Electronics badly needs an infusion of cash so it can
fund DireTV and its other services-based businesses, analysts said.
The company also is planning what it calls ``Spaceway,'' a system
for highspeed internet connection. It needs about $1.4 billion to
build and launch Spaceway in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hughes needs the cash,'' said Caceres. ``Boeing's would come
in real handy.''
</P>
<P>
   But one analyst said Boeing is paying too much for the Hughes
unit if the reported $3.75 billion figure is true.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very big price,'' said Cai von Rumohr of S.G. Cowen &AMP;
Co., who valued the satellite manufacturing operations at $2
billion to $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Nisbet said Boeing is making a strategic move, and the
Hughes unit is worth much more to Boeing than revenue figures would
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strategic buyer such as Boeing would pay more than a
financial buyer because it's a very good fit,'' he said. Boeing, he
said, had about $2.6 billion in cash reserves at the end of the
third quarter, and that has probably grown to nearly $4 billion as
Boeing reduced its airplane inventory in recent months. The company
delivered a record 620 planes in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing also has tremendous borrowing power,'' Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would grow Boeing's $7 billion space and
communications division by more than 30 percent, said analysts, who
have speculated for more than a year that Boeing would eventually
move to acquire the satellite-making arm of Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been rumored for so long you forget it hasn't actually
happened yet,'' said Jon Kutler, president of Quarterdeck
Investment Partners, a Los Angeles based firm that advises
aerospace companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said Boeing has adopted a Microsoft-type strategy of making
key investments to ensure it will be well positioned in new
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This next century will be dominated by space the way the last
century was dominated by aerospace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has enjoyed a close working relationship with Hughes
Space and Communications. Boeing's Delta 2 rocket, which the
company acquired in the merger with McDonnell Douglas, have lofted
many commercial and military satellites built by Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is a key Boeing customer for Sea launch, a moveable ocean
launch platform. It also bought some of the roughly 30 commercial
launch slots Boeing sold for a Delta 4 rocket now in development.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies also are working on a new generation of spy
satellites for the National Reconnaissance Office. Boeing beat out
Lockheed Martin for the $5 billion contract.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing already has the capacity to make military satellites as a
result of its acquisition of Rockwell's space business. Rockwell
built the military's global positioning satellite system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2303EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NY     01-12 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: DOES IT MATTER WHO OWNS WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is the map really being redrawn, or have the countries just
changed colors? That's the question that comes to mind after yet
another largest-ever media merger, AOL's $165 billion acquisition
of Time Warner. Does it make a difference that all the entities
once owned separately by AOL and Time Warner will soon be owned by
them jointly? Put that way, the answer seems to be no. It isn't
hard to see the logic in this deal, nor is it hard to sense the
enormous forces that pulled these companies together. With such a
high degree of consolidation in the media and Internet sectors,
it's possible to argue that a little more merging isn't going to do
much harm.
</P>
<P>
   But the AOL-Time Warner merger isn't just a little more
consolidation. I don't know how to measure the physics of a deal
like this, but it feels as though this merger is less the sum of
adding two companies together than the product of multiplying them.
It is hard to stipulate the unknown, which is one of the
attractions, and one of the worries, of this deal. Steve Case, the
CEO of AOL, and Gerald Levin, the CEO of Time Warner, have tried to
forestall the anxiety this merger causes by asserting that it is a
social good, by promising to guarantee open access to cable
subscribers, and by reminding us that even corporations this
enormous actually have people in them.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with these reassurances is that neither Case nor
Levin can control the forces that brought them together in the
first place. What drove this merger was the power unleashed by the
enormous market valuation of Internet companies. What also drove it
was the clear sense that the only way to survive at that level of
competition was to unite every possible spectrum of electronic
distribution and every possible source of content _ that sad word _
under a single banner. Synergy in this case is just another word
for vertical integration, for controlling creativity, copyright and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The major problem this deal poses is neither customer access nor
access to customers. It is the customers' inveterate habit of
treating brands like CNN, Time magazine and Netscape as if they
still identified independent companies. Much of the trust the media
earned, journalistically speaking, is based on a time when that
habit still reflected reality. Brand value has been a marketing
cliche for years. But in a deal like this, the hidden value of a
treasured brand _ and, I suspect, its real value _ is the fact that
we have such a hard time remembering that it no longer stands on
its own. We behave as if nothing had changed when, in fact,
everything has changed. The layers of potential conflict in this
new world of news gathering are enormous, and it will take the
diligence of a scholar to remember who owns whom and where the
ethical lines must be drawn.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another, subtler risk in the potential synergy this
kind of merger represents. The residual gravity of such an enormous
corporation _ its ethos, its habits _ will take a toll on
creativity, in content or business operations, all the way down the
line. Call it an efficiency tax, the edge that vanishes when
everything is tailored for the pipeline, so to speak. No matter how
you spin it, this merger, like other, similar mergers in the past
few years, represents a move toward uniformity and away from
diversity, toward the globalization of a consumerist, mass culture
that is best purveyed by globalized mass corporations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0473 </DOCNO>
