<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JAN. 13
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CUBAN-BOY (moved on Tuesday, Jan. 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Jan. 11,
about the immigration case involving Elian Gonzalez misattributed a
comment about the failure of a family court judge to disclose a
prior business relationship with a spokesman for the boy's
relatives. It was Anthony V. Alfieri, director of the Center for
Ethics and Public Service at the University of Miami, who said the
judge's action _ granting temporary custody to Elian's great-uncle
in Miami _ was troubling. (It was not Celena Rios, director of
family court operations for the Eleventh Judicial Circuit of
Florida.)
</P>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-REALNETWORKS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 9,
about software that is used to transmit and receive audio and video
files over the Internet misstated the capabilities of Apple
Computer's QuickTime software. QuickTime allows a computer user to
immediately see or hear files sent from a Web site. It does not
require the user to download the files to the computer before
playing them.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PATENTS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 9,
about databases of trademarks misspelled the name of a company that
maintains one. It is Thomson &AMP; Thomson, not Thompson &AMP; Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   BC-KOZENY-INVEST-SUIT-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 21,
about Viktor Kozeny, a promoter of a foreign investment fund in
Azerbaijan, overstated the wealth of Richard Friedman, an American
investor who participated in the fund. Friedman says he is not a
billionaire.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TV-CROSSING-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 9,
</P>
<P>
   about ``The Crossing'' on A&AMP;E misidentified a general on George
Washington's staff who was skeptical of the American troops'
abilities. He was Horatio Gates, played by Nigel Bennett, not Henry
Knox, played by John Henry Caravan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
