<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      01-12 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: ATTACKED OVER HITLER
</P>
<P>
   Former Economics Minister Juergen Moellemann, chairman of the
Free Democratic Party in North Rhine-Westphalia, was sharply
criticized for using an image of Hitler in his campaign posters for
the state election on May 14. Hitler's face is above a warning
saying: ``If we do not move quickly to put more teachers in the
schools, our children will look for their own teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: COMMUNIST'S PLEA REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   Egon Krenz, the last leader of Communist East Germany, was
ordered to begin a six-year sentence Thursday after a federal court
rejected his appeal. Krenz was found guilty of complicity in the
shooting of people trying to escape across the Berlin Wall. The
unrepentant former leader has a further appeal before the European
Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: WOODWARD PARENTS CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   The estranged parents of Louise Woodward, the British au pair
convicted of manslaughter in Boston in 1997, were ordered to stand
trial on charges of defrauding their daughter's defense fund. Gary
Woodward, 44, and Susan Woodward, 43, are accused of billing the
British fund $15,400 for Boston accommodations they received free
of charge.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: POLITICAL WARNING
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary committee warned that the growth in the number
of politically motivated special advisers since Labor came to power
in 1997 was threatening the independence and authority of impartial
civil servants who have traditionally served British ministers. The
committee proposed a statutory limit on their number, which have
risen from 38 to 74.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: TRUCKERS LIFT BLOCKADE
</P>
<P>
   Truck owners lifted their blockades of border crossings and
strategic transit routes after government concessions on diesel
price rises and plans to limit the workweek. But the accord may
only have brought temporary peace as truck drivers are considering
whether the plan satisfies them.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: PUTIN'S KEY BACKING
</P>
<P>
   Acting President Vladimir Putin was formally nominated for
president by dozens of figures from the business, political and
social elite, the first step toward the March 26 election. Putin
must now gather 500,000 supporters' signatures by Feb. 13, a task
aides said will take but 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: MIDEAST DATES
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican announced that Pope John Paul II's trip to the Holy
Land would take place from March 20 to 26, and it will include
visits to Israel's Holocaust memorial and a Palestinian refugee
camp. It will also include meetings with President Ezer Weizman of
Israel and King Abdullah of Jordan, where the trip will begin.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBELS KILL 24
</P>
<P>
   In the first outbreak of fighting since a holiday truce declared
by the largest left-wing guerrilla group expired, the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia attacked several police stations in the
southern province of Narino. At least 24 soldiers, policemen and
civilians are reported to have been killed, and government
spokesmen said about 20 rebels were also killed.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: STRIKE WEAKENED
</P>
<P>
   The transport workers' union in Quito has pulled out of the
coalition sponsoring a general strike scheduled to begin on
Saturday, a move that dims prospects for success of the civil
disobedience campaign the opposition alliance has been calling for
in hopes of forcing President Jamil Mahuad to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND: HEROIN SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   Tipped off by U.S. counter-drug agents, the police made their
largest heroin seizure in several years, intercepting 277 pounds of
the narcotic at Bangkok's international airport. The heroin,
destined for the United States, had traveled south from the Golden
Triangle, a rugged opium-growing area where Thailand's borders with
Myanmar and Laos converge.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: OPPOSITION JOINS IN
</P>
<P>
   A major opposition party, the Ivoirian Popular Front, has joined
a transitional government formed by the country's new military
rulers. The party initially pulled out of the government,
criticizing its leadership as too close to a party headed by
Alassane D. Ouattara, a former prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
