<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      01-12 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE DINOSAUR ON DISPLAY AT STATE CAPITOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Generations from now, pa leontologists will look back
in awe and envy at the events of January 2000, when journalists
slogging through the muck on West Washington Street stumbled upon a
living, breathing speci men from a category of prehis toric beings
long thought to be extinct.
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was immediately identi fied as a fully preserved exam ple of
Crackpotus Fanatisaurus, a small but vigorous subgroup of the genus
and species Numbskullus Politisaurus, which thrived for a time in
the area of the Arizona State Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters on the scene dubbed the discovery, ``State Rep. Karen
Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   The origin of this particular class of creature was said to have
been the area described as ``east Mesa.''
</P>
<P>
   Individuals from that geo graphic location were known to have
learned to walk upright and make use of simple tools, but few at
the time believed they had achieved a level of mental acuity that
would have allowed them to formulate ef fective language skills.
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Johnson spoke, this theory was proved true.
</P>
<P>
   She announced this week that she planned to introduce in the
state Legislature a bill requir ing public schools to set aside
time to present ``scientific evi dence'' that disputes the most
accepted theories of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Though her bill doesn't men tion it specifically, Johnson told a
local talk-show host that she'd like to see religious ``creation
ism'' taught in schools.
</P>
<P>
   As Rep. Johnson told one re porter, ``If you come from a lit tle
bit of slime out in a pool, then what's so great about life?''
</P>
<P>
   Before judging her too harshly, please take into consid eration
who is speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson apparently is unfa miliar with the universally ac cepted
theory that, as a politician, her origins actually can be traced to
an enormous bit of slime.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to this swamp-like political legacy have been
discovered in all parts of the world, thought the fossil fields are
particularly rich in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, for instance, the education lobbyist for then-Gov.
Evan Mecham, a former state representative named Jim Coo per, told
a committee at the state House, ``If a student wants to say the
world is flat, the teacher doesn't have the right to try to prove
otherwise. . . . The schools don't have any busi ness telling
people what to be lieve.''
</P>
<P>
   During that same era, there was a female member of the
Legislature whose last name also happened to be Johnson. Her first
name was Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to vigorously op posing things like the holiday
named in honor of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., Rep. Leslie
Johnson once said, ``I am sick of more government pro grams for the
poor. I think the poor are doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Johnson also intro duced a law outlawing what she called
``sexual devices.'' The bill failed to pass, but it did lead to the
production and sale of an extremely popular bumper sticker that
read:
</P>
<P>
   ``When dildos are outlawed, only outlaws will have dildos.''
</P>
<P>
   Given such a heritage, some might suggest that as backward as
Rep. Karen Johnson appears to be, she is more evolved than her
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would disagree.
</P>
<P>
   She does not believe in evolu tion and, unlike the scientists
she opposes, she has proof posi tive.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars must rely on fossils, radioisotopic dating, compara
tive anatomy, embryology, bio chemistry and other sciences to
support their conclusions about evolution.
</P>
<P>
   All Johnson must do to refute them is open her mouth. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or at (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
