<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-COL-MRSCLINTON-NYT     01-12 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY ON LATE SHOW: TV RULES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was perfect, nothing short of perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary and Dave, neighbors and friends, candidate and comedian,
politician and antipolitician, enjoying a few laughs, reading a few
lists, exchanging one-liners and a few teasing moments. Nothing
tough, nothing rough. Just fun.
</P>
<P>
   Could there be a more perfect example of campaign politics, year
2000? The virtual interview, handled with aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``She couldn't pay for this,'' said one of the two dozen
reporters who sat through a screening of the taping of Hillary
Rodham Clinton's much-heralded 20 minutes on ``Late Show With David
Letterman'' on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The press screening came complete with graciously provided
pizza, Coke, bottled water and Dunkin' Donuts (honest), gratis from
the Letterman people, who may have felt a little guilty because the
press corps wasn't allowed into a screening room during the taping.
Reporters had to wait to see a dubbed tape on a small television
set in an 11th-floor conference room after Mrs. Clinton had left.
Letterman rules, not Hillary rules.
</P>
<P>
   Other reporters, the ones with cameras and microphones and a few
with notebooks, crowded around the stage door on West 53rd Street
to see Mrs. Clinton leave and wave to the crowd across the street
that was also waiting to see her leave the studio and wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is prettier than on television,'' said Mark Alexander, 30,
a disc jockey visiting from Washington. He said he had heard on
Dave's show Tuesday night that she would be on Wednesday night. He
also heard it from Barbara Walters, who chatted about it on ``The
View'' on ABC. In fact, ``You couldn't go a block without hearing
about it,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   After the show, about 7 Wednesday night, Mrs. Clinton thrilled
the shouting crowd by acknowledging them for 30 seconds before
climbing into her car. ``Did I hear that right, did she say,
`Great, had a wonderful time?''' one Hillary watcher asked another.
Probably.
</P>
<P>
   By now, those who care know what Mrs. Clinton said to Letterman
and vice versa. It sort of doesn't matter. What does matter is that
she showed up. Plus she didn't mess up, appeared calm if a bit
programmed, wasn't thrown for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   That is what counts in politics now, and to get serious for a
moment, just a moment, is this the politics we want? Mrs. Clinton
on Letterman (and, a few weeks ago, on Rosie O'Donnell's program).
Vice President Al Gore on Letterman. Donald Trump on ``The Tonight
Show With Jay Leno.'' And on and on.
</P>
<P>
   America is seeing the ultimate in the fusion of not just
entertainment and news, but entertainment, news and politics. Truth
be told, the candidates have no choice. They have to play. The
public demands it.
</P>
<P>
   We have gone from an appearance on the old, stodgy ``Meet the
Press'' as political validation to softballs from Larry King to
David Letterman, a comedian who hides his smarts and retreats
behind his Top 10 lists ( Wednesday night's Top 10 list was
questions dumb guys would ask the first lady. No. 1: Have you ever
met my Dad, George Bush?
</P>
<P>
   That's fine. Letterman chooses to be a funny man, not a
political analyst. The question for us all to ask is why a
candidate is compelled to get into the celebrity game, why Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani has to joke with Letterman, as he did a few
years ago, about kicking posteriors (not the word he used). Why,
for that matter, do the Tom Brokaws, Peter Jennings and Ted Koppels
feel they have to make the talk show scene? Why would Walter
Cronkite turn up for a cameo on Letterman last night before Mrs.
Clinton's appearance, warning him, ``Try not to be a jackass, will
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Rhetorical questions. Because to succeed politically and
sometimes journalistically these days, we have made it a necessity
to enter the popular culture. To say no is to appear grim and out
of it. Nor can a public figure afford to offend the Lettermans and
Lenos, because they so affect the collective public psyche,
somehow.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Letterman's amiable executive producer, Rob Burnett,
briefed the press. He was admirably forthcoming, more so than some
dissembling political press secretaries. But he was briefing us
about a bit of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder people are confused about the importance of celebrity,
mistaking it for accomplishment. No wonder we elect actors and
people who could be actors, and Donald Trump actually gets himself
taken seriously as a political figure in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, no wonder a columnist for The New York Times was at
the Letterman stage door last night. She did not, she would like to
emphasize, eat a slice of pizza or a doughnut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
