<HEADLINE>
BUSH ENDORSED BY 2 MORE SENATORS; MCCAIN CRACK BECOMES SUBJECT OF
AD: CLINTON ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUPPORT FROM ASHCROFT
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was endorsed Wednesday by two
prominent senators, bringing to 33 the number of Republican
senators who have decided to back Bush as the Republican
presidential nominee instead of John McCain, their colleague in
that chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers were Sens. John Ashcroft of Missouri, a social
conservative who had briefly flirted with a run at the Republican
presidential nomination, and Connie Mack of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, who appeared in West Columbia, S.C., with Bush, said
that it was good to join a ``winning team'' and that he was as
optimistic about America's future as Bush was. ``We're far too
young to die,'' he said, referring to the American empire. ``It's
time again to fly. And let this mighty eagle soar again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Frank Bruni &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHOSE LAUGH?
</P>
<P>
   One day last September, Sen. John McCain was bantering with
reporters on his campaign bus about something that had slipped his
mind, and he joked that at 63 he was becoming old and senile. ``The
nice thing about Alzheimer's,'' he cracked, ``is you get to hide
your own Easter eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the New Hampshire affiliate of the National Right to
Life Committee, which opposes McCain's presidential candidacy
because he wants to change campaign finance laws, picked up on the
joke and began running a 30-second radio spot accusing the senator
of being insensitive to the elderly. ``Four million Americans
suffer from Alzheimer's disease,'' the ad begins.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the McCain campaign here said New Hampshire
voters would have no trouble recognizing the remark as a joke.
</P>
<P>
   _ By David E. Rosenbaum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE PRESIDENT ON THE TRAIL
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton came to the aid of a Democratic congresswoman
Tuesday night at a $1,000-a-person fund-raiser in Houston. But the
visit was more of a reward to a loyal ally than a rescue of a
candidate in distress.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate, Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, was one of the
president's most outspoken defenders during the House impeachment
hearings in 1998. When the case moved to the Senate, she listened
to the trial day after day from the back of the Senate chamber, and
during breaks in the proceedings disparaged the case to reporters
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson-Lee is not exactly running scared in her re-election
bid. She won nearly 90 percent of the vote in 1998, a reflection of
the Democratic hold on her district, and she is expected to coast
to re-election this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening Clinton attended a fund-raiser for the
Texas Legislative Victory Fund. Texas is expected to gain
congressional seats after the 2000 Census, and control of the
legislature will determine how those seats are apportioned.
Democrats narrowly control the state House and Republicans narrowly
control the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Marc Lacey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Campaigns in Sioux City, Iowa, and later in Manchester,
N.H.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Campaigns in Laconia and Portsmouth, N.H., and
later in Council Bluffs, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Campaigns in Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN MCCAIN: Campaigns in Keene, Nashua, and Hooksett, N.H. and
addresses the New Hampshire Legislature in Concord.
</P>
