<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES     01-12 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: REVAMPED PITCH FOR COKE WILL PAVE WAY FOR HIGHER
PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: sidebar at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT and CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be an exaggeration to assert that a new campaign for
the flagship soft drink sold by Coca-Cola Co. is a make-or-break
effort. After all, the beverage, known as Coca-Cola Classic in
North America and Coca-Cola elsewhere, is the world's best-selling
soda and most recognized brand.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the television, print and Internet campaign, the first
revamping of the venerable product's pitch in almost seven years,
is being introduced at a crucial time for the company. Coca-Cola is
facing what could be its toughest marketing battle in recent memory
as it seeks to persuade American customers to pay more for soft
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola and its principal rival, the Pepsi-Cola unit of
PepsiCo, have begun to increase prices for the concentrate they
sell to bottlers, which will most likely end an era of continuous
bargains on cans and bottles of soda in supermarkets, drugstores
and mass merchandise outlets. Higher prices, even if they mean
lower volume, are intended to make the retail business more
profitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under that model, Coca-Cola and Pepsi-Cola will probably spend
more to try to stimulate demand for their brands. But they risk
making shoppers balk at paying more for carbonated sugared water,
particularly when more alternatives _ teas, fruit drinks, sports
beverages, even water _ are more available than ever.
</P>
<P>
   So the Coke Classic campaign, scheduled to blitz American
consumers starting Monday, is more focused on product qualities and
benefits than its predecessor, which carried the theme ``Always
Coca-Cola.'' That reorientation is underscored by the new theme _
plainly and simply ``Coca-Cola. Enjoy'' _ which is celebrated in
the lyrics of a sprightly jingle in at least 19 musical genres from
``urban/Latino/rap'' to ``country/traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads ``leverage what's unique about Coke, the flavor
composition, the spice and aromatics, the good memories, the feel
of the bottle,'' said Charles Frenette, who until Friday is the
chief marketing officer of Coca-Cola, based in Atlanta, ``and how
it adds a little bit of magic, a little sparkle, to the little
moments of everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We happen to be a cola, but we're Coca-Cola,'' Frenette said,
referring to the year-old ``Joy of cola'' campaign for Pepsi-Cola.
``It's about fun and good times, refreshment through renewal, not
just quenching a parched throat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole notion is about making Coke more useful, talking
about what Coke does for its user,'' he continued. ``And we think
people ascribe value to usefulness.''
</P>
<P>
   Frenette, who is being sent to Europe by the company's
designated new chairman and chief executive, Douglas Daft, to
become president of its struggling operations there, joined with
Ian Rowden, the company's vice president and advertising director,
to offer a preview of the campaign in meetings with reporters
Tuesday in New York. The meetings preceded the presentation of the
campaign to Coca-Cola bottlers in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the new jingle and the content of the ads are an effort
to entertain the consumer and attract attention,'' said John
Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter. ``But at
the same time, the prevalence of the bubbles and the fizzing energy
try to convey something to the consumer about the attributes of the
product.''
</P>
<P>
   In emphasizing the ``Cokeness,'' as it were, of Coca-Cola, the
campaign makes a harder sell than its diffused predecessor, though
the hawking is swaddled in soft surroundings. The low-key nature of
the ads is embodied in the catchy jingle, far less bombastic than
its Pepsi counterpart, which is complemented in commercials by
humor, special effects, attractive young casts and even a soupcon
of sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not `Enjoy Coca-Cola' but `Coca-Cola. Enjoy,''' Rowden
said. ``It's not directive; it's not prescriptive. It's an
invitation, allowing people to view life through the optimistic
lens we provide.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the campaign is Proustian, offering remembrances of
Cokes past, though the trappings are contemporary in keeping with a
corporate belief that, as quoted by Frenette, ``the genius behind
Coca-Cola is the fact it's renewed for each generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Several spots are nostalgic, centered on memories of consumers
in their teens and 20s of a going-away party, frolicking under a
waterfall, romping in the snow and a night out with friends. There
are familiar characters like the polar bears and the thirsty summer
sun, joining newcomers like a race of pink aliens that thrive on
Coke Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The jingle lyrics evoke the famous slogan ``It's the real
thing.'' And updated versions of the classic contoured Coke bottle
_ augmented by a redesigned ``bell glass'' and traditional red
coolers _ play as large a role in every ad as ``Is that your final
answer?'' plays on every episode of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty impressed with the campaign,'' said Gary A.
Hemphill, vice president at Beverage Marketing Corp., a research,
data and consulting company. ``It's well thought out, striving to
make Coca-Cola more relevant and useful rather than building
awareness, which the brand already has.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time for a change,'' he added. `` `Always' had run its
course. And Coca-Cola needs to move the needle, though it's a
pretty large needle given their size and scope. By playing on the
mystique of the brand'' _ a concept Frenette also referred to,
using the term ``gestalt'' _ ``the campaign makes Coke appear
special. And that may be a pretty strong approach when concentrate
prices are rising.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To create the ``Enjoy'' campaign, Coca-Cola is turning first to
a shortened list of agencies that have worked on the brand in
various countries. The initial batch of commercials and print ads
for worldwide consumption is being produced by Edge Creative, which
had been the lead creative agency for Coca-Cola Classic, and Leo
Burnett Co. unit of the Leo Group.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett is contributing the winter commercial, a funny spot
about a parrot that mimics the sound of a Coca-Cola bottle opening,
a lavish commercial centered on children's first taste of Coke, and
a spot in which a large crowd at a rock concert turns into
effervescent bubbles. The Edge contributions include the
commercials about the aliens, the waterfall and the party.
</P>
<P>
   Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, which has specialized in Coke ads with sports
themes, is developing global spots devoted to the Summer Olympics,
football and soccer, Rowden said. Four other agencies are working
on local and regional ads that could be seen more widely, he added:
D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications, part of MacManus
Group; Doner; McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising, a division of
the McCann-Erickson World Group, owned by Interpublic Group of
Cos.; and Publicis, part of Publicis SA.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plans to overhaul the Web site (www.cocacola.com)
for Coca-Cola, effective Monday, in its first redesign since it was
introduced in 1995. The revamping, by the interactive shop
Agency.com, will replace the current staid, bland graphics with
more interactive features like links to commercials and jingles
that can be downloaded, screen savers and e-commerce (as in
``enjoy'' or ``electronic''). For instance, products like toy polar
bears will be available for purchase, Rowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether consumers enjoy, dislike or ignore the ``Enjoy''
campaign, it is likely to be around for a while, said Emanuel
Goldman, a global consumer-products analyst for Merrill Lynch,
adding that Coca-Cola ``will push extra hard this year, but it's
not just this year; this is longer term.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR)
</P>
<P>
   DOWN THROUGH THE DECADES WITH COKE SLOGANS
</P>
<P>
   For many years, signs and vending machines have urged consumers
to ``Enjoy Coca-Cola.'' But the new campaign theme being introduced
Monday, ``Coca-Cola. Enjoy,'' is the first time the word has been
officially included in the brand's main slogan. Here is a look back
at other slogans, from the archives of Coca-Cola Co.:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1929 ``The pause that refreshes.''
</P>
<P>
   1936 ``It's the refreshing thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   1942 ``It's the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   1944 ``Global high sign.''
</P>
<P>
   1959 ``Be really refreshed.''
</P>
<P>
   1963 ``Things go better with Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   1969 ``It's the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   1971 ``I'd like to buy the world a Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   1976 ``Coke adds life.''
</P>
<P>
   1982 ``Coke is it.''
</P>
<P>
   1986 ``Red, white and you.''
</P>
<P>
   1989 ``Can't beat the feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   1990 ``Can't beat the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   1993 ``Always Coca-Cola.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
