<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-2NDLD-WRITE     01-12 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLINE LIFTED FOR RETURN OF RESCUED CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Fla.)   (Eds.: Includes changes in 2nd, 4th and 5th graphs and inserts
graphs about relatives' lawyer, the administration and members of
Congress)  
(jw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Wednesday that
only federal courts had the authority to decide whether a
6-year-old boy should be reunited with his father in Cuba but said
immigration officials had lifted a Friday deadline for his return
to allow his relatives to appeal in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to lawyers for the boy's relatives in Miami, Reno
said a Florida state court had no jurisdiction in the case of the
boy, Elian Gonzalez. The child was rescued at sea clinging to an
inner tube in November after his mother drowned.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, Reno emphatically reaffirmed her belief that the
law required that Elian should be returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is considering going to court this week
to ask a federal judge to enforce the immigration ruling in hope of
speedily resolving a difficult, emotional political and diplomatic
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has adopted a dual approach to
dealing with the case. On one hand, officials want to show that
their ruling giving Elian's father the right to make the decision
for the boy is the product of well-established law that sets a
priority on family unification and that they are willing to have it
tested in federal court. At the same time, the administration is
moving to end the stalemate quickly, possibly seeking a court order
that could lead to federal marshals' being sent to fetch Elian from
the Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, Reno said that a separate lawsuit filed in
Florida state court by the relatives to gain custody of Elian had
no bearing on the case, which she said could only be decided in
federal court. Judge Rosa Rodriguez of the Miami-Dade Circuit Court
ruled Monday that Elian must remain in the United States until a
March 6 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Reno brushed aside that ruling Wednesday, saying that the state
court order had ``no force or effect'' on the Immigration and
Naturalization Service's decision in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of who may speak for a 6-year-old child in
applying for admission or asylum is a matter of federal immigration
law,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials and legal analysts said they
believed that Reno had the authority to decide as she did because
the immigration issues under federal jurisdiction took precedence
over the custody matter before the Florida court.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Eig, a lawyer for the Florida relatives, said in a
telephone interview that the family would soon take up Reno's
invitation to file a challenge to the immigration ruling in federal
court. But he said the relatives would also maintain efforts to
have a state court award them legal custody of Elian. ``We are not
removing this case from the state court,'' he said. ``We will seek
protection for Elian's civil rights in federal court as a separate
action.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for the Miami relatives will ask the court to
reinstate an asylum petition on behalf of Elian and argue that
immigration officials wrongly decided that boy's father was in a
position to make a decision in the child's best interests.
</P>
<P>
   No clear end appears in sight in the stalemate over Elian's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have been hoping that Elian's
relatives will not dig in their heels and refuse to allow the boy
to return to Cuba. But since last week's ruling by the immigration
service, hundreds of Cuban-Americans have staged protests in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Wednesday's action in lifting the deadline
was part of the effort to demonstrate that the decision to rule in
favor of the father was a product of the law. One official said
that the deep fear behind all the legal maneuvering was that the
situation would deteriorate to a stage where the federal government
would have to use marshals to assume physical custody of the boy.
``We are still hopeful that we can resolve this matter soon,'' a
senior official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been sensitive from the beginning to the
political implications of the case. While reluctant to offend
Cuban-American voters, senior officials have also been eager to end
the situation to prevent any worsening of relations with Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, several members of Congress, Democrats and
Republicans, sent a letter to Reno urging her to respect the role
of the Florida courts. The signers included Rep. Dan Burton,
R-Ind., and Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Eig said Wednesday that the family would abide by any court
decision and fully understood that it would not be in the best
interests of the child to have any confrontation with the federal
authorities in which Elian would be forcibly taken from them. But
he left open the possibility that the relatives might feel that a
state court ruling in their favor on custody might trump the
federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that Reno would not respect a state court
ruling on what is essentially a state matter,'' Eig said, adding it
was common for federal courts to look to state courts to determine
a person's status in making immigration rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Reno made it clear Wednesday that she believed otherwise. She
also offered a long rebuttal to the lawyers' contention that
immigration service guidelines mandated that Elian should be given
a full hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2334EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000112.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-12 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-SALE-NYT     01-12 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DEAL YET FOR SALE OF THE DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talks over the possible purchase of the Devils by the YankeeNets
appear to be moving forward, with the newly merged baseball and
basketball teams tentatively agreeing to pay $175 million for the
hockey team, people involved in the negotiations said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is not final, and either side could still change
its mind. John McMullen, the owner of the Devils, even denied
Wednesday that a tentative accord had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Others involved in the discussions insisted, however, that a
nonbinding agreement was signed last month; it essentially compels
the YankeeNets and McMullen to negotiate toward a final contract in
good faith, although each side could walk away from a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The document started a period during which the YankeeNets may
examine the hockey team's finances, with an eye toward finding
liabilities or lawsuits that could affect the sale price, which
stands to be one of the highest for a National Hockey League team.
</P>
<P>
   But McMullen insisted, in strong terms, that there was no deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not selling anything,'' he said by telephone from Florida,
adding that there was ``absolutely no truth'' to the existence of
such a tentative contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made up my mind,'' he said. ``There's no agreement.
It's not so.''
</P>
<P>
   He said YankeeNets officials had made him offers. ``They're
talking to me, that's all,'' McMullen said. ``They'd love to buy
me. I'm the best team in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubenstein, a spokesman for and board member of the
YankeeNets, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But people involved in the talks insisted that both sides had
signed the nonbinding contract and that the negotiations were far
more advanced than McMullen acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal comes to fruition, the Devils will make a sensible
fit with the YankeeNets, which wants to relocate the Nets from
Continental Arena in the Meadowlands to an arena that would be
built in downtown Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the Devils would provide a second tenant for the proposed
$290 million arena, making it much more likely to be profitable and
therefore easier to finance. The Nets' lease in the Meadowlands
expires in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   It might be worth it for the YankeeNets to pay $175 million _
$40 million above Forbes magazine's recent estimate of the Devils'
value _ to fill a new arena in Newark with two teams, guaranteeing
more than 80 regular-season games a year.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman has said that state aid for infrastructure
at a Newark arena, estimated to be worth as much as $75 million,
would hinge on the housing of two teams.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen continues to lobby state officials to build a privately
financed arena for the Devils in Hoboken, N.J., in a proposed
venture with Cablevision. But he has been thwarted by the
governor's refusal to grant him crucial air rights over state-owned
New Jersey Transit railroad tracks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
