<SLUG> BC-NY-ACTOR-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY ACTOR FILES SUIT IN WRONGFUL ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A leading actor in the Broadway musical ``Ragtime''
who was mistakenly arrested last summer filed a lawsuit against the
Police Department on Wednesday that demands changes in arrest
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, Alton Fitzgerald White, 35, who will finish his run
as Coalhouse Walker Jr. when ``Ragtime'' closes on Sunday, was
arrested July 16 in the vestibule of his apartment building in
Harlem by officers who said they had received a call about Hispanic
men in T-shirts who were carrying guns.
</P>
<P>
   White was handcuffed, and taken to the 33rd Precinct station
house, where he was strip-searched, held for four hours and
initially questioned without being read his rights, the suit said.
He was released without being charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Civil Liberties Union, which is representing White,
contends in the lawsuit that White's arrest was part of a broad
pattern by the Police Department ``to arrest thousands of New
Yorkers every year without legal justification.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, cited
recent news reports that in 1998 local district attorneys refused
to prosecute 18,000 cases in which the police had arrested New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   White, reached by phone between scenes during the first act of
Wednesday's matinee performance of ``Ragtime,'' said he hoped his
case would focus attention on the pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a victim in the sense that it happened to me,'' he said,
``but it's broader than that. In the grand scheme of things, it's
reality, and it's a reality that needs to be no more.''
</P>
<P>
   A police official, George Grasso, deputy commissioner for legal
matters, sharply criticized the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear-cut example of police officers putting their
lives on the line and acting well within the scope of their duties
to protect the lives of Mr. White and his neighbors,'' Grasso said
in a written statement. ``It is, indeed, a shame that Mr. White
refuses to understand this concept.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said they found a kilogram of cocaine in the lobby of
the building July 16 and arrested five men in addition to White.
Two were charged with criminal drug possession.
</P>
<P>
   The other men who were arrested but not charged filed a separate
civil rights lawsuit Wednesday. Each of the three, Ronald Jackson,
Christopher Montgomery and Marcus McCollum, was held for about five
hours before being released.
</P>
<P>
   All four men in the lawsuits are black. Both suits accuse the
police of singling out members of minorities in New York for
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Montgomery had just arrived in New York, their suit
said. Jackson, 28, was going to work as the student activities
coordinator at Columbia University, while Montgomery, 24, was
entering Columbia's business school, the suit said. McCollum, 29,
was employed as a publicist in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Montgomery were excited about coming to the city,
said their lawyer, Lewis Steele, and ``on the very first day, the
police treat them like the lowest of criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seeking compensatory and punitive damages, both
lawsuits seek a declaration by a judge that the police engaged in
illegal arrest practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeking systemic change,'' said Norman Siegel, executive
director of the civil liberties union, ``and an end to police
practices that are poisoning police-community relations in New York
City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
