<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER CLAIMS NO EVIL INTENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves reliever John Rocker insisted Wednesday that he
was not a racist and that the published portrayal of his comments
``grossly misrepresented'' the person he is. But in his first
interview since his inflammatory comments ran in Sports Illustrated
last month, he often sounded defensive, and rather than deflate the
controversy he created, he may have fueled it further.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a racist, would I want a black guy living in my
house?'' Rocker asked rhetorically, speaking in an interview with
ESPN. ``I would invite him to come to my house? I did that three
times over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I want to do is offend people and ostracize
myself. I like being around people and like being accepted by
people, and if I had ever felt any of these comments would
ostracize myself and take me back and put me on a pedestal and
segregated, I certainly never would've said it because that wasn't
my intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was asked what he would have thought if he had read
comments like his attributed to another person. ``I would've
thought I was a complete jerk,'' he said. ``Like, `Who the heck
does this guy think he is, mouthing off like this, and what kind of
experience does he have to talk from?'''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker tried to provide a context for his remarks, mentioning
how harshly he had been treated while he played in Shea Stadium
against the New York Mets last season, how he had been spat upon,
and how someone had dumped a beer on him at Yankee Stadium during
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker did not deny making the comments that were attributed to
him, but implied that the article did not correctly reflect his
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig has ordered Rocker to undergo a
psychological evaluation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
