u a BC-NY-COLLEGE-SAVINGS-NY     01-12 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLEGE-SAVINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGE OF INVESTORS DOUBLES ASSETS OF N.Y. COLLEGE SAVINGS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some, it was the lure of the tax deduction. For others, it
was the chance to save for the college education of a son, daughter
or grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the motivation, a flood of new checks in 1999 sent
the assets in New York's College Savings Program to $374 million,
more than double the total a year ago, just months after it was
started.
</P>
<P>
   The number of accounts jumped during the past year to 83,143,
from about 43,000. The average account was up, too, to about
$4,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did expect a good response, but it's really been quite
overwhelming,'' said state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, who oversees
the accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The college savings plan allows individuals to put aside money
for themselves, relatives or friends in tax-sheltered accounts to
be used for tuition at accredited colleges or graduate or
professional schools.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan's rules, contributions of up to $5,000 per
taxpayer each year are not subject to state and local taxes but are
subject to federal taxes. Income earned is also exempt from state
and local taxes, and federal taxes on earnings are deferred until
the money is withdrawn, at which time it is taxed at the student's
rate. On contributions over $5,000, only the interest is exempt
from local and state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The rates of return on the accounts varied last year depending
on the age of the beneficiaries. The plan is structured so that
accounts for young children are mostly invested in the stock
market, while those for older children and adults have much smaller
investments in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said the plan is at the limit (currently 45 percent) on
how much money can be invested in equities. He and Gov. George
Pataki are pressing for legislation to lift those limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
