u p BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-N     01-12 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSEMBLY DEMOCRATS SHIFT STANCE ON FUND-RAISER BAN
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a turnabout, Democratic leaders of the state
Assembly Wednesday called for a ban on political fund-raisers in
the Albany area while the Legislature was in session. The proposal
is part of a campaign finance bill that includes a perennially
unsuccessful proposal to give candidates taxpayer money to help
finance their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Just six months ago, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver,
D-Manhattan, said he did not see a problem with Albany
fund-raisers. At the time, he was expressing opposition to a
similar proposal put forward by Gov. George Pataki introduced in
June. That bill was not taken up by either the Assembly or the
Republican-led Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have long held fund-raisers in Albany during the
session to attract lobbyists' donations. Silver's endorsement of
the ban comes at a time when lobbyists have been under more
legislative and public scrutiny. Silver was widely criticized last
month for refusing to go along with a Senate bill to restrict
lawmakers from accepting most meals and gifts from lobbyists.
Senate members adopted the restrictions on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lynch, a spokeswoman for Silver, said his proposed ban on
fund-raisers was a separate issue from lobbying reform and grew out
of his commitment to campaign finance overhaul. ``It was just an
evolution of the issue,'' she said. ``As we go into the new
millennium, he feels it should be part of a serious campaign
finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legislative experts, though, say the proposed ban is an
attempt by Democrats to win public support for a campaign finance
bill that has been proposed every year for two decades. Senate
leaders and the governor remain opposed to any measure that would
allow public money to be spent on political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, whose district is in the
Albany area, raised questions about the Assembly's commitment on
lobbying reform, given its refusal to go along with the Senate's
effort last month to ban lobbyists' gifts. He urged Assembly
members to ban fund-raisers on their own if they were to be taken
seriously. ``The silence out of the Assembly has been deafening,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have repeatedly pledged to undertake reforms in
campaign financing and in lobbying, have passed bills that were not
taken up by the other chamber, and then have accused each other of
not taking those issues seriously. And Pataki, after broaching
campaign finance reform for the first time in June, notably did not
mention it last week in his annual address to the Legislature. His
office did not return calls Wednesday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lynch rejected the idea that Assembly leaders had proposed
the ban on Albany fund-raisers as a political maneuver. ``If they
don't like our bill, fine, pass their own,'' she said of the Senate
members. ``Lobby reform and campaign finance reform are two
separate issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
