A4699 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-FLEE-NYT &LR;      01-12 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FLEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES SPLIT ON WHETHER FLIGHT FROM POLICE IS CAUSE FOR SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SCOTUS-POLICE) 
(mk) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ It was an October afternoon in 1989, and Richard
Tucker was sitting on the stoop of a tenement on Rutherford Avenue
in downtown Trenton. A police car approached. Tucker fled, running
practically into the arms of a second police car that had been
alerted by the first about a fleeing man.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he was captured, Tucker tossed a clear bag into a
cellar opening. It contained crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's decision to run would become, in 1994, the basis of New
Jersey's judicial ruling that flight at the sight of a law
enforcement officer was not valid grounds for seizure under the
Fourth Amendment's prohibition of unreasonable search.
</P>
<P>
   Flight alone, the court said in a ruling that puts New Jersey at
odds with Wednesday's Supreme Court decision in Illinois vs.
Wardlow, was no basis for stopping someone unless there was more
evidence to support the police decision to give chase. Tucker went
free.
</P>
<P>
   But a Connecticut court looked at similar circumstances _ a
sudden flight, seizure, search and the finding of illegal drugs _
and ruled the opposite way. In the case of Connecticut vs. Maia,
the state trial court held in 1997 that when Eric Maia ran from
approaching police officers _ he hid in an apartment house _ he
gave the officers enough cause to stop and search him.
</P>
<P>
   They found marijuana, and charged Maia with possession with
intent to distribute, the same charge with which Tucker was
originally convicted in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Maia's appeal failed in the Connecticut Appellate Court; the
state Supreme Court, with the notable dissent of Judge Robert
Berdon, Connecticut's famous legal maverick, declined to review it.
Maia went to jail.
</P>
<P>
   That two should disagree on such a fundamental matter of
law is unusual, said George Thomas, a professor of law at Rutgers
Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually you won't find very many states departing from the
federal model on matters like his,'' Thomas said. ``It wouldn't
surprise me if there were more than half a dozen states in the
country that went their own way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported Wednesday that besides New Jersey,
courts in Alaska, California, Colorado, Maryland, Michigan, Nevada
and Utah had held that the police could not generally question
people simply because they fled at the sight of a badge. But, in
addition to Connecticut, courts in Indiana, Louisiana, Minnesota,
North Carolina, Ohio and Wisconsin have handed down decisions in
line with Wednesday's Supreme Court ruling that flight may
constitute a probable cause for questioning and searching a
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   New York had its own famous arrest-after-flight case under Judge
Harold Baer Jr. of the U.S. District Court for the Southern
District of New York, who in 1995 suppressed as evidence 80 pounds
of cocaine and heroin found in the car of Carol Bayless on the
ground that the police had decided to search the car only after men
who were seen loading it fled as the police approached.
</P>
<P>
   Baer's decision provoked a political ruckus that became an issue
in the subsequent city elections and even drew criticism from
President Clinton, who had appointed him in 1994. The judge
reversed himself in 1997, admitted the drugs into evidence and then
took himself off the case. Ms. Bayless, now 46, was later convicted
and sentenced to four and a half years in prison in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In each of these cases, the issue the court had to decide was
whether evidence found after the suspects had been stopped for
fleeing was admissible. All three defendants argued that since
running away did not provide probable cause for arrest and search,
the drugs could not be used in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   (Maia further maintained that because he ran into a house and
closed the door _ although it was not his house _ he had a
reasonable expectation of privacy under the Fourth Amendment.)
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court, at least, agreed. ``Flight must be
accompanied by some circumstance present and unexplained that, in
conjunction with the flight, reasonably justifies an inference that
it was done with a consciousness of guilt and pursuant to an effort
to avoid an accusation based on that guilt,'' the court ruled
unanimously, with one justice abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Connecticut Appellate Court saw the same facts
differently. ``Reasonable and articulable suspicion is an objective
standard that focuses not on the mind of the police officer, but on
whether a reasonable person having the information available to and
known by the police would have had that level of suspicion,'' the
majority wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
