<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR AND FIRST LADY TALK ABOUT SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With huffs and puffs and language that seemed more suited to
nuclear arms negotiations than a contest for the U.S. Senate, aides
to Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and to Hillary Rodham Clinton opened
talks Wednesday on ways to limit the use of largely unregulated
soft-money contributions for their campaigns. The talks faltered by
dusk.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely at this point that either Giuliani or Mrs.
Clinton would agree to any measures that would curtail spending on
what both sides expect to be the most expensive Senate race in New
York history. But at the very least, the exchanges _ a telephone
conversation between the two campaign managers, followed by faxed
letters _ allowed Giuliani and Mrs. Clinton to reprise complaints
about each other's fund-raising practices while claiming to seize
the ethical high ground.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion began after Mrs. Clinton said to reporters in
Syracuse last month that she would be willing to consider a
bilateral ban on the soft money and on expenditures on behalf of
the candidates by independent committees. Mrs. Clinton has come
under attack for her aggressive efforts to raise soft money through
a network of committees across the nation, and several Republicans
have suggested that she floated the idea to gain some political
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's campaign manager, Bill de Blasio, called
Giuliani's campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, on Tuesday to begin
talks about the proposal. Teitelbaum called him back Wednesday.
They talked for five minutes. Within 30 minutes, Teitelbaum
responded with a letter saying that Giuliani was open to such
discussions but only if Mrs. Clinton took steps to create a ``level
playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Teitelbaum called on Mrs. Clinton to reimburse
the Democratic National Committee for advertisements it financed on
Mrs. Clinton's behalf that ran upstate last year, as well as an
up-to-date accounting of soft money raised on her behalf. Soft
money given to political parties is intended for ``party building''
activities, not campaigns, but it is used for advertising on
issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
