<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-SERVICES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK TO TURN TAX OUTLETS INTO FINANCIAL SERVICES CENTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Inc. outlined broad plans Wednesday
for transforming its network of seasonal tax offices into
year-round financial services centers for middle-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kicking off what we call the new H&AMP;R Block,'' said Frank
L. Salizzoni, Block's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans, which are going into effect now, include:
</P>
<P>
   - Opening 94 year-round Block Financial Centers throughout the
United States. People may go to these centers for financial
planning, investment services, home mortgages, online trading and
other services, as well as for tax help.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy of the new centers formerly were offices of Olde
Financial Corp., which Block bought last year.
</P>
<P>
   - Offering many of those same tax preparation, mortgage and
brokerage services online to home computer users through an
expanded Web site at www.hrblock.com.
</P>
<P>
   - Introducing a Refund Rewards program, in which Block will load
taxpayers' refunds onto special buying cards. Taxpayers can use the
cards to get cash from automated teller machines or buy everything
from cars to consumer goods to airline tickets at discounts from
participating companies.
</P>
<P>
   Block's financial software publishing arm also is incorporating
new features in this year's products to help people filing at home
get refunds faster and use the new cards if they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Salizzoni, Chairman Henry Bloch and other top company executives
were in New York on Wednesday to discuss the changes with market
analysts and to ring the opening bell on the New York Stock
Exchange, where Block shares later closed at 47, down .
</P>
<P>
   Salizzoni and Mark Ernst, Block's chief operating officer, said
the changes were a natural extension of a drive that began long ago
to diversify the company's operations and produce a more dependable
yearlong stream of revenue and profits than tax work provides.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many of the new services unveiled Wednesday will prompt
changes at Block's 9,000 traditional U.S. tax preparation offices,
Ernst said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is offering free electronic filing to customers at
most of those offices, and preparers there will be ready to refer
clients to Block's other financial service offerings if the clients
ask, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many clients probably will ask, Ernst said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on historical experience, ``many people are more focused
on financial matters during tax season than any other time of the
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And based on market research Block did in preparation for the
plans announced Wednesday, many middle-income taxpayers seem
inclined to look to H&AMP;R Block as a potential source of financial
advice more often than more established Wall Street names that are
perceived to prefer wealthier clients, Ernst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that gives us an advantage that no one else has,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Block historically reports its greatest revenue and most of its
profit in its fourth quarter, which ends in April, because peak tax
seasons in the United States, Canada, Australia and other countries
where Block operates generally don't start until January.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its diversification drive, Block also has bought
several regional accounting firms over the last two years and woven
them into a new business and accounting services subsidiary that is
the nation's sixth-largest accounting firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
