<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-CENTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMERS INSURANCE TO EMPLOY 500 AT CUSTOMER CARE CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ Farmers Insurance Group, the nation's
third-largest home and auto insurer, plans to open a Customer Care
Center in Olathe this year and double its 500-member Kansas City
area work force.
</P>
<P>
   The center, under construction in Olathe's Technology Park, will
add to the area's reputation as a call center hub. It is one of two
centers that Farmers is opening to provide nationwide claims
service around the clock, said Vince Donofrio, the company's
support services director.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers' other new national claims center is being built near
Oklahoma City and also will employ about 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Both centers are designed to be models of a new, streamlined
claims process for Farmers customers in more than 40 states, said
Frank Soldano, vice president for strategic initiatives at the
company's headquarters in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Each center will be a 24-hour-a-day, year-round operation where
claims representatives will be able almost immediately to begin
processing reports of damaged property and authorizing home or auto
repairs, Soldano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process should be seamless,'' he said. ``Our care centers
go beyond a typical call center. They represent a focal point for
customer service and management.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials estimate the 500 specialized and mostly
clerical workers needed in Olathe probably would earn an average of
$32,000, with benefits, a year.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers plans to recruit all but about 50 of the 500 additional
Kansas City area workers from the local work force, Donofrio said.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming construction continues on schedule, hiring will begin
this spring. The center is to open in this year's third quarter and
will be fully staffed by April 2001, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and executives of Karbank &AMP; Co., Technology Park's
developers, signed a 10-year lease Wednesday in Los Angeles for the
80,000 square feet in Olathe that the insurance company will
occupy. Details of the lease agreement weren't available.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers will be eligible for more than $2 million in state
economic development incentives that are related to training
workers in higher-tech jobs as well as some other tax benefits that
cannot be calculated yet, said Kansas Lt. Gov. Gary Sherrer, who
also is the state's commerce and housing secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company presumably will benefit from a 10-year,
50 percent Olathe tax abatement for which all Technology Park
tenants will qualify, said Kevin Hammeke, the city's financial
services director.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the area's most recent job expansions have involved
communications centers.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be surprising, said Jill McCarthy, business
development director the Kansas City Area Development Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more than 40 companies having substantial call center
operations here already, we have both a highly trained work force
and an infrastructure to attract more companies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers picked the Kansas City and Oklahoma City areas from a
short list of first 10 and then five other cities examined in a
nationwide search, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Central location, top-quality work forces and the relatively low
cost of living weighed heavily in both cities' favor, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City's case, it also helped that ``we've had a lot of
good experiences here,'' said Joe Moss, Farmers' executive director
for Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the state office that Moss leads, Farmers has
both a Kansas City Service Center and a National Catastrophe
Center, all in Overland Park, with a total work force of about 500
people.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas civic and political hailed Farmers' announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another example of a well-respected business taking
advantage of the outstanding benefits Kansas has to offer,'' Kansas
Gov. Bill Graves said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
