<SLUG> BC-CHILD-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE IN NEW YORK REFUSES TO RETURN CHILDREN TO FRANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Manhattan refused Wednesday to
order the return of two children to France, saying that their
mother had been abused by their father in Paris and that forcing
them to return would expose them to a grave risk of psychological
harm.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge Denny Chin of U.S. District Court in
Manhattan came in a bitterly contested dispute in which the
governments of France and the United States had both urged that the
judge return the children under the 1980 Hague Convention, an
international treaty that in almost all cases encourages the prompt
return of abducted children in international custody disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute also raised child welfare issues that in some ways
resembled those surrounding Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban
boy whose status has sparked an international debate.
</P>
<P>
   In the French case, Chin said although he had confidence that
France's courts could adequately protect the children _ 8-year-old
Marie-Eline Blondin, and her brother, Francois, 4 _ from physical
harm if they were returned, uprooting them from their new life in
the United States would be too risky psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Marthe Dubois, who moved in with relatives in
Woodbridge, N.J., admitted forging travel documents so she could
take the children out of France in August 1997. She said that she
wanted to escape seven years of repeated beatings by her boyfriend,
Felix Blondin, the children's father.
</P>
<P>
   Blondin denied the allegations, and French officials have
indicated they might seek to extradite Ms. Dubois to face charges
in France if Chin did not return the children under the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But Chin, who wrote that he was troubled by what he called
France's veiled threats to extradite if he did not issue a
favorable ruling, said the case fit a narrow exception in the Hague
treaty. The exception says children may remain if returning them
would pose a ``grave risk'' of psychological or physical harm.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubois' lawyer, Leonard F. Joy, said his client was
gratified by the ruling. He said it was ``faithful'' to the treaty
``and most important, is in the best interests of the children it
was designed to protect.''
</P>
<P>
   Blondin's lawyers, who said they had not yet been able to reach
their client in Paris, said an appeal would be considered.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers, Sanford J. Hausler, said the ruling could
lead to greater trauma for the children if Ms. Dubois was now
extradited.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan, which represented the
views of the government, had no comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-12-00 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
