<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNES-AND-NOBLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF LEAVING BARNESANDNOBLE.COM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After little more than a year as Barnesandnoble.com's chief
executive, Jonathan Bulkeley announced his departure from the No. 2
online bookseller Wednesday, saying that he wanted to devote more
time to his own Internet investments and his growing family.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Bulkeley, 39, effective in February, came
after discussions between him and Leonard Riggio, the chairman and
chief executive of Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc., which owns the bookstore in
a partnership with Bertelsmann, the media conglomerate..
</P>
<P>
   The company announced that Riggio's brother, Stephen Riggio,
would step in as the acting chief executive until a replacement is
found.
</P>
<P>
   Bulkeley is one of a handful of senior executives who have left
the online bookseller after little more than a year at the growing
company, which was started in 1997. The other executives have
included a chief operating officer, a chief financial officer, a
technology officer and a director of communications.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Bulkeley stressed that he wanted to
focus his time on investments that he maintains in other Internet
start-up companies, like QXL.com, a leading European Web auctioneer
that he presides over as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about everyone else,'' he said of the other
executive departures. ``I'm not fleeing. I'm going to do other
stuff that I really enjoy. My wife is having another baby and this
will be No. 4. And I've been on the Internet for eight years and
I'm ready to be a chairman and a board member and a father.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Leonard Riggio said that he had been discussing
Bulkeley's departure for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a decision that we both came to,'' Riggio said,
adding that the resignation ``was really no surprise; there's been
no acrimony in our relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior book publishing executive said that it was clear before
the Christmas holidays that there were tensions between the chief
executive and the parent company, which had exerted increasing
control over the infant bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hearing rumors that this marriage was not made in
heaven and was about to end up in court,'' the executive said. ``I
think that the word from Barnes &AMP; Noble was that they were very
unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulkeley's resignation came a week after the company reported
that its sales had tripled in its most recent quarter to $81.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Barnesandnoble.com shares fell by 62.5 cents, to
$15.4375, well below the high of $26.625 they reached after the
company's initial public offering last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry about these stock prices,'' Riggio said. ``And
I certainly can't hold these managers or even myself responsible.
You do your best, but with these companies you've got to manage
them well and the stock price ought to follow. So, I'm not happy
with the stock price at Barnesandnoble.com, but I don't think it's
a function of the way Jonathan had managed the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble and Bertelsmann each own about 41 percent of the
online bookseller. Bertelsmann's chief executive, Thomas
Middelhoff, issued a statement Wednesday expressing confidence in
Riggio's ability to lead the company and the decision to appoint
his brother temporarily as the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message, he reaffirmed that statement: ``I really
believe this. You'll see what will happen very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggio said that the company is searching for a chief executive
but did not specify a timetable, denying rumors within the book
industry that the company was considering a top publishing
executive for the position.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on the qualifications the company had in
mind for a new leader. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
