<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI BUDGET WOULD SLOW NEW YORK CITY'S GAINS FOR SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The budget that Gov. George E. Pataki proposed
calls for a modest increase in state aid to schools, but it would
worsen a disparity that has for years led the New York City school
system to receive less state aid per pupil than other districts.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's budget seeks to increase overall state spending for
education by $355 million, or 2.8 percent, for the coming school
year. But the city would receive only $102 million of the total
increase, or 29 percent, even though it has 37 percent of the
state's students.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the imbalance is that while Pataki's plan
calls for increasing the main form of state aid to school
districts, including New York City's, he is seeking to eliminate a
handful of programs that primarily benefit the city school system
and other urban districts.
</P>
<P>
   Those cuts are mainly directed at two programs: one that raises
the salaries of teachers in urban school districts and another that
provides such districts money to undertake minor maintenance
projects in aging school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the state gave the city roughly $95 million to provide
those programs this year. But most if not all of that money is
likely to be restored in negotiations with the Legislature, as it
has been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's budget also calls for other changes in school aid for
the city. It would scale back an agreement that the governor and
legislative leaders reached in 1997 that called for gradually
expanding pre-kindergarten classes and reducing classroom size over
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's budget calls for providing an additional $20
million for these programs in the coming year, bringing the amount
spent on them to $195 million. But Democrats and even some of the
governor's fellow Republicans say the 1997 agreement calls for
spending about $170 million more than what the governor has
proposed for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's budget stirred some protests, with critics saying
that it would do nothing to change the state's longstanding
practice of providing city students with less than their fair share
of aid, compared to students in other districts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rebell, the executive director for the Campaign for
Fiscal Equality, a group that in a lawsuit had charged that the
state discriminated against poor urban districts like the city's,
said Pataki's budget represents more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget fails to take into account student wealth and
need,'' Rebell said. ``Rather than targeting more funds for
high-need districts, it leaves the current funding formula intact,
which is nothing more than a political manipulation of state
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   But the governor's aides said that Pataki has tried to move the
city's share of state education financing closer to parity for the
last five years. More than that, though, the governor's budget
would provide the city with nearly 38 percent of the main form of
financing that the state provides to schools, they said. That
financing is known as formula aid and is distributed to all
districts for general operations. The aides also noted that New
York City has received a 35 percent increase in education money
over the last six years compared with 25 percent on average for the
rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's budget would also bring mixed results to school
districts on Long Island and in Westchester County. While some
districts would see overall increases, others would lose money. On
Long Island, slightly more than half of the school districts would
see decreases under the governor's proposals. In Westchester, the
school districts overall would receive $2.8 million additional,
barely 1 percent above current financing levels.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also used his budget to renew his battle with the
Board of Regents, the body charged with setting educational policy
in the state. Pataki has in the past called for abolishing the
board, whose members are chosen by the governor's Democratic rivals
in the Legislature. But this time, Pataki made a proposal in his
budget to give the governor the authority to make nominations to
the 16-member board, and those nominees would have to be approved
by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also proposed giving the governor power to name the
commissioner of education, without the approval of the Legislature.
The commissioner is now selected by the Regents. The governor is
also seeking to switch $250,000 of the financing for charter
schools from the Department of Education to an agency essentially
under his control. In 1998, Pataki pushed a bill through the
Legislature authorizing the creation of charter schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
