<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUND-MANAGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE FIDELITY FUND MANAGER RESIGNS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Vanderheiden, who managed several top-performing Fidelity
funds in the shadow of Peter Lynch during the 1980s but had
recently seen his track record suffer as his more conservative,
value-investing style fell out of favor, announced Wednesday that
he was quitting effective Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderheiden, 54, is manager of the $29 billion Fidelity Advisor
Growth Opportunities Fund and the $7 billion Fidelity Destiny I
fund, making him one of the most prominent managers at Fidelity
Investments in Boston, a unit of the FMR Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the decision to leave was entirely his own and that
he would spend one day a week working as a part-time mentor for
analysts and managers at Fidelity. Otherwise, he said he planned to
spend time with his family, hiking and climbing mountains, and
managing his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderheiden's biggest fund, Advisor Growth Opportunities, will
pass to Bettina Doulton, who had been manager of two large Fidelity
funds, Puritan and Equity-Income II. The Destiny I fund will be
managed by Karen Firestone, who will continue to run Fidelity's
Large Cap Stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said those changes, particularly at the Destiny I fund,
could lead to a more aggressive, growth-oriented investing style.
Under Ms. Doulton, the Puritan fund ranked in the top 39 percent of
its peers for the three years ended in November, according to
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago research firm, while Equity-Income II
ranked in the top fifth. Ms. Firestone, who took over Large Cap
Stock in April 1998, led it to a 30.2 percent return last year,
compared with 21 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say these other managers will be a little
more growth oriented than where George is now,'' said Robert C.
Pozen, who oversees all of Fidelity's funds.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderheiden's oldest fund, Destiny I, has returned 19.3 percent
annually since he took it over in December 1980, according to
Morningstar _ far ahead of the S&AMP;P's 16.8 percent annual return
over the same time. That makes Vanderheiden one of only a handful
of diversified fund managers to beat the index over such a long
period.
</P>
<P>
   But his funds have not done well lately and have lagged well
behind the S&AMP;P 500 last year as investors favored technology,
Internet and growth stocks. ``There's no question he's had a rotten
record'' lately, said Scott Cooley, a Morningstar analyst. ``But
I'd take that long-term record. It's unbelievably good.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lowell, editor of Fidelity Investor, an independent
newsletter that tracks Fidelity, said, ``Right through early 1995,
his career was stellar.'' But he said Vanderheiden had suffered by
not joining the ``momentum'' stock bandwagon. ``Hanging up his
spurs today probably signals that he is exhausted from banging his
head against that momentum wall,'' Lowell said &UR;  &LR; Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderheiden said he thought a value revival might be just
around the corner, noting that the end of other investing crazes _
the run-up in the Japanese stock market during the 1980s, the
biotechnology craze of 1991 and the rise of the Nifty 50 in 1972 _
all fizzled around the start of a new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've found over a lot of years is that a lot of these
manias seem to end at the end of the year,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
