u s BC-FBN-JETS-OWNER-NYT &LR;      01-12 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-OWNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' NEW OWNER DROPS IN FOR A CHAT WITH PARCELLS AND GUTMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see FBN-COLUMN-JETS) 
(bl) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The New York Jets' new owner, Robert Wood
Johnson IV, took a look late Wednesday at part of what he bought
for $635 million.
</P>
<P>
   But he apparently did not get into the nitty-gritty of whether
Bill Parcells would return as head coach, or who would coach the
team next season if Parcells does not return. But Johnson has
reportedly told friends and associates that he wants Parcells and
is willing to pay for him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, associates of Johnson say he wanted to meet Parcells and
Gutman in a relaxed atmosphere before getting into a serious
discussion of the team's future _ especially Parcells'.
</P>
<P>
   No coach is likely to be named until at least Tuesday; that is
when the full ownership of the National Football League meets in
New York and is expected to formally approve Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson arrived at the Jets' training complex and spent about
two hours meeting Parcells and team president Steve Gutman.
</P>
<P>
   Al Groh, the linebackers coach and the apparent heir to the
coaching post if Parcells decides not to return, said he did not
meet Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in to work out, really, that's the reason I was here,''
Groh said. ``We never got a chance to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh said he had taken a brief vacation while speculation
swirled about who would be the next coach after last week's
stunning developments: Parcells stepped down after the Jets' final
game, named Bill Belichick as his replacement _ as his contract
called for _ then watched as Belichick quit the next day. In the
interim, the New England Patriots had asked to interview Belichick
for their coach's job.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has protested the validity of his Jets contract, and
he and his lawyer will meet Gutman on Thursday at the league
counsel's office in Times Square to argue whether the contract is
valid. If the Jets win, most people expect the Patriots to try to
make a deal for Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Groh would not comment about his status. One possibility, if
Parcells returns, would see Groh elevated to an assistant head
coach's post, be prepared to take over when Parcells finally does
step down.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Groh left, Johnson got into his car, too, without
stopping to comment. One of the several former policemen who work
as security officers for the Jets told a person inside the training
complex that three reporters and three photographers were waiting
at the main entrance. Johnson then was ushered into a car through a
previously locked rear gate and was driven away.
</P>
<P>
   But he was seen by some employees through the course of his
visit. One of them was Jim Pons, the Jets' director of football
video and a one-time member of the rock groups, the Turtles and the
Mothers of Invention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was meeting my date's dad,'' said Pons.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the Jets' support staff hope to be retained by
Johnson. Several go back to the 1960s; a core of workers joined the
Jets in 1970s. They all were known to the late Leon Hess, the
paternal former owner who was almost always absent but whose rare
visits to a team practice turned into special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, the Jets merely said that Johnson met for
about two hours with Parcells and Gutman. It was described as a
get-acquainted meeting. Johnson also toured the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his hunger for Parcells, it is apparently Johnson's wish
to wait until early next week before formally announcing a new
coach. Johnson is reluctant to meet the news media or say anything
about the coaching situation until he is the owner, officially.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that if he can get Parcells to return, the
move would put an exclamation point on his ownership, and give him
immediate credibility in a field in which he is a novice.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a friend of Belichick's said he is prepared to sit
out a year if necessary. Also, the friend said, there were other
options for Belichick besides the Patriots _ such as the vacant
head coaching positions with the New Orleans Saints and the Dallas
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Belichick goes, he will probably take with him the
club's defensive assistant, Eric Mangini. Mangini worked on
ball-control drills, helped Belichick tutor the defensive backs and
also worked on film studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tribute to Bill Belichick that a lot of his
former players have called him at home to see what is going on, and
to wish him well,'' the friend said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
